{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"platoDialogues","displayName":"Plato — Selected Dialogues","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Benjamin Jowett Translation, 1871","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Ancient Greek","audienceTags":["philosophy","study"],"sortPriority":41,"itemCount":3554,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["work","section"],"groupingLabels":["Work","Section"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Plato_Dialogues.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"plato-apology-1","text":"In what relation the “Apology” of Plato stands to the real defence of\r Socrates, there are no means of determining. It certainly agrees in\r tone and character with the description of Xenophon, who says in the\r “Memorabilia” that Socrates might have been acquitted “if in any\r moderate degree he would have conciliated the favour of the dicasts;”\r and who informs us in another passage, on the testimony of Hermogenes,\r the friend of Socrates, that he had no wish to live; and that the\r divine sign refused to allow him to prepare a defence, and also that\r Socrates himself declared this to be unneces","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"plato-apology-2","text":"Yet some of the topics may have been actually used by Socrates; and the\r recollection of his very words may have rung in the ears of his\r disciple. The “Apology” of Plato may be compared generally with those\r speeches of Thucydides in which he has embodied his conception of the\r lofty character and policy of the great Pericles, and which at the same\r time furnish a commentary on the situation of affairs from the point of\r view of the historian. So in the “Apology” there is an ideal rather\r than a literal truth; much is said which was not said, and is only\r Plato’s view of the situation. Plato ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"plato-apology-3","text":"There is not much in the other Dialogues which can be compared with the\r “Apology”. The same recollection of his master may have been present to\r the mind of Plato when depicting the sufferings of the Just in the\r “Republic”. The “Crito” may also be regarded as a sort of appendage to\r the “Apology”, in which Socrates, who has defied the judges, is\r nevertheless represented as scrupulously obedient to the laws. The\r idealization of the sufferer is carried still further in the\r “Georgias”, in which the thesis is maintained, that “to suffer is\r better than to do evil;” and the art of rhetoric is ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"plato-apology-4","text":"The “Apology” or Platonic defence of Socrates is divided into three\r parts: 1st. The defence properly so called; 2nd. The shorter address in\r mitigation of the penalty; 3rd. The last words of prophetic rebuke and\r exhortation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"plato-apology-5","text":"The first part commences with an apology for his colloquial style; he\r is, as he has always been, the enemy of rhetoric, and knows of no\r rhetoric but truth; he will not falsify his character by making a\r speech. Then he proceeds to divide his accusers into two classes;\r first, there is the nameless accuser—public opinion. All the world from\r their earliest years had heard that he was a corrupter of youth, and\r had seen him caricatured in the “Clouds” of Aristophanes. Secondly,\r there are the professed accusers, who are but the mouth-piece of the\r others. The accusations of both might be summe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"plato-apology-6","text":"The answer begins by clearing up a confusion. In the representations of\r the Comic poets, and in the opinion of the multitude, he had been\r identified with the teachers of physical science and with the Sophists.\r But this was an error. For both of them he professes a respect in the\r open court, which contrasts with his manner of speaking about them in\r other places. (Compare for Anaxagoras, Phædo, Laws; for the Sophists,\r Meno, Republic, Tim., Theaet., Soph., etc.) But at the same time he\r shows that he is not one of them. Of natural philosophy he knows\r nothing; not that he despises such purs","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"plato-apology-7","text":"He then goes on to explain the reason why he is in such an evil name.\r That had arisen out of a peculiar mission which he had taken upon\r himself. The enthusiastic Chaerephon (probably in anticipation of the\r answer which he received) had gone to Delphi and asked the oracle if\r there was any man wiser than Socrates; and the answer was, that there\r was no man wiser. What could be the meaning of this—that he who knew\r nothing, and knew that he knew nothing, should be declared by the\r oracle to be the wisest of men? Reflecting upon the answer, he\r determined to refute it by finding “a wiser;” and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"plato-apology-8","text":"The second accusation he meets by interrogating Meletus, who is present\r and can be interrogated. “If he is the corrupter, who is the improver\r of the citizens?” (Compare Meno.) “All men everywhere.” But how absurd,\r how contrary to analogy is this! How inconceivable too, that he should\r make the citizens worse when he has to live with them. This surely\r cannot be intentional; and if unintentional, he ought to have been\r instructed by Meletus, and not accused in the court.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"plato-apology-9","text":"But there is another part of the indictment which says that he teaches\r men not to receive the gods whom the city receives, and has other new\r gods. “Is that the way in which he is supposed to corrupt the youth?”\r “Yes, it is.” “Has he only new gods, or none at all?” “None at all.”\r “What, not even the sun and moon?” “No; why, he says that the sun is a\r stone, and the moon earth.” That, replies Socrates, is the old\r confusion about Anaxagoras; the Athenian people are not so ignorant as\r to attribute to the influence of Socrates notions which have found\r their way into the drama, and may be lea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"plato-apology-10","text":"Leaving Meletus, who has had enough words spent upon him, he returns to\r the original accusation. The question may be asked, Why will he persist\r in following a profession which leads him to death? Why?—because he\r must remain at his post where the god has placed him, as he remained at\r Potidaea, and Amphipolis, and Delium, where the generals placed him.\r Besides, he is not so overwise as to imagine that he knows whether\r death is a good or an evil; and he is certain that desertion of his\r duty is an evil. Anytus is quite right in saying that they should never\r have indicted him if they meant ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"plato-apology-11","text":"He is desirous that they should let him live—not for his own sake, but\r for theirs; because he is their heaven-sent friend (and they will never\r have such another), or, as he may be ludicrously described, he is the\r gadfly who stirs the generous steed into motion. Why then has he never\r taken part in public affairs? Because the familiar divine voice has\r hindered him; if he had been a public man, and had fought for the\r right, as he would certainly have fought against the many, he would not\r have lived, and could therefore have done no good. Twice in public\r matters he has risked his life for ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"plato-apology-12","text":"But, though not a public man, he has passed his days in instructing the\r citizens without fee or reward—this was his mission. Whether his\r disciples have turned out well or ill, he cannot justly be charged with\r the result, for he never promised to teach them anything. They might\r come if they liked, and they might stay away if they liked: and they\r did come, because they found an amusement in hearing the pretenders to\r wisdom detected. If they have been corrupted, their elder relatives (if\r not themselves) might surely come into court and witness against him,\r and there is an opportunity stil","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"plato-apology-13","text":"This is about all that he has to say. He will not entreat the judges to\r spare his life; neither will he present a spectacle of weeping\r children, although he, too, is not made of “rock or oak.” Some of the\r judges themselves may have complied with this practice on similar\r occasions, and he trusts that they will not be angry with him for not\r following their example. But he feels that such conduct brings\r discredit on the name of Athens: he feels too, that the judge has sworn\r not to give away justice; and he cannot be guilty of the impiety of\r asking the judge to break his oath, when he is h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"plato-apology-14","text":"As he expected, and probably intended, he is convicted. And now the\r tone of the speech, instead of being more conciliatory, becomes more\r lofty and commanding. Anytus proposes death as the penalty: and what\r counter-proposition shall he make? He, the benefactor of the Athenian\r people, whose whole life has been spent in doing them good, should at\r least have the Olympic victor’s reward of maintenance in the Prytaneum.\r Or why should he propose any counter-penalty when he does not know\r whether death, which Anytus proposes, is a good or an evil? And he is\r certain that imprisonment is an evil,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"plato-apology-15","text":"He is an old man already, and the Athenians will gain nothing but\r disgrace by depriving him of a few years of life. Perhaps he could have\r escaped, if he had chosen to throw down his arms and entreat for his\r life. But he does not at all repent of the manner of his defence; he\r would rather die in his own fashion than live in theirs. For the\r penalty of unrighteousness is swifter than death; that penalty has\r already overtaken his accusers as death will soon overtake him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"plato-apology-16","text":"And now, as one who is about to die, he will prophesy to them. They\r have put him to death in order to escape the necessity of giving an\r account of their lives. But his death “will be the seed” of many\r disciples who will convince them of their evil ways, and will come\r forth to reprove them in harsher terms, because they are younger and\r more inconsiderate.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"plato-apology-17","text":"He would like to say a few words, while there is time, to those who\r would have acquitted him. He wishes them to know that the divine sign\r never interrupted him in the course of his defence; the reason of\r which, as he conjectures, is that the death to which he is going is a\r good and not an evil. For either death is a long sleep, the best of\r sleeps, or a journey to another world in which the souls of the dead\r are gathered together, and in which there may be a hope of seeing the\r heroes of old—in which, too, there are just judges; and as all are\r immortal, there can be no fear of any one su","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"plato-apology-18","text":"Nothing evil can happen to the good man either in life or death, and\r his own death has been permitted by the gods, because it was better for\r him to depart; and therefore he forgives his judges because they have\r done him no harm, although they never meant to do him any good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"plato-apology-19","text":"He has a last request to make to them—that they will trouble his sons\r as he has troubled them, if they appear to prefer riches to virtue, or\r to think themselves something when they are nothing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"19"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"plato-apology-20","text":"“Few persons will be found to wish that Socrates should have defended\r himself otherwise,”—if, as we must add, his defence was that with which\r Plato has provided him. But leaving this question, which does not admit\r of a precise solution, we may go on to ask what was the impression\r which Plato in the “Apology” intended to give of the character and\r conduct of his master in the last great scene? Did he intend to\r represent him (1) as employing sophistries; (2) as designedly\r irritating the judges? Or are these sophistries to be regarded as\r belonging to the age in which he lived and to his pe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"plato-apology-21","text":"For example, when he says that it is absurd to suppose that one man is\r the corrupter and all the rest of the world the improvers of the youth;\r or, when he argues that he never could have corrupted the men with whom\r he had to live; or, when he proves his belief in the gods because he\r believes in the sons of gods, is he serious or jesting? It may be\r observed that these sophisms all occur in his cross-examination of\r Meletus, who is easily foiled and mastered in the hands of the great\r dialectician. Perhaps he regarded these answers as good enough for his\r accuser, of whom he makes very ligh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"plato-apology-22","text":"That the manner in which he defends himself about the lives of his\r disciples is not satisfactory, can hardly be denied. Fresh in the\r memory of the Athenians, and detestable as they deserved to be to the\r newly restored democracy, were the names of Alcibiades, Critias,\r Charmides. It is obviously not a sufficient answer that Socrates had\r never professed to teach them anything, and is therefore not justly\r chargeable with their crimes. Yet the defence, when taken out of this\r ironical form, is doubtless sound: that his teaching had nothing to do\r with their evil lives. Here, then, the sophist","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"plato-apology-23","text":"Truly characteristic of Socrates is another point in his answer, which\r may also be regarded as sophistical. He says that “if he has corrupted\r the youth, he must have corrupted them involuntarily.” But if, as\r Socrates argues, all evil is involuntary, then all criminals ought to\r be admonished and not punished. In these words the Socratic doctrine of\r the involuntariness of evil is clearly intended to be conveyed. Here\r again, as in the former instance, the defence of Socrates is untrue\r practically, but may be true in some ideal or transcendental sense. The\r commonplace reply, that if he had","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"plato-apology-24","text":"Again, when Socrates argues that he must believe in the gods because he\r believes in the sons of gods, we must remember that this is a\r refutation not of the original indictment, which is consistent\r enough—“Socrates does not receive the gods whom the city receives, and\r has other new divinities”—but of the interpretation put upon the words\r by Meletus, who has affirmed that he is a downright atheist. To this\r Socrates fairly answers, in accordance with the ideas of the time, that\r a downright atheist cannot believe in the sons of gods or in divine\r things. The notion that demons or lesser div","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"plato-apology-25","text":"The second question, whether Plato meant to represent Socrates as\r braving or irritating his judges, must also be answered in the\r negative. His irony, his superiority, his audacity, “regarding not the\r person of man,” necessarily flow out of the loftiness of his situation.\r He is not acting a part upon a great occasion, but he is what he has\r been all his life long, “a king of men.” He would rather not appear\r insolent, if he could avoid it (ouch os authadizomenos touto lego).\r Neither is he desirous of hastening his own end, for life and death are\r simply indifferent to him. But such a defen","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"plato-apology-26","text":"It has been remarked that the prophecy of a new generation of teachers\r who would rebuke and exhort the Athenian people in harsher and more\r violent terms was, as far as we know, never fulfilled. No inference can\r be drawn from this circumstance as to the probability of the words\r attributed to him having been actually uttered. They express the\r aspiration of the first martyr of philosophy, that he would leave\r behind him many followers, accompanied by the not unnatural feeling\r that they would be fiercer and more inconsiderate in their words when\r emancipated from his control.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"plato-apology-27","text":"The above remarks must be understood as applying with any degree of\r certainty to the Platonic Socrates only. For, although these or similar\r words may have been spoken by Socrates himself, we cannot exclude the\r possibility, that like so much else, _e.g._ the wisdom of Critias, the\r poem of Solon, the virtues of Charmides, they may have been due only to\r the imagination of Plato. The arguments of those who maintain that the\r Apology was composed during the process, resting on no evidence, do not\r require a serious refutation. Nor are the reasonings of Schleiermacher,\r who argues that the Plat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"plato-apology-28","text":"How you, O Athenians, have been affected by my accusers, I cannot tell;\r but I know that they almost made me forget who I was—so persuasively\r did they speak; and yet they have hardly uttered a word of truth. But\r of the many falsehoods told by them, there was one which quite amazed\r me;—I mean when they said that you should be upon your guard and not\r allow yourselves to be deceived by the force of my eloquence. To say\r this, when they were certain to be detected as soon as I opened my lips\r and proved myself to be anything but a great speaker, did indeed appear\r to me most shameless—unless b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"plato-apology-29","text":"And first, I have to reply to the older charges and to my first\r accusers, and then I will go on to the later ones. For of old I have\r had many accusers, who have accused me falsely to you during many\r years; and I am more afraid of them than of Anytus and his associates,\r who are dangerous, too, in their own way. But far more dangerous are\r the others, who began when you were children, and took possession of\r your minds with their falsehoods, telling of one Socrates, a wise man,\r who speculated about the heaven above, and searched into the earth\r beneath, and made the worse appear the better ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"plato-apology-30","text":"Well, then, I must make my defence, and endeavour to clear away in a\r short time, a slander which has lasted a long time. May I succeed, if\r to succeed be for my good and yours, or likely to avail me in my cause!\r The task is not an easy one; I quite understand the nature of it. And\r so leaving the event with God, in obedience to the law I will now make\r my defence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"plato-apology-31","text":"I will begin at the beginning, and ask what is the accusation which has\r given rise to the slander of me, and in fact has encouraged Meletus to\r proof this charge against me. Well, what do the slanderers say? They\r shall be my prosecutors, and I will sum up their words in an affidavit:\r “Socrates is an evil-doer, and a curious person, who searches into\r things under the earth and in heaven, and he makes the worse appear the\r better cause; and he teaches the aforesaid doctrines to others.” Such\r is the nature of the accusation: it is just what you have yourselves\r seen in the comedy of Aristoph","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"plato-apology-32","text":"As little foundation is there for the report that I am a teacher, and\r take money; this accusation has no more truth in it than the other.\r Although, if a man were really able to instruct mankind, to receive\r money for giving instruction would, in my opinion, be an honour to him.\r There is Gorgias of Leontium, and Prodicus of Ceos, and Hippias of\r Elis, who go the round of the cities, and are able to persuade the\r young men to leave their own citizens by whom they might be taught for\r nothing, and come to them whom they not only pay, but are thankful if\r they may be allowed to pay them. There ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"plato-apology-33","text":"I dare say, Athenians, that some one among you will reply, “Yes,\r Socrates, but what is the origin of these accusations which are brought\r against you; there must have been something strange which you have been\r doing? All these rumours and this talk about you would never have\r arisen if you had been like other men: tell us, then, what is the cause\r of them, for we should be sorry to judge hastily of you.” Now I regard\r this as a fair challenge, and I will endeavour to explain to you the\r reason why I am called wise and have such an evil fame. Please to\r attend then. And although some of you m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"plato-apology-34","text":"Why do I mention this? Because I am going to explain to you why I have\r such an evil name. When I heard the answer, I said to myself, What can\r the god mean? and what is the interpretation of his riddle? for I know\r that I have no wisdom, small or great. What then can he mean when he\r says that I am the wisest of men? And yet he is a god, and cannot lie;\r that would be against his nature. After long consideration, I thought\r of a method of trying the question. I reflected that if I could only\r find a man wiser than myself, then I might go to the god with a\r refutation in my hand. I should say ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"plato-apology-35","text":"Then I went to one man after another, being not unconscious of the\r enmity which I provoked, and I lamented and feared this: but necessity\r was laid upon me,—the word of God, I thought, ought to be considered\r first. And I said to myself, Go I must to all who appear to know, and\r find out the meaning of the oracle. And I swear to you, Athenians, by\r the dog I swear!—for I must tell you the truth—the result of my mission\r was just this: I found that the men most in repute were all but the\r most foolish; and that others less esteemed were really wiser and\r better. I will tell you the tale of my ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"plato-apology-36","text":"At last I went to the artisans. I was conscious that I knew nothing at\r all, as I may say, and I was sure that they knew many fine things; and\r here I was not mistaken, for they did know many things of which I was\r ignorant, and in this they certainly were wiser than I was. But I\r observed that even the good artisans fell into the same error as the\r poets;—because they were good workmen they thought that they also knew\r all sorts of high matters, and this defect in them overshadowed their\r wisdom; and therefore I asked myself on behalf of the oracle, whether I\r would like to be as I was, neith","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"plato-apology-37","text":"This inquisition has led to my having many enemies of the worst and\r most dangerous kind, and has given occasion also to many calumnies. And\r I am called wise, for my hearers always imagine that I myself possess\r the wisdom which I find wanting in others: but the truth is, O men of\r Athens, that God only is wise; and by his answer he intends to show\r that the wisdom of men is worth little or nothing; he is not speaking\r of Socrates, he is only using my name by way of illustration, as if he\r said, He, O men, is the wisest, who, like Socrates, knows that his\r wisdom is in truth worth nothing. An","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"plato-apology-38","text":"There is another thing:—young men of the richer classes, who have not\r much to do, come about me of their own accord; they like to hear the\r pretenders examined, and they often imitate me, and proceed to examine\r others; there are plenty of persons, as they quickly discover, who\r think that they know something, but really know little or nothing; and\r then those who are examined by them instead of being angry with\r themselves are angry with me: This confounded Socrates, they say; this\r villainous misleader of youth!—and then if somebody asks them, Why,\r what evil does he practise or teach? they","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"plato-apology-39","text":"I have said enough in my defence against the first class of my\r accusers; I turn to the second class. They are headed by Meletus, that\r good man and true lover of his country, as he calls himself. Against\r these, too, I must try to make a defence:—Let their affidavit be read:\r it contains something of this kind: It says that Socrates is a doer of\r evil, who corrupts the youth; and who does not believe in the gods of\r the state, but has other new divinities of his own. Such is the charge;\r and now let us examine the particular counts. He says that I am a doer\r of evil, and corrupt the youth; bu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"plato-apology-40","text":"Come hither, Meletus, and let me ask a question of you. You think a\r great deal about the improvement of youth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"plato-apology-41","text":"Tell the judges, then, who is their improver; for you must know, as you\r have taken the pains to discover their corrupter, and are citing and\r accusing me before them. Speak, then, and tell the judges who their\r improver is.—Observe, Meletus, that you are silent, and have nothing to\r say. But is not this rather disgraceful, and a very considerable proof\r of what I was saying, that you have no interest in the matter? Speak\r up, friend, and tell us who their improver is.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"plato-apology-42","text":"But that, my good sir, is not my meaning. I want to know who the person\r is, who, in the first place, knows the laws.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"plato-apology-43","text":"What, do you mean to say, Meletus, that they are able to instruct and\r improve youth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"plato-apology-44","text":"By the goddess Here, that is good news! There are plenty of improvers,\r then. And what do you say of the audience,—do they improve them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"plato-apology-45","text":"But perhaps the members of the assembly corrupt them?—or do they too\r improve them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"plato-apology-46","text":"Then every Athenian improves and elevates them; all with the exception\r of myself; and I alone am their corrupter? Is that what you affirm?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"plato-apology-47","text":"I am very unfortunate if you are right. But suppose I ask you a\r question: How about horses? Does one man do them harm and all the world\r good? Is not the exact opposite the truth? One man is able to do them\r good, or at least not many;—the trainer of horses, that is to say, does\r them good, and others who have to do with them rather injure them? Is\r not that true, Meletus, of horses, or of any other animals? Most\r assuredly it is; whether you and Anytus say yes or no. Happy indeed\r would be the condition of youth if they had one corrupter only, and all\r the rest of the world were their improv","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"plato-apology-48","text":"And now, Meletus, I will ask you another question—by Zeus I will: Which\r is better, to live among bad citizens, or among good ones? Answer,\r friend, I say; the question is one which may be easily answered. Do not\r the good do their neighbours good, and the bad do them evil?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"plato-apology-49","text":"And is there anyone who would rather be injured than benefited by those\r who live with him? Answer, my good friend, the law requires you to\r answer—does any one like to be injured?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"plato-apology-50","text":"And when you accuse me of corrupting and deteriorating the youth, do\r you allege that I corrupt them intentionally or unintentionally?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"plato-apology-51","text":"But you have just admitted that the good do their neighbours good, and\r the evil do them evil. Now, is that a truth which your superior wisdom\r has recognized thus early in life, and am I, at my age, in such\r darkness and ignorance as not to know that if a man with whom I have to\r live is corrupted by me, I am very likely to be harmed by him; and yet\r I corrupt him, and intentionally, too—so you say, although neither I\r nor any other human being is ever likely to be convinced by you. But\r either I do not corrupt them, or I corrupt them unintentionally; and on\r either view of the case you lie. ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"plato-apology-52","text":"It will be very clear to you, Athenians, as I was saying, that Meletus\r has no care at all, great or small, about the matter. But still I\r should like to know, Meletus, in what I am affirmed to corrupt the\r young. I suppose you mean, as I infer from your indictment, that I\r teach them not to acknowledge the gods which the state acknowledges,\r but some other new divinities or spiritual agencies in their stead.\r These are the lessons by which I corrupt the youth, as you say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"plato-apology-53","text":"Then, by the gods, Meletus, of whom we are speaking, tell me and the\r court, in somewhat plainer terms, what you mean! for I do not as yet\r understand whether you affirm that I teach other men to acknowledge\r some gods, and therefore that I do believe in gods, and am not an\r entire atheist—this you do not lay to my charge,—but only you say that\r they are not the same gods which the city recognizes—the charge is that\r they are different gods. Or, do you mean that I am an atheist simply,\r and a teacher of atheism?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"plato-apology-54","text":"What an extraordinary statement! Why do you think so, Meletus? Do you\r mean that I do not believe in the godhead of the sun or moon, like\r other men?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"plato-apology-55","text":"I assure you, judges, that he does not: for he says that the sun is\r stone, and the moon earth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"plato-apology-56","text":"Friend Meletus, you think that you are accusing Anaxagoras: and you\r have but a bad opinion of the judges, if you fancy them illiterate to\r such a degree as not to know that these doctrines are found in the\r books of Anaxagoras the Clazomenian, which are full of them. And so,\r forsooth, the youth are said to be taught them by Socrates, when there\r are not unfrequently exhibitions of them at the theatre (Probably in\r allusion to Aristophanes who caricatured, and to Euripides who borrowed\r the notions of Anaxagoras, as well as to other dramatic poets.) (price\r of admission one drachma at the mos","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"plato-apology-57","text":"Nobody will believe you, Meletus, and I am pretty sure that you do not\r believe yourself. I cannot help thinking, men of Athens, that Meletus\r is reckless and impudent, and that he has written this indictment in a\r spirit of mere wantonness and youthful bravado. Has he not compounded a\r riddle, thinking to try me? He said to himself:—I shall see whether the\r wise Socrates will discover my facetious contradiction, or whether I\r shall be able to deceive him and the rest of them. For he certainly\r does appear to me to contradict himself in the indictment as much as if\r he said that Socrates is gu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"plato-apology-58","text":"I should like you, O men of Athens, to join me in examining what I\r conceive to be his inconsistency; and do you, Meletus, answer. And I\r must remind the audience of my request that they would not make a\r disturbance if I speak in my accustomed manner:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"plato-apology-59","text":"Did ever man, Meletus, believe in the existence of human things, and\r not of human beings?...I wish, men of Athens, that he would answer, and\r not be always trying to get up an interruption. Did ever any man\r believe in horsemanship, and not in horses? or in flute-playing, and\r not in flute-players? No, my friend; I will answer to you and to the\r court, as you refuse to answer for yourself. There is no man who ever\r did. But now please to answer the next question: Can a man believe in\r spiritual and divine agencies, and not in spirits or demigods?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"plato-apology-60","text":"How lucky I am to have extracted that answer, by the assistance of the\r court! But then you swear in the indictment that I teach and believe in\r divine or spiritual agencies (new or old, no matter for that); at any\r rate, I believe in spiritual agencies,—so you say and swear in the\r affidavit; and yet if I believe in divine beings, how can I help\r believing in spirits or demigods;—must I not? To be sure I must; and\r therefore I may assume that your silence gives consent. Now what are\r spirits or demigods? Are they not either gods or the sons of gods?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"plato-apology-61","text":"But this is what I call the facetious riddle invented by you: the\r demigods or spirits are gods, and you say first that I do not believe\r in gods, and then again that I do believe in gods; that is, if I\r believe in demigods. For if the demigods are the illegitimate sons of\r gods, whether by the nymphs or by any other mothers, of whom they are\r said to be the sons—what human being will ever believe that there are\r no gods if they are the sons of gods? You might as well affirm the\r existence of mules, and deny that of horses and asses. Such nonsense,\r Meletus, could only have been intended by yo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"plato-apology-62","text":"I have said enough in answer to the charge of Meletus: any elaborate\r defence is unnecessary, but I know only too well how many are the\r enmities which I have incurred, and this is what will be my destruction\r if I am destroyed;—not Meletus, nor yet Anytus, but the envy and\r detraction of the world, which has been the death of many good men, and\r will probably be the death of many more; there is no danger of my being\r the last of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"plato-apology-63","text":"Some one will say: And are you not ashamed, Socrates, of a course of\r life which is likely to bring you to an untimely end? To him I may\r fairly answer: There you are mistaken: a man who is good for anything\r ought not to calculate the chance of living or dying; he ought only to\r consider whether in doing anything he is doing right or wrong—acting\r the part of a good man or of a bad. Whereas, upon your view, the heroes\r who fell at Troy were not good for much, and the son of Thetis above\r all, who altogether despised danger in comparison with disgrace; and\r when he was so eager to slay Hector,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"plato-apology-64","text":"Strange, indeed, would be my conduct, O men of Athens, if I who, when I\r was ordered by the generals whom you chose to command me at Potidaea\r and Amphipolis and Delium, remained where they placed me, like any\r other man, facing death—if now, when, as I conceive and imagine, God\r orders me to fulfil the philosopher’s mission of searching into myself\r and other men, I were to desert my post through fear of death, or any\r other fear; that would indeed be strange, and I might justly be\r arraigned in court for denying the existence of the gods, if I\r disobeyed the oracle because I was afraid of de","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"plato-apology-65","text":"Men of Athens, do not interrupt, but hear me; there was an\r understanding between us that you should hear me to the end: I have\r something more to say, at which you may be inclined to cry out; but I\r believe that to hear me will be good for you, and therefore I beg that\r you will not cry out. I would have you know, that if you kill such an\r one as I am, you will injure yourselves more than you will injure me.\r Nothing will injure me, not Meletus nor yet Anytus—they cannot, for a\r bad man is not permitted to injure a better than himself. I do not deny\r that Anytus may, perhaps, kill him, or dri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"plato-apology-66","text":"And now, Athenians, I am not going to argue for my own sake, as you may\r think, but for yours, that you may not sin against the God by\r condemning me, who am his gift to you. For if you kill me you will not\r easily find a successor to me, who, if I may use such a ludicrous\r figure of speech, am a sort of gadfly, given to the state by God; and\r the state is a great and noble steed who is tardy in his motions owing\r to his very size, and requires to be stirred into life. I am that\r gadfly which God has attached to the state, and all day long and in all\r places am always fastening upon you, arous","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"plato-apology-67","text":"Some one may wonder why I go about in private giving advice and busying\r myself with the concerns of others, but do not venture to come forward\r in public and advise the state. I will tell you why. You have heard me\r speak at sundry times and in divers places of an oracle or sign which\r comes to me, and is the divinity which Meletus ridicules in the\r indictment. This sign, which is a kind of voice, first began to come to\r me when I was a child; it always forbids but never commands me to do\r anything which I am going to do. This is what deters me from being a\r politician. And rightly, as I thin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"plato-apology-68","text":"I can give you convincing evidence of what I say, not words only, but\r what you value far more—actions. Let me relate to you a passage of my\r own life which will prove to you that I should never have yielded to\r injustice from any fear of death, and that “as I should have refused to\r yield” I must have died at once. I will tell you a tale of the courts,\r not very interesting perhaps, but nevertheless true. The only office of\r state which I ever held, O men of Athens, was that of senator: the\r tribe Antiochis, which is my tribe, had the presidency at the trial of\r the generals who had not taken","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"plato-apology-69","text":"Now do you really imagine that I could have survived all these years,\r if I had led a public life, supposing that like a good man I had always\r maintained the right and had made justice, as I ought, the first thing?\r No indeed, men of Athens, neither I nor any other man. But I have been\r always the same in all my actions, public as well as private, and never\r have I yielded any base compliance to those who are slanderously termed\r my disciples, or to any other. Not that I have any regular disciples.\r But if any one likes to come and hear me while I am pursuing my\r mission, whether he be young ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"plato-apology-70","text":"But I shall be asked, Why do people delight in continually conversing\r with you? I have told you already, Athenians, the whole truth about\r this matter: they like to hear the cross-examination of the pretenders\r to wisdom; there is amusement in it. Now this duty of cross-examining\r other men has been imposed upon me by God; and has been signified to me\r by oracles, visions, and in every way in which the will of divine power\r was ever intimated to any one. This is true, O Athenians, or, if not\r true, would be soon refuted. If I am or have been corrupting the youth,\r those of them who are now gr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"plato-apology-71","text":"Well, Athenians, this and the like of this is all the defence which I\r have to offer. Yet a word more. Perhaps there may be some one who is\r offended at me, when he calls to mind how he himself on a similar, or\r even a less serious occasion, prayed and entreated the judges with many\r tears, and how he produced his children in court, which was a moving\r spectacle, together with a host of relations and friends; whereas I,\r who am probably in danger of my life, will do none of these things. The\r contrast may occur to his mind, and he may be set against me, and vote\r in anger because he is displea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"plato-apology-72","text":"But, setting aside the question of public opinion, there seems to be\r something wrong in asking a favour of a judge, and thus procuring an\r acquittal, instead of informing and convincing him. For his duty is,\r not to make a present of justice, but to give judgment; and he has\r sworn that he will judge according to the laws, and not according to\r his own good pleasure; and we ought not to encourage you, nor should\r you allow yourselves to be encouraged, in this habit of perjury—there\r can be no piety in that. Do not then require me to do what I consider\r dishonourable and impious and wrong, esp","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"plato-apology-73","text":"There are many reasons why I am not grieved, O men of Athens, at the\r vote of condemnation. I expected it, and am only surprised that the\r votes are so nearly equal; for I had thought that the majority against\r me would have been far larger; but now, had thirty votes gone over to\r the other side, I should have been acquitted. And I may say, I think,\r that I have escaped Meletus. I may say more; for without the assistance\r of Anytus and Lycon, any one may see that he would not have had a fifth\r part of the votes, as the law requires, in which case he would have\r incurred a fine of a thousand dr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"plato-apology-74","text":"And so he proposes death as the penalty. And what shall I propose on my\r part, O men of Athens? Clearly that which is my due. And what is my\r due? What return shall be made to the man who has never had the wit to\r be idle during his whole life; but has been careless of what the many\r care for—wealth, and family interests, and military offices, and\r speaking in the assembly, and magistracies, and plots, and parties.\r Reflecting that I was really too honest a man to be a politician and\r live, I did not go where I could do no good to you or to myself; but\r where I could do the greatest good priva","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"plato-apology-75","text":"Perhaps you think that I am braving you in what I am saying now, as in\r what I said before about the tears and prayers. But this is not so. I\r speak rather because I am convinced that I never intentionally wronged\r any one, although I cannot convince you—the time has been too short; if\r there were a law at Athens, as there is in other cities, that a capital\r cause should not be decided in one day, then I believe that I should\r have convinced you. But I cannot in a moment refute great slanders;\r and, as I am convinced that I never wronged another, I will assuredly\r not wrong myself. I will not ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"plato-apology-76","text":"Some one will say: Yes, Socrates, but cannot you hold your tongue, and\r then you may go into a foreign city, and no one will interfere with\r you? Now I have great difficulty in making you understand my answer to\r this. For if I tell you that to do as you say would be a disobedience\r to the God, and therefore that I cannot hold my tongue, you will not\r believe that I am serious; and if I say again that daily to discourse\r about virtue, and of those other things about which you hear me\r examining myself and others, is the greatest good of man, and that the\r unexamined life is not worth living, y","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"plato-apology-77","text":"Not much time will be gained, O Athenians, in return for the evil name\r which you will get from the detractors of the city, who will say that\r you killed Socrates, a wise man; for they will call me wise, even\r although I am not wise, when they want to reproach you. If you had\r waited a little while, your desire would have been fulfilled in the\r course of nature. For I am far advanced in years, as you may perceive,\r and not far from death. I am speaking now not to all of you, but only\r to those who have condemned me to death. And I have another thing to\r say to them: you think that I was convic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"plato-apology-78","text":"And now, O men who have condemned me, I would fain prophesy to you; for\r I am about to die, and in the hour of death men are gifted with\r prophetic power. And I prophesy to you who are my murderers, that\r immediately after my departure punishment far heavier than you have\r inflicted on me will surely await you. Me you have killed because you\r wanted to escape the accuser, and not to give an account of your lives.\r But that will not be as you suppose: far otherwise. For I say that\r there will be more accusers of you than there are now; accusers whom\r hitherto I have restrained: and as they are ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"plato-apology-79","text":"Friends, who would have acquitted me, I would like also to talk with\r you about the thing which has come to pass, while the magistrates are\r busy, and before I go to the place at which I must die. Stay then a\r little, for we may as well talk with one another while there is time.\r You are my friends, and I should like to show you the meaning of this\r event which has happened to me. O my judges—for you I may truly call\r judges—I should like to tell you of a wonderful circumstance. Hitherto\r the divine faculty of which the internal oracle is the source has\r constantly been in the habit of opposin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"plato-apology-80","text":"Let us reflect in another way, and we shall see that there is great\r reason to hope that death is a good; for one of two things—either death\r is a state of nothingness and utter unconsciousness, or, as men say,\r there is a change and migration of the soul from this world to another.\r Now if you suppose that there is no consciousness, but a sleep like the\r sleep of him who is undisturbed even by dreams, death will be an\r unspeakable gain. For if a person were to select the night in which his\r sleep was undisturbed even by dreams, and were to compare with this the\r other days and nights of his l","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"plato-apology-81","text":"Wherefore, O judges, be of good cheer about death, and know of a\r certainty, that no evil can happen to a good man, either in life or\r after death. He and his are not neglected by the gods; nor has my own\r approaching end happened by mere chance. But I see clearly that the\r time had arrived when it was better for me to die and be released from\r trouble; wherefore the oracle gave no sign. For which reason, also, I\r am not angry with my condemners, or with my accusers; they have done me\r no harm, although they did not mean to do me any good; and for this I\r may gently blame them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"81"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"plato-apology-82","text":"Still I have a favour to ask of them. When my sons are grown up, I\r would ask you, O my friends, to punish them; and I would have you\r trouble them, as I have troubled you, if they seem to care about\r riches, or anything, more than about virtue; or if they pretend to be\r something when they are really nothing,—then reprove them, as I have\r reproved you, for not caring about that for which they ought to care,\r and thinking that they are something when they are really nothing. And\r if you do this, both I and my sons will have received justice at your\r hands.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"plato-apology-83","text":"The hour of departure has arrived, and we go our ways—I to die, and you\r to live. Which is better God only knows.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Apology (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Apology","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"plato-phaedo-1","text":"After an interval of some months or years, and at Phlius, a town of\r Peloponnesus, the tale of the last hours of Socrates is narrated to\r Echecrates and other Phliasians by Phaedo the 'beloved disciple.' The\r Dialogue necessarily takes the form of a narrative, because Socrates has\r to be described acting as well as speaking. The minutest particulars of\r the event are interesting to distant friends, and the narrator has an\r equal interest in them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"1"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"plato-phaedo-2","text":"During the voyage of the sacred ship to and from Delos, which has\r occupied thirty days, the execution of Socrates has been deferred.\r (Compare Xen. Mem.) The time has been passed by him in conversation with\r a select company of disciples. But now the holy season is over, and the\r disciples meet earlier than usual in order that they may converse with\r Socrates for the last time. Those who were present, and those who might\r have been expected to be present, are mentioned by name. There are\r Simmias and Cebes (Crito), two disciples of Philolaus whom Socrates\r 'by his enchantments has attracted f","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"2"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"plato-phaedo-3","text":"Cebes asks why suicide is thought not to be right, if death is to be\r accounted a good? Well, (1) according to one explanation, because man is\r a prisoner, who must not open the door of his prison and run away--this\r is the truth in a 'mystery.' Or (2) rather, because he is not his own\r property, but a possession of the gods, and has no right to make away\r with that which does not belong to him. But why, asks Cebes, if he is a\r possession of the gods, should he wish to die and leave them? For he is\r under their protection; and surely he cannot take better care of himself\r than they take of him","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"plato-phaedo-4","text":"The philosopher desires death--which the wicked world will insinuate\r that he also deserves: and perhaps he does, but not in any sense which\r they are capable of understanding. Enough of them: the real question\r is, What is the nature of that death which he desires? Death is\r the separation of soul and body--and the philosopher desires such\r a separation. He would like to be freed from the dominion of bodily\r pleasures and of the senses, which are always perturbing his mental\r vision. He wants to get rid of eyes and ears, and with the light of the\r mind only to behold the light of truth. All t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"plato-phaedo-5","text":"Besides, the philosopher has notions of good and evil unlike those of\r other men. For they are courageous because they are afraid of greater\r dangers, and temperate because they desire greater pleasures. But he\r disdains this balancing of pleasures and pains, which is the exchange\r of commerce and not of virtue. All the virtues, including wisdom, are\r regarded by him only as purifications of the soul. And this was the\r meaning of the founders of the mysteries when they said, 'Many are the\r wand-bearers but few are the mystics.' (Compare Matt. xxii.: 'Many are\r called but few are chosen.') And ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"plato-phaedo-6","text":"Still, a fear is expressed that the soul upon leaving the body may\r vanish away like smoke or air. Socrates in answer appeals first of all\r to the old Orphic tradition that the souls of the dead are in the world\r below, and that the living come from them. This he attempts to found\r on a philosophical assumption that all opposites--e.g. less, greater;\r weaker, stronger; sleeping, waking; life, death--are generated out of\r each other. Nor can the process of generation be only a passage from\r living to dying, for then all would end in death. The perpetual sleeper\r (Endymion) would be no longer di","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"plato-phaedo-7","text":"The Platonic doctrine of reminiscence is then adduced as a confirmation\r of the pre-existence of the soul. Some proofs of this doctrine are\r demanded. One proof given is the same as that of the Meno, and is\r derived from the latent knowledge of mathematics, which may be elicited\r from an unlearned person when a diagram is presented to him. Again,\r there is a power of association, which from seeing Simmias may remember\r Cebes, or from seeing a picture of Simmias may remember Simmias. The\r lyre may recall the player of the lyre, and equal pieces of wood or\r stone may be associated with the highe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"plato-phaedo-8","text":"It is objected by Simmias and Cebes that these arguments only prove a\r former and not a future existence. Socrates answers this objection by\r recalling the previous argument, in which he had shown that the living\r come from the dead. But the fear that the soul at departing may vanish\r into air (especially if there is a wind blowing at the time) has not yet\r been charmed away. He proceeds: When we fear that the soul will vanish\r away, let us ask ourselves what is that which we suppose to be liable\r to dissolution? Is it the simple or the compound, the unchanging or the\r changing, the invisible ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"plato-phaedo-9","text":"But the soul which is polluted and engrossed by the corporeal, and has\r no eye except that of the senses, and is weighed down by the bodily\r appetites, cannot attain to this abstraction. In her fear of the world\r below she lingers about the sepulchre, loath to leave the body which\r she loved, a ghostly apparition, saturated with sense, and therefore\r visible. At length entering into some animal of a nature congenial to\r her former life of sensuality or violence, she takes the form of an ass,\r a wolf or a kite. And of these earthly souls the happiest are those who\r have practised virtue without","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"plato-phaedo-10","text":"Simmias and Cebes remain in doubt; but they are unwilling to raise\r objections at such a time. Socrates wonders at their reluctance. Let\r them regard him rather as the swan, who, having sung the praises of\r Apollo all his life long, sings at his death more lustily than ever.\r Simmias acknowledges that there is cowardice in not probing truth to the\r bottom. 'And if truth divine and inspired is not to be had, then let\r a man take the best of human notions, and upon this frail bark let him\r sail through life.' He proceeds to state his difficulty: It has been\r argued that the soul is invisible and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"plato-phaedo-11","text":"The audience, like the chorus in a play, for a moment interpret the\r feelings of the actors; there is a temporary depression, and then the\r enquiry is resumed. It is a melancholy reflection that arguments, like\r men, are apt to be deceivers; and those who have been often deceived\r become distrustful both of arguments and of friends. But this\r unfortunate experience should not make us either haters of men or haters\r of arguments. The want of health and truth is not in the argument, but\r in ourselves. Socrates, who is about to die, is sensible of his own\r weakness; he desires to be impartial, bu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"plato-phaedo-12","text":"At his request Simmias and Cebes repeat their objections. They do not\r go to the length of denying the pre-existence of ideas. Simmias is of\r opinion that the soul is a harmony of the body. But the admission of the\r pre-existence of ideas, and therefore of the soul, is at variance with\r this. (Compare a parallel difficulty in Theaet.) For a harmony is\r an effect, whereas the soul is not an effect, but a cause; a harmony\r follows, but the soul leads; a harmony admits of degrees, and the soul\r has no degrees. Again, upon the supposition that the soul is a harmony,\r why is one soul better than an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"plato-phaedo-13","text":"The goddess Harmonia, as Socrates playfully terms the argument of\r Simmias, has been happily disposed of; and now an answer has to be given\r to the Theban Cadmus. Socrates recapitulates the argument of Cebes,\r which, as he remarks, involves the whole question of natural growth or\r causation; about this he proposes to narrate his own mental experience.\r When he was young he had puzzled himself with physics: he had enquired\r into the growth and decay of animals, and the origin of thought, until\r at last he began to doubt the self-evident fact that growth is the\r result of eating and drinking; an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"plato-phaedo-14","text":"Then he heard some one reading out of a book of Anaxagoras, that mind is\r the cause of all things. And he said to himself: If mind is the cause\r of all things, surely mind must dispose them all for the best. The new\r teacher will show me this 'order of the best' in man and nature. How\r great had been his hopes and how great his disappointment! For he found\r that his new friend was anything but consistent in his use of mind as\r a cause, and that he soon introduced winds, waters, and other eccentric\r notions. (Compare Arist. Metaph.) It was as if a person had said that\r Socrates is sitting here ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"plato-phaedo-15","text":"Now there is a danger in the contemplation of the nature of things, as\r there is a danger in looking at the sun during an eclipse, unless the\r precaution is taken of looking only at the image reflected in the water,\r or in a glass. (Compare Laws; Republic.) 'I was afraid,' says Socrates,\r 'that I might injure the eye of the soul. I thought that I had better\r return to the old and safe method of ideas. Though I do not mean to say\r that he who contemplates existence through the medium of ideas sees\r only through a glass darkly, any more than he who contemplates actual\r effects.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"plato-phaedo-16","text":"If the existence of ideas is granted to him, Socrates is of opinion that\r he will then have no difficulty in proving the immortality of the soul.\r He will only ask for a further admission:--that beauty is the cause of\r the beautiful, greatness the cause of the great, smallness of the small,\r and so on of other things. This is a safe and simple answer, which\r escapes the contradictions of greater and less (greater by reason of\r that which is smaller!), of addition and subtraction, and the other\r difficulties of relation. These subtleties he is for leaving to wiser\r heads than his own; he prefer","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"plato-phaedo-17","text":"The doctrine of ideas, which has long ago received the assent of the\r Socratic circle, is now affirmed by the Phliasian auditor to command\r the assent of any man of sense. The narrative is continued; Socrates is\r desirous of explaining how opposite ideas may appear to co-exist but do\r not really co-exist in the same thing or person. For example, Simmias\r may be said to have greatness and also smallness, because he is greater\r than Socrates and less than Phaedo. And yet Simmias is not really great\r and also small, but only when compared to Phaedo and Socrates. I use the\r illustration, says Socr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"plato-phaedo-18","text":"One of the company here remarked that this was inconsistent with the\r old assertion that opposites generated opposites. But that, replies\r Socrates, was affirmed, not of opposite ideas either in us or in\r nature, but of opposition in the concrete--not of life and death, but\r of individuals living and dying. When this objection has been removed,\r Socrates proceeds: This doctrine of the mutual exclusion of opposites\r is not only true of the opposites themselves, but of things which are\r inseparable from them. For example, cold and heat are opposed; and fire,\r which is inseparable from heat, cann","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"plato-phaedo-19","text":"Thus all objections appear to be finally silenced. And now the\r application has to be made: If the soul is immortal, 'what manner of\r persons ought we to be?' having regard not only to time but to eternity.\r For death is not the end of all, and the wicked is not released from his\r evil by death; but every one carries with him into the world below that\r which he is or has become, and that only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"19"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"plato-phaedo-20","text":"For after death the soul is carried away to judgment, and when she has\r received her punishment returns to earth in the course of ages. The wise\r soul is conscious of her situation, and follows the attendant angel who\r guides her through the windings of the world below; but the impure soul\r wanders hither and thither without companion or guide, and is carried\r at last to her own place, as the pure soul is also carried away to hers.\r 'In order that you may understand this, I must first describe to you the\r nature and conformation of the earth.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"plato-phaedo-21","text":"Now the whole earth is a globe placed in the centre of the heavens, and\r is maintained there by the perfection of balance. That which we call the\r earth is only one of many small hollows, wherein collect the mists and\r waters and the thick lower air; but the true earth is above, and is in\r a finer and subtler element. And if, like birds, we could fly to the\r surface of the air, in the same manner that fishes come to the top of\r the sea, then we should behold the true earth and the true heaven and\r the true stars. Our earth is everywhere corrupted and corroded; and even\r the land which is faire","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"plato-phaedo-22","text":"The hollows on the surface of the globe vary in size and shape from that\r which we inhabit: but all are connected by passages and perforations in\r the interior of the earth. And there is one huge chasm or opening called\r Tartarus, into which streams of fire and water and liquid mud are ever\r flowing; of these small portions find their way to the surface and\r form seas and rivers and volcanoes. There is a perpetual inhalation and\r exhalation of the air rising and falling as the waters pass into the\r depths of the earth and return again, in their course forming lakes\r and rivers, but never desce","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"plato-phaedo-23","text":"The dead are first of all judged according to their deeds, and those who\r are incurable are thrust into Tartarus, from which they never come out.\r Those who have only committed venial sins are first purified of them,\r and then rewarded for the good which they have done. Those who have\r committed crimes, great indeed, but not unpardonable, are thrust\r into Tartarus, but are cast forth at the end of a year by way of\r Pyriphlegethon or Cocytus, and these carry them as far as the Acherusian\r lake, where they call upon their victims to let them come out of the\r rivers into the lake. And if they pre","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"plato-phaedo-24","text":"Socrates is not prepared to insist on the literal accuracy of this\r description, but he is confident that something of the kind is true.\r He who has sought after the pleasures of knowledge and rejected the\r pleasures of the body, has reason to be of good hope at the approach of\r death; whose voice is already speaking to him, and who will one day be\r heard calling all men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"plato-phaedo-25","text":"The hour has come at which he must drink the poison, and not much\r remains to be done. How shall they bury him? That is a question which he\r refuses to entertain, for they are burying, not him, but his dead body.\r His friends had once been sureties that he would remain, and they shall\r now be sureties that he has run away. Yet he would not die without the\r customary ceremonies of washing and burial. Shall he make a libation of\r the poison? In the spirit he will, but not in the letter. One request he\r utters in the very act of death, which has been a puzzle to after ages.\r With a sort of irony ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"plato-phaedo-26","text":"1. The doctrine of the immortality of the soul has sunk deep into\r the heart of the human race; and men are apt to rebel against any\r examination of the nature or grounds of their belief. They do not like\r to acknowledge that this, as well as the other 'eternal ideas; of\r man, has a history in time, which may be traced in Greek poetry or\r philosophy, and also in the Hebrew Scriptures. They convert feeling into\r reasoning, and throw a network of dialectics over that which is really\r a deeply-rooted instinct. In the same temper which Socrates reproves in\r himself they are disposed to think that ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"plato-phaedo-27","text":"2. In former ages there was a customary rather than a reasoned belief\r in the immortality of the soul. It was based on the authority of the\r Church, on the necessity of such a belief to morality and the order of\r society, on the evidence of an historical fact, and also on analogies\r and figures of speech which filled up the void or gave an expression\r in words to a cherished instinct. The mass of mankind went on their\r way busy with the affairs of this life, hardly stopping to think about\r another. But in our own day the question has been reopened, and it is\r doubtful whether the belief which ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"plato-phaedo-28","text":"3. At the outset of the discussion we may clear away a confusion. We\r certainly do not mean by the immortality of the soul the immortality of\r fame, which whether worth having or not can only be ascribed to a very\r select class of the whole race of mankind, and even the interest in\r these few is comparatively short-lived. To have been a benefactor to the\r world, whether in a higher or a lower sphere of life and thought, is a\r great thing: to have the reputation of being one, when men have passed\r out of the sphere of earthly praise or blame, is hardly worthy of\r consideration. The memory of a ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"plato-phaedo-29","text":"4. Modern philosophy is perplexed at this whole question, which is\r sometimes fairly given up and handed over to the realm of faith. The\r perplexity should not be forgotten by us when we attempt to submit the\r Phaedo of Plato to the requirements of logic. For what idea can we form\r of the soul when separated from the body? Or how can the soul be united\r with the body and still be independent? Is the soul related to the\r body as the ideal to the real, or as the whole to the parts, or as the\r subject to the object, or as the cause to the effect, or as the end to\r the means? Shall we say with Ari","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"plato-phaedo-30","text":"5. Again, believing in the immortality of the soul, we must still\r ask the question of Socrates, 'What is that which we suppose to be\r immortal?' Is it the personal and individual element in us, or the\r spiritual and universal? Is it the principle of knowledge or of\r goodness, or the union of the two? Is it the mere force of life which is\r determined to be, or the consciousness of self which cannot be got rid\r of, or the fire of genius which refuses to be extinguished? Or is there\r a hidden being which is allied to the Author of all existence, who is\r because he is perfect, and to whom our ide","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"plato-phaedo-31","text":"There are some other questions which are disturbing to us because we\r have no answer to them. What is to become of the animals in a future\r state? Have we not seen dogs more faithful and intelligent than men,\r and men who are more stupid and brutal than any animals? Does their life\r cease at death, or is there some 'better thing reserved' also for\r them? They may be said to have a shadow or imitation of morality, and\r imperfect moral claims upon the benevolence of man and upon the justice\r of God. We cannot think of the least or lowest of them, the insect, the\r bird, the inhabitants of the sea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"plato-phaedo-32","text":"6. Again, ideas must be given through something; and we are always prone\r to argue about the soul from analogies of outward things which may serve\r to embody our thoughts, but are also partly delusive. For we cannot\r reason from the natural to the spiritual, or from the outward to the\r inward. The progress of physiological science, without bringing us\r nearer to the great secret, has tended to remove some erroneous notions\r respecting the relations of body and mind, and in this we have the\r advantage of the ancients. But no one imagines that any seed of\r immortality is to be discerned in our m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"plato-phaedo-33","text":"7. When we speak of the immortality of the soul, we must ask further\r what we mean by the word immortality. For of the duration of a living\r being in countless ages we can form no conception; far less than a three\r years' old child of the whole of life. The naked eye might as well try\r to see the furthest star in the infinity of heaven. Whether time and\r space really exist when we take away the limits of them may be doubted;\r at any rate the thought of them when unlimited us so overwhelming to us\r as to lose all distinctness. Philosophers have spoken of them as forms\r of the human mind, but wh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"plato-phaedo-34","text":"8. Another life must be described, if at all, in forms of thought\r and not of sense. To draw pictures of heaven and hell, whether in the\r language of Scripture or any other, adds nothing to our real knowledge,\r but may perhaps disguise our ignorance. The truest conception which\r we can form of a future life is a state of progress or education--a\r progress from evil to good, from ignorance to knowledge. To this we are\r led by the analogy of the present life, in which we see different races\r and nations of men, and different men and women of the same nation,\r in various states or stages of culti","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"plato-phaedo-35","text":"For we do not argue merely from the analogy of the present state of this\r world to another, but from the analogy of a probable future to which we\r are tending. The greatest changes of which we have had experience as yet\r are due to our increasing knowledge of history and of nature. They\r have been produced by a few minds appearing in three or four favoured\r nations, in a comparatively short period of time. May we be allowed to\r imagine the minds of men everywhere working together during many ages\r for the completion of our knowledge? May not the science of physiology\r transform the world? Agai","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"plato-phaedo-36","text":"Nothing therefore, either in the present state of man or in the\r tendencies of the future, as far as we can entertain conjecture of them,\r would lead us to suppose that God governs us vindictively in this\r world, and therefore we have no reason to infer that he will govern us\r vindictively in another. The true argument from analogy is not, 'This\r life is a mixed state of justice and injustice, of great waste, of\r sudden casualties, of disproportionate punishments, and therefore the\r like inconsistencies, irregularities, injustices are to be expected\r in another;' but 'This life is subject to l","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"plato-phaedo-37","text":"9. But some one will say: That we cannot reason from the seen to the\r unseen, and that we are creating another world after the image of this,\r just as men in former ages have created gods in their own likeness. And\r we, like the companions of Socrates, may feel discouraged at hearing\r our favourite 'argument from analogy' thus summarily disposed of. Like\r himself, too, we may adduce other arguments in which he seems to have\r anticipated us, though he expresses them in different language. For we\r feel that the soul partakes of the ideal and invisible; and can never\r fall into the error of confu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"plato-phaedo-38","text":"10. The last ground of our belief in immortality, and the strongest, is\r the perfection of the divine nature. The mere fact of the existence of\r God does not tend to show the continued existence of man. An evil God\r or an indifferent God might have had the power, but not the will, to\r preserve us. He might have regarded us as fitted to minister to his\r service by a succession of existences,--like the animals, without\r attributing to each soul an incomparable value. But if he is perfect,\r he must will that all rational beings should partake of that perfection\r which he himself is. In the words ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"plato-phaedo-39","text":"In speaking of divine perfection, we mean to say that God is just and\r true and loving, the author of order and not of disorder, of good and\r not of evil. Or rather, that he is justice, that he is truth, that he\r is love, that he is order, that he is the very progress of which we were\r speaking; and that wherever these qualities are present, whether in the\r human soul or in the order of nature, there is God. We might still see\r him everywhere, if we had not been mistakenly seeking for him apart from\r us, instead of in us; away from the laws of nature, instead of in\r them. And we become united ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"plato-phaedo-40","text":"Thus the belief in the immortality of the soul rests at last on the\r belief in God. If there is a good and wise God, then there is a progress\r of mankind towards perfection; and if there is no progress of men\r towards perfection, then there is no good and wise God. We cannot\r suppose that the moral government of God of which we see the beginnings\r in the world and in ourselves will cease when we pass out of life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"plato-phaedo-41","text":"11. Considering the 'feebleness of the human faculties and the\r uncertainty of the subject,' we are inclined to believe that the fewer\r our words the better. At the approach of death there is not much said;\r good men are too honest to go out of the world professing more than they\r know. There is perhaps no important subject about which, at any time,\r even religious people speak so little to one another. In the fulness\r of life the thought of death is mostly awakened by the sight or\r recollection of the death of others rather than by the prospect of our\r own. We must also acknowledge that there","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"plato-phaedo-42","text":"But besides differences of theological opinion which must ever prevail\r about things unseen, the hope of immortality is weaker or stronger in\r men at one time of life than at another; it even varies from day to day.\r It comes and goes; the mind, like the sky, is apt to be overclouded.\r Other generations of men may have sometimes lived under an 'eclipse of\r faith,' to us the total disappearance of it might be compared to the\r 'sun falling from heaven.' And we may sometimes have to begin again and\r acquire the belief for ourselves; or to win it back again when it is\r lost. It is really weakest i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"plato-phaedo-43","text":"12. When we think of God and of man in his relation to God; of the\r imperfection of our present state and yet of the progress which is\r observable in the history of the world and of the human mind; of the\r depth and power of our moral ideas which seem to partake of the very\r nature of God Himself; when we consider the contrast between the\r physical laws to which we are subject and the higher law which raises us\r above them and is yet a part of them; when we reflect on our capacity of\r becoming the 'spectators of all time and all existence,' and of framing\r in our own minds the ideal of a perfe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"plato-phaedo-44","text":"13. It is well also that we should sometimes think of the forms of\r thought under which the idea of immortality is most naturally presented\r to us. It is clear that to our minds the risen soul can no longer be\r described, as in a picture, by the symbol of a creature half-bird,\r half-human, nor in any other form of sense. The multitude of angels, as\r in Milton, singing the Almighty's praises, are a noble image, and may\r furnish a theme for the poet or the painter, but they are no longer an\r adequate expression of the kingdom of God which is within us. Neither is\r there any mansion, in this worl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"plato-phaedo-45","text":"First of all there is the thought of rest and freedom from pain; they\r have gone home, as the common saying is, and the cares of this world\r touch them no more. Secondly, we may imagine them as they were at\r their best and brightest, humbly fulfilling their daily round of\r duties--selfless, childlike, unaffected by the world; when the eye was\r single and the whole body seemed to be full of light; when the mind was\r clear and saw into the purposes of God. Thirdly, we may think of them\r as possessed by a great love of God and man, working out His will at a\r further stage in the heavenly pilgrima","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"plato-phaedo-46","text":"14. Returning now to the earlier stage of human thought which is\r represented by the writings of Plato, we find that many of the\r same questions have already arisen: there is the same tendency to\r materialism; the same inconsistency in the application of the idea of\r mind; the same doubt whether the soul is to be regarded as a cause or as\r an effect; the same falling back on moral convictions. In the Phaedo the\r soul is conscious of her divine nature, and the separation from the body\r which has been commenced in this life is perfected in another. Beginning\r in mystery, Socrates, in the interme","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"plato-phaedo-47","text":"15. The doctrine of the immortality of the soul was not new to the\r Greeks in the age of Socrates, but, like the unity of God, had a\r foundation in the popular belief. The old Homeric notion of a gibbering\r ghost flitting away to Hades; or of a few illustrious heroes enjoying\r the isles of the blest; or of an existence divided between the two; or\r the Hesiodic, of righteous spirits, who become guardian angels,--had\r given place in the mysteries and the Orphic poets to representations,\r partly fanciful, of a future state of rewards and punishments. (Laws.)\r The reticence of the Greeks on public","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"plato-phaedo-48","text":"16. Yet after all the belief in the individuality of the soul after\r death had but a feeble hold on the Greek mind. Like the personality of\r God, the personality of man in a future state was not inseparably bound\r up with the reality of his existence. For the distinction between the\r personal and impersonal, and also between the divine and human, was far\r less marked to the Greek than to ourselves. And as Plato readily passes\r from the notion of the good to that of God, he also passes almost\r imperceptibly to himself and his reader from the future life of the\r individual soul to the eternal be","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"plato-phaedo-49","text":"17. Living in an age when logic was beginning to mould human thought,\r Plato naturally cast his belief in immortality into a logical form. And\r when we consider how much the doctrine of ideas was also one of words,\r it is not surprising that he should have fallen into verbal fallacies:\r early logic is always mistaking the truth of the form for the truth of\r the matter. It is easy to see that the alternation of opposites is\r not the same as the generation of them out of each other; and that the\r generation of them out of each other, which is the first argument in\r the Phaedo, is at variance wit","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"plato-phaedo-50","text":"18. To deal fairly with such arguments, they should be translated as\r far as possible into their modern equivalents. 'If the ideas of men are\r eternal, their souls are eternal, and if not the ideas, then not the\r souls.' Such an argument stands nearly in the same relation to Plato and\r his age, as the argument from the existence of God to immortality among\r ourselves. 'If God exists, then the soul exists after death; and if\r there is no God, there is no existence of the soul after death.' For\r the ideas are to his mind the reality, the truth, the principle of\r permanence, as well as of intelli","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"plato-phaedo-51","text":"19. The main argument of the Phaedo is derived from the existence of\r eternal ideas of which the soul is a partaker; the other argument of the\r alternation of opposites is replaced by this. And there have not been\r wanting philosophers of the idealist school who have imagined that the\r doctrine of the immortality of the soul is a theory of knowledge, and\r that in what has preceded Plato is accommodating himself to the popular\r belief. Such a view can only be elicited from the Phaedo by what may\r be termed the transcendental method of interpretation, and is obviously\r inconsistent with the Gorg","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"plato-phaedo-52","text":"20. Two arguments of this ethical character occur in the Phaedo. The\r first may be described as the aspiration of the soul after another state\r of being. Like the Oriental or Christian mystic, the philosopher is\r seeking to withdraw from impurities of sense, to leave the world and the\r things of the world, and to find his higher self. Plato recognizes in\r these aspirations the foretaste of immortality; as Butler and Addison in\r modern times have argued, the one from the moral tendencies of mankind,\r the other from the progress of the soul towards perfection. In using\r this argument Plato has c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"plato-phaedo-53","text":"21. The ethical proof of the immortality of the soul is derived from the\r necessity of retribution. The wicked would be too well off if their\r evil deeds came to an end. It is not to be supposed that an Ardiaeus,\r an Archelaus, an Ismenias could ever have suffered the penalty of\r their crimes in this world. The manner in which this retribution is\r accomplished Plato represents under the figures of mythology. Doubtless\r he felt that it was easier to improve than to invent, and that in\r religion especially the traditional form was required in order to give\r verisimilitude to the myth. The myth t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"plato-phaedo-54","text":"The Dialogue must be read in the light of the situation. And first of\r all we are struck by the calmness of the scene. Like the spectators\r at the time, we cannot pity Socrates; his mien and his language are\r so noble and fearless. He is the same that he ever was, but milder and\r gentler, and he has in no degree lost his interest in dialectics;\r he will not forego the delight of an argument in compliance with the\r jailer's intimation that he should not heat himself with talking. At\r such a time he naturally expresses the hope of his life, that he has\r been a true mystic and not a mere retainer","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"plato-phaedo-55","text":"The other persons of the Dialogue may be considered under two heads: (1)\r private friends; (2) the respondents in the argument.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"plato-phaedo-56","text":"First there is Crito, who has been already introduced to us in the\r Euthydemus and the Crito; he is the equal in years of Socrates, and\r stands in quite a different relation to him from his younger disciples.\r He is a man of the world who is rich and prosperous (compare the jest\r in the Euthydemus), the best friend of Socrates, who wants to know his\r commands, in whose presence he talks to his family, and who performs\r the last duty of closing his eyes. It is observable too that, as in the\r Euthydemus, Crito shows no aptitude for philosophical discussions. Nor\r among the friends of Socrates mu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"plato-phaedo-57","text":"Another person who takes no part in the philosophical discussion is the\r excitable Apollodorus, the same who, in the Symposium, of which he is\r the narrator, is called 'the madman,' and who testifies his grief by the\r most violent emotions. Phaedo is also present, the 'beloved disciple'\r as he may be termed, who is described, if not 'leaning on his bosom,'\r as seated next to Socrates, who is playing with his hair. He too, like\r Apollodorus, takes no part in the discussion, but he loves above all\r things to hear and speak of Socrates after his death. The calmness\r of his behaviour, veiling his ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"plato-phaedo-58","text":"The two principal interlocutors are Simmias and Cebes, the disciples of\r Philolaus the Pythagorean philosopher of Thebes. Simmias is described\r in the Phaedrus as fonder of an argument than any man living; and\r Cebes, although finally persuaded by Socrates, is said to be the most\r incredulous of human beings. It is Cebes who at the commencement of\r the Dialogue asks why 'suicide is held to be unlawful,' and who\r first supplies the doctrine of recollection in confirmation of the\r pre-existence of the soul. It is Cebes who urges that the pre-existence\r does not necessarily involve the future exi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"plato-phaedo-59","text":"Other persons, Menexenus, Ctesippus, Lysis, are old friends; Evenus\r has been already satirized in the Apology; Aeschines and Epigenes\r were present at the trial; Euclid and Terpsion will reappear in the\r Introduction to the Theaetetus, Hermogenes has already appeared in\r the Cratylus. No inference can fairly be drawn from the absence of\r Aristippus, nor from the omission of Xenophon, who at the time of\r Socrates' death was in Asia. The mention of Plato's own absence seems\r like an expression of sorrow, and may, perhaps, be an indication that\r the report of the conversation is not to be taken ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"plato-phaedo-60","text":"The place of the Dialogue in the series is doubtful. The doctrine of\r ideas is certainly carried beyond the Socratic point of view; in no\r other of the writings of Plato is the theory of them so completely\r developed. Whether the belief in immortality can be attributed to\r Socrates or not is uncertain; the silence of the Memorabilia, and of the\r earlier Dialogues of Plato, is an argument to the contrary. Yet in the\r Cyropaedia Xenophon has put language into the mouth of the dying Cyrus\r which recalls the Phaedo, and may have been derived from the teaching of\r Socrates. It may be fairly urged t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"plato-phaedo-61","text":"The Phaedo is not one of the Socratic Dialogues of Plato; nor, on the\r other hand, can it be assigned to that later stage of the Platonic\r writings at which the doctrine of ideas appears to be forgotten. It\r belongs rather to the intermediate period of the Platonic philosophy,\r which roughly corresponds to the Phaedrus, Gorgias, Republic,\r Theaetetus. Without pretending to determine the real time of their\r composition, the Symposium, Meno, Euthyphro, Apology, Phaedo may be\r conveniently read by us in this order as illustrative of the life of\r Socrates. Another chain may be formed of the Meno, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"plato-phaedo-62","text":"As in several other Dialogues, there is more of system in the Phaedo\r than appears at first sight. The succession of arguments is based on\r previous philosophies; beginning with the mysteries and the Heracleitean\r alternation of opposites, and proceeding to the Pythagorean harmony and\r transmigration; making a step by the aid of Platonic reminiscence, and\r a further step by the help of the nous of Anaxagoras; until at last we\r rest in the conviction that the soul is inseparable from the ideas,\r and belongs to the world of the invisible and unknown. Then, as in\r the Gorgias or Republic, the cur","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"plato-phaedo-63","text":"Difficulties of two kinds occur in the Phaedo--one kind to be explained\r out of contemporary philosophy, the other not admitting of an entire\r solution. (1) The difficulty which Socrates says that he experienced in\r explaining generation and corruption; the assumption of hypotheses which\r proceed from the less general to the more general, and are tested by\r their consequences; the puzzle about greater and less; the resort to the\r method of ideas, which to us appear only abstract terms,--these are to\r be explained out of the position of Socrates and Plato in the history of\r philosophy. They wer","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"plato-phaedo-64","text":"Some resemblances to the Greek drama may be noted in all the Dialogues\r of Plato. The Phaedo is the tragedy of which Socrates is the protagonist\r and Simmias and Cebes the secondary performers, standing to them in the\r same relation as to Glaucon and Adeimantus in the Republic. No Dialogue\r has a greater unity of subject and feeling. Plato has certainly\r fulfilled the condition of Greek, or rather of all art, which requires\r that scenes of death and suffering should be clothed in beauty. The\r gathering of the friends at the commencement of the Dialogue, the\r dismissal of Xanthippe, whose prese","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"plato-phaedo-65","text":"'The art of concealing art' is nowhere more perfect than in those\r writings of Plato which describe the trial and death of Socrates. Their\r charm is their simplicity, which gives them verisimilitude; and yet\r they touch, as if incidentally, and because they were suitable to the\r occasion, on some of the deepest truths of philosophy. There is nothing\r in any tragedy, ancient or modern, nothing in poetry or history (with\r one exception), like the last hours of Socrates in Plato. The master\r could not be more fitly occupied at such a time than in discoursing of\r immortality; nor the disciples mor","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"plato-phaedo-66","text":"Phaedo, who is the narrator of the dialogue to Echecrates of Phlius.\r Socrates, Apollodorus, Simmias, Cebes, Crito and an Attendant of the\r Prison.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"plato-phaedo-67","text":"ECHECRATES: Were you yourself, Phaedo, in the prison with Socrates on\r the day when he drank the poison?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"plato-phaedo-68","text":"ECHECRATES: I should so like to hear about his death. What did he say in\r his last hours? We were informed that he died by taking poison, but no\r one knew anything more; for no Phliasian ever goes to Athens now, and it\r is a long time since any stranger from Athens has found his way hither;\r so that we had no clear account.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"plato-phaedo-69","text":"ECHECRATES: Yes; some one told us about the trial, and we could not\r understand why, having been condemned, he should have been put to death,\r not at the time, but long afterwards. What was the reason of this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"plato-phaedo-70","text":"PHAEDO: An accident, Echecrates: the stern of the ship which the\r Athenians send to Delos happened to have been crowned on the day before\r he was tried.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"plato-phaedo-71","text":"PHAEDO: It is the ship in which, according to Athenian tradition,\r Theseus went to Crete when he took with him the fourteen youths, and was\r the saviour of them and of himself. And they were said to have vowed\r to Apollo at the time, that if they were saved they would send a yearly\r mission to Delos. Now this custom still continues, and the whole period\r of the voyage to and from Delos, beginning when the priest of Apollo\r crowns the stern of the ship, is a holy season, during which the city is\r not allowed to be polluted by public executions; and when the vessel\r is detained by contrary winds","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"plato-phaedo-72","text":"ECHECRATES: What was the manner of his death, Phaedo? What was said or\r done? And which of his friends were with him? Or did the authorities\r forbid them to be present--so that he had no friends near him when he\r died?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"plato-phaedo-73","text":"ECHECRATES: If you have nothing to do, I wish that you would tell me\r what passed, as exactly as you can.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"plato-phaedo-74","text":"PHAEDO: I have nothing at all to do, and will try to gratify your wish.\r To be reminded of Socrates is always the greatest delight to me, whether\r I speak myself or hear another speak of him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"plato-phaedo-75","text":"ECHECRATES: You will have listeners who are of the same mind with you,\r and I hope that you will be as exact as you can.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"plato-phaedo-76","text":"PHAEDO: I had a singular feeling at being in his company. For I\r could hardly believe that I was present at the death of a friend, and\r therefore I did not pity him, Echecrates; he died so fearlessly, and\r his words and bearing were so noble and gracious, that to me he appeared\r blessed. I thought that in going to the other world he could not be\r without a divine call, and that he would be happy, if any man ever was,\r when he arrived there, and therefore I did not pity him as might have\r seemed natural at such an hour. But I had not the pleasure which I\r usually feel in philosophical discourse","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"plato-phaedo-77","text":"PHAEDO: Of native Athenians there were, besides Apollodorus, Critobulus\r and his father Crito, Hermogenes, Epigenes, Aeschines, Antisthenes;\r likewise Ctesippus of the deme of Paeania, Menexenus, and some others;\r Plato, if I am not mistaken, was ill.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"plato-phaedo-78","text":"PHAEDO: Yes, there were; Simmias the Theban, and Cebes, and Phaedondes;\r Euclid and Terpison, who came from Megara.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"plato-phaedo-79","text":"PHAEDO: I will begin at the beginning, and endeavour to repeat the\r entire conversation. On the previous days we had been in the habit of\r assembling early in the morning at the court in which the trial took\r place, and which is not far from the prison. There we used to wait\r talking with one another until the opening of the doors (for they were\r not opened very early); then we went in and generally passed the day\r with Socrates. On the last morning we assembled sooner than usual,\r having heard on the day before when we quitted the prison in the evening\r that the sacred ship had come from Delo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"plato-phaedo-80","text":"Upon this Cebes said: I am glad, Socrates, that you have mentioned the\r name of Aesop. For it reminds me of a question which has been asked by\r many, and was asked of me only the day before yesterday by Evenus the\r poet--he will be sure to ask it again, and therefore if you would like\r me to have an answer ready for him, you may as well tell me what I\r should say to him:--he wanted to know why you, who never before wrote\r a line of poetry, now that you are in prison are turning Aesop's fables\r into verse, and also composing that hymn in honour of Apollo.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"plato-phaedo-81","text":"Tell him, Cebes, he replied, what is the truth--that I had no idea of\r rivalling him or his poems; to do so, as I knew, would be no easy task.\r But I wanted to see whether I could purge away a scruple which I felt\r about the meaning of certain dreams. In the course of my life I have\r often had intimations in dreams 'that I should compose music.' The same\r dream came to me sometimes in one form, and sometimes in another, but\r always saying the same or nearly the same words: 'Cultivate and make\r music,' said the dream. And hitherto I had imagined that this was only\r intended to exhort and encour","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"81"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"plato-phaedo-82","text":"Simmias said: What a message for such a man! having been a frequent\r companion of his I should say that, as far as I know him, he will never\r take your advice unless he is obliged.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"plato-phaedo-83","text":"Then he, or any man who has the spirit of philosophy, will be willing to\r die, but he will not take his own life, for that is held to be unlawful.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"plato-phaedo-84","text":"Here he changed his position, and put his legs off the couch on to the\r ground, and during the rest of the conversation he remained sitting.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"plato-phaedo-85","text":"Why do you say, enquired Cebes, that a man ought not to take his own\r life, but that the philosopher will be ready to follow the dying?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"plato-phaedo-86","text":"Socrates replied: And have you, Cebes and Simmias, who are the disciples\r of Philolaus, never heard him speak of this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"plato-phaedo-87","text":"My words, too, are only an echo; but there is no reason why I should not\r repeat what I have heard: and indeed, as I am going to another place,\r it is very meet for me to be thinking and talking of the nature of\r the pilgrimage which I am about to make. What can I do better in the\r interval between this and the setting of the sun?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"plato-phaedo-88","text":"Then tell me, Socrates, why is suicide held to be unlawful? as I have\r certainly heard Philolaus, about whom you were just now asking, affirm\r when he was staying with us at Thebes: and there are others who say the\r same, although I have never understood what was meant by any of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"plato-phaedo-89","text":"Do not lose heart, replied Socrates, and the day may come when you will\r understand. I suppose that you wonder why, when other things which are\r evil may be good at certain times and to certain persons, death is to\r be the only exception, and why, when a man is better dead, he is not\r permitted to be his own benefactor, but must wait for the hand of\r another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"89"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"plato-phaedo-90","text":"I admit the appearance of inconsistency in what I am saying; but\r there may not be any real inconsistency after all. There is a doctrine\r whispered in secret that man is a prisoner who has no right to open\r the door and run away; this is a great mystery which I do not quite\r understand. Yet I too believe that the gods are our guardians, and that\r we are a possession of theirs. Do you not agree?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"plato-phaedo-91","text":"And if one of your own possessions, an ox or an ass, for example, took\r the liberty of putting himself out of the way when you had given no\r intimation of your wish that he should die, would you not be angry with\r him, and would you not punish him if you could?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"plato-phaedo-92","text":"Then, if we look at the matter thus, there may be reason in saying that\r a man should wait, and not take his own life until God summons him, as\r he is now summoning me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"plato-phaedo-93","text":"Yes, Socrates, said Cebes, there seems to be truth in what you say. And\r yet how can you reconcile this seemingly true belief that God is our\r guardian and we his possessions, with the willingness to die which we\r were just now attributing to the philosopher? That the wisest of men\r should be willing to leave a service in which they are ruled by the gods\r who are the best of rulers, is not reasonable; for surely no wise man\r thinks that when set at liberty he can take better care of himself than\r the gods take of him. A fool may perhaps think so--he may argue that he\r had better run away from ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"plato-phaedo-94","text":"The earnestness of Cebes seemed to please Socrates. Here, said he,\r turning to us, is a man who is always inquiring, and is not so easily\r convinced by the first thing which he hears.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"plato-phaedo-95","text":"And certainly, added Simmias, the objection which he is now making does\r appear to me to have some force. For what can be the meaning of a truly\r wise man wanting to fly away and lightly leave a master who is better\r than himself? And I rather imagine that Cebes is referring to you; he\r thinks that you are too ready to leave us, and too ready to leave the\r gods whom you acknowledge to be our good masters.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"plato-phaedo-96","text":"Yes, replied Socrates; there is reason in what you say. And so you think\r that I ought to answer your indictment as if I were in a court?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"plato-phaedo-97","text":"Then I must try to make a more successful defence before you than I\r did when before the judges. For I am quite ready to admit, Simmias and\r Cebes, that I ought to be grieved at death, if I were not persuaded in\r the first place that I am going to other gods who are wise and good (of\r which I am as certain as I can be of any such matters), and secondly\r (though I am not so sure of this last) to men departed, better than\r those whom I leave behind; and therefore I do not grieve as I might have\r done, for I have good hope that there is yet something remaining for the\r dead, and as has been said ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"plato-phaedo-98","text":"But do you mean to take away your thoughts with you, Socrates? said\r Simmias. Will you not impart them to us?--for they are a benefit\r in which we too are entitled to share. Moreover, if you succeed in\r convincing us, that will be an answer to the charge against yourself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"plato-phaedo-99","text":"I will do my best, replied Socrates. But you must first let me hear what\r Crito wants; he has long been wishing to say something to me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"plato-phaedo-100","text":"Only this, Socrates, replied Crito:--the attendant who is to give you\r the poison has been telling me, and he wants me to tell you, that you\r are not to talk much, talking, he says, increases heat, and this is\r apt to interfere with the action of the poison; persons who excite\r themselves are sometimes obliged to take a second or even a third dose.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"plato-phaedo-101","text":"Then, said Socrates, let him mind his business and be prepared to give\r the poison twice or even thrice if necessary; that is all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"plato-phaedo-102","text":"I knew quite well what you would say, replied Crito; but I was obliged\r to satisfy him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"plato-phaedo-103","text":"And now, O my judges, I desire to prove to you that the real philosopher\r has reason to be of good cheer when he is about to die, and that after\r death he may hope to obtain the greatest good in the other world. And\r how this may be, Simmias and Cebes, I will endeavour to explain. For I\r deem that the true votary of philosophy is likely to be misunderstood\r by other men; they do not perceive that he is always pursuing death and\r dying; and if this be so, and he has had the desire of death all his\r life long, why when his time comes should he repine at that which he has\r been always pursuing an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"plato-phaedo-104","text":"Simmias said laughingly: Though not in a laughing humour, you have made\r me laugh, Socrates; for I cannot help thinking that the many when they\r hear your words will say how truly you have described philosophers, and\r our people at home will likewise say that the life which philosophers\r desire is in reality death, and that they have found them out to be\r deserving of the death which they desire.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"plato-phaedo-105","text":"And they are right, Simmias, in thinking so, with the exception of the\r words 'they have found them out'; for they have not found out either\r what is the nature of that death which the true philosopher deserves,\r or how he deserves or desires death. But enough of them:--let us discuss\r the matter among ourselves: Do we believe that there is such a thing as\r death?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"plato-phaedo-106","text":"Is it not the separation of soul and body? And to be dead is the\r completion of this; when the soul exists in herself, and is released\r from the body and the body is released from the soul, what is this but\r death?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"plato-phaedo-107","text":"There is another question, which will probably throw light on our\r present inquiry if you and I can agree about it:--Ought the philosopher\r to care about the pleasures--if they are to be called pleasures--of\r eating and drinking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"plato-phaedo-108","text":"And will he think much of the other ways of indulging the body, for\r example, the acquisition of costly raiment, or sandals, or other\r adornments of the body? Instead of caring about them, does he not rather\r despise anything more than nature needs? What do you say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"108"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"plato-phaedo-109","text":"Would you not say that he is entirely concerned with the soul and not\r with the body? He would like, as far as he can, to get away from the\r body and to turn to the soul.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"plato-phaedo-110","text":"In matters of this sort philosophers, above all other men, may be\r observed in every sort of way to dissever the soul from the communion of\r the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"plato-phaedo-111","text":"Whereas, Simmias, the rest of the world are of opinion that to him who\r has no sense of pleasure and no part in bodily pleasure, life is not\r worth having; and that he who is indifferent about them is as good as\r dead.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"plato-phaedo-112","text":"What again shall we say of the actual acquirement of knowledge?--is the\r body, if invited to share in the enquiry, a hinderer or a helper? I mean\r to say, have sight and hearing any truth in them? Are they not, as the\r poets are always telling us, inaccurate witnesses? and yet, if even\r they are inaccurate and indistinct, what is to be said of the other\r senses?--for you will allow that they are the best of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"plato-phaedo-113","text":"Then when does the soul attain truth?--for in attempting to consider\r anything in company with the body she is obviously deceived.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"plato-phaedo-114","text":"And thought is best when the mind is gathered into herself and none of\r these things trouble her--neither sounds nor sights nor pain nor any\r pleasure,--when she takes leave of the body, and has as little as\r possible to do with it, when she has no bodily sense or desire, but is\r aspiring after true being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"114"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"plato-phaedo-115","text":"And in this the philosopher dishonours the body; his soul runs away from\r his body and desires to be alone and by herself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"plato-phaedo-116","text":"Well, but there is another thing, Simmias: Is there or is there not an\r absolute justice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"116"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"plato-phaedo-117","text":"Or did you ever reach them with any other bodily sense?--and I speak not\r of these alone, but of absolute greatness, and health, and strength,\r and of the essence or true nature of everything. Has the reality of them\r ever been perceived by you through the bodily organs? or rather, is not\r the nearest approach to the knowledge of their several natures made\r by him who so orders his intellectual vision as to have the most exact\r conception of the essence of each thing which he considers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"plato-phaedo-118","text":"And he attains to the purest knowledge of them who goes to each with the\r mind alone, not introducing or intruding in the act of thought sight\r or any other sense together with reason, but with the very light of the\r mind in her own clearness searches into the very truth of each; he who\r has got rid, as far as he can, of eyes and ears and, so to speak, of the\r whole body, these being in his opinion distracting elements which when\r they infect the soul hinder her from acquiring truth and knowledge--who,\r if not he, is likely to attain the knowledge of true being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"plato-phaedo-119","text":"And when real philosophers consider all these things, will they not be\r led to make a reflection which they will express in words something like\r the following? 'Have we not found,' they will say, 'a path of thought\r which seems to bring us and our argument to the conclusion, that while\r we are in the body, and while the soul is infected with the evils of the\r body, our desire will not be satisfied? and our desire is of the truth.\r For the body is a source of endless trouble to us by reason of the mere\r requirement of food; and is liable also to diseases which overtake and\r impede us in the se","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"plato-phaedo-120","text":"But, O my friend, if this is true, there is great reason to hope that,\r going whither I go, when I have come to the end of my journey, I shall\r attain that which has been the pursuit of my life. And therefore I go on\r my way rejoicing, and not I only, but every other man who believes that\r his mind has been made ready and that he is in a manner purified.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"plato-phaedo-121","text":"And what is purification but the separation of the soul from the body,\r as I was saying before; the habit of the soul gathering and collecting\r herself into herself from all sides out of the body; the dwelling in\r her own place alone, as in another life, so also in this, as far as she\r can;--the release of the soul from the chains of the body?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"121"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"plato-phaedo-122","text":"And the true philosophers, and they only, are ever seeking to release\r the soul. Is not the separation and release of the soul from the body\r their especial study?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"122"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"plato-phaedo-123","text":"And, as I was saying at first, there would be a ridiculous contradiction\r in men studying to live as nearly as they can in a state of death, and\r yet repining when it comes upon them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"123"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"plato-phaedo-124","text":"And the true philosophers, Simmias, are always occupied in the practice\r of dying, wherefore also to them least of all men is death terrible.\r Look at the matter thus:--if they have been in every way the enemies of\r the body, and are wanting to be alone with the soul, when this desire of\r theirs is granted, how inconsistent would they be if they trembled and\r repined, instead of rejoicing at their departure to that place where,\r when they arrive, they hope to gain that which in life they desired--and\r this was wisdom--and at the same time to be rid of the company of their\r enemy. Many a man ha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"124"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"plato-phaedo-125","text":"And when you see a man who is repining at the approach of death, is not\r his reluctance a sufficient proof that he is not a lover of wisdom, but\r a lover of the body, and probably at the same time a lover of either\r money or power, or both?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"125"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"plato-phaedo-126","text":"And is not courage, Simmias, a quality which is specially characteristic\r of the philosopher?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"126"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"plato-phaedo-127","text":"There is temperance again, which even by the vulgar is supposed to\r consist in the control and regulation of the passions, and in the sense\r of superiority to them--is not temperance a virtue belonging to those\r only who despise the body, and who pass their lives in philosophy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"127"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"plato-phaedo-128","text":"For the courage and temperance of other men, if you will consider them,\r are really a contradiction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"128"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"plato-phaedo-129","text":"Well, he said, you are aware that death is regarded by men in general as\r a great evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"129"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"plato-phaedo-130","text":"And do not courageous men face death because they are afraid of yet\r greater evils?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"130"},"sequenceIndex":212},{"id":"plato-phaedo-131","text":"Then all but the philosophers are courageous only from fear, and because\r they are afraid; and yet that a man should be courageous from fear, and\r because he is a coward, is surely a strange thing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"131"},"sequenceIndex":213},{"id":"plato-phaedo-132","text":"And are not the temperate exactly in the same case? They are temperate\r because they are intemperate--which might seem to be a contradiction,\r but is nevertheless the sort of thing which happens with this foolish\r temperance. For there are pleasures which they are afraid of losing; and\r in their desire to keep them, they abstain from some pleasures, because\r they are overcome by others; and although to be conquered by pleasure is\r called by men intemperance, to them the conquest of pleasure consists in\r being conquered by pleasure. And that is what I mean by saying that, in\r a sense, they are ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"132"},"sequenceIndex":214},{"id":"plato-phaedo-133","text":"Yet the exchange of one fear or pleasure or pain for another fear or\r pleasure or pain, and of the greater for the less, as if they were\r coins, is not the exchange of virtue. O my blessed Simmias, is there not\r one true coin for which all things ought to be exchanged?--and that\r is wisdom; and only in exchange for this, and in company with this, is\r anything truly bought or sold, whether courage or temperance or justice.\r And is not all true virtue the companion of wisdom, no matter what fears\r or pleasures or other similar goods or evils may or may not attend her?\r But the virtue which is ma","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"133"},"sequenceIndex":215},{"id":"plato-phaedo-134","text":"Cebes answered: I agree, Socrates, in the greater part of what you say.\r But in what concerns the soul, men are apt to be incredulous; they fear\r that when she has left the body her place may be nowhere, and that on\r the very day of death she may perish and come to an end--immediately on\r her release from the body, issuing forth dispersed like smoke or air\r and in her flight vanishing away into nothingness. If she could only be\r collected into herself after she has obtained release from the evils of\r which you are speaking, there would be good reason to hope, Socrates,\r that what you say is tr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"134"},"sequenceIndex":216},{"id":"plato-phaedo-135","text":"True, Cebes, said Socrates; and shall I suggest that we converse a\r little of the probabilities of these things?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"135"},"sequenceIndex":217},{"id":"plato-phaedo-136","text":"I am sure, said Cebes, that I should greatly like to know your opinion\r about them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"136"},"sequenceIndex":218},{"id":"plato-phaedo-137","text":"I reckon, said Socrates, that no one who heard me now, not even if he\r were one of my old enemies, the Comic poets, could accuse me of idle\r talking about matters in which I have no concern:--If you please, then,\r we will proceed with the inquiry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"137"},"sequenceIndex":219},{"id":"plato-phaedo-138","text":"Suppose we consider the question whether the souls of men after death\r are or are not in the world below. There comes into my mind an ancient\r doctrine which affirms that they go from hence into the other world, and\r returning hither, are born again from the dead. Now if it be true that\r the living come from the dead, then our souls must exist in the other\r world, for if not, how could they have been born again? And this would\r be conclusive, if there were any real evidence that the living are only\r born from the dead; but if this is not so, then other arguments will\r have to be adduced.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"138"},"sequenceIndex":220},{"id":"plato-phaedo-139","text":"Then let us consider the whole question, not in relation to man only,\r but in relation to animals generally, and to plants, and to everything\r of which there is generation, and the proof will be easier. Are not all\r things which have opposites generated out of their opposites? I mean\r such things as good and evil, just and unjust--and there are innumerable\r other opposites which are generated out of opposites. And I want to show\r that in all opposites there is of necessity a similar alternation;\r I mean to say, for example, that anything which becomes greater must\r become greater after being l","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"139"},"sequenceIndex":221},{"id":"plato-phaedo-140","text":"And that which becomes less must have been once greater and then have\r become less.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"140"},"sequenceIndex":222},{"id":"plato-phaedo-141","text":"And the weaker is generated from the stronger, and the swifter from the\r slower.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"141"},"sequenceIndex":223},{"id":"plato-phaedo-142","text":"And is this true of all opposites? and are we convinced that all of them\r are generated out of opposites?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"142"},"sequenceIndex":224},{"id":"plato-phaedo-143","text":"And in this universal opposition of all things, are there not also two\r intermediate processes which are ever going on, from one to the other\r opposite, and back again; where there is a greater and a less there is\r also an intermediate process of increase and diminution, and that which\r grows is said to wax, and that which decays to wane?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"143"},"sequenceIndex":225},{"id":"plato-phaedo-144","text":"And there are many other processes, such as division and composition,\r cooling and heating, which equally involve a passage into and out of one\r another. And this necessarily holds of all opposites, even though not\r always expressed in words--they are really generated out of one another,\r and there is a passing or process from one to the other of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"144"},"sequenceIndex":226},{"id":"plato-phaedo-145","text":"Well, and is there not an opposite of life, as sleep is the opposite of\r waking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"145"},"sequenceIndex":227},{"id":"plato-phaedo-146","text":"And these, if they are opposites, are generated the one from the other,\r and have there their two intermediate processes also?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"146"},"sequenceIndex":228},{"id":"plato-phaedo-147","text":"Now, said Socrates, I will analyze one of the two pairs of opposites\r which I have mentioned to you, and also its intermediate processes, and\r you shall analyze the other to me. One of them I term sleep, the other\r waking. The state of sleep is opposed to the state of waking, and out\r of sleeping waking is generated, and out of waking, sleeping; and the\r process of generation is in the one case falling asleep, and in the\r other waking up. Do you agree?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"147"},"sequenceIndex":229},{"id":"plato-phaedo-148","text":"Then, suppose that you analyze life and death to me in the same manner.\r Is not death opposed to life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"148"},"sequenceIndex":230},{"id":"plato-phaedo-149","text":"Then the living, whether things or persons, Cebes, are generated from\r the dead?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"149"},"sequenceIndex":231},{"id":"plato-phaedo-150","text":"And one of the two processes or generations is visible--for surely the\r act of dying is visible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"150"},"sequenceIndex":232},{"id":"plato-phaedo-151","text":"What then is to be the result? Shall we exclude the opposite process?\r And shall we suppose nature to walk on one leg only? Must we not rather\r assign to death some corresponding process of generation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"151"},"sequenceIndex":233},{"id":"plato-phaedo-152","text":"And return to life, if there be such a thing, is the birth of the dead\r into the world of the living?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"152"},"sequenceIndex":234},{"id":"plato-phaedo-153","text":"Then here is a new way by which we arrive at the conclusion that the\r living come from the dead, just as the dead come from the living; and\r this, if true, affords a most certain proof that the souls of the dead\r exist in some place out of which they come again.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"153"},"sequenceIndex":235},{"id":"plato-phaedo-154","text":"Yes, Socrates, he said; the conclusion seems to flow necessarily out of\r our previous admissions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"154"},"sequenceIndex":236},{"id":"plato-phaedo-155","text":"And that these admissions were not unfair, Cebes, he said, may be shown,\r I think, as follows: If generation were in a straight line only, and\r there were no compensation or circle in nature, no turn or return of\r elements into their opposites, then you know that all things would at\r last have the same form and pass into the same state, and there would be\r no more generation of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"155"},"sequenceIndex":237},{"id":"plato-phaedo-156","text":"A simple thing enough, which I will illustrate by the case of sleep,\r he replied. You know that if there were no alternation of sleeping\r and waking, the tale of the sleeping Endymion would in the end have no\r meaning, because all other things would be asleep, too, and he would not\r be distinguishable from the rest. Or if there were composition only,\r and no division of substances, then the chaos of Anaxagoras would come\r again. And in like manner, my dear Cebes, if all things which partook\r of life were to die, and after they were dead remained in the form\r of death, and did not come to life ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"156"},"sequenceIndex":238},{"id":"plato-phaedo-157","text":"There is no escape, Socrates, said Cebes; and to me your argument seems\r to be absolutely true.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"157"},"sequenceIndex":239},{"id":"plato-phaedo-158","text":"Yes, he said, Cebes, it is and must be so, in my opinion; and we have\r not been deluded in making these admissions; but I am confident that\r there truly is such a thing as living again, and that the living spring\r from the dead, and that the souls of the dead are in existence, and that\r the good souls have a better portion than the evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"158"},"sequenceIndex":240},{"id":"plato-phaedo-159","text":"Cebes added: Your favorite doctrine, Socrates, that knowledge is simply\r recollection, if true, also necessarily implies a previous time in\r which we have learned that which we now recollect. But this would be\r impossible unless our soul had been in some place before existing in the\r form of man; here then is another proof of the soul's immortality.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"159"},"sequenceIndex":241},{"id":"plato-phaedo-160","text":"But tell me, Cebes, said Simmias, interposing, what arguments are urged\r in favour of this doctrine of recollection. I am not very sure at the\r moment that I remember them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"160"},"sequenceIndex":242},{"id":"plato-phaedo-161","text":"One excellent proof, said Cebes, is afforded by questions. If you put\r a question to a person in a right way, he will give a true answer of\r himself, but how could he do this unless there were knowledge and right\r reason already in him? And this is most clearly shown when he is taken\r to a diagram or to anything of that sort. (Compare Meno.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"161"},"sequenceIndex":243},{"id":"plato-phaedo-162","text":"But if, said Socrates, you are still incredulous, Simmias, I would ask\r you whether you may not agree with me when you look at the matter\r in another way;--I mean, if you are still incredulous as to whether\r knowledge is recollection.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"162"},"sequenceIndex":244},{"id":"plato-phaedo-163","text":"Incredulous, I am not, said Simmias; but I want to have this doctrine\r of recollection brought to my own recollection, and, from what Cebes has\r said, I am beginning to recollect and be convinced; but I should still\r like to hear what you were going to say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"163"},"sequenceIndex":245},{"id":"plato-phaedo-164","text":"This is what I would say, he replied:--We should agree, if I am not\r mistaken, that what a man recollects he must have known at some previous\r time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"164"},"sequenceIndex":246},{"id":"plato-phaedo-165","text":"And what is the nature of this knowledge or recollection? I mean to\r ask, Whether a person who, having seen or heard or in any way perceived\r anything, knows not only that, but has a conception of something\r else which is the subject, not of the same but of some other kind of\r knowledge, may not be fairly said to recollect that of which he has the\r conception?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"165"},"sequenceIndex":247},{"id":"plato-phaedo-166","text":"I mean what I may illustrate by the following instance:--The knowledge\r of a lyre is not the same as the knowledge of a man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"166"},"sequenceIndex":248},{"id":"plato-phaedo-167","text":"And yet what is the feeling of lovers when they recognize a lyre, or\r a garment, or anything else which the beloved has been in the habit of\r using? Do not they, from knowing the lyre, form in the mind's eye an\r image of the youth to whom the lyre belongs? And this is recollection.\r In like manner any one who sees Simmias may remember Cebes; and there\r are endless examples of the same thing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"167"},"sequenceIndex":249},{"id":"plato-phaedo-168","text":"And recollection is most commonly a process of recovering that which has\r been already forgotten through time and inattention.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"168"},"sequenceIndex":250},{"id":"plato-phaedo-169","text":"Well; and may you not also from seeing the picture of a horse or a\r lyre remember a man? and from the picture of Simmias, you may be led to\r remember Cebes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"169"},"sequenceIndex":251},{"id":"plato-phaedo-170","text":"And in all these cases, the recollection may be derived from things\r either like or unlike?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"170"},"sequenceIndex":252},{"id":"plato-phaedo-171","text":"And when the recollection is derived from like things, then another\r consideration is sure to arise, which is--whether the likeness in any\r degree falls short or not of that which is recollected?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"171"},"sequenceIndex":253},{"id":"plato-phaedo-172","text":"And shall we proceed a step further, and affirm that there is such a\r thing as equality, not of one piece of wood or stone with another, but\r that, over and above this, there is absolute equality? Shall we say so?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"172"},"sequenceIndex":254},{"id":"plato-phaedo-173","text":"Say so, yes, replied Simmias, and swear to it, with all the confidence\r in life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"173"},"sequenceIndex":255},{"id":"plato-phaedo-174","text":"And whence did we obtain our knowledge? Did we not see equalities of\r material things, such as pieces of wood and stones, and gather from\r them the idea of an equality which is different from them? For you will\r acknowledge that there is a difference. Or look at the matter in another\r way:--Do not the same pieces of wood or stone appear at one time equal,\r and at another time unequal?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"174"},"sequenceIndex":256},{"id":"plato-phaedo-175","text":"But are real equals ever unequal? or is the idea of equality the same as\r of inequality?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"175"},"sequenceIndex":257},{"id":"plato-phaedo-176","text":"And yet from these equals, although differing from the idea of equality,\r you conceived and attained that idea?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"176"},"sequenceIndex":258},{"id":"plato-phaedo-177","text":"But that makes no difference; whenever from seeing one thing you\r conceived another, whether like or unlike, there must surely have been\r an act of recollection?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"177"},"sequenceIndex":259},{"id":"plato-phaedo-178","text":"But what would you say of equal portions of wood and stone, or other\r material equals? and what is the impression produced by them? Are they\r equals in the same sense in which absolute equality is equal? or do they\r fall short of this perfect equality in a measure?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"178"},"sequenceIndex":260},{"id":"plato-phaedo-179","text":"And must we not allow, that when I or any one, looking at any object,\r observes that the thing which he sees aims at being some other thing,\r but falls short of, and cannot be, that other thing, but is inferior, he\r who makes this observation must have had a previous knowledge of that to\r which the other, although similar, was inferior?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"179"},"sequenceIndex":261},{"id":"plato-phaedo-180","text":"And has not this been our own case in the matter of equals and of\r absolute equality?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"180"},"sequenceIndex":262},{"id":"plato-phaedo-181","text":"Then we must have known equality previously to the time when we first\r saw the material equals, and reflected that all these apparent equals\r strive to attain absolute equality, but fall short of it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"181"},"sequenceIndex":263},{"id":"plato-phaedo-182","text":"And we recognize also that this absolute equality has only been known,\r and can only be known, through the medium of sight or touch, or of some\r other of the senses, which are all alike in this respect?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"182"},"sequenceIndex":264},{"id":"plato-phaedo-183","text":"Yes, Socrates, as far as the argument is concerned, one of them is the\r same as the other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"183"},"sequenceIndex":265},{"id":"plato-phaedo-184","text":"From the senses then is derived the knowledge that all sensible things\r aim at an absolute equality of which they fall short?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"184"},"sequenceIndex":266},{"id":"plato-phaedo-185","text":"Then before we began to see or hear or perceive in any way, we must have\r had a knowledge of absolute equality, or we could not have referred to\r that standard the equals which are derived from the senses?--for to that\r they all aspire, and of that they fall short.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"185"},"sequenceIndex":267},{"id":"plato-phaedo-186","text":"And did we not see and hear and have the use of our other senses as soon\r as we were born?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"186"},"sequenceIndex":268},{"id":"plato-phaedo-187","text":"And if we acquired this knowledge before we were born, and were born\r having the use of it, then we also knew before we were born and at the\r instant of birth not only the equal or the greater or the less, but all\r other ideas; for we are not speaking only of equality, but of beauty,\r goodness, justice, holiness, and of all which we stamp with the name of\r essence in the dialectical process, both when we ask and when we answer\r questions. Of all this we may certainly affirm that we acquired the\r knowledge before birth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"187"},"sequenceIndex":269},{"id":"plato-phaedo-188","text":"But if, after having acquired, we have not forgotten what in each case\r we acquired, then we must always have come into life having knowledge,\r and shall always continue to know as long as life lasts--for knowing\r is the acquiring and retaining knowledge and not forgetting. Is not\r forgetting, Simmias, just the losing of knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"188"},"sequenceIndex":270},{"id":"plato-phaedo-189","text":"But if the knowledge which we acquired before birth was lost by us at\r birth, and if afterwards by the use of the senses we recovered what\r we previously knew, will not the process which we call learning be a\r recovering of the knowledge which is natural to us, and may not this be\r rightly termed recollection?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"189"},"sequenceIndex":271},{"id":"plato-phaedo-190","text":"So much is clear--that when we perceive something, either by the help of\r sight, or hearing, or some other sense, from that perception we are\r able to obtain a notion of some other thing like or unlike which is\r associated with it but has been forgotten. Whence, as I was saying, one\r of two alternatives follows:--either we had this knowledge at birth, and\r continued to know through life; or, after birth, those who are said to\r learn only remember, and learning is simply recollection.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"190"},"sequenceIndex":272},{"id":"plato-phaedo-191","text":"And which alternative, Simmias, do you prefer? Had we the knowledge at\r our birth, or did we recollect the things which we knew previously to\r our birth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"191"},"sequenceIndex":273},{"id":"plato-phaedo-192","text":"At any rate you can decide whether he who has knowledge will or will not\r be able to render an account of his knowledge? What do you say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"192"},"sequenceIndex":274},{"id":"plato-phaedo-193","text":"But do you think that every man is able to give an account of these very\r matters about which we are speaking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"193"},"sequenceIndex":275},{"id":"plato-phaedo-194","text":"Would that they could, Socrates, but I rather fear that to-morrow, at\r this time, there will no longer be any one alive who is able to give an\r account of them such as ought to be given.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"194"},"sequenceIndex":276},{"id":"plato-phaedo-195","text":"Then, Simmias, our souls must also have existed without bodies before\r they were in the form of man, and must have had intelligence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"195"},"sequenceIndex":277},{"id":"plato-phaedo-196","text":"Unless indeed you suppose, Socrates, that these notions are given us at\r the very moment of birth; for this is the only time which remains.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"196"},"sequenceIndex":278},{"id":"plato-phaedo-197","text":"Yes, my friend, but if so, when do we lose them? for they are not in\r us when we are born--that is admitted. Do we lose them at the moment of\r receiving them, or if not at what other time?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"197"},"sequenceIndex":279},{"id":"plato-phaedo-198","text":"Then may we not say, Simmias, that if, as we are always repeating, there\r is an absolute beauty, and goodness, and an absolute essence of all\r things; and if to this, which is now discovered to have existed in our\r former state, we refer all our sensations, and with this compare them,\r finding these ideas to be pre-existent and our inborn possession--then\r our souls must have had a prior existence, but if not, there would be\r no force in the argument? There is the same proof that these ideas must\r have existed before we were born, as that our souls existed before we\r were born; and if not the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"198"},"sequenceIndex":280},{"id":"plato-phaedo-199","text":"Yes, Socrates; I am convinced that there is precisely the same necessity\r for the one as for the other; and the argument retreats successfully\r to the position that the existence of the soul before birth cannot be\r separated from the existence of the essence of which you speak. For\r there is nothing which to my mind is so patent as that beauty, goodness,\r and the other notions of which you were just now speaking, have a most\r real and absolute existence; and I am satisfied with the proof.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"199"},"sequenceIndex":281},{"id":"plato-phaedo-200","text":"I think, said Simmias, that Cebes is satisfied: although he is the most\r incredulous of mortals, yet I believe that he is sufficiently convinced\r of the existence of the soul before birth. But that after death the soul\r will continue to exist is not yet proven even to my own satisfaction.\r I cannot get rid of the feeling of the many to which Cebes was\r referring--the feeling that when the man dies the soul will be\r dispersed, and that this may be the extinction of her. For admitting\r that she may have been born elsewhere, and framed out of other elements,\r and was in existence before entering ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"200"},"sequenceIndex":282},{"id":"plato-phaedo-201","text":"Very true, Simmias, said Cebes; about half of what was required has been\r proven; to wit, that our souls existed before we were born:--that the\r soul will exist after death as well as before birth is the other half of\r which the proof is still wanting, and has to be supplied; when that is\r given the demonstration will be complete.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"201"},"sequenceIndex":283},{"id":"plato-phaedo-202","text":"But that proof, Simmias and Cebes, has been already given, said\r Socrates, if you put the two arguments together--I mean this and the\r former one, in which we admitted that everything living is born of the\r dead. For if the soul exists before birth, and in coming to life and\r being born can be born only from death and dying, must she not after\r death continue to exist, since she has to be born again?--Surely the\r proof which you desire has been already furnished. Still I suspect\r that you and Simmias would be glad to probe the argument further. Like\r children, you are haunted with a fear that ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"202"},"sequenceIndex":284},{"id":"plato-phaedo-203","text":"Cebes answered with a smile: Then, Socrates, you must argue us out of\r our fears--and yet, strictly speaking, they are not our fears, but there\r is a child within us to whom death is a sort of hobgoblin; him too we\r must persuade not to be afraid when he is alone in the dark.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"203"},"sequenceIndex":285},{"id":"plato-phaedo-204","text":"Socrates said: Let the voice of the charmer be applied daily until you\r have charmed away the fear.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"204"},"sequenceIndex":286},{"id":"plato-phaedo-205","text":"And where shall we find a good charmer of our fears, Socrates, when you\r are gone?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"205"},"sequenceIndex":287},{"id":"plato-phaedo-206","text":"Hellas, he replied, is a large place, Cebes, and has many good men, and\r there are barbarous races not a few: seek for him among them all, far\r and wide, sparing neither pains nor money; for there is no better way\r of spending your money. And you must seek among yourselves too; for you\r will not find others better able to make the search.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"206"},"sequenceIndex":288},{"id":"plato-phaedo-207","text":"The search, replied Cebes, shall certainly be made. And now, if\r you please, let us return to the point of the argument at which we\r digressed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"207"},"sequenceIndex":289},{"id":"plato-phaedo-208","text":"Must we not, said Socrates, ask ourselves what that is which, as we\r imagine, is liable to be scattered, and about which we fear? and what\r again is that about which we have no fear? And then we may proceed\r further to enquire whether that which suffers dispersion is or is not\r of the nature of soul--our hopes and fears as to our own souls will turn\r upon the answers to these questions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"208"},"sequenceIndex":290},{"id":"plato-phaedo-209","text":"Now the compound or composite may be supposed to be naturally capable,\r as of being compounded, so also of being dissolved; but that which is\r uncompounded, and that only, must be, if anything is, indissoluble.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"209"},"sequenceIndex":291},{"id":"plato-phaedo-210","text":"And the uncompounded may be assumed to be the same and unchanging,\r whereas the compound is always changing and never the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"210"},"sequenceIndex":292},{"id":"plato-phaedo-211","text":"Then now let us return to the previous discussion. Is that idea or\r essence, which in the dialectical process we define as essence or true\r existence--whether essence of equality, beauty, or anything else--are\r these essences, I say, liable at times to some degree of change? or\r are they each of them always what they are, having the same simple\r self-existent and unchanging forms, not admitting of variation at all,\r or in any way, or at any time?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"211"},"sequenceIndex":293},{"id":"plato-phaedo-212","text":"And what would you say of the many beautiful--whether men or horses or\r garments or any other things which are named by the same names and may\r be called equal or beautiful,--are they all unchanging and the same\r always, or quite the reverse? May they not rather be described as almost\r always changing and hardly ever the same, either with themselves or with\r one another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"212"},"sequenceIndex":294},{"id":"plato-phaedo-213","text":"And these you can touch and see and perceive with the senses, but\r the unchanging things you can only perceive with the mind--they are\r invisible and are not seen?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"213"},"sequenceIndex":295},{"id":"plato-phaedo-214","text":"Well, then, added Socrates, let us suppose that there are two sorts of\r existences--one seen, the other unseen.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"214"},"sequenceIndex":296},{"id":"plato-phaedo-215","text":"And what we mean by 'seen' and 'not seen' is that which is or is not\r visible to the eye of man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"215"},"sequenceIndex":297},{"id":"plato-phaedo-216","text":"And were we not saying long ago that the soul when using the body as an\r instrument of perception, that is to say, when using the sense of sight\r or hearing or some other sense (for the meaning of perceiving through\r the body is perceiving through the senses)--were we not saying that the\r soul too is then dragged by the body into the region of the changeable,\r and wanders and is confused; the world spins round her, and she is like\r a drunkard, when she touches change?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"216"},"sequenceIndex":298},{"id":"plato-phaedo-217","text":"But when returning into herself she reflects, then she passes into the\r other world, the region of purity, and eternity, and immortality, and\r unchangeableness, which are her kindred, and with them she ever lives,\r when she is by herself and is not let or hindered; then she ceases\r from her erring ways, and being in communion with the unchanging is\r unchanging. And this state of the soul is called wisdom?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"217"},"sequenceIndex":299},{"id":"plato-phaedo-218","text":"And to which class is the soul more nearly alike and akin, as far as may\r be inferred from this argument, as well as from the preceding one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"218"},"sequenceIndex":300},{"id":"plato-phaedo-219","text":"I think, Socrates, that, in the opinion of every one who follows the\r argument, the soul will be infinitely more like the unchangeable--even\r the most stupid person will not deny that.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"219"},"sequenceIndex":301},{"id":"plato-phaedo-220","text":"Yet once more consider the matter in another light: When the soul and\r the body are united, then nature orders the soul to rule and govern, and\r the body to obey and serve. Now which of these two functions is akin to\r the divine? and which to the mortal? Does not the divine appear to you\r to be that which naturally orders and rules, and the mortal to be that\r which is subject and servant?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"220"},"sequenceIndex":302},{"id":"plato-phaedo-221","text":"The soul resembles the divine, and the body the mortal--there can be no\r doubt of that, Socrates.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"221"},"sequenceIndex":303},{"id":"plato-phaedo-222","text":"Then reflect, Cebes: of all which has been said is not this the\r conclusion?--that the soul is in the very likeness of the divine,\r and immortal, and intellectual, and uniform, and indissoluble, and\r unchangeable; and that the body is in the very likeness of the human,\r and mortal, and unintellectual, and multiform, and dissoluble, and\r changeable. Can this, my dear Cebes, be denied?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"222"},"sequenceIndex":304},{"id":"plato-phaedo-223","text":"But if it be true, then is not the body liable to speedy dissolution?\r and is not the soul almost or altogether indissoluble?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"223"},"sequenceIndex":305},{"id":"plato-phaedo-224","text":"And do you further observe, that after a man is dead, the body, or\r visible part of him, which is lying in the visible world, and is\r called a corpse, and would naturally be dissolved and decomposed and\r dissipated, is not dissolved or decomposed at once, but may remain for a\r for some time, nay even for a long time, if the constitution be sound at\r the time of death, and the season of the year favourable? For the body\r when shrunk and embalmed, as the manner is in Egypt, may remain almost\r entire through infinite ages; and even in decay, there are still\r some portions, such as the bones and l","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"224"},"sequenceIndex":306},{"id":"plato-phaedo-225","text":"And is it likely that the soul, which is invisible, in passing to the\r place of the true Hades, which like her is invisible, and pure, and\r noble, and on her way to the good and wise God, whither, if God will, my\r soul is also soon to go,--that the soul, I repeat, if this be her nature\r and origin, will be blown away and destroyed immediately on quitting the\r body, as the many say? That can never be, my dear Simmias and Cebes.\r The truth rather is, that the soul which is pure at departing and draws\r after her no bodily taint, having never voluntarily during life had\r connection with the body, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"225"},"sequenceIndex":307},{"id":"plato-phaedo-226","text":"That soul, I say, herself invisible, departs to the invisible world--to\r the divine and immortal and rational: thither arriving, she is secure of\r bliss and is released from the error and folly of men, their fears and\r wild passions and all other human ills, and for ever dwells, as they say\r of the initiated, in company with the gods (compare Apol.). Is not this\r true, Cebes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"226"},"sequenceIndex":308},{"id":"plato-phaedo-227","text":"But the soul which has been polluted, and is impure at the time of her\r departure, and is the companion and servant of the body always, and is\r in love with and fascinated by the body and by the desires and pleasures\r of the body, until she is led to believe that the truth only exists in\r a bodily form, which a man may touch and see and taste, and use for the\r purposes of his lusts,--the soul, I mean, accustomed to hate and fear\r and avoid the intellectual principle, which to the bodily eye is dark\r and invisible, and can be attained only by philosophy;--do you suppose\r that such a soul will d","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"227"},"sequenceIndex":309},{"id":"plato-phaedo-228","text":"She is held fast by the corporeal, which the continual association and\r constant care of the body have wrought into her nature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"228"},"sequenceIndex":310},{"id":"plato-phaedo-229","text":"And this corporeal element, my friend, is heavy and weighty and earthy,\r and is that element of sight by which a soul is depressed and dragged\r down again into the visible world, because she is afraid of the\r invisible and of the world below--prowling about tombs and sepulchres,\r near which, as they tell us, are seen certain ghostly apparitions\r of souls which have not departed pure, but are cloyed with sight and\r therefore visible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"229"},"sequenceIndex":311},{"id":"plato-phaedo-230","text":"'But when lust,\r      By unchaste looks, loose gestures, and foul talk,\r      But most by lewd and lavish act of sin,\r      Lets in defilement to the inward parts,\r      The soul grows clotted by contagion,\r      Imbodies, and imbrutes, till she quite lose,\r      The divine property of her first being.\r      Such are those thick and gloomy shadows damp\r      Oft seen in charnel vaults and sepulchres,\r      Lingering, and sitting by a new made grave,\r      As loath to leave the body that it lov'd,\r      And linked itself by carnal sensuality\r      To a degenerate and degraded state.')","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"230"},"sequenceIndex":312},{"id":"plato-phaedo-231","text":"Yes, that is very likely, Cebes; and these must be the souls, not of the\r good, but of the evil, which are compelled to wander about such places\r in payment of the penalty of their former evil way of life; and they\r continue to wander until through the craving after the corporeal which\r never leaves them, they are imprisoned finally in another body. And they\r may be supposed to find their prisons in the same natures which they\r have had in their former lives.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"231"},"sequenceIndex":313},{"id":"plato-phaedo-232","text":"What I mean is that men who have followed after gluttony, and\r wantonness, and drunkenness, and have had no thought of avoiding them,\r would pass into asses and animals of that sort. What do you think?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"232"},"sequenceIndex":314},{"id":"plato-phaedo-233","text":"And those who have chosen the portion of injustice, and tyranny, and\r violence, will pass into wolves, or into hawks and kites;--whither else\r can we suppose them to go?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"233"},"sequenceIndex":315},{"id":"plato-phaedo-234","text":"And there is no difficulty, he said, in assigning to all of them places\r answering to their several natures and propensities?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"234"},"sequenceIndex":316},{"id":"plato-phaedo-235","text":"Some are happier than others; and the happiest both in themselves and\r in the place to which they go are those who have practised the civil and\r social virtues which are called temperance and justice, and are acquired\r by habit and attention without philosophy and mind. (Compare Republic.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"235"},"sequenceIndex":317},{"id":"plato-phaedo-236","text":"Because they may be expected to pass into some gentle and social kind\r which is like their own, such as bees or wasps or ants, or back again\r into the form of man, and just and moderate men may be supposed to\r spring from them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"236"},"sequenceIndex":318},{"id":"plato-phaedo-237","text":"No one who has not studied philosophy and who is not entirely pure at\r the time of his departure is allowed to enter the company of the Gods,\r but the lover of knowledge only. And this is the reason, Simmias and\r Cebes, why the true votaries of philosophy abstain from all fleshly\r lusts, and hold out against them and refuse to give themselves up to\r them,--not because they fear poverty or the ruin of their families, like\r the lovers of money, and the world in general; nor like the lovers of\r power and honour, because they dread the dishonour or disgrace of evil\r deeds.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"237"},"sequenceIndex":319},{"id":"plato-phaedo-238","text":"No indeed, he replied; and therefore they who have any care of their\r own souls, and do not merely live moulding and fashioning the body, say\r farewell to all this; they will not walk in the ways of the blind: and\r when philosophy offers them purification and release from evil, they\r feel that they ought not to resist her influence, and whither she leads\r they turn and follow.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"238"},"sequenceIndex":320},{"id":"plato-phaedo-239","text":"I will tell you, he said. The lovers of knowledge are conscious that\r the soul was simply fastened and glued to the body--until philosophy\r received her, she could only view real existence through the bars of\r a prison, not in and through herself; she was wallowing in the mire of\r every sort of ignorance; and by reason of lust had become the principal\r accomplice in her own captivity. This was her original state; and\r then, as I was saying, and as the lovers of knowledge are well aware,\r philosophy, seeing how terrible was her confinement, of which she was\r to herself the cause, received and g","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"239"},"sequenceIndex":321},{"id":"plato-phaedo-240","text":"The evil is that when the feeling of pleasure or pain is most intense,\r every soul of man imagines the objects of this intense feeling to be\r then plainest and truest: but this is not so, they are really the things\r of sight.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"240"},"sequenceIndex":322},{"id":"plato-phaedo-241","text":"Why, because each pleasure and pain is a sort of nail which nails\r and rivets the soul to the body, until she becomes like the body, and\r believes that to be true which the body affirms to be true; and from\r agreeing with the body and having the same delights she is obliged to\r have the same habits and haunts, and is not likely ever to be pure at\r her departure to the world below, but is always infected by the body;\r and so she sinks into another body and there germinates and grows,\r and has therefore no part in the communion of the divine and pure and\r simple.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"241"},"sequenceIndex":323},{"id":"plato-phaedo-242","text":"And this, Cebes, is the reason why the true lovers of knowledge are\r temperate and brave; and not for the reason which the world gives.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"242"},"sequenceIndex":324},{"id":"plato-phaedo-243","text":"Certainly not! The soul of a philosopher will reason in quite another\r way; she will not ask philosophy to release her in order that when\r released she may deliver herself up again to the thraldom of pleasures\r and pains, doing a work only to be undone again, weaving instead of\r unweaving her Penelope's web. But she will calm passion, and follow\r reason, and dwell in the contemplation of her, beholding the true\r and divine (which is not matter of opinion), and thence deriving\r nourishment. Thus she seeks to live while she lives, and after death she\r hopes to go to her own kindred and to that w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"243"},"sequenceIndex":325},{"id":"plato-phaedo-244","text":"When Socrates had done speaking, for a considerable time there was\r silence; he himself appeared to be meditating, as most of us were, on\r what had been said; only Cebes and Simmias spoke a few words to one\r another. And Socrates observing them asked what they thought of the\r argument, and whether there was anything wanting? For, said he, there\r are many points still open to suspicion and attack, if any one were\r disposed to sift the matter thoroughly. Should you be considering\r some other matter I say no more, but if you are still in doubt do not\r hesitate to say exactly what you think, and l","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"244"},"sequenceIndex":326},{"id":"plato-phaedo-245","text":"Simmias said: I must confess, Socrates, that doubts did arise in our\r minds, and each of us was urging and inciting the other to put the\r question which we wanted to have answered and which neither of us liked\r to ask, fearing that our importunity might be troublesome under present\r at such a time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"245"},"sequenceIndex":327},{"id":"plato-phaedo-246","text":"Socrates replied with a smile: O Simmias, what are you saying? I am\r not very likely to persuade other men that I do not regard my present\r situation as a misfortune, if I cannot even persuade you that I am no\r worse off now than at any other time in my life. Will you not allow that\r I have as much of the spirit of prophecy in me as the swans? For they,\r when they perceive that they must die, having sung all their life long,\r do then sing more lustily than ever, rejoicing in the thought that\r they are about to go away to the god whose ministers they are. But men,\r because they are themselves a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"246"},"sequenceIndex":328},{"id":"plato-phaedo-247","text":"Very good, Socrates, said Simmias; then I will tell you my difficulty,\r and Cebes will tell you his. I feel myself, (and I daresay that you have\r the same feeling), how hard or rather impossible is the attainment of\r any certainty about questions such as these in the present life. And yet\r I should deem him a coward who did not prove what is said about them to\r the uttermost, or whose heart failed him before he had examined them\r on every side. For he should persevere until he has achieved one of two\r things: either he should discover, or be taught the truth about them;\r or, if this be impossi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"247"},"sequenceIndex":329},{"id":"plato-phaedo-248","text":"Socrates answered: I dare say, my friend, that you may be right, but I\r should like to know in what respect the argument is insufficient.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"248"},"sequenceIndex":330},{"id":"plato-phaedo-249","text":"In this respect, replied Simmias:--Suppose a person to use the same\r argument about harmony and the lyre--might he not say that harmony is\r a thing invisible, incorporeal, perfect, divine, existing in the lyre\r which is harmonized, but that the lyre and the strings are matter and\r material, composite, earthy, and akin to mortality? And when some one\r breaks the lyre, or cuts and rends the strings, then he who takes this\r view would argue as you do, and on the same analogy, that the harmony\r survives and has not perished--you cannot imagine, he would say, that\r the lyre without the strings, and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"249"},"sequenceIndex":331},{"id":"plato-phaedo-250","text":"Socrates looked fixedly at us as his manner was, and said with a smile:\r Simmias has reason on his side; and why does not some one of you who\r is better able than myself answer him? for there is force in his attack\r upon me. But perhaps, before we answer him, we had better also hear what\r Cebes has to say that we may gain time for reflection, and when they\r have both spoken, we may either assent to them, if there is truth in\r what they say, or if not, we will maintain our position. Please to tell\r me then, Cebes, he said, what was the difficulty which troubled you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"250"},"sequenceIndex":332},{"id":"plato-phaedo-251","text":"Cebes said: I will tell you. My feeling is that the argument is where it\r was, and open to the same objections which were urged before; for I am\r ready to admit that the existence of the soul before entering into\r the bodily form has been very ingeniously, and, if I may say so, quite\r sufficiently proven; but the existence of the soul after death is still,\r in my judgment, unproven. Now my objection is not the same as that of\r Simmias; for I am not disposed to deny that the soul is stronger and\r more lasting than the body, being of opinion that in all such respects\r the soul very far excels th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"251"},"sequenceIndex":333},{"id":"plato-phaedo-252","text":"All of us, as we afterwards remarked to one another, had an unpleasant\r feeling at hearing what they said. When we had been so firmly convinced\r before, now to have our faith shaken seemed to introduce a confusion and\r uncertainty, not only into the previous argument, but into any future\r one; either we were incapable of forming a judgment, or there were no\r grounds of belief.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"252"},"sequenceIndex":334},{"id":"plato-phaedo-253","text":"ECHECRATES: There I feel with you--by heaven I do, Phaedo, and when you\r were speaking, I was beginning to ask myself the same question: What\r argument can I ever trust again? For what could be more convincing than\r the argument of Socrates, which has now fallen into discredit? That\r the soul is a harmony is a doctrine which has always had a wonderful\r attraction for me, and, when mentioned, came back to me at once, as my\r own original conviction. And now I must begin again and find another\r argument which will assure me that when the man is dead the soul\r survives. Tell me, I implore you, how","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"253"},"sequenceIndex":335},{"id":"plato-phaedo-254","text":"PHAEDO: Often, Echecrates, I have wondered at Socrates, but never more\r than on that occasion. That he should be able to answer was nothing,\r but what astonished me was, first, the gentle and pleasant and approving\r manner in which he received the words of the young men, and then his\r quick sense of the wound which had been inflicted by the argument, and\r the readiness with which he healed it. He might be compared to a general\r rallying his defeated and broken army, urging them to accompany him and\r return to the field of argument.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"254"},"sequenceIndex":336},{"id":"plato-phaedo-255","text":"PHAEDO: You shall hear, for I was close to him on his right hand, seated\r on a sort of stool, and he on a couch which was a good deal higher.\r He stroked my head, and pressed the hair upon my neck--he had a way of\r playing with my hair; and then he said: To-morrow, Phaedo, I suppose\r that these fair locks of yours will be severed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"255"},"sequenceIndex":337},{"id":"plato-phaedo-256","text":"To-day, he replied, and not to-morrow, if this argument dies and we\r cannot bring it to life again, you and I will both shave our locks; and\r if I were you, and the argument got away from me, and I could not hold\r my ground against Simmias and Cebes, I would myself take an oath, like\r the Argives, not to wear hair any more until I had renewed the conflict\r and defeated them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"256"},"sequenceIndex":338},{"id":"plato-phaedo-257","text":"I summon you rather, I rejoined, not as Heracles summoning Iolaus, but\r as Iolaus might summon Heracles.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"257"},"sequenceIndex":339},{"id":"plato-phaedo-258","text":"That will do as well, he said. But first let us take care that we avoid\r a danger.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"258"},"sequenceIndex":340},{"id":"plato-phaedo-259","text":"Lest we become misologists, he replied, no worse thing can happen to a\r man than this. For as there are misanthropists or haters of men, there\r are also misologists or haters of ideas, and both spring from the same\r cause, which is ignorance of the world. Misanthropy arises out of the\r too great confidence of inexperience;--you trust a man and think him\r altogether true and sound and faithful, and then in a little while he\r turns out to be false and knavish; and then another and another, and\r when this has happened several times to a man, especially when it\r happens among those whom he deems t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"259"},"sequenceIndex":341},{"id":"plato-phaedo-260","text":"And is not the feeling discreditable? Is it not obvious that such an\r one having to deal with other men, was clearly without any experience of\r human nature; for experience would have taught him the true state of\r the case, that few are the good and few the evil, and that the great\r majority are in the interval between them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"260"},"sequenceIndex":342},{"id":"plato-phaedo-261","text":"I mean, he replied, as you might say of the very large and very small,\r that nothing is more uncommon than a very large or very small man; and\r this applies generally to all extremes, whether of great and small, or\r swift and slow, or fair and foul, or black and white: and whether\r the instances you select be men or dogs or anything else, few are the\r extremes, but many are in the mean between them. Did you never observe\r this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"261"},"sequenceIndex":343},{"id":"plato-phaedo-262","text":"And do you not imagine, he said, that if there were a competition in\r evil, the worst would be found to be very few?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"262"},"sequenceIndex":344},{"id":"plato-phaedo-263","text":"Yes, that is very likely, he replied; although in this respect arguments\r are unlike men--there I was led on by you to say more than I had\r intended; but the point of comparison was, that when a simple man who\r has no skill in dialectics believes an argument to be true which he\r afterwards imagines to be false, whether really false or not, and\r then another and another, he has no longer any faith left, and great\r disputers, as you know, come to think at last that they have grown to be\r the wisest of mankind; for they alone perceive the utter unsoundness and\r instability of all arguments, or in","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"263"},"sequenceIndex":345},{"id":"plato-phaedo-264","text":"Yes, Phaedo, he replied, and how melancholy, if there be such a thing as\r truth or certainty or possibility of knowledge--that a man should have\r lighted upon some argument or other which at first seemed true and then\r turned out to be false, and instead of blaming himself and his own want\r of wit, because he is annoyed, should at last be too glad to transfer\r the blame from himself to arguments in general: and for ever afterwards\r should hate and revile them, and lose truth and the knowledge of\r realities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"264"},"sequenceIndex":346},{"id":"plato-phaedo-265","text":"Let us then, in the first place, he said, be careful of allowing or of\r admitting into our souls the notion that there is no health or soundness\r in any arguments at all. Rather say that we have not yet attained to\r soundness in ourselves, and that we must struggle manfully and do our\r best to gain health of mind--you and all other men having regard to the\r whole of your future life, and I myself in the prospect of death. For at\r this moment I am sensible that I have not the temper of a philosopher;\r like the vulgar, I am only a partisan. Now the partisan, when he is\r engaged in a dispute, car","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"265"},"sequenceIndex":347},{"id":"plato-phaedo-266","text":"And now let us proceed, he said. And first of all let me be sure that\r I have in my mind what you were saying. Simmias, if I remember rightly,\r has fears and misgivings whether the soul, although a fairer and diviner\r thing than the body, being as she is in the form of harmony, may not\r perish first. On the other hand, Cebes appeared to grant that the soul\r was more lasting than the body, but he said that no one could know\r whether the soul, after having worn out many bodies, might not perish\r herself and leave her last body behind her; and that this is death,\r which is the destruction not of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"266"},"sequenceIndex":348},{"id":"plato-phaedo-267","text":"He proceeded: And did you deny the force of the whole preceding\r argument, or of a part only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"267"},"sequenceIndex":349},{"id":"plato-phaedo-268","text":"And what did you think, he said, of that part of the argument in which\r we said that knowledge was recollection, and hence inferred that the\r soul must have previously existed somewhere else before she was enclosed\r in the body?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"268"},"sequenceIndex":350},{"id":"plato-phaedo-269","text":"Cebes said that he had been wonderfully impressed by that part of the\r argument, and that his conviction remained absolutely unshaken. Simmias\r agreed, and added that he himself could hardly imagine the possibility\r of his ever thinking differently.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"269"},"sequenceIndex":351},{"id":"plato-phaedo-270","text":"But, rejoined Socrates, you will have to think differently, my Theban\r friend, if you still maintain that harmony is a compound, and that the\r soul is a harmony which is made out of strings set in the frame of the\r body; for you will surely never allow yourself to say that a harmony is\r prior to the elements which compose it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"270"},"sequenceIndex":352},{"id":"plato-phaedo-271","text":"But do you not see that this is what you imply when you say that the\r soul existed before she took the form and body of man, and was made up\r of elements which as yet had no existence? For harmony is not like\r the soul, as you suppose; but first the lyre, and the strings, and the\r sounds exist in a state of discord, and then harmony is made last of\r all, and perishes first. And how can such a notion of the soul as this\r agree with the other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"271"},"sequenceIndex":353},{"id":"plato-phaedo-272","text":"And yet, he said, there surely ought to be harmony in a discourse of\r which harmony is the theme.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"272"},"sequenceIndex":354},{"id":"plato-phaedo-273","text":"But there is no harmony, he said, in the two propositions that knowledge\r is recollection, and that the soul is a harmony. Which of them will you\r retain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"273"},"sequenceIndex":355},{"id":"plato-phaedo-274","text":"I think, he replied, that I have a much stronger faith, Socrates, in the\r first of the two, which has been fully demonstrated to me, than in\r the latter, which has not been demonstrated at all, but rests only on\r probable and plausible grounds; and is therefore believed by the many. I\r know too well that these arguments from probabilities are impostors, and\r unless great caution is observed in the use of them, they are apt to\r be deceptive--in geometry, and in other things too. But the doctrine of\r knowledge and recollection has been proven to me on trustworthy grounds;\r and the proof was that","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"274"},"sequenceIndex":356},{"id":"plato-phaedo-275","text":"Let me put the matter, Simmias, he said, in another point of view: Do\r you imagine that a harmony or any other composition can be in a state\r other than that of the elements, out of which it is compounded?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"275"},"sequenceIndex":357},{"id":"plato-phaedo-276","text":"Then a harmony does not, properly speaking, lead the parts or elements\r which make up the harmony, but only follows them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"276"},"sequenceIndex":358},{"id":"plato-phaedo-277","text":"For harmony cannot possibly have any motion, or sound, or other quality\r which is opposed to its parts.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"277"},"sequenceIndex":359},{"id":"plato-phaedo-278","text":"And does not the nature of every harmony depend upon the manner in which\r the elements are harmonized?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"278"},"sequenceIndex":360},{"id":"plato-phaedo-279","text":"I mean to say that a harmony admits of degrees, and is more of a\r harmony, and more completely a harmony, when more truly and fully\r harmonized, to any extent which is possible; and less of a harmony, and\r less completely a harmony, when less truly and fully harmonized.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"279"},"sequenceIndex":361},{"id":"plato-phaedo-280","text":"But does the soul admit of degrees? or is one soul in the very least\r degree more or less, or more or less completely, a soul than another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"280"},"sequenceIndex":362},{"id":"plato-phaedo-281","text":"Yet surely of two souls, one is said to have intelligence and virtue,\r and to be good, and the other to have folly and vice, and to be an evil\r soul: and this is said truly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"281"},"sequenceIndex":363},{"id":"plato-phaedo-282","text":"But what will those who maintain the soul to be a harmony say of this\r presence of virtue and vice in the soul?--will they say that here is\r another harmony, and another discord, and that the virtuous soul is\r harmonized, and herself being a harmony has another harmony within her,\r and that the vicious soul is inharmonical and has no harmony within her?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"282"},"sequenceIndex":364},{"id":"plato-phaedo-283","text":"I cannot tell, replied Simmias; but I suppose that something of the sort\r would be asserted by those who say that the soul is a harmony.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"283"},"sequenceIndex":365},{"id":"plato-phaedo-284","text":"And we have already admitted that no soul is more a soul than another;\r which is equivalent to admitting that harmony is not more or less\r harmony, or more or less completely a harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"284"},"sequenceIndex":366},{"id":"plato-phaedo-285","text":"And that which is not more or less harmonized cannot have more or less\r of harmony, but only an equal harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"285"},"sequenceIndex":367},{"id":"plato-phaedo-286","text":"Then one soul not being more or less absolutely a soul than another, is\r not more or less harmonized?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"286"},"sequenceIndex":368},{"id":"plato-phaedo-287","text":"And having neither more nor less of harmony or of discord, one soul\r has no more vice or virtue than another, if vice be discord and virtue\r harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"287"},"sequenceIndex":369},{"id":"plato-phaedo-288","text":"Or speaking more correctly, Simmias, the soul, if she is a harmony, will\r never have any vice; because a harmony, being absolutely a harmony, has\r no part in the inharmonical.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"288"},"sequenceIndex":370},{"id":"plato-phaedo-289","text":"Then, if all souls are equally by their nature souls, all souls of all\r living creatures will be equally good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"289"},"sequenceIndex":371},{"id":"plato-phaedo-290","text":"And can all this be true, think you? he said; for these are the\r consequences which seem to follow from the assumption that the soul is a\r harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"290"},"sequenceIndex":372},{"id":"plato-phaedo-291","text":"Once more, he said, what ruler is there of the elements of human nature\r other than the soul, and especially the wise soul? Do you know of any?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"291"},"sequenceIndex":373},{"id":"plato-phaedo-292","text":"And is the soul in agreement with the affections of the body? or is she\r at variance with them? For example, when the body is hot and thirsty,\r does not the soul incline us against drinking? and when the body\r is hungry, against eating? And this is only one instance out of ten\r thousand of the opposition of the soul to the things of the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"292"},"sequenceIndex":374},{"id":"plato-phaedo-293","text":"But we have already acknowledged that the soul, being a harmony, can\r never utter a note at variance with the tensions and relaxations and\r vibrations and other affections of the strings out of which she is\r composed; she can only follow, she cannot lead them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"293"},"sequenceIndex":375},{"id":"plato-phaedo-294","text":"And yet do we not now discover the soul to be doing the exact\r opposite--leading the elements of which she is believed to be composed;\r almost always opposing and coercing them in all sorts of ways throughout\r life, sometimes more violently with the pains of medicine and gymnastic;\r then again more gently; now threatening, now admonishing the desires,\r passions, fears, as if talking to a thing which is not herself, as Homer\r in the Odyssee represents Odysseus doing in the words--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"294"},"sequenceIndex":376},{"id":"plato-phaedo-295","text":"'He beat his breast, and thus reproached his heart: Endure, my heart;\r far worse hast thou endured!'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"295"},"sequenceIndex":377},{"id":"plato-phaedo-296","text":"Do you think that Homer wrote this under the idea that the soul is a\r harmony capable of being led by the affections of the body, and not\r rather of a nature which should lead and master them--herself a far\r diviner thing than any harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"296"},"sequenceIndex":378},{"id":"plato-phaedo-297","text":"Then, my friend, we can never be right in saying that the soul is a\r harmony, for we should contradict the divine Homer, and contradict\r ourselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"297"},"sequenceIndex":379},{"id":"plato-phaedo-298","text":"Thus much, said Socrates, of Harmonia, your Theban goddess, who has\r graciously yielded to us; but what shall I say, Cebes, to her husband\r Cadmus, and how shall I make peace with him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"298"},"sequenceIndex":380},{"id":"plato-phaedo-299","text":"I think that you will discover a way of propitiating him, said Cebes; I\r am sure that you have put the argument with Harmonia in a manner that\r I could never have expected. For when Simmias was mentioning his\r difficulty, I quite imagined that no answer could be given to him, and\r therefore I was surprised at finding that his argument could not sustain\r the first onset of yours, and not impossibly the other, whom you call\r Cadmus, may share a similar fate.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"299"},"sequenceIndex":381},{"id":"plato-phaedo-300","text":"Nay, my good friend, said Socrates, let us not boast, lest some evil eye\r should put to flight the word which I am about to speak. That, however,\r may be left in the hands of those above, while I draw near in Homeric\r fashion, and try the mettle of your words. Here lies the point:--You\r want to have it proven to you that the soul is imperishable and\r immortal, and the philosopher who is confident in death appears to you\r to have but a vain and foolish confidence, if he believes that he will\r fare better in the world below than one who has led another sort of\r life, unless he can prove this; an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"300"},"sequenceIndex":382},{"id":"plato-phaedo-301","text":"But, said Cebes, as far as I see at present, I have nothing to add or\r subtract: I mean what you say that I mean.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"301"},"sequenceIndex":383},{"id":"plato-phaedo-302","text":"Socrates paused awhile, and seemed to be absorbed in reflection. At\r length he said: You are raising a tremendous question, Cebes, involving\r the whole nature of generation and corruption, about which, if you like,\r I will give you my own experience; and if anything which I say is likely\r to avail towards the solution of your difficulty you may make use of it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"302"},"sequenceIndex":384},{"id":"plato-phaedo-303","text":"Then I will tell you, said Socrates. When I was young, Cebes, I had a\r prodigious desire to know that department of philosophy which is called\r the investigation of nature; to know the causes of things, and why\r a thing is and is created or destroyed appeared to me to be a lofty\r profession; and I was always agitating myself with the consideration of\r questions such as these:--Is the growth of animals the result of some\r decay which the hot and cold principle contracts, as some have said? Is\r the blood the element with which we think, or the air, or the fire? or\r perhaps nothing of the kind--b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"303"},"sequenceIndex":385},{"id":"plato-phaedo-304","text":"Well; but let me tell you something more. There was a time when I\r thought that I understood the meaning of greater and less pretty well;\r and when I saw a great man standing by a little one, I fancied that one\r was taller than the other by a head; or one horse would appear to\r be greater than another horse: and still more clearly did I seem to\r perceive that ten is two more than eight, and that two cubits are more\r than one, because two is the double of one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"304"},"sequenceIndex":386},{"id":"plato-phaedo-305","text":"I should be far enough from imagining, he replied, that I knew the cause\r of any of them, by heaven I should; for I cannot satisfy myself that,\r when one is added to one, the one to which the addition is made becomes\r two, or that the two units added together make two by reason of the\r addition. I cannot understand how, when separated from the other, each\r of them was one and not two, and now, when they are brought together,\r the mere juxtaposition or meeting of them should be the cause of their\r becoming two: neither can I understand how the division of one is the\r way to make two; for then a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"305"},"sequenceIndex":387},{"id":"plato-phaedo-306","text":"Then I heard some one reading, as he said, from a book of Anaxagoras,\r that mind was the disposer and cause of all, and I was delighted at this\r notion, which appeared quite admirable, and I said to myself: If mind\r is the disposer, mind will dispose all for the best, and put each\r particular in the best place; and I argued that if any one desired to\r find out the cause of the generation or destruction or existence of\r anything, he must find out what state of being or doing or suffering was\r best for that thing, and therefore a man had only to consider the best\r for himself and others, and the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"306"},"sequenceIndex":388},{"id":"plato-phaedo-307","text":"What expectations I had formed, and how grievously was I disappointed!\r As I proceeded, I found my philosopher altogether forsaking mind or any\r other principle of order, but having recourse to air, and ether, and\r water, and other eccentricities. I might compare him to a person who\r began by maintaining generally that mind is the cause of the actions\r of Socrates, but who, when he endeavoured to explain the causes of my\r several actions in detail, went on to show that I sit here because my\r body is made up of bones and muscles; and the bones, as he would say,\r are hard and have joints which d","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"307"},"sequenceIndex":389},{"id":"plato-phaedo-308","text":"Socrates proceeded:--I thought that as I had failed in the contemplation\r of true existence, I ought to be careful that I did not lose the eye of\r my soul; as people may injure their bodily eye by observing and gazing\r on the sun during an eclipse, unless they take the precaution of only\r looking at the image reflected in the water, or in some similar medium.\r So in my own case, I was afraid that my soul might be blinded altogether\r if I looked at things with my eyes or tried to apprehend them by the\r help of the senses. And I thought that I had better have recourse to the\r world of mind and s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"308"},"sequenceIndex":390},{"id":"plato-phaedo-309","text":"There is nothing new, he said, in what I am about to tell you; but\r only what I have been always and everywhere repeating in the previous\r discussion and on other occasions: I want to show you the nature of that\r cause which has occupied my thoughts. I shall have to go back to those\r familiar words which are in the mouth of every one, and first of all\r assume that there is an absolute beauty and goodness and greatness, and\r the like; grant me this, and I hope to be able to show you the nature of\r the cause, and to prove the immortality of the soul.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"309"},"sequenceIndex":391},{"id":"plato-phaedo-310","text":"Well, he said, then I should like to know whether you agree with me\r in the next step; for I cannot help thinking, if there be anything\r beautiful other than absolute beauty should there be such, that it can\r be beautiful only in as far as it partakes of absolute beauty--and I\r should say the same of everything. Do you agree in this notion of the\r cause?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"310"},"sequenceIndex":392},{"id":"plato-phaedo-311","text":"He proceeded: I know nothing and can understand nothing of any other of\r those wise causes which are alleged; and if a person says to me that\r the bloom of colour, or form, or any such thing is a source of beauty,\r I leave all that, which is only confusing to me, and simply and singly,\r and perhaps foolishly, hold and am assured in my own mind that nothing\r makes a thing beautiful but the presence and participation of beauty in\r whatever way or manner obtained; for as to the manner I am uncertain,\r but I stoutly contend that by beauty all beautiful things become\r beautiful. This appears to me ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"311"},"sequenceIndex":393},{"id":"plato-phaedo-312","text":"And that by greatness only great things become great and greater\r greater, and by smallness the less become less?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"312"},"sequenceIndex":394},{"id":"plato-phaedo-313","text":"Then if a person were to remark that A is taller by a head than B, and\r B less by a head than A, you would refuse to admit his statement, and\r would stoutly contend that what you mean is only that the greater is\r greater by, and by reason of, greatness, and the less is less only by,\r and by reason of, smallness; and thus you would avoid the danger of\r saying that the greater is greater and the less less by the measure of\r the head, which is the same in both, and would also avoid the monstrous\r absurdity of supposing that the greater man is greater by reason of the\r head, which is small. You wo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"313"},"sequenceIndex":395},{"id":"plato-phaedo-314","text":"In like manner you would be afraid to say that ten exceeded eight by,\r and by reason of, two; but would say by, and by reason of, number; or\r you would say that two cubits exceed one cubit not by a half, but by\r magnitude?-for there is the same liability to error in all these cases.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"314"},"sequenceIndex":396},{"id":"plato-phaedo-315","text":"Again, would you not be cautious of affirming that the addition of\r one to one, or the division of one, is the cause of two? And you would\r loudly asseverate that you know of no way in which anything comes\r into existence except by participation in its own proper essence,\r and consequently, as far as you know, the only cause of two is\r the participation in duality--this is the way to make two, and the\r participation in one is the way to make one. You would say: I will let\r alone puzzles of division and addition--wiser heads than mine may answer\r them; inexperienced as I am, and ready to start,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"315"},"sequenceIndex":397},{"id":"plato-phaedo-316","text":"ECHECRATES: Yes, Phaedo; and I do not wonder at their assenting. Any\r one who has the least sense will acknowledge the wonderful clearness of\r Socrates' reasoning.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"316"},"sequenceIndex":398},{"id":"plato-phaedo-317","text":"PHAEDO: Certainly, Echecrates; and such was the feeling of the whole\r company at the time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"317"},"sequenceIndex":399},{"id":"plato-phaedo-318","text":"ECHECRATES: Yes, and equally of ourselves, who were not of the company,\r and are now listening to your recital. But what followed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"318"},"sequenceIndex":400},{"id":"plato-phaedo-319","text":"PHAEDO: After all this had been admitted, and they had that ideas exist,\r and that other things participate in them and derive their names from\r them, Socrates, if I remember rightly, said:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"319"},"sequenceIndex":401},{"id":"plato-phaedo-320","text":"This is your way of speaking; and yet when you say that Simmias is\r greater than Socrates and less than Phaedo, do you not predicate of\r Simmias both greatness and smallness?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"320"},"sequenceIndex":402},{"id":"plato-phaedo-321","text":"But still you allow that Simmias does not really exceed Socrates, as\r the words may seem to imply, because he is Simmias, but by reason of the\r size which he has; just as Simmias does not exceed Socrates because he\r is Simmias, any more than because Socrates is Socrates, but because he\r has smallness when compared with the greatness of Simmias?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"321"},"sequenceIndex":403},{"id":"plato-phaedo-322","text":"And if Phaedo exceeds him in size, this is not because Phaedo is\r Phaedo, but because Phaedo has greatness relatively to Simmias, who is\r comparatively smaller?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"322"},"sequenceIndex":404},{"id":"plato-phaedo-323","text":"And therefore Simmias is said to be great, and is also said to be small,\r because he is in a mean between them, exceeding the smallness of the one\r by his greatness, and allowing the greatness of the other to exceed his\r smallness. He added, laughing, I am speaking like a book, but I believe\r that what I am saying is true.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"323"},"sequenceIndex":405},{"id":"plato-phaedo-324","text":"I speak as I do because I want you to agree with me in thinking, not\r only that absolute greatness will never be great and also small, but\r that greatness in us or in the concrete will never admit the small or\r admit of being exceeded: instead of this, one of two things will happen,\r either the greater will fly or retire before the opposite, which is the\r less, or at the approach of the less has already ceased to exist; but\r will not, if allowing or admitting of smallness, be changed by that;\r even as I, having received and admitted smallness when compared with\r Simmias, remain just as I was, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"324"},"sequenceIndex":406},{"id":"plato-phaedo-325","text":"Hereupon one of the company, though I do not exactly remember which of\r them, said: In heaven's name, is not this the direct contrary of what\r was admitted before--that out of the greater came the less and out of\r the less the greater, and that opposites were simply generated from\r opposites; but now this principle seems to be utterly denied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"325"},"sequenceIndex":407},{"id":"plato-phaedo-326","text":"Socrates inclined his head to the speaker and listened. I like your\r courage, he said, in reminding us of this. But you do not observe that\r there is a difference in the two cases. For then we were speaking of\r opposites in the concrete, and now of the essential opposite which, as\r is affirmed, neither in us nor in nature can ever be at variance with\r itself: then, my friend, we were speaking of things in which opposites\r are inherent and which are called after them, but now about the\r opposites which are inherent in them and which give their name to them;\r and these essential opposites will n","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"326"},"sequenceIndex":408},{"id":"plato-phaedo-327","text":"No, I do not feel so, said Cebes; and yet I cannot deny that I am often\r disturbed by objections.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"327"},"sequenceIndex":409},{"id":"plato-phaedo-328","text":"Then we are agreed after all, said Socrates, that the opposite will\r never in any case be opposed to itself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"328"},"sequenceIndex":410},{"id":"plato-phaedo-329","text":"Yet once more let me ask you to consider the question from another point\r of view, and see whether you agree with me:--There is a thing which you\r term heat, and another thing which you term cold?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"329"},"sequenceIndex":411},{"id":"plato-phaedo-330","text":"And yet you will surely admit, that when snow, as was before said, is\r under the influence of heat, they will not remain snow and heat; but at\r the advance of the heat, the snow will either retire or perish?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"330"},"sequenceIndex":412},{"id":"plato-phaedo-331","text":"And the fire too at the advance of the cold will either retire or\r perish; and when the fire is under the influence of the cold, they will\r not remain as before, fire and cold.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"331"},"sequenceIndex":413},{"id":"plato-phaedo-332","text":"And in some cases the name of the idea is not only attached to the idea\r in an eternal connection, but anything else which, not being the idea,\r exists only in the form of the idea, may also lay claim to it. I will\r try to make this clearer by an example:--The odd number is always called\r by the name of odd?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"332"},"sequenceIndex":414},{"id":"plato-phaedo-333","text":"But is this the only thing which is called odd? Are there not other\r things which have their own name, and yet are called odd, because,\r although not the same as oddness, they are never without oddness?--that\r is what I mean to ask--whether numbers such as the number three are not\r of the class of odd. And there are many other examples: would you not\r say, for example, that three may be called by its proper name, and also\r be called odd, which is not the same with three? and this may be said\r not only of three but also of five, and of every alternate number--each\r of them without being oddness","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"333"},"sequenceIndex":415},{"id":"plato-phaedo-334","text":"Then now mark the point at which I am aiming:--not only do essential\r opposites exclude one another, but also concrete things, which, although\r not in themselves opposed, contain opposites; these, I say, likewise\r reject the idea which is opposed to that which is contained in them,\r and when it approaches them they either perish or withdraw. For example;\r Will not the number three endure annihilation or anything sooner than be\r converted into an even number, while remaining three?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"334"},"sequenceIndex":416},{"id":"plato-phaedo-335","text":"Then not only do opposite ideas repel the advance of one another, but\r also there are other natures which repel the approach of opposites.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"335"},"sequenceIndex":417},{"id":"plato-phaedo-336","text":"Are they not, Cebes, such as compel the things of which they have\r possession, not only to take their own form, but also the form of some\r opposite?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"336"},"sequenceIndex":418},{"id":"plato-phaedo-337","text":"I mean, as I was just now saying, and as I am sure that you know, that\r those things which are possessed by the number three must not only be\r three in number, but must also be odd.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"337"},"sequenceIndex":419},{"id":"plato-phaedo-338","text":"And on this oddness, of which the number three has the impress, the\r opposite idea will never intrude?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"338"},"sequenceIndex":420},{"id":"plato-phaedo-339","text":"To return then to my distinction of natures which are not opposed, and\r yet do not admit opposites--as, in the instance given, three, although\r not opposed to the even, does not any the more admit of the even, but\r always brings the opposite into play on the other side; or as two does\r not receive the odd, or fire the cold--from these examples (and there\r are many more of them) perhaps you may be able to arrive at the general\r conclusion, that not only opposites will not receive opposites, but also\r that nothing which brings the opposite will admit the opposite of\r that which it brings, in tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"339"},"sequenceIndex":421},{"id":"plato-phaedo-340","text":"And now, he said, let us begin again; and do not you answer my question\r in the words in which I ask it: let me have not the old safe answer of\r which I spoke at first, but another equally safe, of which the truth\r will be inferred by you from what has been just said. I mean that if any\r one asks you 'what that is, of which the inherence makes the body\r hot,' you will reply not heat (this is what I call the safe and\r stupid answer), but fire, a far superior answer, which we are now in a\r condition to give. Or if any one asks you 'why a body is diseased,' you\r will not say from disease, but fro","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"340"},"sequenceIndex":422},{"id":"plato-phaedo-341","text":"Then the soul, as has been acknowledged, will never receive the opposite\r of what she brings.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"341"},"sequenceIndex":423},{"id":"plato-phaedo-342","text":"And now, he said, what did we just now call that principle which repels\r the even?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"342"},"sequenceIndex":424},{"id":"plato-phaedo-343","text":"And if that which is cold were imperishable, when the warm principle\r came attacking the snow, must not the snow have retired whole and\r unmelted--for it could never have perished, nor could it have remained\r and admitted the heat?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"343"},"sequenceIndex":425},{"id":"plato-phaedo-344","text":"Again, if the uncooling or warm principle were imperishable, the fire\r when assailed by cold would not have perished or have been extinguished,\r but would have gone away unaffected?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"344"},"sequenceIndex":426},{"id":"plato-phaedo-345","text":"And the same may be said of the immortal: if the immortal is also\r imperishable, the soul when attacked by death cannot perish; for the\r preceding argument shows that the soul will not admit of death, or ever\r be dead, any more than three or the odd number will admit of the even,\r or fire or the heat in the fire, of the cold. Yet a person may say: 'But\r although the odd will not become even at the approach of the even, why\r may not the odd perish and the even take the place of the odd?' Now to\r him who makes this objection, we cannot answer that the odd principle is\r imperishable; for this has","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"345"},"sequenceIndex":427},{"id":"plato-phaedo-346","text":"And the same may be said of the immortal: if the immortal is also\r imperishable, then the soul will be imperishable as well as immortal;\r but if not, some other proof of her imperishableness will have to be\r given.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"346"},"sequenceIndex":428},{"id":"plato-phaedo-347","text":"No other proof is needed, he said; for if the immortal, being eternal,\r is liable to perish, then nothing is imperishable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"347"},"sequenceIndex":429},{"id":"plato-phaedo-348","text":"Yes, replied Socrates, and yet all men will agree that God, and the\r essential form of life, and the immortal in general, will never perish.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"348"},"sequenceIndex":430},{"id":"plato-phaedo-349","text":"Yes, all men, he said--that is true; and what is more, gods, if I am not\r mistaken, as well as men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"349"},"sequenceIndex":431},{"id":"plato-phaedo-350","text":"Seeing then that the immortal is indestructible, must not the soul, if\r she is immortal, be also imperishable?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"350"},"sequenceIndex":432},{"id":"plato-phaedo-351","text":"Then when death attacks a man, the mortal portion of him may be supposed\r to die, but the immortal retires at the approach of death and is\r preserved safe and sound?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"351"},"sequenceIndex":433},{"id":"plato-phaedo-352","text":"Then, Cebes, beyond question, the soul is immortal and imperishable, and\r our souls will truly exist in another world!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"352"},"sequenceIndex":434},{"id":"plato-phaedo-353","text":"I am convinced, Socrates, said Cebes, and have nothing more to object;\r but if my friend Simmias, or any one else, has any further objection to\r make, he had better speak out, and not keep silence, since I do not know\r to what other season he can defer the discussion, if there is anything\r which he wants to say or to have said.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"353"},"sequenceIndex":435},{"id":"plato-phaedo-354","text":"But I have nothing more to say, replied Simmias; nor can I see any\r reason for doubt after what has been said. But I still feel and cannot\r help feeling uncertain in my own mind, when I think of the greatness of\r the subject and the feebleness of man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"354"},"sequenceIndex":436},{"id":"plato-phaedo-355","text":"Yes, Simmias, replied Socrates, that is well said: and I may add that\r first principles, even if they appear certain, should be carefully\r considered; and when they are satisfactorily ascertained, then, with a\r sort of hesitating confidence in human reason, you may, I think, follow\r the course of the argument; and if that be plain and clear, there will\r be no need for any further enquiry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"355"},"sequenceIndex":437},{"id":"plato-phaedo-356","text":"But then, O my friends, he said, if the soul is really immortal, what\r care should be taken of her, not only in respect of the portion of time\r which is called life, but of eternity! And the danger of neglecting her\r from this point of view does indeed appear to be awful. If death had\r only been the end of all, the wicked would have had a good bargain in\r dying, for they would have been happily quit not only of their body, but\r of their own evil together with their souls. But now, inasmuch as the\r soul is manifestly immortal, there is no release or salvation from evil\r except the attainment of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"356"},"sequenceIndex":438},{"id":"plato-phaedo-357","text":"For after death, as they say, the genius of each individual, to whom\r he belonged in life, leads him to a certain place in which the dead are\r gathered together, whence after judgment has been given they pass into\r the world below, following the guide, who is appointed to conduct them\r from this world to the other: and when they have there received their\r due and remained their time, another guide brings them back again after\r many revolutions of ages. Now this way to the other world is not, as\r Aeschylus says in the Telephus, a single and straight path--if that were\r so no guide would be need","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"357"},"sequenceIndex":439},{"id":"plato-phaedo-358","text":"Now the earth has divers wonderful regions, and is indeed in nature\r and extent very unlike the notions of geographers, as I believe on the\r authority of one who shall be nameless.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"358"},"sequenceIndex":440},{"id":"plato-phaedo-359","text":"What do you mean, Socrates? said Simmias. I have myself heard many\r descriptions of the earth, but I do not know, and I should very much\r like to know, in which of these you put faith.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"359"},"sequenceIndex":441},{"id":"plato-phaedo-360","text":"And I, Simmias, replied Socrates, if I had the art of Glaucus would tell\r you; although I know not that the art of Glaucus could prove the truth\r of my tale, which I myself should never be able to prove, and even if\r I could, I fear, Simmias, that my life would come to an end before the\r argument was completed. I may describe to you, however, the form and\r regions of the earth according to my conception of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"360"},"sequenceIndex":442},{"id":"plato-phaedo-361","text":"Well, then, he said, my conviction is, that the earth is a round body\r in the centre of the heavens, and therefore has no need of air or any\r similar force to be a support, but is kept there and hindered from\r falling or inclining any way by the equability of the surrounding heaven\r and by her own equipoise. For that which, being in equipoise, is in the\r centre of that which is equably diffused, will not incline any way in\r any degree, but will always remain in the same state and not deviate.\r And this is my first notion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"361"},"sequenceIndex":443},{"id":"plato-phaedo-362","text":"Also I believe that the earth is very vast, and that we who dwell in\r the region extending from the river Phasis to the Pillars of Heracles\r inhabit a small portion only about the sea, like ants or frogs about a\r marsh, and that there are other inhabitants of many other like places;\r for everywhere on the face of the earth there are hollows of various\r forms and sizes, into which the water and the mist and the lower\r air collect. But the true earth is pure and situated in the pure\r heaven--there are the stars also; and it is the heaven which is commonly\r spoken of by us as the ether, and of wh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"362"},"sequenceIndex":444},{"id":"plato-phaedo-363","text":"The tale, my friend, he said, is as follows:--In the first place, the\r earth, when looked at from above, is in appearance streaked like one of\r those balls which have leather coverings in twelve pieces, and is decked\r with various colours, of which the colours used by painters on earth are\r in a manner samples. But there the whole earth is made up of them,\r and they are brighter far and clearer than ours; there is a purple of\r wonderful lustre, also the radiance of gold, and the white which is in\r the earth is whiter than any chalk or snow. Of these and other colours\r the earth is made up, and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"363"},"sequenceIndex":445},{"id":"plato-phaedo-364","text":"Such is the nature of the whole earth, and of the things which are\r around the earth; and there are divers regions in the hollows on the\r face of the globe everywhere, some of them deeper and more extended than\r that which we inhabit, others deeper but with a narrower opening\r than ours, and some are shallower and also wider. All have numerous\r perforations, and there are passages broad and narrow in the interior of\r the earth, connecting them with one another; and there flows out of and\r into them, as into basins, a vast tide of water, and huge subterranean\r streams of perennial rivers, and s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"364"},"sequenceIndex":446},{"id":"plato-phaedo-365","text":"and which he in other places, and many other poets, have called\r Tartarus. And the see-saw is caused by the streams flowing into and out\r of this chasm, and they each have the nature of the soil through which\r they flow. And the reason why the streams are always flowing in and out,\r is that the watery element has no bed or bottom, but is swinging and\r surging up and down, and the surrounding wind and air do the same; they\r follow the water up and down, hither and thither, over the earth--just\r as in the act of respiration the air is always in process of inhalation\r and exhalation;--and the win","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"365"},"sequenceIndex":447},{"id":"plato-phaedo-366","text":"Now these rivers are many, and mighty, and diverse, and there are four\r principal ones, of which the greatest and outermost is that called\r Oceanus, which flows round the earth in a circle; and in the opposite\r direction flows Acheron, which passes under the earth through desert\r places into the Acherusian lake: this is the lake to the shores of\r which the souls of the many go when they are dead, and after waiting an\r appointed time, which is to some a longer and to some a shorter time,\r they are sent back to be born again as animals. The third river passes\r out between the two, and near the p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"366"},"sequenceIndex":448},{"id":"plato-phaedo-367","text":"Such is the nature of the other world; and when the dead arrive at the\r place to which the genius of each severally guides them, first of all,\r they have sentence passed upon them, as they have lived well and piously\r or not. And those who appear to have lived neither well nor ill, go to\r the river Acheron, and embarking in any vessels which they may find, are\r carried in them to the lake, and there they dwell and are purified of\r their evil deeds, and having suffered the penalty of the wrongs which\r they have done to others, they are absolved, and receive the rewards of\r their good deeds, eac","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"367"},"sequenceIndex":449},{"id":"plato-phaedo-368","text":"Wherefore, Simmias, seeing all these things, what ought not we to do\r that we may obtain virtue and wisdom in this life? Fair is the prize,\r and the hope great!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"368"},"sequenceIndex":450},{"id":"plato-phaedo-369","text":"A man of sense ought not to say, nor will I be very confident, that the\r description which I have given of the soul and her mansions is exactly\r true. But I do say that, inasmuch as the soul is shown to be immortal,\r he may venture to think, not improperly or unworthily, that something of\r the kind is true. The venture is a glorious one, and he ought to comfort\r himself with words like these, which is the reason why I lengthen out\r the tale. Wherefore, I say, let a man be of good cheer about his soul,\r who having cast away the pleasures and ornaments of the body as alien to\r him and working ha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"369"},"sequenceIndex":451},{"id":"plato-phaedo-370","text":"When he had done speaking, Crito said: And have you any commands for us,\r Socrates--anything to say about your children, or any other matter in\r which we can serve you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"370"},"sequenceIndex":452},{"id":"plato-phaedo-371","text":"Nothing particular, Crito, he replied: only, as I have always told\r you, take care of yourselves; that is a service which you may be ever\r rendering to me and mine and to all of us, whether you promise to do so\r or not. But if you have no thought for yourselves, and care not to walk\r according to the rule which I have prescribed for you, not now for the\r first time, however much you may profess or promise at the moment, it\r will be of no avail.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"371"},"sequenceIndex":453},{"id":"plato-phaedo-372","text":"In any way that you like; but you must get hold of me, and take care\r that I do not run away from you. Then he turned to us, and added with a\r smile:--I cannot make Crito believe that I am the same Socrates who have\r been talking and conducting the argument; he fancies that I am the other\r Socrates whom he will soon see, a dead body--and he asks, How shall he\r bury me? And though I have spoken many words in the endeavour to show\r that when I have drunk the poison I shall leave you and go to the joys\r of the blessed,--these words of mine, with which I was comforting you\r and myself, have had, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"372"},"sequenceIndex":454},{"id":"plato-phaedo-373","text":"When he had spoken these words, he arose and went into a chamber to\r bathe; Crito followed him and told us to wait. So we remained behind,\r talking and thinking of the subject of discourse, and also of the\r greatness of our sorrow; he was like a father of whom we were being\r bereaved, and we were about to pass the rest of our lives as orphans.\r When he had taken the bath his children were brought to him--(he had two\r young sons and an elder one); and the women of his family also came,\r and he talked to them and gave them a few directions in the presence of\r Crito; then he dismissed them and re","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"373"},"sequenceIndex":455},{"id":"plato-phaedo-374","text":"Now the hour of sunset was near, for a good deal of time had passed\r while he was within. When he came out, he sat down with us again after\r his bath, but not much was said. Soon the jailer, who was the servant of\r the Eleven, entered and stood by him, saying:--To you, Socrates, whom\r I know to be the noblest and gentlest and best of all who ever came to\r this place, I will not impute the angry feelings of other men, who rage\r and swear at me, when, in obedience to the authorities, I bid them drink\r the poison--indeed, I am sure that you will not be angry with me; for\r others, as you are aware","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"374"},"sequenceIndex":456},{"id":"plato-phaedo-375","text":"Socrates looked at him and said: I return your good wishes, and will do\r as you bid. Then turning to us, he said, How charming the man is: since\r I have been in prison he has always been coming to see me, and at times\r he would talk to me, and was as good to me as could be, and now see how\r generously he sorrows on my account. We must do as he says, Crito; and\r therefore let the cup be brought, if the poison is prepared: if not, let\r the attendant prepare some.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"375"},"sequenceIndex":457},{"id":"plato-phaedo-376","text":"Yet, said Crito, the sun is still upon the hill-tops, and I know that\r many a one has taken the draught late, and after the announcement has\r been made to him, he has eaten and drunk, and enjoyed the society of his\r beloved; do not hurry--there is time enough.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"376"},"sequenceIndex":458},{"id":"plato-phaedo-377","text":"Socrates said: Yes, Crito, and they of whom you speak are right in so\r acting, for they think that they will be gainers by the delay; but I am\r right in not following their example, for I do not think that I should\r gain anything by drinking the poison a little later; I should only be\r ridiculous in my own eyes for sparing and saving a life which is already\r forfeit. Please then to do as I say, and not to refuse me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"377"},"sequenceIndex":459},{"id":"plato-phaedo-378","text":"Crito made a sign to the servant, who was standing by; and he went out,\r and having been absent for some time, returned with the jailer\r carrying the cup of poison. Socrates said: You, my good friend, who\r are experienced in these matters, shall give me directions how I am to\r proceed. The man answered: You have only to walk about until your legs\r are heavy, and then to lie down, and the poison will act. At the same\r time he handed the cup to Socrates, who in the easiest and gentlest\r manner, without the least fear or change of colour or feature, looking\r at the man with all his eyes, Echecrat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"378"},"sequenceIndex":460},{"id":"plato-phaedo-379","text":"Such was the end, Echecrates, of our friend; concerning whom I may\r truly say, that of all the men of his time whom I have known, he was the\r wisest and justest and best.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Phaedo (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Phaedo","section":"379"},"sequenceIndex":461},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1","text":"The Republic of Plato is the longest of his works with the exception of\r the Laws, and is certainly the greatest of them. There are nearer\r approaches to modern metaphysics in the Philebus and in the Sophist;\r the Politicus or Statesman is more ideal; the form and institutions of\r the State are more clearly drawn out in the Laws; as works of art, the\r Symposium and the Protagoras are of higher excellence. But no other\r Dialogue of Plato has the same largeness of view and the same\r perfection of style; no other shows an equal knowledge of the world, or\r contains more of those thoughts which are","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1"},"sequenceIndex":462},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2","text":"Neither must we forget that the Republic is but the third part of a\r still larger design which was to have included an ideal history of\r Athens, as well as a political and physical philosophy. The fragment of\r the Critias has given birth to a world-famous fiction, second only in\r importance to the tale of Troy and the legend of Arthur; and is said as\r a fact to have inspired some of the early navigators of the sixteenth\r century. This mythical tale, of which the subject was a history of the\r wars of the Athenians against the Island of Atlantis, is supposed to be\r founded upon an unfinished poe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2"},"sequenceIndex":463},{"id":"plato-the-repu-3","text":"Again, Plato may be regarded as the ‘captain’ (‘arhchegoz’) or leader\r of a goodly band of followers; for in the Republic is to be found the\r original of Cicero’s De Republica, of St. Augustine’s City of God, of\r the Utopia of Sir Thomas More, and of the numerous other imaginary\r States which are framed upon the same model. The extent to which\r Aristotle or the Aristotelian school were indebted to him in the\r Politics has been little recognised, and the recognition is the more\r necessary because it is not made by Aristotle himself. The two\r philosophers had more in common than they were consci","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":464},{"id":"plato-the-repu-4","text":"The argument of the Republic is the search after Justice, the nature of\r which is first hinted at by Cephalus, the just and blameless old\r man—then discussed on the basis of proverbial morality by Socrates and\r Polemarchus—then caricatured by Thrasymachus and partially explained by\r Socrates—reduced to an abstraction by Glaucon and Adeimantus, and\r having become invisible in the individual reappears at length in the\r ideal State which is constructed by Socrates. The first care of the\r rulers is to be education, of which an outline is drawn after the old\r Hellenic model, providing only for an i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":465},{"id":"plato-the-repu-5","text":"The division into books, like all similar divisions (Cp. Sir G.C. Lewis\r in the Classical Museum, vol. ii. p 1.), is probably later than the age\r of Plato. The natural divisions are five in number;—(1) Book I and the\r first half of Book II down to the paragraph beginning, ‘I had always\r admired the genius of Glaucon and Adeimantus,’ which is introductory;\r the first book containing a refutation of the popular and sophistical\r notions of justice, and concluding, like some of the earlier Dialogues,\r without arriving at any definite result. To this is appended a\r restatement of the nature of just","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":466},{"id":"plato-the-repu-6","text":"Or a more general division into two parts may be adopted; the first\r (Books I - IV) containing the description of a State framed generally\r in accordance with Hellenic notions of religion and morality, while in\r the second (Books V - X) the Hellenic State is transformed into an\r ideal kingdom of philosophy, of which all other governments are the\r perversions. These two points of view are really opposed, and the\r opposition is only veiled by the genius of Plato. The Republic, like\r the Phaedrus (see Introduction to Phaedrus), is an imperfect whole; the\r higher light of philosophy breaks through","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":467},{"id":"plato-the-repu-7","text":"The second title, ‘Concerning Justice,’ is not the one by which the\r Republic is quoted, either by Aristotle or generally in antiquity, and,\r like the other second titles of the Platonic Dialogues, may therefore\r be assumed to be of later date. Morgenstern and others have asked\r whether the definition of justice, which is the professed aim, or the\r construction of the State is the principal argument of the work. The\r answer is, that the two blend in one, and are two faces of the same\r truth; for justice is the order of the State, and the State is the\r visible embodiment of justice under the co","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":468},{"id":"plato-the-repu-8","text":"Too much, however, has been made of this question both in ancient and\r modern times. There is a stage of criticism in which all works, whether\r of nature or of art, are referred to design. Now in ancient writings,\r and indeed in literature generally, there remains often a large element\r which was not comprehended in the original design. For the plan grows\r under the author’s hand; new thoughts occur to him in the act of\r writing; he has not worked out the argument to the end before he\r begins. The reader who seeks to find some one idea under which the\r whole may be conceived, must necessarily ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":469},{"id":"plato-the-repu-9","text":"Is not the Republic the vehicle of three or four great truths which, to\r Plato’s own mind, are most naturally represented in the form of the\r State? Just as in the Jewish prophets the reign of Messiah, or ‘the day\r of the Lord,’ or the suffering Servant or people of God, or the ‘Sun of\r righteousness with healing in his wings’ only convey, to us at least,\r their great spiritual ideals, so through the Greek State Plato reveals\r to us his own thoughts about divine perfection, which is the idea of\r good—like the sun in the visible world;—about human perfection, which\r is justice—about education b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":470},{"id":"plato-the-repu-10","text":"It is not necessary to discuss at length a minor question which has\r been raised by Boeckh, respecting the imaginary date at which the\r conversation was held (the year 411 B.C. which is proposed by him will\r do as well as any other); for a writer of fiction, and especially a\r writer who, like Plato, is notoriously careless of chronology (cp.\r Rep., Symp., 193 A, etc.), only aims at general probability. Whether\r all the persons mentioned in the Republic could ever have met at any\r one time is not a difficulty which would have occurred to an Athenian\r reading the work forty years later, or to Pl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":471},{"id":"plato-the-repu-11","text":"The principal characters in the Republic are Cephalus, Polemarchus,\r Thrasymachus, Socrates, Glaucon, and Adeimantus. Cephalus appears in\r the introduction only, Polemarchus drops at the end of the first\r argument, and Thrasymachus is reduced to silence at the close of the\r first book. The main discussion is carried on by Socrates, Glaucon, and\r Adeimantus. Among the company are Lysias (the orator) and Euthydemus,\r the sons of Cephalus and brothers of Polemarchus, an unknown\r Charmantides—these are mute auditors; also there is Cleitophon, who\r once interrupts, where, as in the Dialogue which b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":472},{"id":"plato-the-repu-12","text":"Cephalus, the patriarch of the house, has been appropriately engaged in\r offering a sacrifice. He is the pattern of an old man who has almost\r done with life, and is at peace with himself and with all mankind. He\r feels that he is drawing nearer to the world below, and seems to linger\r around the memory of the past. He is eager that Socrates should come to\r visit him, fond of the poetry of the last generation, happy in the\r consciousness of a well-spent life, glad at having escaped from the\r tyranny of youthful lusts. His love of conversation, his affection, his\r indifference to riches, even h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":473},{"id":"plato-the-repu-13","text":"His ‘son and heir’ Polemarchus has the frankness and impetuousness of\r youth; he is for detaining Socrates by force in the opening scene, and\r will not ‘let him off’ on the subject of women and children. Like\r Cephalus, he is limited in his point of view, and represents the\r proverbial stage of morality which has rules of life rather than\r principles; and he quotes Simonides (cp. Aristoph. Clouds) as his\r father had quoted Pindar. But after this he has no more to say; the\r answers which he makes are only elicited from him by the dialectic of\r Socrates. He has not yet experienced the influence ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":474},{"id":"plato-the-repu-14","text":"The ‘Chalcedonian giant,’ Thrasymachus, of whom we have already heard\r in the Phaedrus, is the personification of the Sophists, according to\r Plato’s conception of them, in some of their worst characteristics. He\r is vain and blustering, refusing to discourse unless he is paid, fond\r of making an oration, and hoping thereby to escape the inevitable\r Socrates; but a mere child in argument, and unable to foresee that the\r next ‘move’ (to use a Platonic expression) will ‘shut him up.’ He has\r reached the stage of framing general notions, and in this respect is in\r advance of Cephalus and Polemarc","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":475},{"id":"plato-the-repu-15","text":"When Thrasymachus has been silenced, the two principal respondents,\r Glaucon and Adeimantus, appear on the scene: here, as in Greek tragedy\r (cp. Introd. to Phaedo), three actors are introduced. At first sight\r the two sons of Ariston may seem to wear a family likeness, like the\r two friends Simmias and Cebes in the Phaedo. But on a nearer\r examination of them the similarity vanishes, and they are seen to be\r distinct characters. Glaucon is the impetuous youth who can ‘just never\r have enough of fechting’ (cp. the character of him in Xen. Mem. iii.\r 6); the man of pleasure who is acquainted wi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":476},{"id":"plato-the-repu-16","text":"Thus in a succession of characters Plato represents the successive\r stages of morality, beginning with the Athenian gentleman of the olden\r time, who is followed by the practical man of that day regulating his\r life by proverbs and saws; to him succeeds the wild generalization of\r the Sophists, and lastly come the young disciples of the great teacher,\r who know the sophistical arguments but will not be convinced by them,\r and desire to go deeper into the nature of things. These too, like\r Cephalus, Polemarchus, Thrasymachus, are clearly distinguished from one\r another. Neither in the Republic,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":477},{"id":"plato-the-repu-17","text":"The delineation of Socrates in the Republic is not wholly consistent.\r In the first book we have more of the real Socrates, such as he is\r depicted in the Memorabilia of Xenophon, in the earliest Dialogues of\r Plato, and in the Apology. He is ironical, provoking, questioning, the\r old enemy of the Sophists, ready to put on the mask of Silenus as well\r as to argue seriously. But in the sixth book his enmity towards the\r Sophists abates; he acknowledges that they are the representatives\r rather than the corrupters of the world. He also becomes more dogmatic\r and constructive, passing beyond the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":478},{"id":"plato-the-repu-18","text":"Neither can we be absolutely certain that Socrates himself taught the\r immortality of the soul, which is unknown to his disciple Glaucon in\r the Republic (cp. Apol.); nor is there any reason to suppose that he\r used myths or revelations of another world as a vehicle of instruction,\r or that he would have banished poetry or have denounced the Greek\r mythology. His favorite oath is retained, and a slight mention is made\r of the daemonium, or internal sign, which is alluded to by Socrates as\r a phenomenon peculiar to himself. A real element of Socratic teaching,\r which is more prominent in the Re","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":479},{"id":"plato-the-repu-19","text":"Plato is most true to the character of his master when he describes him\r as ‘not of this world.’ And with this representation of him the ideal\r state and the other paradoxes of the Republic are quite in accordance,\r though they cannot be shown to have been speculations of Socrates. To\r him, as to other great teachers both philosophical and religious, when\r they looked upward, the world seemed to be the embodiment of error and\r evil. The common sense of mankind has revolted against this view, or\r has only partially admitted it. And even in Socrates himself the\r sterner judgement of the multitud","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"19"},"sequenceIndex":480},{"id":"plato-the-repu-20","text":"Leaving the characters we may now analyse the contents of the Republic,\r and then proceed to consider (1) The general aspects of this Hellenic\r ideal of the State, (2) The modern lights in which the thoughts of\r Plato may be read.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":481},{"id":"plato-the-repu-21","text":"When the rhetorical advantage of reciting the Dialogue has been gained,\r the attention is not distracted by any reference to the audience; nor\r is the reader further reminded of the extraordinary length of the\r narrative. Of the numerous company, three only take any serious part in\r the discussion; nor are we informed whether in the evening they went to\r the torch-race, or talked, as in the Symposium, through the night. The\r manner in which the conversation has arisen is described as\r follows:—Socrates and his companion Glaucon are about to leave the\r festival when they are detained by a messa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":482},{"id":"plato-the-repu-22","text":"The description of old age is finished, and Plato, as his manner is,\r has touched the key-note of the whole work in asking for the definition\r of justice, first suggesting the question which Glaucon afterwards\r pursues respecting external goods, and preparing for the concluding\r mythus of the world below in the slight allusion of Cephalus. The\r portrait of the just man is a natural frontispiece or introduction to\r the long discourse which follows, and may perhaps imply that in all our\r perplexity about the nature of justice, there is no difficulty in\r discerning ‘who is a just man.’ The first ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":483},{"id":"plato-the-repu-23","text":"...He proceeds: What did Simonides mean by this saying of his? Did he\r mean that I was to give back arms to a madman? ‘No, not in that case,\r not if the parties are friends, and evil would result. He meant that\r you were to do what was proper, good to friends and harm to enemies.’\r Every act does something to somebody; and following this analogy,\r Socrates asks, What is this due and proper thing which justice does,\r and to whom? He is answered that justice does good to friends and harm\r to enemies. But in what way good or harm? ‘In making alliances with the\r one, and going to war with the othe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":484},{"id":"plato-the-repu-24","text":"Thus the first stage of aphoristic or unconscious morality is shown to\r be inadequate to the wants of the age; the authority of the poets is\r set aside, and through the winding mazes of dialectic we make an\r approach to the Christian precept of forgiveness of injuries. Similar\r words are applied by the Persian mystic poet to the Divine being when\r the questioning spirit is stirred within him:—‘If because I do evil,\r Thou punishest me by evil, what is the difference between Thee and me?’\r In this both Plato and Kheyam rise above the level of many Christian\r (?) theologians. The first definition","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":485},{"id":"plato-the-repu-25","text":"...Here Thrasymachus, who has made several attempts to interrupt, but\r has hitherto been kept in order by the company, takes advantage of a\r pause and rushes into the arena, beginning, like a savage animal, with\r a roar. ‘Socrates,’ he says, ‘what folly is this?—Why do you agree to\r be vanquished by one another in a pretended argument?’ He then\r prohibits all the ordinary definitions of justice; to which Socrates\r replies that he cannot tell how many twelve is, if he is forbidden to\r say 2 x 6, or 3 x 4, or 6 x 2, or 4 x 3. At first Thrasymachus is\r reluctant to argue; but at length, with a pr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":486},{"id":"plato-the-repu-26","text":"Of course this was not the original assertion, nor is the new\r interpretation accepted by Thrasymachus himself. But Socrates is not\r disposed to quarrel about words, if, as he significantly insinuates,\r his adversary has changed his mind. In what follows Thrasymachus does\r in fact withdraw his admission that the ruler may make a mistake, for\r he affirms that the ruler as a ruler is infallible. Socrates is quite\r ready to accept the new position, which he equally turns against\r Thrasymachus by the help of the analogy of the arts. Every art or\r science has an interest, but this interest is to be","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":487},{"id":"plato-the-repu-27","text":"Thrasymachus is on the brink of the inevitable conclusion, when he\r makes a bold diversion. ‘Tell me, Socrates,’ he says, ‘have you a\r nurse?’ What a question! Why do you ask? ‘Because, if you have, she\r neglects you and lets you go about drivelling, and has not even taught\r you to know the shepherd from the sheep. For you fancy that shepherds\r and rulers never think of their own interest, but only of their sheep\r or subjects, whereas the truth is that they fatten them for their use,\r sheep and subjects alike. And experience proves that in every relation\r of life the just man is the loser and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":488},{"id":"plato-the-repu-28","text":"Thrasymachus, who is better at a speech than at a close argument,\r having deluged the company with words, has a mind to escape. But the\r others will not let him go, and Socrates adds a humble but earnest\r request that he will not desert them at such a crisis of their fate.\r ‘And what can I do more for you?’ he says; ‘would you have me put the\r words bodily into your souls?’ God forbid! replies Socrates; but we\r want you to be consistent in the use of terms, and not to employ\r ‘physician’ in an exact sense, and then again ‘shepherd’ or ‘ruler’ in\r an inexact,—if the words are strictly taken, th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":489},{"id":"plato-the-repu-29","text":"The satire on existing governments is heightened by the simple and\r apparently incidental manner in which the last remark is introduced.\r There is a similar irony in the argument that the governors of mankind\r do not like being in office, and that therefore they demand pay.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":490},{"id":"plato-the-repu-30","text":"...Enough of this: the other assertion of Thrasymachus is far more\r important—that the unjust life is more gainful than the just. Now, as\r you and I, Glaucon, are not convinced by him, we must reply to him; but\r if we try to compare their respective gains we shall want a judge to\r decide for us; we had better therefore proceed by making mutual\r admissions of the truth to one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":491},{"id":"plato-the-repu-31","text":"Thrasymachus had asserted that perfect injustice was more gainful than\r perfect justice, and after a little hesitation he is induced by\r Socrates to admit the still greater paradox that injustice is virtue\r and justice vice. Socrates praises his frankness, and assumes the\r attitude of one whose only wish is to understand the meaning of his\r opponents. At the same time he is weaving a net in which Thrasymachus\r is finally enclosed. The admission is elicited from him that the just\r man seeks to gain an advantage over the unjust only, but not over the\r just, while the unjust would gain an advanta","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":492},{"id":"plato-the-repu-32","text":"There was great difficulty in bringing Thrasymachus to the point; the\r day was hot and he was streaming with perspiration, and for the first\r time in his life he was seen to blush. But his other thesis that\r injustice was stronger than justice has not yet been refuted, and\r Socrates now proceeds to the consideration of this, which, with the\r assistance of Thrasymachus, he hopes to clear up; the latter is at\r first churlish, but in the judicious hands of Socrates is soon restored\r to good-humour: Is there not honour among thieves? Is not the strength\r of injustice only a remnant of justice? Is ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":493},{"id":"plato-the-repu-33","text":"Another question has not been answered: Is the just or the unjust the\r happier? To this we reply, that every art has an end and an excellence\r or virtue by which the end is accomplished. And is not the end of the\r soul happiness, and justice the excellence of the soul by which\r happiness is attained? Justice and happiness being thus shown to be\r inseparable, the question whether the just or the unjust is the happier\r has disappeared.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":494},{"id":"plato-the-repu-34","text":"Thrasymachus replies: ‘Let this be your entertainment, Socrates, at the\r festival of Bendis.’ Yes; and a very good entertainment with which your\r kindness has supplied me, now that you have left off scolding. And yet\r not a good entertainment—but that was my own fault, for I tasted of too\r many things. First of all the nature of justice was the subject of our\r enquiry, and then whether justice is virtue and wisdom, or evil and\r folly; and then the comparative advantages of just and unjust: and the\r sum of all is that I know not what justice is; how then shall I know\r whether the just is happy ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":495},{"id":"plato-the-repu-35","text":"Thus the sophistical fabric has been demolished, chiefly by appealing\r to the analogy of the arts. ‘Justice is like the arts (1) in having no\r external interest, and (2) in not aiming at excess, and (3) justice is\r to happiness what the implement of the workman is to his work.’ At this\r the modern reader is apt to stumble, because he forgets that Plato is\r writing in an age when the arts and the virtues, like the moral and\r intellectual faculties, were still undistinguished. Among early\r enquirers into the nature of human action the arts helped to fill up\r the void of speculation; and at first","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":496},{"id":"plato-the-repu-36","text":"The expression ‘an art of pay’ which is described as ‘common to all the\r arts’ is not in accordance with the ordinary use of language. Nor is it\r employed elsewhere either by Plato or by any other Greek writer. It is\r suggested by the argument, and seems to extend the conception of art to\r doing as well as making. Another flaw or inaccuracy of language may be\r noted in the words ‘men who are injured are made more unjust.’ For\r those who are injured are not necessarily made worse, but only harmed\r or ill-treated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":497},{"id":"plato-the-repu-37","text":"The second of the three arguments, ‘that the just does not aim at\r excess,’ has a real meaning, though wrapped up in an enigmatical form.\r That the good is of the nature of the finite is a peculiarly Hellenic\r sentiment, which may be compared with the language of those modern\r writers who speak of virtue as fitness, and of freedom as obedience to\r law. The mathematical or logical notion of limit easily passes into an\r ethical one, and even finds a mythological expression in the conception\r of envy (Greek). Ideas of measure, equality, order, unity, proportion,\r still linger in the writings of m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":498},{"id":"plato-the-repu-38","text":"‘When workmen strive to do better than well,\r They do confound their skill in covetousness.’ (King John. Act. iv. Sc.\r 2.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":499},{"id":"plato-the-repu-39","text":"The harmony of the soul and body, and of the parts of the soul with one\r another, a harmony ‘fairer than that of musical notes,’ is the true\r Hellenic mode of conceiving the perfection of human nature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":500},{"id":"plato-the-repu-40","text":"In what may be called the epilogue of the discussion with Thrasymachus,\r Plato argues that evil is not a principle of strength, but of discord\r and dissolution, just touching the question which has been often\r treated in modern times by theologians and philosophers, of the\r negative nature of evil. In the last argument we trace the germ of the\r Aristotelian doctrine of an end and a virtue directed towards the end,\r which again is suggested by the arts. The final reconcilement of\r justice and happiness and the identity of the individual and the State\r are also intimated. Socrates reassumes the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":501},{"id":"plato-the-repu-41","text":"‘To do injustice is said to be a good; to suffer injustice an evil. As\r the evil is discovered by experience to be greater than the good, the\r sufferers, who cannot also be doers, make a compact that they will have\r neither, and this compact or mean is called justice, but is really the\r impossibility of doing injustice. No one would observe such a compact\r if he were not obliged. Let us suppose that the just and unjust have\r two rings, like that of Gyges in the well-known story, which make them\r invisible, and then no difference will appear in them, for every one\r will do evil if he can. And h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":502},{"id":"plato-the-repu-42","text":"‘And now let us frame an ideal of the just and unjust. Imagine the\r unjust man to be master of his craft, seldom making mistakes and easily\r correcting them; having gifts of money, speech, strength—the greatest\r villain bearing the highest character: and at his side let us place the\r just in his nobleness and simplicity—being, not seeming—without name or\r reward—clothed in his justice only—the best of men who is thought to be\r the worst, and let him die as he has lived. I might add (but I would\r rather put the rest into the mouth of the panegyrists of injustice—they\r will tell you) that the ju","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":503},{"id":"plato-the-repu-43","text":"I was thinking what to answer, when Adeimantus joined in the already\r unequal fray. He considered that the most important point of all had\r been omitted:—‘Men are taught to be just for the sake of rewards;\r parents and guardians make reputation the incentive to virtue. And\r other advantages are promised by them of a more solid kind, such as\r wealthy marriages and high offices. There are the pictures in Homer and\r Hesiod of fat sheep and heavy fleeces, rich corn-fields and trees\r toppling with fruit, which the gods provide in this life for the just.\r And the Orphic poets add a similar picture o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":504},{"id":"plato-the-repu-44","text":"‘Take another kind of argument which is found both in poetry and\r prose:—“Virtue,” as Hesiod says, “is honourable but difficult, vice is\r easy and profitable.” You may often see the wicked in great prosperity\r and the righteous afflicted by the will of heaven. And mendicant\r prophets knock at rich men’s doors, promising to atone for the sins of\r themselves or their fathers in an easy fashion with sacrifices and\r festive games, or with charms and invocations to get rid of an enemy\r good or bad by divine help and at a small charge;—they appeal to books\r professing to be written by Musaeus and Or","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":505},{"id":"plato-the-repu-45","text":"‘When a lively-minded ingenuous youth hears all this, what will be his\r conclusion? “Will he,” in the language of Pindar, “make justice his\r high tower, or fortify himself with crooked deceit?” Justice, he\r reflects, without the appearance of justice, is misery and ruin;\r injustice has the promise of a glorious life. Appearance is master of\r truth and lord of happiness. To appearance then I will turn,—I will put\r on the show of virtue and trail behind me the fox of Archilochus. I\r hear some one saying that “wickedness is not easily concealed,” to\r which I reply that “nothing great is easy.” Un","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":506},{"id":"plato-the-repu-46","text":"‘How can we resist such arguments in favour of injustice? Add good\r manners, and, as the wise tell us, we shall make the best of both\r worlds. Who that is not a miserable caitiff will refrain from smiling\r at the praises of justice? Even if a man knows the better part he will\r not be angry with others; for he knows also that more than human virtue\r is needed to save a man, and that he only praises justice who is\r incapable of injustice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":507},{"id":"plato-the-repu-47","text":"‘The origin of the evil is that all men from the beginning, heroes,\r poets, instructors of youth, have always asserted “the temporal\r dispensation,” the honours and profits of justice. Had we been taught\r in early youth the power of justice and injustice inherent in the soul,\r and unseen by any human or divine eye, we should not have needed others\r to be our guardians, but every one would have been the guardian of\r himself. This is what I want you to show, Socrates;—other men use\r arguments which rather tend to strengthen the position of Thrasymachus\r that “might is right;” but from you I expe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":508},{"id":"plato-the-repu-48","text":"The thesis, which for the sake of argument has been maintained by\r Glaucon, is the converse of that of Thrasymachus—not right is the\r interest of the stronger, but right is the necessity of the weaker.\r Starting from the same premises he carries the analysis of society a\r step further back;—might is still right, but the might is the weakness\r of the many combined against the strength of the few.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":509},{"id":"plato-the-repu-49","text":"There have been theories in modern as well as in ancient times which\r have a family likeness to the speculations of Glaucon; e.g. that power\r is the foundation of right; or that a monarch has a divine right to\r govern well or ill; or that virtue is self-love or the love of power;\r or that war is the natural state of man; or that private vices are\r public benefits. All such theories have a kind of plausibility from\r their partial agreement with experience. For human nature oscillates\r between good and evil, and the motives of actions and the origin of\r institutions may be explained to a certain","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":510},{"id":"plato-the-repu-50","text":"The two brothers ask Socrates to prove to them that the just is happy\r when they have taken from him all that in which happiness is ordinarily\r supposed to consist. Not that there is (1) any absurdity in the attempt\r to frame a notion of justice apart from circumstances. For the ideal\r must always be a paradox when compared with the ordinary conditions of\r human life. Neither the Stoical ideal nor the Christian ideal is true\r as a fact, but they may serve as a basis of education, and may exercise\r an ennobling influence. An ideal is none the worse because ‘some one\r has made the discovery’ tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":511},{"id":"plato-the-repu-51","text":"Nor again, (2) must we forget that Plato, though he agrees generally\r with the view implied in the argument of the two brothers, is not\r expressing his own final conclusion, but rather seeking to dramatize\r one of the aspects of ethical truth. He is developing his idea\r gradually in a series of positions or situations. He is exhibiting\r Socrates for the first time undergoing the Socratic interrogation.\r Lastly, (3) the word ‘happiness’ involves some degree of confusion\r because associated in the language of modern philosophy with conscious\r pleasure or satisfaction, which was not equally prese","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":512},{"id":"plato-the-repu-52","text":"Glaucon has been drawing a picture of the misery of the just and the\r happiness of the unjust, to which the misery of the tyrant in Book IX\r is the answer and parallel. And still the unjust must appear just; that\r is ‘the homage which vice pays to virtue.’ But now Adeimantus, taking\r up the hint which had been already given by Glaucon, proceeds to show\r that in the opinion of mankind justice is regarded only for the sake of\r rewards and reputation, and points out the advantage which is given to\r such arguments as those of Thrasymachus and Glaucon by the conventional\r morality of mankind. He se","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":513},{"id":"plato-the-repu-53","text":"It has been objected that justice is honesty in the sense of Glaucon\r and Adeimantus, but is taken by Socrates to mean all virtue. May we not\r more truly say that the old-fashioned notion of justice is enlarged by\r Socrates, and becomes equivalent to universal order or well-being,\r first in the State, and secondly in the individual? He has found a new\r answer to his old question (Protag.), ‘whether the virtues are one or\r many,’ viz. that one is the ordering principle of the three others. In\r seeking to establish the purely internal nature of justice, he is met\r by the fact that man is a socia","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":514},{"id":"plato-the-repu-54","text":"The remainder of the Republic is developed out of the question of the\r sons of Ariston. Three points are deserving of remark in what\r immediately follows:—First, that the answer of Socrates is altogether\r indirect. He does not say that happiness consists in the contemplation\r of the idea of justice, and still less will he be tempted to affirm the\r Stoical paradox that the just man can be happy on the rack. But first\r he dwells on the difficulty of the problem and insists on restoring man\r to his natural condition, before he will answer the question at all. He\r too will frame an ideal, but his ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":515},{"id":"plato-the-repu-55","text":"Secondly, it may be remarked that Plato preserves the genuine character\r of Greek thought in beginning with the State and in going on to the\r individual. First ethics, then politics—this is the order of ideas to\r us; the reverse is the order of history. Only after many struggles of\r thought does the individual assert his right as a moral being. In early\r ages he is not ONE, but one of many, the citizen of a State which is\r prior to him; and he has no notion of good or evil apart from the law\r of his country or the creed of his church. And to this type he is\r constantly tending to revert, whene","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":516},{"id":"plato-the-repu-56","text":"Thirdly, we may observe the confusion or identification of the\r individual and the State, of ethics and politics, which pervades early\r Greek speculation, and even in modern times retains a certain degree of\r influence. The subtle difference between the collective and individual\r action of mankind seems to have escaped early thinkers, and we too are\r sometimes in danger of forgetting the conditions of united human\r action, whenever we either elevate politics into ethics, or lower\r ethics to the standard of politics. The good man and the good citizen\r only coincide in the perfect State; and thi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":517},{"id":"plato-the-repu-57","text":"...Socrates praises the sons of Ariston, ‘inspired offspring of the\r renowned hero,’ as the elegiac poet terms them; but he does not\r understand how they can argue so eloquently on behalf of injustice\r while their character shows that they are uninfluenced by their own\r arguments. He knows not how to answer them, although he is afraid of\r deserting justice in the hour of need. He therefore makes a condition,\r that having weak eyes he shall be allowed to read the large letters\r first and then go on to the smaller, that is, he must look for justice\r in the State first, and will then proceed to t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":518},{"id":"plato-the-repu-58","text":"Society arises out of the wants of man. His first want is food; his\r second a house; his third a coat. The sense of these needs and the\r possibility of satisfying them by exchange, draw individuals together\r on the same spot; and this is the beginning of a State, which we take\r the liberty to invent, although necessity is the real inventor. There\r must be first a husbandman, secondly a builder, thirdly a weaver, to\r which may be added a cobbler. Four or five citizens at least are\r required to make a city. Now men have different natures, and one man\r will do one thing better than many; and busi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":519},{"id":"plato-the-repu-59","text":"Here follows a rustic picture of their way of life. They spend their\r days in houses which they have built for themselves; they make their\r own clothes and produce their own corn and wine. Their principal food\r is meal and flour, and they drink in moderation. They live on the best\r of terms with each other, and take care not to have too many children.\r ‘But,’ said Glaucon, interposing, ‘are they not to have a relish?’\r Certainly; they will have salt and olives and cheese, vegetables and\r fruits, and chestnuts to roast at the fire. ‘’Tis a city of pigs,\r Socrates.’ Why, I replied, what do you w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":520},{"id":"plato-the-repu-60","text":"But what shall their education be? Is any better than the old-fashioned\r sort which is comprehended under the name of music and gymnastic? Music\r includes literature, and literature is of two kinds, true and false.\r ‘What do you mean?’ he said. I mean that children hear stories before\r they learn gymnastics, and that the stories are either untrue, or have\r at most one or two grains of truth in a bushel of falsehood. Now early\r life is very impressible, and children ought not to learn what they\r will have to unlearn when they grow up; we must therefore have a\r censorship of nursery tales, banis","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":521},{"id":"plato-the-repu-61","text":"And our first principle is, that God must be represented as he is; not\r as the author of all things, but of good only. We will not suffer the\r poets to say that he is the steward of good and evil, or that he has\r two casks full of destinies;—or that Athene and Zeus incited Pandarus\r to break the treaty; or that God caused the sufferings of Niobe, or of\r Pelops, or the Trojan war; or that he makes men sin when he wishes to\r destroy them. Either these were not the actions of the gods, or God was\r just, and men were the better for being punished. But that the deed was\r evil, and God the author, i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":522},{"id":"plato-the-repu-62","text":"And the second principle is like unto it:—With God is no variableness\r or change of form. Reason teaches us this; for if we suppose a change\r in God, he must be changed either by another or by himself. By\r another?—but the best works of nature and art and the noblest qualities\r of mind are least liable to be changed by any external force. By\r himself?—but he cannot change for the better; he will hardly change for\r the worse. He remains for ever fairest and best in his own image.\r Therefore we refuse to listen to the poets who tell us of Here begging\r in the likeness of a priestess or of other ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":523},{"id":"plato-the-repu-63","text":"In order to give clearness to his conception of the State, Plato\r proceeds to trace the first principles of mutual need and of division\r of labour in an imaginary community of four or five citizens. Gradually\r this community increases; the division of labour extends to countries;\r imports necessitate exports; a medium of exchange is required, and\r retailers sit in the market-place to save the time of the producers.\r These are the steps by which Plato constructs the first or primitive\r State, introducing the elements of political economy by the way. As he\r is going to frame a second or civilize","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":524},{"id":"plato-the-repu-64","text":"Several interesting remarks which in modern times would have a place in\r a treatise on Political Economy are scattered up and down the writings\r of Plato: especially Laws, Population; Free Trade; Adulteration; Wills\r and Bequests; Begging; Eryxias, (though not Plato’s), Value and Demand;\r Republic, Division of Labour. The last subject, and also the origin of\r Retail Trade, is treated with admirable lucidity in the second book of\r the Republic. But Plato never combined his economic ideas into a\r system, and never seems to have recognized that Trade is one of the\r great motive powers of the Stat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":525},{"id":"plato-the-repu-65","text":"The disappointment of Glaucon at the ‘city of pigs,’ the ludicrous\r description of the ministers of luxury in the more refined State, and\r the afterthought of the necessity of doctors, the illustration of the\r nature of the guardian taken from the dog, the desirableness of\r offering some almost unprocurable victim when impure mysteries are to\r be celebrated, the behaviour of Zeus to his father and of Hephaestus to\r his mother, are touches of humour which have also a serious meaning. In\r speaking of education Plato rather startles us by affirming that a\r child must be trained in falsehood first","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":526},{"id":"plato-the-repu-66","text":"A Greek in the age of Plato attached no importance to the question\r whether his religion was an historical fact. He was just beginning to\r be conscious that the past had a history; but he could see nothing\r beyond Homer and Hesiod. Whether their narratives were true or false\r did not seriously affect the political or social life of Hellas. Men\r only began to suspect that they were fictions when they recognised them\r to be immoral. And so in all religions: the consideration of their\r morality comes first, afterwards the truth of the documents in which\r they are recorded, or of the events natura","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":527},{"id":"plato-the-repu-67","text":"We note in passing that the allegorical interpretation of mythology,\r said to have been first introduced as early as the sixth century before\r Christ by Theagenes of Rhegium, was well established in the age of\r Plato, and here, as in the Phaedrus, though for a different reason, was\r rejected by him. That anachronisms whether of religion or law, when men\r have reached another stage of civilization, should be got rid of by\r fictions is in accordance with universal experience. Great is the art\r of interpretation; and by a natural process, which when once discovered\r was always going on, what coul","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":528},{"id":"plato-the-repu-68","text":"A singular conception which occurs towards the end of the book is the\r lie in the soul; this is connected with the Platonic and Socratic\r doctrine that involuntary ignorance is worse than voluntary. The lie in\r the soul is a true lie, the corruption of the highest truth, the\r deception of the highest part of the soul, from which he who is\r deceived has no power of delivering himself. For example, to represent\r God as false or immoral, or, according to Plato, as deluding men with\r appearances or as the author of evil; or again, to affirm with\r Protagoras that ‘knowledge is sensation,’ or that ‘","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":529},{"id":"plato-the-repu-69","text":"Truth should have a high place among the virtues, for falsehood, as we\r were saying, is useless to the gods, and only useful to men as a\r medicine. But this employment of falsehood must remain a privilege of\r state; the common man must not in return tell a lie to the ruler; any\r more than the patient would tell a lie to his physician, or the sailor\r to his captain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":530},{"id":"plato-the-repu-70","text":"In the next place our youth must be temperate, and temperance consists\r in self-control and obedience to authority. That is a lesson which\r Homer teaches in some places: ‘The Achaeans marched on breathing\r prowess, in silent awe of their leaders;’—but a very different one in\r other places: ‘O heavy with wine, who hast the eyes of a dog, but the\r heart of a stag.’ Language of the latter kind will not impress\r self-control on the minds of youth. The same may be said about his\r praises of eating and drinking and his dread of starvation; also about\r the verses in which he tells of the rapturous lo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":531},{"id":"plato-the-repu-71","text":"Enough of gods and heroes;—what shall we say about men? What the poets\r and story-tellers say—that the wicked prosper and the righteous are\r afflicted, or that justice is another’s gain? Such misrepresentations\r cannot be allowed by us. But in this we are anticipating the definition\r of justice, and had therefore better defer the enquiry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":532},{"id":"plato-the-repu-72","text":"The subjects of poetry have been sufficiently treated; next follows\r style. Now all poetry is a narrative of events past, present, or to\r come; and narrative is of three kinds, the simple, the imitative, and a\r composition of the two. An instance will make my meaning clear. The\r first scene in Homer is of the last or mixed kind, being partly\r description and partly dialogue. But if you throw the dialogue into the\r ‘oratio obliqua,’ the passage will run thus: The priest came and prayed\r Apollo that the Achaeans might take Troy and have a safe return if\r Agamemnon would only give him back his da","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":533},{"id":"plato-the-repu-73","text":"Next as to the music. A song or ode has three parts,—the subject, the\r harmony, and the rhythm; of which the two last are dependent upon the\r first. As we banished strains of lamentation, so we may now banish the\r mixed Lydian harmonies, which are the harmonies of lamentation; and as\r our citizens are to be temperate, we may also banish convivial\r harmonies, such as the Ionian and pure Lydian. Two remain—the Dorian\r and Phrygian, the first for war, the second for peace; the one\r expressive of courage, the other of obedience or instruction or\r religious feeling. And as we reject varieties of ha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":534},{"id":"plato-the-repu-74","text":"Other artists as well as poets should be warned against meanness or\r unseemliness. Sculpture and painting equally with music must conform to\r the law of simplicity. He who violates it cannot be allowed to work in\r our city, and to corrupt the taste of our citizens. For our guardians\r must grow up, not amid images of deformity which will gradually poison\r and corrupt their souls, but in a land of health and beauty where they\r will drink in from every object sweet and harmonious influences. And of\r all these influences the greatest is the education given by music,\r which finds a way into the inn","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":535},{"id":"plato-the-repu-75","text":"Next we pass on to gymnastics; about which I would remark, that the\r soul is related to the body as a cause to an effect, and therefore if\r we educate the mind we may leave the education of the body in her\r charge, and need only give a general outline of the course to be\r pursued. In the first place the guardians must abstain from strong\r drink, for they should be the last persons to lose their wits. Whether\r the habits of the palaestra are suitable to them is more doubtful, for\r the ordinary gymnastic is a sleepy sort of thing, and if left off\r suddenly is apt to endanger health. But our warr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":536},{"id":"plato-the-repu-76","text":"Glaucon then asks Socrates whether the best physicians and the best\r judges will not be those who have had severally the greatest experience\r of diseases and of crimes. Socrates draws a distinction between the two\r professions. The physician should have had experience of disease in his\r own body, for he cures with his mind and not with his body. But the\r judge controls mind by mind; and therefore his mind should not be\r corrupted by crime. Where then is he to gain experience? How is he to\r be wise and also innocent? When young a good man is apt to be deceived\r by evil-doers, because he has no ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":537},{"id":"plato-the-repu-77","text":"The next question is, Who are to be our rulers? First, the elder must\r rule the younger; and the best of the elders will be the best\r guardians. Now they will be the best who love their subjects most, and\r think that they have a common interest with them in the welfare of the\r state. These we must select; but they must be watched at every epoch of\r life to see whether they have retained the same opinions and held out\r against force and enchantment. For time and persuasion and the love of\r pleasure may enchant a man into a change of purpose, and the force of\r grief and pain may compel him. And ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":538},{"id":"plato-the-repu-78","text":"And now for one magnificent lie, in the belief of which, Oh that we\r could train our rulers!—at any rate let us make the attempt with the\r rest of the world. What I am going to tell is only another version of\r the legend of Cadmus; but our unbelieving generation will be slow to\r accept such a story. The tale must be imparted, first to the rulers,\r then to the soldiers, lastly to the people. We will inform them that\r their youth was a dream, and that during the time when they seemed to\r be undergoing their education they were really being fashioned in the\r earth, who sent them up when they were","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":539},{"id":"plato-the-repu-79","text":"Now let the earthborn men go forth under the command of their rulers,\r and look about and pitch their camp in a high place, which will be safe\r against enemies from without, and likewise against insurrections from\r within. There let them sacrifice and set up their tents; for soldiers\r they are to be and not shopkeepers, the watchdogs and guardians of the\r sheep; and luxury and avarice will turn them into wolves and tyrants.\r Their habits and their dwellings should correspond to their education.\r They should have no property; their pay should only meet their\r expenses; and they should have comm","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":540},{"id":"plato-the-repu-80","text":"The religious and ethical aspect of Plato’s education will hereafter be\r considered under a separate head. Some lesser points may be more\r conveniently noticed in this place.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":541},{"id":"plato-the-repu-81","text":"1. The constant appeal to the authority of Homer, whom, with grave\r irony, Plato, after the manner of his age, summons as a witness about\r ethics and psychology, as well as about diet and medicine; attempting\r to distinguish the better lesson from the worse, sometimes altering the\r text from design; more than once quoting or alluding to Homer\r inaccurately, after the manner of the early logographers turning the\r Iliad into prose, and delighting to draw far-fetched inferences from\r his words, or to make ludicrous applications of them. He does not, like\r Heracleitus, get into a rage with Homer a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"81"},"sequenceIndex":542},{"id":"plato-the-repu-82","text":"2. ‘The style is to conform to the subject and the metre to the style.’\r Notwithstanding the fascination which the word ‘classical’ exercises\r over us, we can hardly maintain that this rule is observed in all the\r Greek poetry which has come down to us. We cannot deny that the thought\r often exceeds the power of lucid expression in Aeschylus and Pindar; or\r that rhetoric gets the better of the thought in the Sophist-poet\r Euripides. Only perhaps in Sophocles is there a perfect harmony of the\r two; in him alone do we find a grace of language like the beauty of a\r Greek statue, in which there is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":543},{"id":"plato-the-repu-83","text":"3. In the third book of the Republic a nearer approach is made to a\r theory of art than anywhere else in Plato. His views may be summed up\r as follows:—True art is not fanciful and imitative, but simple and\r ideal,—the expression of the highest moral energy, whether in action or\r repose. To live among works of plastic art which are of this noble and\r simple character, or to listen to such strains, is the best of\r influences,—the true Greek atmosphere, in which youth should be brought\r up. That is the way to create in them a natural good taste, which will\r have a feeling of truth and beauty in ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":544},{"id":"plato-the-repu-84","text":"There is hardly any mention in Plato of the creative arts; only in two\r or three passages does he even allude to them (Rep.; Soph.). He is not\r lost in rapture at the great works of Phidias, the Parthenon, the\r Propylea, the statues of Zeus or Athene. He would probably have\r regarded any abstract truth of number or figure as higher than the\r greatest of them. Yet it is hard to suppose that some influence, such\r as he hopes to inspire in youth, did not pass into his own mind from\r the works of art which he saw around him. We are living upon the\r fragments of them, and find in a few broken stone","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":545},{"id":"plato-the-repu-85","text":"4. Plato makes the true and subtle remark that the physician had better\r not be in robust health; and should have known what illness is in his\r own person. But the judge ought to have had no similar experience of\r evil; he is to be a good man who, having passed his youth in innocence,\r became acquainted late in life with the vices of others. And therefore,\r according to Plato, a judge should not be young, just as a young man\r according to Aristotle is not fit to be a hearer of moral philosophy.\r The bad, on the other hand, have a knowledge of vice, but no knowledge\r of virtue. It may be doubte","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":546},{"id":"plato-the-repu-86","text":"5. One of the most remarkable conceptions of Plato, because un-Greek\r and also very different from anything which existed at all in his age\r of the world, is the transposition of ranks. In the Spartan state there\r had been enfranchisement of Helots and degradation of citizens under\r special circumstances. And in the ancient Greek aristocracies, merit\r was certainly recognized as one of the elements on which government was\r based. The founders of states were supposed to be their benefactors,\r who were raised by their great actions above the ordinary level of\r humanity; at a later period, the se","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":547},{"id":"plato-the-repu-87","text":"6. Two paradoxes which strike the modern reader as in the highest\r degree fanciful and ideal, and which suggest to him many reflections,\r are to be found in the third book of the Republic: first, the great\r power of music, so much beyond any influence which is experienced by us\r in modern times, when the art or science has been far more developed,\r and has found the secret of harmony, as well as of melody; secondly,\r the indefinite and almost absolute control which the soul is supposed\r to exercise over the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":548},{"id":"plato-the-repu-88","text":"In the first we suspect some degree of exaggeration, such as we may\r also observe among certain masters of the art, not unknown to us, at\r the present day. With this natural enthusiasm, which is felt by a few\r only, there seems to mingle in Plato a sort of Pythagorean reverence\r for numbers and numerical proportion to which Aristotle is a stranger.\r Intervals of sound and number are to him sacred things which have a law\r of their own, not dependent on the variations of sense. They rise above\r sense, and become a connecting link with the world of ideas. But it is\r evident that Plato is describi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":549},{"id":"plato-the-repu-89","text":"The second paradox leads up to some curious and interesting\r questions—How far can the mind control the body? Is the relation\r between them one of mutual antagonism or of mutual harmony? Are they\r two or one, and is either of them the cause of the other? May we not at\r times drop the opposition between them, and the mode of describing\r them, which is so familiar to us, and yet hardly conveys any precise\r meaning, and try to view this composite creature, man, in a more simple\r manner? Must we not at any rate admit that there is in human nature a\r higher and a lower principle, divided by no dist","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"89"},"sequenceIndex":550},{"id":"plato-the-repu-90","text":"We are disappointed to find that Plato, in the general condemnation\r which he passes on the practice of medicine prevailing in his own day,\r depreciates the effects of diet. He would like to have diseases of a\r definite character and capable of receiving a definite treatment. He is\r afraid of invalidism interfering with the business of life. He does not\r recognize that time is the great healer both of mental and bodily\r disorders; and that remedies which are gradual and proceed little by\r little are safer than those which produce a sudden catastrophe. Neither\r does he see that there is no way ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":551},{"id":"plato-the-repu-91","text":"(1) The affected ignorance of music, which is Plato’s way of expressing\r that he is passing lightly over the subject.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":552},{"id":"plato-the-repu-92","text":"(2) The tentative manner in which here, as in the second book, he\r proceeds with the construction of the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":553},{"id":"plato-the-repu-93","text":"(3) The description of the State sometimes as a reality, and then again\r as a work of imagination only; these are the arts by which he sustains\r the reader’s interest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":554},{"id":"plato-the-repu-94","text":"(4) Connecting links, or the preparation for the entire expulsion of\r the poets in Book X.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":555},{"id":"plato-the-repu-95","text":"(5) The companion pictures of the lover of litigation and the\r valetudinarian, the satirical jest about the maxim of Phocylides, the\r manner in which the image of the gold and silver citizens is taken up\r into the subject, and the argument from the practice of Asclepius,\r should not escape notice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":556},{"id":"plato-the-repu-96","text":"To the size of the state there is no limit but the necessity of unity;\r it must be neither too large nor too small to be one. This is a matter\r of secondary importance, like the principle of transposition which was\r intimated in the parable of the earthborn men. The meaning there\r implied was that every man should do that for which he was fitted, and\r be at one with himself, and then the whole city would be united. But\r all these things are secondary, if education, which is the great\r matter, be duly regarded. When the wheel has once been set in motion,\r the speed is always increasing; and eac","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":557},{"id":"plato-the-repu-97","text":"But without education they may patch and mend as they please; they will\r make no progress, any more than a patient who thinks to cure himself by\r some favourite remedy and will not give up his luxurious mode of\r living. If you tell such persons that they must first alter their\r habits, then they grow angry; they are charming people. ‘Charming,—nay,\r the very reverse.’ Evidently these gentlemen are not in your good\r graces, nor the state which is like them. And such states there are\r which first ordain under penalty of death that no one shall alter the\r constitution, and then suffer themselves ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":558},{"id":"plato-the-repu-98","text":"And now what remains of the work of legislation? Nothing for us; but to\r Apollo the god of Delphi we leave the ordering of the greatest of all\r things—that is to say, religion. Only our ancestral deity sitting upon\r the centre and navel of the earth will be trusted by us if we have any\r sense, in an affair of such magnitude. No foreign god shall be supreme\r in our realms...","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":559},{"id":"plato-the-repu-99","text":"Here, as Socrates would say, let us ‘reflect on’ (Greek) what has\r preceded: thus far we have spoken not of the happiness of the citizens,\r but only of the well-being of the State. They may be the happiest of\r men, but our principal aim in founding the State was not to make them\r happy. They were to be guardians, not holiday-makers. In this pleasant\r manner is presented to us the famous question both of ancient and\r modern philosophy, touching the relation of duty to happiness, of right\r to utility.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":560},{"id":"plato-the-repu-100","text":"First duty, then happiness, is the natural order of our moral ideas.\r The utilitarian principle is valuable as a corrective of error, and\r shows to us a side of ethics which is apt to be neglected. It may be\r admitted further that right and utility are co-extensive, and that he\r who makes the happiness of mankind his object has one of the highest\r and noblest motives of human action. But utility is not the historical\r basis of morality; nor the aspect in which moral and religious ideas\r commonly occur to the mind. The greatest happiness of all is, as we\r believe, the far-off result of the divi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":561},{"id":"plato-the-repu-101","text":"The same question reappears in politics, where the useful or expedient\r seems to claim a larger sphere and to have a greater authority. For\r concerning political measures, we chiefly ask: How will they affect the\r happiness of mankind? Yet here too we may observe that what we term\r expediency is merely the law of right limited by the conditions of\r human society. Right and truth are the highest aims of government as\r well as of individuals; and we ought not to lose sight of them because\r we cannot directly enforce them. They appeal to the better mind of\r nations; and sometimes they are too muc","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":562},{"id":"plato-the-repu-102","text":"(1) The manner in which the objection of Adeimantus here, is designed\r to draw out and deepen the argument of Socrates.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":563},{"id":"plato-the-repu-103","text":"(2) The conception of a whole as lying at the foundation both of\r politics and of art, in the latter supplying the only principle of\r criticism, which, under the various names of harmony, symmetry,\r measure, proportion, unity, the Greek seems to have applied to works of\r art.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":564},{"id":"plato-the-repu-104","text":"(3) The requirement that the State should be limited in size, after the\r traditional model of a Greek state; as in the Politics of Aristotle,\r the fact that the cities of Hellas were small is converted into a\r principle.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":565},{"id":"plato-the-repu-105","text":"(4) The humorous pictures of the lean dogs and the fatted sheep, of the\r light active boxer upsetting two stout gentlemen at least, of the\r ‘charming’ patients who are always making themselves worse; or again,\r the playful assumption that there is no State but our own; or the grave\r irony with which the statesman is excused who believes that he is six\r feet high because he is told so, and having nothing to measure with is\r to be pardoned for his ignorance—he is too amusing for us to be\r seriously angry with him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":566},{"id":"plato-the-repu-106","text":"(5) The light and superficial manner in which religion is passed over\r when provision has been made for two great principles,—first, that\r religion shall be based on the highest conception of the gods,\r secondly, that the true national or Hellenic type shall be\r maintained...","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":567},{"id":"plato-the-repu-107","text":"Socrates proceeds: But where amid all this is justice? Son of Ariston,\r tell me where. Light a candle and search the city, and get your brother\r and the rest of our friends to help in seeking for her. ‘That won’t\r do,’ replied Glaucon, ‘you yourself promised to make the search and\r talked about the impiety of deserting justice.’ Well, I said, I will\r lead the way, but do you follow. My notion is, that our State being\r perfect will contain all the four virtues—wisdom, courage, temperance,\r justice. If we eliminate the three first, the unknown remainder will be\r justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":568},{"id":"plato-the-repu-108","text":"First then, of wisdom: the State which we have called into being will\r be wise because politic. And policy is one among many kinds of\r skill,—not the skill of the carpenter, or of the worker in metal, or of\r the husbandman, but the skill of him who advises about the interests of\r the whole State. Of such a kind is the skill of the guardians, who are\r a small class in number, far smaller than the blacksmiths; but in them\r is concentrated the wisdom of the State. And if this small ruling class\r have wisdom, then the whole State will be wise.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"108"},"sequenceIndex":569},{"id":"plato-the-repu-109","text":"Our second virtue is courage, which we have no difficulty in finding in\r another class—that of soldiers. Courage may be defined as a sort of\r salvation—the never-failing salvation of the opinions which law and\r education have prescribed concerning dangers. You know the way in which\r dyers first prepare the white ground and then lay on the dye of purple\r or of any other colour. Colours dyed in this way become fixed, and no\r soap or lye will ever wash them out. Now the ground is education, and\r the laws are the colours; and if the ground is properly laid, neither\r the soap of pleasure nor the ly","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":570},{"id":"plato-the-repu-110","text":"Two virtues remain; temperance and justice. More than the preceding\r virtues temperance suggests the idea of harmony. Some light is thrown\r upon the nature of this virtue by the popular description of a man as\r ‘master of himself’—which has an absurd sound, because the master is\r also the servant. The expression really means that the better principle\r in a man masters the worse. There are in cities whole classes—women,\r slaves and the like—who correspond to the worse, and a few only to the\r better; and in our State the former class are held under control by the\r latter. Now to which of these c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":571},{"id":"plato-the-repu-111","text":"And now we are near the spot; let us draw in and surround the cover and\r watch with all our eyes, lest justice should slip away and escape. Tell\r me, if you see the thicket move first. ‘Nay, I would have you lead.’\r Well then, offer up a prayer and follow. The way is dark and difficult;\r but we must push on. I begin to see a track. ‘Good news.’ Why, Glaucon,\r our dulness of scent is quite ludicrous! While we are straining our\r eyes into the distance, justice is tumbling out at our feet. We are as\r bad as people looking for a thing which they have in their hands. Have\r you forgotten our old pri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":572},{"id":"plato-the-repu-112","text":"Socrates proceeds to discover the nature of justice by a method of\r residues. Each of the first three virtues corresponds to one of the\r three parts of the soul and one of the three classes in the State,\r although the third, temperance, has more of the nature of a harmony\r than the first two. If there be a fourth virtue, that can only be\r sought for in the relation of the three parts in the soul or classes in\r the State to one another. It is obvious and simple, and for that very\r reason has not been found out. The modern logician will be inclined to\r object that ideas cannot be separated like ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":573},{"id":"plato-the-repu-113","text":"There is a famous question discussed in one of the earlier Dialogues of\r Plato (Protagoras; Arist. Nic. Ethics), ‘Whether the virtues are one or\r many?’ This receives an answer which is to the effect that there are\r four cardinal virtues (now for the first time brought together in\r ethical philosophy), and one supreme over the rest, which is not like\r Aristotle’s conception of universal justice, virtue relative to others,\r but the whole of virtue relative to the parts. To this universal\r conception of justice or order in the first education and in the moral\r nature of man, the still more unive","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":574},{"id":"plato-the-repu-114","text":"...Socrates is now going to identify the individual and the State. But\r first he must prove that there are three parts of the individual soul.\r His argument is as follows:—Quantity makes no difference in quality.\r The word ‘just,’ whether applied to the individual or to the State, has\r the same meaning. And the term ‘justice’ implied that the same three\r principles in the State and in the individual were doing their own\r business. But are they really three or one? The question is difficult,\r and one which can hardly be solved by the methods which we are now\r using; but the truer and longer way","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"114"},"sequenceIndex":575},{"id":"plato-the-repu-115","text":"And now, at last, we have reached firm ground, and are able to infer\r that the virtues of the State and of the individual are the same. For\r wisdom and courage and justice in the State are severally the wisdom\r and courage and justice in the individuals who form the State. Each of\r the three classes will do the work of its own class in the State, and\r each part in the individual soul; reason, the superior, and passion,\r the inferior, will be harmonized by the influence of music and\r gymnastic. The counsellor and the warrior, the head and the arm, will\r act together in the town of Mansoul, and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":576},{"id":"plato-the-repu-116","text":"Again the old question returns upon us: Is justice or injustice the\r more profitable? The question has become ridiculous. For injustice,\r like mortal disease, makes life not worth having. Come up with me to\r the hill which overhangs the city and look down upon the single form of\r virtue, and the infinite forms of vice, among which are four special\r ones, characteristic both of states and of individuals. And the state\r which corresponds to the single form of virtue is that which we have\r been describing, wherein reason rules under one of two names—monarchy\r and aristocracy. Thus there are five ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"116"},"sequenceIndex":577},{"id":"plato-the-repu-117","text":"In attempting to prove that the soul has three separate faculties,\r Plato takes occasion to discuss what makes difference of faculties. And\r the criterion which he proposes is difference in the working of the\r faculties. The same faculty cannot produce contradictory effects. But\r the path of early reasoners is beset by thorny entanglements, and he\r will not proceed a step without first clearing the ground. This leads\r him into a tiresome digression, which is intended to explain the nature\r of contradiction. First, the contradiction must be at the same time and\r in the same relation. Secondly, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":578},{"id":"plato-the-repu-118","text":"The psychology of Plato extends no further than the division of the\r soul into the rational, irascible, and concupiscent elements, which, as\r far as we know, was first made by him, and has been retained by\r Aristotle and succeeding ethical writers. The chief difficulty in this\r early analysis of the mind is to define exactly the place of the\r irascible faculty (Greek), which may be variously described under the\r terms righteous indignation, spirit, passion. It is the foundation of\r courage, which includes in Plato moral courage, the courage of enduring\r pain, and of surmounting intellectual di","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":579},{"id":"plato-the-repu-119","text":"We may observe how nearly Plato approaches Aristotle’s famous thesis,\r that ‘good actions produce good habits.’ The words ‘as healthy\r practices (Greek) produce health, so do just practices produce\r justice,’ have a sound very like the Nicomachean Ethics. But we note\r also that an incidental remark in Plato has become a far-reaching\r principle in Aristotle, and an inseparable part of a great Ethical\r system.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":580},{"id":"plato-the-repu-120","text":"There is a difficulty in understanding what Plato meant by ‘the longer\r way’: he seems to intimate some metaphysic of the future which will not\r be satisfied with arguing from the principle of contradiction. In the\r sixth and seventh books (compare Sophist and Parmenides) he has given\r us a sketch of such a metaphysic; but when Glaucon asks for the final\r revelation of the idea of good, he is put off with the declaration that\r he has not yet studied the preliminary sciences. How he would have\r filled up the sketch, or argued about such questions from a higher\r point of view, we can only conjec","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":581},{"id":"plato-the-repu-121","text":"Socrates proceeds:—The guardians of our state are to be watch-dogs, as\r we have already said. Now dogs are not divided into hes and shes—we do\r not take the masculine gender out to hunt and leave the females at home\r to look after their puppies. They have the same employments—the only\r difference between them is that the one sex is stronger and the other\r weaker. But if women are to have the same employments as men, they must\r have the same education—they must be taught music and gymnastics, and\r the art of war. I know that a great joke will be made of their riding\r on horseback and carrying w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"121"},"sequenceIndex":582},{"id":"plato-the-repu-122","text":"The first question is, whether women are able either wholly or\r partially to share in the employments of men. And here we may be\r charged with inconsistency in making the proposal at all. For we\r started originally with the division of labour; and the diversity of\r employments was based on the difference of natures. But is there no\r difference between men and women? Nay, are they not wholly different?\r THERE was the difficulty, Glaucon, which made me unwilling to speak of\r family relations. However, when a man is out of his depth, whether in a\r pool or in an ocean, he can only swim for his lif","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"122"},"sequenceIndex":583},{"id":"plato-the-repu-123","text":"The argument is, that different natures have different uses, and the\r natures of men and women are said to differ. But this is only a verbal\r opposition. We do not consider that the difference may be purely\r nominal and accidental; for example, a bald man and a hairy man are\r opposed in a single point of view, but you cannot infer that because a\r bald man is a cobbler a hairy man ought not to be a cobbler. Now why is\r such an inference erroneous? Simply because the opposition between them\r is partial only, like the difference between a male physician and a\r female physician, not running throug","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"123"},"sequenceIndex":584},{"id":"plato-the-repu-124","text":"The first wave is past, and the argument is compelled to admit that men\r and women have common duties and pursuits. A second and greater wave is\r rolling in—community of wives and children; is this either expedient or\r possible? The expediency I do not doubt; I am not so sure of the\r possibility. ‘Nay, I think that a considerable doubt will be\r entertained on both points.’ I meant to have escaped the trouble of\r proving the first, but as you have detected the little stratagem I must\r even submit. Only allow me to feed my fancy like the solitary in his\r walks, with a dream of what might be, and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"124"},"sequenceIndex":585},{"id":"plato-the-repu-125","text":"In the first place our rulers will enforce the laws and make new ones\r where they are wanted, and their allies or ministers will obey. You, as\r legislator, have already selected the men; and now you shall select the\r women. After the selection has been made, they will dwell in common\r houses and have their meals in common, and will be brought together by\r a necessity more certain than that of mathematics. But they cannot be\r allowed to live in licentiousness; that is an unholy thing, which the\r rulers are determined to prevent. For the avoidance of this, holy\r marriage festivals will be instit","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"125"},"sequenceIndex":586},{"id":"plato-the-repu-126","text":"The parents ought to be in the prime of life, which for a man may be\r reckoned at thirty years—from twenty-five, when he has ‘passed the\r point at which the speed of life is greatest,’ to fifty-five; and at\r twenty years for a woman—from twenty to forty. Any one above or below\r those ages who partakes in the hymeneals shall be guilty of impiety;\r also every one who forms a marriage connexion at other times without\r the consent of the rulers. This latter regulation applies to those who\r are within the specified ages, after which they may range at will,\r provided they avoid the prohibited degree","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"126"},"sequenceIndex":587},{"id":"plato-the-repu-127","text":"Socrates proceeds: I have now to prove that this scheme is advantageous\r and also consistent with our entire polity. The greatest good of a\r State is unity; the greatest evil, discord and distraction. And there\r will be unity where there are no private pleasures or pains or\r interests—where if one member suffers all the members suffer, if one\r citizen is touched all are quickly sensitive; and the least hurt to the\r little finger of the State runs through the whole body and vibrates to\r the soul. For the true State, like an individual, is injured as a whole\r when any part is affected. Every Sta","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"127"},"sequenceIndex":588},{"id":"plato-the-repu-128","text":"Can there be strife and contention among those who are of one mind; or\r lawsuits about property when men have nothing but their bodies which\r they call their own; or suits about violence when every one is bound to\r defend himself? The permission to strike when insulted will be an\r ‘antidote’ to the knife and will prevent disturbances in the State. But\r no younger man will strike an elder; reverence will prevent him from\r laying hands on his kindred, and he will fear that the rest of the\r family may retaliate. Moreover, our citizens will be rid of the lesser\r evils of life; there will be no fla","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"128"},"sequenceIndex":589},{"id":"plato-the-repu-129","text":"But is such a community possible?—as among the animals, so also among\r men; and if possible, in what way possible? About war there is no\r difficulty; the principle of communism is adapted to military service.\r Parents will take their children to look on at a battle, just as\r potters’ boys are trained to the business by looking on at the wheel.\r And to the parents themselves, as to other animals, the sight of their\r young ones will prove a great incentive to bravery. Young warriors must\r learn, but they must not run into danger, although a certain degree of\r risk is worth incurring when the ben","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"129"},"sequenceIndex":590},{"id":"plato-the-repu-130","text":"Cowards and deserters shall be degraded to the class of husbandmen;\r gentlemen who allow themselves to be taken prisoners, may be presented\r to the enemy. But what shall be done to the hero? First of all he shall\r be crowned by all the youths in the army; secondly, he shall receive\r the right hand of fellowship; and thirdly, do you think that there is\r any harm in his being kissed? We have already determined that he shall\r have more wives than others, in order that he may have as many children\r as possible. And at a feast he shall have more to eat; we have the\r authority of Homer for honouring","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"130"},"sequenceIndex":591},{"id":"plato-the-repu-131","text":"The next question is, How shall we treat our enemies? Shall Hellenes be\r enslaved? No; for there is too great a risk of the whole race passing\r under the yoke of the barbarians. Or shall the dead be despoiled?\r Certainly not; for that sort of thing is an excuse for skulking, and\r has been the ruin of many an army. There is meanness and feminine\r malice in making an enemy of the dead body, when the soul which was the\r owner has fled—like a dog who cannot reach his assailants, and quarrels\r with the stones which are thrown at him instead. Again, the arms of\r Hellenes should not be offered up in ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"131"},"sequenceIndex":592},{"id":"plato-the-repu-132","text":"‘But, my dear Socrates, you are forgetting the main question: Is such a\r State possible? I grant all and more than you say about the blessedness\r of being one family—fathers, brothers, mothers, daughters, going out to\r war together; but I want to ascertain the possibility of this ideal\r State.’ You are too unmerciful. The first wave and the second wave I\r have hardly escaped, and now you will certainly drown me with the\r third. When you see the towering crest of the wave, I expect you to\r take pity. ‘Not a whit.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"132"},"sequenceIndex":593},{"id":"plato-the-repu-133","text":"Well, then, we were led to form our ideal polity in the search after\r justice, and the just man answered to the just State. Is this ideal at\r all the worse for being impracticable? Would the picture of a perfectly\r beautiful man be any the worse because no such man ever lived? Can any\r reality come up to the idea? Nature will not allow words to be fully\r realized; but if I am to try and realize the ideal of the State in a\r measure, I think that an approach may be made to the perfection of\r which I dream by one or two, I do not say slight, but possible changes\r in the present constitution of St","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"133"},"sequenceIndex":594},{"id":"plato-the-repu-134","text":"You would acknowledge the existence of abstract ideas, such as justice,\r beauty, good, evil, which are severally one, yet in their various\r combinations appear to be many. Those who recognize these realities are\r philosophers; whereas the other class hear sounds and see colours, and\r understand their use in the arts, but cannot attain to the true or\r waking vision of absolute justice or beauty or truth; they have not the\r light of knowledge, but of opinion, and what they see is a dream only.\r Perhaps he of whom we say the last will be angry with us; can we pacify\r him without revealing the dis","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"134"},"sequenceIndex":595},{"id":"plato-the-repu-135","text":"The fifth book is the new beginning of the Republic, in which the\r community of property and of family are first maintained, and the\r transition is made to the kingdom of philosophers. For both of these\r Plato, after his manner, has been preparing in some chance words of\r Book IV, which fall unperceived on the reader’s mind, as they are\r supposed at first to have fallen on the ear of Glaucon and Adeimantus.\r The ‘paradoxes,’ as Morgenstern terms them, of this book of the\r Republic will be reserved for another place; a few remarks on the\r style, and some explanations of difficulties, may be bri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"135"},"sequenceIndex":596},{"id":"plato-the-repu-136","text":"First, there is the image of the waves, which serves for a sort of\r scheme or plan of the book. The first wave, the second wave, the third\r and greatest wave come rolling in, and we hear the roar of them. All\r that can be said of the extravagance of Plato’s proposals is\r anticipated by himself. Nothing is more admirable than the hesitation\r with which he proposes the solemn text, ‘Until kings are philosophers,’\r etc.; or the reaction from the sublime to the ridiculous, when Glaucon\r describes the manner in which the new truth will be received by\r mankind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"136"},"sequenceIndex":597},{"id":"plato-the-repu-137","text":"Some defects and difficulties may be noted in the execution of the\r communistic plan. Nothing is told us of the application of communism to\r the lower classes; nor is the table of prohibited degrees capable of\r being made out. It is quite possible that a child born at one hymeneal\r festival may marry one of its own brothers or sisters, or even one of\r its parents, at another. Plato is afraid of incestuous unions, but at\r the same time he does not wish to bring before us the fact that the\r city would be divided into families of those born seven and nine months\r after each hymeneal festival. If ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"137"},"sequenceIndex":598},{"id":"plato-the-repu-138","text":"In the delineation of the philosopher, the illustrations of the nature\r of philosophy derived from love are more suited to the apprehension of\r Glaucon, the Athenian man of pleasure, than to modern tastes or\r feelings. They are partly facetious, but also contain a germ of truth.\r That science is a whole, remains a true principle of inductive as well\r as of metaphysical philosophy; and the love of universal knowledge is\r still the characteristic of the philosopher in modern as well as in\r ancient times.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"138"},"sequenceIndex":599},{"id":"plato-the-repu-139","text":"At the end of the fifth book Plato introduces the figment of contingent\r matter, which has exercised so great an influence both on the Ethics\r and Theology of the modern world, and which occurs here for the first\r time in the history of philosophy. He did not remark that the degrees\r of knowledge in the subject have nothing corresponding to them in the\r object. With him a word must answer to an idea; and he could not\r conceive of an opinion which was an opinion about nothing. The\r influence of analogy led him to invent ‘parallels and conjugates’ and\r to overlook facts. To us some of his diffic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"139"},"sequenceIndex":600},{"id":"plato-the-repu-140","text":"Here Adeimantus interposes:—‘No man can answer you, Socrates; but every\r man feels that this is owing to his own deficiency in argument. He is\r driven from one position to another, until he has nothing more to say,\r just as an unskilful player at draughts is reduced to his last move by\r a more skilled opponent. And yet all the time he may be right. He may\r know, in this very instance, that those who make philosophy the\r business of their lives, generally turn out rogues if they are bad men,\r and fools if they are good. What do you say?’ I should say that he is\r quite right. ‘Then how is such a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"140"},"sequenceIndex":601},{"id":"plato-the-repu-141","text":"I shall answer you in a parable which will also let you see how poor a\r hand I am at the invention of allegories. The relation of good men to\r their governments is so peculiar, that in order to defend them I must\r take an illustration from the world of fiction. Conceive the captain of\r a ship, taller by a head and shoulders than any of the crew, yet a\r little deaf, a little blind, and rather ignorant of the seaman’s art.\r The sailors want to steer, although they know nothing of the art; and\r they have a theory that it cannot be learned. If the helm is refused\r them, they drug the captain’s pos","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"141"},"sequenceIndex":602},{"id":"plato-the-repu-142","text":"The point which has to be considered, is the origin of this corruption\r in nature. Every one will admit that the philosopher, in our\r description of him, is a rare being. But what numberless causes tend to\r destroy these rare beings! There is no good thing which may not be a\r cause of evil—health, wealth, strength, rank, and the virtues\r themselves, when placed under unfavourable circumstances. For as in the\r animal or vegetable world the strongest seeds most need the\r accompaniment of good air and soil, so the best of human characters\r turn out the worst when they fall upon an unsuitable soil","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"142"},"sequenceIndex":603},{"id":"plato-the-repu-143","text":"Enough, then, of the causes why philosophy has such an evil name.\r Another question is, Which of existing states is suited to her? Not one\r of them; at present she is like some exotic seed which degenerates in a\r strange soil; only in her proper state will she be shown to be of\r heavenly growth. ‘And is her proper state ours or some other?’ Ours in\r all points but one, which was left undetermined. You may remember our\r saying that some living mind or witness of the legislator was needed in\r states. But we were afraid to enter upon a subject of such difficulty,\r and now the question recurs and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"143"},"sequenceIndex":604},{"id":"plato-the-repu-144","text":"In the first place, I say boldly that nothing can be worse than the\r present mode of study. Persons usually pick up a little philosophy in\r early youth, and in the intervals of business, but they never master\r the real difficulty, which is dialectic. Later, perhaps, they\r occasionally go to a lecture on philosophy. Years advance, and the sun\r of philosophy, unlike that of Heracleitus, sets never to rise again.\r This order of education should be reversed; it should begin with\r gymnastics in youth, and as the man strengthens, he should increase the\r gymnastics of his soul. Then, when active life","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"144"},"sequenceIndex":605},{"id":"plato-the-repu-145","text":"I gained nothing by evading the troublesome questions which arose\r concerning women and children. I will be wiser now and acknowledge that\r we must go to the bottom of another question: What is to be the\r education of our guardians? It was agreed that they were to be lovers\r of their country, and were to be tested in the refiner’s fire of\r pleasures and pains, and those who came forth pure and remained fixed\r in their principles were to have honours and rewards in life and after\r death. But at this point, the argument put on her veil and turned into\r another path. I hesitated to make the asser","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"145"},"sequenceIndex":606},{"id":"plato-the-repu-146","text":"Like Socrates, we may recapitulate the virtues of the philosopher. In\r language which seems to reach beyond the horizon of that age and\r country, he is described as ‘the spectator of all time and all\r existence.’ He has the noblest gifts of nature, and makes the highest\r use of them. All his desires are absorbed in the love of wisdom, which\r is the love of truth. None of the graces of a beautiful soul are\r wanting in him; neither can he fear death, or think much of human life.\r The ideal of modern times hardly retains the simplicity of the antique;\r there is not the same originality either in ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"146"},"sequenceIndex":607},{"id":"plato-the-repu-147","text":"Adeimantus objects first of all to the form of the Socratic reasoning,\r thus showing that Plato is aware of the imperfection of his own method.\r He brings the accusation against himself which might be brought against\r him by a modern logician—that he extracts the answer because he knows\r how to put the question. In a long argument words are apt to change\r their meaning slightly, or premises may be assumed or conclusions\r inferred with rather too much certainty or universality; the variation\r at each step may be unobserved, and yet at last the divergence becomes\r considerable. Hence the failure","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"147"},"sequenceIndex":608},{"id":"plato-the-repu-148","text":"The objection, though fairly met by Socrates in this particular\r instance, may be regarded as implying a reflection upon the Socratic\r mode of reasoning. And here, as elsewhere, Plato seems to intimate that\r the time had come when the negative and interrogative method of\r Socrates must be superseded by a positive and constructive one, of\r which examples are given in some of the later dialogues. Adeimantus\r further argues that the ideal is wholly at variance with facts; for\r experience proves philosophers to be either useless or rogues. Contrary\r to all expectation Socrates has no hesitation in","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"148"},"sequenceIndex":609},{"id":"plato-the-repu-149","text":"The uselessness of philosophers is explained by the circumstance that\r mankind will not use them. The world in all ages has been divided\r between contempt and fear of those who employ the power of ideas and\r know no other weapons. Concerning the false philosopher, Socrates\r argues that the best is most liable to corruption; and that the finer\r nature is more likely to suffer from alien conditions. We too observe\r that there are some kinds of excellence which spring from a peculiar\r delicacy of constitution; as is evidently true of the poetical and\r imaginative temperament, which often seems to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"149"},"sequenceIndex":610},{"id":"plato-the-repu-150","text":"Yet the thesis, ‘corruptio optimi pessima,’ cannot be maintained\r generally or without regard to the kind of excellence which is\r corrupted. The alien conditions which are corrupting to one nature, may\r be the elements of culture to another. In general a man can only\r receive his highest development in a congenial state or family, among\r friends or fellow-workers. But also he may sometimes be stirred by\r adverse circumstances to such a degree that he rises up against them\r and reforms them. And while weaker or coarser characters will extract\r good out of evil, say in a corrupt state of the chu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"150"},"sequenceIndex":611},{"id":"plato-the-repu-151","text":"Plato would have us consider how easily the best natures are\r overpowered by public opinion, and what efforts the rest of mankind\r will make to get possession of them. The world, the church, their own\r profession, any political or party organization, are always carrying\r them off their legs and teaching them to apply high and holy names to\r their own prejudices and interests. The ‘monster’ corporation to which\r they belong judges right and truth to be the pleasure of the community.\r The individual becomes one with his order; or, if he resists, the world\r is too much for him, and will sooner or","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"151"},"sequenceIndex":612},{"id":"plato-the-repu-152","text":"When the higher natures are corrupted by politics, the lower take\r possession of the vacant place of philosophy. This is described in one\r of those continuous images in which the argument, to use a Platonic\r expression, ‘veils herself,’ and which is dropped and reappears at\r intervals. The question is asked,—Why are the citizens of states so\r hostile to philosophy? The answer is, that they do not know her. And\r yet there is also a better mind of the many; they would believe if they\r were taught. But hitherto they have only known a conventional imitation\r of philosophy, words without thoughts, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"152"},"sequenceIndex":613},{"id":"plato-the-repu-153","text":"In the latter part of the sixth book, three questions have to be\r considered: 1st, the nature of the longer and more circuitous way,\r which is contrasted with the shorter and more imperfect method of Book\r IV; 2nd, the heavenly pattern or idea of the state; 3rd, the relation\r of the divisions of knowledge to one another and to the corresponding\r faculties of the soul:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"153"},"sequenceIndex":614},{"id":"plato-the-repu-154","text":"1. Of the higher method of knowledge in Plato we have only a glimpse.\r Neither here nor in the Phaedrus or Symposium, nor yet in the Philebus\r or Sophist, does he give any clear explanation of his meaning. He would\r probably have described his method as proceeding by regular steps to a\r system of universal knowledge, which inferred the parts from the whole\r rather than the whole from the parts. This ideal logic is not practised\r by him in the search after justice, or in the analysis of the parts of\r the soul; there, like Aristotle in the Nicomachean Ethics, he argues\r from experience and the c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"154"},"sequenceIndex":615},{"id":"plato-the-repu-155","text":"In modern times we hardly need to be reminded that the process of\r acquiring knowledge is here confused with the contemplation of absolute\r knowledge. In all science a priori and a posteriori truths mingle in\r various proportions. The a priori part is that which is derived from\r the most universal experience of men, or is universally accepted by\r them; the a posteriori is that which grows up around the more general\r principles and becomes imperceptibly one with them. But Plato\r erroneously imagines that the synthesis is separable from the analysis,\r and that the method of science can anticipat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"155"},"sequenceIndex":616},{"id":"plato-the-repu-156","text":"2. Plato supposes that when the tablet has been made blank the artist\r will fill in the lineaments of the ideal state. Is this a pattern laid\r up in heaven, or mere vacancy on which he is supposed to gaze with\r wondering eye? The answer is, that such ideals are framed partly by the\r omission of particulars, partly by imagination perfecting the form\r which experience supplies (Phaedo). Plato represents these ideals in a\r figure as belonging to another world; and in modern times the idea will\r sometimes seem to precede, at other times to co-operate with the hand\r of the artist. As in science, so","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"156"},"sequenceIndex":617},{"id":"plato-the-repu-157","text":"3. There is no difficulty in seeing that Plato’s divisions of knowledge\r are based, first, on the fundamental antithesis of sensible and\r intellectual which pervades the whole pre-Socratic philosophy; in which\r is implied also the opposition of the permanent and transient, of the\r universal and particular. But the age of philosophy in which he lived\r seemed to require a further distinction;—numbers and figures were\r beginning to separate from ideas. The world could no longer regard\r justice as a cube, and was learning to see, though imperfectly, that\r the abstractions of sense were distinct fr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"157"},"sequenceIndex":618},{"id":"plato-the-repu-158","text":"There is more difficulty in comprehending how he arrived at the first\r term of the series, which is nowhere else mentioned, and has no\r reference to any other part of his system. Nor indeed does the relation\r of shadows to objects correspond to the relation of numbers to ideas.\r Probably Plato has been led by the love of analogy (Timaeus) to make\r four terms instead of three, although the objects perceived in both\r divisions of the lower sphere are equally objects of sense. He is also\r preparing the way, as his manner is, for the shadows of images at the\r beginning of the seventh book, and the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"158"},"sequenceIndex":619},{"id":"plato-the-repu-159","text":"The difference between understanding and mind or reason (Greek) is\r analogous to the difference between acquiring knowledge in the parts\r and the contemplation of the whole. True knowledge is a whole, and is\r at rest; consistency and universality are the tests of truth. To this\r self-evidencing knowledge of the whole the faculty of mind is supposed\r to correspond. But there is a knowledge of the understanding which is\r incomplete and in motion always, because unable to rest in the\r subordinate ideas. Those ideas are called both images and\r hypotheses—images because they are clothed in sense, h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"159"},"sequenceIndex":620},{"id":"plato-the-repu-160","text":"The general meaning of the passage, ‘Noble, then, is the bond which\r links together sight...And of this kind I spoke as the intelligible...’\r so far as the thought contained in it admits of being translated into\r the terms of modern philosophy, may be described or explained as\r follows:—There is a truth, one and self-existent, to which by the help\r of a ladder let down from above, the human intelligence may ascend.\r This unity is like the sun in the heavens, the light by which all\r things are seen, the being by which they are created and sustained. It\r is the IDEA of good. And the steps of the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"160"},"sequenceIndex":621},{"id":"plato-the-repu-161","text":"We cannot give any more precise meaning to this remarkable passage, but\r we may trace in it several rudiments or vestiges of thought which are\r common to us and to Plato: such as (1) the unity and correlation of the\r sciences, or rather of science, for in Plato’s time they were not yet\r parted off or distinguished; (2) the existence of a Divine Power, or\r life or idea or cause or reason, not yet conceived or no longer\r conceived as in the Timaeus and elsewhere under the form of a person;\r (3) the recognition of the hypothetical and conditional character of\r the mathematical sciences, and in a ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"161"},"sequenceIndex":622},{"id":"plato-the-repu-162","text":"The method of Socrates is hesitating and tentative, awaiting the fuller\r explanation of the idea of good, and of the nature of dialectic in the\r seventh book. The imperfect intelligence of Glaucon, and the reluctance\r of Socrates to make a beginning, mark the difficulty of the subject.\r The allusion to Theages’ bridle, and to the internal oracle, or demonic\r sign, of Socrates, which here, as always in Plato, is only prohibitory;\r the remark that the salvation of any remnant of good in the present\r evil state of the world is due to God only; the reference to a future\r state of existence, which ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"162"},"sequenceIndex":623},{"id":"plato-the-repu-163","text":"Yet a few more words may be added, on the old theme, which was so oft\r discussed in the Socratic circle, of which we, like Glaucon and\r Adeimantus, would fain, if possible, have a clearer notion. Like them,\r we are dissatisfied when we are told that the idea of good can only be\r revealed to a student of the mathematical sciences, and we are inclined\r to think that neither we nor they could have been led along that path\r to any satisfactory goal. For we have learned that differences of\r quantity cannot pass into differences of quality, and that the\r mathematical sciences can never rise above th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"163"},"sequenceIndex":624},{"id":"plato-the-repu-164","text":"The idea of good is one of those sacred words or forms of thought,\r which were beginning to take the place of the old mythology. It meant\r unity, in which all time and all existence were gathered up. It was the\r truth of all things, and also the light in which they shone forth, and\r became evident to intelligences human and divine. It was the cause of\r all things, the power by which they were brought into being. It was the\r universal reason divested of a human personality. It was the life as\r well as the light of the world, all knowledge and all power were\r comprehended in it. The way to it wa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"164"},"sequenceIndex":625},{"id":"plato-the-repu-165","text":"This, or something like this, is the meaning of the idea of good as\r conceived by Plato. Ideas of number, order, harmony, development may\r also be said to enter into it. The paraphrase which has just been given\r of it goes beyond the actual words of Plato. We have perhaps arrived at\r the stage of philosophy which enables us to understand what he is\r aiming at, better than he did himself. We are beginning to realize what\r he saw darkly and at a distance. But if he could have been told that\r this, or some conception of the same kind, but higher than this, was\r the truth at which he was aiming, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"165"},"sequenceIndex":626},{"id":"plato-the-repu-166","text":"Then now comes the question,—How shall we create our rulers; what way\r is there from darkness to light? The change is effected by philosophy;\r it is not the turning over of an oyster-shell, but the conversion of a\r soul from night to day, from becoming to being. And what training will\r draw the soul upwards? Our former education had two branches,\r gymnastic, which was occupied with the body, and music, the sister art,\r which infused a natural harmony into mind and literature; but neither\r of these sciences gave any promise of doing what we want. Nothing\r remains to us but that universal or pri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"166"},"sequenceIndex":627},{"id":"plato-the-repu-167","text":"Let our second branch of education be geometry. ‘I can easily see,’\r replied Glaucon, ‘that the skill of the general will be doubled by his\r knowledge of geometry.’ That is a small matter; the use of geometry, to\r which I refer, is the assistance given by it in the contemplation of\r the idea of good, and the compelling the mind to look at true being,\r and not at generation only. Yet the present mode of pursuing these\r studies, as any one who is the least of a mathematician is aware, is\r mean and ridiculous; they are made to look downwards to the arts, and\r not upwards to eternal existence. The","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"167"},"sequenceIndex":628},{"id":"plato-the-repu-168","text":"Shall we propose, as a third branch of our education, astronomy? ‘Very\r good,’ replied Glaucon; ‘the knowledge of the heavens is necessary at\r once for husbandry, navigation, military tactics.’ I like your way of\r giving useful reasons for everything in order to make friends of the\r world. And there is a difficulty in proving to mankind that education\r is not only useful information but a purification of the eye of the\r soul, which is better than the bodily eye, for by this alone is truth\r seen. Now, will you appeal to mankind in general or to the philosopher?\r or would you prefer to look to y","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"168"},"sequenceIndex":629},{"id":"plato-the-repu-169","text":"‘Very good, and now let us proceed to astronomy, about which I am\r willing to speak in your lofty strain. No one can fail to see that the\r contemplation of the heavens draws the soul upwards.’ I am an\r exception, then; astronomy as studied at present appears to me to draw\r the soul not upwards, but downwards. Star-gazing is just looking up at\r the ceiling—no better; a man may lie on his back on land or on water—he\r may look up or look down, but there is no science in that. The vision\r of knowledge of which I speak is seen not with the eyes, but with the\r mind. All the magnificence of the heave","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"169"},"sequenceIndex":630},{"id":"plato-the-repu-170","text":"Still, mathematics admit of other applications, as the Pythagoreans\r say, and we agree. There is a sister science of harmonical motion,\r adapted to the ear as astronomy is to the eye, and there may be other\r applications also. Let us inquire of the Pythagoreans about them, not\r forgetting that we have an aim higher than theirs, which is the\r relation of these sciences to the idea of good. The error which\r pervades astronomy also pervades harmonics. The musicians put their\r ears in the place of their minds. ‘Yes,’ replied Glaucon, ‘I like to\r see them laying their ears alongside of their neighb","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"170"},"sequenceIndex":631},{"id":"plato-the-repu-171","text":"All these sciences are the prelude of the strain, and are profitable if\r they are regarded in their natural relations to one another. ‘I dare\r say, Socrates,’ said Glaucon; ‘but such a study will be an endless\r business.’ What study do you mean—of the prelude, or what? For all\r these things are only the prelude, and you surely do not suppose that a\r mere mathematician is also a dialectician? ‘Certainly not. I have\r hardly ever known a mathematician who could reason.’ And yet, Glaucon,\r is not true reasoning that hymn of dialectic which is the music of the\r intellectual world, and which was by ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"171"},"sequenceIndex":632},{"id":"plato-the-repu-172","text":"‘So far, I agree with you. But now, leaving the prelude, let us proceed\r to the hymn. What, then, is the nature of dialectic, and what are the\r paths which lead thither?’ Dear Glaucon, you cannot follow me here.\r There can be no revelation of the absolute truth to one who has not\r been disciplined in the previous sciences. But that there is a science\r of absolute truth, which is attained in some way very different from\r those now practised, I am confident. For all other arts or sciences are\r relative to human needs and opinions; and the mathematical sciences are\r but a dream or hypothesis of t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"172"},"sequenceIndex":633},{"id":"plato-the-repu-173","text":"I dare say that you have not forgotten how our rulers were chosen; and\r the process of selection may be carried a step further:—As before, they\r must be constant and valiant, good-looking, and of noble manners, but\r now they must also have natural ability which education will improve;\r that is to say, they must be quick at learning, capable of mental toil,\r retentive, solid, diligent natures, who combine intellectual with moral\r virtues; not lame and one-sided, diligent in bodily exercise and\r indolent in mind, or conversely; not a maimed soul, which hates\r falsehood and yet unintentionally is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"173"},"sequenceIndex":634},{"id":"plato-the-repu-174","text":"‘You are a statuary, Socrates, and have made a perfect image of our\r governors.’ Yes, and of our governesses, for the women will share in\r all things with the men. And you will admit that our State is not a\r mere aspiration, but may really come into being when there shall arise\r philosopher-kings, one or more, who will despise earthly vanities, and\r will be the servants of justice only. ‘And how will they begin their\r work?’ Their first act will be to send away into the country all those\r who are more than ten years of age, and to proceed with those who are\r left...","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"174"},"sequenceIndex":635},{"id":"plato-the-repu-175","text":"At the commencement of the sixth book, Plato anticipated his\r explanation of the relation of the philosopher to the world in an\r allegory, in this, as in other passages, following the order which he\r prescribes in education, and proceeding from the concrete to the\r abstract. At the commencement of Book VII, under the figure of a cave\r having an opening towards a fire and a way upwards to the true light,\r he returns to view the divisions of knowledge, exhibiting familiarly,\r as in a picture, the result which had been hardly won by a great effort\r of thought in the previous discussion; at the sa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"175"},"sequenceIndex":636},{"id":"plato-the-repu-176","text":"There seem to be two great aims in the philosophy of Plato,—first, to\r realize abstractions; secondly, to connect them. According to him, the\r true education is that which draws men from becoming to being, and to a\r comprehensive survey of all being. He desires to develop in the human\r mind the faculty of seeing the universal in all things; until at last\r the particulars of sense drop away and the universal alone remains. He\r then seeks to combine the universals which he has disengaged from\r sense, not perceiving that the correlation of them has no other basis\r but the common use of language. ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"176"},"sequenceIndex":637},{"id":"plato-the-repu-177","text":"The modern mathematician will readily sympathise with Plato’s delight\r in the properties of pure mathematics. He will not be disinclined to\r say with him:—Let alone the heavens, and study the beauties of number\r and figure in themselves. He too will be apt to depreciate their\r application to the arts. He will observe that Plato has a conception of\r geometry, in which figures are to be dispensed with; thus in a distant\r and shadowy way seeming to anticipate the possibility of working\r geometrical problems by a more general mode of analysis. He will remark\r with interest on the backward state of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"177"},"sequenceIndex":638},{"id":"plato-the-repu-178","text":"The metaphysical philosopher from his point of view recognizes\r mathematics as an instrument of education,—which strengthens the power\r of attention, developes the sense of order and the faculty of\r construction, and enables the mind to grasp under simple formulae the\r quantitative differences of physical phenomena. But while acknowledging\r their value in education, he sees also that they have no connexion with\r our higher moral and intellectual ideas. In the attempt which Plato\r makes to connect them, we easily trace the influences of ancient\r Pythagorean notions. There is no reason to suppos","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"178"},"sequenceIndex":639},{"id":"plato-the-repu-179","text":"Two passages seem to require more particular explanations. First, that\r which relates to the analysis of vision. The difficulty in this passage\r may be explained, like many others, from differences in the modes of\r conception prevailing among ancient and modern thinkers. To us, the\r perceptions of sense are inseparable from the act of the mind which\r accompanies them. The consciousness of form, colour, distance, is\r indistinguishable from the simple sensation, which is the medium of\r them. Whereas to Plato sense is the Heraclitean flux of sense, not the\r vision of objects in the order in which","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"179"},"sequenceIndex":640},{"id":"plato-the-repu-180","text":"The second difficulty relates to Plato’s conception of harmonics. Three\r classes of harmonists are distinguished by him:—first, the\r Pythagoreans, whom he proposes to consult as in the previous discussion\r on music he was to consult Damon—they are acknowledged to be masters in\r the art, but are altogether deficient in the knowledge of its higher\r import and relation to the good; secondly, the mere empirics, whom\r Glaucon appears to confuse with them, and whom both he and Socrates\r ludicrously describe as experimenting by mere auscultation on the\r intervals of sounds. Both of these fall short i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"180"},"sequenceIndex":641},{"id":"plato-the-repu-181","text":"The allegory has a political as well as a philosophical meaning. The\r den or cave represents the narrow sphere of politics or law (compare\r the description of the philosopher and lawyer in the Theaetetus), and\r the light of the eternal ideas is supposed to exercise a disturbing\r influence on the minds of those who return to this lower world. In\r other words, their principles are too wide for practical application;\r they are looking far away into the past and future, when their business\r is with the present. The ideal is not easily reduced to the conditions\r of actual life, and may often be at ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"181"},"sequenceIndex":642},{"id":"plato-the-repu-182","text":"Many illustrations of this part of the Republic may be found in modern\r Politics and in daily life. For among ourselves, too, there have been\r two sorts of Politicians or Statesmen, whose eyesight has become\r disordered in two different ways. First, there have been great men who,\r in the language of Burke, ‘have been too much given to general maxims,’\r who, like J.S. Mill or Burke himself, have been theorists or\r philosophers before they were politicians, or who, having been students\r of history, have allowed some great historical parallel, such as the\r English Revolution of 1688, or possibly ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"182"},"sequenceIndex":643},{"id":"plato-the-repu-183","text":"With this disorder of eyesight may be contrasted another—of those who\r see not far into the distance, but what is near only; who have been\r engaged all their lives in a trade or a profession; who are limited to\r a set or sect of their own. Men of this kind have no universal except\r their own interests or the interests of their class, no principle but\r the opinion of persons like themselves, no knowledge of affairs beyond\r what they pick up in the streets or at their club. Suppose them to be\r sent into a larger world, to undertake some higher calling, from being\r tradesmen to turn generals or p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"183"},"sequenceIndex":644},{"id":"plato-the-repu-184","text":"Nor have we any difficulty in drawing a parallel between the young\r Athenian in the fifth century before Christ who became unsettled by new\r ideas, and the student of a modern University who has been the subject\r of a similar ‘aufklärung.’ We too observe that when young men begin to\r criticise customary beliefs, or to analyse the constitution of human\r nature, they are apt to lose hold of solid principle (ἅπαν τὸ βέβαιον\r αὐτῶν ἐξοίχεται). They are like trees which have been frequently\r transplanted. The earth about them is loose, and they have no roots\r reaching far into the soil. They ‘light","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"184"},"sequenceIndex":645},{"id":"plato-the-repu-185","text":"The distinction between the mathematician and the dialectician is also\r noticeable. Plato is very well aware that the faculty of the\r mathematician is quite distinct from the higher philosophical sense\r which recognizes and combines first principles. The contempt which he\r expresses for distinctions of words, the danger of involuntary\r falsehood, the apology which Socrates makes for his earnestness of\r speech, are highly characteristic of the Platonic style and mode of\r thought. The quaint notion that if Palamedes was the inventor of number\r Agamemnon could not have counted his feet; the art b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"185"},"sequenceIndex":646},{"id":"plato-the-repu-186","text":"But how did timocracy arise out of the perfect State? Plainly, like all\r changes of government, from division in the rulers. But whence came\r division? ‘Sing, heavenly Muses,’ as Homer says;—let them condescend to\r answer us, as if we were children, to whom they put on a solemn face in\r jest. ‘And what will they say?’ They will say that human things are\r fated to decay, and even the perfect State will not escape from this\r law of destiny, when ‘the wheel comes full circle’ in a period short or\r long. Plants or animals have times of fertility and sterility, which\r the intelligence of rulers bec","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"186"},"sequenceIndex":647},{"id":"plato-the-repu-187","text":"The new form of government resembles the ideal in obedience to rulers\r and contempt for trade, and having common meals, and in devotion to\r warlike and gymnastic exercises. But corruption has crept into\r philosophy, and simplicity of character, which was once her note, is\r now looked for only in the military class. Arts of war begin to prevail\r over arts of peace; the ruler is no longer a philosopher; as in\r oligarchies, there springs up among them an extravagant love of\r gain—get another man’s and save your own, is their principle; and they\r have dark places in which they hoard their gold and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"187"},"sequenceIndex":648},{"id":"plato-the-repu-188","text":"And what manner of man answers to such a State? ‘In love of\r contention,’ replied Adeimantus, ‘he will be like our friend Glaucon.’\r In that respect, perhaps, but not in others. He is self-asserting and\r ill-educated, yet fond of literature, although not himself a\r speaker,—fierce with slaves, but obedient to rulers, a lover of power\r and honour, which he hopes to gain by deeds of arms,—fond, too, of\r gymnastics and of hunting. As he advances in years he grows avaricious,\r for he has lost philosophy, which is the only saviour and guardian of\r men. His origin is as follows:—His father is a good","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"188"},"sequenceIndex":649},{"id":"plato-the-repu-189","text":"And now let us set another city over against another man. The next form\r of government is oligarchy, in which the rule is of the rich only; nor\r is it difficult to see how such a State arises. The decline begins with\r the possession of gold and silver; illegal modes of expenditure are\r invented; one draws another on, and the multitude are infected; riches\r outweigh virtue; lovers of money take the place of lovers of honour;\r misers of politicians; and, in time, political privileges are confined\r by law to the rich, who do not shrink from violence in order to effect\r their purposes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"189"},"sequenceIndex":650},{"id":"plato-the-repu-190","text":"Thus much of the origin,—let us next consider the evils of oligarchy.\r Would a man who wanted to be safe on a voyage take a bad pilot because\r he was rich, or refuse a good one because he was poor? And does not the\r analogy apply still more to the State? And there are yet greater evils:\r two nations are struggling together in one—the rich and the poor; and\r the rich dare not put arms into the hands of the poor, and are\r unwilling to pay for defenders out of their own money. And have we not\r already condemned that State in which the same persons are warriors as\r well as shopkeepers? The greates","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"190"},"sequenceIndex":651},{"id":"plato-the-repu-191","text":"Like State, like man,—the change in the latter begins with the\r representative of timocracy; he walks at first in the ways of his\r father, who may have been a statesman, or general, perhaps; and\r presently he sees him ‘fallen from his high estate,’ the victim of\r informers, dying in prison or exile, or by the hand of the executioner.\r The lesson which he thus receives, makes him cautious; he leaves\r politics, represses his pride, and saves pence. Avarice is enthroned as\r his bosom’s lord, and assumes the style of the Great King; the rational\r and spirited elements sit humbly on the ground at e","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"191"},"sequenceIndex":652},{"id":"plato-the-repu-192","text":"Next comes democracy and the democratic man, out of oligarchy and the\r oligarchical man. Insatiable avarice is the ruling passion of an\r oligarchy; and they encourage expensive habits in order that they may\r gain by the ruin of extravagant youth. Thus men of family often lose\r their property or rights of citizenship; but they remain in the city,\r full of hatred against the new owners of their estates and ripe for\r revolution. The usurer with stooping walk pretends not to see them; he\r passes by, and leaves his sting—that is, his money—in some other\r victim; and many a man has to pay the parent","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"192"},"sequenceIndex":653},{"id":"plato-the-repu-193","text":"The manner of life in such a State is that of democrats; there is\r freedom and plainness of speech, and every man does what is right in\r his own eyes, and has his own way of life. Hence arise the most various\r developments of character; the State is like a piece of embroidery of\r which the colours and figures are the manners of men, and there are\r many who, like women and children, prefer this variety to real beauty\r and excellence. The State is not one but many, like a bazaar at which\r you can buy anything. The great charm is, that you may do as you like;\r you may govern if you like, let it a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"193"},"sequenceIndex":654},{"id":"plato-the-repu-194","text":"Let us now inspect the individual democrat; and first, as in the case\r of the State, we will trace his antecedents. He is the son of a miserly\r oligarch, and has been taught by him to restrain the love of\r unnecessary pleasures. Perhaps I ought to explain this latter\r term:—Necessary pleasures are those which are good, and which we cannot\r do without; unnecessary pleasures are those which do no good, and of\r which the desire might be eradicated by early training. For example,\r the pleasures of eating and drinking are necessary and healthy, up to a\r certain point; beyond that point they are ali","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"194"},"sequenceIndex":655},{"id":"plato-the-repu-195","text":"The oligarch changes into the democrat in the following manner:—The\r youth who has had a miserly bringing up, gets a taste of the drone’s\r honey; he meets with wild companions, who introduce him to every new\r pleasure. As in the State, so in the individual, there are allies on\r both sides, temptations from without and passions from within; there is\r reason also and external influences of parents and friends in alliance\r with the oligarchical principle; and the two factions are in violent\r conflict with one another. Sometimes the party of order prevails, but\r then again new desires and new diso","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"195"},"sequenceIndex":656},{"id":"plato-the-repu-196","text":"There remains still the finest and fairest of all men and all\r States—tyranny and the tyrant. Tyranny springs from democracy much as\r democracy springs from oligarchy. Both arise from excess; the one from\r excess of wealth, the other from excess of freedom. ‘The great natural\r good of life,’ says the democrat, ‘is freedom.’ And this exclusive love\r of freedom and regardlessness of everything else, is the cause of the\r change from democracy to tyranny. The State demands the strong wine of\r freedom, and unless her rulers give her a plentiful draught, punishes\r and insults them; equality and frat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"196"},"sequenceIndex":657},{"id":"plato-the-repu-197","text":"In the early days of his tyranny he smiles and beams upon everybody; he\r is not a ‘dominus,’ no, not he: he has only come to put an end to debt\r and the monopoly of land. Having got rid of foreign enemies, he makes\r himself necessary to the State by always going to war. He is thus\r enabled to depress the poor by heavy taxes, and so keep them at work;\r and he can get rid of bolder spirits by handing them over to the enemy.\r Then comes unpopularity; some of his old associates have the courage to\r oppose him. The consequence is, that he has to make a purgation of the\r State; but, unlike the physi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"197"},"sequenceIndex":658},{"id":"plato-the-repu-198","text":"In the previous books Plato has described the ideal State; now he\r returns to the perverted or declining forms, on which he had lightly\r touched at the end of Book IV. These he describes in a succession of\r parallels between the individuals and the States, tracing the origin of\r either in the State or individual which has preceded them. He begins by\r asking the point at which he digressed; and is thus led shortly to\r recapitulate the substance of the three former books, which also\r contain a parallel of the philosopher and the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"198"},"sequenceIndex":659},{"id":"plato-the-repu-199","text":"Of the first decline he gives no intelligible account; he would not\r have liked to admit the most probable causes of the fall of his ideal\r State, which to us would appear to be the impracticability of communism\r or the natural antagonism of the ruling and subject classes. He throws\r a veil of mystery over the origin of the decline, which he attributes\r to ignorance of the law of population. Of this law the famous\r geometrical figure or number is the expression. Like the ancients in\r general, he had no idea of the gradual perfectibility of man or of the\r education of the human race. His ideal ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"199"},"sequenceIndex":660},{"id":"plato-the-repu-200","text":"The first of these declining States is timocracy, or the government of\r soldiers and lovers of honour, which answers to the Spartan State; this\r is a government of force, in which education is not inspired by the\r Muses, but imposed by the law, and in which all the finer elements of\r organization have disappeared. The philosopher himself has lost the\r love of truth, and the soldier, who is of a simpler and honester\r nature, rules in his stead. The individual who answers to timocracy has\r some noticeable qualities. He is described as ill educated, but, like\r the Spartan, a lover of literature; ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"200"},"sequenceIndex":661},{"id":"plato-the-repu-201","text":"The two next stages in the decline of constitutions have even less\r historical foundation. For there is no trace in Greek history of a\r polity like the Spartan or Cretan passing into an oligarchy of wealth,\r or of the oligarchy of wealth passing into a democracy. The order of\r history appears to be different; first, in the Homeric times there is\r the royal or patriarchal form of government, which a century or two\r later was succeeded by an oligarchy of birth rather than of wealth, and\r in which wealth was only the accident of the hereditary possession of\r land and power. Sometimes this oligarc","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"201"},"sequenceIndex":662},{"id":"plato-the-repu-202","text":"The portrait of the tyrant himself is just such as the later Greek\r delighted to draw of Phalaris and Dionysius, in which, as in the lives\r of mediaeval saints or mythic heroes, the conduct and actions of one\r were attributed to another in order to fill up the outline. There was\r no enormity which the Greek was not today to believe of them; the\r tyrant was the negation of government and law; his assassination was\r glorious; there was no crime, however unnatural, which might not with\r probability be attributed to him. In this, Plato was only following the\r common thought of his countrymen, whic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"202"},"sequenceIndex":663},{"id":"plato-the-repu-203","text":"Plato in a hyperbolical and serio-comic vein exaggerates the follies of\r democracy which he also sees reflected in social life. To him democracy\r is a state of individualism or dissolution; in which every one is doing\r what is right in his own eyes. Of a people animated by a common spirit\r of liberty, rising as one man to repel the Persian host, which is the\r leading idea of democracy in Herodotus and Thucydides, he never seems\r to think. But if he is not a believer in liberty, still less is he a\r lover of tyranny. His deeper and more serious condemnation is reserved\r for the tyrant, who is th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"203"},"sequenceIndex":664},{"id":"plato-the-repu-204","text":"Each of these governments and individuals has a corresponding ethical\r gradation: the ideal State is under the rule of reason, not\r extinguishing but harmonizing the passions, and training them in\r virtue; in the timocracy and the timocratic man the constitution,\r whether of the State or of the individual, is based, first, upon\r courage, and secondly, upon the love of honour; this latter virtue,\r which is hardly to be esteemed a virtue, has superseded all the rest.\r In the second stage of decline the virtues have altogether disappeared,\r and the love of gain has succeeded to them; in the third","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"204"},"sequenceIndex":665},{"id":"plato-the-repu-205","text":"The eighth book of the Republic abounds in pictures of life and\r fanciful allusions; the use of metaphorical language is carried to a\r greater extent than anywhere else in Plato. We may remark,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"205"},"sequenceIndex":666},{"id":"plato-the-repu-206","text":"(1), the description of the two nations in one, which become more and\r more divided in the Greek Republics, as in feudal times, and perhaps\r also in our own;","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"206"},"sequenceIndex":667},{"id":"plato-the-repu-207","text":"(2), the notion of democracy expressed in a sort of Pythagorean formula\r as equality among unequals;","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"207"},"sequenceIndex":668},{"id":"plato-the-repu-208","text":"(3), the free and easy ways of men and animals, which are\r characteristic of liberty, as foreign mercenaries and universal\r mistrust are of the tyrant;","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"208"},"sequenceIndex":669},{"id":"plato-the-repu-209","text":"(4), the proposal that mere debts should not be recoverable by law is a\r speculation which has often been entertained by reformers of the law in\r modern times, and is in harmony with the tendencies of modern\r legislation. Debt and land were the two great difficulties of the\r ancient lawgiver: in modern times we may be said to have almost, if not\r quite, solved the first of these difficulties, but hardly the second.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"209"},"sequenceIndex":670},{"id":"plato-the-repu-210","text":"Still more remarkable are the corresponding portraits of individuals:\r there is the family picture of the father and mother and the old\r servant of the timocratical man, and the outward respectability and\r inherent meanness of the oligarchical; the uncontrolled licence and\r freedom of the democrat, in which the young Alcibiades seems to be\r depicted, doing right or wrong as he pleases, and who at last, like the\r prodigal, goes into a far country (note here the play of language by\r which the democratic man is himself represented under the image of a\r State having a citadel and receiving embassi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"210"},"sequenceIndex":671},{"id":"plato-the-repu-211","text":"There remains to be considered the great difficulty of this book of the\r Republic, the so-called number of the State. This is a puzzle almost as\r great as the Number of the Beast in the Book of Revelation, and though\r apparently known to Aristotle, is referred to by Cicero as a proverb of\r obscurity (Ep. ad Att.). And some have imagined that there is no answer\r to the puzzle, and that Plato has been practising upon his readers. But\r such a deception as this is inconsistent with the manner in which\r Aristotle speaks of the number (Pol.), and would have been ridiculous\r to any reader of the Repu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"211"},"sequenceIndex":672},{"id":"plato-the-repu-212","text":"Our hope of understanding the passage depends principally on an\r accurate study of the words themselves; on which a faint light is\r thrown by the parallel passage in the ninth book. Another help is the\r allusion in Aristotle, who makes the important remark that the latter\r part of the passage (Greek) describes a solid figure. (Pol.—‘He only\r says that nothing is abiding, but that all things change in a certain\r cycle; and that the origin of the change is a base of numbers which are\r in the ratio of 4:3; and this when combined with a figure of five gives\r two harmonies; he means when the number","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"212"},"sequenceIndex":673},{"id":"plato-the-repu-213","text":"Plato begins by speaking of a perfect or cyclical number (Tim.), i.e. a\r number in which the sum of the divisors equals the whole; this is the\r divine or perfect number in which all lesser cycles or revolutions are\r complete. He also speaks of a human or imperfect number, having four\r terms and three intervals of numbers which are related to one another\r in certain proportions; these he converts into figures, and finds in\r them when they have been raised to the third power certain elements of\r number, which give two ‘harmonies,’ the one square, the other oblong;\r but he does not say that the s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"213"},"sequenceIndex":674},{"id":"plato-the-repu-214","text":"The explanation given in the text supposes the two harmonies to make up\r the number 8000. This explanation derives a certain plausibility from\r the circumstance that 8000 is the ancient number of the Spartan\r citizens (Herod.), and would be what Plato might have called ‘a number\r which nearly concerns the population of a city’; the mysterious\r disappearance of the Spartan population may possibly have suggested to\r him the first cause of his decline of States. The lesser or square\r ‘harmony,’ of 400, might be a symbol of the guardians,—the larger or\r oblong ‘harmony,’ of the people, and the num","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"214"},"sequenceIndex":675},{"id":"plato-the-repu-215","text":"The terms used in the statement of the problem may be explained as\r follows. A perfect number (Greek), as already stated, is one which is\r equal to the sum of its divisors. Thus 6, which is the first perfect or\r cyclical number, = 1 + 2 + 3. The words (Greek), ‘terms’ or ‘notes,’\r and (Greek), ‘intervals,’ are applicable to music as well as to number\r and figure. (Greek) is the ‘base’ on which the whole calculation\r depends, or the ‘lowest term’ from which it can be worked out. The\r words (Greek) have been variously translated—‘squared and cubed’\r (Donaldson), ‘equalling and equalled in power’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"215"},"sequenceIndex":676},{"id":"plato-the-repu-216","text":"The conclusions which he draws from these data are summed up by him as\r follows. Having assumed that the number of the perfect or divine cycle\r is the number of the world, and the number of the imperfect cycle the\r number of the state, he proceeds: ‘The period of the world is defined\r by the perfect number 6, that of the state by the cube of that number\r or 216, which is the product of the last pair of terms in the Platonic\r Tetractys (a series of seven terms, 1, 2, 3, 4, 9, 8, 27); and if we\r take this as the basis of our computation, we shall have two cube\r numbers (Greek), viz. 8 and 27; an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"216"},"sequenceIndex":677},{"id":"plato-the-repu-217","text":"The reasons which have inclined me to agree with Dr. Donaldson and also\r with Schleiermacher in supposing that 216 is the Platonic number of\r births are: (1) that it coincides with the description of the number\r given in the first part of the passage (Greek...): (2) that the number\r 216 with its permutations would have been familiar to a Greek\r mathematician, though unfamiliar to us: (3) that 216 is the cube of 6,\r and also the sum of 3 cubed, 4 cubed, 5 cubed, the numbers 3, 4, 5\r representing the Pythagorean triangle, of which the sides when squared\r equal the square of the hypotenuse (9 + 1","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"217"},"sequenceIndex":678},{"id":"plato-the-repu-218","text":"But though agreeing with Dr. Donaldson thus far, I see no reason for\r supposing, as he does, that the first or perfect number is the world,\r the human or imperfect number the state; nor has he given any proof\r that the second harmony is a cube. Nor do I think that (Greek) can mean\r ‘two incommensurables,’ which he arbitrarily assumes to be 2 and 3, but\r rather, as the preceding clause implies, (Greek), i.e. two square\r numbers based upon irrational diameters of a figure the side of which\r is 5 = 50 x 2.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"218"},"sequenceIndex":679},{"id":"plato-the-repu-219","text":"The greatest objection to the translation is the sense given to the\r words (Greek), ‘a base of three with a third added to it, multiplied by\r 5.’ In this somewhat forced manner Plato introduces once more the\r numbers of the Pythagorean triangle. But the coincidences in the\r numbers which follow are in favour of the explanation. The first\r harmony of 400, as has been already remarked, probably represents the\r rulers; the second and oblong harmony of 7600, the people.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"219"},"sequenceIndex":680},{"id":"plato-the-repu-220","text":"And here we take leave of the difficulty. The discovery of the riddle\r would be useless, and would throw no light on ancient mathematics. The\r point of interest is that Plato should have used such a symbol, and\r that so much of the Pythagorean spirit should have prevailed in him.\r His general meaning is that divine creation is perfect, and is\r represented or presided over by a perfect or cyclical number; human\r generation is imperfect, and represented or presided over by an\r imperfect number or series of numbers. The number 5040, which is the\r number of the citizens in the Laws, is expressly b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"220"},"sequenceIndex":681},{"id":"plato-the-repu-221","text":"To return:—You remember what was said of the democrat; that he was the\r son of a miserly father, who encouraged the saving desires and\r repressed the ornamental and expensive ones; presently the youth got\r into fine company, and began to entertain a dislike to his father’s\r narrow ways; and being a better man than the corrupters of his youth,\r he came to a mean, and led a life, not of lawless or slavish passion,\r but of regular and successive indulgence. Now imagine that the youth\r has become a father, and has a son who is exposed to the same\r temptations, and has companions who lead him into ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"221"},"sequenceIndex":682},{"id":"plato-the-repu-222","text":"And how does such an one live? ‘Nay, that you must tell me.’ Well then,\r I fancy that he will live amid revelries and harlotries, and love will\r be the lord and master of the house. Many desires require much money,\r and so he spends all that he has and borrows more; and when he has\r nothing the young ravens are still in the nest in which they were\r hatched, crying for food. Love urges them on; and they must be\r gratified by force or fraud, or if not, they become painful and\r troublesome; and as the new pleasures succeed the old ones, so will the\r son take possession of the goods of his parents","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"222"},"sequenceIndex":683},{"id":"plato-the-repu-223","text":"Like man, like State,—the tyrannical man will answer to tyranny, which\r is the extreme opposite of the royal State; for one is the best and the\r other the worst. But which is the happier? Great and terrible as the\r tyrant may appear enthroned amid his satellites, let us not be afraid\r to go in and ask; and the answer is, that the monarchical is the\r happiest, and the tyrannical the most miserable of States. And may we\r not ask the same question about the men themselves, requesting some one\r to look into them who is able to penetrate the inner nature of man, and\r will not be panic-struck by the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"223"},"sequenceIndex":684},{"id":"plato-the-repu-224","text":"Assuming that we ourselves are the impartial judge for whom we seek,\r let us begin by comparing the individual and State, and ask first of\r all, whether the State is likely to be free or enslaved—Will there not\r be a little freedom and a great deal of slavery? And the freedom is of\r the bad, and the slavery of the good; and this applies to the man as\r well as to the State; for his soul is full of meanness and slavery, and\r the better part is enslaved to the worse. He cannot do what he would,\r and his mind is full of confusion; he is the very reverse of a freeman.\r The State will be poor and fu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"224"},"sequenceIndex":685},{"id":"plato-the-repu-225","text":"Having so many evils, will not the most miserable of men be still more\r miserable in a public station? Master of others when he is not master\r of himself; like a sick man who is compelled to be an athlete; the\r meanest of slaves and the most abject of flatterers; wanting all\r things, and never able to satisfy his desires; always in fear and\r distraction, like the State of which he is the representative. His\r jealous, hateful, faithless temper grows worse with command; he is more\r and more faithless, envious, unrighteous,—the most wretched of men, a\r misery to himself and to others. And so let ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"225"},"sequenceIndex":686},{"id":"plato-the-repu-226","text":"This is our first proof. The second is derived from the three kinds of\r pleasure, which answer to the three elements of the soul—reason,\r passion, desire; under which last is comprehended avarice as well as\r sensual appetite, while passion includes ambition, party-feeling, love\r of reputation. Reason, again, is solely directed to the attainment of\r truth, and careless of money and reputation. In accordance with the\r difference of men’s natures, one of these three principles is in the\r ascendant, and they have their several pleasures corresponding to them.\r Interrogate now the three natures, an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"226"},"sequenceIndex":687},{"id":"plato-the-repu-227","text":"Twice has the just man overthrown the unjust—once more, as in an\r Olympian contest, first offering up a prayer to the saviour Zeus, let\r him try a fall. A wise man whispers to me that the pleasures of the\r wise are true and pure; all others are a shadow only. Let us examine\r this: Is not pleasure opposed to pain, and is there not a mean state\r which is neither? When a man is sick, nothing is more pleasant to him\r than health. But this he never found out while he was well. In pain he\r desires only to cease from pain; on the other hand, when he is in an\r ecstasy of pleasure, rest is painful to h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"227"},"sequenceIndex":688},{"id":"plato-the-repu-228","text":"The same may be said of the passionate element:—the desires of the\r ambitious soul, as well as of the covetous, have an inferior\r satisfaction. Only when under the guidance of reason do either of the\r other principles do their own business or attain the pleasure which is\r natural to them. When not attaining, they compel the other parts of the\r soul to pursue a shadow of pleasure which is not theirs. And the more\r distant they are from philosophy and reason, the more distant they will\r be from law and order, and the more illusive will be their pleasures.\r The desires of love and tyranny are the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"228"},"sequenceIndex":689},{"id":"plato-the-repu-229","text":"Perhaps you may remember some one saying at the beginning of our\r discussion that the unjust man was profited if he had the reputation of\r justice. Now that we know the nature of justice and injustice, let us\r make an image of the soul, which will personify his words. First of\r all, fashion a multitudinous beast, having a ring of heads of all\r manner of animals, tame and wild, and able to produce and change them\r at pleasure. Suppose now another form of a lion, and another of a man;\r the second smaller than the first, the third than the second; join them\r together and cover them with a human s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"229"},"sequenceIndex":690},{"id":"plato-the-repu-230","text":"But now, let us reason with the unjust, who is not intentionally in\r error. Is not the noble that which subjects the beast to the man, or\r rather to the God in man; the ignoble, that which subjects the man to\r the beast? And if so, who would receive gold on condition that he was\r to degrade the noblest part of himself under the worst?—who would sell\r his son or daughter into the hands of brutal and evil men, for any\r amount of money? And will he sell his own fairer and diviner part\r without any compunction to the most godless and foul? Would he not be\r worse than Eriphyle, who sold her husband","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"230"},"sequenceIndex":691},{"id":"plato-the-repu-231","text":"‘What, then, shall a man profit, if he gain the whole world’ and become\r more and more wicked? Or what shall he profit by escaping discovery, if\r the concealment of evil prevents the cure? If he had been punished, the\r brute within him would have been silenced, and the gentler element\r liberated; and he would have united temperance, justice, and wisdom in\r his soul—a union better far than any combination of bodily gifts. The\r man of understanding will honour knowledge above all; in the next place\r he will keep under his body, not only for the sake of health and\r strength, but in order to attai","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"231"},"sequenceIndex":692},{"id":"plato-the-repu-232","text":"The most noticeable points in the 9th Book of the Republic are:—(1) the\r account of pleasure; (2) the number of the interval which divides the\r king from the tyrant; (3) the pattern which is in heaven.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"232"},"sequenceIndex":693},{"id":"plato-the-repu-233","text":"1. Plato’s account of pleasure is remarkable for moderation, and in\r this respect contrasts with the later Platonists and the views which\r are attributed to them by Aristotle. He is not, like the Cynics,\r opposed to all pleasure, but rather desires that the several parts of\r the soul shall have their natural satisfaction; he even agrees with the\r Epicureans in describing pleasure as something more than the absence of\r pain. This is proved by the circumstance that there are pleasures which\r have no antecedent pains (as he also remarks in the Philebus), such as\r the pleasures of smell, and also ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"233"},"sequenceIndex":694},{"id":"plato-the-repu-234","text":"2. The number of the interval which separates the king from the tyrant,\r and royal from tyrannical pleasures, is 729, the cube of 9. Which Plato\r characteristically designates as a number concerned with human life,\r because NEARLY equivalent to the number of days and nights in the year.\r He is desirous of proclaiming that the interval between them is\r immeasurable, and invents a formula to give expression to his idea.\r Those who spoke of justice as a cube, of virtue as an art of measuring\r (Prot.), saw no inappropriateness in conceiving the soul under the\r figure of a line, or the pleasure of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"234"},"sequenceIndex":695},{"id":"plato-the-repu-235","text":"The simple observation that the comparison of two similar solids is\r effected by the comparison of the cubes of their sides, is the\r mathematical groundwork of this fanciful expression. There is some\r difficulty in explaining the steps by which the number 729 is obtained;\r the oligarch is removed in the third degree from the royal and\r aristocratical, and the tyrant in the third degree from the\r oligarchical; but we have to arrange the terms as the sides of a square\r and to count the oligarch twice over, thus reckoning them not as = 5\r but as = 9. The square of 9 is passed lightly over as only","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"235"},"sequenceIndex":696},{"id":"plato-the-repu-236","text":"3. Towards the close of the Republic, Plato seems to be more and more\r convinced of the ideal character of his own speculations. At the end of\r the 9th Book the pattern which is in heaven takes the place of the city\r of philosophers on earth. The vision which has received form and\r substance at his hands, is now discovered to be at a distance. And yet\r this distant kingdom is also the rule of man’s life. (‘Say not lo!\r here, or lo! there, for the kingdom of God is within you.’) Thus a note\r is struck which prepares for the revelation of a future life in the\r following Book. But the future life","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"236"},"sequenceIndex":697},{"id":"plato-the-repu-237","text":"Let us now interrogate Homer and the poets. Friend Homer, say I to him,\r I am not going to ask you about medicine, or any art to which your\r poems incidentally refer, but about their main subjects—war, military\r tactics, politics. If you are only twice and not thrice removed from\r the truth—not an imitator or an image-maker, please to inform us what\r good you have ever done to mankind? Is there any city which professes\r to have received laws from you, as Sicily and Italy have from\r Charondas, Sparta from Lycurgus, Athens from Solon? Or was any war ever\r carried on by your counsels? or is any i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"237"},"sequenceIndex":698},{"id":"plato-the-repu-238","text":"And now let us enquire, what is the faculty in man which answers to\r imitation. Allow me to explain my meaning: Objects are differently seen\r when in the water and when out of the water, when near and when at a\r distance; and the painter or juggler makes use of this variation to\r impose upon us. And the art of measuring and weighing and calculating\r comes in to save our bewildered minds from the power of appearance;\r for, as we were saying, two contrary opinions of the same about the\r same and at the same time, cannot both of them be true. But which of\r them is true is determined by the art of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"238"},"sequenceIndex":699},{"id":"plato-the-repu-239","text":"But we have not yet mentioned the heaviest count in the indictment—the\r power which poetry has of injuriously exciting the feelings. When we\r hear some passage in which a hero laments his sufferings at tedious\r length, you know that we sympathize with him and praise the poet; and\r yet in our own sorrows such an exhibition of feeling is regarded as\r effeminate and unmanly (Ion). Now, ought a man to feel pleasure in\r seeing another do what he hates and abominates in himself? Is he not\r giving way to a sentiment which in his own case he would control?—he is\r off his guard because the sorrow is an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"239"},"sequenceIndex":700},{"id":"plato-the-repu-240","text":"These are our grounds for expelling poetry; but lest she should charge\r us with discourtesy, let us also make an apology to her. We will remind\r her that there is an ancient quarrel between poetry and philosophy, of\r which there are many traces in the writings of the poets, such as the\r saying of ‘the she-dog, yelping at her mistress,’ and ‘the philosophers\r who are ready to circumvent Zeus,’ and ‘the philosophers who are\r paupers.’ Nevertheless we bear her no ill-will, and will gladly allow\r her to return upon condition that she makes a defence of herself in\r verse; and her supporters who are","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"240"},"sequenceIndex":701},{"id":"plato-the-repu-241","text":"And yet the rewards of virtue are greater far than I have described.\r ‘And can we conceive things greater still?’ Not, perhaps, in this brief\r span of life: but should an immortal being care about anything short of\r eternity? ‘I do not understand what you mean?’ Do you not know that the\r soul is immortal? ‘Surely you are not prepared to prove that?’ Indeed I\r am. ‘Then let me hear this argument, of which you make so light.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"241"},"sequenceIndex":702},{"id":"plato-the-repu-242","text":"You would admit that everything has an element of good and of evil. In\r all things there is an inherent corruption; and if this cannot destroy\r them, nothing else will. The soul too has her own corrupting\r principles, which are injustice, intemperance, cowardice, and the like.\r But none of these destroy the soul in the same sense that disease\r destroys the body. The soul may be full of all iniquities, but is not,\r by reason of them, brought any nearer to death. Nothing which was not\r destroyed from within ever perished by external affection of evil. The\r body, which is one thing, cannot be des","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"242"},"sequenceIndex":703},{"id":"plato-the-repu-243","text":"Thus far, as the argument required, we have said nothing of the rewards\r and honours which the poets attribute to justice; we have contented\r ourselves with showing that justice in herself is best for the soul in\r herself, even if a man should put on a Gyges’ ring and have the helmet\r of Hades too. And now you shall repay me what you borrowed; and I will\r enumerate the rewards of justice in life and after death. I granted,\r for the sake of argument, as you will remember, that evil might perhaps\r escape the knowledge of Gods and men, although this was really\r impossible. And since I have shown ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"243"},"sequenceIndex":704},{"id":"plato-the-repu-244","text":"But all the blessings of this present life are as nothing when compared\r with those which await good men after death. ‘I should like to hear\r about them.’ Come, then, and I will tell you the story of Er, the son\r of Armenius, a valiant man. He was supposed to have died in battle, but\r ten days afterwards his body was found untouched by corruption and sent\r home for burial. On the twelfth day he was placed on the funeral pyre\r and there he came to life again, and told what he had seen in the world\r below. He said that his soul went with a great company to a place, in\r which there were two chasm","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"244"},"sequenceIndex":705},{"id":"plato-the-repu-245","text":"On the eighth day the souls of the pilgrims resumed their journey, and\r in four days came to a spot whence they looked down upon a line of\r light, in colour like a rainbow, only brighter and clearer. One day\r more brought them to the place, and they saw that this was the column\r of light which binds together the whole universe. The ends of the\r column were fastened to heaven, and from them hung the distaff of\r Necessity, on which all the heavenly bodies turned—the hook and spindle\r were of adamant, and the whorl of a mixed substance. The whorl was in\r form like a number of boxes fitting into o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"245"},"sequenceIndex":706},{"id":"plato-the-repu-246","text":"When all the souls had chosen they went to Lachesis, who sent with each\r of them their genius or attendant to fulfil their lot. He first of all\r brought them under the hand of Clotho, and drew them within the\r revolution of the spindle impelled by her hand; from her they were\r carried to Atropos, who made the threads irreversible; whence, without\r turning round, they passed beneath the throne of Necessity; and when\r they had all passed, they moved on in scorching heat to the plain of\r Forgetfulness and rested at evening by the river Unmindful, whose water\r could not be retained in any vessel; ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"246"},"sequenceIndex":707},{"id":"plato-the-repu-247","text":"Thus, Glaucon, the tale has been saved, and will be our salvation, if\r we believe that the soul is immortal, and hold fast to the heavenly way\r of Justice and Knowledge. So shall we pass undefiled over the river of\r Forgetfulness, and be dear to ourselves and to the Gods, and have a\r crown of reward and happiness both in this world and also in the\r millennial pilgrimage of the other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"247"},"sequenceIndex":708},{"id":"plato-the-repu-248","text":"The Tenth Book of the Republic of Plato falls into two divisions:\r first, resuming an old thread which has been interrupted, Socrates\r assails the poets, who, now that the nature of the soul has been\r analyzed, are seen to be very far gone from the truth; and secondly,\r having shown the reality of the happiness of the just, he demands that\r appearance shall be restored to him, and then proceeds to prove the\r immortality of the soul. The argument, as in the Phaedo and Gorgias, is\r supplemented by the vision of a future life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"248"},"sequenceIndex":709},{"id":"plato-the-repu-249","text":"Why Plato, who was himself a poet, and whose dialogues are poems and\r dramas, should have been hostile to the poets as a class, and\r especially to the dramatic poets; why he should not have seen that\r truth may be embodied in verse as well as in prose, and that there are\r some indefinable lights and shadows of human life which can only be\r expressed in poetry—some elements of imagination which always entwine\r with reason; why he should have supposed epic verse to be inseparably\r associated with the impurities of the old Hellenic mythology; why he\r should try Homer and Hesiod by the unfair and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"249"},"sequenceIndex":710},{"id":"plato-the-repu-250","text":"He is the enemy of the poets because poetry was declining in his own\r lifetime, and a theatrocracy, as he says in the Laws, had taken the\r place of an intellectual aristocracy. Euripides exhibited the last\r phase of the tragic drama, and in him Plato saw the friend and\r apologist of tyrants, and the Sophist of tragedy. The old comedy was\r almost extinct; the new had not yet arisen. Dramatic and lyric poetry,\r like every other branch of Greek literature, was falling under the\r power of rhetoric. There was no ‘second or third’ to Aeschylus and\r Sophocles in the generation which followed them. Ar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"250"},"sequenceIndex":711},{"id":"plato-the-repu-251","text":"There were other reasons for the antagonism of Plato to poetry. The\r profession of an actor was regarded by him as a degradation of human\r nature, for ‘one man in his life’ cannot ‘play many parts;’ the\r characters which the actor performs seem to destroy his own character,\r and to leave nothing which can be truly called himself. Neither can any\r man live his life and act it. The actor is the slave of his art, not\r the master of it. Taking this view Plato is more decided in his\r expulsion of the dramatic than of the epic poets, though he must have\r known that the Greek tragedians afforded nobl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"251"},"sequenceIndex":712},{"id":"plato-the-repu-252","text":"In the Tenth Book Plato introduces a new series of objections. First,\r he says that the poet or painter is an imitator, and in the third\r degree removed from the truth. His creations are not tested by rule and\r measure; they are only appearances. In modern times we should say that\r art is not merely imitation, but rather the expression of the ideal in\r forms of sense. Even adopting the humble image of Plato, from which his\r argument derives a colour, we should maintain that the artist may\r ennoble the bed which he paints by the folds of the drapery, or by the\r feeling of home which he introduc","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"252"},"sequenceIndex":713},{"id":"plato-the-repu-253","text":"Again, Plato objects to the imitative arts that they express the\r emotional rather than the rational part of human nature. He does not\r admit Aristotle’s theory, that tragedy or other serious imitations are\r a purgation of the passions by pity and fear; to him they appear only\r to afford the opportunity of indulging them. Yet we must acknowledge\r that we may sometimes cure disordered emotions by giving expression to\r them; and that they often gain strength when pent up within our own\r breast. It is not every indulgence of the feelings which is to be\r condemned. For there may be a gratification","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"253"},"sequenceIndex":714},{"id":"plato-the-repu-254","text":"He tells us that he rejoices in the banishment of the poets, since he\r has found by the analysis of the soul that they are concerned with the\r inferior faculties. He means to say that the higher faculties have to\r do with universals, the lower with particulars of sense. The poets are\r on a level with their own age, but not on a level with Socrates and\r Plato; and he was well aware that Homer and Hesiod could not be made a\r rule of life by any process of legitimate interpretation; his ironical\r use of them is in fact a denial of their authority; he saw, too, that\r the poets were not critics—as ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"254"},"sequenceIndex":715},{"id":"plato-the-repu-255","text":"The things which are seen are opposed in Scripture to the things which\r are unseen—they are equally opposed in Plato to universals and ideas.\r To him all particulars appear to be floating about in a world of sense;\r they have a taint of error or even of evil. There is no difficulty in\r seeing that this is an illusion; for there is no more error or\r variation in an individual man, horse, bed, etc., than in the class\r man, horse, bed, etc.; nor is the truth which is displayed in\r individual instances less certain than that which is conveyed through\r the medium of ideas. But Plato, who is deeply ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"255"},"sequenceIndex":716},{"id":"plato-the-repu-256","text":"But the poets are also the representatives of falsehood and feigning in\r all departments of life and knowledge, like the sophists and\r rhetoricians of the Gorgias and Phaedrus; they are the false priests,\r false prophets, lying spirits, enchanters of the world. There is\r another count put into the indictment against them by Plato, that they\r are the friends of the tyrant, and bask in the sunshine of his\r patronage. Despotism in all ages has had an apparatus of false ideas\r and false teachers at its service—in the history of Modern Europe as\r well as of Greece and Rome. For no government of men","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"256"},"sequenceIndex":717},{"id":"plato-the-repu-257","text":"A further objection which Plato makes to poetry and the imitative arts\r is that they excite the emotions. Here the modern reader will be\r disposed to introduce a distinction which appears to have escaped him.\r For the emotions are neither bad nor good in themselves, and are not\r most likely to be controlled by the attempt to eradicate them, but by\r the moderate indulgence of them. And the vocation of art is to present\r thought in the form of feeling, to enlist the feelings on the side of\r reason, to inspire even for a moment courage or resignation; perhaps to\r suggest a sense of infinity and e","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"257"},"sequenceIndex":718},{"id":"plato-the-repu-258","text":"In the present stage of the human mind, poetry and other forms of\r fiction may certainly be regarded as a good. But we can also imagine\r the existence of an age in which a severer conception of truth has\r either banished or transformed them. At any rate we must admit that\r they hold a different place at different periods of the world’s\r history. In the infancy of mankind, poetry, with the exception of\r proverbs, is the whole of literature, and the only instrument of\r intellectual culture; in modern times she is the shadow or echo of her\r former self, and appears to have a precarious existence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"258"},"sequenceIndex":719},{"id":"plato-the-repu-259","text":"Art cannot claim to be on a level with philosophy or religion, and may\r often corrupt them. It is possible to conceive a mental state in which\r all artistic representations are regarded as a false and imperfect\r expression, either of the religious ideal or of the philosophical\r ideal. The fairest forms may be revolting in certain moods of mind, as\r is proved by the fact that the Mahometans, and many sects of\r Christians, have renounced the use of pictures and images. The\r beginning of a great religion, whether Christian or Gentile, has not\r been ‘wood or stone,’ but a spirit moving in the hear","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"259"},"sequenceIndex":720},{"id":"plato-the-repu-260","text":"But poetry and art may also be the expression of the highest truth and\r the purest sentiment. Plato himself seems to waver between two opposite\r views—when, as in the third Book, he insists that youth should be\r brought up amid wholesome imagery; and again in Book X, when he\r banishes the poets from his Republic. Admitting that the arts, which\r some of us almost deify, have fallen short of their higher aim, we must\r admit on the other hand that to banish imagination wholly would be\r suicidal as well as impossible. For nature too is a form of art; and a\r breath of the fresh air or a single glan","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"260"},"sequenceIndex":721},{"id":"plato-the-repu-261","text":"Plato does not seriously intend to expel poets from life and society.\r But he feels strongly the unreality of their writings; he is protesting\r against the degeneracy of poetry in his own day as we might protest\r against the want of serious purpose in modern fiction, against the\r unseemliness or extravagance of some of our poets or novelists, against\r the time-serving of preachers or public writers, against the\r regardlessness of truth which to the eye of the philosopher seems to\r characterize the greater part of the world. For we too have reason to\r complain that our poets and novelists ‘pain","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"261"},"sequenceIndex":722},{"id":"plato-the-repu-262","text":"For there might be a poetry which would be the hymn of divine\r perfection, the harmony of goodness and truth among men: a strain which\r should renew the youth of the world, and bring back the ages in which\r the poet was man’s only teacher and best friend,—which would find\r materials in the living present as well as in the romance of the past,\r and might subdue to the fairest forms of speech and verse the\r intractable materials of modern civilisation,—which might elicit the\r simple principles, or, as Plato would have called them, the essential\r forms, of truth and justice out of the variety of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"262"},"sequenceIndex":723},{"id":"plato-the-repu-263","text":"Returning to Plato, we may observe that a similar mixture of truth and\r error appears in other parts of the argument. He is aware of the\r absurdity of mankind framing their whole lives according to Homer; just\r as in the Phaedrus he intimates the absurdity of interpreting mythology\r upon rational principles; both these were the modern tendencies of his\r own age, which he deservedly ridicules. On the other hand, his argument\r that Homer, if he had been able to teach mankind anything worth\r knowing, would not have been allowed by them to go about begging as a\r rhapsodist, is both false and contr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"263"},"sequenceIndex":724},{"id":"plato-the-repu-264","text":"The argument for immortality seems to rest on the absolute dualism of\r soul and body. Admitting the existence of the soul, we know of no force\r which is able to put an end to her. Vice is her own proper evil; and if\r she cannot be destroyed by that, she cannot be destroyed by any other.\r Yet Plato has acknowledged that the soul may be so overgrown by the\r incrustations of earth as to lose her original form; and in the Timaeus\r he recognizes more strongly than in the Republic the influence which\r the body has over the mind, denying even the voluntariness of human\r actions, on the ground that th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"264"},"sequenceIndex":725},{"id":"plato-the-repu-265","text":"The vision of another world is ascribed to Er, the son of Armenius, who\r is said by Clement of Alexandria to have been Zoroaster. The tale has\r certainly an oriental character, and may be compared with the\r pilgrimages of the soul in the Zend Avesta (Haug, Avesta). But no trace\r of acquaintance with Zoroaster is found elsewhere in Plato’s writings,\r and there is no reason for giving him the name of Er the Pamphylian.\r The philosophy of Heracleitus cannot be shown to be borrowed from\r Zoroaster, and still less the myths of Plato.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"265"},"sequenceIndex":726},{"id":"plato-the-repu-266","text":"The local arrangement of the vision is less distinct than that of the\r Phaedrus and Phaedo. Astronomy is mingled with symbolism and mythology;\r the great sphere of heaven is represented under the symbol of a\r cylinder or box, containing the seven orbits of the planets and the\r fixed stars; this is suspended from an axis or spindle which turns on\r the knees of Necessity; the revolutions of the seven orbits contained\r in the cylinder are guided by the fates, and their harmonious motion\r produces the music of the spheres. Through the innermost or eighth of\r these, which is the moon, is passed the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"266"},"sequenceIndex":727},{"id":"plato-the-repu-267","text":"The orrery or picture of the heavens given in the Republic differs in\r its mode of representation from the circles of the same and of the\r other in the Timaeus. In both the fixed stars are distinguished from\r the planets, and they move in orbits without them, although in an\r opposite direction: in the Republic as in the Timaeus they are all\r moving round the axis of the world. But we are not certain that in the\r former they are moving round the earth. No distinct mention is made in\r the Republic of the circles of the same and other; although both in the\r Timaeus and in the Republic the motion ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"267"},"sequenceIndex":728},{"id":"plato-the-repu-268","text":"The description of the axis as a spindle, and of the heavenly bodies as\r forming a whole, partly arises out of the attempt to connect the\r motions of the heavenly bodies with the mythological image of the web,\r or weaving of the Fates. The giving of the lots, the weaving of them,\r and the making of them irreversible, which are ascribed to the three\r Fates—Lachesis, Clotho, Atropos, are obviously derived from their\r names. The element of chance in human life is indicated by the order of\r the lots. But chance, however adverse, may be overcome by the wisdom of\r man, if he knows how to choose arig","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"268"},"sequenceIndex":729},{"id":"plato-the-repu-269","text":"The freedom of the will to refuse the evil and to choose the good is\r distinctly asserted. ‘Virtue is free, and as a man honours or\r dishonours her he will have more or less of her.’ The life of man is\r ‘rounded’ by necessity; there are circumstances prior to birth which\r affect him (Pol.). But within the walls of necessity there is an open\r space in which he is his own master, and can study for himself the\r effects which the variously compounded gifts of nature or fortune have\r upon the soul, and act accordingly. All men cannot have the first\r choice in everything. But the lot of all men is g","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"269"},"sequenceIndex":730},{"id":"plato-the-repu-270","text":"The verisimilitude which is given to the pilgrimage of a thousand\r years, by the intimation that Ardiaeus had lived a thousand years\r before; the coincidence of Er coming to life on the twelfth day after\r he was supposed to have been dead with the seven days which the\r pilgrims passed in the meadow, and the four days during which they\r journeyed to the column of light; the precision with which the soul is\r mentioned who chose the twentieth lot; the passing remarks that there\r was no definite character among the souls, and that the souls which had\r chosen ill blamed any one rather than themselv","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"270"},"sequenceIndex":731},{"id":"plato-the-repu-271","text":"There still remain to be considered some points which have been\r intentionally reserved to the end: (1) the Janus-like character of the\r Republic, which presents two faces—one an Hellenic state, the other a\r kingdom of philosophers. Connected with the latter of the two aspects\r are (2) the paradoxes of the Republic, as they have been termed by\r Morgenstern: (a) the community of property; (b) of families; (c) the\r rule of philosophers; (d) the analogy of the individual and the State,\r which, like some other analogies in the Republic, is carried too far.\r We may then proceed to consider (3) the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"271"},"sequenceIndex":732},{"id":"plato-the-repu-272","text":"1. Plato expressly says that he is intending to found an Hellenic State\r (Book V). Many of his regulations are characteristically Spartan; such\r as the prohibition of gold and silver, the common meals of the men, the\r military training of the youth, the gymnastic exercises of the women.\r The life of Sparta was the life of a camp (Laws), enforced even more\r rigidly in time of peace than in war; the citizens of Sparta, like\r Plato’s, were forbidden to trade—they were to be soldiers and not\r shopkeepers. Nowhere else in Greece was the individual so completely\r subjected to the State; the time whe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"272"},"sequenceIndex":733},{"id":"plato-the-repu-273","text":"Many traditions were preserved at Sparta of the severity with which the\r magistrates had maintained the primitive rule of music and poetry; as\r in the Republic of Plato, the new-fangled poet was to be expelled.\r Hymns to the Gods, which are the only kind of music admitted into the\r ideal State, were the only kind which was permitted at Sparta. The\r Spartans, though an unpoetical race, were nevertheless lovers of\r poetry; they had been stirred by the Elegiac strains of Tyrtaeus, they\r had crowded around Hippias to hear his recitals of Homer; but in this\r they resembled the citizens of the timoc","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"273"},"sequenceIndex":734},{"id":"plato-the-repu-274","text":"To the Spartan type the ideal State reverts in the first decline; and\r the character of the individual timocrat is borrowed from the Spartan\r citizen. The love of Lacedaemon not only affected Plato and Xenophon,\r but was shared by many undistinguished Athenians; there they seemed to\r find a principle which was wanting in their own democracy. The (Greek)\r of the Spartans attracted them, that is to say, not the goodness of\r their laws, but the spirit of order and loyalty which prevailed.\r Fascinated by the idea, citizens of Athens would imitate the\r Lacedaemonians in their dress and manners; the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"274"},"sequenceIndex":735},{"id":"plato-the-repu-275","text":"But there are other features of the Platonic Republic, as, for example,\r the literary and philosophical education, and the grace and beauty of\r life, which are the reverse of Spartan. Plato wishes to give his\r citizens a taste of Athenian freedom as well as of Lacedaemonian\r discipline. His individual genius is purely Athenian, although in\r theory he is a lover of Sparta; and he is something more than either—he\r has also a true Hellenic feeling. He is desirous of humanizing the wars\r of Hellenes against one another; he acknowledges that the Delphian God\r is the grand hereditary interpreter of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"275"},"sequenceIndex":736},{"id":"plato-the-repu-276","text":"There is yet another thread which is interwoven in the texture of the\r work; for the Republic is not only a Dorian State, but a Pythagorean\r league. The ‘way of life’ which was connected with the name of\r Pythagoras, like the Catholic monastic orders, showed the power which\r the mind of an individual might exercise over his contemporaries, and\r may have naturally suggested to Plato the possibility of reviving such\r ‘mediaeval institutions.’ The Pythagoreans, like Plato, enforced a rule\r of life and a moral and intellectual training. The influence ascribed\r to music, which to us seems exaggerat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"276"},"sequenceIndex":737},{"id":"plato-the-repu-277","text":"But as in his philosophy, so also in the form of his State, he goes far\r beyond the old Pythagoreans. He attempts a task really impossible,\r which is to unite the past of Greek history with the future of\r philosophy, analogous to that other impossibility, which has often been\r the dream of Christendom, the attempt to unite the past history of\r Europe with the kingdom of Christ. Nothing actually existing in the\r world at all resembles Plato’s ideal State; nor does he himself imagine\r that such a State is possible. This he repeats again and again; e.g. in\r the Republic, or in the Laws where, cas","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"277"},"sequenceIndex":738},{"id":"plato-the-repu-278","text":"Niebuhr has asked a trifling question, which may be briefly noticed in\r this place—Was Plato a good citizen? If by this is meant, Was he loyal\r to Athenian institutions?—he can hardly be said to be the friend of\r democracy: but neither is he the friend of any other existing form of\r government; all of them he regarded as ‘states of faction’ (Laws); none\r attained to his ideal of a voluntary rule over voluntary subjects,\r which seems indeed more nearly to describe democracy than any other;\r and the worst of them is tyranny. The truth is, that the question has\r hardly any meaning when applied to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"278"},"sequenceIndex":739},{"id":"plato-the-repu-279","text":"2. The idea of the perfect State is full of paradox when judged of\r according to the ordinary notions of mankind. The paradoxes of one age\r have been said to become the commonplaces of the next; but the\r paradoxes of Plato are at least as paradoxical to us as they were to\r his contemporaries. The modern world has either sneered at them as\r absurd, or denounced them as unnatural and immoral; men have been\r pleased to find in Aristotle’s criticisms of them the anticipation of\r their own good sense. The wealthy and cultivated classes have disliked\r and also dreaded them; they have pointed with sa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"279"},"sequenceIndex":740},{"id":"plato-the-repu-280","text":"(a) The first paradox is the community of goods, which is mentioned\r slightly at the end of the third Book, and seemingly, as Aristotle\r observes, is confined to the guardians; at least no mention is made of\r the other classes. But the omission is not of any real significance,\r and probably arises out of the plan of the work, which prevents the\r writer from entering into details.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"280"},"sequenceIndex":741},{"id":"plato-the-repu-281","text":"Aristotle censures the community of property much in the spirit of\r modern political economy, as tending to repress industry, and as doing\r away with the spirit of benevolence. Modern writers almost refuse to\r consider the subject, which is supposed to have been long ago settled\r by the common opinion of mankind. But it must be remembered that the\r sacredness of property is a notion far more fixed in modern than in\r ancient times. The world has grown older, and is therefore more\r conservative. Primitive society offered many examples of land held in\r common, either by a tribe or by a township, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"281"},"sequenceIndex":742},{"id":"plato-the-repu-282","text":"We can hardly judge what effect Plato’s views would have upon his own\r contemporaries; they would perhaps have seemed to them only an\r exaggeration of the Spartan commonwealth. Even modern writers would\r acknowledge that the right of private property is based on expediency,\r and may be interfered with in a variety of ways for the public good.\r Any other mode of vesting property which was found to be more\r advantageous, would in time acquire the same basis of right; ‘the most\r useful,’ in Plato’s words, ‘would be the most sacred.’ The lawyers and\r ecclesiastics of former ages would have spoken ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"282"},"sequenceIndex":743},{"id":"plato-the-repu-283","text":"When we consider the question, without any fear of immediate\r application to practice, in the spirit of Plato’s Republic, are we\r quite sure that the received notions of property are the best? Is the\r distribution of wealth which is customary in civilized countries the\r most favourable that can be conceived for the education and development\r of the mass of mankind? Can ‘the spectator of all time and all\r existence’ be quite convinced that one or two thousand years hence,\r great changes will not have taken place in the rights of property, or\r even that the very notion of property, beyond what i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"283"},"sequenceIndex":744},{"id":"plato-the-repu-284","text":"Such reflections appear visionary to the eye of the practical\r statesman, but they are within the range of possibility to the\r philosopher. He can imagine that in some distant age or clime, and\r through the influence of some individual, the notion of common property\r may or might have sunk as deep into the heart of a race, and have\r become as fixed to them, as private property is to ourselves. He knows\r that this latter institution is not more than four or five thousand\r years old: may not the end revert to the beginning? In our own age even\r Utopias affect the spirit of legislation, and an ab","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"284"},"sequenceIndex":745},{"id":"plato-the-repu-285","text":"The objections that would be generally urged against Plato’s community\r of property, are the old ones of Aristotle, that motives for exertion\r would be taken away, and that disputes would arise when each was\r dependent upon all. Every man would produce as little and consume as\r much as he liked. The experience of civilized nations has hitherto been\r adverse to Socialism. The effort is too great for human nature; men try\r to live in common, but the personal feeling is always breaking in. On\r the other hand it may be doubted whether our present notions of\r property are not conventional, for they","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"285"},"sequenceIndex":746},{"id":"plato-the-repu-286","text":"Now that the world has once been set in motion, and is no longer held\r fast under the tyranny of custom and ignorance; now that criticism has\r pierced the veil of tradition and the past no longer overpowers the\r present,—the progress of civilization may be expected to be far greater\r and swifter than heretofore. Even at our present rate of speed the\r point at which we may arrive in two or three generations is beyond the\r power of imagination to foresee. There are forces in the world which\r work, not in an arithmetical, but in a geometrical ratio of increase.\r Education, to use the expression o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"286"},"sequenceIndex":747},{"id":"plato-the-repu-287","text":"(b) Neither to the mind of Plato nor of Aristotle did the doctrine of\r community of property present at all the same difficulty, or appear to\r be the same violation of the common Hellenic sentiment, as the\r community of wives and children. This paradox he prefaces by another\r proposal, that the occupations of men and women shall be the same, and\r that to this end they shall have a common training and education. Male\r and female animals have the same pursuits—why not also the two sexes of\r man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"287"},"sequenceIndex":748},{"id":"plato-the-repu-288","text":"But have we not here fallen into a contradiction? for we were saying\r that different natures should have different pursuits. How then can men\r and women have the same? And is not the proposal inconsistent with our\r notion of the division of labour?—These objections are no sooner raised\r than answered; for, according to Plato, there is no organic difference\r between men and women, but only the accidental one that men beget and\r women bear children. Following the analogy of the other animals, he\r contends that all natural gifts are scattered about indifferently among\r both sexes, though there ma","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"288"},"sequenceIndex":749},{"id":"plato-the-repu-289","text":"That Plato should have emancipated himself from the ideas of his own\r country and from the example of the East, shows a wonderful\r independence of mind. He is conscious that women are half the human\r race, in some respects the more important half (Laws); and for the sake\r both of men and women he desires to raise the woman to a higher level\r of existence. He brings, not sentiment, but philosophy to bear upon a\r question which both in ancient and modern times has been chiefly\r regarded in the light of custom or feeling. The Greeks had noble\r conceptions of womanhood in the goddesses Athene and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"289"},"sequenceIndex":750},{"id":"plato-the-repu-290","text":"The modern antagonist of the equality of the sexes would argue that the\r differences between men and women are not confined to the single point\r urged by Plato; that sensibility, gentleness, grace, are the qualities\r of women, while energy, strength, higher intelligence, are to be looked\r for in men. And the criticism is just: the differences affect the whole\r nature, and are not, as Plato supposes, confined to a single point. But\r neither can we say how far these differences are due to education and\r the opinions of mankind, or physically inherited from the habits and\r opinions of former gene","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"290"},"sequenceIndex":751},{"id":"plato-the-repu-291","text":"The first wave having been passed, we proceed to the second—community\r of wives and children. ‘Is it possible? Is it desirable?’ For as\r Glaucon intimates, and as we far more strongly insist, ‘Great doubts\r may be entertained about both these points.’ Any free discussion of the\r question is impossible, and mankind are perhaps right in not allowing\r the ultimate bases of social life to be examined. Few of us can safely\r enquire into the things which nature hides, any more than we can\r dissect our own bodies. Still, the manner in which Plato arrived at his\r conclusions should be considered. For ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"291"},"sequenceIndex":752},{"id":"plato-the-repu-292","text":"We start back horrified from this Platonic ideal, in the belief, first,\r that the higher feelings of humanity are far too strong to be crushed\r out; secondly, that if the plan could be carried into execution we\r should be poorly recompensed by improvements in the breed for the loss\r of the best things in life. The greatest regard for the weakest and\r meanest of human beings—the infant, the criminal, the insane, the\r idiot, truly seems to us one of the noblest results of Christianity. We\r have learned, though as yet imperfectly, that the individual man has an\r endless value in the sight of God,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"292"},"sequenceIndex":753},{"id":"plato-the-repu-293","text":"The great error in these and similar speculations is that the\r difference between man and the animals is forgotten in them. The human\r being is regarded with the eye of a dog- or bird-fancier, or at best of\r a slave-owner; the higher or human qualities are left out. The breeder\r of animals aims chiefly at size or speed or strength; in a few cases at\r courage or temper; most often the fitness of the animal for food is the\r great desideratum. But mankind are not bred to be eaten, nor yet for\r their superiority in fighting or in running or in drawing carts.\r Neither does the improvement of the hu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"293"},"sequenceIndex":754},{"id":"plato-the-repu-294","text":"An eminent physiologist thinks it worth while ‘to try and place life on\r a physical basis.’ But should not life rest on the moral rather than\r upon the physical? The higher comes first, then the lower, first the\r human and rational, afterwards the animal. Yet they are not absolutely\r divided; and in times of sickness or moments of self-indulgence they\r seem to be only different aspects of a common human nature which\r includes them both. Neither is the moral the limit of the physical, but\r the expansion and enlargement of it,—the highest form which the\r physical is capable of receiving. As Plat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"294"},"sequenceIndex":755},{"id":"plato-the-repu-295","text":"That the greatest of ancient philosophers should in his regulations\r about marriage have fallen into the error of separating body and mind,\r does indeed appear surprising. Yet the wonder is not so much that Plato\r should have entertained ideas of morality which to our own age are\r revolting, but that he should have contradicted himself to an extent\r which is hardly credible, falling in an instant from the heaven of\r idealism into the crudest animalism. Rejoicing in the newly found gift\r of reflection, he appears to have thought out a subject about which he\r had better have followed the enlight","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"295"},"sequenceIndex":756},{"id":"plato-the-repu-296","text":"Yet because the illusion is always returning (for the animal part of\r human nature will from time to time assert itself in the disguise of\r philosophy as well as of poetry), and also because any departure from\r established morality, even where this is not intended, is apt to be\r unsettling, it may be worth while to draw out a little more at length\r the objections to the Platonic marriage. In the first place, history\r shows that wherever polygamy has been largely allowed the race has\r deteriorated. One man to one woman is the law of God and nature. Nearly\r all the civilized peoples of the world","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"296"},"sequenceIndex":757},{"id":"plato-the-repu-297","text":"Recent enquirers have indeed arrived at the conclusion that among\r primitive tribes there existed a community of wives as of property, and\r that the captive taken by the spear was the only wife or slave whom any\r man was permitted to call his own. The partial existence of such\r customs among some of the lower races of man, and the survival of\r peculiar ceremonies in the marriages of some civilized nations, are\r thought to furnish a proof of similar institutions having been once\r universal. There can be no question that the study of anthropology has\r considerably changed our views respecting th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"297"},"sequenceIndex":758},{"id":"plato-the-repu-298","text":"Such speculations are apt to be unsettling, because they seem to show\r that an institution which was thought to be a revelation from heaven,\r is only the growth of history and experience. We ask what is the origin\r of marriage, and we are told that like the right of property, after\r many wars and contests, it has gradually arisen out of the selfishness\r of barbarians. We stand face to face with human nature in its primitive\r nakedness. We are compelled to accept, not the highest, but the lowest\r account of the origin of human society. But on the other hand we may\r truly say that every step in ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"298"},"sequenceIndex":759},{"id":"plato-the-repu-299","text":"To the doubts and queries raised by these ‘social reformers’ respecting\r the relation of the sexes and the moral nature of man, there is a\r sufficient answer, if any is needed. The difference about them and us\r is really one of fact. They are speaking of man as they wish or fancy\r him to be, but we are speaking of him as he is. They isolate the animal\r part of his nature; we regard him as a creature having many sides, or\r aspects, moving between good and evil, striving to rise above himself\r and to become ‘a little lower than the angels.’ We also, to use a\r Platonic formula, are not ignorant o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"299"},"sequenceIndex":760},{"id":"plato-the-repu-300","text":"For strength and health are not the only qualities to be desired; there\r are the more important considerations of mind and character and soul.\r We know how human nature may be degraded; we do not know how by\r artificial means any improvement in the breed can be effected. The\r problem is a complex one, for if we go back only four steps (and these\r at least enter into the composition of a child), there are commonly\r thirty progenitors to be taken into account. Many curious facts, rarely\r admitting of proof, are told us respecting the inheritance of disease\r or character from a remote ancestor. W","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"300"},"sequenceIndex":761},{"id":"plato-the-repu-301","text":"but scarcely less often the differences which distinguish children both\r from their parents and from one another. We are told of similar mental\r peculiarities running in families, and again of a tendency, as in the\r animals, to revert to a common or original stock. But we have a\r difficulty in distinguishing what is a true inheritance of genius or\r other qualities, and what is mere imitation or the result of similar\r circumstances. Great men and great women have rarely had great fathers\r and mothers. Nothing that we know of in the circumstances of their\r birth or lineage will explain their app","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"301"},"sequenceIndex":762},{"id":"plato-the-repu-302","text":"Few persons would deny that we bring into the world an inheritance of\r mental and physical qualities derived first from our parents, or\r through them from some remoter ancestor, secondly from our race,\r thirdly from the general condition of mankind into which we are born.\r Nothing is commoner than the remark, that ‘So and so is like his father\r or his uncle’; and an aged person may not unfrequently note a\r resemblance in a youth to a long-forgotten ancestor, observing that\r ‘Nature sometimes skips a generation.’ It may be true also, that if we\r knew more about our ancestors, these similarities","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"302"},"sequenceIndex":763},{"id":"plato-the-repu-303","text":"There is another aspect of the marriage question to which Plato is a\r stranger. All the children born in his state are foundlings. It never\r occurred to him that the greater part of them, according to universal\r experience, would have perished. For children can only be brought up in\r families. There is a subtle sympathy between the mother and the child\r which cannot be supplied by other mothers, or by ‘strong nurses one or\r more’ (Laws). If Plato’s ‘pen’ was as fatal as the Creches of Paris, or\r the foundling hospital of Dublin, more than nine-tenths of his children\r would have perished. There","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"303"},"sequenceIndex":764},{"id":"plato-the-repu-304","text":"What Plato had heard or seen of Sparta was applied by him in a mistaken\r way to his ideal commonwealth. He probably observed that both the\r Spartan men and women were superior in form and strength to the other\r Greeks; and this superiority he was disposed to attribute to the laws\r and customs relating to marriage. He did not consider that the desire\r of a noble offspring was a passion among the Spartans, or that their\r physical superiority was to be attributed chiefly, not to their\r marriage customs, but to their temperance and training. He did not\r reflect that Sparta was great, not in conseq","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"304"},"sequenceIndex":765},{"id":"plato-the-repu-305","text":"Still, while condemning Plato, we must acknowledge that neither\r Christianity, nor any other form of religion and society, has hitherto\r been able to cope with this most difficult of social problems, and that\r the side from which Plato regarded it is that from which we turn away.\r Population is the most untameable force in the political and social\r world. Do we not find, especially in large cities, that the greatest\r hindrance to the amelioration of the poor is their improvidence in\r marriage?—a small fault truly, if not involving endless consequences.\r There are whole countries too, such as I","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"305"},"sequenceIndex":766},{"id":"plato-the-repu-306","text":"When again in private life we see a whole family one by one dropping\r into the grave under the Ate of some inherited malady, and the parents\r perhaps surviving them, do our minds ever go back silently to that day\r twenty-five or thirty years before on which under the fairest auspices,\r amid the rejoicings of friends and acquaintances, a bride and\r bridegroom joined hands with one another? In making such a reflection\r we are not opposing physical considerations to moral, but moral to\r physical; we are seeking to make the voice of reason heard, which\r drives us back from the extravagance of sent","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"306"},"sequenceIndex":767},{"id":"plato-the-repu-307","text":"Lastly, no one can have observed the first rising flood of the passions\r in youth, the difficulty of regulating them, and the effects on the\r whole mind and nature which follow from them, the stimulus which is\r given to them by the imagination, without feeling that there is\r something unsatisfactory in our method of treating them. That the most\r important influence on human life should be wholly left to chance or\r shrouded in mystery, and instead of being disciplined or understood,\r should be required to conform only to an external standard of\r propriety—cannot be regarded by the philosopher a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"307"},"sequenceIndex":768},{"id":"plato-the-repu-308","text":"Nor is Plato wrong in asserting that family attachments may interfere\r with higher aims. If there have been some who ‘to party gave up what\r was meant for mankind,’ there have certainly been others who to family\r gave up what was meant for mankind or for their country. The cares of\r children, the necessity of procuring money for their support, the\r flatteries of the rich by the poor, the exclusiveness of caste, the\r pride of birth or wealth, the tendency of family life to divert men\r from the pursuit of the ideal or the heroic, are as lowering in our own\r age as in that of Plato. And if we pre","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"308"},"sequenceIndex":769},{"id":"plato-the-repu-309","text":"We hardly appreciate the power which the idea of the State, like all\r other abstract ideas, exercised over the mind of Plato. To us the State\r seems to be built up out of the family, or sometimes to be the\r framework in which family and social life is contained. But to Plato in\r his present mood of mind the family is only a disturbing influence\r which, instead of filling up, tends to disarrange the higher unity of\r the State. No organization is needed except a political, which,\r regarded from another point of view, is a military one. The State is\r all-sufficing for the wants of man, and, like ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"309"},"sequenceIndex":770},{"id":"plato-the-repu-310","text":"(c) But Plato has an equal, or, in his own estimation, even greater\r paradox in reserve, which is summed up in the famous text, ‘Until kings\r are philosophers or philosophers are kings, cities will never cease\r from ill.’ And by philosophers he explains himself to mean those who\r are capable of apprehending ideas, especially the idea of good. To the\r attainment of this higher knowledge the second education is directed.\r Through a process of training which has already made them good citizens\r they are now to be made good legislators. We find with some surprise\r (not unlike the feeling which Ari","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"310"},"sequenceIndex":771},{"id":"plato-the-repu-311","text":"The discovery of a great metaphysical conception seems to ravish the\r mind with a prophetic consciousness which takes away the power of\r estimating its value. No metaphysical enquirer has ever fairly\r criticised his own speculations; in his own judgment they have been\r above criticism; nor has he understood that what to him seemed to be\r absolute truth may reappear in the next generation as a form of logic\r or an instrument of thought. And posterity have also sometimes equally\r misapprehended the real value of his speculations. They appear to them\r to have contributed nothing to the stock of h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"311"},"sequenceIndex":772},{"id":"plato-the-repu-312","text":"Nor is there anything unnatural in the hasty application of these vast\r metaphysical conceptions to practical and political life. In the first\r enthusiasm of ideas men are apt to see them everywhere, and to apply\r them in the most remote sphere. They do not understand that the\r experience of ages is required to enable them to fill up ‘the\r intermediate axioms.’ Plato himself seems to have imagined that the\r truths of psychology, like those of astronomy and harmonics, would be\r arrived at by a process of deduction, and that the method which he has\r pursued in the Fourth Book, of inferring them ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"312"},"sequenceIndex":773},{"id":"plato-the-repu-313","text":"There is no mention of the idea of good in the Timaeus, nor of the\r divine Creator of the world in the Republic; and we are naturally led\r to ask in what relation they stand to one another. Is God above or\r below the idea of good? Or is the Idea of Good another mode of\r conceiving God? The latter appears to be the truer answer. To the Greek\r philosopher the perfection and unity of God was a far higher conception\r than his personality, which he hardly found a word to express, and\r which to him would have seemed to be borrowed from mythology. To the\r Christian, on the other hand, or to the moder","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"313"},"sequenceIndex":774},{"id":"plato-the-repu-314","text":"The question whether the ruler or statesman should be a philosopher is\r one that has not lost interest in modern times. In most countries of\r Europe and Asia there has been some one in the course of ages who has\r truly united the power of command with the power of thought and\r reflection, as there have been also many false combinations of these\r qualities. Some kind of speculative power is necessary both in\r practical and political life; like the rhetorician in the Phaedrus, men\r require to have a conception of the varieties of human character, and\r to be raised on great occasions above the co","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"314"},"sequenceIndex":775},{"id":"plato-the-repu-315","text":"But as the philosopher is apt to fail in the routine of political life,\r so the ordinary statesman is also apt to fail in extraordinary crises.\r When the face of the world is beginning to alter, and thunder is heard\r in the distance, he is still guided by his old maxims, and is the slave\r of his inveterate party prejudices; he cannot perceive the signs of the\r times; instead of looking forward he looks back; he learns nothing and\r forgets nothing; with ‘wise saws and modern instances’ he would stem\r the rising tide of revolution. He lives more and more within the circle\r of his own party, as t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"315"},"sequenceIndex":776},{"id":"plato-the-repu-316","text":"(d) Plato, labouring under what, to modern readers, appears to have\r been a confusion of ideas, assimilates the state to the individual, and\r fails to distinguish Ethics from Politics. He thinks that to be most of\r a state which is most like one man, and in which the citizens have the\r greatest uniformity of character. He does not see that the analogy is\r partly fallacious, and that the will or character of a state or nation\r is really the balance or rather the surplus of individual wills, which\r are limited by the condition of having to act in common. The movement\r of a body of men can never ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"316"},"sequenceIndex":777},{"id":"plato-the-repu-317","text":"Still, through this fallacious medium, a real enlargement of ideas is\r attained. When the virtues as yet presented no distinct conception to\r the mind, a great advance was made by the comparison of them with the\r arts; for virtue is partly art, and has an outward form as well as an\r inward principle. The harmony of music affords a lively image of the\r harmonies of the world and of human life, and may be regarded as a\r splendid illustration which was naturally mistaken for a real analogy.\r In the same way the identification of ethics with politics has a\r tendency to give definiteness to ethics,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"317"},"sequenceIndex":778},{"id":"plato-the-repu-318","text":"3. Plato’s views of education are in several respects remarkable; like\r the rest of the Republic they are partly Greek and partly ideal,\r beginning with the ordinary curriculum of the Greek youth, and\r extending to after-life. Plato is the first writer who distinctly says\r that education is to comprehend the whole of life, and to be a\r preparation for another in which education begins again. This is the\r continuous thread which runs through the Republic, and which more than\r any other of his ideas admits of an application to modern life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"318"},"sequenceIndex":779},{"id":"plato-the-repu-319","text":"He has long given up the notion that virtue cannot be taught; and he is\r disposed to modify the thesis of the Protagoras, that the virtues are\r one and not many. He is not unwilling to admit the sensible world into\r his scheme of truth. Nor does he assert in the Republic the\r involuntariness of vice, which is maintained by him in the Timaeus,\r Sophist, and Laws (Protag., Apol., Gorg.). Nor do the so-called\r Platonic ideas recovered from a former state of existence affect his\r theory of mental improvement. Still we observe in him the remains of\r the old Socratic doctrine, that true knowledge mu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"319"},"sequenceIndex":780},{"id":"plato-the-repu-320","text":"He treats first of music or literature, which he divides into true and\r false, and then goes on to gymnastics; of infancy in the Republic he\r takes no notice, though in the Laws he gives sage counsels about the\r nursing of children and the management of the mothers, and would have\r an education which is even prior to birth. But in the Republic he\r begins with the age at which the child is capable of receiving ideas,\r and boldly asserts, in language which sounds paradoxical to modern\r ears, that he must be taught the false before he can learn the true.\r The modern and ancient philosophical worl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"320"},"sequenceIndex":781},{"id":"plato-the-repu-321","text":"The young are to be brought up in happy surroundings, out of the way of\r sights or sounds which may hurt the character or vitiate the taste.\r They are to live in an atmosphere of health; the breeze is always to be\r wafting to them the impressions of truth and goodness. Could such an\r education be realized, or if our modern religious education could be\r bound up with truth and virtue and good manners and good taste, that\r would be the best hope of human improvement. Plato, like ourselves, is\r looking forward to changes in the moral and religious world, and is\r preparing for them. He recognizes ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"321"},"sequenceIndex":782},{"id":"plato-the-repu-322","text":"The second stage of education is gymnastic, which answers to the period\r of muscular growth and development. The simplicity which is enforced in\r music is extended to gymnastic; Plato is aware that the training of the\r body may be inconsistent with the training of the mind, and that bodily\r exercise may be easily overdone. Excessive training of the body is apt\r to give men a headache or to render them sleepy at a lecture on\r philosophy, and this they attribute not to the true cause, but to the\r nature of the subject. Two points are noticeable in Plato’s treatment\r of gymnastic:—First, that the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"322"},"sequenceIndex":783},{"id":"plato-the-repu-323","text":"The subject of gymnastic leads Plato to the sister subject of medicine,\r which he further illustrates by the parallel of law. The modern\r disbelief in medicine has led in this, as in some other departments of\r knowledge, to a demand for greater simplicity; physicians are becoming\r aware that they often make diseases ‘greater and more complicated’ by\r their treatment of them (Rep.). In two thousand years their art has\r made but slender progress; what they have gained in the analysis of the\r parts is in a great degree lost by their feebler conception of the\r human frame as a whole. They have att","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"323"},"sequenceIndex":784},{"id":"plato-the-repu-324","text":"The perplexity of medicine is paralleled by the perplexity of law; in\r which, again, Plato would have men follow the golden rule of\r simplicity. Greater matters are to be determined by the legislator or\r by the oracle of Delphi, lesser matters are to be left to the temporary\r regulation of the citizens themselves. Plato is aware that laissez\r faire is an important element of government. The diseases of a State\r are like the heads of a hydra; they multiply when they are cut off. The\r true remedy for them is not extirpation but prevention. And the way to\r prevent them is to take care of educatio","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"324"},"sequenceIndex":785},{"id":"plato-the-repu-325","text":"When the training in music and gymnastic is completed, there follows\r the first stage of active and public life. But soon education is to\r begin again from a new point of view. In the interval between the\r Fourth and Seventh Books we have discussed the nature of knowledge, and\r have thence been led to form a higher conception of what was required\r of us. For true knowledge, according to Plato, is of abstractions, and\r has to do, not with particulars or individuals, but with universals\r only; not with the beauties of poetry, but with the ideas of\r philosophy. And the great aim of education is t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"325"},"sequenceIndex":786},{"id":"plato-the-repu-326","text":"Mathematics in the age of Plato comprehended a very small part of that\r which is now included in them; but they bore a much larger proportion\r to the sum of human knowledge. They were the only organon of thought\r which the human mind at that time possessed, and the only measure by\r which the chaos of particulars could be reduced to rule and order. The\r faculty which they trained was naturally at war with the poetical or\r imaginative; and hence to Plato, who is everywhere seeking for\r abstractions and trying to get rid of the illusions of sense, nearly\r the whole of education is contained in th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"326"},"sequenceIndex":787},{"id":"plato-the-repu-327","text":"This self-proving unity or idea of good is a mere vision of which no\r distinct explanation can be given, relative only to a particular stage\r in Greek philosophy. It is an abstraction under which no individuals\r are comprehended, a whole which has no parts (Arist., Nic. Eth.). The\r vacancy of such a form was perceived by Aristotle, but not by Plato.\r Nor did he recognize that in the dialectical process are included two\r or more methods of investigation which are at variance with each other.\r He did not see that whether he took the longer or the shorter road, no\r advance could be made in this w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"327"},"sequenceIndex":788},{"id":"plato-the-repu-328","text":"The Idea of good is so called only in the Republic, but there are\r traces of it in other dialogues of Plato. It is a cause as well as an\r idea, and from this point of view may be compared with the creator of\r the Timaeus, who out of his goodness created all things. It corresponds\r to a certain extent with the modern conception of a law of nature, or\r of a final cause, or of both in one, and in this regard may be\r connected with the measure and symmetry of the Philebus. It is\r represented in the Symposium under the aspect of beauty, and is\r supposed to be attained there by stages of initiation,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"328"},"sequenceIndex":789},{"id":"plato-the-repu-329","text":"If we ask whether this science of dialectic which Plato only half\r explains to us is more akin to logic or to metaphysics, the answer is\r that in his mind the two sciences are not as yet distinguished, any\r more than the subjective and objective aspects of the world and of man,\r which German philosophy has revealed to us. Nor has he determined\r whether his science of dialectic is at rest or in motion, concerned\r with the contemplation of absolute being, or with a process of\r development and evolution. Modern metaphysics may be described as the\r science of abstractions, or as the science of the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"329"},"sequenceIndex":790},{"id":"plato-the-repu-330","text":"Many criticisms may be made on Plato’s theory of education. While in\r some respects he unavoidably falls short of modern thinkers, in others\r he is in advance of them. He is opposed to the modes of education which\r prevailed in his own time; but he can hardly be said to have discovered\r new ones. He does not see that education is relative to the characters\r of individuals; he only desires to impress the same form of the state\r on the minds of all. He has no sufficient idea of the effect of\r literature on the formation of the mind, and greatly exaggerates that\r of mathematics. His aim is above ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"330"},"sequenceIndex":791},{"id":"plato-the-repu-331","text":"On the other hand, Plato is far in advance of modern philosophers and\r theologians when he teaches that education is to be continued through\r life and will begin again in another. He would never allow education of\r some kind to cease; although he was aware that the proverbial saying of\r Solon, ‘I grow old learning many things,’ cannot be applied literally.\r Himself ravished with the contemplation of the idea of good, and\r delighting in solid geometry (Rep.), he has no difficulty in imagining\r that a lifetime might be passed happily in such pursuits. We who know\r how many more men of business t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"331"},"sequenceIndex":792},{"id":"plato-the-repu-332","text":"Yet the thought of Plato may not be wholly incapable of application to\r our own times. Even if regarded as an ideal which can never be\r realized, it may have a great effect in elevating the characters of\r mankind, and raising them above the routine of their ordinary\r occupation or profession. It is the best form under which we can\r conceive the whole of life. Nevertheless the idea of Plato is not\r easily put into practice. For the education of after life is\r necessarily the education which each one gives himself. Men and women\r cannot be brought together in schools or colleges at forty or fift","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"332"},"sequenceIndex":793},{"id":"plato-the-repu-333","text":"The want of energy is one of the main reasons why so few persons\r continue to improve in later years. They have not the will, and do not\r know the way. They ‘never try an experiment,’ or look up a point of\r interest for themselves; they make no sacrifices for the sake of\r knowledge; their minds, like their bodies, at a certain age become\r fixed. Genius has been defined as ‘the power of taking pains’; but\r hardly any one keeps up his interest in knowledge throughout a whole\r life. The troubles of a family, the business of making money, the\r demands of a profession destroy the elasticity of the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"333"},"sequenceIndex":794},{"id":"plato-the-repu-334","text":"If any one is desirous of carrying out in detail the Platonic education\r of after-life, some such counsels as the following may be offered to\r him:—That he shall choose the branch of knowledge to which his own mind\r most distinctly inclines, and in which he takes the greatest delight,\r either one which seems to connect with his own daily employment, or,\r perhaps, furnishes the greatest contrast to it. He may study from the\r speculative side the profession or business in which he is practically\r engaged. He may make Homer, Dante, Shakespeare, Plato, Bacon the\r friends and companions of his life","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"334"},"sequenceIndex":795},{"id":"plato-the-repu-335","text":"4. We remark with surprise that the progress of nations or the natural\r growth of institutions which fill modern treatises on political\r philosophy seem hardly ever to have attracted the attention of Plato\r and Aristotle. The ancients were familiar with the mutability of human\r affairs; they could moralize over the ruins of cities and the fall of\r empires (Plato, Statesman, and Sulpicius’ Letter to Cicero); by them\r fate and chance were deemed to be real powers, almost persons, and to\r have had a great share in political events. The wiser of them like\r Thucydides believed that ‘what had been w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"335"},"sequenceIndex":796},{"id":"plato-the-repu-336","text":"The early legends of Hellas have no real connection with the later\r history: they are at a distance, and the intermediate region is\r concealed from view; there is no road or path which leads from one to\r the other. At the beginning of Greek history, in the vestibule of the\r temple, is seen standing first of all the figure of the legislator,\r himself the interpreter and servant of the God. The fundamental laws\r which he gives are not supposed to change with time and circumstances.\r The salvation of the state is held rather to depend on the inviolable\r maintenance of them. They were sanctioned b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"336"},"sequenceIndex":797},{"id":"plato-the-repu-337","text":"Passing from speculations to facts, we observe that progress has been\r the exception rather than the law of human history. And therefore we\r are not surprised to find that the idea of progress is of modern rather\r than of ancient date; and, like the idea of a philosophy of history, is\r not more than a century or two old. It seems to have arisen out of the\r impression left on the human mind by the growth of the Roman Empire and\r of the Christian Church, and to be due to the political and social\r improvements which they introduced into the world; and still more in\r our own century to the idealis","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"337"},"sequenceIndex":798},{"id":"plato-the-repu-338","text":"5. For the relation of the Republic to the Statesman and the Laws, and\r the two other works of Plato which directly treat of politics, see the\r Introductions to the two latter; a few general points of comparison may\r be touched upon in this place.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"338"},"sequenceIndex":799},{"id":"plato-the-repu-339","text":"(1) The Republic, though probably written at intervals, yet speaking\r generally and judging by the indications of thought and style, may be\r reasonably ascribed to the middle period of Plato’s life: the Laws are\r certainly the work of his declining years, and some portions of them at\r any rate seem to have been written in extreme old age.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"339"},"sequenceIndex":800},{"id":"plato-the-repu-340","text":"(2) The Republic is full of hope and aspiration: the Laws bear the\r stamp of failure and disappointment. The one is a finished work which\r received the last touches of the author: the other is imperfectly\r executed, and apparently unfinished. The one has the grace and beauty\r of youth: the other has lost the poetical form, but has more of the\r severity and knowledge of life which is characteristic of old age.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"340"},"sequenceIndex":801},{"id":"plato-the-repu-341","text":"(3) The most conspicuous defect of the Laws is the failure of dramatic\r power, whereas the Republic is full of striking contrasts of ideas and\r oppositions of character.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"341"},"sequenceIndex":802},{"id":"plato-the-repu-342","text":"(4) The Laws may be said to have more the nature of a sermon, the\r Republic of a poem; the one is more religious, the other more\r intellectual.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"342"},"sequenceIndex":803},{"id":"plato-the-repu-343","text":"(5) Many theories of Plato, such as the doctrine of ideas, the\r government of the world by philosophers, are not found in the Laws; the\r immortality of the soul is first mentioned in xii; the person of\r Socrates has altogether disappeared. The community of women and\r children is renounced; the institution of common or public meals for\r women (Laws) is for the first time introduced (Ar. Pol.).","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"343"},"sequenceIndex":804},{"id":"plato-the-repu-344","text":"(6) There remains in the Laws the old enmity to the poets, who are\r ironically saluted in high-flown terms, and, at the same time, are\r peremptorily ordered out of the city, if they are not willing to submit\r their poems to the censorship of the magistrates (Rep.).","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"344"},"sequenceIndex":805},{"id":"plato-the-repu-345","text":"(7) Though the work is in most respects inferior, there are a few\r passages in the Laws, such as the honour due to the soul, the evils of\r licentious or unnatural love, the whole of Book x. (religion), the\r dishonesty of retail trade, and bequests, which come more home to us,\r and contain more of what may be termed the modern element in Plato than\r almost anything in the Republic.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"345"},"sequenceIndex":806},{"id":"plato-the-repu-346","text":"‘The same, or nearly the same, objections apply to Plato’s later work,\r the Laws, and therefore we had better examine briefly the constitution\r which is therein described. In the Republic, Socrates has definitely\r settled in all a few questions only; such as the community of women and\r children, the community of property, and the constitution of the state.\r The population is divided into two classes—one of husbandmen, and the\r other of warriors; from this latter is taken a third class of\r counsellors and rulers of the state. But Socrates has not determined\r whether the husbandmen and artists a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"346"},"sequenceIndex":807},{"id":"plato-the-repu-347","text":"‘The first and highest form of the state and of the government and of\r the law is that in which there prevails most widely the ancient saying\r that “Friends have all things in common.” Whether there is now, or ever\r will be, this communion of women and children and of property, in which\r the private and individual is altogether banished from life, and things\r which are by nature private, such as eyes and ears and hands, have\r become common, and all men express praise and blame, and feel joy and\r sorrow, on the same occasions, and the laws unite the city to the\r utmost,—whether all this is poss","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"347"},"sequenceIndex":808},{"id":"plato-the-repu-348","text":"The comparatively short work called the Statesman or Politicus in its\r style and manner is more akin to the Laws, while in its idealism it\r rather resembles the Republic. As far as we can judge by various\r indications of language and thought, it must be later than the one and\r of course earlier than the other. In both the Republic and Statesman a\r close connection is maintained between Politics and Dialectic. In the\r Statesman, enquiries into the principles of Method are interspersed\r with discussions about Politics. The comparative advantages of the rule\r of law and of a person are considered","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"348"},"sequenceIndex":809},{"id":"plato-the-repu-349","text":"6. Others as well as Plato have chosen an ideal Republic to be the\r vehicle of thoughts which they could not definitely express, or which\r went beyond their own age. The classical writing which approaches most\r nearly to the Republic of Plato is the ‘De Republica’ of Cicero; but\r neither in this nor in any other of his dialogues does he rival the art\r of Plato. The manners are clumsy and inferior; the hand of the\r rhetorician is apparent at every turn. Yet noble sentiments are\r constantly recurring: the true note of Roman patriotism—‘We Romans are\r a great people’—resounds through the whole wo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"349"},"sequenceIndex":810},{"id":"plato-the-repu-350","text":"Plato’s Republic has been said to be a church and not a state; and such\r an ideal of a city in the heavens has always hovered over the Christian\r world, and is embodied in St. Augustine’s ‘De Civitate Dei,’ which is\r suggested by the decay and fall of the Roman Empire, much in the same\r manner in which we may imagine the Republic of Plato to have been\r influenced by the decline of Greek politics in the writer’s own age.\r The difference is that in the time of Plato the degeneracy, though\r certain, was gradual and insensible: whereas the taking of Rome by the\r Goths stirred like an earthquake th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"350"},"sequenceIndex":811},{"id":"plato-the-repu-351","text":"The short treatise de Monarchia of Dante is by far the most remarkable\r of mediaeval ideals, and bears the impress of the great genius in whom\r Italy and the Middle Ages are so vividly reflected. It is the vision of\r an Universal Empire, which is supposed to be the natural and necessary\r government of the world, having a divine authority distinct from the\r Papacy, yet coextensive with it. It is not ‘the ghost of the dead Roman\r Empire sitting crowned upon the grave thereof,’ but the legitimate heir\r and successor of it, justified by the ancient virtues of the Romans and\r the beneficence of the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"351"},"sequenceIndex":812},{"id":"plato-the-repu-352","text":"The ‘Utopia’ of Sir Thomas More is a surprising monument of his genius,\r and shows a reach of thought far beyond his contemporaries. The book\r was written by him at the age of about 34 or 35, and is full of the\r generous sentiments of youth. He brings the light of Plato to bear upon\r the miserable state of his own country. Living not long after the Wars\r of the Roses, and in the dregs of the Catholic Church in England, he is\r indignant at the corruption of the clergy, at the luxury of the\r nobility and gentry, at the sufferings of the poor, at the calamities\r caused by war. To the eye of More ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"352"},"sequenceIndex":813},{"id":"plato-the-repu-353","text":"He is gifted with far greater dramatic invention than any one who\r succeeded him, with the exception of Swift. In the art of feigning he\r is a worthy disciple of Plato. Like him, starting from a small portion\r of fact, he founds his tale with admirable skill on a few lines in the\r Latin narrative of the voyages of Amerigo Vespucci. He is very precise\r about dates and facts, and has the power of making us believe that the\r narrator of the tale must have been an eyewitness. We are fairly\r puzzled by his manner of mixing up real and imaginary persons; his boy\r John Clement and Peter Giles, citize","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"353"},"sequenceIndex":814},{"id":"plato-the-repu-354","text":"The words of Phaedrus, ‘O Socrates, you can easily invent Egyptians or\r anything,’ are recalled to our mind as we read this lifelike fiction.\r Yet the greater merit of the work is not the admirable art, but the\r originality of thought. More is as free as Plato from the prejudices of\r his age, and far more tolerant. The Utopians do not allow him who\r believes not in the immortality of the soul to share in the\r administration of the state (Laws), ‘howbeit they put him to no\r punishment, because they be persuaded that it is in no man’s power to\r believe what he list’; and ‘no man is to be blamed ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"354"},"sequenceIndex":815},{"id":"plato-the-repu-355","text":"Nor is he less in advance of popular opinion in his political and moral\r speculations. He would like to bring military glory into contempt; he\r would set all sorts of idle people to profitable occupation, including\r in the same class, priests, women, noblemen, gentlemen, and ‘sturdy and\r valiant beggars,’ that the labour of all may be reduced to six hours a\r day. His dislike of capital punishment, and plans for the reformation\r of offenders; his detestation of priests and lawyers (Compare his\r satirical observation: ‘They (the Utopians) have priests of exceeding\r holiness, and therefore very f","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"355"},"sequenceIndex":816},{"id":"plato-the-repu-356","text":"Like Plato he is full of satirical reflections on governments and\r princes; on the state of the world and of knowledge. The hero of his\r discourse (Hythloday) is very unwilling to become a minister of state,\r considering that he would lose his independence and his advice would\r never be heeded (Compare an exquisite passage, of which the conclusion\r is as follows: ‘And verily it is naturally given...suppressed and\r ended.’) He ridicules the new logic of his time; the Utopians could\r never be made to understand the doctrine of Second Intentions (‘For\r they have not devised one of all those rules","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"356"},"sequenceIndex":817},{"id":"plato-the-repu-357","text":"The ‘New Atlantis’ is only a fragment, and far inferior in merit to the\r ‘Utopia.’ The work is full of ingenuity, but wanting in creative fancy,\r and by no means impresses the reader with a sense of credibility. In\r some places Lord Bacon is characteristically different from Sir Thomas\r More, as, for example, in the external state which he attributes to the\r governor of Solomon’s House, whose dress he minutely describes, while\r to Sir Thomas More such trappings appear simple ridiculous. Yet, after\r this programme of dress, Bacon adds the beautiful trait, ‘that he had a\r look as though he pitie","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"357"},"sequenceIndex":818},{"id":"plato-the-repu-358","text":"The ‘City of the Sun’ written by Campanella (1568-1639), a Dominican\r friar, several years after the ‘New Atlantis’ of Bacon, has many\r resemblances to the Republic of Plato. The citizens have wives and\r children in common; their marriages are of the same temporary sort, and\r are arranged by the magistrates from time to time. They do not,\r however, adopt his system of lots, but bring together the best natures,\r male and female, ‘according to philosophical rules.’ The infants until\r two years of age are brought up by their mothers in public temples; and\r since individuals for the most part educ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"358"},"sequenceIndex":819},{"id":"plato-the-repu-359","text":"Many details are given about their customs of eating and drinking,\r about their mode of dressing, their employments, their wars. Campanella\r looks forward to a new mode of education, which is to be a study of\r nature, and not of Aristotle. He would not have his citizens waste\r their time in the consideration of what he calls ‘the dead signs of\r things.’ He remarks that he who knows one science only, does not really\r know that one any more than the rest, and insists strongly on the\r necessity of a variety of knowledge. More scholars are turned out in\r the City of the Sun in one year than by con","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"359"},"sequenceIndex":820},{"id":"plato-the-repu-360","text":"There is a good deal of ingenuity and even originality in this work,\r and a most enlightened spirit pervades it. But it has little or no\r charm of style, and falls very far short of the ‘New Atlantis’ of\r Bacon, and still more of the ‘Utopia’ of Sir Thomas More. It is full of\r inconsistencies, and though borrowed from Plato, shows but a\r superficial acquaintance with his writings. It is a work such as one\r might expect to have been written by a philosopher and man of genius\r who was also a friar, and who had spent twenty-seven years of his life\r in a prison of the Inquisition. The most interes","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"360"},"sequenceIndex":821},{"id":"plato-the-repu-361","text":"Other writings on ideal states, such as the ‘Oceana’ of Harrington, in\r which the Lord Archon, meaning Cromwell, is described, not as he was,\r but as he ought to have been; or the ‘Argenis’ of Barclay, which is an\r historical allegory of his own time, are too unlike Plato to be worth\r mentioning. More interesting than either of these, and far more\r Platonic in style and thought, is Sir John Eliot’s ‘Monarchy of Man,’\r in which the prisoner of the Tower, no longer able ‘to be a politician\r in the land of his birth,’ turns away from politics to view ‘that other\r city which is within him,’ and fi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"361"},"sequenceIndex":822},{"id":"plato-the-repu-362","text":"7. Human life and conduct are affected by ideals in the same way that\r they are affected by the examples of eminent men. Neither the one nor\r the other are immediately applicable to practice, but there is a virtue\r flowing from them which tends to raise individuals above the common\r routine of society or trade, and to elevate States above the mere\r interests of commerce or the necessities of self-defence. Like the\r ideals of art they are partly framed by the omission of particulars;\r they require to be viewed at a certain distance, and are apt to fade\r away if we attempt to approach them. They","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"362"},"sequenceIndex":823},{"id":"plato-the-repu-363","text":"8. Two other ideals, which never appeared above the horizon in Greek\r Philosophy, float before the minds of men in our own day: one seen more\r clearly than formerly, as though each year and each generation brought\r us nearer to some great change; the other almost in the same degree\r retiring from view behind the laws of nature, as if oppressed by them,\r but still remaining a silent hope of we know not what hidden in the\r heart of man. The first ideal is the future of the human race in this\r world; the second the future of the individual in another. The first is\r the more perfect realization of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"363"},"sequenceIndex":824},{"id":"plato-the-repu-364","text":"The greatest of all ideals may, or rather must be conceived by us under\r similitudes derived from human qualities; although sometimes, like the\r Jewish prophets, we may dash away these figures of speech and describe\r the nature of God only in negatives. These again by degrees acquire a\r positive meaning. It would be well, if when meditating on the higher\r truths either of philosophy or religion, we sometimes substituted one\r form of expression for another, lest through the necessities of\r language we should become the slaves of mere words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"364"},"sequenceIndex":825},{"id":"plato-the-repu-365","text":"There is a third ideal, not the same, but akin to these, which has a\r place in the home and heart of every believer in the religion of\r Christ, and in which men seem to find a nearer and more familiar truth,\r the Divine man, the Son of Man, the Saviour of mankind, Who is the\r first-born and head of the whole family in heaven and earth, in Whom\r the Divine and human, that which is without and that which is within\r the range of our earthly faculties, are indissolubly united. Neither is\r this divine form of goodness wholly separable from the ideal of the\r Christian Church, which is said in the Ne","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"365"},"sequenceIndex":826},{"id":"plato-the-repu-366","text":"The scene is laid in the house of Cephalus at the Piraeus; and the\r whole dialogue is narrated by Socrates the day after it actually took\r place to Timaeus, Hermocrates, Critias, and a nameless person, who are\r introduced in the Timaeus.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"366"},"sequenceIndex":827},{"id":"plato-the-repu-367","text":"I went down yesterday to the Piraeus with Glaucon the son of Ariston,\r that I might offer up my prayers to the goddess (Bendis, the Thracian\r Artemis.); and also because I wanted to see in what manner they would\r celebrate the festival, which was a new thing. I was delighted with the\r procession of the inhabitants; but that of the Thracians was equally,\r if not more, beautiful. When we had finished our prayers and viewed the\r spectacle, we turned in the direction of the city; and at that instant\r Polemarchus the son of Cephalus chanced to catch sight of us from a\r distance as we were starting ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"367"},"sequenceIndex":828},{"id":"plato-the-repu-368","text":"Certainly we will, said Glaucon; and in a few minutes Polemarchus\r appeared, and with him Adeimantus, Glaucon’s brother, Niceratus the son\r of Nicias, and several others who had been at the procession.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"368"},"sequenceIndex":829},{"id":"plato-the-repu-369","text":"Polemarchus said to me: I perceive, Socrates, that you and your\r companion are already on your way to the city.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"369"},"sequenceIndex":830},{"id":"plato-the-repu-370","text":"And are you stronger than all these? for if not, you will have to\r remain where you are.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"370"},"sequenceIndex":831},{"id":"plato-the-repu-371","text":"May there not be the alternative, I said, that we may persuade you to\r let us go?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"371"},"sequenceIndex":832},{"id":"plato-the-repu-372","text":"Adeimantus added: Has no one told you of the torch-race on horseback in\r honour of the goddess which will take place in the evening?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"372"},"sequenceIndex":833},{"id":"plato-the-repu-373","text":"With horses! I replied: That is a novelty. Will horsemen carry torches\r and pass them one to another during the race?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"373"},"sequenceIndex":834},{"id":"plato-the-repu-374","text":"Yes, said Polemarchus, and not only so, but a festival will be\r celebrated at night, which you certainly ought to see. Let us rise soon\r after supper and see this festival; there will be a gathering of young\r men, and we will have a good talk. Stay then, and do not be perverse.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"374"},"sequenceIndex":835},{"id":"plato-the-repu-375","text":"Accordingly we went with Polemarchus to his house; and there we found\r his brothers Lysias and Euthydemus, and with them Thrasymachus the\r Chalcedonian, Charmantides the Paeanian, and Cleitophon the son of\r Aristonymus. There too was Cephalus the father of Polemarchus, whom I\r had not seen for a long time, and I thought him very much aged. He was\r seated on a cushioned chair, and had a garland on his head, for he had\r been sacrificing in the court; and there were some other chairs in the\r room arranged in a semicircle, upon which we sat down by him. He\r saluted me eagerly, and then he said:—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"375"},"sequenceIndex":836},{"id":"plato-the-repu-376","text":"You don’t come to see me, Socrates, as often as you ought: If I were\r still able to go and see you I would not ask you to come to me. But at\r my age I can hardly get to the city, and therefore you should come\r oftener to the Piraeus. For let me tell you, that the more the\r pleasures of the body fade away, the greater to me is the pleasure and\r charm of conversation. Do not then deny my request, but make our house\r your resort and keep company with these young men; we are old friends,\r and you will be quite at home with us.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"376"},"sequenceIndex":837},{"id":"plato-the-repu-377","text":"I replied: There is nothing which for my part I like better, Cephalus,\r than conversing with aged men; for I regard them as travellers who have\r gone a journey which I too may have to go, and of whom I ought to\r enquire, whether the way is smooth and easy, or rugged and difficult.\r And this is a question which I should like to ask of you who have\r arrived at that time which the poets call the ‘threshold of old age’—Is\r life harder towards the end, or what report do you give of it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"377"},"sequenceIndex":838},{"id":"plato-the-repu-378","text":"I will tell you, Socrates, he said, what my own feeling is. Men of my\r age flock together; we are birds of a feather, as the old proverb says;\r and at our meetings the tale of my acquaintance commonly is—I cannot\r eat, I cannot drink; the pleasures of youth and love are fled away:\r there was a good time once, but now that is gone, and life is no longer\r life. Some complain of the slights which are put upon them by\r relations, and they will tell you sadly of how many evils their old age\r is the cause. But to me, Socrates, these complainers seem to blame that\r which is not really in fault. For i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"378"},"sequenceIndex":839},{"id":"plato-the-repu-379","text":"I listened in admiration, and wanting to draw him out, that he might go\r on—Yes, Cephalus, I said: but I rather suspect that people in general\r are not convinced by you when you speak thus; they think that old age\r sits lightly upon you, not because of your happy disposition, but\r because you are rich, and wealth is well known to be a great comforter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"379"},"sequenceIndex":840},{"id":"plato-the-repu-380","text":"You are right, he replied; they are not convinced: and there is\r something in what they say; not, however, so much as they imagine. I\r might answer them as Themistocles answered the Seriphian who was\r abusing him and saying that he was famous, not for his own merits but\r because he was an Athenian: ‘If you had been a native of my country or\r I of yours, neither of us would have been famous.’ And to those who are\r not rich and are impatient of old age, the same reply may be made; for\r to the good poor man old age cannot be a light burden, nor can a bad\r rich man ever have peace with himself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"380"},"sequenceIndex":841},{"id":"plato-the-repu-381","text":"May I ask, Cephalus, whether your fortune was for the most part\r inherited or acquired by you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"381"},"sequenceIndex":842},{"id":"plato-the-repu-382","text":"Acquired! Socrates; do you want to know how much I acquired? In the art\r of making money I have been midway between my father and grandfather:\r for my grandfather, whose name I bear, doubled and trebled the value of\r his patrimony, that which he inherited being much what I possess now;\r but my father Lysanias reduced the property below what it is at\r present: and I shall be satisfied if I leave to these my sons not less\r but a little more than I received.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"382"},"sequenceIndex":843},{"id":"plato-the-repu-383","text":"That was why I asked you the question, I replied, because I see that\r you are indifferent about money, which is a characteristic rather of\r those who have inherited their fortunes than of those who have acquired\r them; the makers of fortunes have a second love of money as a creation\r of their own, resembling the affection of authors for their own poems,\r or of parents for their children, besides that natural love of it for\r the sake of use and profit which is common to them and all men. And\r hence they are very bad company, for they can talk about nothing but\r the praises of wealth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"383"},"sequenceIndex":844},{"id":"plato-the-repu-384","text":"Yes, that is very true, but may I ask another question?—What do you\r consider to be the greatest blessing which you have reaped from your\r wealth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"384"},"sequenceIndex":845},{"id":"plato-the-repu-385","text":"One, he said, of which I could not expect easily to convince others.\r For let me tell you, Socrates, that when a man thinks himself to be\r near death, fears and cares enter into his mind which he never had\r before; the tales of a world below and the punishment which is exacted\r there of deeds done here were once a laughing matter to him, but now he\r is tormented with the thought that they may be true: either from the\r weakness of age, or because he is now drawing nearer to that other\r place, he has a clearer view of these things; suspicions and alarms\r crowd thickly upon him, and he begins to ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"385"},"sequenceIndex":846},{"id":"plato-the-repu-386","text":"‘Hope,’ he says, ‘cherishes the soul of him who lives in justice and\r holiness, and is the nurse of his age and the companion of his\r journey;—hope which is mightiest to sway the restless soul of man.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"386"},"sequenceIndex":847},{"id":"plato-the-repu-387","text":"How admirable are his words! And the great blessing of riches, I do not\r say to every man, but to a good man, is, that he has had no occasion to\r deceive or to defraud others, either intentionally or unintentionally;\r and when he departs to the world below he is not in any apprehension\r about offerings due to the gods or debts which he owes to men. Now to\r this peace of mind the possession of wealth greatly contributes; and\r therefore I say, that, setting one thing against another, of the many\r advantages which wealth has to give, to a man of sense this is in my\r opinion the greatest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"387"},"sequenceIndex":848},{"id":"plato-the-repu-388","text":"Well said, Cephalus, I replied; but as concerning justice, what is\r it?—to speak the truth and to pay your debts—no more than this? And\r even to this are there not exceptions? Suppose that a friend when in\r his right mind has deposited arms with me and he asks for them when he\r is not in his right mind, ought I to give them back to him? No one\r would say that I ought or that I should be right in doing so, any more\r than they would say that I ought always to speak the truth to one who\r is in his condition.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"388"},"sequenceIndex":849},{"id":"plato-the-repu-389","text":"But then, I said, speaking the truth and paying your debts is not a\r correct definition of justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"389"},"sequenceIndex":850},{"id":"plato-the-repu-390","text":"Quite correct, Socrates, if Simonides is to be believed, said\r Polemarchus interposing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"390"},"sequenceIndex":851},{"id":"plato-the-repu-391","text":"I fear, said Cephalus, that I must go now, for I have to look after the\r sacrifices, and I hand over the argument to Polemarchus and the\r company.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"391"},"sequenceIndex":852},{"id":"plato-the-repu-392","text":"Tell me then, O thou heir of the argument, what did Simonides say, and\r according to you truly say, about justice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"392"},"sequenceIndex":853},{"id":"plato-the-repu-393","text":"He said that the repayment of a debt is just, and in saying so he\r appears to me to be right.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"393"},"sequenceIndex":854},{"id":"plato-the-repu-394","text":"I should be sorry to doubt the word of such a wise and inspired man,\r but his meaning, though probably clear to you, is the reverse of clear\r to me. For he certainly does not mean, as we were just now saying, that\r I ought to return a deposit of arms or of anything else to one who asks\r for it when he is not in his right senses; and yet a deposit cannot be\r denied to be a debt.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"394"},"sequenceIndex":855},{"id":"plato-the-repu-395","text":"Then when the person who asks me is not in his right mind I am by no\r means to make the return?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"395"},"sequenceIndex":856},{"id":"plato-the-repu-396","text":"When Simonides said that the repayment of a debt was justice, he did\r not mean to include that case?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"396"},"sequenceIndex":857},{"id":"plato-the-repu-397","text":"Certainly not; for he thinks that a friend ought always to do good to a\r friend and never evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"397"},"sequenceIndex":858},{"id":"plato-the-repu-398","text":"You mean that the return of a deposit of gold which is to the injury of\r the receiver, if the two parties are friends, is not the repayment of a\r debt,—that is what you would imagine him to say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"398"},"sequenceIndex":859},{"id":"plato-the-repu-399","text":"To be sure, he said, they are to receive what we owe them, and an\r enemy, as I take it, owes to an enemy that which is due or proper to\r him—that is to say, evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"399"},"sequenceIndex":860},{"id":"plato-the-repu-400","text":"Simonides, then, after the manner of poets, would seem to have spoken\r darkly of the nature of justice; for he really meant to say that\r justice is the giving to each man what is proper to him, and this he\r termed a debt.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"400"},"sequenceIndex":861},{"id":"plato-the-repu-401","text":"By heaven! I replied; and if we asked him what due or proper thing is\r given by medicine, and to whom, what answer do you think that he would\r make to us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"401"},"sequenceIndex":862},{"id":"plato-the-repu-402","text":"He would surely reply that medicine gives drugs and meat and drink to\r human bodies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"402"},"sequenceIndex":863},{"id":"plato-the-repu-403","text":"If, Socrates, we are to be guided at all by the analogy of the\r preceding instances, then justice is the art which gives good to\r friends and evil to enemies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"403"},"sequenceIndex":864},{"id":"plato-the-repu-404","text":"And who is best able to do good to his friends and evil to his enemies\r in time of sickness?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"404"},"sequenceIndex":865},{"id":"plato-the-repu-405","text":"And in what sort of actions or with a view to what result is the just\r man most able to do harm to his enemy and good to his friend?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"405"},"sequenceIndex":866},{"id":"plato-the-repu-406","text":"But is the just man or the skilful player a more useful and better\r partner at a game of draughts?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"406"},"sequenceIndex":867},{"id":"plato-the-repu-407","text":"And in the laying of bricks and stones is the just man a more useful or\r better partner than the builder?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"407"},"sequenceIndex":868},{"id":"plato-the-repu-408","text":"Then in what sort of partnership is the just man a better partner than\r the harp-player, as in playing the harp the harp-player is certainly a\r better partner than the just man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"408"},"sequenceIndex":869},{"id":"plato-the-repu-409","text":"Yes, Polemarchus, but surely not in the use of money; for you do not\r want a just man to be your counsellor in the purchase or sale of a\r horse; a man who is knowing about horses would be better for that,\r would he not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"409"},"sequenceIndex":870},{"id":"plato-the-repu-410","text":"Then what is that joint use of silver or gold in which the just man is\r to be preferred?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"410"},"sequenceIndex":871},{"id":"plato-the-repu-411","text":"And when you want to keep a pruning-hook safe, then justice is useful\r to the individual and to the state; but when you want to use it, then\r the art of the vine-dresser?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"411"},"sequenceIndex":872},{"id":"plato-the-repu-412","text":"And when you want to keep a shield or a lyre, and not to use them, you\r would say that justice is useful; but when you want to use them, then\r the art of the soldier or of the musician?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"412"},"sequenceIndex":873},{"id":"plato-the-repu-413","text":"And so of all other things;—justice is useful when they are useless,\r and useless when they are useful?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"413"},"sequenceIndex":874},{"id":"plato-the-repu-414","text":"Then justice is not good for much. But let us consider this further\r point: Is not he who can best strike a blow in a boxing match or in any\r kind of fighting best able to ward off a blow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"414"},"sequenceIndex":875},{"id":"plato-the-repu-415","text":"And he who is most skilful in preventing or escaping from a disease is\r best able to create one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"415"},"sequenceIndex":876},{"id":"plato-the-repu-416","text":"And he is the best guard of a camp who is best able to steal a march\r upon the enemy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"416"},"sequenceIndex":877},{"id":"plato-the-repu-417","text":"Then after all the just man has turned out to be a thief. And this is a\r lesson which I suspect you must have learnt out of Homer; for he,\r speaking of Autolycus, the maternal grandfather of Odysseus, who is a\r favourite of his, affirms that","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"417"},"sequenceIndex":878},{"id":"plato-the-repu-418","text":"And so, you and Homer and Simonides are agreed that justice is an art\r of theft; to be practised however ‘for the good of friends and for the\r harm of enemies,’—that was what you were saying?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"418"},"sequenceIndex":879},{"id":"plato-the-repu-419","text":"No, certainly not that, though I do not now know what I did say; but I\r still stand by the latter words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"419"},"sequenceIndex":880},{"id":"plato-the-repu-420","text":"Well, there is another question: By friends and enemies do we mean\r those who are so really, or only in seeming?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"420"},"sequenceIndex":881},{"id":"plato-the-repu-421","text":"Surely, he said, a man may be expected to love those whom he thinks\r good, and to hate those whom he thinks evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"421"},"sequenceIndex":882},{"id":"plato-the-repu-422","text":"Yes, but do not persons often err about good and evil: many who are not\r good seem to be so, and conversely?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"422"},"sequenceIndex":883},{"id":"plato-the-repu-423","text":"Then to them the good will be enemies and the evil will be their\r friends? True.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"423"},"sequenceIndex":884},{"id":"plato-the-repu-424","text":"And in that case they will be right in doing good to the evil and evil\r to the good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"424"},"sequenceIndex":885},{"id":"plato-the-repu-425","text":"But see the consequence:—Many a man who is ignorant of human nature has\r friends who are bad friends, and in that case he ought to do harm to\r them; and he has good enemies whom he ought to benefit; but, if so, we\r shall be saying the very opposite of that which we affirmed to be the\r meaning of Simonides.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"425"},"sequenceIndex":886},{"id":"plato-the-repu-426","text":"Very true, he said: and I think that we had better correct an error\r into which we seem to have fallen in the use of the words ‘friend’ and\r ‘enemy.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"426"},"sequenceIndex":887},{"id":"plato-the-repu-427","text":"We should rather say that he is a friend who is, as well as seems,\r good; and that he who seems only, and is not good, only seems to be and\r is not a friend; and of an enemy the same may be said.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"427"},"sequenceIndex":888},{"id":"plato-the-repu-428","text":"And instead of saying simply as we did at first, that it is just to do\r good to our friends and harm to our enemies, we should further say: It\r is just to do good to our friends when they are good and harm to our\r enemies when they are evil?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"428"},"sequenceIndex":889},{"id":"plato-the-repu-429","text":"And will not men who are injured be deteriorated in that which is the\r proper virtue of man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"429"},"sequenceIndex":890},{"id":"plato-the-repu-430","text":"And can the just by justice make men unjust, or speaking generally, can\r the good by virtue make them bad?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"430"},"sequenceIndex":891},{"id":"plato-the-repu-431","text":"Then to injure a friend or any one else is not the act of a just man,\r but of the opposite, who is the unjust?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"431"},"sequenceIndex":892},{"id":"plato-the-repu-432","text":"Then if a man says that justice consists in the repayment of debts, and\r that good is the debt which a just man owes to his friends, and evil\r the debt which he owes to his enemies,—to say this is not wise; for it\r is not true, if, as has been clearly shown, the injuring of another can\r be in no case just.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"432"},"sequenceIndex":893},{"id":"plato-the-repu-433","text":"Then you and I are prepared to take up arms against any one who\r attributes such a saying to Simonides or Bias or Pittacus, or any other\r wise man or seer?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"433"},"sequenceIndex":894},{"id":"plato-the-repu-434","text":"I believe that Periander or Perdiccas or Xerxes or Ismenias the Theban,\r or some other rich and mighty man, who had a great opinion of his own\r power, was the first to say that justice is ‘doing good to your friends\r and harm to your enemies.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"434"},"sequenceIndex":895},{"id":"plato-the-repu-435","text":"Yes, I said; but if this definition of justice also breaks down, what\r other can be offered?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"435"},"sequenceIndex":896},{"id":"plato-the-repu-436","text":"Several times in the course of the discussion Thrasymachus had made an\r attempt to get the argument into his own hands, and had been put down\r by the rest of the company, who wanted to hear the end. But when\r Polemarchus and I had done speaking and there was a pause, he could no\r longer hold his peace; and, gathering himself up, he came at us like a\r wild beast, seeking to devour us. We were quite panic-stricken at the\r sight of him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"436"},"sequenceIndex":897},{"id":"plato-the-repu-437","text":"He roared out to the whole company: What folly, Socrates, has taken\r possession of you all? And why, sillybillies, do you knock under to one\r another? I say that if you want really to know what justice is, you\r should not only ask but answer, and you should not seek honour to\r yourself from the refutation of an opponent, but have your own answer;\r for there is many a one who can ask and cannot answer. And now I will\r not have you say that justice is duty or advantage or profit or gain or\r interest, for this sort of nonsense will not do for me; I must have\r clearness and accuracy.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"437"},"sequenceIndex":898},{"id":"plato-the-repu-438","text":"I was panic-stricken at his words, and could not look at him without\r trembling. Indeed I believe that if I had not fixed my eye upon him, I\r should have been struck dumb: but when I saw his fury rising, I looked\r at him first, and was therefore able to reply to him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"438"},"sequenceIndex":899},{"id":"plato-the-repu-439","text":"Thrasymachus, I said, with a quiver, don’t be hard upon us. Polemarchus\r and I may have been guilty of a little mistake in the argument, but I\r can assure you that the error was not intentional. If we were seeking\r for a piece of gold, you would not imagine that we were ‘knocking under\r to one another,’ and so losing our chance of finding it. And why, when\r we are seeking for justice, a thing more precious than many pieces of\r gold, do you say that we are weakly yielding to one another and not\r doing our utmost to get at the truth? Nay, my good friend, we are most\r willing and anxious to do so","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"439"},"sequenceIndex":900},{"id":"plato-the-repu-440","text":"How characteristic of Socrates! he replied, with a bitter laugh;—that’s\r your ironical style! Did I not foresee—have I not already told you,\r that whatever he was asked he would refuse to answer, and try irony or\r any other shuffle, in order that he might avoid answering?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"440"},"sequenceIndex":901},{"id":"plato-the-repu-441","text":"You are a philosopher, Thrasymachus, I replied, and well know that if\r you ask a person what numbers make up twelve, taking care to prohibit\r him whom you ask from answering twice six, or three times four, or six\r times two, or four times three, ‘for this sort of nonsense will not do\r for me,’—then obviously, if that is your way of putting the question,\r no one can answer you. But suppose that he were to retort,\r ‘Thrasymachus, what do you mean? If one of these numbers which you\r interdict be the true answer to the question, am I falsely to say some\r other number which is not the right one?—is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"441"},"sequenceIndex":902},{"id":"plato-the-repu-442","text":"Why should they not be? I replied; and even if they are not, but only\r appear to be so to the person who is asked, ought he not to say what he\r thinks, whether you and I forbid him or not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"442"},"sequenceIndex":903},{"id":"plato-the-repu-443","text":"I dare say that I may, notwithstanding the danger, if upon reflection I\r approve of any of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"443"},"sequenceIndex":904},{"id":"plato-the-repu-444","text":"But what if I give you an answer about justice other and better, he\r said, than any of these? What do you deserve to have done to you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"444"},"sequenceIndex":905},{"id":"plato-the-repu-445","text":"Done to me!—as becomes the ignorant, I must learn from the wise—that is\r what I deserve to have done to me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"445"},"sequenceIndex":906},{"id":"plato-the-repu-446","text":"But you have, Socrates, said Glaucon: and you, Thrasymachus, need be\r under no anxiety about money, for we will all make a contribution for\r Socrates.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"446"},"sequenceIndex":907},{"id":"plato-the-repu-447","text":"Yes, he replied, and then Socrates will do as he always does—refuse to\r answer himself, but take and pull to pieces the answer of some one\r else.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"447"},"sequenceIndex":908},{"id":"plato-the-repu-448","text":"Why, my good friend, I said, how can any one answer who knows, and says\r that he knows, just nothing; and who, even if he has some faint notions\r of his own, is told by a man of authority not to utter them? The\r natural thing is, that the speaker should be some one like yourself who\r professes to know and can tell what he knows. Will you then kindly\r answer, for the edification of the company and of myself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"448"},"sequenceIndex":909},{"id":"plato-the-repu-449","text":"Glaucon and the rest of the company joined in my request, and\r Thrasymachus, as any one might see, was in reality eager to speak; for\r he thought that he had an excellent answer, and would distinguish\r himself. But at first he affected to insist on my answering; at length\r he consented to begin. Behold, he said, the wisdom of Socrates; he\r refuses to teach himself, and goes about learning of others, to whom he\r never even says Thank you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"449"},"sequenceIndex":910},{"id":"plato-the-repu-450","text":"That I learn of others, I replied, is quite true; but that I am\r ungrateful I wholly deny. Money I have none, and therefore I pay in\r praise, which is all I have; and how ready I am to praise any one who\r appears to me to speak well you will very soon find out when you\r answer; for I expect that you will answer well.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"450"},"sequenceIndex":911},{"id":"plato-the-repu-451","text":"Listen, then, he said; I proclaim that justice is nothing else than the\r interest of the stronger. And now why do you not praise me? But of\r course you won’t.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"451"},"sequenceIndex":912},{"id":"plato-the-repu-452","text":"Let me first understand you, I replied. Justice, as you say, is the\r interest of the stronger. What, Thrasymachus, is the meaning of this?\r You cannot mean to say that because Polydamas, the pancratiast, is\r stronger than we are, and finds the eating of beef conducive to his\r bodily strength, that to eat beef is therefore equally for our good who\r are weaker than he is, and right and just for us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"452"},"sequenceIndex":913},{"id":"plato-the-repu-453","text":"That’s abominable of you, Socrates; you take the words in the sense\r which is most damaging to the argument.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"453"},"sequenceIndex":914},{"id":"plato-the-repu-454","text":"Not at all, my good sir, I said; I am trying to understand them; and I\r wish that you would be a little clearer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"454"},"sequenceIndex":915},{"id":"plato-the-repu-455","text":"Well, he said, have you never heard that forms of government differ;\r there are tyrannies, and there are democracies, and there are\r aristocracies?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"455"},"sequenceIndex":916},{"id":"plato-the-repu-456","text":"And the different forms of government make laws democratical,\r aristocratical, tyrannical, with a view to their several interests; and\r these laws, which are made by them for their own interests, are the\r justice which they deliver to their subjects, and him who transgresses\r them they punish as a breaker of the law, and unjust. And that is what\r I mean when I say that in all states there is the same principle of\r justice, which is the interest of the government; and as the government\r must be supposed to have power, the only reasonable conclusion is, that\r everywhere there is one principle of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"456"},"sequenceIndex":917},{"id":"plato-the-repu-457","text":"Now I understand you, I said; and whether you are right or not I will\r try to discover. But let me remark, that in defining justice you have\r yourself used the word ‘interest’ which you forbade me to use. It is\r true, however, that in your definition the words ‘of the stronger’ are\r added.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"457"},"sequenceIndex":918},{"id":"plato-the-repu-458","text":"Great or small, never mind about that: we must first enquire whether\r what you are saying is the truth. Now we are both agreed that justice\r is interest of some sort, but you go on to say ‘of the stronger’; about\r this addition I am not so sure, and must therefore consider further.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"458"},"sequenceIndex":919},{"id":"plato-the-repu-459","text":"I will; and first tell me, Do you admit that it is just for subjects to\r obey their rulers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"459"},"sequenceIndex":920},{"id":"plato-the-repu-460","text":"But are the rulers of states absolutely infallible, or are they\r sometimes liable to err?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"460"},"sequenceIndex":921},{"id":"plato-the-repu-461","text":"Then in making their laws they may sometimes make them rightly, and\r sometimes not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"461"},"sequenceIndex":922},{"id":"plato-the-repu-462","text":"When they make them rightly, they make them agreeably to their\r interest; when they are mistaken, contrary to their interest; you admit\r that?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"462"},"sequenceIndex":923},{"id":"plato-the-repu-463","text":"And the laws which they make must be obeyed by their subjects,—and that\r is what you call justice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"463"},"sequenceIndex":924},{"id":"plato-the-repu-464","text":"Then justice, according to your argument, is not only obedience to the\r interest of the stronger but the reverse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"464"},"sequenceIndex":925},{"id":"plato-the-repu-465","text":"I am only repeating what you are saying, I believe. But let us\r consider: Have we not admitted that the rulers may be mistaken about\r their own interest in what they command, and also that to obey them is\r justice? Has not that been admitted?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"465"},"sequenceIndex":926},{"id":"plato-the-repu-466","text":"Then you must also have acknowledged justice not to be for the interest\r of the stronger, when the rulers unintentionally command things to be\r done which are to their own injury. For if, as you say, justice is the\r obedience which the subject renders to their commands, in that case, O\r wisest of men, is there any escape from the conclusion that the weaker\r are commanded to do, not what is for the interest, but what is for the\r injury of the stronger?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"466"},"sequenceIndex":927},{"id":"plato-the-repu-467","text":"But there is no need of any witness, said Polemarchus, for Thrasymachus\r himself acknowledges that rulers may sometimes command what is not for\r their own interest, and that for subjects to obey them is justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"467"},"sequenceIndex":928},{"id":"plato-the-repu-468","text":"Yes, Polemarchus,—Thrasymachus said that for subjects to do what was\r commanded by their rulers is just.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"468"},"sequenceIndex":929},{"id":"plato-the-repu-469","text":"Yes, Cleitophon, but he also said that justice is the interest of the\r stronger, and, while admitting both these propositions, he further\r acknowledged that the stronger may command the weaker who are his\r subjects to do what is not for his own interest; whence follows that\r justice is the injury quite as much as the interest of the stronger.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"469"},"sequenceIndex":930},{"id":"plato-the-repu-470","text":"But, said Cleitophon, he meant by the interest of the stronger what the\r stronger thought to be his interest,—this was what the weaker had to\r do; and this was affirmed by him to be justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"470"},"sequenceIndex":931},{"id":"plato-the-repu-471","text":"Never mind, I replied, if he now says that they are, let us accept his\r statement. Tell me, Thrasymachus, I said, did you mean by justice what\r the stronger thought to be his interest, whether really so or not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"471"},"sequenceIndex":932},{"id":"plato-the-repu-472","text":"Certainly not, he said. Do you suppose that I call him who is mistaken\r the stronger at the time when he is mistaken?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"472"},"sequenceIndex":933},{"id":"plato-the-repu-473","text":"Yes, I said, my impression was that you did so, when you admitted that\r the ruler was not infallible but might be sometimes mistaken.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"473"},"sequenceIndex":934},{"id":"plato-the-repu-474","text":"You argue like an informer, Socrates. Do you mean, for example, that he\r who is mistaken about the sick is a physician in that he is mistaken?\r or that he who errs in arithmetic or grammar is an arithmetician or\r grammarian at the time when he is making the mistake, in respect of the\r mistake? True, we say that the physician or arithmetician or grammarian\r has made a mistake, but this is only a way of speaking; for the fact is\r that neither the grammarian nor any other person of skill ever makes a\r mistake in so far as he is what his name implies; they none of them err\r unless their skill fail","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"474"},"sequenceIndex":935},{"id":"plato-the-repu-475","text":"And do you suppose that I ask these questions with any design of\r injuring you in the argument?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"475"},"sequenceIndex":936},{"id":"plato-the-repu-476","text":"Nay, he replied, ‘suppose’ is not the word—I know it; but you will be\r found out, and by sheer force of argument you will never prevail.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"476"},"sequenceIndex":937},{"id":"plato-the-repu-477","text":"I shall not make the attempt, my dear man; but to avoid any\r misunderstanding occurring between us in future, let me ask, in what\r sense do you speak of a ruler or stronger whose interest, as you were\r saying, he being the superior, it is just that the inferior should\r execute—is he a ruler in the popular or in the strict sense of the\r term?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"477"},"sequenceIndex":938},{"id":"plato-the-repu-478","text":"In the strictest of all senses, he said. And now cheat and play the\r informer if you can; I ask no quarter at your hands. But you never will\r be able, never.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"478"},"sequenceIndex":939},{"id":"plato-the-repu-479","text":"And do you imagine, I said, that I am such a madman as to try and\r cheat, Thrasymachus? I might as well shave a lion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"479"},"sequenceIndex":940},{"id":"plato-the-repu-480","text":"Enough, I said, of these civilities. It will be better that I should\r ask you a question: Is the physician, taken in that strict sense of\r which you are speaking, a healer of the sick or a maker of money? And\r remember that I am now speaking of the true physician.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"480"},"sequenceIndex":941},{"id":"plato-the-repu-481","text":"And the pilot—that is to say, the true pilot—is he a captain of sailors\r or a mere sailor?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"481"},"sequenceIndex":942},{"id":"plato-the-repu-482","text":"The circumstance that he sails in the ship is not to be taken into\r account; neither is he to be called a sailor; the name pilot by which\r he is distinguished has nothing to do with sailing, but is significant\r of his skill and of his authority over the sailors.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"482"},"sequenceIndex":943},{"id":"plato-the-repu-483","text":"I mean what I may illustrate negatively by the example of the body.\r Suppose you were to ask me whether the body is self-sufficing or has\r wants, I should reply: Certainly the body has wants; for the body may\r be ill and require to be cured, and has therefore interests to which\r the art of medicine ministers; and this is the origin and intention of\r medicine, as you will acknowledge. Am I not right?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"483"},"sequenceIndex":944},{"id":"plato-the-repu-484","text":"But is the art of medicine or any other art faulty or deficient in any\r quality in the same way that the eye may be deficient in sight or the\r ear fail of hearing, and therefore requires another art to provide for\r the interests of seeing and hearing—has art in itself, I say, any\r similar liability to fault or defect, and does every art require\r another supplementary art to provide for its interests, and that\r another and another without end? Or have the arts to look only after\r their own interests? Or have they no need either of themselves or of\r another?—having no faults or defects, they hav","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"484"},"sequenceIndex":945},{"id":"plato-the-repu-485","text":"Then medicine does not consider the interest of medicine, but the\r interest of the body?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"485"},"sequenceIndex":946},{"id":"plato-the-repu-486","text":"Nor does the art of horsemanship consider the interests of the art of\r horsemanship, but the interests of the horse; neither do any other arts\r care for themselves, for they have no needs; they care only for that\r which is the subject of their art?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"486"},"sequenceIndex":947},{"id":"plato-the-repu-487","text":"But surely, Thrasymachus, the arts are the superiors and rulers of\r their own subjects?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"487"},"sequenceIndex":948},{"id":"plato-the-repu-488","text":"Then, I said, no science or art considers or enjoins the interest of\r the stronger or superior, but only the interest of the subject and\r weaker?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"488"},"sequenceIndex":949},{"id":"plato-the-repu-489","text":"Then, I continued, no physician, in so far as he is a physician,\r considers his own good in what he prescribes, but the good of his\r patient; for the true physician is also a ruler having the human body\r as a subject, and is not a mere money-maker; that has been admitted?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"489"},"sequenceIndex":950},{"id":"plato-the-repu-490","text":"And the pilot likewise, in the strict sense of the term, is a ruler of\r sailors and not a mere sailor?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"490"},"sequenceIndex":951},{"id":"plato-the-repu-491","text":"And such a pilot and ruler will provide and prescribe for the interest\r of the sailor who is under him, and not for his own or the ruler’s\r interest?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"491"},"sequenceIndex":952},{"id":"plato-the-repu-492","text":"Then, I said, Thrasymachus, there is no one in any rule who, in so far\r as he is a ruler, considers or enjoins what is for his own interest,\r but always what is for the interest of his subject or suitable to his\r art; to that he looks, and that alone he considers in everything which\r he says and does.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"492"},"sequenceIndex":953},{"id":"plato-the-repu-493","text":"When we had got to this point in the argument, and every one saw that\r the definition of justice had been completely upset, Thrasymachus,\r instead of replying to me, said: Tell me, Socrates, have you got a\r nurse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"493"},"sequenceIndex":954},{"id":"plato-the-repu-494","text":"Because she leaves you to snivel, and never wipes your nose: she has\r not even taught you to know the shepherd from the sheep.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"494"},"sequenceIndex":955},{"id":"plato-the-repu-495","text":"Because you fancy that the shepherd or neatherd fattens or tends the\r sheep or oxen with a view to their own good and not to the good of\r himself or his master; and you further imagine that the rulers of\r states, if they are true rulers, never think of their subjects as\r sheep, and that they are not studying their own advantage day and\r night. Oh, no; and so entirely astray are you in your ideas about the\r just and unjust as not even to know that justice and the just are in\r reality another’s good; that is to say, the interest of the ruler and\r stronger, and the loss of the subject and servant","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"495"},"sequenceIndex":956},{"id":"plato-the-repu-496","text":"Thrasymachus, when he had thus spoken, having, like a bath-man, deluged\r our ears with his words, had a mind to go away. But the company would\r not let him; they insisted that he should remain and defend his\r position; and I myself added my own humble request that he would not\r leave us. Thrasymachus, I said to him, excellent man, how suggestive\r are your remarks! And are you going to run away before you have fairly\r taught or learned whether they are true or not? Is the attempt to\r determine the way of man’s life so small a matter in your eyes—to\r determine how life may be passed by each one ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"496"},"sequenceIndex":957},{"id":"plato-the-repu-497","text":"You appear rather, I replied, to have no care or thought about us,\r Thrasymachus—whether we live better or worse from not knowing what you\r say you know, is to you a matter of indifference. Prithee, friend, do\r not keep your knowledge to yourself; we are a large party; and any\r benefit which you confer upon us will be amply rewarded. For my own\r part I openly declare that I am not convinced, and that I do not\r believe injustice to be more gainful than justice, even if uncontrolled\r and allowed to have free play. For, granting that there may be an\r unjust man who is able to commit injustice eit","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"497"},"sequenceIndex":958},{"id":"plato-the-repu-498","text":"And how am I to convince you, he said, if you are not already convinced\r by what I have just said; what more can I do for you? Would you have me\r put the proof bodily into your souls?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"498"},"sequenceIndex":959},{"id":"plato-the-repu-499","text":"Heaven forbid! I said; I would only ask you to be consistent; or, if\r you change, change openly and let there be no deception. For I must\r remark, Thrasymachus, if you will recall what was previously said, that\r although you began by defining the true physician in an exact sense,\r you did not observe a like exactness when speaking of the shepherd; you\r thought that the shepherd as a shepherd tends the sheep not with a view\r to their own good, but like a mere diner or banquetter with a view to\r the pleasures of the table; or, again, as a trader for sale in the\r market, and not as a shepherd. Ye","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"499"},"sequenceIndex":960},{"id":"plato-the-repu-500","text":"Then why in the case of lesser offices do men never take them willingly\r without payment, unless under the idea that they govern for the\r advantage not of themselves but of others? Let me ask you a question:\r Are not the several arts different, by reason of their each having a\r separate function? And, my dear illustrious friend, do say what you\r think, that we may make a little progress.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"500"},"sequenceIndex":961},{"id":"plato-the-repu-501","text":"And each art gives us a particular good and not merely a general\r one—medicine, for example, gives us health; navigation, safety at sea,\r and so on?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"501"},"sequenceIndex":962},{"id":"plato-the-repu-502","text":"And the art of payment has the special function of giving pay: but we\r do not confuse this with other arts, any more than the art of the pilot\r is to be confused with the art of medicine, because the health of the\r pilot may be improved by a sea voyage. You would not be inclined to\r say, would you, that navigation is the art of medicine, at least if we\r are to adopt your exact use of language?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"502"},"sequenceIndex":963},{"id":"plato-the-repu-503","text":"Or because a man is in good health when he receives pay you would not\r say that the art of payment is medicine?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"503"},"sequenceIndex":964},{"id":"plato-the-repu-504","text":"Nor would you say that medicine is the art of receiving pay because a\r man takes fees when he is engaged in healing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"504"},"sequenceIndex":965},{"id":"plato-the-repu-505","text":"And we have admitted, I said, that the good of each art is specially\r confined to the art?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"505"},"sequenceIndex":966},{"id":"plato-the-repu-506","text":"Then, if there be any good which all artists have in common, that is to\r be attributed to something of which they all have the common use?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"506"},"sequenceIndex":967},{"id":"plato-the-repu-507","text":"And when the artist is benefited by receiving pay the advantage is\r gained by an additional use of the art of pay, which is not the art\r professed by him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"507"},"sequenceIndex":968},{"id":"plato-the-repu-508","text":"Then the pay is not derived by the several artists from their\r respective arts. But the truth is, that while the art of medicine gives\r health, and the art of the builder builds a house, another art attends\r them which is the art of pay. The various arts may be doing their own\r business and benefiting that over which they preside, but would the\r artist receive any benefit from his art unless he were paid as well?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"508"},"sequenceIndex":969},{"id":"plato-the-repu-509","text":"Then now, Thrasymachus, there is no longer any doubt that neither arts\r nor governments provide for their own interests; but, as we were before\r saying, they rule and provide for the interests of their subjects who\r are the weaker and not the stronger—to their good they attend and not\r to the good of the superior. And this is the reason, my dear\r Thrasymachus, why, as I was just now saying, no one is willing to\r govern; because no one likes to take in hand the reformation of evils\r which are not his concern without remuneration. For, in the execution\r of his work, and in giving his orders to a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"509"},"sequenceIndex":970},{"id":"plato-the-repu-510","text":"What do you mean, Socrates? said Glaucon. The first two modes of\r payment are intelligible enough, but what the penalty is I do not\r understand, or how a penalty can be a payment.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"510"},"sequenceIndex":971},{"id":"plato-the-repu-511","text":"You mean that you do not understand the nature of this payment which to\r the best men is the great inducement to rule? Of course you know that\r ambition and avarice are held to be, as indeed they are, a disgrace?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"511"},"sequenceIndex":972},{"id":"plato-the-repu-512","text":"And for this reason, I said, money and honour have no attraction for\r them; good men do not wish to be openly demanding payment for governing\r and so to get the name of hirelings, nor by secretly helping themselves\r out of the public revenues to get the name of thieves. And not being\r ambitious they do not care about honour. Wherefore necessity must be\r laid upon them, and they must be induced to serve from the fear of\r punishment. And this, as I imagine, is the reason why the forwardness\r to take office, instead of waiting to be compelled, has been deemed\r dishonourable. Now the worst part of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"512"},"sequenceIndex":973},{"id":"plato-the-repu-513","text":"I for my part deem the life of the just to be the more advantageous, he\r answered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"513"},"sequenceIndex":974},{"id":"plato-the-repu-514","text":"Did you hear all the advantages of the unjust which Thrasymachus was\r rehearsing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"514"},"sequenceIndex":975},{"id":"plato-the-repu-515","text":"Then shall we try to find some way of convincing him, if we can, that\r he is saying what is not true?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"515"},"sequenceIndex":976},{"id":"plato-the-repu-516","text":"If, I said, he makes a set speech and we make another recounting all\r the advantages of being just, and he answers and we rejoin, there must\r be a numbering and measuring of the goods which are claimed on either\r side, and in the end we shall want judges to decide; but if we proceed\r in our enquiry as we lately did, by making admissions to one another,\r we shall unite the offices of judge and advocate in our own persons.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"516"},"sequenceIndex":977},{"id":"plato-the-repu-517","text":"Well, then, Thrasymachus, I said, suppose you begin at the beginning\r and answer me. You say that perfect injustice is more gainful than\r perfect justice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"517"},"sequenceIndex":978},{"id":"plato-the-repu-518","text":"And what is your view about them? Would you call one of them virtue and\r the other vice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"518"},"sequenceIndex":979},{"id":"plato-the-repu-519","text":"What a charming notion! So likely too, seeing that I affirm injustice\r to be profitable and justice not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"519"},"sequenceIndex":980},{"id":"plato-the-repu-520","text":"Yes, he said; at any rate those of them who are able to be perfectly\r unjust, and who have the power of subduing states and nations; but\r perhaps you imagine me to be talking of cutpurses. Even this profession\r if undetected has advantages, though they are not to be compared with\r those of which I was just now speaking.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"520"},"sequenceIndex":981},{"id":"plato-the-repu-521","text":"I do not think that I misapprehend your meaning, Thrasymachus, I\r replied; but still I cannot hear without amazement that you class\r injustice with wisdom and virtue, and justice with the opposite.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"521"},"sequenceIndex":982},{"id":"plato-the-repu-522","text":"Now, I said, you are on more substantial and almost unanswerable\r ground; for if the injustice which you were maintaining to be\r profitable had been admitted by you as by others to be vice and\r deformity, an answer might have been given to you on received\r principles; but now I perceive that you will call injustice honourable\r and strong, and to the unjust you will attribute all the qualities\r which were attributed by us before to the just, seeing that you do not\r hesitate to rank injustice with wisdom and virtue.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"522"},"sequenceIndex":983},{"id":"plato-the-repu-523","text":"Then I certainly ought not to shrink from going through with the\r argument so long as I have reason to think that you, Thrasymachus, are\r speaking your real mind; for I do believe that you are now in earnest\r and are not amusing yourself at our expense.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"523"},"sequenceIndex":984},{"id":"plato-the-repu-524","text":"I may be in earnest or not, but what is that to you?—to refute the\r argument is your business.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"524"},"sequenceIndex":985},{"id":"plato-the-repu-525","text":"Very true, I said; that is what I have to do: But will you be so good\r as answer yet one more question? Does the just man try to gain any\r advantage over the just?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"525"},"sequenceIndex":986},{"id":"plato-the-repu-526","text":"Far otherwise; if he did he would not be the simple amusing creature\r which he is.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"526"},"sequenceIndex":987},{"id":"plato-the-repu-527","text":"And how would he regard the attempt to gain an advantage over the\r unjust; would that be considered by him as just or unjust?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"527"},"sequenceIndex":988},{"id":"plato-the-repu-528","text":"He would think it just, and would try to gain the advantage; but he\r would not be able.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"528"},"sequenceIndex":989},{"id":"plato-the-repu-529","text":"Whether he would or would not be able, I said, is not to the point. My\r question is only whether the just man, while refusing to have more than\r another just man, would wish and claim to have more than the unjust?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"529"},"sequenceIndex":990},{"id":"plato-the-repu-530","text":"And what of the unjust—does he claim to have more than the just man and\r to do more than is just?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"530"},"sequenceIndex":991},{"id":"plato-the-repu-531","text":"And the unjust man will strive and struggle to obtain more than the\r unjust man or action, in order that he may have more than all?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"531"},"sequenceIndex":992},{"id":"plato-the-repu-532","text":"We may put the matter thus, I said—the just does not desire more than\r his like but more than his unlike, whereas the unjust desires more than\r both his like and his unlike?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"532"},"sequenceIndex":993},{"id":"plato-the-repu-533","text":"Of course, he said, he who is of a certain nature, is like those who\r are of a certain nature; he who is not, not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"533"},"sequenceIndex":994},{"id":"plato-the-repu-534","text":"Very good, Thrasymachus, I said; and now to take the case of the arts:\r you would admit that one man is a musician and another not a musician?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"534"},"sequenceIndex":995},{"id":"plato-the-repu-535","text":"And do you think, my excellent friend, that a musician when he adjusts\r the lyre would desire or claim to exceed or go beyond a musician in the\r tightening and loosening the strings?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"535"},"sequenceIndex":996},{"id":"plato-the-repu-536","text":"And what would you say of the physician? In prescribing meats and\r drinks would he wish to go beyond another physician or beyond the\r practice of medicine?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"536"},"sequenceIndex":997},{"id":"plato-the-repu-537","text":"And about knowledge and ignorance in general; see whether you think\r that any man who has knowledge ever would wish to have the choice of\r saying or doing more than another man who has knowledge. Would he not\r rather say or do the same as his like in the same case?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"537"},"sequenceIndex":998},{"id":"plato-the-repu-538","text":"And what of the ignorant? would he not desire to have more than either\r the knowing or the ignorant?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"538"},"sequenceIndex":999},{"id":"plato-the-repu-539","text":"Then the wise and good will not desire to gain more than his like, but\r more than his unlike and opposite?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"539"},"sequenceIndex":1000},{"id":"plato-the-repu-540","text":"But did we not say, Thrasymachus, that the unjust goes beyond both his\r like and unlike? Were not these your words?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"540"},"sequenceIndex":1001},{"id":"plato-the-repu-541","text":"Then the just is like the wise and good, and the unjust like the evil\r and ignorant?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"541"},"sequenceIndex":1002},{"id":"plato-the-repu-542","text":"Then the just has turned out to be wise and good and the unjust evil\r and ignorant.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"542"},"sequenceIndex":1003},{"id":"plato-the-repu-543","text":"Thrasymachus made all these admissions, not fluently, as I repeat them,\r but with extreme reluctance; it was a hot summer’s day, and the\r perspiration poured from him in torrents; and then I saw what I had\r never seen before, Thrasymachus blushing. As we were now agreed that\r justice was virtue and wisdom, and injustice vice and ignorance, I\r proceeded to another point:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"543"},"sequenceIndex":1004},{"id":"plato-the-repu-544","text":"Well, I said, Thrasymachus, that matter is now settled; but were we not\r also saying that injustice had strength; do you remember?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"544"},"sequenceIndex":1005},{"id":"plato-the-repu-545","text":"Yes, I remember, he said, but do not suppose that I approve of what you\r are saying or have no answer; if however I were to answer, you would be\r quite certain to accuse me of haranguing; therefore either permit me to\r have my say out, or if you would rather ask, do so, and I will answer\r ‘Very good,’ as they say to story-telling old women, and will nod ‘Yes’\r and ‘No.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"545"},"sequenceIndex":1006},{"id":"plato-the-repu-546","text":"Yes, he said, I will, to please you, since you will not let me speak.\r What else would you have?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"546"},"sequenceIndex":1007},{"id":"plato-the-repu-547","text":"Nothing in the world, I said; and if you are so disposed I will ask and\r you shall answer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"547"},"sequenceIndex":1008},{"id":"plato-the-repu-548","text":"Then I will repeat the question which I asked before, in order that our\r examination of the relative nature of justice and injustice may be\r carried on regularly. A statement was made that injustice is stronger\r and more powerful than justice, but now justice, having been identified\r with wisdom and virtue, is easily shown to be stronger than injustice,\r if injustice is ignorance; this can no longer be questioned by any one.\r But I want to view the matter, Thrasymachus, in a different way: You\r would not deny that a state may be unjust and may be unjustly\r attempting to enslave other states, o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"548"},"sequenceIndex":1009},{"id":"plato-the-repu-549","text":"True, he replied; and I will add that the best and most perfectly\r unjust state will be most likely to do so.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"549"},"sequenceIndex":1010},{"id":"plato-the-repu-550","text":"I know, I said, that such was your position; but what I would further\r consider is, whether this power which is possessed by the superior\r state can exist or be exercised without justice or only with justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"550"},"sequenceIndex":1011},{"id":"plato-the-repu-551","text":"If you are right in your view, and justice is wisdom, then only with\r justice; but if I am right, then without justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"551"},"sequenceIndex":1012},{"id":"plato-the-repu-552","text":"I am delighted, Thrasymachus, to see you not only nodding assent and\r dissent, but making answers which are quite excellent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"552"},"sequenceIndex":1013},{"id":"plato-the-repu-553","text":"You are very kind, I said; and would you have the goodness also to\r inform me, whether you think that a state, or an army, or a band of\r robbers and thieves, or any other gang of evil-doers could act at all\r if they injured one another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"553"},"sequenceIndex":1014},{"id":"plato-the-repu-554","text":"But if they abstained from injuring one another, then they might act\r together better?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"554"},"sequenceIndex":1015},{"id":"plato-the-repu-555","text":"And this is because injustice creates divisions and hatreds and\r fighting, and justice imparts harmony and friendship; is not that true,\r Thrasymachus?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"555"},"sequenceIndex":1016},{"id":"plato-the-repu-556","text":"How good of you, I said; but I should like to know also whether\r injustice, having this tendency to arouse hatred, wherever existing,\r among slaves or among freemen, will not make them hate one another and\r set them at variance and render them incapable of common action?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"556"},"sequenceIndex":1017},{"id":"plato-the-repu-557","text":"And even if injustice be found in two only, will they not quarrel and\r fight, and become enemies to one another and to the just?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"557"},"sequenceIndex":1018},{"id":"plato-the-repu-558","text":"And suppose injustice abiding in a single person, would your wisdom say\r that she loses or that she retains her natural power?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"558"},"sequenceIndex":1019},{"id":"plato-the-repu-559","text":"Yet is not the power which injustice exercises of such a nature that\r wherever she takes up her abode, whether in a city, in an army, in a\r family, or in any other body, that body is, to begin with, rendered\r incapable of united action by reason of sedition and distraction; and\r does it not become its own enemy and at variance with all that opposes\r it, and with the just? Is not this the case?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"559"},"sequenceIndex":1020},{"id":"plato-the-repu-560","text":"And is not injustice equally fatal when existing in a single person; in\r the first place rendering him incapable of action because he is not at\r unity with himself, and in the second place making him an enemy to\r himself and the just? Is not that true, Thrasymachus?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"560"},"sequenceIndex":1021},{"id":"plato-the-repu-561","text":"But if so, the unjust will be the enemy of the gods, and the just will\r be their friend?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"561"},"sequenceIndex":1022},{"id":"plato-the-repu-562","text":"Feast away in triumph, and take your fill of the argument; I will not\r oppose you, lest I should displease the company.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"562"},"sequenceIndex":1023},{"id":"plato-the-repu-563","text":"Well then, proceed with your answers, and let me have the remainder of\r my repast. For we have already shown that the just are clearly wiser\r and better and abler than the unjust, and that the unjust are incapable\r of common action; nay more, that to speak as we did of men who are evil\r acting at any time vigorously together, is not strictly true, for if\r they had been perfectly evil, they would have laid hands upon one\r another; but it is evident that there must have been some remnant of\r justice in them, which enabled them to combine; if there had not been\r they would have injured one anothe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"563"},"sequenceIndex":1024},{"id":"plato-the-repu-564","text":"I will proceed by asking a question: Would you not say that a horse has\r some end?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"564"},"sequenceIndex":1025},{"id":"plato-the-repu-565","text":"And the end or use of a horse or of anything would be that which could\r not be accomplished, or not so well accomplished, by any other thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"565"},"sequenceIndex":1026},{"id":"plato-the-repu-566","text":"But you can cut off a vine-branch with a dagger or with a chisel, and\r in many other ways?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"566"},"sequenceIndex":1027},{"id":"plato-the-repu-567","text":"Then now I think you will have no difficulty in understanding my\r meaning when I asked the question whether the end of anything would be\r that which could not be accomplished, or not so well accomplished, by\r any other thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"567"},"sequenceIndex":1028},{"id":"plato-the-repu-568","text":"And that to which an end is appointed has also an excellence? Need I\r ask again whether the eye has an end?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"568"},"sequenceIndex":1029},{"id":"plato-the-repu-569","text":"And the same is true of all other things; they have each of them an end\r and a special excellence?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"569"},"sequenceIndex":1030},{"id":"plato-the-repu-570","text":"Well, and can the eyes fulfil their end if they are wanting in their\r own proper excellence and have a defect instead?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"570"},"sequenceIndex":1031},{"id":"plato-the-repu-571","text":"You mean to say, if they have lost their proper excellence, which is\r sight; but I have not arrived at that point yet. I would rather ask the\r question more generally, and only enquire whether the things which\r fulfil their ends fulfil them by their own proper excellence, and fail\r of fulfilling them by their own defect?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"571"},"sequenceIndex":1032},{"id":"plato-the-repu-572","text":"I might say the same of the ears; when deprived of their own proper\r excellence they cannot fulfil their end?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"572"},"sequenceIndex":1033},{"id":"plato-the-repu-573","text":"Well; and has not the soul an end which nothing else can fulfil? for\r example, to superintend and command and deliberate and the like. Are\r not these functions proper to the soul, and can they rightly be\r assigned to any other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"573"},"sequenceIndex":1034},{"id":"plato-the-repu-574","text":"And can she or can she not fulfil her own ends when deprived of that\r excellence?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"574"},"sequenceIndex":1035},{"id":"plato-the-repu-575","text":"Then an evil soul must necessarily be an evil ruler and superintendent,\r and the good soul a good ruler?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"575"},"sequenceIndex":1036},{"id":"plato-the-repu-576","text":"And we have admitted that justice is the excellence of the soul, and\r injustice the defect of the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"576"},"sequenceIndex":1037},{"id":"plato-the-repu-577","text":"Then the just soul and the just man will live well, and the unjust man\r will live ill?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"577"},"sequenceIndex":1038},{"id":"plato-the-repu-578","text":"And he who lives well is blessed and happy, and he who lives ill the\r reverse of happy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"578"},"sequenceIndex":1039},{"id":"plato-the-repu-579","text":"Then, my blessed Thrasymachus, injustice can never be more profitable\r than justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"579"},"sequenceIndex":1040},{"id":"plato-the-repu-580","text":"For which I am indebted to you, I said, now that you have grown gentle\r towards me and have left off scolding. Nevertheless, I have not been\r well entertained; but that was my own fault and not yours. As an\r epicure snatches a taste of every dish which is successively brought to\r table, he not having allowed himself time to enjoy the one before, so\r have I gone from one subject to another without having discovered what\r I sought at first, the nature of justice. I left that enquiry and\r turned away to consider whether justice is virtue and wisdom or evil\r and folly; and when there arose a furth","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"580"},"sequenceIndex":1041},{"id":"plato-the-repu-581","text":"With these words I was thinking that I had made an end of the\r discussion; but the end, in truth, proved to be only a beginning. For\r Glaucon, who is always the most pugnacious of men, was dissatisfied at\r Thrasymachus’ retirement; he wanted to have the battle out. So he said\r to me: Socrates, do you wish really to persuade us, or only to seem to\r have persuaded us, that to be just is always better than to be unjust?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"581"},"sequenceIndex":1042},{"id":"plato-the-repu-582","text":"Then you certainly have not succeeded. Let me ask you now:—How would\r you arrange goods—are there not some which we welcome for their own\r sakes, and independently of their consequences, as, for example,\r harmless pleasures and enjoyments, which delight us at the time,\r although nothing follows from them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"582"},"sequenceIndex":1043},{"id":"plato-the-repu-583","text":"Is there not also a second class of goods, such as knowledge, sight,\r health, which are desirable not only in themselves, but also for their\r results?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"583"},"sequenceIndex":1044},{"id":"plato-the-repu-584","text":"And would you not recognize a third class, such as gymnastic, and the\r care of the sick, and the physician’s art; also the various ways of\r money-making—these do us good but we regard them as disagreeable; and\r no one would choose them for their own sakes, but only for the sake of\r some reward or result which flows from them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"584"},"sequenceIndex":1045},{"id":"plato-the-repu-585","text":"In the highest class, I replied,—among those goods which he who would\r be happy desires both for their own sake and for the sake of their\r results.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"585"},"sequenceIndex":1046},{"id":"plato-the-repu-586","text":"Then the many are of another mind; they think that justice is to be\r reckoned in the troublesome class, among goods which are to be pursued\r for the sake of rewards and of reputation, but in themselves are\r disagreeable and rather to be avoided.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"586"},"sequenceIndex":1047},{"id":"plato-the-repu-587","text":"I know, I said, that this is their manner of thinking, and that this\r was the thesis which Thrasymachus was maintaining just now, when he\r censured justice and praised injustice. But I am too stupid to be\r convinced by him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"587"},"sequenceIndex":1048},{"id":"plato-the-repu-588","text":"I wish, he said, that you would hear me as well as him, and then I\r shall see whether you and I agree. For Thrasymachus seems to me, like a\r snake, to have been charmed by your voice sooner than he ought to have\r been; but to my mind the nature of justice and injustice have not yet\r been made clear. Setting aside their rewards and results, I want to\r know what they are in themselves, and how they inwardly work in the\r soul. If you, please, then, I will revive the argument of Thrasymachus.\r And first I will speak of the nature and origin of justice according to\r the common view of them. Secondl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"588"},"sequenceIndex":1049},{"id":"plato-the-repu-589","text":"Indeed I do; nor can I imagine any theme about which a man of sense\r would oftener wish to converse.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"589"},"sequenceIndex":1050},{"id":"plato-the-repu-590","text":"I am delighted, he replied, to hear you say so, and shall begin by\r speaking, as I proposed, of the nature and origin of justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"590"},"sequenceIndex":1051},{"id":"plato-the-repu-591","text":"They say that to do injustice is, by nature, good; to suffer injustice,\r evil; but that the evil is greater than the good. And so when men have\r both done and suffered injustice and have had experience of both, not\r being able to avoid the one and obtain the other, they think that they\r had better agree among themselves to have neither; hence there arise\r laws and mutual covenants; and that which is ordained by law is termed\r by them lawful and just. This they affirm to be the origin and nature\r of justice;—it is a mean or compromise, between the best of all, which\r is to do injustice and not ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"591"},"sequenceIndex":1052},{"id":"plato-the-repu-592","text":"Now that those who practise justice do so involuntarily and because\r they have not the power to be unjust will best appear if we imagine\r something of this kind: having given both to the just and the unjust\r power to do what they will, let us watch and see whither desire will\r lead them; then we shall discover in the very act the just and unjust\r man to be proceeding along the same road, following their interest,\r which all natures deem to be their good, and are only diverted into the\r path of justice by the force of law. The liberty which we are supposing\r may be most completely given to them","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"592"},"sequenceIndex":1053},{"id":"plato-the-repu-593","text":"Now, if we are to form a real judgment of the life of the just and\r unjust, we must isolate them; there is no other way; and how is the\r isolation to be effected? I answer: Let the unjust man be entirely\r unjust, and the just man entirely just; nothing is to be taken away\r from either of them, and both are to be perfectly furnished for the\r work of their respective lives. First, let the unjust be like other\r distinguished masters of craft; like the skilful pilot or physician,\r who knows intuitively his own powers and keeps within their limits, and\r who, if he fails at any point, is able to rec","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"593"},"sequenceIndex":1054},{"id":"plato-the-repu-594","text":"Heavens! my dear Glaucon, I said, how energetically you polish them up\r for the decision, first one and then the other, as if they were two\r statues.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"594"},"sequenceIndex":1055},{"id":"plato-the-repu-595","text":"I do my best, he said. And now that we know what they are like there is\r no difficulty in tracing out the sort of life which awaits either of\r them. This I will proceed to describe; but as you may think the\r description a little too coarse, I ask you to suppose, Socrates, that\r the words which follow are not mine.—Let me put them into the mouths of\r the eulogists of injustice: They will tell you that the just man who is\r thought unjust will be scourged, racked, bound—will have his eyes burnt\r out; and, at last, after suffering every kind of evil, he will be\r impaled: Then he will understand th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"595"},"sequenceIndex":1056},{"id":"plato-the-repu-596","text":"‘His mind has a soil deep and fertile, Out of which spring his prudent\r counsels.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"596"},"sequenceIndex":1057},{"id":"plato-the-repu-597","text":"In the first place, he is thought just, and therefore bears rule in the\r city; he can marry whom he will, and give in marriage to whom he will;\r also he can trade and deal where he likes, and always to his own\r advantage, because he has no misgivings about injustice; and at every\r contest, whether in public or private, he gets the better of his\r antagonists, and gains at their expense, and is rich, and out of his\r gains he can benefit his friends, and harm his enemies; moreover, he\r can offer sacrifices, and dedicate gifts to the gods abundantly and\r magnificently, and can honour the gods or a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"597"},"sequenceIndex":1058},{"id":"plato-the-repu-598","text":"I was going to say something in answer to Glaucon, when Adeimantus, his\r brother, interposed: Socrates, he said, you do not suppose that there\r is nothing more to be urged?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"598"},"sequenceIndex":1059},{"id":"plato-the-repu-599","text":"Well, then, according to the proverb, ‘Let brother help brother’—if he\r fails in any part do you assist him; although I must confess that\r Glaucon has already said quite enough to lay me in the dust, and take\r from me the power of helping justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"599"},"sequenceIndex":1060},{"id":"plato-the-repu-600","text":"Nonsense, he replied. But let me add something more: There is another\r side to Glaucon’s argument about the praise and censure of justice and\r injustice, which is equally required in order to bring out what I\r believe to be his meaning. Parents and tutors are always telling their\r sons and their wards that they are to be just; but why? not for the\r sake of justice, but for the sake of character and reputation; in the\r hope of obtaining for him who is reputed just some of those offices,\r marriages, and the like which Glaucon has enumerated among the\r advantages accruing to the unjust from the r","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"600"},"sequenceIndex":1061},{"id":"plato-the-repu-601","text":"‘To bear acorns at their summit, and bees in the middle;\r And the sheep are bowed down with the weight of their fleeces,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"601"},"sequenceIndex":1062},{"id":"plato-the-repu-602","text":"and many other blessings of a like kind are provided for them. And\r Homer has a very similar strain; for he speaks of one whose fame is—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"602"},"sequenceIndex":1063},{"id":"plato-the-repu-603","text":"‘As the fame of some blameless king who, like a god, Maintains justice;\r to whom the black earth brings forth Wheat and barley, whose trees are\r bowed with fruit, And his sheep never fail to bear, and the sea gives\r him fish.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"603"},"sequenceIndex":1064},{"id":"plato-the-repu-604","text":"Still grander are the gifts of heaven which Musaeus and his son\r vouchsafe to the just; they take them down into the world below, where\r they have the saints lying on couches at a feast, everlastingly drunk,\r crowned with garlands; their idea seems to be that an immortality of\r drunkenness is the highest meed of virtue. Some extend their rewards\r yet further; the posterity, as they say, of the faithful and just shall\r survive to the third and fourth generation. This is the style in which\r they praise justice. But about the wicked there is another strain; they\r bury them in a slough in Hades, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"604"},"sequenceIndex":1065},{"id":"plato-the-repu-605","text":"Once more, Socrates, I will ask you to consider another way of speaking\r about justice and injustice, which is not confined to the poets, but is\r found in prose writers. The universal voice of mankind is always\r declaring that justice and virtue are honourable, but grievous and\r toilsome; and that the pleasures of vice and injustice are easy of\r attainment, and are only censured by law and opinion. They say also\r that honesty is for the most part less profitable than dishonesty; and\r they are quite ready to call wicked men happy, and to honour them both\r in public and private when they are ric","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"605"},"sequenceIndex":1066},{"id":"plato-the-repu-606","text":"‘Vice may be had in abundance without trouble; the way is smooth and\r her dwelling-place is near. But before virtue the gods have set toil,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"606"},"sequenceIndex":1067},{"id":"plato-the-repu-607","text":"and a tedious and uphill road: then citing Homer as a witness that the\r gods may be influenced by men; for he also says:—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"607"},"sequenceIndex":1068},{"id":"plato-the-repu-608","text":"‘The gods, too, may be turned from their purpose; and men pray to them\r and avert their wrath by sacrifices and soothing entreaties, and by\r libations and the odour of fat, when they have sinned and\r transgressed.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"608"},"sequenceIndex":1069},{"id":"plato-the-repu-609","text":"And they produce a host of books written by Musaeus and Orpheus, who\r were children of the Moon and the Muses—that is what they say—according\r to which they perform their ritual, and persuade not only individuals,\r but whole cities, that expiations and atonements for sin may be made by\r sacrifices and amusements which fill a vacant hour, and are equally at\r the service of the living and the dead; the latter sort they call\r mysteries, and they redeem us from the pains of hell, but if we neglect\r them no one knows what awaits us.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"609"},"sequenceIndex":1070},{"id":"plato-the-repu-610","text":"He proceeded: And now when the young hear all this said about virtue\r and vice, and the way in which gods and men regard them, how are their\r minds likely to be affected, my dear Socrates,—those of them, I mean,\r who are quickwitted, and, like bees on the wing, light on every flower,\r and from all that they hear are prone to draw conclusions as to what\r manner of persons they should be and in what way they should walk if\r they would make the best of life? Probably the youth will say to\r himself in the words of Pindar—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"610"},"sequenceIndex":1071},{"id":"plato-the-repu-611","text":"‘Can I by justice or by crooked ways of deceit ascend a loftier tower\r which may be a fortress to me all my days?’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"611"},"sequenceIndex":1072},{"id":"plato-the-repu-612","text":"For what men say is that, if I am really just and am not also thought\r just profit there is none, but the pain and loss on the other hand are\r unmistakeable. But if, though unjust, I acquire the reputation of\r justice, a heavenly life is promised to me. Since then, as philosophers\r prove, appearance tyrannizes over truth and is lord of happiness, to\r appearance I must devote myself. I will describe around me a picture\r and shadow of virtue to be the vestibule and exterior of my house;\r behind I will trail the subtle and crafty fox, as Archilochus, greatest\r of sages, recommends. But I hear som","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"612"},"sequenceIndex":1073},{"id":"plato-the-repu-613","text":"On what principle, then, shall we any longer choose justice rather than\r the worst injustice? when, if we only unite the latter with a deceitful\r regard to appearances, we shall fare to our mind both with gods and\r men, in life and after death, as the most numerous and the highest\r authorities tell us. Knowing all this, Socrates, how can a man who has\r any superiority of mind or person or rank or wealth, be willing to\r honour justice; or indeed to refrain from laughing when he hears\r justice praised? And even if there should be some one who is able to\r disprove the truth of my words, and who i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"613"},"sequenceIndex":1074},{"id":"plato-the-repu-614","text":"The cause of all this, Socrates, was indicated by us at the beginning\r of the argument, when my brother and I told you how astonished we were\r to find that of all the professing panegyrists of justice—beginning\r with the ancient heroes of whom any memorial has been preserved to us,\r and ending with the men of our own time—no one has ever blamed\r injustice or praised justice except with a view to the glories,\r honours, and benefits which flow from them. No one has ever adequately\r described either in verse or prose the true essential nature of either\r of them abiding in the soul, and invisible ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"614"},"sequenceIndex":1075},{"id":"plato-the-repu-615","text":"I had always admired the genius of Glaucon and Adeimantus, but on\r hearing these words I was quite delighted, and said: Sons of an\r illustrious father, that was not a bad beginning of the Elegiac verses\r which the admirer of Glaucon made in honour of you after you had\r distinguished yourselves at the battle of Megara:—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"615"},"sequenceIndex":1076},{"id":"plato-the-repu-616","text":"The epithet is very appropriate, for there is something truly divine in\r being able to argue as you have done for the superiority of injustice,\r and remaining unconvinced by your own arguments. And I do believe that\r you are not convinced—this I infer from your general character, for had\r I judged only from your speeches I should have mistrusted you. But now,\r the greater my confidence in you, the greater is my difficulty in\r knowing what to say. For I am in a strait between two; on the one hand\r I feel that I am unequal to the task; and my inability is brought home\r to me by the fact that you","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"616"},"sequenceIndex":1077},{"id":"plato-the-repu-617","text":"Glaucon and the rest entreated me by all means not to let the question\r drop, but to proceed in the investigation. They wanted to arrive at the\r truth, first, about the nature of justice and injustice, and secondly,\r about their relative advantages. I told them, what I really thought,\r that the enquiry would be of a serious nature, and would require very\r good eyes. Seeing then, I said, that we are no great wits, I think that\r we had better adopt a method which I may illustrate thus; suppose that\r a short-sighted person had been asked by some one to read small letters\r from a distance; and it ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"617"},"sequenceIndex":1078},{"id":"plato-the-repu-618","text":"Very true, said Adeimantus; but how does the illustration apply to our\r enquiry?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"618"},"sequenceIndex":1079},{"id":"plato-the-repu-619","text":"I will tell you, I replied; justice, which is the subject of our\r enquiry, is, as you know, sometimes spoken of as the virtue of an\r individual, and sometimes as the virtue of a State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"619"},"sequenceIndex":1080},{"id":"plato-the-repu-620","text":"Then in the larger the quantity of justice is likely to be larger and\r more easily discernible. I propose therefore that we enquire into the\r nature of justice and injustice, first as they appear in the State, and\r secondly in the individual, proceeding from the greater to the lesser\r and comparing them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"620"},"sequenceIndex":1081},{"id":"plato-the-repu-621","text":"And if we imagine the State in process of creation, we shall see the\r justice and injustice of the State in process of creation also.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"621"},"sequenceIndex":1082},{"id":"plato-the-repu-622","text":"When the State is completed there may be a hope that the object of our\r search will be more easily discovered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"622"},"sequenceIndex":1083},{"id":"plato-the-repu-623","text":"But ought we to attempt to construct one? I said; for to do so, as I am\r inclined to think, will be a very serious task. Reflect therefore.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"623"},"sequenceIndex":1084},{"id":"plato-the-repu-624","text":"A State, I said, arises, as I conceive, out of the needs of mankind; no\r one is self-sufficing, but all of us have many wants. Can any other\r origin of a State be imagined?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"624"},"sequenceIndex":1085},{"id":"plato-the-repu-625","text":"Then, as we have many wants, and many persons are needed to supply\r them, one takes a helper for one purpose and another for another; and\r when these partners and helpers are gathered together in one habitation\r the body of inhabitants is termed a State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"625"},"sequenceIndex":1086},{"id":"plato-the-repu-626","text":"And they exchange with one another, and one gives, and another\r receives, under the idea that the exchange will be for their good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"626"},"sequenceIndex":1087},{"id":"plato-the-repu-627","text":"Then, I said, let us begin and create in idea a State; and yet the true\r creator is necessity, who is the mother of our invention.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"627"},"sequenceIndex":1088},{"id":"plato-the-repu-628","text":"Now the first and greatest of necessities is food, which is the\r condition of life and existence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"628"},"sequenceIndex":1089},{"id":"plato-the-repu-629","text":"And now let us see how our city will be able to supply this great\r demand: We may suppose that one man is a husbandman, another a builder,\r some one else a weaver—shall we add to them a shoemaker, or perhaps\r some other purveyor to our bodily wants?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"629"},"sequenceIndex":1090},{"id":"plato-the-repu-630","text":"And how will they proceed? Will each bring the result of his labours\r into a common stock?—the individual husbandman, for example, producing\r for four, and labouring four times as long and as much as he need in\r the provision of food with which he supplies others as well as himself;\r or will he have nothing to do with others and not be at the trouble of\r producing for them, but provide for himself alone a fourth of the food\r in a fourth of the time, and in the remaining three fourths of his time\r be employed in making a house or a coat or a pair of shoes, having no\r partnership with others, bu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"630"},"sequenceIndex":1091},{"id":"plato-the-repu-631","text":"Adeimantus thought that he should aim at producing food only and not at\r producing everything.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"631"},"sequenceIndex":1092},{"id":"plato-the-repu-632","text":"Probably, I replied, that would be the better way; and when I hear you\r say this, I am myself reminded that we are not all alike; there are\r diversities of natures among us which are adapted to different\r occupations.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"632"},"sequenceIndex":1093},{"id":"plato-the-repu-633","text":"And will you have a work better done when the workman has many\r occupations, or when he has only one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"633"},"sequenceIndex":1094},{"id":"plato-the-repu-634","text":"Further, there can be no doubt that a work is spoilt when not done at\r the right time?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"634"},"sequenceIndex":1095},{"id":"plato-the-repu-635","text":"For business is not disposed to wait until the doer of the business is\r at leisure; but the doer must follow up what he is doing, and make the\r business his first object.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"635"},"sequenceIndex":1096},{"id":"plato-the-repu-636","text":"And if so, we must infer that all things are produced more plentifully\r and easily and of a better quality when one man does one thing which is\r natural to him and does it at the right time, and leaves other things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"636"},"sequenceIndex":1097},{"id":"plato-the-repu-637","text":"Then more than four citizens will be required; for the husbandman will\r not make his own plough or mattock, or other implements of agriculture,\r if they are to be good for anything. Neither will the builder make his\r tools—and he too needs many; and in like manner the weaver and\r shoemaker.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"637"},"sequenceIndex":1098},{"id":"plato-the-repu-638","text":"Then carpenters, and smiths, and many other artisans, will be sharers\r in our little State, which is already beginning to grow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"638"},"sequenceIndex":1099},{"id":"plato-the-repu-639","text":"Yet even if we add neatherds, shepherds, and other herdsmen, in order\r that our husbandmen may have oxen to plough with, and builders as well\r as husbandmen may have draught cattle, and curriers and weavers fleeces\r and hides,—still our State will not be very large.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"639"},"sequenceIndex":1100},{"id":"plato-the-repu-640","text":"That is true; yet neither will it be a very small State which contains\r all these.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"640"},"sequenceIndex":1101},{"id":"plato-the-repu-641","text":"Then, again, there is the situation of the city—to find a place where\r nothing need be imported is wellnigh impossible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"641"},"sequenceIndex":1102},{"id":"plato-the-repu-642","text":"Then there must be another class of citizens who will bring the\r required supply from another city?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"642"},"sequenceIndex":1103},{"id":"plato-the-repu-643","text":"But if the trader goes empty-handed, having nothing which they require\r who would supply his need, he will come back empty-handed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"643"},"sequenceIndex":1104},{"id":"plato-the-repu-644","text":"And therefore what they produce at home must be not only enough for\r themselves, but such both in quantity and quality as to accommodate\r those from whom their wants are supplied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"644"},"sequenceIndex":1105},{"id":"plato-the-repu-645","text":"And if merchandise is to be carried over the sea, skilful sailors will\r also be needed, and in considerable numbers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"645"},"sequenceIndex":1106},{"id":"plato-the-repu-646","text":"Then, again, within the city, how will they exchange their productions?\r To secure such an exchange was, as you will remember, one of our\r principal objects when we formed them into a society and constituted a\r State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"646"},"sequenceIndex":1107},{"id":"plato-the-repu-647","text":"Then they will need a market-place, and a money-token for purposes of\r exchange.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"647"},"sequenceIndex":1108},{"id":"plato-the-repu-648","text":"Suppose now that a husbandman, or an artisan, brings some production to\r market, and he comes at a time when there is no one to exchange with\r him,—is he to leave his calling and sit idle in the market-place?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"648"},"sequenceIndex":1109},{"id":"plato-the-repu-649","text":"Not at all; he will find people there who, seeing the want, undertake\r the office of salesmen. In well-ordered states they are commonly those\r who are the weakest in bodily strength, and therefore of little use for\r any other purpose; their duty is to be in the market, and to give money\r in exchange for goods to those who desire to sell and to take money\r from those who desire to buy.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"649"},"sequenceIndex":1110},{"id":"plato-the-repu-650","text":"This want, then, creates a class of retail-traders in our State. Is not\r ‘retailer’ the term which is applied to those who sit in the\r market-place engaged in buying and selling, while those who wander from\r one city to another are called merchants?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"650"},"sequenceIndex":1111},{"id":"plato-the-repu-651","text":"And there is another class of servants, who are intellectually hardly\r on the level of companionship; still they have plenty of bodily\r strength for labour, which accordingly they sell, and are called, if I\r do not mistake, hirelings, hire being the name which is given to the\r price of their labour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"651"},"sequenceIndex":1112},{"id":"plato-the-repu-652","text":"Where, then, is justice, and where is injustice, and in what part of\r the State did they spring up?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"652"},"sequenceIndex":1113},{"id":"plato-the-repu-653","text":"Probably in the dealings of these citizens with one another. I cannot\r imagine that they are more likely to be found any where else.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"653"},"sequenceIndex":1114},{"id":"plato-the-repu-654","text":"I dare say that you are right in your suggestion, I said; we had better\r think the matter out, and not shrink from the enquiry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"654"},"sequenceIndex":1115},{"id":"plato-the-repu-655","text":"Let us then consider, first of all, what will be their way of life, now\r that we have thus established them. Will they not produce corn, and\r wine, and clothes, and shoes, and build houses for themselves? And when\r they are housed, they will work, in summer, commonly, stripped and\r barefoot, but in winter substantially clothed and shod. They will feed\r on barley-meal and flour of wheat, baking and kneading them, making\r noble cakes and loaves; these they will serve up on a mat of reeds or\r on clean leaves, themselves reclining the while upon beds strewn with\r yew or myrtle. And they and their ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"655"},"sequenceIndex":1116},{"id":"plato-the-repu-656","text":"But, said Glaucon, interposing, you have not given them a relish to\r their meal.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"656"},"sequenceIndex":1117},{"id":"plato-the-repu-657","text":"True, I replied, I had forgotten; of course they must have a\r relish—salt, and olives, and cheese, and they will boil roots and herbs\r such as country people prepare; for a dessert we shall give them figs,\r and peas, and beans; and they will roast myrtle-berries and acorns at\r the fire, drinking in moderation. And with such a diet they may be\r expected to live in peace and health to a good old age, and bequeath a\r similar life to their children after them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"657"},"sequenceIndex":1118},{"id":"plato-the-repu-658","text":"Yes, Socrates, he said, and if you were providing for a city of pigs,\r how else would you feed the beasts?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"658"},"sequenceIndex":1119},{"id":"plato-the-repu-659","text":"Why, he said, you should give them the ordinary conveniences of life.\r People who are to be comfortable are accustomed to lie on sofas, and\r dine off tables, and they should have sauces and sweets in the modern\r style.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"659"},"sequenceIndex":1120},{"id":"plato-the-repu-660","text":"Yes, I said, now I understand: the question which you would have me\r consider is, not only how a State, but how a luxurious State is\r created; and possibly there is no harm in this, for in such a State we\r shall be more likely to see how justice and injustice originate. In my\r opinion the true and healthy constitution of the State is the one which\r I have described. But if you wish also to see a State at fever-heat, I\r have no objection. For I suspect that many will not be satisfied with\r the simpler way of life. They will be for adding sofas, and tables, and\r other furniture; also dainties, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"660"},"sequenceIndex":1121},{"id":"plato-the-repu-661","text":"Then we must enlarge our borders; for the original healthy State is no\r longer sufficient. Now will the city have to fill and swell with a\r multitude of callings which are not required by any natural want; such\r as the whole tribe of hunters and actors, of whom one large class have\r to do with forms and colours; another will be the votaries of\r music—poets and their attendant train of rhapsodists, players, dancers,\r contractors; also makers of divers kinds of articles, including women’s\r dresses. And we shall want more servants. Will not tutors be also in\r request, and nurses wet and dry, tire","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"661"},"sequenceIndex":1122},{"id":"plato-the-repu-662","text":"And living in this way we shall have much greater need of physicians\r than before?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"662"},"sequenceIndex":1123},{"id":"plato-the-repu-663","text":"And the country which was enough to support the original inhabitants\r will be too small now, and not enough?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"663"},"sequenceIndex":1124},{"id":"plato-the-repu-664","text":"Then a slice of our neighbours’ land will be wanted by us for pasture\r and tillage, and they will want a slice of ours, if, like ourselves,\r they exceed the limit of necessity, and give themselves up to the\r unlimited accumulation of wealth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"664"},"sequenceIndex":1125},{"id":"plato-the-repu-665","text":"Then without determining as yet whether war does good or harm, thus\r much we may affirm, that now we have discovered war to be derived from\r causes which are also the causes of almost all the evils in States,\r private as well as public.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"665"},"sequenceIndex":1126},{"id":"plato-the-repu-666","text":"And our State must once more enlarge; and this time the enlargement\r will be nothing short of a whole army, which will have to go out and\r fight with the invaders for all that we have, as well as for the things\r and persons whom we were describing above.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"666"},"sequenceIndex":1127},{"id":"plato-the-repu-667","text":"No, I said; not if we were right in the principle which was\r acknowledged by all of us when we were framing the State: the\r principle, as you will remember, was that one man cannot practise many\r arts with success.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"667"},"sequenceIndex":1128},{"id":"plato-the-repu-668","text":"And the shoemaker was not allowed by us to be a husbandman, or a\r weaver, or a builder—in order that we might have our shoes well made;\r but to him and to every other worker was assigned one work for which he\r was by nature fitted, and at that he was to continue working all his\r life long and at no other; he was not to let opportunities slip, and\r then he would become a good workman. Now nothing can be more important\r than that the work of a soldier should be well done. But is war an art\r so easily acquired that a man may be a warrior who is also a\r husbandman, or shoemaker, or other artisan; ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"668"},"sequenceIndex":1129},{"id":"plato-the-repu-669","text":"Yes, he said, the tools which would teach men their own use would be\r beyond price.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"669"},"sequenceIndex":1130},{"id":"plato-the-repu-670","text":"And the higher the duties of the guardian, I said, the more time, and\r skill, and art, and application will be needed by him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"670"},"sequenceIndex":1131},{"id":"plato-the-repu-671","text":"Then it will be our duty to select, if we can, natures which are fitted\r for the task of guarding the city?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"671"},"sequenceIndex":1132},{"id":"plato-the-repu-672","text":"And the selection will be no easy matter, I said; but we must be brave\r and do our best.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"672"},"sequenceIndex":1133},{"id":"plato-the-repu-673","text":"Is not the noble youth very like a well-bred dog in respect of guarding\r and watching?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"673"},"sequenceIndex":1134},{"id":"plato-the-repu-674","text":"I mean that both of them ought to be quick to see, and swift to\r overtake the enemy when they see him; and strong too if, when they have\r caught him, they have to fight with him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"674"},"sequenceIndex":1135},{"id":"plato-the-repu-675","text":"And is he likely to be brave who has no spirit, whether horse or dog or\r any other animal? Have you never observed how invincible and\r unconquerable is spirit and how the presence of it makes the soul of\r any creature to be absolutely fearless and indomitable?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"675"},"sequenceIndex":1136},{"id":"plato-the-repu-676","text":"Then now we have a clear notion of the bodily qualities which are\r required in the guardian.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"676"},"sequenceIndex":1137},{"id":"plato-the-repu-677","text":"But are not these spirited natures apt to be savage with one another,\r and with everybody else?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"677"},"sequenceIndex":1138},{"id":"plato-the-repu-678","text":"Whereas, I said, they ought to be dangerous to their enemies, and\r gentle to their friends; if not, they will destroy themselves without\r waiting for their enemies to destroy them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"678"},"sequenceIndex":1139},{"id":"plato-the-repu-679","text":"What is to be done then? I said; how shall we find a gentle nature\r which has also a great spirit, for the one is the contradiction of the\r other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"679"},"sequenceIndex":1140},{"id":"plato-the-repu-680","text":"He will not be a good guardian who is wanting in either of these two\r qualities; and yet the combination of them appears to be impossible;\r and hence we must infer that to be a good guardian is impossible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"680"},"sequenceIndex":1141},{"id":"plato-the-repu-681","text":"Here feeling perplexed I began to think over what had preceded.—My\r friend, I said, no wonder that we are in a perplexity; for we have lost\r sight of the image which we had before us.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"681"},"sequenceIndex":1142},{"id":"plato-the-repu-682","text":"I mean to say that there do exist natures gifted with those opposite\r qualities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"682"},"sequenceIndex":1143},{"id":"plato-the-repu-683","text":"Many animals, I replied, furnish examples of them; our friend the dog\r is a very good one: you know that well-bred dogs are perfectly gentle\r to their familiars and acquaintances, and the reverse to strangers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"683"},"sequenceIndex":1144},{"id":"plato-the-repu-684","text":"Then there is nothing impossible or out of the order of nature in our\r finding a guardian who has a similar combination of qualities?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"684"},"sequenceIndex":1145},{"id":"plato-the-repu-685","text":"Would not he who is fitted to be a guardian, besides the spirited\r nature, need to have the qualities of a philosopher?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"685"},"sequenceIndex":1146},{"id":"plato-the-repu-686","text":"The trait of which I am speaking, I replied, may be also seen in the\r dog, and is remarkable in the animal.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"686"},"sequenceIndex":1147},{"id":"plato-the-repu-687","text":"Why, a dog, whenever he sees a stranger, is angry; when an\r acquaintance, he welcomes him, although the one has never done him any\r harm, nor the other any good. Did this never strike you as curious?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"687"},"sequenceIndex":1148},{"id":"plato-the-repu-688","text":"The matter never struck me before; but I quite recognise the truth of\r your remark.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"688"},"sequenceIndex":1149},{"id":"plato-the-repu-689","text":"And surely this instinct of the dog is very charming;—your dog is a\r true philosopher.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"689"},"sequenceIndex":1150},{"id":"plato-the-repu-690","text":"Why, because he distinguishes the face of a friend and of an enemy only\r by the criterion of knowing and not knowing. And must not an animal be\r a lover of learning who determines what he likes and dislikes by the\r test of knowledge and ignorance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"690"},"sequenceIndex":1151},{"id":"plato-the-repu-691","text":"And may we not say confidently of man also, that he who is likely to be\r gentle to his friends and acquaintances, must by nature be a lover of\r wisdom and knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"691"},"sequenceIndex":1152},{"id":"plato-the-repu-692","text":"Then he who is to be a really good and noble guardian of the State will\r require to unite in himself philosophy and spirit and swiftness and\r strength?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"692"},"sequenceIndex":1153},{"id":"plato-the-repu-693","text":"Then we have found the desired natures; and now that we have found\r them, how are they to be reared and educated? Is not this an enquiry\r which may be expected to throw light on the greater enquiry which is\r our final end—How do justice and injustice grow up in States? for we do\r not want either to omit what is to the point or to draw out the\r argument to an inconvenient length.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"693"},"sequenceIndex":1154},{"id":"plato-the-repu-694","text":"Then, I said, my dear friend, the task must not be given up, even if\r somewhat long.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"694"},"sequenceIndex":1155},{"id":"plato-the-repu-695","text":"Come then, and let us pass a leisure hour in story-telling, and our\r story shall be the education of our heroes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"695"},"sequenceIndex":1156},{"id":"plato-the-repu-696","text":"And what shall be their education? Can we find a better than the\r traditional sort?—and this has two divisions, gymnastic for the body,\r and music for the soul.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"696"},"sequenceIndex":1157},{"id":"plato-the-repu-697","text":"You know, I said, that we begin by telling children stories which,\r though not wholly destitute of truth, are in the main fictitious; and\r these stories are told them when they are not of an age to learn\r gymnastics.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"697"},"sequenceIndex":1158},{"id":"plato-the-repu-698","text":"You know also that the beginning is the most important part of any\r work, especially in the case of a young and tender thing; for that is\r the time at which the character is being formed and the desired\r impression is more readily taken.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"698"},"sequenceIndex":1159},{"id":"plato-the-repu-699","text":"And shall we just carelessly allow children to hear any casual tales\r which may be devised by casual persons, and to receive into their minds\r ideas for the most part the very opposite of those which we should wish\r them to have when they are grown up?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"699"},"sequenceIndex":1160},{"id":"plato-the-repu-700","text":"Then the first thing will be to establish a censorship of the writers\r of fiction, and let the censors receive any tale of fiction which is\r good, and reject the bad; and we will desire mothers and nurses to tell\r their children the authorised ones only. Let them fashion the mind with\r such tales, even more fondly than they mould the body with their hands;\r but most of those which are now in use must be discarded.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"700"},"sequenceIndex":1161},{"id":"plato-the-repu-701","text":"You may find a model of the lesser in the greater, I said; for they are\r necessarily of the same type, and there is the same spirit in both of\r them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"701"},"sequenceIndex":1162},{"id":"plato-the-repu-702","text":"Very likely, he replied; but I do not as yet know what you would term\r the greater.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"702"},"sequenceIndex":1163},{"id":"plato-the-repu-703","text":"Those, I said, which are narrated by Homer and Hesiod, and the rest of\r the poets, who have ever been the great story-tellers of mankind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"703"},"sequenceIndex":1164},{"id":"plato-the-repu-704","text":"A fault which is most serious, I said; the fault of telling a lie, and,\r what is more, a bad lie.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"704"},"sequenceIndex":1165},{"id":"plato-the-repu-705","text":"Whenever an erroneous representation is made of the nature of gods and\r heroes,—as when a painter paints a portrait not having the shadow of a\r likeness to the original.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"705"},"sequenceIndex":1166},{"id":"plato-the-repu-706","text":"Yes, he said, that sort of thing is certainly very blameable; but what\r are the stories which you mean?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"706"},"sequenceIndex":1167},{"id":"plato-the-repu-707","text":"First of all, I said, there was that greatest of all lies in high\r places, which the poet told about Uranus, and which was a bad lie\r too,—I mean what Hesiod says that Uranus did, and how Cronus retaliated\r on him. The doings of Cronus, and the sufferings which in turn his son\r inflicted upon him, even if they were true, ought certainly not to be\r lightly told to young and thoughtless persons; if possible, they had\r better be buried in silence. But if there is an absolute necessity for\r their mention, a chosen few might hear them in a mystery, and they\r should sacrifice not a common (Eleusinia","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"707"},"sequenceIndex":1168},{"id":"plato-the-repu-708","text":"Yes, Adeimantus, they are stories not to be repeated in our State; the\r young man should not be told that in committing the worst of crimes he\r is far from doing anything outrageous; and that even if he chastises\r his father when he does wrong, in whatever manner, he will only be\r following the example of the first and greatest among the gods.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"708"},"sequenceIndex":1169},{"id":"plato-the-repu-709","text":"I entirely agree with you, he said; in my opinion those stories are\r quite unfit to be repeated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"709"},"sequenceIndex":1170},{"id":"plato-the-repu-710","text":"Neither, if we mean our future guardians to regard the habit of\r quarrelling among themselves as of all things the basest, should any\r word be said to them of the wars in heaven, and of the plots and\r fightings of the gods against one another, for they are not true. No,\r we shall never mention the battles of the giants, or let them be\r embroidered on garments; and we shall be silent about the innumerable\r other quarrels of gods and heroes with their friends and relatives. If\r they would only believe us we would tell them that quarrelling is\r unholy, and that never up to this time has there bee","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"710"},"sequenceIndex":1171},{"id":"plato-the-repu-711","text":"There you are right, he replied; but if any one asks where are such\r models to be found and of what tales are you speaking—how shall we\r answer him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"711"},"sequenceIndex":1172},{"id":"plato-the-repu-712","text":"I said to him, You and I, Adeimantus, at this moment are not poets, but\r founders of a State: now the founders of a State ought to know the\r general forms in which poets should cast their tales, and the limits\r which must be observed by them, but to make the tales is not their\r business.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"712"},"sequenceIndex":1173},{"id":"plato-the-repu-713","text":"Something of this kind, I replied:—God is always to be represented as\r he truly is, whatever be the sort of poetry, epic, lyric or tragic, in\r which the representation is given.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"713"},"sequenceIndex":1174},{"id":"plato-the-repu-714","text":"It follows therefore that the good is not the cause of all things, but\r of the good only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"714"},"sequenceIndex":1175},{"id":"plato-the-repu-715","text":"Then God, if he be good, is not the author of all things, as the many\r assert, but he is the cause of a few things only, and not of most\r things that occur to men. For few are the goods of human life, and many\r are the evils, and the good is to be attributed to God alone; of the\r evils the causes are to be sought elsewhere, and not in him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"715"},"sequenceIndex":1176},{"id":"plato-the-repu-716","text":"Then we must not listen to Homer or to any other poet who is guilty of\r the folly of saying that two casks","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"716"},"sequenceIndex":1177},{"id":"plato-the-repu-717","text":"‘Lie at the threshold of Zeus, full of lots, one of good, the other of\r evil lots,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"717"},"sequenceIndex":1178},{"id":"plato-the-repu-718","text":"And if any one asserts that the violation of oaths and treaties, which\r was really the work of Pandarus, was brought about by Athene and Zeus,\r or that the strife and contention of the gods was instigated by Themis\r and Zeus, he shall not have our approval; neither will we allow our\r young men to hear the words of Aeschylus, that","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"718"},"sequenceIndex":1179},{"id":"plato-the-repu-719","text":"And if a poet writes of the sufferings of Niobe—the subject of the\r tragedy in which these iambic verses occur—or of the house of Pelops,\r or of the Trojan war or on any similar theme, either we must not permit\r him to say that these are the works of God, or if they are of God, he\r must devise some explanation of them such as we are seeking; he must\r say that God did what was just and right, and they were the better for\r being punished; but that those who are punished are miserable, and that\r God is the author of their misery—the poet is not to be permitted to\r say; though he may say that the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"719"},"sequenceIndex":1180},{"id":"plato-the-repu-720","text":"Let this then be one of our rules and principles concerning the gods,\r to which our poets and reciters will be expected to conform,—that God\r is not the author of all things, but of good only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"720"},"sequenceIndex":1181},{"id":"plato-the-repu-721","text":"And what do you think of a second principle? Shall I ask you whether\r God is a magician, and of a nature to appear insidiously now in one\r shape, and now in another—sometimes himself changing and passing into\r many forms, sometimes deceiving us with the semblance of such\r transformations; or is he one and the same immutably fixed in his own\r proper image?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"721"},"sequenceIndex":1182},{"id":"plato-the-repu-722","text":"Well, I said; but if we suppose a change in anything, that change must\r be effected either by the thing itself, or by some other thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"722"},"sequenceIndex":1183},{"id":"plato-the-repu-723","text":"And things which are at their best are also least liable to be altered\r or discomposed; for example, when healthiest and strongest, the human\r frame is least liable to be affected by meats and drinks, and the plant\r which is in the fullest vigour also suffers least from winds or the\r heat of the sun or any similar causes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"723"},"sequenceIndex":1184},{"id":"plato-the-repu-724","text":"And will not the bravest and wisest soul be least confused or deranged\r by any external influence?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"724"},"sequenceIndex":1185},{"id":"plato-the-repu-725","text":"And the same principle, as I should suppose, applies to all composite\r things—furniture, houses, garments: when good and well made, they are\r least altered by time and circumstances.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"725"},"sequenceIndex":1186},{"id":"plato-the-repu-726","text":"Then everything which is good, whether made by art or nature, or both,\r is least liable to suffer change from without?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"726"},"sequenceIndex":1187},{"id":"plato-the-repu-727","text":"And will he then change himself for the better and fairer, or for the\r worse and more unsightly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"727"},"sequenceIndex":1188},{"id":"plato-the-repu-728","text":"If he change at all he can only change for the worse, for we cannot\r suppose him to be deficient either in virtue or beauty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"728"},"sequenceIndex":1189},{"id":"plato-the-repu-729","text":"Very true, Adeimantus; but then, would any one, whether God or man,\r desire to make himself worse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"729"},"sequenceIndex":1190},{"id":"plato-the-repu-730","text":"Then it is impossible that God should ever be willing to change; being,\r as is supposed, the fairest and best that is conceivable, every God\r remains absolutely and for ever in his own form.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"730"},"sequenceIndex":1191},{"id":"plato-the-repu-731","text":"‘The gods, taking the disguise of strangers from other lands, walk up\r and down cities in all sorts of forms;’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"731"},"sequenceIndex":1192},{"id":"plato-the-repu-732","text":"and let no one slander Proteus and Thetis, neither let any one, either\r in tragedy or in any other kind of poetry, introduce Here disguised in\r the likeness of a priestess asking an alms","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"732"},"sequenceIndex":1193},{"id":"plato-the-repu-733","text":"—let us have no more lies of that sort. Neither must we have mothers\r under the influence of the poets scaring their children with a bad\r version of these myths—telling how certain gods, as they say, ‘Go about\r by night in the likeness of so many strangers and in divers forms;’ but\r let them take heed lest they make cowards of their children, and at the\r same time speak blasphemy against the gods.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"733"},"sequenceIndex":1194},{"id":"plato-the-repu-734","text":"But although the gods are themselves unchangeable, still by witchcraft\r and deception they may make us think that they appear in various forms?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"734"},"sequenceIndex":1195},{"id":"plato-the-repu-735","text":"Well, but can you imagine that God will be willing to lie, whether in\r word or deed, or to put forth a phantom of himself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"735"},"sequenceIndex":1196},{"id":"plato-the-repu-736","text":"Do you not know, I said, that the true lie, if such an expression may\r be allowed, is hated of gods and men?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"736"},"sequenceIndex":1197},{"id":"plato-the-repu-737","text":"I mean that no one is willingly deceived in that which is the truest\r and highest part of himself, or about the truest and highest matters;\r there, above all, he is most afraid of a lie having possession of him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"737"},"sequenceIndex":1198},{"id":"plato-the-repu-738","text":"The reason is, I replied, that you attribute some profound meaning to\r my words; but I am only saying that deception, or being deceived or\r uninformed about the highest realities in the highest part of\r themselves, which is the soul, and in that part of them to have and to\r hold the lie, is what mankind least like;—that, I say, is what they\r utterly detest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"738"},"sequenceIndex":1199},{"id":"plato-the-repu-739","text":"And, as I was just now remarking, this ignorance in the soul of him who\r is deceived may be called the true lie; for the lie in words is only a\r kind of imitation and shadowy image of a previous affection of the\r soul, not pure unadulterated falsehood. Am I not right?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"739"},"sequenceIndex":1200},{"id":"plato-the-repu-740","text":"Whereas the lie in words is in certain cases useful and not hateful; in\r dealing with enemies—that would be an instance; or again, when those\r whom we call our friends in a fit of madness or illusion are going to\r do some harm, then it is useful and is a sort of medicine or\r preventive; also in the tales of mythology, of which we were just now\r speaking—because we do not know the truth about ancient times, we make\r falsehood as much like truth as we can, and so turn it to account.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"740"},"sequenceIndex":1201},{"id":"plato-the-repu-741","text":"But can any of these reasons apply to God? Can we suppose that he is\r ignorant of antiquity, and therefore has recourse to invention?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"741"},"sequenceIndex":1202},{"id":"plato-the-repu-742","text":"Then is God perfectly simple and true both in word and deed; he changes\r not; he deceives not, either by sign or word, by dream or waking\r vision.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"742"},"sequenceIndex":1203},{"id":"plato-the-repu-743","text":"You agree with me then, I said, that this is the second type or form in\r which we should write and speak about divine things. The gods are not\r magicians who transform themselves, neither do they deceive mankind in\r any way.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"743"},"sequenceIndex":1204},{"id":"plato-the-repu-744","text":"Then, although we are admirers of Homer, we do not admire the lying\r dream which Zeus sends to Agamemnon; neither will we praise the verses\r of Aeschylus in which Thetis says that Apollo at her nuptials","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"744"},"sequenceIndex":1205},{"id":"plato-the-repu-745","text":"‘Was celebrating in song her fair progeny whose days were to be long,\r and to know no sickness. And when he had spoken of my lot as in all\r things blessed of heaven he raised a note of triumph and cheered my\r soul. And I thought that the word of Phoebus, being divine and full of\r prophecy, would not fail. And now he himself who uttered the strain, he\r who was present at the banquet, and who said this—he it is who has\r slain my son.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"745"},"sequenceIndex":1206},{"id":"plato-the-repu-746","text":"These are the kind of sentiments about the gods which will arouse our\r anger; and he who utters them shall be refused a chorus; neither shall\r we allow teachers to make use of them in the instruction of the young,\r meaning, as we do, that our guardians, as far as men can be, should be\r true worshippers of the gods and like them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"746"},"sequenceIndex":1207},{"id":"plato-the-repu-747","text":"I entirely agree, he said, in these principles, and promise to make\r them my laws.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"747"},"sequenceIndex":1208},{"id":"plato-the-repu-748","text":"Such then, I said, are our principles of theology—some tales are to be\r told, and others are not to be told to our disciples from their youth\r upwards, if we mean them to honour the gods and their parents, and to\r value friendship with one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"748"},"sequenceIndex":1209},{"id":"plato-the-repu-749","text":"But if they are to be courageous, must they not learn other lessons\r besides these, and lessons of such a kind as will take away the fear of\r death? Can any man be courageous who has the fear of death in him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"749"},"sequenceIndex":1210},{"id":"plato-the-repu-750","text":"And can he be fearless of death, or will he choose death in battle\r rather than defeat and slavery, who believes the world below to be real\r and terrible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"750"},"sequenceIndex":1211},{"id":"plato-the-repu-751","text":"Then we must assume a control over the narrators of this class of tales\r as well as over the others, and beg them not simply to revile but\r rather to commend the world below, intimating to them that their\r descriptions are untrue, and will do harm to our future warriors.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"751"},"sequenceIndex":1212},{"id":"plato-the-repu-752","text":"Then, I said, we shall have to obliterate many obnoxious passages,\r beginning with the verses,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"752"},"sequenceIndex":1213},{"id":"plato-the-repu-753","text":"‘I would rather be a serf on the land of a poor and portionless man\r than rule over all the dead who have come to nought.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"753"},"sequenceIndex":1214},{"id":"plato-the-repu-754","text":"‘Lest the mansions grim and squalid which the gods abhor should be seen\r both of mortals and immortals.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"754"},"sequenceIndex":1215},{"id":"plato-the-repu-755","text":"‘O heavens! verily in the house of Hades there is soul and ghostly form\r but no mind at all!’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"755"},"sequenceIndex":1216},{"id":"plato-the-repu-756","text":"‘(To him even after death did Persephone grant mind,) that he alone\r should be wise; but the other souls are flitting shades.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"756"},"sequenceIndex":1217},{"id":"plato-the-repu-757","text":"‘The soul flying from the limbs had gone to Hades, lamenting her fate,\r leaving manhood and youth.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"757"},"sequenceIndex":1218},{"id":"plato-the-repu-758","text":"‘As bats in hollow of mystic cavern, whenever any of them has dropped\r out of the string and falls from the rock, fly shrilling and cling to\r one another, so did they with shrilling cry hold together as they\r moved.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"758"},"sequenceIndex":1219},{"id":"plato-the-repu-759","text":"And we must beg Homer and the other poets not to be angry if we strike\r out these and similar passages, not because they are unpoetical, or\r unattractive to the popular ear, but because the greater the poetical\r charm of them, the less are they meet for the ears of boys and men who\r are meant to be free, and who should fear slavery more than death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"759"},"sequenceIndex":1220},{"id":"plato-the-repu-760","text":"Also we shall have to reject all the terrible and appalling names which\r describe the world below—Cocytus and Styx, ghosts under the earth, and\r sapless shades, and any similar words of which the very mention causes\r a shudder to pass through the inmost soul of him who hears them. I do\r not say that these horrible stories may not have a use of some kind;\r but there is a danger that the nerves of our guardians may be rendered\r too excitable and effeminate by them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"760"},"sequenceIndex":1221},{"id":"plato-the-repu-761","text":"But shall we be right in getting rid of them? Reflect: our principle is\r that the good man will not consider death terrible to any other good\r man who is his comrade.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"761"},"sequenceIndex":1222},{"id":"plato-the-repu-762","text":"And therefore he will not sorrow for his departed friend as though he\r had suffered anything terrible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"762"},"sequenceIndex":1223},{"id":"plato-the-repu-763","text":"Such an one, as we further maintain, is sufficient for himself and his\r own happiness, and therefore is least in need of other men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"763"},"sequenceIndex":1224},{"id":"plato-the-repu-764","text":"And for this reason the loss of a son or brother, or the deprivation of\r fortune, is to him of all men least terrible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"764"},"sequenceIndex":1225},{"id":"plato-the-repu-765","text":"And therefore he will be least likely to lament, and will bear with the\r greatest equanimity any misfortune of this sort which may befall him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"765"},"sequenceIndex":1226},{"id":"plato-the-repu-766","text":"Then we shall be right in getting rid of the lamentations of famous\r men, and making them over to women (and not even to women who are good\r for anything), or to men of a baser sort, that those who are being\r educated by us to be the defenders of their country may scorn to do the\r like.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"766"},"sequenceIndex":1227},{"id":"plato-the-repu-767","text":"Then we will once more entreat Homer and the other poets not to depict\r Achilles, who is the son of a goddess, first lying on his side, then on\r his back, and then on his face; then starting up and sailing in a\r frenzy along the shores of the barren sea; now taking the sooty ashes\r in both his hands and pouring them over his head, or weeping and\r wailing in the various modes which Homer has delineated. Nor should he\r describe Priam the kinsman of the gods as praying and beseeching,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"767"},"sequenceIndex":1228},{"id":"plato-the-repu-768","text":"Still more earnestly will we beg of him at all events not to introduce\r the gods lamenting and saying,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"768"},"sequenceIndex":1229},{"id":"plato-the-repu-769","text":"But if he must introduce the gods, at any rate let him not dare so\r completely to misrepresent the greatest of the gods, as to make him\r say—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"769"},"sequenceIndex":1230},{"id":"plato-the-repu-770","text":"‘O heavens! with my eyes verily I behold a dear friend of mine chased\r round and round the city, and my heart is sorrowful.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"770"},"sequenceIndex":1231},{"id":"plato-the-repu-771","text":"Woe is me that I am fated to have Sarpedon, dearest of men to me,\r subdued at the hands of Patroclus the son of Menoetius.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"771"},"sequenceIndex":1232},{"id":"plato-the-repu-772","text":"For if, my sweet Adeimantus, our youth seriously listen to such\r unworthy representations of the gods, instead of laughing at them as\r they ought, hardly will any of them deem that he himself, being but a\r man, can be dishonoured by similar actions; neither will he rebuke any\r inclination which may arise in his mind to say and do the like. And\r instead of having any shame or self-control, he will be always whining\r and lamenting on slight occasions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"772"},"sequenceIndex":1233},{"id":"plato-the-repu-773","text":"Yes, I replied; but that surely is what ought not to be, as the\r argument has just proved to us; and by that proof we must abide until\r it is disproved by a better.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"773"},"sequenceIndex":1234},{"id":"plato-the-repu-774","text":"Neither ought our guardians to be given to laughter. For a fit of\r laughter which has been indulged to excess almost always produces a\r violent reaction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"774"},"sequenceIndex":1235},{"id":"plato-the-repu-775","text":"Then persons of worth, even if only mortal men, must not be represented\r as overcome by laughter, and still less must such a representation of\r the gods be allowed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"775"},"sequenceIndex":1236},{"id":"plato-the-repu-776","text":"Then we shall not suffer such an expression to be used about the gods\r as that of Homer when he describes how","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"776"},"sequenceIndex":1237},{"id":"plato-the-repu-777","text":"‘Inextinguishable laughter arose among the blessed gods, when they saw\r Hephaestus bustling about the mansion.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"777"},"sequenceIndex":1238},{"id":"plato-the-repu-778","text":"On my views, if you like to father them on me; that we must not admit\r them is certain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"778"},"sequenceIndex":1239},{"id":"plato-the-repu-779","text":"Again, truth should be highly valued; if, as we were saying, a lie is\r useless to the gods, and useful only as a medicine to men, then the use\r of such medicines should be restricted to physicians; private\r individuals have no business with them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"779"},"sequenceIndex":1240},{"id":"plato-the-repu-780","text":"Then if any one at all is to have the privilege of lying, the rulers of\r the State should be the persons; and they, in their dealings either\r with enemies or with their own citizens, may be allowed to lie for the\r public good. But nobody else should meddle with anything of the kind;\r and although the rulers have this privilege, for a private man to lie\r to them in return is to be deemed a more heinous fault than for the\r patient or the pupil of a gymnasium not to speak the truth about his\r own bodily illnesses to the physician or to the trainer, or for a\r sailor not to tell the captain what is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"780"},"sequenceIndex":1241},{"id":"plato-the-repu-781","text":"he will punish him for introducing a practice which is equally\r subversive and destructive of ship or State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"781"},"sequenceIndex":1242},{"id":"plato-the-repu-782","text":"Are not the chief elements of temperance, speaking generally, obedience\r to commanders and self-control in sensual pleasures?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"782"},"sequenceIndex":1243},{"id":"plato-the-repu-783","text":"and of the words which follow? Would you say that these, or any similar\r impertinences which private individuals are supposed to address to\r their rulers, whether in verse or prose, are well or ill spoken?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"783"},"sequenceIndex":1244},{"id":"plato-the-repu-784","text":"They may very possibly afford some amusement, but they do not conduce\r to temperance. And therefore they are likely to do harm to our young\r men—you would agree with me there?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"784"},"sequenceIndex":1245},{"id":"plato-the-repu-785","text":"And then, again, to make the wisest of men say that nothing in his\r opinion is more glorious than","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"785"},"sequenceIndex":1246},{"id":"plato-the-repu-786","text":"‘When the tables are full of bread and meat, and the cup-bearer carries\r round wine which he draws from the bowl and pours into the cups,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"786"},"sequenceIndex":1247},{"id":"plato-the-repu-787","text":"is it fit or conducive to temperance for a young man to hear such\r words? Or the verse","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"787"},"sequenceIndex":1248},{"id":"plato-the-repu-788","text":"What would you say again to the tale of Zeus, who, while other gods and\r men were asleep and he the only person awake, lay devising plans, but\r forgot them all in a moment through his lust, and was so completely\r overcome at the sight of Here that he would not even go into the hut,\r but wanted to lie with her on the ground, declaring that he had never\r been in such a state of rapture before, even when they first met one\r another","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"788"},"sequenceIndex":1249},{"id":"plato-the-repu-789","text":"or that other tale of how Hephaestus, because of similar goings on,\r cast a chain around Ares and Aphrodite?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"789"},"sequenceIndex":1250},{"id":"plato-the-repu-790","text":"Indeed, he said, I am strongly of opinion that they ought not to hear\r that sort of thing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"790"},"sequenceIndex":1251},{"id":"plato-the-repu-791","text":"But any deeds of endurance which are done or told by famous men, these\r they ought to see and hear; as, for example, what is said in the\r verses,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"791"},"sequenceIndex":1252},{"id":"plato-the-repu-792","text":"‘He smote his breast, and thus reproached his heart, Endure, my heart;\r far worse hast thou endured!’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"792"},"sequenceIndex":1253},{"id":"plato-the-repu-793","text":"In the next place, we must not let them be receivers of gifts or lovers\r of money.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"793"},"sequenceIndex":1254},{"id":"plato-the-repu-794","text":"Neither is Phoenix, the tutor of Achilles, to be approved or deemed to\r have given his pupil good counsel when he told him that he should take\r the gifts of the Greeks and assist them; but that without a gift he\r should not lay aside his anger. Neither will we believe or acknowledge\r Achilles himself to have been such a lover of money that he took\r Agamemnon’s gifts, or that when he had received payment he restored the\r dead body of Hector, but that without payment he was unwilling to do\r so.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"794"},"sequenceIndex":1255},{"id":"plato-the-repu-795","text":"Loving Homer as I do, I hardly like to say that in attributing these\r feelings to Achilles, or in believing that they are truly attributed to\r him, he is guilty of downright impiety. As little can I believe the\r narrative of his insolence to Apollo, where he says,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"795"},"sequenceIndex":1256},{"id":"plato-the-repu-796","text":"‘Thou hast wronged me, O far-darter, most abominable of deities. Verily\r I would be even with thee, if I had only the power;’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"796"},"sequenceIndex":1257},{"id":"plato-the-repu-797","text":"or his insubordination to the river-god, on whose divinity he is ready\r to lay hands; or his offering to the dead Patroclus of his own hair,\r which had been previously dedicated to the other river-god Spercheius,\r and that he actually performed this vow; or that he dragged Hector\r round the tomb of Patroclus, and slaughtered the captives at the pyre;\r of all this I cannot believe that he was guilty, any more than I can\r allow our citizens to believe that he, the wise Cheiron’s pupil, the\r son of a goddess and of Peleus who was the gentlest of men and third in\r descent from Zeus, was so disorde","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"797"},"sequenceIndex":1258},{"id":"plato-the-repu-798","text":"And let us equally refuse to believe, or allow to be repeated, the tale\r of Theseus son of Poseidon, or of Peirithous son of Zeus, going forth\r as they did to perpetrate a horrid rape; or of any other hero or son of\r a god daring to do such impious and dreadful things as they falsely\r ascribe to them in our day: and let us further compel the poets to\r declare either that these acts were not done by them, or that they were\r not the sons of gods;—both in the same breath they shall not be\r permitted to affirm. We will not have them trying to persuade our youth\r that the gods are the authors of ev","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"798"},"sequenceIndex":1259},{"id":"plato-the-repu-799","text":"And further they are likely to have a bad effect on those who hear\r them; for everybody will begin to excuse his own vices when he is\r convinced that similar wickednesses are always being perpetrated by—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"799"},"sequenceIndex":1260},{"id":"plato-the-repu-800","text":"‘The kindred of the gods, the relatives of Zeus, whose ancestral altar,\r the altar of Zeus, is aloft in air on the peak of Ida,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"800"},"sequenceIndex":1261},{"id":"plato-the-repu-801","text":"And therefore let us put an end to such tales, lest they engender\r laxity of morals among the young.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"801"},"sequenceIndex":1262},{"id":"plato-the-repu-802","text":"But now that we are determining what classes of subjects are or are not\r to be spoken of, let us see whether any have been omitted by us. The\r manner in which gods and demigods and heroes and the world below should\r be treated has been already laid down.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"802"},"sequenceIndex":1263},{"id":"plato-the-repu-803","text":"And what shall we say about men? That is clearly the remaining portion\r of our subject.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"803"},"sequenceIndex":1264},{"id":"plato-the-repu-804","text":"Because, if I am not mistaken, we shall have to say that about men\r poets and story-tellers are guilty of making the gravest misstatements\r when they tell us that wicked men are often happy, and the good\r miserable; and that injustice is profitable when undetected, but that\r justice is a man’s own loss and another’s gain—these things we shall\r forbid them to utter, and command them to sing and say the opposite.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"804"},"sequenceIndex":1265},{"id":"plato-the-repu-805","text":"But if you admit that I am right in this, then I shall maintain that\r you have implied the principle for which we have been all along\r contending.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"805"},"sequenceIndex":1266},{"id":"plato-the-repu-806","text":"That such things are or are not to be said about men is a question\r which we cannot determine until we have discovered what justice is, and\r how naturally advantageous to the possessor, whether he seem to be just\r or not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"806"},"sequenceIndex":1267},{"id":"plato-the-repu-807","text":"Enough of the subjects of poetry: let us now speak of the style; and\r when this has been considered, both matter and manner will have been\r completely treated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"807"},"sequenceIndex":1268},{"id":"plato-the-repu-808","text":"Then I must make you understand; and perhaps I may be more intelligible\r if I put the matter in this way. You are aware, I suppose, that all\r mythology and poetry is a narration of events, either past, present, or\r to come?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"808"},"sequenceIndex":1269},{"id":"plato-the-repu-809","text":"And narration may be either simple narration, or imitation, or a union\r of the two?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"809"},"sequenceIndex":1270},{"id":"plato-the-repu-810","text":"I fear that I must be a ridiculous teacher when I have so much\r difficulty in making myself apprehended. Like a bad speaker, therefore,\r I will not take the whole of the subject, but will break a piece off in\r illustration of my meaning. You know the first lines of the Iliad, in\r which the poet says that Chryses prayed Agamemnon to release his\r daughter, and that Agamemnon flew into a passion with him; whereupon\r Chryses, failing of his object, invoked the anger of the God against\r the Achaeans. Now as far as these lines,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"810"},"sequenceIndex":1271},{"id":"plato-the-repu-811","text":"‘And he prayed all the Greeks, but especially the two sons of Atreus,\r the chiefs of the people,’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"811"},"sequenceIndex":1272},{"id":"plato-the-repu-812","text":"the poet is speaking in his own person; he never leads us to suppose\r that he is any one else. But in what follows he takes the person of\r Chryses, and then he does all that he can to make us believe that the\r speaker is not Homer, but the aged priest himself. And in this double\r form he has cast the entire narrative of the events which occurred at\r Troy and in Ithaca and throughout the Odyssey.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"812"},"sequenceIndex":1273},{"id":"plato-the-repu-813","text":"And a narrative it remains both in the speeches which the poet recites\r from time to time and in the intermediate passages?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"813"},"sequenceIndex":1274},{"id":"plato-the-repu-814","text":"But when the poet speaks in the person of another, may we not say that\r he assimilates his style to that of the person who, as he informs you,\r is going to speak?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"814"},"sequenceIndex":1275},{"id":"plato-the-repu-815","text":"And this assimilation of himself to another, either by the use of voice\r or gesture, is the imitation of the person whose character he assumes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"815"},"sequenceIndex":1276},{"id":"plato-the-repu-816","text":"Then in this case the narrative of the poet may be said to proceed by\r way of imitation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"816"},"sequenceIndex":1277},{"id":"plato-the-repu-817","text":"Or, if the poet everywhere appears and never conceals himself, then\r again the imitation is dropped, and his poetry becomes simple\r narration. However, in order that I may make my meaning quite clear,\r and that you may no more say, ‘I don’t understand,’ I will show how the\r change might be effected. If Homer had said, ‘The priest came, having\r his daughter’s ransom in his hands, supplicating the Achaeans, and\r above all the kings;’ and then if, instead of speaking in the person of\r Chryses, he had continued in his own person, the words would have been,\r not imitation, but simple narration. The","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"817"},"sequenceIndex":1278},{"id":"plato-the-repu-818","text":"Or you may suppose the opposite case—that the intermediate passages are\r omitted, and the dialogue only left.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"818"},"sequenceIndex":1279},{"id":"plato-the-repu-819","text":"You have conceived my meaning perfectly; and if I mistake not, what you\r failed to apprehend before is now made clear to you, that poetry and\r mythology are, in some cases, wholly imitative—instances of this are\r supplied by tragedy and comedy; there is likewise the opposite style,\r in which the poet is the only speaker—of this the dithyramb affords the\r best example; and the combination of both is found in epic, and in\r several other styles of poetry. Do I take you with me?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"819"},"sequenceIndex":1280},{"id":"plato-the-repu-820","text":"I will ask you to remember also what I began by saying, that we had\r done with the subject and might proceed to the style.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"820"},"sequenceIndex":1281},{"id":"plato-the-repu-821","text":"In saying this, I intended to imply that we must come to an\r understanding about the mimetic art,—whether the poets, in narrating\r their stories, are to be allowed by us to imitate, and if so, whether\r in whole or in part, and if the latter, in what parts; or should all\r imitation be prohibited?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"821"},"sequenceIndex":1282},{"id":"plato-the-repu-822","text":"You mean, I suspect, to ask whether tragedy and comedy shall be\r admitted into our State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"822"},"sequenceIndex":1283},{"id":"plato-the-repu-823","text":"Yes, I said; but there may be more than this in question: I really do\r not know as yet, but whither the argument may blow, thither we go.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"823"},"sequenceIndex":1284},{"id":"plato-the-repu-824","text":"Then, Adeimantus, let me ask you whether our guardians ought to be\r imitators; or rather, has not this question been decided by the rule\r already laid down that one man can only do one thing well, and not\r many; and that if he attempt many, he will altogether fail of gaining\r much reputation in any?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"824"},"sequenceIndex":1285},{"id":"plato-the-repu-825","text":"And this is equally true of imitation; no one man can imitate many\r things as well as he would imitate a single one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"825"},"sequenceIndex":1286},{"id":"plato-the-repu-826","text":"Then the same person will hardly be able to play a serious part in\r life, and at the same time to be an imitator and imitate many other\r parts as well; for even when two species of imitation are nearly\r allied, the same persons cannot succeed in both, as, for example, the\r writers of tragedy and comedy—did you not just now call them\r imitations?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"826"},"sequenceIndex":1287},{"id":"plato-the-repu-827","text":"Yes, I did; and you are right in thinking that the same persons cannot\r succeed in both.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"827"},"sequenceIndex":1288},{"id":"plato-the-repu-828","text":"Neither are comic and tragic actors the same; yet all these things are\r but imitations.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"828"},"sequenceIndex":1289},{"id":"plato-the-repu-829","text":"And human nature, Adeimantus, appears to have been coined into yet\r smaller pieces, and to be as incapable of imitating many things well,\r as of performing well the actions of which the imitations are copies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"829"},"sequenceIndex":1290},{"id":"plato-the-repu-830","text":"If then we adhere to our original notion and bear in mind that our\r guardians, setting aside every other business, are to dedicate\r themselves wholly to the maintenance of freedom in the State, making\r this their craft, and engaging in no work which does not bear on this\r end, they ought not to practise or imitate anything else; if they\r imitate at all, they should imitate from youth upward only those\r characters which are suitable to their profession—the courageous,\r temperate, holy, free, and the like; but they should not depict or be\r skilful at imitating any kind of illiberality or basenes","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"830"},"sequenceIndex":1291},{"id":"plato-the-repu-831","text":"Then, I said, we will not allow those for whom we profess a care and of\r whom we say that they ought to be good men, to imitate a woman, whether\r young or old, quarrelling with her husband, or striving and vaunting\r against the gods in conceit of her happiness, or when she is in\r affliction, or sorrow, or weeping; and certainly not one who is in\r sickness, love, or labour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"831"},"sequenceIndex":1292},{"id":"plato-the-repu-832","text":"Neither must they represent slaves, male or female, performing the\r offices of slaves?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"832"},"sequenceIndex":1293},{"id":"plato-the-repu-833","text":"And surely not bad men, whether cowards or any others, who do the\r reverse of what we have just been prescribing, who scold or mock or\r revile one another in drink or out of drink, or who in any other manner\r sin against themselves and their neighbours in word or deed, as the\r manner of such is. Neither should they be trained to imitate the action\r or speech of men or women who are mad or bad; for madness, like vice,\r is to be known but not to be practised or imitated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"833"},"sequenceIndex":1294},{"id":"plato-the-repu-834","text":"Neither may they imitate smiths or other artificers, or oarsmen, or\r boatswains, or the like?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"834"},"sequenceIndex":1295},{"id":"plato-the-repu-835","text":"How can they, he said, when they are not allowed to apply their minds\r to the callings of any of these?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"835"},"sequenceIndex":1296},{"id":"plato-the-repu-836","text":"Nor may they imitate the neighing of horses, the bellowing of bulls,\r the murmur of rivers and roll of the ocean, thunder, and all that sort\r of thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"836"},"sequenceIndex":1297},{"id":"plato-the-repu-837","text":"Nay, he said, if madness be forbidden, neither may they copy the\r behaviour of madmen.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"837"},"sequenceIndex":1298},{"id":"plato-the-repu-838","text":"You mean, I said, if I understand you aright, that there is one sort of\r narrative style which may be employed by a truly good man when he has\r anything to say, and that another sort will be used by a man of an\r opposite character and education.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"838"},"sequenceIndex":1299},{"id":"plato-the-repu-839","text":"Suppose, I answered, that a just and good man in the course of a\r narration comes on some saying or action of another good man,—I should\r imagine that he will like to personate him, and will not be ashamed of\r this sort of imitation: he will be most ready to play the part of the\r good man when he is acting firmly and wisely; in a less degree when he\r is overtaken by illness or love or drink, or has met with any other\r disaster. But when he comes to a character which is unworthy of him, he\r will not make a study of that; he will disdain such a person, and will\r assume his likeness, if at all, f","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"839"},"sequenceIndex":1300},{"id":"plato-the-repu-840","text":"Then he will adopt a mode of narration such as we have illustrated out\r of Homer, that is to say, his style will be both imitative and\r narrative; but there will be very little of the former, and a great\r deal of the latter. Do you agree?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"840"},"sequenceIndex":1301},{"id":"plato-the-repu-841","text":"Certainly, he said; that is the model which such a speaker must\r necessarily take.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"841"},"sequenceIndex":1302},{"id":"plato-the-repu-842","text":"But there is another sort of character who will narrate anything, and,\r the worse he is, the more unscrupulous he will be; nothing will be too\r bad for him: and he will be ready to imitate anything, not as a joke,\r but in right good earnest, and before a large company. As I was just\r now saying, he will attempt to represent the roll of thunder, the noise\r of wind and hail, or the creaking of wheels, and pulleys, and the\r various sounds of flutes, pipes, trumpets, and all sorts of\r instruments: he will bark like a dog, bleat like a sheep, or crow like\r a cock; his entire art will consist in imi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"842"},"sequenceIndex":1303},{"id":"plato-the-repu-843","text":"And you would agree with me in saying that one of them is simple and\r has but slight changes; and if the harmony and rhythm are also chosen\r for their simplicity, the result is that the speaker, if he speaks\r correctly, is always pretty much the same in style, and he will keep\r within the limits of a single harmony (for the changes are not great),\r and in like manner he will make use of nearly the same rhythm?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"843"},"sequenceIndex":1304},{"id":"plato-the-repu-844","text":"Whereas the other requires all sorts of harmonies and all sorts of\r rhythms, if the music and the style are to correspond, because the\r style has all sorts of changes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"844"},"sequenceIndex":1305},{"id":"plato-the-repu-845","text":"And do not the two styles, or the mixture of the two, comprehend all\r poetry, and every form of expression in words? No one can say anything\r except in one or other of them or in both together.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"845"},"sequenceIndex":1306},{"id":"plato-the-repu-846","text":"And shall we receive into our State all the three styles, or one only\r of the two unmixed styles? or would you include the mixed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"846"},"sequenceIndex":1307},{"id":"plato-the-repu-847","text":"Yes, I said, Adeimantus, but the mixed style is also very charming: and\r indeed the pantomimic, which is the opposite of the one chosen by you,\r is the most popular style with children and their attendants, and with\r the world in general.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"847"},"sequenceIndex":1308},{"id":"plato-the-repu-848","text":"But I suppose you would argue that such a style is unsuitable to our\r State, in which human nature is not twofold or manifold, for one man\r plays one part only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"848"},"sequenceIndex":1309},{"id":"plato-the-repu-849","text":"And this is the reason why in our State, and in our State only, we\r shall find a shoemaker to be a shoemaker and not a pilot also, and a\r husbandman to be a husbandman and not a dicast also, and a soldier a\r soldier and not a trader also, and the same throughout?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"849"},"sequenceIndex":1310},{"id":"plato-the-repu-850","text":"And therefore when any one of these pantomimic gentlemen, who are so\r clever that they can imitate anything, comes to us, and makes a\r proposal to exhibit himself and his poetry, we will fall down and\r worship him as a sweet and holy and wonderful being; but we must also\r inform him that in our State such as he are not permitted to exist; the\r law will not allow them. And so when we have anointed him with myrrh,\r and set a garland of wool upon his head, we shall send him away to\r another city. For we mean to employ for our souls’ health the rougher\r and severer poet or story-teller, who will i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"850"},"sequenceIndex":1311},{"id":"plato-the-repu-851","text":"Then now, my friend, I said, that part of music or literary education\r which relates to the story or myth may be considered to be finished;\r for the matter and manner have both been discussed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"851"},"sequenceIndex":1312},{"id":"plato-the-repu-852","text":"Every one can see already what we ought to say about them, if we are to\r be consistent with ourselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"852"},"sequenceIndex":1313},{"id":"plato-the-repu-853","text":"I fear, said Glaucon, laughing, that the word ‘every one’ hardly\r includes me, for I cannot at the moment say what they should be; though\r I may guess.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"853"},"sequenceIndex":1314},{"id":"plato-the-repu-854","text":"At any rate you can tell that a song or ode has three parts—the words,\r the melody, and the rhythm; that degree of knowledge I may presuppose?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"854"},"sequenceIndex":1315},{"id":"plato-the-repu-855","text":"And as for the words, there will surely be no difference between words\r which are and which are not set to music; both will conform to the same\r laws, and these have been already determined by us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"855"},"sequenceIndex":1316},{"id":"plato-the-repu-856","text":"We were saying, when we spoke of the subject-matter, that we had no\r need of lamentation and strains of sorrow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"856"},"sequenceIndex":1317},{"id":"plato-the-repu-857","text":"And which are the harmonies expressive of sorrow? You are musical, and\r can tell me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"857"},"sequenceIndex":1318},{"id":"plato-the-repu-858","text":"The harmonies which you mean are the mixed or tenor Lydian, and the\r full-toned or bass Lydian, and such like.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"858"},"sequenceIndex":1319},{"id":"plato-the-repu-859","text":"These then, I said, must be banished; even to women who have a\r character to maintain they are of no use, and much less to men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"859"},"sequenceIndex":1320},{"id":"plato-the-repu-860","text":"In the next place, drunkenness and softness and indolence are utterly\r unbecoming the character of our guardians.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"860"},"sequenceIndex":1321},{"id":"plato-the-repu-861","text":"Quite the reverse, he replied; and if so the Dorian and the Phrygian\r are the only ones which you have left.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"861"},"sequenceIndex":1322},{"id":"plato-the-repu-862","text":"I answered: Of the harmonies I know nothing, but I want to have one\r warlike, to sound the note or accent which a brave man utters in the\r hour of danger and stern resolve, or when his cause is failing, and he\r is going to wounds or death or is overtaken by some other evil, and at\r every such crisis meets the blows of fortune with firm step and a\r determination to endure; and another to be used by him in times of\r peace and freedom of action, when there is no pressure of necessity,\r and he is seeking to persuade God by prayer, or man by instruction and\r admonition, or on the other hand, when h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"862"},"sequenceIndex":1323},{"id":"plato-the-repu-863","text":"And these, he replied, are the Dorian and Phrygian harmonies of which I\r was just now speaking.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"863"},"sequenceIndex":1324},{"id":"plato-the-repu-864","text":"Then, I said, if these and these only are to be used in our songs and\r melodies, we shall not want multiplicity of notes or a panharmonic\r scale?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"864"},"sequenceIndex":1325},{"id":"plato-the-repu-865","text":"Then we shall not maintain the artificers of lyres with three corners\r and complex scales, or the makers of any other many-stringed\r curiously-harmonised instruments?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"865"},"sequenceIndex":1326},{"id":"plato-the-repu-866","text":"But what do you say to flute-makers and flute-players? Would you admit\r them into our State when you reflect that in this composite use of\r harmony the flute is worse than all the stringed instruments put\r together; even the panharmonic music is only an imitation of the flute?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"866"},"sequenceIndex":1327},{"id":"plato-the-repu-867","text":"There remain then only the lyre and the harp for use in the city, and\r the shepherds may have a pipe in the country.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"867"},"sequenceIndex":1328},{"id":"plato-the-repu-868","text":"The preferring of Apollo and his instruments to Marsyas and his\r instruments is not at all strange, I said.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"868"},"sequenceIndex":1329},{"id":"plato-the-repu-869","text":"And so, by the dog of Egypt, we have been unconsciously purging the\r State, which not long ago we termed luxurious.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"869"},"sequenceIndex":1330},{"id":"plato-the-repu-870","text":"Then let us now finish the purgation, I said. Next in order to\r harmonies, rhythms will naturally follow, and they should be subject to\r the same rules, for we ought not to seek out complex systems of metre,\r or metres of every kind, but rather to discover what rhythms are the\r expressions of a courageous and harmonious life; and when we have found\r them, we shall adapt the foot and the melody to words having a like\r spirit, not the words to the foot and melody. To say what these rhythms\r are will be your duty—you must teach me them, as you have already\r taught me the harmonies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"870"},"sequenceIndex":1331},{"id":"plato-the-repu-871","text":"But, indeed, he replied, I cannot tell you. I only know that there are\r some three principles of rhythm out of which metrical systems are\r framed, just as in sounds there are four notes (i.e. the four notes of\r the tetrachord.) out of which all the harmonies are composed; that is\r an observation which I have made. But of what sort of lives they are\r severally the imitations I am unable to say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"871"},"sequenceIndex":1332},{"id":"plato-the-repu-872","text":"Then, I said, we must take Damon into our counsels; and he will tell us\r what rhythms are expressive of meanness, or insolence, or fury, or\r other unworthiness, and what are to be reserved for the expression of\r opposite feelings. And I think that I have an indistinct recollection\r of his mentioning a complex Cretic rhythm; also a dactylic or heroic,\r and he arranged them in some manner which I do not quite understand,\r making the rhythms equal in the rise and fall of the foot, long and\r short alternating; and, unless I am mistaken, he spoke of an iambic as\r well as of a trochaic rhythm, and a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"872"},"sequenceIndex":1333},{"id":"plato-the-repu-873","text":"But there is no difficulty in seeing that grace or the absence of grace\r is an effect of good or bad rhythm.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"873"},"sequenceIndex":1334},{"id":"plato-the-repu-874","text":"And also that good and bad rhythm naturally assimilate to a good and\r bad style; and that harmony and discord in like manner follow style;\r for our principle is that rhythm and harmony are regulated by the\r words, and not the words by them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"874"},"sequenceIndex":1335},{"id":"plato-the-repu-875","text":"And will not the words and the character of the style depend on the\r temper of the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"875"},"sequenceIndex":1336},{"id":"plato-the-repu-876","text":"Then beauty of style and harmony and grace and good rhythm depend on\r simplicity,—I mean the true simplicity of a rightly and nobly ordered\r mind and character, not that other simplicity which is only an\r euphemism for folly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"876"},"sequenceIndex":1337},{"id":"plato-the-repu-877","text":"And if our youth are to do their work in life, must they not make these\r graces and harmonies their perpetual aim?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"877"},"sequenceIndex":1338},{"id":"plato-the-repu-878","text":"And surely the art of the painter and every other creative and\r constructive art are full of them,—weaving, embroidery, architecture,\r and every kind of manufacture; also nature, animal and vegetable,—in\r all of them there is grace or the absence of grace. And ugliness and\r discord and inharmonious motion are nearly allied to ill words and ill\r nature, as grace and harmony are the twin sisters of goodness and\r virtue and bear their likeness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"878"},"sequenceIndex":1339},{"id":"plato-the-repu-879","text":"But shall our superintendence go no further, and are the poets only to\r be required by us to express the image of the good in their works, on\r pain, if they do anything else, of expulsion from our State? Or is the\r same control to be extended to other artists, and are they also to be\r prohibited from exhibiting the opposite forms of vice and intemperance\r and meanness and indecency in sculpture and building and the other\r creative arts; and is he who cannot conform to this rule of ours to be\r prevented from practising his art in our State, lest the taste of our\r citizens be corrupted by him? W","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"879"},"sequenceIndex":1340},{"id":"plato-the-repu-880","text":"And therefore, I said, Glaucon, musical training is a more potent\r instrument than any other, because rhythm and harmony find their way\r into the inward places of the soul, on which they mightily fasten,\r imparting grace, and making the soul of him who is rightly educated\r graceful, or of him who is ill-educated ungraceful; and also because he\r who has received this true education of the inner being will most\r shrewdly perceive omissions or faults in art and nature, and with a\r true taste, while he praises and rejoices over and receives into his\r soul the good, and becomes noble and good, he w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"880"},"sequenceIndex":1341},{"id":"plato-the-repu-881","text":"Yes, he said, I quite agree with you in thinking that our youth should\r be trained in music and on the grounds which you mention.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"881"},"sequenceIndex":1342},{"id":"plato-the-repu-882","text":"Just as in learning to read, I said, we were satisfied when we knew the\r letters of the alphabet, which are very few, in all their recurring\r sizes and combinations; not slighting them as unimportant whether they\r occupy a space large or small, but everywhere eager to make them out;\r and not thinking ourselves perfect in the art of reading until we\r recognise them wherever they are found:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"882"},"sequenceIndex":1343},{"id":"plato-the-repu-883","text":"Or, as we recognise the reflection of letters in the water, or in a\r mirror, only when we know the letters themselves; the same art and\r study giving us the knowledge of both:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"883"},"sequenceIndex":1344},{"id":"plato-the-repu-884","text":"Even so, as I maintain, neither we nor our guardians, whom we have to\r educate, can ever become musical until we and they know the essential\r forms of temperance, courage, liberality, magnificence, and their\r kindred, as well as the contrary forms, in all their combinations, and\r can recognise them and their images wherever they are found, not\r slighting them either in small things or great, but believing them all\r to be within the sphere of one art and study.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"884"},"sequenceIndex":1345},{"id":"plato-the-repu-885","text":"And when a beautiful soul harmonizes with a beautiful form, and the two\r are cast in one mould, that will be the fairest of sights to him who\r has an eye to see it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"885"},"sequenceIndex":1346},{"id":"plato-the-repu-886","text":"And the man who has the spirit of harmony will be most in love with the\r loveliest; but he will not love him who is of an inharmonious soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"886"},"sequenceIndex":1347},{"id":"plato-the-repu-887","text":"That is true, he replied, if the deficiency be in his soul; but if\r there be any merely bodily defect in another he will be patient of it,\r and will love all the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"887"},"sequenceIndex":1348},{"id":"plato-the-repu-888","text":"I perceive, I said, that you have or have had experiences of this sort,\r and I agree. But let me ask you another question: Has excess of\r pleasure any affinity to temperance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"888"},"sequenceIndex":1349},{"id":"plato-the-repu-889","text":"How can that be? he replied; pleasure deprives a man of the use of his\r faculties quite as much as pain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"889"},"sequenceIndex":1350},{"id":"plato-the-repu-890","text":"Then mad or intemperate pleasure must never be allowed to come near the\r lover and his beloved; neither of them can have any part in it if their\r love is of the right sort?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"890"},"sequenceIndex":1351},{"id":"plato-the-repu-891","text":"Then I suppose that in the city which we are founding you would make a\r law to the effect that a friend should use no other familiarity to his\r love than a father would use to his son, and then only for a noble\r purpose, and he must first have the other’s consent; and this rule is\r to limit him in all his intercourse, and he is never to be seen going\r further, or, if he exceeds, he is to be deemed guilty of coarseness and\r bad taste.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"891"},"sequenceIndex":1352},{"id":"plato-the-repu-892","text":"Thus much of music, which makes a fair ending; for what should be the\r end of music if not the love of beauty?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"892"},"sequenceIndex":1353},{"id":"plato-the-repu-893","text":"Gymnastic as well as music should begin in early years; the training in\r it should be careful and should continue through life. Now my belief\r is,—and this is a matter upon which I should like to have your opinion\r in confirmation of my own, but my own belief is,—not that the good body\r by any bodily excellence improves the soul, but, on the contrary, that\r the good soul, by her own excellence, improves the body as far as this\r may be possible. What do you say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"893"},"sequenceIndex":1354},{"id":"plato-the-repu-894","text":"Then, to the mind when adequately trained, we shall be right in handing\r over the more particular care of the body; and in order to avoid\r prolixity we will now only give the general outlines of the subject.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"894"},"sequenceIndex":1355},{"id":"plato-the-repu-895","text":"That they must abstain from intoxication has been already remarked by\r us; for of all persons a guardian should be the last to get drunk and\r not know where in the world he is.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"895"},"sequenceIndex":1356},{"id":"plato-the-repu-896","text":"Yes, he said; that a guardian should require another guardian to take\r care of him is ridiculous indeed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"896"},"sequenceIndex":1357},{"id":"plato-the-repu-897","text":"But next, what shall we say of their food; for the men are in training\r for the great contest of all—are they not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"897"},"sequenceIndex":1358},{"id":"plato-the-repu-898","text":"I am afraid, I said, that a habit of body such as they have is but a\r sleepy sort of thing, and rather perilous to health. Do you not observe\r that these athletes sleep away their lives, and are liable to most\r dangerous illnesses if they depart, in ever so slight a degree, from\r their customary regimen?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"898"},"sequenceIndex":1359},{"id":"plato-the-repu-899","text":"Then, I said, a finer sort of training will be required for our warrior\r athletes, who are to be like wakeful dogs, and to see and hear with the\r utmost keenness; amid the many changes of water and also of food, of\r summer heat and winter cold, which they will have to endure when on a\r campaign, they must not be liable to break down in health.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"899"},"sequenceIndex":1360},{"id":"plato-the-repu-900","text":"The really excellent gymnastic is twin sister of that simple music\r which we were just now describing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"900"},"sequenceIndex":1361},{"id":"plato-the-repu-901","text":"Why, I conceive that there is a gymnastic which, like our music, is\r simple and good; and especially the military gymnastic.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"901"},"sequenceIndex":1362},{"id":"plato-the-repu-902","text":"My meaning may be learned from Homer; he, you know, feeds his heroes at\r their feasts, when they are campaigning, on soldiers’ fare; they have\r no fish, although they are on the shores of the Hellespont, and they\r are not allowed boiled meats but only roast, which is the food most\r convenient for soldiers, requiring only that they should light a fire,\r and not involving the trouble of carrying about pots and pans.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"902"},"sequenceIndex":1363},{"id":"plato-the-repu-903","text":"And I can hardly be mistaken in saying that sweet sauces are nowhere\r mentioned in Homer. In proscribing them, however, he is not singular;\r all professional athletes are well aware that a man who is to be in\r good condition should take nothing of the kind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"903"},"sequenceIndex":1364},{"id":"plato-the-repu-904","text":"Then you would not approve of Syracusan dinners, and the refinements of\r Sicilian cookery?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"904"},"sequenceIndex":1365},{"id":"plato-the-repu-905","text":"Nor, if a man is to be in condition, would you allow him to have a\r Corinthian girl as his fair friend?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"905"},"sequenceIndex":1366},{"id":"plato-the-repu-906","text":"Neither would you approve of the delicacies, as they are thought, of\r Athenian confectionary?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"906"},"sequenceIndex":1367},{"id":"plato-the-repu-907","text":"All such feeding and living may be rightly compared by us to melody and\r song composed in the panharmonic style, and in all the rhythms.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"907"},"sequenceIndex":1368},{"id":"plato-the-repu-908","text":"There complexity engendered licence, and here disease; whereas\r simplicity in music was the parent of temperance in the soul; and\r simplicity in gymnastic of health in the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"908"},"sequenceIndex":1369},{"id":"plato-the-repu-909","text":"But when intemperance and diseases multiply in a State, halls of\r justice and medicine are always being opened; and the arts of the\r doctor and the lawyer give themselves airs, finding how keen is the\r interest which not only the slaves but the freemen of a city take about\r them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"909"},"sequenceIndex":1370},{"id":"plato-the-repu-910","text":"And yet what greater proof can there be of a bad and disgraceful state\r of education than this, that not only artisans and the meaner sort of\r people need the skill of first-rate physicians and judges, but also\r those who would profess to have had a liberal education? Is it not\r disgraceful, and a great sign of want of good-breeding, that a man\r should have to go abroad for his law and physic because he has none of\r his own at home, and must therefore surrender himself into the hands of\r other men whom he makes lords and judges over him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"910"},"sequenceIndex":1371},{"id":"plato-the-repu-911","text":"Would you say ‘most,’ I replied, when you consider that there is a\r further stage of the evil in which a man is not only a life-long\r litigant, passing all his days in the courts, either as plaintiff or\r defendant, but is actually led by his bad taste to pride himself on his\r litigiousness; he imagines that he is a master in dishonesty; able to\r take every crooked turn, and wriggle into and out of every hole,\r bending like a withy and getting out of the way of justice: and all for\r what?—in order to gain small points not worth mentioning, he not\r knowing that so to order his life as to be able","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"911"},"sequenceIndex":1372},{"id":"plato-the-repu-912","text":"Well, I said, and to require the help of medicine, not when a wound has\r to be cured, or on occasion of an epidemic, but just because, by\r indolence and a habit of life such as we have been describing, men fill\r themselves with waters and winds, as if their bodies were a marsh,\r compelling the ingenious sons of Asclepius to find more names for\r diseases, such as flatulence and catarrh; is not this, too, a disgrace?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"912"},"sequenceIndex":1373},{"id":"plato-the-repu-913","text":"Yes, he said, they do certainly give very strange and newfangled names\r to diseases.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"913"},"sequenceIndex":1374},{"id":"plato-the-repu-914","text":"Yes, I said, and I do not believe that there were any such diseases in\r the days of Asclepius; and this I infer from the circumstance that the\r hero Eurypylus, after he has been wounded in Homer, drinks a posset of\r Pramnian wine well besprinkled with barley-meal and grated cheese,\r which are certainly inflammatory, and yet the sons of Asclepius who\r were at the Trojan war do not blame the damsel who gives him the drink,\r or rebuke Patroclus, who is treating his case.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"914"},"sequenceIndex":1375},{"id":"plato-the-repu-915","text":"Well, he said, that was surely an extraordinary drink to be given to a\r person in his condition.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"915"},"sequenceIndex":1376},{"id":"plato-the-repu-916","text":"Not so extraordinary, I replied, if you bear in mind that in former\r days, as is commonly said, before the time of Herodicus, the guild of\r Asclepius did not practise our present system of medicine, which may be\r said to educate diseases. But Herodicus, being a trainer, and himself\r of a sickly constitution, by a combination of training and doctoring\r found out a way of torturing first and chiefly himself, and secondly\r the rest of the world.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"916"},"sequenceIndex":1377},{"id":"plato-the-repu-917","text":"By the invention of lingering death; for he had a mortal disease which\r he perpetually tended, and as recovery was out of the question, he\r passed his entire life as a valetudinarian; he could do nothing but\r attend upon himself, and he was in constant torment whenever he\r departed in anything from his usual regimen, and so dying hard, by the\r help of science he struggled on to old age.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"917"},"sequenceIndex":1378},{"id":"plato-the-repu-918","text":"Yes, I said; a reward which a man might fairly expect who never\r understood that, if Asclepius did not instruct his descendants in\r valetudinarian arts, the omission arose, not from ignorance or\r inexperience of such a branch of medicine, but because he knew that in\r all well-ordered states every individual has an occupation to which he\r must attend, and has therefore no leisure to spend in continually being\r ill. This we remark in the case of the artisan, but, ludicrously\r enough, do not apply the same rule to people of the richer sort.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"918"},"sequenceIndex":1379},{"id":"plato-the-repu-919","text":"I mean this: When a carpenter is ill he asks the physician for a rough\r and ready cure; an emetic or a purge or a cautery or the knife,—these\r are his remedies. And if some one prescribes for him a course of\r dietetics, and tells him that he must swathe and swaddle his head, and\r all that sort of thing, he replies at once that he has no time to be\r ill, and that he sees no good in a life which is spent in nursing his\r disease to the neglect of his customary employment; and therefore\r bidding good-bye to this sort of physician, he resumes his ordinary\r habits, and either gets well and lives and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"919"},"sequenceIndex":1380},{"id":"plato-the-repu-920","text":"Yes, he said, and a man in his condition of life ought to use the art\r of medicine thus far only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"920"},"sequenceIndex":1381},{"id":"plato-the-repu-921","text":"Has he not, I said, an occupation; and what profit would there be in\r his life if he were deprived of his occupation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"921"},"sequenceIndex":1382},{"id":"plato-the-repu-922","text":"But with the rich man this is otherwise; of him we do not say that he\r has any specially appointed work which he must perform, if he would\r live.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"922"},"sequenceIndex":1383},{"id":"plato-the-repu-923","text":"Then you never heard of the saying of Phocylides, that as soon as a man\r has a livelihood he should practise virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"923"},"sequenceIndex":1384},{"id":"plato-the-repu-924","text":"Let us not have a dispute with him about this, I said; but rather ask\r ourselves: Is the practice of virtue obligatory on the rich man, or can\r he live without it? And if obligatory on him, then let us raise a\r further question, whether this dieting of disorders, which is an\r impediment to the application of the mind in carpentering and the\r mechanical arts, does not equally stand in the way of the sentiment of\r Phocylides?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"924"},"sequenceIndex":1385},{"id":"plato-the-repu-925","text":"Of that, he replied, there can be no doubt; such excessive care of the\r body, when carried beyond the rules of gymnastic, is most inimical to\r the practice of virtue.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"925"},"sequenceIndex":1386},{"id":"plato-the-repu-926","text":"Yes, indeed, I replied, and equally incompatible with the management of\r a house, an army, or an office of state; and, what is most important of\r all, irreconcileable with any kind of study or thought or\r self-reflection—there is a constant suspicion that headache and\r giddiness are to be ascribed to philosophy, and hence all practising or\r making trial of virtue in the higher sense is absolutely stopped; for a\r man is always fancying that he is being made ill, and is in constant\r anxiety about the state of his body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"926"},"sequenceIndex":1387},{"id":"plato-the-repu-927","text":"And therefore our politic Asclepius may be supposed to have exhibited\r the power of his art only to persons who, being generally of healthy\r constitution and habits of life, had a definite ailment; such as these\r he cured by purges and operations, and bade them live as usual, herein\r consulting the interests of the State; but bodies which disease had\r penetrated through and through he would not have attempted to cure by\r gradual processes of evacuation and infusion: he did not want to\r lengthen out good-for-nothing lives, or to have weak fathers begetting\r weaker sons;—if a man was not able to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"927"},"sequenceIndex":1388},{"id":"plato-the-repu-928","text":"Clearly; and his character is further illustrated by his sons. Note\r that they were heroes in the days of old and practised the medicines of\r which I am speaking at the siege of Troy: You will remember how, when\r Pandarus wounded Menelaus, they","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"928"},"sequenceIndex":1389},{"id":"plato-the-repu-929","text":"but they never prescribed what the patient was afterwards to eat or\r drink in the case of Menelaus, any more than in the case of Eurypylus;\r the remedies, as they conceived, were enough to heal any man who before\r he was wounded was healthy and regular in his habits; and even though\r he did happen to drink a posset of Pramnian wine, he might get well all\r the same. But they would have nothing to do with unhealthy and\r intemperate subjects, whose lives were of no use either to themselves\r or others; the art of medicine was not designed for their good, and\r though they were as rich as Midas, the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"929"},"sequenceIndex":1390},{"id":"plato-the-repu-930","text":"Naturally so, I replied. Nevertheless, the tragedians and Pindar\r disobeying our behests, although they acknowledge that Asclepius was\r the son of Apollo, say also that he was bribed into healing a rich man\r who was at the point of death, and for this reason he was struck by\r lightning. But we, in accordance with the principle already affirmed by\r us, will not believe them when they tell us both;—if he was the son of\r a god, we maintain that he was not avaricious; or, if he was\r avaricious, he was not the son of a god.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"930"},"sequenceIndex":1391},{"id":"plato-the-repu-931","text":"All that, Socrates, is excellent; but I should like to put a question\r to you: Ought there not to be good physicians in a State, and are not\r the best those who have treated the greatest number of constitutions\r good and bad? and are not the best judges in like manner those who are\r acquainted with all sorts of moral natures?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"931"},"sequenceIndex":1392},{"id":"plato-the-repu-932","text":"Yes, I said, I too would have good judges and good physicians. But do\r you know whom I think good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"932"},"sequenceIndex":1393},{"id":"plato-the-repu-933","text":"I will, if I can. Let me however note that in the same question you\r join two things which are not the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"933"},"sequenceIndex":1394},{"id":"plato-the-repu-934","text":"Why, I said, you join physicians and judges. Now the most skilful\r physicians are those who, from their youth upwards, have combined with\r the knowledge of their art the greatest experience of disease; they had\r better not be robust in health, and should have had all manner of\r diseases in their own persons. For the body, as I conceive, is not the\r instrument with which they cure the body; in that case we could not\r allow them ever to be or to have been sickly; but they cure the body\r with the mind, and the mind which has become and is sick can cure\r nothing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"934"},"sequenceIndex":1395},{"id":"plato-the-repu-935","text":"But with the judge it is otherwise; since he governs mind by mind; he\r ought not therefore to have been trained among vicious minds, and to\r have associated with them from youth upwards, and to have gone through\r the whole calendar of crime, only in order that he may quickly infer\r the crimes of others as he might their bodily diseases from his own\r self-consciousness; the honourable mind which is to form a healthy\r judgment should have had no experience or contamination of evil habits\r when young. And this is the reason why in youth good men often appear\r to be simple, and are easily practise","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"935"},"sequenceIndex":1396},{"id":"plato-the-repu-936","text":"Therefore, I said, the judge should not be young; he should have\r learned to know evil, not from his own soul, but from late and long\r observation of the nature of evil in others: knowledge should be his\r guide, not personal experience.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"936"},"sequenceIndex":1397},{"id":"plato-the-repu-937","text":"Yes, I replied, and he will be a good man (which is my answer to your\r question); for he is good who has a good soul. But the cunning and\r suspicious nature of which we spoke,—he who has committed many crimes,\r and fancies himself to be a master in wickedness, when he is amongst\r his fellows, is wonderful in the precautions which he takes, because he\r judges of them by himself: but when he gets into the company of men of\r virtue, who have the experience of age, he appears to be a fool again,\r owing to his unseasonable suspicions; he cannot recognise an honest\r man, because he has no pattern of","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"937"},"sequenceIndex":1398},{"id":"plato-the-repu-938","text":"Then the good and wise judge whom we are seeking is not this man, but\r the other; for vice cannot know virtue too, but a virtuous nature,\r educated by time, will acquire a knowledge both of virtue and vice: the\r virtuous, and not the vicious, man has wisdom—in my opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"938"},"sequenceIndex":1399},{"id":"plato-the-repu-939","text":"This is the sort of medicine, and this is the sort of law, which you\r will sanction in your state. They will minister to better natures,\r giving health both of soul and of body; but those who are diseased in\r their bodies they will leave to die, and the corrupt and incurable\r souls they will put an end to themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"939"},"sequenceIndex":1400},{"id":"plato-the-repu-940","text":"And thus our youth, having been educated only in that simple music\r which, as we said, inspires temperance, will be reluctant to go to law.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"940"},"sequenceIndex":1401},{"id":"plato-the-repu-941","text":"And the musician, who, keeping to the same track, is content to\r practise the simple gymnastic, will have nothing to do with medicine\r unless in some extreme case.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"941"},"sequenceIndex":1402},{"id":"plato-the-repu-942","text":"The very exercises and tolls which he undergoes are intended to\r stimulate the spirited element of his nature, and not to increase his\r strength; he will not, like common athletes, use exercise and regimen\r to develope his muscles.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"942"},"sequenceIndex":1403},{"id":"plato-the-repu-943","text":"Neither are the two arts of music and gymnastic really designed, as is\r often supposed, the one for the training of the soul, the other for the\r training of the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"943"},"sequenceIndex":1404},{"id":"plato-the-repu-944","text":"I believe, I said, that the teachers of both have in view chiefly the\r improvement of the soul.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"944"},"sequenceIndex":1405},{"id":"plato-the-repu-945","text":"Did you never observe, I said, the effect on the mind itself of\r exclusive devotion to gymnastic, or the opposite effect of an exclusive\r devotion to music?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"945"},"sequenceIndex":1406},{"id":"plato-the-repu-946","text":"The one producing a temper of hardness and ferocity, the other of\r softness and effeminacy, I replied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"946"},"sequenceIndex":1407},{"id":"plato-the-repu-947","text":"Yes, he said, I am quite aware that the mere athlete becomes too much\r of a savage, and that the mere musician is melted and softened beyond\r what is good for him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"947"},"sequenceIndex":1408},{"id":"plato-the-repu-948","text":"Yet surely, I said, this ferocity only comes from spirit, which, if\r rightly educated, would give courage, but, if too much intensified, is\r liable to become hard and brutal.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"948"},"sequenceIndex":1409},{"id":"plato-the-repu-949","text":"On the other hand the philosopher will have the quality of gentleness.\r And this also, when too much indulged, will turn to softness, but, if\r educated rightly, will be gentle and moderate.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"949"},"sequenceIndex":1410},{"id":"plato-the-repu-950","text":"And, when a man allows music to play upon him and to pour into his soul\r through the funnel of his ears those sweet and soft and melancholy airs\r of which we were just now speaking, and his whole life is passed in\r warbling and the delights of song; in the first stage of the process\r the passion or spirit which is in him is tempered like iron, and made\r useful, instead of brittle and useless. But, if he carries on the\r softening and soothing process, in the next stage he begins to melt and\r waste, until he has wasted away his spirit and cut out the sinews of\r his soul; and he becomes a feeble ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"950"},"sequenceIndex":1411},{"id":"plato-the-repu-951","text":"If the element of spirit is naturally weak in him the change is\r speedily accomplished, but if he have a good deal, then the power of\r music weakening the spirit renders him excitable;—on the least\r provocation he flames up at once, and is speedily extinguished; instead\r of having spirit he grows irritable and passionate and is quite\r impracticable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"951"},"sequenceIndex":1412},{"id":"plato-the-repu-952","text":"And so in gymnastics, if a man takes violent exercise and is a great\r feeder, and the reverse of a great student of music and philosophy, at\r first the high condition of his body fills him with pride and spirit,\r and he becomes twice the man that he was.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"952"},"sequenceIndex":1413},{"id":"plato-the-repu-953","text":"And what happens? if he do nothing else, and holds no converse with the\r Muses, does not even that intelligence which there may be in him,\r having no taste of any sort of learning or enquiry or thought or\r culture, grow feeble and dull and blind, his mind never waking up or\r receiving nourishment, and his senses not being purged of their mists?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"953"},"sequenceIndex":1414},{"id":"plato-the-repu-954","text":"And he ends by becoming a hater of philosophy, uncivilized, never using\r the weapon of persuasion,—he is like a wild beast, all violence and\r fierceness, and knows no other way of dealing; and he lives in all\r ignorance and evil conditions, and has no sense of propriety and grace.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"954"},"sequenceIndex":1415},{"id":"plato-the-repu-955","text":"And as there are two principles of human nature, one the spirited and\r the other the philosophical, some God, as I should say, has given\r mankind two arts answering to them (and only indirectly to the soul and\r body), in order that these two principles (like the strings of an\r instrument) may be relaxed or drawn tighter until they are duly\r harmonized.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"955"},"sequenceIndex":1416},{"id":"plato-the-repu-956","text":"And he who mingles music with gymnastic in the fairest proportions, and\r best attempers them to the soul, may be rightly called the true\r musician and harmonist in a far higher sense than the tuner of the\r strings.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"956"},"sequenceIndex":1417},{"id":"plato-the-repu-957","text":"And such a presiding genius will be always required in our State if the\r government is to last.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"957"},"sequenceIndex":1418},{"id":"plato-the-repu-958","text":"Such, then, are our principles of nurture and education: Where would be\r the use of going into further details about the dances of our citizens,\r or about their hunting and coursing, their gymnastic and equestrian\r contests? For these all follow the general principle, and having found\r that, we shall have no difficulty in discovering them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"958"},"sequenceIndex":1419},{"id":"plato-the-repu-959","text":"Very good, I said; then what is the next question? Must we not ask who\r are to be rulers and who subjects?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"959"},"sequenceIndex":1420},{"id":"plato-the-repu-960","text":"And as we are to have the best of guardians for our city, must they not\r be those who have most the character of guardians?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"960"},"sequenceIndex":1421},{"id":"plato-the-repu-961","text":"And to this end they ought to be wise and efficient, and to have a\r special care of the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"961"},"sequenceIndex":1422},{"id":"plato-the-repu-962","text":"And he will be most likely to love that which he regards as having the\r same interests with himself, and that of which the good or evil fortune\r is supposed by him at any time most to affect his own?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"962"},"sequenceIndex":1423},{"id":"plato-the-repu-963","text":"Then there must be a selection. Let us note among the guardians those\r who in their whole life show the greatest eagerness to do what is for\r the good of their country, and the greatest repugnance to do what is\r against her interests.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"963"},"sequenceIndex":1424},{"id":"plato-the-repu-964","text":"And they will have to be watched at every age, in order that we may see\r whether they preserve their resolution, and never, under the influence\r either of force or enchantment, forget or cast off their sense of duty\r to the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"964"},"sequenceIndex":1425},{"id":"plato-the-repu-965","text":"I will explain to you, I replied. A resolution may go out of a man’s\r mind either with his will or against his will; with his will when he\r gets rid of a falsehood and learns better, against his will whenever he\r is deprived of a truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"965"},"sequenceIndex":1426},{"id":"plato-the-repu-966","text":"I understand, he said, the willing loss of a resolution; the meaning of\r the unwilling I have yet to learn.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"966"},"sequenceIndex":1427},{"id":"plato-the-repu-967","text":"Why, I said, do you not see that men are unwillingly deprived of good,\r and willingly of evil? Is not to have lost the truth an evil, and to\r possess the truth a good? and you would agree that to conceive things\r as they are is to possess the truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"967"},"sequenceIndex":1428},{"id":"plato-the-repu-968","text":"Yes, he replied; I agree with you in thinking that mankind are deprived\r of truth against their will.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"968"},"sequenceIndex":1429},{"id":"plato-the-repu-969","text":"And is not this involuntary deprivation caused either by theft, or\r force, or enchantment?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"969"},"sequenceIndex":1430},{"id":"plato-the-repu-970","text":"I fear that I must have been talking darkly, like the tragedians. I\r only mean that some men are changed by persuasion and that others\r forget; argument steals away the hearts of one class, and time of the\r other; and this I call theft. Now you understand me?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"970"},"sequenceIndex":1431},{"id":"plato-the-repu-971","text":"Those again who are forced, are those whom the violence of some pain or\r grief compels to change their opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"971"},"sequenceIndex":1432},{"id":"plato-the-repu-972","text":"And you would also acknowledge that the enchanted are those who change\r their minds either under the softer influence of pleasure, or the\r sterner influence of fear?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"972"},"sequenceIndex":1433},{"id":"plato-the-repu-973","text":"Therefore, as I was just now saying, we must enquire who are the best\r guardians of their own conviction that what they think the interest of\r the State is to be the rule of their lives. We must watch them from\r their youth upwards, and make them perform actions in which they are\r most likely to forget or to be deceived, and he who remembers and is\r not deceived is to be selected, and he who fails in the trial is to be\r rejected. That will be the way?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"973"},"sequenceIndex":1434},{"id":"plato-the-repu-974","text":"And there should also be toils and pains and conflicts prescribed for\r them, in which they will be made to give further proof of the same\r qualities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"974"},"sequenceIndex":1435},{"id":"plato-the-repu-975","text":"And then, I said, we must try them with enchantments—that is the third\r sort of test—and see what will be their behaviour: like those who take\r colts amid noise and tumult to see if they are of a timid nature, so\r must we take our youth amid terrors of some kind, and again pass them\r into pleasures, and prove them more thoroughly than gold is proved in\r the furnace, that we may discover whether they are armed against all\r enchantments, and of a noble bearing always, good guardians of\r themselves and of the music which they have learned, and retaining\r under all circumstances a rhythmical and h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"975"},"sequenceIndex":1436},{"id":"plato-the-repu-976","text":"And perhaps the word ‘guardian’ in the fullest sense ought to be\r applied to this higher class only who preserve us against foreign\r enemies and maintain peace among our citizens at home, that the one may\r not have the will, or the others the power, to harm us. The young men\r whom we before called guardians may be more properly designated\r auxiliaries and supporters of the principles of the rulers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"976"},"sequenceIndex":1437},{"id":"plato-the-repu-977","text":"How then may we devise one of those needful falsehoods of which we\r lately spoke—just one royal lie which may deceive the rulers, if that\r be possible, and at any rate the rest of the city?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"977"},"sequenceIndex":1438},{"id":"plato-the-repu-978","text":"Nothing new, I replied; only an old Phoenician tale (Laws) of what has\r often occurred before now in other places, (as the poets say, and have\r made the world believe,) though not in our time, and I do not know\r whether such an event could ever happen again, or could now even be\r made probable, if it did.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"978"},"sequenceIndex":1439},{"id":"plato-the-repu-979","text":"Well then, I will speak, although I really know not how to look you in\r the face, or in what words to utter the audacious fiction, which I\r propose to communicate gradually, first to the rulers, then to the\r soldiers, and lastly to the people. They are to be told that their\r youth was a dream, and the education and training which they received\r from us, an appearance only; in reality during all that time they were\r being formed and fed in the womb of the earth, where they themselves\r and their arms and appurtenances were manufactured; when they were\r completed, the earth, their mother, sent th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"979"},"sequenceIndex":1440},{"id":"plato-the-repu-980","text":"You had good reason, he said, to be ashamed of the lie which you were\r going to tell.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"980"},"sequenceIndex":1441},{"id":"plato-the-repu-981","text":"True, I replied, but there is more coming; I have only told you half.\r Citizens, we shall say to them in our tale, you are brothers, yet God\r has framed you differently. Some of you have the power of command, and\r in the composition of these he has mingled gold, wherefore also they\r have the greatest honour; others he has made of silver, to be\r auxiliaries; others again who are to be husbandmen and craftsmen he has\r composed of brass and iron; and the species will generally be preserved\r in the children. But as all are of the same original stock, a golden\r parent will sometimes have a silver s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"981"},"sequenceIndex":1442},{"id":"plato-the-repu-982","text":"Not in the present generation, he replied; there is no way of\r accomplishing this; but their sons may be made to believe in the tale,\r and their sons’ sons, and posterity after them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"982"},"sequenceIndex":1443},{"id":"plato-the-repu-983","text":"I see the difficulty, I replied; yet the fostering of such a belief\r will make them care more for the city and for one another. Enough,\r however, of the fiction, which may now fly abroad upon the wings of\r rumour, while we arm our earth-born heroes, and lead them forth under\r the command of their rulers. Let them look round and select a spot\r whence they can best suppress insurrection, if any prove refractory\r within, and also defend themselves against enemies, who like wolves may\r come down on the fold from without; there let them encamp, and when\r they have encamped, let them sacrifice to th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"983"},"sequenceIndex":1444},{"id":"plato-the-repu-984","text":"And their dwellings must be such as will shield them against the cold\r of winter and the heat of summer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"984"},"sequenceIndex":1445},{"id":"plato-the-repu-985","text":"That I will endeavour to explain, I replied. To keep watch-dogs, who,\r from want of discipline or hunger, or some evil habit or other, would\r turn upon the sheep and worry them, and behave not like dogs but\r wolves, would be a foul and monstrous thing in a shepherd?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"985"},"sequenceIndex":1446},{"id":"plato-the-repu-986","text":"And therefore every care must be taken that our auxiliaries, being\r stronger than our citizens, may not grow to be too much for them and\r become savage tyrants instead of friends and allies?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"986"},"sequenceIndex":1447},{"id":"plato-the-repu-987","text":"I cannot be so confident, my dear Glaucon, I said; I am much more\r certain that they ought to be, and that true education, whatever that\r may be, will have the greatest tendency to civilize and humanize them\r in their relations to one another, and to those who are under their\r protection.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"987"},"sequenceIndex":1448},{"id":"plato-the-repu-988","text":"And not only their education, but their habitations, and all that\r belongs to them, should be such as will neither impair their virtue as\r guardians, nor tempt them to prey upon the other citizens. Any man of\r sense must acknowledge that.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"988"},"sequenceIndex":1449},{"id":"plato-the-repu-989","text":"Then now let us consider what will be their way of life, if they are to\r realize our idea of them. In the first place, none of them should have\r any property of his own beyond what is absolutely necessary; neither\r should they have a private house or store closed against any one who\r has a mind to enter; their provisions should be only such as are\r required by trained warriors, who are men of temperance and courage;\r they should agree to receive from the citizens a fixed rate of pay,\r enough to meet the expenses of the year and no more; and they will go\r to mess and live together like soldiers","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"989"},"sequenceIndex":1450},{"id":"plato-the-repu-990","text":"Here Adeimantus interposed a question: How would you answer, Socrates,\r said he, if a person were to say that you are making these people\r miserable, and that they are the cause of their own unhappiness; the\r city in fact belongs to them, but they are none the better for it;\r whereas other men acquire lands, and build large and handsome houses,\r and have everything handsome about them, offering sacrifices to the\r gods on their own account, and practising hospitality; moreover, as you\r were saying just now, they have gold and silver, and all that is usual\r among the favourites of fortune; but o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"990"},"sequenceIndex":1451},{"id":"plato-the-repu-991","text":"Yes, I said; and you may add that they are only fed, and not paid in\r addition to their food, like other men; and therefore they cannot, if\r they would, take a journey of pleasure; they have no money to spend on\r a mistress or any other luxurious fancy, which, as the world goes, is\r thought to be happiness; and many other accusations of the same nature\r might be added.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"991"},"sequenceIndex":1452},{"id":"plato-the-repu-992","text":"If we proceed along the old path, my belief, I said, is that we shall\r find the answer. And our answer will be that, even as they are, our\r guardians may very likely be the happiest of men; but that our aim in\r founding the State was not the disproportionate happiness of any one\r class, but the greatest happiness of the whole; we thought that in a\r State which is ordered with a view to the good of the whole we should\r be most likely to find justice, and in the ill-ordered State injustice:\r and, having found them, we might then decide which of the two is the\r happier. At present, I take it, we ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"992"},"sequenceIndex":1453},{"id":"plato-the-repu-993","text":"The process is as follows: When a potter becomes rich, will he, think\r you, any longer take the same pains with his art?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"993"},"sequenceIndex":1454},{"id":"plato-the-repu-994","text":"But, on the other hand, if he has no money, and cannot provide himself\r with tools or instruments, he will not work equally well himself, nor\r will he teach his sons or apprentices to work equally well.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"994"},"sequenceIndex":1455},{"id":"plato-the-repu-995","text":"Then, under the influence either of poverty or of wealth, workmen and\r their work are equally liable to degenerate?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"995"},"sequenceIndex":1456},{"id":"plato-the-repu-996","text":"Here, then, is a discovery of new evils, I said, against which the\r guardians will have to watch, or they will creep into the city\r unobserved.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"996"},"sequenceIndex":1457},{"id":"plato-the-repu-997","text":"Wealth, I said, and poverty; the one is the parent of luxury and\r indolence, and the other of meanness and viciousness, and both of\r discontent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"997"},"sequenceIndex":1458},{"id":"plato-the-repu-998","text":"That is very true, he replied; but still I should like to know,\r Socrates, how our city will be able to go to war, especially against an\r enemy who is rich and powerful, if deprived of the sinews of war.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"998"},"sequenceIndex":1459},{"id":"plato-the-repu-999","text":"There would certainly be a difficulty, I replied, in going to war with\r one such enemy; but there is no difficulty where there are two of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"999"},"sequenceIndex":1460},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1000","text":"In the first place, I said, if we have to fight, our side will be\r trained warriors fighting against an army of rich men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1000"},"sequenceIndex":1461},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1001","text":"And do you not suppose, Adeimantus, that a single boxer who was perfect\r in his art would easily be a match for two stout and well-to-do\r gentlemen who were not boxers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1001"},"sequenceIndex":1462},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1002","text":"What, now, I said, if he were able to run away and then turn and strike\r at the one who first came up? And supposing he were to do this several\r times under the heat of a scorching sun, might he not, being an expert,\r overturn more than one stout personage?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1002"},"sequenceIndex":1463},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1003","text":"And yet rich men probably have a greater superiority in the science and\r practise of boxing than they have in military qualities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1003"},"sequenceIndex":1464},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1004","text":"Then we may assume that our athletes will be able to fight with two or\r three times their own number?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1004"},"sequenceIndex":1465},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1005","text":"And suppose that, before engaging, our citizens send an embassy to one\r of the two cities, telling them what is the truth: Silver and gold we\r neither have nor are permitted to have, but you may; do you therefore\r come and help us in war, and take the spoils of the other city: Who, on\r hearing these words, would choose to fight against lean wiry dogs,\r rather than, with the dogs on their side, against fat and tender sheep?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1005"},"sequenceIndex":1466},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1006","text":"That is not likely; and yet there might be a danger to the poor State\r if the wealth of many States were to be gathered into one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1006"},"sequenceIndex":1467},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1007","text":"You ought to speak of other States in the plural number; not one of\r them is a city, but many cities, as they say in the game. For indeed\r any city, however small, is in fact divided into two, one the city of\r the poor, the other of the rich; these are at war with one another; and\r in either there are many smaller divisions, and you would be altogether\r beside the mark if you treated them all as a single State. But if you\r deal with them as many, and give the wealth or power or persons of the\r one to the others, you will always have a great many friends and not\r many enemies. And your State, w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1007"},"sequenceIndex":1468},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1008","text":"And what, I said, will be the best limit for our rulers to fix when\r they are considering the size of the State and the amount of territory\r which they are to include, and beyond which they will not go?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1008"},"sequenceIndex":1469},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1009","text":"I would allow the State to increase so far as is consistent with unity;\r that, I think, is the proper limit.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1009"},"sequenceIndex":1470},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1010","text":"Here then, I said, is another order which will have to be conveyed to\r our guardians: Let our city be accounted neither large nor small, but\r one and self-sufficing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1010"},"sequenceIndex":1471},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1011","text":"And surely, said he, this is not a very severe order which we impose\r upon them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1011"},"sequenceIndex":1472},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1012","text":"And the other, said I, of which we were speaking before is lighter\r still,—I mean the duty of degrading the offspring of the guardians when\r inferior, and of elevating into the rank of guardians the offspring of\r the lower classes, when naturally superior. The intention was, that, in\r the case of the citizens generally, each individual should be put to\r the use for which nature intended him, one to one work, and then every\r man would do his own business, and be one and not many; and so the\r whole city would be one and not many.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1012"},"sequenceIndex":1473},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1013","text":"The regulations which we are prescribing, my good Adeimantus, are not,\r as might be supposed, a number of great principles, but trifles all, if\r care be taken, as the saying is, of the one great thing,—a thing,\r however, which I would rather call, not great, but sufficient for our\r purpose.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1013"},"sequenceIndex":1474},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1014","text":"Education, I said, and nurture: If our citizens are well educated, and\r grow into sensible men, they will easily see their way through all\r these, as well as other matters which I omit; such, for example, as\r marriage, the possession of women and the procreation of children,\r which will all follow the general principle that friends have all\r things in common, as the proverb says.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1014"},"sequenceIndex":1475},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1015","text":"Also, I said, the State, if once started well, moves with accumulating\r force like a wheel. For good nurture and education implant good\r constitutions, and these good constitutions taking root in a good\r education improve more and more, and this improvement affects the breed\r in man as in other animals.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1015"},"sequenceIndex":1476},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1016","text":"Then to sum up: This is the point to which, above all, the attention of\r our rulers should be directed,—that music and gymnastic be preserved in\r their original form, and no innovation made. They must do their utmost\r to maintain them intact. And when any one says that mankind most regard","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1016"},"sequenceIndex":1477},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1017","text":"they will be afraid that he may be praising, not new songs, but a new\r kind of song; and this ought not to be praised, or conceived to be the\r meaning of the poet; for any musical innovation is full of danger to\r the whole State, and ought to be prohibited. So Damon tells me, and I\r can quite believe him;—he says that when modes of music change, the\r fundamental laws of the State always change with them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1017"},"sequenceIndex":1478},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1018","text":"Then, I said, our guardians must lay the foundations of their fortress\r in music?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1018"},"sequenceIndex":1479},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1019","text":"Yes, I replied, in the form of amusement; and at first sight it appears\r harmless.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1019"},"sequenceIndex":1480},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1020","text":"Why, yes, he said, and there is no harm; were it not that little by\r little this spirit of licence, finding a home, imperceptibly penetrates\r into manners and customs; whence, issuing with greater force, it\r invades contracts between man and man, and from contracts goes on to\r laws and constitutions, in utter recklessness, ending at last,\r Socrates, by an overthrow of all rights, private as well as public.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1020"},"sequenceIndex":1481},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1021","text":"Then, as I was saying, our youth should be trained from the first in a\r stricter system, for if amusements become lawless, and the youths\r themselves become lawless, they can never grow up into well-conducted\r and virtuous citizens.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1021"},"sequenceIndex":1482},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1022","text":"And when they have made a good beginning in play, and by the help of\r music have gained the habit of good order, then this habit of order, in\r a manner how unlike the lawless play of the others! will accompany them\r in all their actions and be a principle of growth to them, and if there\r be any fallen places in the State will raise them up again.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1022"},"sequenceIndex":1483},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1023","text":"Thus educated, they will invent for themselves any lesser rules which\r their predecessors have altogether neglected.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1023"},"sequenceIndex":1484},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1024","text":"I mean such things as these:—when the young are to be silent before\r their elders; how they are to show respect to them by standing and\r making them sit; what honour is due to parents; what garments or shoes\r are to be worn; the mode of dressing the hair; deportment and manners\r in general. You would agree with me?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1024"},"sequenceIndex":1485},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1025","text":"But there is, I think, small wisdom in legislating about such\r matters,—I doubt if it is ever done; nor are any precise written\r enactments about them likely to be lasting.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1025"},"sequenceIndex":1486},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1026","text":"It would seem, Adeimantus, that the direction in which education starts\r a man, will determine his future life. Does not like always attract\r like?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1026"},"sequenceIndex":1487},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1027","text":"Until some one rare and grand result is reached which may be good, and\r may be the reverse of good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1027"},"sequenceIndex":1488},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1028","text":"And for this reason, I said, I shall not attempt to legislate further\r about them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1028"},"sequenceIndex":1489},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1029","text":"Well, and about the business of the agora, and the ordinary dealings\r between man and man, or again about agreements with artisans; about\r insult and injury, or the commencement of actions, and the appointment\r of juries, what would you say? there may also arise questions about any\r impositions and exactions of market and harbour dues which may be\r required, and in general about the regulations of markets, police,\r harbours, and the like. But, oh heavens! shall we condescend to\r legislate on any of these particulars?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1029"},"sequenceIndex":1490},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1030","text":"I think, he said, that there is no need to impose laws about them on\r good men; what regulations are necessary they will find out soon enough\r for themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1030"},"sequenceIndex":1491},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1031","text":"Yes, I said, my friend, if God will only preserve to them the laws\r which we have given them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1031"},"sequenceIndex":1492},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1032","text":"And without divine help, said Adeimantus, they will go on for ever\r making and mending their laws and their lives in the hope of attaining\r perfection.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1032"},"sequenceIndex":1493},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1033","text":"You would compare them, I said, to those invalids who, having no\r self-restraint, will not leave off their habits of intemperance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1033"},"sequenceIndex":1494},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1034","text":"Yes, I said; and what a delightful life they lead! they are always\r doctoring and increasing and complicating their disorders, and always\r fancying that they will be cured by any nostrum which anybody advises\r them to try.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1034"},"sequenceIndex":1495},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1035","text":"Yes, I replied; and the charming thing is that they deem him their\r worst enemy who tells them the truth, which is simply that, unless they\r give up eating and drinking and wenching and idling, neither drug nor\r cautery nor spell nor amulet nor any other remedy will avail.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1035"},"sequenceIndex":1496},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1036","text":"Charming! he replied. I see nothing charming in going into a passion\r with a man who tells you what is right.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1036"},"sequenceIndex":1497},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1037","text":"Nor would you praise the behaviour of States which act like the men\r whom I was just now describing. For are there not ill-ordered States in\r which the citizens are forbidden under pain of death to alter the\r constitution; and yet he who most sweetly courts those who live under\r this regime and indulges them and fawns upon them and is skilful in\r anticipating and gratifying their humours is held to be a great and\r good statesman—do not these States resemble the persons whom I was\r describing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1037"},"sequenceIndex":1498},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1038","text":"Yes, he said; the States are as bad as the men; and I am very far from\r praising them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1038"},"sequenceIndex":1499},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1039","text":"But do you not admire, I said, the coolness and dexterity of these\r ready ministers of political corruption?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1039"},"sequenceIndex":1500},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1040","text":"Yes, he said, I do; but not of all of them, for there are some whom the\r applause of the multitude has deluded into the belief that they are\r really statesmen, and these are not much to be admired.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1040"},"sequenceIndex":1501},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1041","text":"What do you mean? I said; you should have more feeling for them. When a\r man cannot measure, and a great many others who cannot measure declare\r that he is four cubits high, can he help believing what they say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1041"},"sequenceIndex":1502},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1042","text":"Well, then, do not be angry with them; for are they not as good as a\r play, trying their hand at paltry reforms such as I was describing;\r they are always fancying that by legislation they will make an end of\r frauds in contracts, and the other rascalities which I was mentioning,\r not knowing that they are in reality cutting off the heads of a hydra?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1042"},"sequenceIndex":1503},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1043","text":"I conceive, I said, that the true legislator will not trouble himself\r with this class of enactments whether concerning laws or the\r constitution either in an ill-ordered or in a well-ordered State; for\r in the former they are quite useless, and in the latter there will be\r no difficulty in devising them; and many of them will naturally flow\r out of our previous regulations.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1043"},"sequenceIndex":1504},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1044","text":"Nothing to us, I replied; but to Apollo, the God of Delphi, there\r remains the ordering of the greatest and noblest and chiefest things of\r all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1044"},"sequenceIndex":1505},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1045","text":"The institution of temples and sacrifices, and the entire service of\r gods, demigods, and heroes; also the ordering of the repositories of\r the dead, and the rites which have to be observed by him who would\r propitiate the inhabitants of the world below. These are matters of\r which we are ignorant ourselves, and as founders of a city we should be\r unwise in trusting them to any interpreter but our ancestral deity. He\r is the god who sits in the centre, on the navel of the earth, and he is\r the interpreter of religion to all mankind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1045"},"sequenceIndex":1506},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1046","text":"But where, amid all this, is justice? son of Ariston, tell me where.\r Now that our city has been made habitable, light a candle and search,\r and get your brother and Polemarchus and the rest of our friends to\r help, and let us see where in it we can discover justice and where\r injustice, and in what they differ from one another, and which of them\r the man who would be happy should have for his portion, whether seen or\r unseen by gods and men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1046"},"sequenceIndex":1507},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1047","text":"Nonsense, said Glaucon: did you not promise to search yourself, saying\r that for you not to help justice in her need would be an impiety?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1047"},"sequenceIndex":1508},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1048","text":"I do not deny that I said so, and as you remind me, I will be as good\r as my word; but you must join.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1048"},"sequenceIndex":1509},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1049","text":"Well, then, I hope to make the discovery in this way: I mean to begin\r with the assumption that our State, if rightly ordered, is perfect.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1049"},"sequenceIndex":1510},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1050","text":"And whichever of these qualities we find in the State, the one which is\r not found will be the residue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1050"},"sequenceIndex":1511},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1051","text":"If there were four things, and we were searching for one of them,\r wherever it might be, the one sought for might be known to us from the\r first, and there would be no further trouble; or we might know the\r other three first, and then the fourth would clearly be the one left.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1051"},"sequenceIndex":1512},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1052","text":"And is not a similar method to be pursued about the virtues, which are\r also four in number?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1052"},"sequenceIndex":1513},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1053","text":"First among the virtues found in the State, wisdom comes into view, and\r in this I detect a certain peculiarity.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1053"},"sequenceIndex":1514},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1054","text":"The State which we have been describing is said to be wise as being\r good in counsel?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1054"},"sequenceIndex":1515},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1055","text":"And good counsel is clearly a kind of knowledge, for not by ignorance,\r but by knowledge, do men counsel well?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1055"},"sequenceIndex":1516},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1056","text":"There is the knowledge of the carpenter; but is that the sort of\r knowledge which gives a city the title of wise and good in counsel?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1056"},"sequenceIndex":1517},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1057","text":"Certainly not; that would only give a city the reputation of skill in\r carpentering.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1057"},"sequenceIndex":1518},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1058","text":"Then a city is not to be called wise because possessing a knowledge\r which counsels for the best about wooden implements?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1058"},"sequenceIndex":1519},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1059","text":"Nor by reason of a knowledge which advises about brazen pots, I said,\r nor as possessing any other similar knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1059"},"sequenceIndex":1520},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1060","text":"Nor yet by reason of a knowledge which cultivates the earth; that would\r give the city the name of agricultural?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1060"},"sequenceIndex":1521},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1061","text":"Well, I said, and is there any knowledge in our recently-founded State\r among any of the citizens which advises, not about any particular thing\r in the State, but about the whole, and considers how a State can best\r deal with itself and with other States?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1061"},"sequenceIndex":1522},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1062","text":"It is the knowledge of the guardians, he replied, and is found among\r those whom we were just now describing as perfect guardians.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1062"},"sequenceIndex":1523},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1063","text":"And what is the name which the city derives from the possession of this\r sort of knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1063"},"sequenceIndex":1524},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1064","text":"Will not the guardians be the smallest of all the classes who receive a\r name from the profession of some kind of knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1064"},"sequenceIndex":1525},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1065","text":"And so by reason of the smallest part or class, and of the knowledge\r which resides in this presiding and ruling part of itself, the whole\r State, being thus constituted according to nature, will be wise; and\r this, which has the only knowledge worthy to be called wisdom, has been\r ordained by nature to be of all classes the least.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1065"},"sequenceIndex":1526},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1066","text":"Thus, then, I said, the nature and place in the State of one of the\r four virtues has somehow or other been discovered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1066"},"sequenceIndex":1527},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1067","text":"Again, I said, there is no difficulty in seeing the nature of courage,\r and in what part that quality resides which gives the name of\r courageous to the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1067"},"sequenceIndex":1528},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1068","text":"Why, I said, every one who calls any State courageous or cowardly, will\r be thinking of the part which fights and goes out to war on the State’s\r behalf.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1068"},"sequenceIndex":1529},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1069","text":"The rest of the citizens may be courageous or may be cowardly, but\r their courage or cowardice will not, as I conceive, have the effect of\r making the city either the one or the other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1069"},"sequenceIndex":1530},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1070","text":"The city will be courageous in virtue of a portion of herself which\r preserves under all circumstances that opinion about the nature of\r things to be feared and not to be feared in which our legislator\r educated them; and this is what you term courage.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1070"},"sequenceIndex":1531},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1071","text":"I should like to hear what you are saying once more, for I do not think\r that I perfectly understand you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1071"},"sequenceIndex":1532},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1072","text":"Of the opinion respecting things to be feared, what they are and of\r what nature, which the law implants through education; and I mean by\r the words ‘under all circumstances’ to intimate that in pleasure or in\r pain, or under the influence of desire or fear, a man preserves, and\r does not lose this opinion. Shall I give you an illustration?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1072"},"sequenceIndex":1533},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1073","text":"You know, I said, that dyers, when they want to dye wool for making the\r true sea-purple, begin by selecting their white colour first; this they\r prepare and dress with much care and pains, in order that the white\r ground may take the purple hue in full perfection. The dyeing then\r proceeds; and whatever is dyed in this manner becomes a fast colour,\r and no washing either with lyes or without them can take away the\r bloom. But, when the ground has not been duly prepared, you will have\r noticed how poor is the look either of purple or of any other colour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1073"},"sequenceIndex":1534},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1074","text":"Then now, I said, you will understand what our object was in selecting\r our soldiers, and educating them in music and gymnastic; we were\r contriving influences which would prepare them to take the dye of the\r laws in perfection, and the colour of their opinion about dangers and\r of every other opinion was to be indelibly fixed by their nurture and\r training, not to be washed away by such potent lyes as\r pleasure—mightier agent far in washing the soul than any soda or lye;\r or by sorrow, fear, and desire, the mightiest of all other solvents.\r And this sort of universal saving power of true opin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1074"},"sequenceIndex":1535},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1075","text":"But I agree, he replied; for I suppose that you mean to exclude mere\r uninstructed courage, such as that of a wild beast or of a slave—this,\r in your opinion, is not the courage which the law ordains, and ought to\r have another name.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1075"},"sequenceIndex":1536},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1076","text":"Why, yes, said I, you may, and if you add the words ‘of a citizen,’ you\r will not be far wrong;—hereafter, if you like, we will carry the\r examination further, but at present we are seeking not for courage but\r justice; and for the purpose of our enquiry we have said enough.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1076"},"sequenceIndex":1537},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1077","text":"Two virtues remain to be discovered in the State—first, temperance, and\r then justice which is the end of our search.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1077"},"sequenceIndex":1538},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1078","text":"I do not know how that can be accomplished, he said, nor do I desire\r that justice should be brought to light and temperance lost sight of;\r and therefore I wish that you would do me the favour of considering\r temperance first.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1078"},"sequenceIndex":1539},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1079","text":"Yes, I replied; I will; and as far as I can at present see, the virtue\r of temperance has more of the nature of harmony and symphony than the\r preceding.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1079"},"sequenceIndex":1540},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1080","text":"Temperance, I replied, is the ordering or controlling of certain\r pleasures and desires; this is curiously enough implied in the saying\r of ‘a man being his own master;’ and other traces of the same notion\r may be found in language.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1080"},"sequenceIndex":1541},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1081","text":"There is something ridiculous in the expression ‘master of himself;’\r for the master is also the servant and the servant the master; and in\r all these modes of speaking the same person is denoted.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1081"},"sequenceIndex":1542},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1082","text":"The meaning is, I believe, that in the human soul there is a better and\r also a worse principle; and when the better has the worse under\r control, then a man is said to be master of himself; and this is a term\r of praise: but when, owing to evil education or association, the better\r principle, which is also the smaller, is overwhelmed by the greater\r mass of the worse—in this case he is blamed and is called the slave of\r self and unprincipled.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1082"},"sequenceIndex":1543},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1083","text":"And now, I said, look at our newly-created State, and there you will\r find one of these two conditions realized; for the State, as you will\r acknowledge, may be justly called master of itself, if the words\r ‘temperance’ and ‘self-mastery’ truly express the rule of the better\r part over the worse.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1083"},"sequenceIndex":1544},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1084","text":"Let me further note that the manifold and complex pleasures and desires\r and pains are generally found in children and women and servants, and\r in the freemen so called who are of the lowest and more numerous class.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1084"},"sequenceIndex":1545},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1085","text":"Whereas the simple and moderate desires which follow reason, and are\r under the guidance of mind and true opinion, are to be found only in a\r few, and those the best born and best educated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1085"},"sequenceIndex":1546},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1086","text":"These two, as you may perceive, have a place in our State; and the\r meaner desires of the many are held down by the virtuous desires and\r wisdom of the few.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1086"},"sequenceIndex":1547},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1087","text":"Then if there be any city which may be described as master of its own\r pleasures and desires, and master of itself, ours may claim such a\r designation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1087"},"sequenceIndex":1548},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1088","text":"And if there be any State in which rulers and subjects will be agreed\r as to the question who are to rule, that again will be our State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1088"},"sequenceIndex":1549},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1089","text":"And the citizens being thus agreed among themselves, in which class\r will temperance be found—in the rulers or in the subjects?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1089"},"sequenceIndex":1550},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1090","text":"Do you observe that we were not far wrong in our guess that temperance\r was a sort of harmony?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1090"},"sequenceIndex":1551},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1091","text":"Why, because temperance is unlike courage and wisdom, each of which\r resides in a part only, the one making the State wise and the other\r valiant; not so temperance, which extends to the whole, and runs\r through all the notes of the scale, and produces a harmony of the\r weaker and the stronger and the middle class, whether you suppose them\r to be stronger or weaker in wisdom or power or numbers or wealth, or\r anything else. Most truly then may we deem temperance to be the\r agreement of the naturally superior and inferior, as to the right to\r rule of either, both in states and individuals.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1091"},"sequenceIndex":1552},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1092","text":"And so, I said, we may consider three out of the four virtues to have\r been discovered in our State. The last of those qualities which make a\r state virtuous must be justice, if we only knew what that was.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1092"},"sequenceIndex":1553},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1093","text":"The time then has arrived, Glaucon, when, like huntsmen, we should\r surround the cover, and look sharp that justice does not steal away,\r and pass out of sight and escape us; for beyond a doubt she is\r somewhere in this country: watch therefore and strive to catch a sight\r of her, and if you see her first, let me know.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1093"},"sequenceIndex":1554},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1094","text":"Would that I could! but you should regard me rather as a follower who\r has just eyes enough to see what you show him—that is about as much as\r I am good for.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1094"},"sequenceIndex":1555},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1095","text":"Here is no path, I said, and the wood is dark and perplexing; still we\r must push on.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1095"},"sequenceIndex":1556},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1096","text":"Here I saw something: Halloo! I said, I begin to perceive a track, and\r I believe that the quarry will not escape.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1096"},"sequenceIndex":1557},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1097","text":"Why, my good sir, at the beginning of our enquiry, ages ago, there was\r justice tumbling out at our feet, and we never saw her; nothing could\r be more ridiculous. Like people who go about looking for what they have\r in their hands—that was the way with us—we looked not at what we were\r seeking, but at what was far off in the distance; and therefore, I\r suppose, we missed her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1097"},"sequenceIndex":1558},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1098","text":"I mean to say that in reality for a long time past we have been talking\r of justice, and have failed to recognise her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1098"},"sequenceIndex":1559},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1099","text":"Well then, tell me, I said, whether I am right or not: You remember the\r original principle which we were always laying down at the foundation\r of the State, that one man should practise one thing only, the thing to\r which his nature was best adapted;—now justice is this principle or a\r part of it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1099"},"sequenceIndex":1560},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1100","text":"Further, we affirmed that justice was doing one’s own business, and not\r being a busybody; we said so again and again, and many others have said\r the same to us.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1100"},"sequenceIndex":1561},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1101","text":"Then to do one’s own business in a certain way may be assumed to be\r justice. Can you tell me whence I derive this inference?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1101"},"sequenceIndex":1562},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1102","text":"Because I think that this is the only virtue which remains in the State\r when the other virtues of temperance and courage and wisdom are\r abstracted; and, that this is the ultimate cause and condition of the\r existence of all of them, and while remaining in them is also their\r preservative; and we were saying that if the three were discovered by\r us, justice would be the fourth or remaining one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1102"},"sequenceIndex":1563},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1103","text":"If we are asked to determine which of these four qualities by its\r presence contributes most to the excellence of the State, whether the\r agreement of rulers and subjects, or the preservation in the soldiers\r of the opinion which the law ordains about the true nature of dangers,\r or wisdom and watchfulness in the rulers, or whether this other which I\r am mentioning, and which is found in children and women, slave and\r freeman, artisan, ruler, subject,—the quality, I mean, of every one\r doing his own work, and not being a busybody, would claim the palm—the\r question is not so easily answered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1103"},"sequenceIndex":1564},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1104","text":"Then the power of each individual in the State to do his own work\r appears to compete with the other political virtues, wisdom,\r temperance, courage.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1104"},"sequenceIndex":1565},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1105","text":"Let us look at the question from another point of view: Are not the\r rulers in a State those to whom you would entrust the office of\r determining suits at law?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1105"},"sequenceIndex":1566},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1106","text":"And are suits decided on any other ground but that a man may neither\r take what is another’s, nor be deprived of what is his own?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1106"},"sequenceIndex":1567},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1107","text":"Then on this view also justice will be admitted to be the having and\r doing what is a man’s own, and belongs to him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1107"},"sequenceIndex":1568},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1108","text":"Think, now, and say whether you agree with me or not. Suppose a\r carpenter to be doing the business of a cobbler, or a cobbler of a\r carpenter; and suppose them to exchange their implements or their\r duties, or the same person to be doing the work of both, or whatever be\r the change; do you think that any great harm would result to the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1108"},"sequenceIndex":1569},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1109","text":"But when the cobbler or any other man whom nature designed to be a\r trader, having his heart lifted up by wealth or strength or the number\r of his followers, or any like advantage, attempts to force his way into\r the class of warriors, or a warrior into that of legislators and\r guardians, for which he is unfitted, and either to take the implements\r or the duties of the other; or when one man is trader, legislator, and\r warrior all in one, then I think you will agree with me in saying that\r this interchange and this meddling of one with another is the ruin of\r the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1109"},"sequenceIndex":1570},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1110","text":"Seeing then, I said, that there are three distinct classes, any\r meddling of one with another, or the change of one into another, is the\r greatest harm to the State, and may be most justly termed evil-doing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1110"},"sequenceIndex":1571},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1111","text":"And the greatest degree of evil-doing to one’s own city would be termed\r by you injustice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1111"},"sequenceIndex":1572},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1112","text":"This then is injustice; and on the other hand when the trader, the\r auxiliary, and the guardian each do their own business, that is\r justice, and will make the city just.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1112"},"sequenceIndex":1573},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1113","text":"We will not, I said, be over-positive as yet; but if, on trial, this\r conception of justice be verified in the individual as well as in the\r State, there will be no longer any room for doubt; if it be not\r verified, we must have a fresh enquiry. First let us complete the old\r investigation, which we began, as you remember, under the impression\r that, if we could previously examine justice on the larger scale, there\r would be less difficulty in discerning her in the individual. That\r larger example appeared to be the State, and accordingly we constructed\r as good a one as we could, knowing well","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1113"},"sequenceIndex":1574},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1114","text":"I proceeded to ask: When two things, a greater and less, are called by\r the same name, are they like or unlike in so far as they are called the\r same?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1114"},"sequenceIndex":1575},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1115","text":"The just man then, if we regard the idea of justice only, will be like\r the just State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1115"},"sequenceIndex":1576},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1116","text":"And a State was thought by us to be just when the three classes in the\r State severally did their own business; and also thought to be\r temperate and valiant and wise by reason of certain other affections\r and qualities of these same classes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1116"},"sequenceIndex":1577},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1117","text":"And so of the individual; we may assume that he has the same three\r principles in his own soul which are found in the State; and he may be\r rightly described in the same terms, because he is affected in the same\r manner?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1117"},"sequenceIndex":1578},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1118","text":"Once more then, O my friend, we have alighted upon an easy\r question—whether the soul has these three principles or not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1118"},"sequenceIndex":1579},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1119","text":"An easy question! Nay, rather, Socrates, the proverb holds that hard is\r the good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1119"},"sequenceIndex":1580},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1120","text":"Very true, I said; and I do not think that the method which we are\r employing is at all adequate to the accurate solution of this question;\r the true method is another and a longer one. Still we may arrive at a\r solution not below the level of the previous enquiry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1120"},"sequenceIndex":1581},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1121","text":"May we not be satisfied with that? he said;—under the circumstances, I\r am quite content.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1121"},"sequenceIndex":1582},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1122","text":"Must we not acknowledge, I said, that in each of us there are the same\r principles and habits which there are in the State; and that from the\r individual they pass into the State?—how else can they come there? Take\r the quality of passion or spirit;—it would be ridiculous to imagine\r that this quality, when found in States, is not derived from the\r individuals who are supposed to possess it, e.g. the Thracians,\r Scythians, and in general the northern nations; and the same may be\r said of the love of knowledge, which is the special characteristic of\r our part of the world, or of the love of mon","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1122"},"sequenceIndex":1583},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1123","text":"But the question is not quite so easy when we proceed to ask whether\r these principles are three or one; whether, that is to say, we learn\r with one part of our nature, are angry with another, and with a third\r part desire the satisfaction of our natural appetites; or whether the\r whole soul comes into play in each sort of action—to determine that is\r the difficulty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1123"},"sequenceIndex":1584},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1124","text":"I replied as follows: The same thing clearly cannot act or be acted\r upon in the same part or in relation to the same thing at the same\r time, in contrary ways; and therefore whenever this contradiction\r occurs in things apparently the same, we know that they are really not\r the same, but different.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1124"},"sequenceIndex":1585},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1125","text":"For example, I said, can the same thing be at rest and in motion at the\r same time in the same part?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1125"},"sequenceIndex":1586},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1126","text":"Still, I said, let us have a more precise statement of terms, lest we\r should hereafter fall out by the way. Imagine the case of a man who is\r standing and also moving his hands and his head, and suppose a person\r to say that one and the same person is in motion and at rest at the\r same moment—to such a mode of speech we should object, and should\r rather say that one part of him is in motion while another is at rest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1126"},"sequenceIndex":1587},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1127","text":"And suppose the objector to refine still further, and to draw the nice\r distinction that not only parts of tops, but whole tops, when they spin\r round with their pegs fixed on the spot, are at rest and in motion at\r the same time (and he may say the same of anything which revolves in\r the same spot), his objection would not be admitted by us, because in\r such cases things are not at rest and in motion in the same parts of\r themselves; we should rather say that they have both an axis and a\r circumference, and that the axis stands still, for there is no\r deviation from the perpendicular; and tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1127"},"sequenceIndex":1588},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1128","text":"Then none of these objections will confuse us, or incline us to believe\r that the same thing at the same time, in the same part or in relation\r to the same thing, can act or be acted upon in contrary ways.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1128"},"sequenceIndex":1589},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1129","text":"Yet, I said, that we may not be compelled to examine all such\r objections, and prove at length that they are untrue, let us assume\r their absurdity, and go forward on the understanding that hereafter, if\r this assumption turn out to be untrue, all the consequences which\r follow shall be withdrawn.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1129"},"sequenceIndex":1590},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1130","text":"Well, I said, would you not allow that assent and dissent, desire and\r aversion, attraction and repulsion, are all of them opposites, whether\r they are regarded as active or passive (for that makes no difference in\r the fact of their opposition)?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1130"},"sequenceIndex":1591},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1131","text":"Well, I said, and hunger and thirst, and the desires in general, and\r again willing and wishing,—all these you would refer to the classes\r already mentioned. You would say—would you not?—that the soul of him\r who desires is seeking after the object of his desire; or that he is\r drawing to himself the thing which he wishes to possess: or again, when\r a person wants anything to be given him, his mind, longing for the\r realization of his desire, intimates his wish to have it by a nod of\r assent, as if he had been asked a question?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1131"},"sequenceIndex":1592},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1132","text":"And what would you say of unwillingness and dislike and the absence of\r desire; should not these be referred to the opposite class of repulsion\r and rejection?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1132"},"sequenceIndex":1593},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1133","text":"Admitting this to be true of desire generally, let us suppose a\r particular class of desires, and out of these we will select hunger and\r thirst, as they are termed, which are the most obvious of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1133"},"sequenceIndex":1594},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1134","text":"And here comes the point: is not thirst the desire which the soul has\r of drink, and of drink only; not of drink qualified by anything else;\r for example, warm or cold, or much or little, or, in a word, drink of\r any particular sort: but if the thirst be accompanied by heat, then the\r desire is of cold drink; or, if accompanied by cold, then of warm\r drink; or, if the thirst be excessive, then the drink which is desired\r will be excessive; or, if not great, the quantity of drink will also be\r small: but thirst pure and simple will desire drink pure and simple,\r which is the natural satisfactio","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1134"},"sequenceIndex":1595},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1135","text":"Yes, he said; the simple desire is, as you say, in every case of the\r simple object, and the qualified desire of the qualified object.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1135"},"sequenceIndex":1596},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1136","text":"But here a confusion may arise; and I should wish to guard against an\r opponent starting up and saying that no man desires drink only, but\r good drink, or food only, but good food; for good is the universal\r object of desire, and thirst being a desire, will necessarily be thirst\r after good drink; and the same is true of every other desire.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1136"},"sequenceIndex":1597},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1137","text":"Nevertheless I should still maintain, that of relatives some have a\r quality attached to either term of the relation; others are simple and\r have their correlatives simple.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1137"},"sequenceIndex":1598},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1138","text":"And the sometime greater to the sometime less, and the greater that is\r to be to the less that is to be?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1138"},"sequenceIndex":1599},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1139","text":"And so of more and less, and of other correlative terms, such as the\r double and the half, or again, the heavier and the lighter, the swifter\r and the slower; and of hot and cold, and of any other relatives;—is not\r this true of all of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1139"},"sequenceIndex":1600},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1140","text":"And does not the same principle hold in the sciences? The object of\r science is knowledge (assuming that to be the true definition), but the\r object of a particular science is a particular kind of knowledge; I\r mean, for example, that the science of house-building is a kind of\r knowledge which is defined and distinguished from other kinds and is\r therefore termed architecture.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1140"},"sequenceIndex":1601},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1141","text":"And it has this particular quality because it has an object of a\r particular kind; and this is true of the other arts and sciences?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1141"},"sequenceIndex":1602},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1142","text":"Now, then, if I have made myself clear, you will understand my original\r meaning in what I said about relatives. My meaning was, that if one\r term of a relation is taken alone, the other is taken alone; if one\r term is qualified, the other is also qualified. I do not mean to say\r that relatives may not be disparate, or that the science of health is\r healthy, or of disease necessarily diseased, or that the sciences of\r good and evil are therefore good and evil; but only that, when the term\r science is no longer used absolutely, but has a qualified object which\r in this case is the nature of hea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1142"},"sequenceIndex":1603},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1143","text":"Would you not say that thirst is one of these essentially relative\r terms, having clearly a relation—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1143"},"sequenceIndex":1604},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1144","text":"And a certain kind of thirst is relative to a certain kind of drink;\r but thirst taken alone is neither of much nor little, nor of good nor\r bad, nor of any particular kind of drink, but of drink only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1144"},"sequenceIndex":1605},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1145","text":"Then the soul of the thirsty one, in so far as he is thirsty, desires\r only drink; for this he yearns and tries to obtain it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1145"},"sequenceIndex":1606},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1146","text":"And if you suppose something which pulls a thirsty soul away from\r drink, that must be different from the thirsty principle which draws\r him like a beast to drink; for, as we were saying, the same thing\r cannot at the same time with the same part of itself act in contrary\r ways about the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1146"},"sequenceIndex":1607},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1147","text":"No more than you can say that the hands of the archer push and pull the\r bow at the same time, but what you say is that one hand pushes and the\r other pulls.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1147"},"sequenceIndex":1608},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1148","text":"And in such a case what is one to say? Would you not say that there was\r something in the soul bidding a man to drink, and something else\r forbidding him, which is other and stronger than the principle which\r bids him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1148"},"sequenceIndex":1609},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1149","text":"And the forbidding principle is derived from reason, and that which\r bids and attracts proceeds from passion and disease?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1149"},"sequenceIndex":1610},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1150","text":"Then we may fairly assume that they are two, and that they differ from\r one another; the one with which a man reasons, we may call the rational\r principle of the soul, the other, with which he loves and hungers and\r thirsts and feels the flutterings of any other desire, may be termed\r the irrational or appetitive, the ally of sundry pleasures and\r satisfactions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1150"},"sequenceIndex":1611},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1151","text":"Then let us finally determine that there are two principles existing in\r the soul. And what of passion, or spirit? Is it a third, or akin to one\r of the preceding?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1151"},"sequenceIndex":1612},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1152","text":"Well, I said, there is a story which I remember to have heard, and in\r which I put faith. The story is, that Leontius, the son of Aglaion,\r coming up one day from the Piraeus, under the north wall on the\r outside, observed some dead bodies lying on the ground at the place of\r execution. He felt a desire to see them, and also a dread and\r abhorrence of them; for a time he struggled and covered his eyes, but\r at length the desire got the better of him; and forcing them open, he\r ran up to the dead bodies, saying, Look, ye wretches, take your fill of\r the fair sight.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1152"},"sequenceIndex":1613},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1153","text":"The moral of the tale is, that anger at times goes to war with desire,\r as though they were two distinct things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1153"},"sequenceIndex":1614},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1154","text":"And are there not many other cases in which we observe that when a\r man’s desires violently prevail over his reason, he reviles himself,\r and is angry at the violence within him, and that in this struggle,\r which is like the struggle of factions in a State, his spirit is on the\r side of his reason;—but for the passionate or spirited element to take\r part with the desires when reason decides that she should not be\r opposed, is a sort of thing which I believe that you never observed\r occurring in yourself, nor, as I should imagine, in any one else?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1154"},"sequenceIndex":1615},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1155","text":"Suppose that a man thinks he has done a wrong to another, the nobler he\r is the less able is he to feel indignant at any suffering, such as\r hunger, or cold, or any other pain which the injured person may inflict\r upon him—these he deems to be just, and, as I say, his anger refuses to\r be excited by them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1155"},"sequenceIndex":1616},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1156","text":"But when he thinks that he is the sufferer of the wrong, then he boils\r and chafes, and is on the side of what he believes to be justice; and\r because he suffers hunger or cold or other pain he is only the more\r determined to persevere and conquer. His noble spirit will not be\r quelled until he either slays or is slain; or until he hears the voice\r of the shepherd, that is, reason, bidding his dog bark no more.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1156"},"sequenceIndex":1617},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1157","text":"The illustration is perfect, he replied; and in our State, as we were\r saying, the auxiliaries were to be dogs, and to hear the voice of the\r rulers, who are their shepherds.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1157"},"sequenceIndex":1618},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1158","text":"I perceive, I said, that you quite understand me; there is, however, a\r further point which I wish you to consider.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1158"},"sequenceIndex":1619},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1159","text":"You remember that passion or spirit appeared at first sight to be a\r kind of desire, but now we should say quite the contrary; for in the\r conflict of the soul spirit is arrayed on the side of the rational\r principle.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1159"},"sequenceIndex":1620},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1160","text":"But a further question arises: Is passion different from reason also,\r or only a kind of reason; in which latter case, instead of three\r principles in the soul, there will only be two, the rational and the\r concupiscent; or rather, as the State was composed of three classes,\r traders, auxiliaries, counsellors, so may there not be in the\r individual soul a third element which is passion or spirit, and when\r not corrupted by bad education is the natural auxiliary of reason?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1160"},"sequenceIndex":1621},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1161","text":"Yes, I replied, if passion, which has already been shown to be\r different from desire, turn out also to be different from reason.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1161"},"sequenceIndex":1622},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1162","text":"But that is easily proved:—We may observe even in young children that\r they are full of spirit almost as soon as they are born, whereas some\r of them never seem to attain to the use of reason, and most of them\r late enough.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1162"},"sequenceIndex":1623},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1163","text":"Excellent, I said, and you may see passion equally in brute animals,\r which is a further proof of the truth of what you are saying. And we\r may once more appeal to the words of Homer, which have been already\r quoted by us,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1163"},"sequenceIndex":1624},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1164","text":"for in this verse Homer has clearly supposed the power which reasons\r about the better and worse to be different from the unreasoning anger\r which is rebuked by it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1164"},"sequenceIndex":1625},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1165","text":"And so, after much tossing, we have reached land, and are fairly agreed\r that the same principles which exist in the State exist also in the\r individual, and that they are three in number.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1165"},"sequenceIndex":1626},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1166","text":"Must we not then infer that the individual is wise in the same way, and\r in virtue of the same quality which makes the State wise?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1166"},"sequenceIndex":1627},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1167","text":"Also that the same quality which constitutes courage in the State\r constitutes courage in the individual, and that both the State and the\r individual bear the same relation to all the other virtues?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1167"},"sequenceIndex":1628},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1168","text":"And the individual will be acknowledged by us to be just in the same\r way in which the State is just?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1168"},"sequenceIndex":1629},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1169","text":"We cannot but remember that the justice of the State consisted in each\r of the three classes doing the work of its own class?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1169"},"sequenceIndex":1630},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1170","text":"We must recollect that the individual in whom the several qualities of\r his nature do their own work will be just, and will do his own work?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1170"},"sequenceIndex":1631},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1171","text":"And ought not the rational principle, which is wise, and has the care\r of the whole soul, to rule, and the passionate or spirited principle to\r be the subject and ally?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1171"},"sequenceIndex":1632},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1172","text":"And, as we were saying, the united influence of music and gymnastic\r will bring them into accord, nerving and sustaining the reason with\r noble words and lessons, and moderating and soothing and civilizing the\r wildness of passion by harmony and rhythm?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1172"},"sequenceIndex":1633},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1173","text":"And these two, thus nurtured and educated, and having learned truly to\r know their own functions, will rule over the concupiscent, which in\r each of us is the largest part of the soul and by nature most\r insatiable of gain; over this they will keep guard, lest, waxing great\r and strong with the fulness of bodily pleasures, as they are termed,\r the concupiscent soul, no longer confined to her own sphere, should\r attempt to enslave and rule those who are not her natural-born\r subjects, and overturn the whole life of man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1173"},"sequenceIndex":1634},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1174","text":"Both together will they not be the best defenders of the whole soul and\r the whole body against attacks from without; the one counselling, and\r the other fighting under his leader, and courageously executing his\r commands and counsels?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1174"},"sequenceIndex":1635},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1175","text":"And he is to be deemed courageous whose spirit retains in pleasure and\r in pain the commands of reason about what he ought or ought not to\r fear?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1175"},"sequenceIndex":1636},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1176","text":"And him we call wise who has in him that little part which rules, and\r which proclaims these commands; that part too being supposed to have a\r knowledge of what is for the interest of each of the three parts and of\r the whole?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1176"},"sequenceIndex":1637},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1177","text":"And would you not say that he is temperate who has these same elements\r in friendly harmony, in whom the one ruling principle of reason, and\r the two subject ones of spirit and desire are equally agreed that\r reason ought to rule, and do not rebel?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1177"},"sequenceIndex":1638},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1178","text":"Certainly, he said, that is the true account of temperance whether in\r the State or individual.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1178"},"sequenceIndex":1639},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1179","text":"And surely, I said, we have explained again and again how and by virtue\r of what quality a man will be just.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1179"},"sequenceIndex":1640},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1180","text":"And is justice dimmer in the individual, and is her form different, or\r is she the same which we found her to be in the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1180"},"sequenceIndex":1641},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1181","text":"Because, if any doubt is still lingering in our minds, a few\r commonplace instances will satisfy us of the truth of what I am saying.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1181"},"sequenceIndex":1642},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1182","text":"If the case is put to us, must we not admit that the just State, or the\r man who is trained in the principles of such a State, will be less\r likely than the unjust to make away with a deposit of gold or silver?\r Would any one deny this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1182"},"sequenceIndex":1643},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1183","text":"Will the just man or citizen ever be guilty of sacrilege or theft, or\r treachery either to his friends or to his country?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1183"},"sequenceIndex":1644},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1184","text":"No one will be less likely to commit adultery, or to dishonour his\r father and mother, or to fail in his religious duties?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1184"},"sequenceIndex":1645},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1185","text":"And the reason is that each part of him is doing its own business,\r whether in ruling or being ruled?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1185"},"sequenceIndex":1646},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1186","text":"Are you satisfied then that the quality which makes such men and such\r states is justice, or do you hope to discover some other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1186"},"sequenceIndex":1647},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1187","text":"Then our dream has been realized; and the suspicion which we\r entertained at the beginning of our work of construction, that some\r divine power must have conducted us to a primary form of justice, has\r now been verified?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1187"},"sequenceIndex":1648},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1188","text":"And the division of labour which required the carpenter and the\r shoemaker and the rest of the citizens to be doing each his own\r business, and not another’s, was a shadow of justice, and for that\r reason it was of use?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1188"},"sequenceIndex":1649},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1189","text":"But in reality justice was such as we were describing, being concerned\r however, not with the outward man, but with the inward, which is the\r true self and concernment of man: for the just man does not permit the\r several elements within him to interfere with one another, or any of\r them to do the work of others,—he sets in order his own inner life, and\r is his own master and his own law, and at peace with himself; and when\r he has bound together the three principles within him, which may be\r compared to the higher, lower, and middle notes of the scale, and the\r intermediate intervals—when he ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1189"},"sequenceIndex":1650},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1190","text":"Very good; and if we were to affirm that we had discovered the just man\r and the just State, and the nature of justice in each of them, we\r should not be telling a falsehood?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1190"},"sequenceIndex":1651},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1191","text":"Must not injustice be a strife which arises among the three\r principles—a meddlesomeness, and interference, and rising up of a part\r of the soul against the whole, an assertion of unlawful authority,\r which is made by a rebellious subject against a true prince, of whom he\r is the natural vassal,—what is all this confusion and delusion but\r injustice, and intemperance and cowardice and ignorance, and every form\r of vice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1191"},"sequenceIndex":1652},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1192","text":"And if the nature of justice and injustice be known, then the meaning\r of acting unjustly and being unjust, or, again, of acting justly, will\r also be perfectly clear?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1192"},"sequenceIndex":1653},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1193","text":"Why, I said, they are like disease and health; being in the soul just\r what disease and health are in the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1193"},"sequenceIndex":1654},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1194","text":"Why, I said, that which is healthy causes health, and that which is\r unhealthy causes disease.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1194"},"sequenceIndex":1655},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1195","text":"And the creation of health is the institution of a natural order and\r government of one by another in the parts of the body; and the creation\r of disease is the production of a state of things at variance with this\r natural order?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1195"},"sequenceIndex":1656},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1196","text":"And is not the creation of justice the institution of a natural order\r and government of one by another in the parts of the soul, and the\r creation of injustice the production of a state of things at variance\r with the natural order?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1196"},"sequenceIndex":1657},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1197","text":"Then virtue is the health and beauty and well-being of the soul, and\r vice the disease and weakness and deformity of the same?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1197"},"sequenceIndex":1658},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1198","text":"Still our old question of the comparative advantage of justice and\r injustice has not been answered: Which is the more profitable, to be\r just and act justly and practise virtue, whether seen or unseen of gods\r and men, or to be unjust and act unjustly, if only unpunished and\r unreformed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1198"},"sequenceIndex":1659},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1199","text":"In my judgment, Socrates, the question has now become ridiculous. We\r know that, when the bodily constitution is gone, life is no longer\r endurable, though pampered with all kinds of meats and drinks, and\r having all wealth and all power; and shall we be told that when the\r very essence of the vital principle is undermined and corrupted, life\r is still worth having to a man, if only he be allowed to do whatever he\r likes with the single exception that he is not to acquire justice and\r virtue, or to escape from injustice and vice; assuming them both to be\r such as we have described?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1199"},"sequenceIndex":1660},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1200","text":"Yes, I said, the question is, as you say, ridiculous. Still, as we are\r near the spot at which we may see the truth in the clearest manner with\r our own eyes, let us not faint by the way.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1200"},"sequenceIndex":1661},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1201","text":"Come up hither, I said, and behold the various forms of vice, those of\r them, I mean, which are worth looking at.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1201"},"sequenceIndex":1662},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1202","text":"I said, The argument seems to have reached a height from which, as from\r some tower of speculation, a man may look down and see that virtue is\r one, but that the forms of vice are innumerable; there being four\r special ones which are deserving of note.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1202"},"sequenceIndex":1663},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1203","text":"I mean, I replied, that there appear to be as many forms of the soul as\r there are distinct forms of the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1203"},"sequenceIndex":1664},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1204","text":"The first, I said, is that which we have been describing, and which may\r be said to have two names, monarchy and aristocracy, accordingly as\r rule is exercised by one distinguished man or by many.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1204"},"sequenceIndex":1665},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1205","text":"But I regard the two names as describing one form only; for whether the\r government is in the hands of one or many, if the governors have been\r trained in the manner which we have supposed, the fundamental laws of\r the State will be maintained.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1205"},"sequenceIndex":1666},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1206","text":"Such is the good and true City or State, and the good and true man is\r of the same pattern; and if this is right every other is wrong; and the\r evil is one which affects not only the ordering of the State, but also\r the regulation of the individual soul, and is exhibited in four forms.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1206"},"sequenceIndex":1667},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1207","text":"I was proceeding to tell the order in which the four evil forms\r appeared to me to succeed one another, when Polemarchus, who was\r sitting a little way off, just beyond Adeimantus, began to whisper to\r him: stretching forth his hand, he took hold of the upper part of his\r coat by the shoulder, and drew him towards him, leaning forward himself\r so as to be quite close and saying something in his ear, of which I\r only caught the words, ‘Shall we let him off, or what shall we do?’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1207"},"sequenceIndex":1668},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1208","text":"Why, he said, we think that you are lazy, and mean to cheat us out of a\r whole chapter which is a very important part of the story; and you\r fancy that we shall not notice your airy way of proceeding; as if it\r were self-evident to everybody, that in the matter of women and\r children ‘friends have all things in common.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1208"},"sequenceIndex":1669},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1209","text":"Yes, he said; but what is right in this particular case, like\r everything else, requires to be explained; for community may be of many\r kinds. Please, therefore, to say what sort of community you mean. We\r have been long expecting that you would tell us something about the\r family life of your citizens—how they will bring children into the\r world, and rear them when they have arrived, and, in general, what is\r the nature of this community of women and children—for we are of\r opinion that the right or wrong management of such matters will have a\r great and paramount influence on the State for g","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1209"},"sequenceIndex":1670},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1210","text":"And without more ado, said Thrasymachus, you may consider us all to be\r equally agreed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1210"},"sequenceIndex":1671},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1211","text":"I said, You know not what you are doing in thus assailing me: What an\r argument are you raising about the State! Just as I thought that I had\r finished, and was only too glad that I had laid this question to sleep,\r and was reflecting how fortunate I was in your acceptance of what I\r then said, you ask me to begin again at the very foundation, ignorant\r of what a hornet’s nest of words you are stirring. Now I foresaw this\r gathering trouble, and avoided it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1211"},"sequenceIndex":1672},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1212","text":"For what purpose do you conceive that we have come here, said\r Thrasymachus,—to look for gold, or to hear discourse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1212"},"sequenceIndex":1673},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1213","text":"Yes, Socrates, said Glaucon, and the whole of life is the only limit\r which wise men assign to the hearing of such discourses. But never mind\r about us; take heart yourself and answer the question in your own way:\r What sort of community of women and children is this which is to\r prevail among our guardians? and how shall we manage the period between\r birth and education, which seems to require the greatest care? Tell us\r how these things will be.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1213"},"sequenceIndex":1674},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1214","text":"Yes, my simple friend, but the answer is the reverse of easy; many more\r doubts arise about this than about our previous conclusions. For the\r practicability of what is said may be doubted; and looked at in another\r point of view, whether the scheme, if ever so practicable, would be for\r the best, is also doubtful. Hence I feel a reluctance to approach the\r subject, lest our aspiration, my dear friend, should turn out to be a\r dream only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1214"},"sequenceIndex":1675},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1215","text":"Fear not, he replied, for your audience will not be hard upon you; they\r are not sceptical or hostile.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1215"},"sequenceIndex":1676},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1216","text":"I said: My good friend, I suppose that you mean to encourage me by\r these words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1216"},"sequenceIndex":1677},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1217","text":"Then let me tell you that you are doing just the reverse; the\r encouragement which you offer would have been all very well had I\r myself believed that I knew what I was talking about: to declare the\r truth about matters of high interest which a man honours and loves\r among wise men who love him need occasion no fear or faltering in his\r mind; but to carry on an argument when you are yourself only a\r hesitating enquirer, which is my condition, is a dangerous and slippery\r thing; and the danger is not that I shall be laughed at (of which the\r fear would be childish), but that I shall miss the tr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1217"},"sequenceIndex":1678},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1218","text":"Glaucon laughed and said: Well then, Socrates, in case you and your\r argument do us any serious injury you shall be acquitted beforehand of\r the homicide, and shall not be held to be a deceiver; take courage then\r and speak.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1218"},"sequenceIndex":1679},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1219","text":"Well, I said, the law says that when a man is acquitted he is free from\r guilt, and what holds at law may hold in argument.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1219"},"sequenceIndex":1680},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1220","text":"Well, I replied, I suppose that I must retrace my steps and say what I\r perhaps ought to have said before in the proper place. The part of the\r men has been played out, and now properly enough comes the turn of the\r women. Of them I will proceed to speak, and the more readily since I am\r invited by you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1220"},"sequenceIndex":1681},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1221","text":"For men born and educated like our citizens, the only way, in my\r opinion, of arriving at a right conclusion about the possession and use\r of women and children is to follow the path on which we originally\r started, when we said that the men were to be the guardians and\r watchdogs of the herd.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1221"},"sequenceIndex":1682},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1222","text":"Let us further suppose the birth and education of our women to be\r subject to similar or nearly similar regulations; then we shall see\r whether the result accords with our design.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1222"},"sequenceIndex":1683},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1223","text":"What I mean may be put into the form of a question, I said: Are dogs\r divided into hes and shes, or do they both share equally in hunting and\r in keeping watch and in the other duties of dogs? or do we entrust to\r the males the entire and exclusive care of the flocks, while we leave\r the females at home, under the idea that the bearing and suckling their\r puppies is labour enough for them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1223"},"sequenceIndex":1684},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1224","text":"No, he said, they share alike; the only difference between them is that\r the males are stronger and the females weaker.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1224"},"sequenceIndex":1685},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1225","text":"But can you use different animals for the same purpose, unless they are\r bred and fed in the same way?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1225"},"sequenceIndex":1686},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1226","text":"Then, if women are to have the same duties as men, they must have the\r same nurture and education?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1226"},"sequenceIndex":1687},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1227","text":"Then women must be taught music and gymnastic and also the art of war,\r which they must practise like the men?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1227"},"sequenceIndex":1688},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1228","text":"I should rather expect, I said, that several of our proposals, if they\r are carried out, being unusual, may appear ridiculous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1228"},"sequenceIndex":1689},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1229","text":"Yes, and the most ridiculous thing of all will be the sight of women\r naked in the palaestra, exercising with the men, especially when they\r are no longer young; they certainly will not be a vision of beauty, any\r more than the enthusiastic old men who in spite of wrinkles and\r ugliness continue to frequent the gymnasia.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1229"},"sequenceIndex":1690},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1230","text":"Yes, indeed, he said: according to present notions the proposal would\r be thought ridiculous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1230"},"sequenceIndex":1691},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1231","text":"But then, I said, as we have determined to speak our minds, we must not\r fear the jests of the wits which will be directed against this sort of\r innovation; how they will talk of women’s attainments both in music and\r gymnastic, and above all about their wearing armour and riding upon\r horseback!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1231"},"sequenceIndex":1692},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1232","text":"Yet having begun we must go forward to the rough places of the law; at\r the same time begging of these gentlemen for once in their life to be\r serious. Not long ago, as we shall remind them, the Hellenes were of\r the opinion, which is still generally received among the barbarians,\r that the sight of a naked man was ridiculous and improper; and when\r first the Cretans and then the Lacedaemonians introduced the custom,\r the wits of that day might equally have ridiculed the innovation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1232"},"sequenceIndex":1693},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1233","text":"But when experience showed that to let all things be uncovered was far\r better than to cover them up, and the ludicrous effect to the outward\r eye vanished before the better principle which reason asserted, then\r the man was perceived to be a fool who directs the shafts of his\r ridicule at any other sight but that of folly and vice, or seriously\r inclines to weigh the beautiful by any other standard but that of the\r good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1233"},"sequenceIndex":1694},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1234","text":"First, then, whether the question is to be put in jest or in earnest,\r let us come to an understanding about the nature of woman: Is she\r capable of sharing either wholly or partially in the actions of men, or\r not at all? And is the art of war one of those arts in which she can or\r can not share? That will be the best way of commencing the enquiry, and\r will probably lead to the fairest conclusion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1234"},"sequenceIndex":1695},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1235","text":"Shall we take the other side first and begin by arguing against\r ourselves; in this manner the adversary’s position will not be\r undefended.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1235"},"sequenceIndex":1696},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1236","text":"Then let us put a speech into the mouths of our opponents. They will\r say: ‘Socrates and Glaucon, no adversary need convict you, for you\r yourselves, at the first foundation of the State, admitted the\r principle that everybody was to do the one work suited to his own\r nature.’ And certainly, if I am not mistaken, such an admission was\r made by us. ‘And do not the natures of men and women differ very much\r indeed?’ And we shall reply: Of course they do. Then we shall be asked,\r ‘Whether the tasks assigned to men and to women should not be\r different, and such as are agreeable to their different","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1236"},"sequenceIndex":1697},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1237","text":"That is not an easy question to answer when asked suddenly; and I shall\r and I do beg of you to draw out the case on our side.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1237"},"sequenceIndex":1698},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1238","text":"These are the objections, Glaucon, and there are many others of a like\r kind, which I foresaw long ago; they made me afraid and reluctant to\r take in hand any law about the possession and nurture of women and\r children.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1238"},"sequenceIndex":1699},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1239","text":"Why yes, I said, but the fact is that when a man is out of his depth,\r whether he has fallen into a little swimming bath or into mid ocean, he\r has to swim all the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1239"},"sequenceIndex":1700},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1240","text":"And must not we swim and try to reach the shore: we will hope that\r Arion’s dolphin or some other miraculous help may save us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1240"},"sequenceIndex":1701},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1241","text":"Well then, let us see if any way of escape can be found. We\r acknowledged—did we not? that different natures ought to have different\r pursuits, and that men’s and women’s natures are different. And now\r what are we saying?—that different natures ought to have the same\r pursuits,—this is the inconsistency which is charged upon us.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1241"},"sequenceIndex":1702},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1242","text":"Because I think that many a man falls into the practice against his\r will. When he thinks that he is reasoning he is really disputing, just\r because he cannot define and divide, and so know that of which he is\r speaking; and he will pursue a merely verbal opposition in the spirit\r of contention and not of fair discussion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1242"},"sequenceIndex":1703},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1243","text":"Yes, he replied, such is very often the case; but what has that to do\r with us and our argument?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1243"},"sequenceIndex":1704},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1244","text":"A great deal; for there is certainly a danger of our getting\r unintentionally into a verbal opposition.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1244"},"sequenceIndex":1705},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1245","text":"Why we valiantly and pugnaciously insist upon the verbal truth, that\r different natures ought to have different pursuits, but we never\r considered at all what was the meaning of sameness or difference of\r nature, or why we distinguished them when we assigned different\r pursuits to different natures and the same to the same natures.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1245"},"sequenceIndex":1706},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1246","text":"I said: Suppose that by way of illustration we were to ask the question\r whether there is not an opposition in nature between bald men and hairy\r men; and if this is admitted by us, then, if bald men are cobblers, we\r should forbid the hairy men to be cobblers, and conversely?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1246"},"sequenceIndex":1707},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1247","text":"Yes, I said, a jest; and why? because we never meant when we\r constructed the State, that the opposition of natures should extend to\r every difference, but only to those differences which affected the\r pursuit in which the individual is engaged; we should have argued, for\r example, that a physician and one who is in mind a physician may be\r said to have the same nature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1247"},"sequenceIndex":1708},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1248","text":"And if, I said, the male and female sex appear to differ in their\r fitness for any art or pursuit, we should say that such pursuit or art\r ought to be assigned to one or the other of them; but if the difference\r consists only in women bearing and men begetting children, this does\r not amount to a proof that a woman differs from a man in respect of the\r sort of education she should receive; and we shall therefore continue\r to maintain that our guardians and their wives ought to have the same\r pursuits.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1248"},"sequenceIndex":1709},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1249","text":"Next, we shall ask our opponent how, in reference to any of the\r pursuits or arts of civic life, the nature of a woman differs from that\r of a man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1249"},"sequenceIndex":1710},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1250","text":"And perhaps he, like yourself, will reply that to give a sufficient\r answer on the instant is not easy; but after a little reflection there\r is no difficulty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1250"},"sequenceIndex":1711},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1251","text":"Suppose then that we invite him to accompany us in the argument, and\r then we may hope to show him that there is nothing peculiar in the\r constitution of women which would affect them in the administration of\r the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1251"},"sequenceIndex":1712},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1252","text":"Let us say to him: Come now, and we will ask you a question:—when you\r spoke of a nature gifted or not gifted in any respect, did you mean to\r say that one man will acquire a thing easily, another with difficulty;\r a little learning will lead the one to discover a great deal; whereas\r the other, after much study and application, no sooner learns than he\r forgets; or again, did you mean, that the one has a body which is a\r good servant to his mind, while the body of the other is a hindrance to\r him?—would not these be the sort of differences which distinguish the\r man gifted by nature from the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1252"},"sequenceIndex":1713},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1253","text":"And can you mention any pursuit of mankind in which the male sex has\r not all these gifts and qualities in a higher degree than the female?\r Need I waste time in speaking of the art of weaving, and the management\r of pancakes and preserves, in which womankind does really appear to be\r great, and in which for her to be beaten by a man is of all things the\r most absurd?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1253"},"sequenceIndex":1714},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1254","text":"You are quite right, he replied, in maintaining the general inferiority\r of the female sex: although many women are in many things superior to\r many men, yet on the whole what you say is true.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1254"},"sequenceIndex":1715},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1255","text":"And if so, my friend, I said, there is no special faculty of\r administration in a state which a woman has because she is a woman, or\r which a man has by virtue of his sex, but the gifts of nature are alike\r diffused in both; all the pursuits of men are the pursuits of women\r also, but in all of them a woman is inferior to a man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1255"},"sequenceIndex":1716},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1256","text":"One woman has a gift of healing, another not; one is a musician, and\r another has no music in her nature?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1256"},"sequenceIndex":1717},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1257","text":"And one woman has a turn for gymnastic and military exercises, and\r another is unwarlike and hates gymnastics?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1257"},"sequenceIndex":1718},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1258","text":"And one woman is a philosopher, and another is an enemy of philosophy;\r one has spirit, and another is without spirit?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1258"},"sequenceIndex":1719},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1259","text":"Then one woman will have the temper of a guardian, and another not. Was\r not the selection of the male guardians determined by differences of\r this sort?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1259"},"sequenceIndex":1720},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1260","text":"Men and women alike possess the qualities which make a guardian; they\r differ only in their comparative strength or weakness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1260"},"sequenceIndex":1721},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1261","text":"And those women who have such qualities are to be selected as the\r companions and colleagues of men who have similar qualities and whom\r they resemble in capacity and in character?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1261"},"sequenceIndex":1722},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1262","text":"Then, as we were saying before, there is nothing unnatural in assigning\r music and gymnastic to the wives of the guardians—to that point we come\r round again.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1262"},"sequenceIndex":1723},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1263","text":"The law which we then enacted was agreeable to nature, and therefore\r not an impossibility or mere aspiration; and the contrary practice,\r which prevails at present, is in reality a violation of nature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1263"},"sequenceIndex":1724},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1264","text":"We had to consider, first, whether our proposals were possible, and\r secondly whether they were the most beneficial?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1264"},"sequenceIndex":1725},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1265","text":"You will admit that the same education which makes a man a good\r guardian will make a woman a good guardian; for their original nature\r is the same?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1265"},"sequenceIndex":1726},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1266","text":"Would you say that all men are equal in excellence, or is one man\r better than another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1266"},"sequenceIndex":1727},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1267","text":"And in the commonwealth which we were founding do you conceive the\r guardians who have been brought up on our model system to be more\r perfect men, or the cobblers whose education has been cobbling?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1267"},"sequenceIndex":1728},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1268","text":"You have answered me, I replied: Well, and may we not further say that\r our guardians are the best of our citizens?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1268"},"sequenceIndex":1729},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1269","text":"And can there be anything better for the interests of the State than\r that the men and women of a State should be as good as possible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1269"},"sequenceIndex":1730},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1270","text":"And this is what the arts of music and gymnastic, when present in such\r manner as we have described, will accomplish?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1270"},"sequenceIndex":1731},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1271","text":"Then we have made an enactment not only possible but in the highest\r degree beneficial to the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1271"},"sequenceIndex":1732},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1272","text":"Then let the wives of our guardians strip, for their virtue will be\r their robe, and let them share in the toils of war and the defence of\r their country; only in the distribution of labours the lighter are to\r be assigned to the women, who are the weaker natures, but in other\r respects their duties are to be the same. And as for the man who laughs\r at naked women exercising their bodies from the best of motives, in his\r laughter he is plucking","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1272"},"sequenceIndex":1733},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1273","text":"and he himself is ignorant of what he is laughing at, or what he is\r about;—for that is, and ever will be, the best of sayings, That the\r useful is the noble and the hurtful is the base.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1273"},"sequenceIndex":1734},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1274","text":"Here, then, is one difficulty in our law about women, which we may say\r that we have now escaped; the wave has not swallowed us up alive for\r enacting that the guardians of either sex should have all their\r pursuits in common; to the utility and also to the possibility of this\r arrangement the consistency of the argument with itself bears witness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1274"},"sequenceIndex":1735},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1275","text":"Yes, I said, but a greater is coming; you will not think much of this\r when you see the next.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1275"},"sequenceIndex":1736},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1276","text":"The law, I said, which is the sequel of this and of all that has\r preceded, is to the following effect,—‘that the wives of our guardians\r are to be common, and their children are to be common, and no parent is\r to know his own child, nor any child his parent.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1276"},"sequenceIndex":1737},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1277","text":"Yes, he said, that is a much greater wave than the other; and the\r possibility as well as the utility of such a law are far more\r questionable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1277"},"sequenceIndex":1738},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1278","text":"I do not think, I said, that there can be any dispute about the very\r great utility of having wives and children in common; the possibility\r is quite another matter, and will be very much disputed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1278"},"sequenceIndex":1739},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1279","text":"You imply that the two questions must be combined, I replied. Now I\r meant that you should admit the utility; and in this way, as I thought,\r I should escape from one of them, and then there would remain only the\r possibility.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1279"},"sequenceIndex":1740},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1280","text":"But that little attempt is detected, and therefore you will please to\r give a defence of both.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1280"},"sequenceIndex":1741},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1281","text":"Well, I said, I submit to my fate. Yet grant me a little favour: let me\r feast my mind with the dream as day dreamers are in the habit of\r feasting themselves when they are walking alone; for before they have\r discovered any means of effecting their wishes—that is a matter which\r never troubles them—they would rather not tire themselves by thinking\r about possibilities; but assuming that what they desire is already\r granted to them, they proceed with their plan, and delight in detailing\r what they mean to do when their wish has come true—that is a way which\r they have of not doing much good to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1281"},"sequenceIndex":1742},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1282","text":"First, I think that if our rulers and their auxiliaries are to be\r worthy of the name which they bear, there must be willingness to obey\r in the one and the power of command in the other; the guardians must\r themselves obey the laws, and they must also imitate the spirit of them\r in any details which are entrusted to their care.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1282"},"sequenceIndex":1743},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1283","text":"You, I said, who are their legislator, having selected the men, will\r now select the women and give them to them;—they must be as far as\r possible of like natures with them; and they must live in common houses\r and meet at common meals. None of them will have anything specially his\r or her own; they will be together, and will be brought up together, and\r will associate at gymnastic exercises. And so they will be drawn by a\r necessity of their natures to have intercourse with each\r other—necessity is not too strong a word, I think?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1283"},"sequenceIndex":1744},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1284","text":"Yes, he said;—necessity, not geometrical, but another sort of necessity\r which lovers know, and which is far more convincing and constraining to\r the mass of mankind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1284"},"sequenceIndex":1745},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1285","text":"True, I said; and this, Glaucon, like all the rest, must proceed after\r an orderly fashion; in a city of the blessed, licentiousness is an\r unholy thing which the rulers will forbid.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1285"},"sequenceIndex":1746},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1286","text":"Then clearly the next thing will be to make matrimony sacred in the\r highest degree, and what is most beneficial will be deemed sacred?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1286"},"sequenceIndex":1747},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1287","text":"And how can marriages be made most beneficial?—that is a question which\r I put to you, because I see in your house dogs for hunting, and of the\r nobler sort of birds not a few. Now, I beseech you, do tell me, have\r you ever attended to their pairing and breeding?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1287"},"sequenceIndex":1748},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1288","text":"Why, in the first place, although they are all of a good sort, are not\r some better than others?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1288"},"sequenceIndex":1749},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1289","text":"And do you breed from them all indifferently, or do you take care to\r breed from the best only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1289"},"sequenceIndex":1750},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1290","text":"And if care was not taken in the breeding, your dogs and birds would\r greatly deteriorate?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1290"},"sequenceIndex":1751},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1291","text":"Good heavens! my dear friend, I said, what consummate skill will our\r rulers need if the same principle holds of the human species!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1291"},"sequenceIndex":1752},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1292","text":"Certainly, the same principle holds; but why does this involve any\r particular skill?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1292"},"sequenceIndex":1753},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1293","text":"Because, I said, our rulers will often have to practise upon the body\r corporate with medicines. Now you know that when patients do not\r require medicines, but have only to be put under a regimen, the\r inferior sort of practitioner is deemed to be good enough; but when\r medicine has to be given, then the doctor should be more of a man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1293"},"sequenceIndex":1754},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1294","text":"I mean, I replied, that our rulers will find a considerable dose of\r falsehood and deceit necessary for the good of their subjects: we were\r saying that the use of all these things regarded as medicines might be\r of advantage.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1294"},"sequenceIndex":1755},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1295","text":"And this lawful use of them seems likely to be often needed in the\r regulations of marriages and births.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1295"},"sequenceIndex":1756},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1296","text":"Why, I said, the principle has been already laid down that the best of\r either sex should be united with the best as often, and the inferior\r with the inferior, as seldom as possible; and that they should rear the\r offspring of the one sort of union, but not of the other, if the flock\r is to be maintained in first-rate condition. Now these goings on must\r be a secret which the rulers only know, or there will be a further\r danger of our herd, as the guardians may be termed, breaking out into\r rebellion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1296"},"sequenceIndex":1757},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1297","text":"Had we not better appoint certain festivals at which we will bring\r together the brides and bridegrooms, and sacrifices will be offered and\r suitable hymeneal songs composed by our poets: the number of weddings\r is a matter which must be left to the discretion of the rulers, whose\r aim will be to preserve the average of population? There are many other\r things which they will have to consider, such as the effects of wars\r and diseases and any similar agencies, in order as far as this is\r possible to prevent the State from becoming either too large or too\r small.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1297"},"sequenceIndex":1758},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1298","text":"We shall have to invent some ingenious kind of lots which the less\r worthy may draw on each occasion of our bringing them together, and\r then they will accuse their own ill-luck and not the rulers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1298"},"sequenceIndex":1759},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1299","text":"And I think that our braver and better youth, besides their other\r honours and rewards, might have greater facilities of intercourse with\r women given them; their bravery will be a reason, and such fathers\r ought to have as many sons as possible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1299"},"sequenceIndex":1760},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1300","text":"And the proper officers, whether male or female or both, for offices\r are to be held by women as well as by men—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1300"},"sequenceIndex":1761},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1301","text":"The proper officers will take the offspring of the good parents to the\r pen or fold, and there they will deposit them with certain nurses who\r dwell in a separate quarter; but the offspring of the inferior, or of\r the better when they chance to be deformed, will be put away in some\r mysterious, unknown place, as they should be.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1301"},"sequenceIndex":1762},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1302","text":"Yes, he said, that must be done if the breed of the guardians is to be\r kept pure.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1302"},"sequenceIndex":1763},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1303","text":"They will provide for their nurture, and will bring the mothers to the\r fold when they are full of milk, taking the greatest possible care that\r no mother recognises her own child; and other wet-nurses may be engaged\r if more are required. Care will also be taken that the process of\r suckling shall not be protracted too long; and the mothers will have no\r getting up at night or other trouble, but will hand over all this sort\r of thing to the nurses and attendants.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1303"},"sequenceIndex":1764},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1304","text":"You suppose the wives of our guardians to have a fine easy time of it\r when they are having children.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1304"},"sequenceIndex":1765},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1305","text":"Why, said I, and so they ought. Let us, however, proceed with our\r scheme. We were saying that the parents should be in the prime of life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1305"},"sequenceIndex":1766},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1306","text":"And what is the prime of life? May it not be defined as a period of\r about twenty years in a woman’s life, and thirty in a man’s?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1306"},"sequenceIndex":1767},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1307","text":"A woman, I said, at twenty years of age may begin to bear children to\r the State, and continue to bear them until forty; a man may begin at\r five-and-twenty, when he has passed the point at which the pulse of\r life beats quickest, and continue to beget children until he be\r fifty-five.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1307"},"sequenceIndex":1768},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1308","text":"Certainly, he said, both in men and women those years are the prime of\r physical as well as of intellectual vigour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1308"},"sequenceIndex":1769},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1309","text":"Any one above or below the prescribed ages who takes part in the public\r hymeneals shall be said to have done an unholy and unrighteous thing;\r the child of which he is the father, if it steals into life, will have\r been conceived under auspices very unlike the sacrifices and prayers,\r which at each hymeneal priestesses and priest and the whole city will\r offer, that the new generation may be better and more useful than their\r good and useful parents, whereas his child will be the offspring of\r darkness and strange lust.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1309"},"sequenceIndex":1770},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1310","text":"And the same law will apply to any one of those within the prescribed\r age who forms a connection with any woman in the prime of life without\r the sanction of the rulers; for we shall say that he is raising up a\r bastard to the State, uncertified and unconsecrated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1310"},"sequenceIndex":1771},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1311","text":"This applies, however, only to those who are within the specified age:\r after that we allow them to range at will, except that a man may not\r marry his daughter or his daughter’s daughter, or his mother or his\r mother’s mother; and women, on the other hand, are prohibited from\r marrying their sons or fathers, or son’s son or father’s father, and so\r on in either direction. And we grant all this, accompanying the\r permission with strict orders to prevent any embryo which may come into\r being from seeing the light; and if any force a way to the birth, the\r parents must understand that the offspr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1311"},"sequenceIndex":1772},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1312","text":"That also, he said, is a reasonable proposition. But how will they know\r who are fathers and daughters, and so on?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1312"},"sequenceIndex":1773},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1313","text":"They will never know. The way will be this:—dating from the day of the\r hymeneal, the bridegroom who was then married will call all the male\r children who are born in the seventh and tenth month afterwards his\r sons, and the female children his daughters, and they will call him\r father, and he will call their children his grandchildren, and they\r will call the elder generation grandfathers and grandmothers. All who\r were begotten at the time when their fathers and mothers came together\r will be called their brothers and sisters, and these, as I was saying,\r will be forbidden to inter-marry. Th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1313"},"sequenceIndex":1774},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1314","text":"Such is the scheme, Glaucon, according to which the guardians of our\r State are to have their wives and families in common. And now you would\r have the argument show that this community is consistent with the rest\r of our polity, and also that nothing can be better—would you not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1314"},"sequenceIndex":1775},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1315","text":"Shall we try to find a common basis by asking of ourselves what ought\r to be the chief aim of the legislator in making laws and in the\r organization of a State,—what is the greatest good, and what is the\r greatest evil, and then consider whether our previous description has\r the stamp of the good or of the evil?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1315"},"sequenceIndex":1776},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1316","text":"Can there be any greater evil than discord and distraction and\r plurality where unity ought to reign? or any greater good than the bond\r of unity?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1316"},"sequenceIndex":1777},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1317","text":"And there is unity where there is community of pleasures and\r pains—where all the citizens are glad or grieved on the same occasions\r of joy and sorrow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1317"},"sequenceIndex":1778},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1318","text":"Yes; and where there is no common but only private feeling a State is\r disorganized—when you have one half of the world triumphing and the\r other plunged in grief at the same events happening to the city or the\r citizens?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1318"},"sequenceIndex":1779},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1319","text":"Such differences commonly originate in a disagreement about the use of\r the terms ‘mine’ and ‘not mine,’ ‘his’ and ‘not his.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1319"},"sequenceIndex":1780},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1320","text":"And is not that the best-ordered State in which the greatest number of\r persons apply the terms ‘mine’ and ‘not mine’ in the same way to the\r same thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1320"},"sequenceIndex":1781},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1321","text":"Or that again which most nearly approaches to the condition of the\r individual—as in the body, when but a finger of one of us is hurt, the\r whole frame, drawn towards the soul as a centre and forming one kingdom\r under the ruling power therein, feels the hurt and sympathizes all\r together with the part affected, and we say that the man has a pain in\r his finger; and the same expression is used about any other part of the\r body, which has a sensation of pain at suffering or of pleasure at the\r alleviation of suffering.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1321"},"sequenceIndex":1782},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1322","text":"Very true, he replied; and I agree with you that in the best-ordered\r State there is the nearest approach to this common feeling which you\r describe.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1322"},"sequenceIndex":1783},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1323","text":"Then when any one of the citizens experiences any good or evil, the\r whole State will make his case their own, and will either rejoice or\r sorrow with him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1323"},"sequenceIndex":1784},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1324","text":"It will now be time, I said, for us to return to our State and see\r whether this or some other form is most in accordance with these\r fundamental principles.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1324"},"sequenceIndex":1785},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1325","text":"But is there not another name which people give to their rulers in\r other States?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1325"},"sequenceIndex":1786},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1326","text":"Generally they call them masters, but in democratic States they simply\r call them rulers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1326"},"sequenceIndex":1787},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1327","text":"And in our State what other name besides that of citizens do the people\r give the rulers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1327"},"sequenceIndex":1788},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1328","text":"Did you ever know an example in any other State of a ruler who would\r speak of one of his colleagues as his friend and of another as not\r being his friend?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1328"},"sequenceIndex":1789},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1329","text":"And the friend he regards and describes as one in whom he has an\r interest, and the other as a stranger in whom he has no interest?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1329"},"sequenceIndex":1790},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1330","text":"But would any of your guardians think or speak of any other guardian as\r a stranger?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1330"},"sequenceIndex":1791},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1331","text":"Certainly he would not; for every one whom they meet will be regarded\r by them either as a brother or sister, or father or mother, or son or\r daughter, or as the child or parent of those who are thus connected\r with him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1331"},"sequenceIndex":1792},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1332","text":"Capital, I said; but let me ask you once more: Shall they be a family\r in name only; or shall they in all their actions be true to the name?\r For example, in the use of the word ‘father,’ would the care of a\r father be implied and the filial reverence and duty and obedience to\r him which the law commands; and is the violator of these duties to be\r regarded as an impious and unrighteous person who is not likely to\r receive much good either at the hands of God or of man? Are these to be\r or not to be the strains which the children will hear repeated in their\r ears by all the citizens about those","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1332"},"sequenceIndex":1793},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1333","text":"These, he said, and none other; for what can be more ridiculous than\r for them to utter the names of family ties with the lips only and not\r to act in the spirit of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1333"},"sequenceIndex":1794},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1334","text":"Then in our city the language of harmony and concord will be more often\r heard than in any other. As I was describing before, when any one is\r well or ill, the universal word will be ‘with me it is well’ or ‘it is\r ill.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1334"},"sequenceIndex":1795},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1335","text":"And agreeably to this mode of thinking and speaking, were we not saying\r that they will have their pleasures and pains in common?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1335"},"sequenceIndex":1796},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1336","text":"And they will have a common interest in the same thing which they will\r alike call ‘my own,’ and having this common interest they will have a\r common feeling of pleasure and pain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1336"},"sequenceIndex":1797},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1337","text":"And the reason of this, over and above the general constitution of the\r State, will be that the guardians will have a community of women and\r children?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1337"},"sequenceIndex":1798},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1338","text":"And this unity of feeling we admitted to be the greatest good, as was\r implied in our own comparison of a well-ordered State to the relation\r of the body and the members, when affected by pleasure or pain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1338"},"sequenceIndex":1799},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1339","text":"Then the community of wives and children among our citizens is clearly\r the source of the greatest good to the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1339"},"sequenceIndex":1800},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1340","text":"And this agrees with the other principle which we were affirming,—that\r the guardians were not to have houses or lands or any other property;\r their pay was to be their food, which they were to receive from the\r other citizens, and they were to have no private expenses; for we\r intended them to preserve their true character of guardians.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1340"},"sequenceIndex":1801},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1341","text":"Both the community of property and the community of families, as I am\r saying, tend to make them more truly guardians; they will not tear the\r city in pieces by differing about ‘mine’ and ‘not mine;’ each man\r dragging any acquisition which he has made into a separate house of his\r own, where he has a separate wife and children and private pleasures\r and pains; but all will be affected as far as may be by the same\r pleasures and pains because they are all of one opinion about what is\r near and dear to them, and therefore they all tend towards a common\r end.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1341"},"sequenceIndex":1802},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1342","text":"And as they have nothing but their persons which they can call their\r own, suits and complaints will have no existence among them; they will\r be delivered from all those quarrels of which money or children or\r relations are the occasion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1342"},"sequenceIndex":1803},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1343","text":"Neither will trials for assault or insult ever be likely to occur among\r them. For that equals should defend themselves against equals we shall\r maintain to be honourable and right; we shall make the protection of\r the person a matter of necessity.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1343"},"sequenceIndex":1804},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1344","text":"Yes; and there is a further good in the law; viz. that if a man has a\r quarrel with another he will satisfy his resentment then and there, and\r not proceed to more dangerous lengths.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1344"},"sequenceIndex":1805},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1345","text":"Nor can there be a doubt that the younger will not strike or do any\r other violence to an elder, unless the magistrates command him; nor\r will he slight him in any way. For there are two guardians, shame and\r fear, mighty to prevent him: shame, which makes men refrain from laying\r hands on those who are to them in the relation of parents; fear, that\r the injured one will be succoured by the others who are his brothers,\r sons, fathers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1345"},"sequenceIndex":1806},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1346","text":"Then in every way the laws will help the citizens to keep the peace\r with one another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1346"},"sequenceIndex":1807},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1347","text":"And as the guardians will never quarrel among themselves there will be\r no danger of the rest of the city being divided either against them or\r against one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1347"},"sequenceIndex":1808},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1348","text":"I hardly like even to mention the little meannesses of which they will\r be rid, for they are beneath notice: such, for example, as the flattery\r of the rich by the poor, and all the pains and pangs which men\r experience in bringing up a family, and in finding money to buy\r necessaries for their household, borrowing and then repudiating,\r getting how they can, and giving the money into the hands of women and\r slaves to keep—the many evils of so many kinds which people suffer in\r this way are mean enough and obvious enough, and not worth speaking of.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1348"},"sequenceIndex":1809},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1349","text":"And from all these evils they will be delivered, and their life will be\r blessed as the life of Olympic victors and yet more blessed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1349"},"sequenceIndex":1810},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1350","text":"The Olympic victor, I said, is deemed happy in receiving a part only of\r the blessedness which is secured to our citizens, who have won a more\r glorious victory and have a more complete maintenance at the public\r cost. For the victory which they have won is the salvation of the whole\r State; and the crown with which they and their children are crowned is\r the fulness of all that life needs; they receive rewards from the hands\r of their country while living, and after death have an honourable\r burial.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1350"},"sequenceIndex":1811},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1351","text":"Do you remember, I said, how in the course of the previous discussion\r some one who shall be nameless accused us of making our guardians\r unhappy—they had nothing and might have possessed all things—to whom we\r replied that, if an occasion offered, we might perhaps hereafter\r consider this question, but that, as at present advised, we would make\r our guardians truly guardians, and that we were fashioning the State\r with a view to the greatest happiness, not of any particular class, but\r of the whole?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1351"},"sequenceIndex":1812},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1352","text":"And what do you say, now that the life of our protectors is made out to\r be far better and nobler than that of Olympic victors—is the life of\r shoemakers, or any other artisans, or of husbandmen, to be compared\r with it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1352"},"sequenceIndex":1813},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1353","text":"At the same time I ought here to repeat what I have said elsewhere,\r that if any of our guardians shall try to be happy in such a manner\r that he will cease to be a guardian, and is not content with this safe\r and harmonious life, which, in our judgment, is of all lives the best,\r but infatuated by some youthful conceit of happiness which gets up into\r his head shall seek to appropriate the whole state to himself, then he\r will have to learn how wisely Hesiod spoke, when he said, ‘half is more\r than the whole.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1353"},"sequenceIndex":1814},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1354","text":"If he were to consult me, I should say to him: Stay where you are, when\r you have the offer of such a life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1354"},"sequenceIndex":1815},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1355","text":"You agree then, I said, that men and women are to have a common way of\r life such as we have described—common education, common children; and\r they are to watch over the citizens in common whether abiding in the\r city or going out to war; they are to keep watch together, and to hunt\r together like dogs; and always and in all things, as far as they are\r able, women are to share with the men? And in so doing they will do\r what is best, and will not violate, but preserve the natural relation\r of the sexes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1355"},"sequenceIndex":1816},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1356","text":"The enquiry, I said, has yet to be made, whether such a community be\r found possible—as among other animals, so also among men—and if\r possible, in what way possible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1356"},"sequenceIndex":1817},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1357","text":"Why, of course they will go on expeditions together; and will take with\r them any of their children who are strong enough, that, after the\r manner of the artisan’s child, they may look on at the work which they\r will have to do when they are grown up; and besides looking on they\r will have to help and be of use in war, and to wait upon their fathers\r and mothers. Did you never observe in the arts how the potters’ boys\r look on and help, long before they touch the wheel?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1357"},"sequenceIndex":1818},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1358","text":"And shall potters be more careful in educating their children and in\r giving them the opportunity of seeing and practising their duties than\r our guardians will be?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1358"},"sequenceIndex":1819},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1359","text":"There is also the effect on the parents, with whom, as with other\r animals, the presence of their young ones will be the greatest\r incentive to valour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1359"},"sequenceIndex":1820},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1360","text":"That is quite true, Socrates; and yet if they are defeated, which may\r often happen in war, how great the danger is! the children will be lost\r as well as their parents, and the State will never recover.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1360"},"sequenceIndex":1821},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1361","text":"Well, but if they are ever to run a risk should they not do so on some\r occasion when, if they escape disaster, they will be the better for it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1361"},"sequenceIndex":1822},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1362","text":"Whether the future soldiers do or do not see war in the days of their\r youth is a very important matter, for the sake of which some risk may\r fairly be incurred.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1362"},"sequenceIndex":1823},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1363","text":"This then must be our first step,—to make our children spectators of\r war; but we must also contrive that they shall be secured against\r danger; then all will be well.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1363"},"sequenceIndex":1824},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1364","text":"Their parents may be supposed not to be blind to the risks of war, but\r to know, as far as human foresight can, what expeditions are safe and\r what dangerous?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1364"},"sequenceIndex":1825},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1365","text":"And they will take them on the safe expeditions and be cautious about\r the dangerous ones?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1365"},"sequenceIndex":1826},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1366","text":"And they will place them under the command of experienced veterans who\r will be their leaders and teachers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1366"},"sequenceIndex":1827},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1367","text":"Still, the dangers of war cannot be always foreseen; there is a good\r deal of chance about them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1367"},"sequenceIndex":1828},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1368","text":"Then against such chances the children must be at once furnished with\r wings, in order that in the hour of need they may fly away and escape.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1368"},"sequenceIndex":1829},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1369","text":"I mean that we must mount them on horses in their earliest youth, and\r when they have learnt to ride, take them on horseback to see war: the\r horses must not be spirited and warlike, but the most tractable and yet\r the swiftest that can be had. In this way they will get an excellent\r view of what is hereafter to be their own business; and if there is\r danger they have only to follow their elder leaders and escape.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1369"},"sequenceIndex":1830},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1370","text":"Next, as to war; what are to be the relations of your soldiers to one\r another and to their enemies? I should be inclined to propose that the\r soldier who leaves his rank or throws away his arms, or is guilty of\r any other act of cowardice, should be degraded into the rank of a\r husbandman or artisan. What do you think?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1370"},"sequenceIndex":1831},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1371","text":"And he who allows himself to be taken prisoner may as well be made a\r present of to his enemies; he is their lawful prey, and let them do\r what they like with him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1371"},"sequenceIndex":1832},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1372","text":"But the hero who has distinguished himself, what shall be done to him?\r In the first place, he shall receive honour in the army from his\r youthful comrades; every one of them in succession shall crown him.\r What do you say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1372"},"sequenceIndex":1833},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1373","text":"Most certainly, and I should be disposed to go further, and say: Let no\r one whom he has a mind to kiss refuse to be kissed by him while the\r expedition lasts. So that if there be a lover in the army, whether his\r love be youth or maiden, he may be more eager to win the prize of\r valour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1373"},"sequenceIndex":1834},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1374","text":"Capital, I said. That the brave man is to have more wives than others\r has been already determined: and he is to have first choices in such\r matters more than others, in order that he may have as many children as\r possible?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1374"},"sequenceIndex":1835},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1375","text":"Again, there is another manner in which, according to Homer, brave\r youths should be honoured; for he tells how Ajax, after he had\r distinguished himself in battle, was rewarded with long chines, which\r seems to be a compliment appropriate to a hero in the flower of his\r age, being not only a tribute of honour but also a very strengthening\r thing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1375"},"sequenceIndex":1836},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1376","text":"Then in this, I said, Homer shall be our teacher; and we too, at\r sacrifices and on the like occasions, will honour the brave according\r to the measure of their valour, whether men or women, with hymns and\r those other distinctions which we were mentioning; also with","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1376"},"sequenceIndex":1837},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1377","text":"Yes, I said; and when a man dies gloriously in war shall we not say, in\r the first place, that he is of the golden race?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1377"},"sequenceIndex":1838},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1378","text":"‘They are holy angels upon the earth, authors of good, averters of\r evil, the guardians of speech-gifted men’?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1378"},"sequenceIndex":1839},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1379","text":"We must learn of the god how we are to order the sepulture of divine\r and heroic personages, and what is to be their special distinction; and\r we must do as he bids?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1379"},"sequenceIndex":1840},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1380","text":"And in ages to come we will reverence them and kneel before their\r sepulchres as at the graves of heroes. And not only they but any who\r are deemed pre-eminently good, whether they die from age, or in any\r other way, shall be admitted to the same honours.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1380"},"sequenceIndex":1841},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1381","text":"First of all, in regard to slavery? Do you think it right that Hellenes\r should enslave Hellenic States, or allow others to enslave them, if\r they can help? Should not their custom be to spare them, considering\r the danger which there is that the whole race may one day fall under\r the yoke of the barbarians?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1381"},"sequenceIndex":1842},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1382","text":"Then no Hellene should be owned by them as a slave; that is a rule\r which they will observe and advise the other Hellenes to observe.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1382"},"sequenceIndex":1843},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1383","text":"Certainly, he said; they will in this way be united against the\r barbarians and will keep their hands off one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1383"},"sequenceIndex":1844},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1384","text":"Next as to the slain; ought the conquerors, I said, to take anything\r but their armour? Does not the practice of despoiling an enemy afford\r an excuse for not facing the battle? Cowards skulk about the dead,\r pretending that they are fulfilling a duty, and many an army before now\r has been lost from this love of plunder.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1384"},"sequenceIndex":1845},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1385","text":"And is there not illiberality and avarice in robbing a corpse, and also\r a degree of meanness and womanishness in making an enemy of the dead\r body when the real enemy has flown away and left only his fighting gear\r behind him,—is not this rather like a dog who cannot get at his\r assailant, quarrelling with the stones which strike him instead?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1385"},"sequenceIndex":1846},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1386","text":"Neither shall we offer up arms at the temples of the gods, least of all\r the arms of Hellenes, if we care to maintain good feeling with other\r Hellenes; and, indeed, we have reason to fear that the offering of\r spoils taken from kinsmen may be a pollution unless commanded by the\r god himself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1386"},"sequenceIndex":1847},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1387","text":"Again, as to the devastation of Hellenic territory or the burning of\r houses, what is to be the practice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1387"},"sequenceIndex":1848},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1388","text":"Both should be forbidden, in my judgment; I would take the annual\r produce and no more. Shall I tell you why?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1388"},"sequenceIndex":1849},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1389","text":"Why, you see, there is a difference in the names ‘discord’ and ‘war,’\r and I imagine that there is also a difference in their natures; the one\r is expressive of what is internal and domestic, the other of what is\r external and foreign; and the first of the two is termed discord, and\r only the second, war.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1389"},"sequenceIndex":1850},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1390","text":"And may I not observe with equal propriety that the Hellenic race is\r all united together by ties of blood and friendship, and alien and\r strange to the barbarians?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1390"},"sequenceIndex":1851},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1391","text":"And therefore when Hellenes fight with barbarians and barbarians with\r Hellenes, they will be described by us as being at war when they fight,\r and by nature enemies, and this kind of antagonism should be called\r war; but when Hellenes fight with one another we shall say that Hellas\r is then in a state of disorder and discord, they being by nature\r friends; and such enmity is to be called discord.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1391"},"sequenceIndex":1852},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1392","text":"Consider then, I said, when that which we have acknowledged to be\r discord occurs, and a city is divided, if both parties destroy the\r lands and burn the houses of one another, how wicked does the strife\r appear! No true lover of his country would bring himself to tear in\r pieces his own nurse and mother: There might be reason in the conqueror\r depriving the conquered of their harvest, but still they would have the\r idea of peace in their hearts and would not mean to go on fighting for\r ever.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1392"},"sequenceIndex":1853},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1393","text":"And will they not be lovers of Hellas, and think of Hellas as their own\r land, and share in the common temples?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1393"},"sequenceIndex":1854},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1394","text":"And any difference which arises among them will be regarded by them as\r discord only—a quarrel among friends, which is not to be called a war?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1394"},"sequenceIndex":1855},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1395","text":"They will use friendly correction, but will not enslave or destroy\r their opponents; they will be correctors, not enemies?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1395"},"sequenceIndex":1856},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1396","text":"And as they are Hellenes themselves they will not devastate Hellas, nor\r will they burn houses, nor ever suppose that the whole population of a\r city—men, women, and children—are equally their enemies, for they know\r that the guilt of war is always confined to a few persons and that the\r many are their friends. And for all these reasons they will be\r unwilling to waste their lands and rase their houses; their enmity to\r them will only last until the many innocent sufferers have compelled\r the guilty few to give satisfaction?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1396"},"sequenceIndex":1857},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1397","text":"I agree, he said, that our citizens should thus deal with their\r Hellenic enemies; and with barbarians as the Hellenes now deal with one\r another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1397"},"sequenceIndex":1858},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1398","text":"Then let us enact this law also for our guardians:—that they are\r neither to devastate the lands of Hellenes nor to burn their houses.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1398"},"sequenceIndex":1859},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1399","text":"Agreed; and we may agree also in thinking that these, like all our\r previous enactments, are very good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1399"},"sequenceIndex":1860},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1400","text":"But still I must say, Socrates, that if you are allowed to go on in\r this way you will entirely forget the other question which at the\r commencement of this discussion you thrust aside:—Is such an order of\r things possible, and how, if at all? For I am quite ready to\r acknowledge that the plan which you propose, if only feasible, would do\r all sorts of good to the State. I will add, what you have omitted, that\r your citizens will be the bravest of warriors, and will never leave\r their ranks, for they will all know one another, and each will call the\r other father, brother, son; and if you supp","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1400"},"sequenceIndex":1861},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1401","text":"If I loiter for a moment, you instantly make a raid upon me, I said,\r and have no mercy; I have hardly escaped the first and second waves,\r and you seem not to be aware that you are now bringing upon me the\r third, which is the greatest and heaviest. When you have seen and heard\r the third wave, I think you will be more considerate and will\r acknowledge that some fear and hesitation was natural respecting a\r proposal so extraordinary as that which I have now to state and\r investigate.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1401"},"sequenceIndex":1862},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1402","text":"The more appeals of this sort which you make, he said, the more\r determined are we that you shall tell us how such a State is possible:\r speak out and at once.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1402"},"sequenceIndex":1863},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1403","text":"Let me begin by reminding you that we found our way hither in the\r search after justice and injustice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1403"},"sequenceIndex":1864},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1404","text":"I was only going to ask whether, if we have discovered them, we are to\r require that the just man should in nothing fail of absolute justice;\r or may we be satisfied with an approximation, and the attainment in him\r of a higher degree of justice than is to be found in other men?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1404"},"sequenceIndex":1865},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1405","text":"We were enquiring into the nature of absolute justice and into the\r character of the perfectly just, and into injustice and the perfectly\r unjust, that we might have an ideal. We were to look at these in order\r that we might judge of our own happiness and unhappiness according to\r the standard which they exhibited and the degree in which we resembled\r them, but not with any view of showing that they could exist in fact.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1405"},"sequenceIndex":1866},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1406","text":"Would a painter be any the worse because, after having delineated with\r consummate art an ideal of a perfectly beautiful man, he was unable to\r show that any such man could ever have existed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1406"},"sequenceIndex":1867},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1407","text":"And is our theory a worse theory because we are unable to prove the\r possibility of a city being ordered in the manner described?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1407"},"sequenceIndex":1868},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1408","text":"That is the truth, I said. But if, at your request, I am to try and\r show how and under what conditions the possibility is highest, I must\r ask you, having this in view, to repeat your former admissions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1408"},"sequenceIndex":1869},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1409","text":"I want to know whether ideals are ever fully realized in language? Does\r not the word express more than the fact, and must not the actual,\r whatever a man may think, always, in the nature of things, fall short\r of the truth? What do you say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1409"},"sequenceIndex":1870},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1410","text":"Then you must not insist on my proving that the actual State will in\r every respect coincide with the ideal: if we are only able to discover\r how a city may be governed nearly as we proposed, you will admit that\r we have discovered the possibility which you demand; and will be\r contented. I am sure that I should be contented—will not you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1410"},"sequenceIndex":1871},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1411","text":"Let me next endeavour to show what is that fault in States which is the\r cause of their present maladministration, and what is the least change\r which will enable a State to pass into the truer form; and let the\r change, if possible, be of one thing only, or, if not, of two; at any\r rate, let the changes be as few and slight as possible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1411"},"sequenceIndex":1872},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1412","text":"I think, I said, that there might be a reform of the State if only one\r change were made, which is not a slight or easy though still a possible\r one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1412"},"sequenceIndex":1873},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1413","text":"Now then, I said, I go to meet that which I liken to the greatest of\r the waves; yet shall the word be spoken, even though the wave break and\r drown me in laughter and dishonour; and do you mark my words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1413"},"sequenceIndex":1874},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1414","text":"I said: ‘Until philosophers are kings, or the kings and princes of this\r world have the spirit and power of philosophy, and political greatness\r and wisdom meet in one, and those commoner natures who pursue either to\r the exclusion of the other are compelled to stand aside, cities will\r never have rest from their evils,—nor the human race, as I believe,—and\r then only will this our State have a possibility of life and behold the\r light of day.’ Such was the thought, my dear Glaucon, which I would\r fain have uttered if it had not seemed too extravagant; for to be\r convinced that in no other Sta","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1414"},"sequenceIndex":1875},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1415","text":"Socrates, what do you mean? I would have you consider that the word\r which you have uttered is one at which numerous persons, and very\r respectable persons too, in a figure pulling off their coats all in a\r moment, and seizing any weapon that comes to hand, will run at you\r might and main, before you know where you are, intending to do heaven\r knows what; and if you don’t prepare an answer, and put yourself in\r motion, you will be ‘pared by their fine wits,’ and no mistake.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1415"},"sequenceIndex":1876},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1416","text":"And I was quite right; however, I will do all I can to get you out of\r it; but I can only give you good-will and good advice, and, perhaps, I\r may be able to fit answers to your questions better than another—that\r is all. And now, having such an auxiliary, you must do your best to\r show the unbelievers that you are right.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1416"},"sequenceIndex":1877},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1417","text":"I ought to try, I said, since you offer me such invaluable assistance.\r And I think that, if there is to be a chance of our escaping, we must\r explain to them whom we mean when we say that philosophers are to rule\r in the State; then we shall be able to defend ourselves: There will be\r discovered to be some natures who ought to study philosophy and to be\r leaders in the State; and others who are not born to be philosophers,\r and are meant to be followers rather than leaders.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1417"},"sequenceIndex":1878},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1418","text":"Follow me, I said, and I hope that I may in some way or other be able\r to give you a satisfactory explanation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1418"},"sequenceIndex":1879},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1419","text":"I dare say that you remember, and therefore I need not remind you, that\r a lover, if he is worthy of the name, ought to show his love, not to\r some one part of that which he loves, but to the whole.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1419"},"sequenceIndex":1880},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1420","text":"Another person, I said, might fairly reply as you do; but a man of\r pleasure like yourself ought to know that all who are in the flower of\r youth do somehow or other raise a pang or emotion in a lover’s breast,\r and are thought by him to be worthy of his affectionate regards. Is not\r this a way which you have with the fair: one has a snub nose, and you\r praise his charming face; the hook-nose of another has, you say, a\r royal look; while he who is neither snub nor hooked has the grace of\r regularity: the dark visage is manly, the fair are children of the\r gods; and as to the sweet ‘honey pale,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1420"},"sequenceIndex":1881},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1421","text":"If you make me an authority in matters of love, for the sake of the\r argument, I assent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1421"},"sequenceIndex":1882},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1422","text":"And what do you say of lovers of wine? Do you not see them doing the\r same? They are glad of any pretext of drinking any wine.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1422"},"sequenceIndex":1883},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1423","text":"And the same is true of ambitious men; if they cannot command an army,\r they are willing to command a file; and if they cannot be honoured by\r really great and important persons, they are glad to be honoured by\r lesser and meaner people,—but honour of some kind they must have.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1423"},"sequenceIndex":1884},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1424","text":"Once more let me ask: Does he who desires any class of goods, desire\r the whole class or a part only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1424"},"sequenceIndex":1885},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1425","text":"And may we not say of the philosopher that he is a lover, not of a part\r of wisdom only, but of the whole?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1425"},"sequenceIndex":1886},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1426","text":"And he who dislikes learning, especially in youth, when he has no power\r of judging what is good and what is not, such an one we maintain not to\r be a philosopher or a lover of knowledge, just as he who refuses his\r food is not hungry, and may be said to have a bad appetite and not a\r good one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1426"},"sequenceIndex":1887},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1427","text":"Whereas he who has a taste for every sort of knowledge and who is\r curious to learn and is never satisfied, may be justly termed a\r philosopher? Am I not right?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1427"},"sequenceIndex":1888},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1428","text":"Glaucon said: If curiosity makes a philosopher, you will find many a\r strange being will have a title to the name. All the lovers of sights\r have a delight in learning, and must therefore be included. Musical\r amateurs, too, are a folk strangely out of place among philosophers,\r for they are the last persons in the world who would come to anything\r like a philosophical discussion, if they could help, while they run\r about at the Dionysiac festivals as if they had let out their ears to\r hear every chorus; whether the performance is in town or country—that\r makes no difference—they are there. No","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1428"},"sequenceIndex":1889},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1429","text":"To another, I replied, I might have a difficulty in explaining; but I\r am sure that you will admit a proposition which I am about to make.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1429"},"sequenceIndex":1890},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1430","text":"And of just and unjust, good and evil, and of every other class, the\r same remark holds: taken singly, each of them is one; but from the\r various combinations of them with actions and things and with one\r another, they are seen in all sorts of lights and appear many?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1430"},"sequenceIndex":1891},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1431","text":"And this is the distinction which I draw between the sight-loving,\r art-loving, practical class and those of whom I am speaking, and who\r are alone worthy of the name of philosophers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1431"},"sequenceIndex":1892},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1432","text":"The lovers of sounds and sights, I replied, are, as I conceive, fond of\r fine tones and colours and forms and all the artificial products that\r are made out of them, but their mind is incapable of seeing or loving\r absolute beauty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1432"},"sequenceIndex":1893},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1433","text":"And he who, having a sense of beautiful things has no sense of absolute\r beauty, or who, if another lead him to a knowledge of that beauty is\r unable to follow—of such an one I ask, Is he awake or in a dream only?\r Reflect: is not the dreamer, sleeping or waking, one who likens\r dissimilar things, who puts the copy in the place of the real object?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1433"},"sequenceIndex":1894},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1434","text":"But take the case of the other, who recognises the existence of\r absolute beauty and is able to distinguish the idea from the objects\r which participate in the idea, neither putting the objects in the place\r of the idea nor the idea in the place of the objects—is he a dreamer,\r or is he awake?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1434"},"sequenceIndex":1895},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1435","text":"And may we not say that the mind of the one who knows has knowledge,\r and that the mind of the other, who opines only, has opinion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1435"},"sequenceIndex":1896},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1436","text":"But suppose that the latter should quarrel with us and dispute our\r statement, can we administer any soothing cordial or advice to him,\r without revealing to him that there is sad disorder in his wits?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1436"},"sequenceIndex":1897},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1437","text":"Come, then, and let us think of something to say to him. Shall we begin\r by assuring him that he is welcome to any knowledge which he may have,\r and that we are rejoiced at his having it? But we should like to ask\r him a question: Does he who has knowledge know something or nothing?\r (You must answer for him.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1437"},"sequenceIndex":1898},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1438","text":"And are we assured, after looking at the matter from many points of\r view, that absolute being is or may be absolutely known, but that the\r utterly non-existent is utterly unknown?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1438"},"sequenceIndex":1899},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1439","text":"Good. But if there be anything which is of such a nature as to be and\r not to be, that will have a place intermediate between pure being and\r the absolute negation of being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1439"},"sequenceIndex":1900},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1440","text":"And, as knowledge corresponded to being and ignorance of necessity to\r not-being, for that intermediate between being and not-being there has\r to be discovered a corresponding intermediate between ignorance and\r knowledge, if there be such?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1440"},"sequenceIndex":1901},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1441","text":"Then opinion and knowledge have to do with different kinds of matter\r corresponding to this difference of faculties?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1441"},"sequenceIndex":1902},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1442","text":"And knowledge is relative to being and knows being. But before I\r proceed further I will make a division.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1442"},"sequenceIndex":1903},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1443","text":"I will begin by placing faculties in a class by themselves: they are\r powers in us, and in all other things, by which we do as we do. Sight\r and hearing, for example, I should call faculties. Have I clearly\r explained the class which I mean?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1443"},"sequenceIndex":1904},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1444","text":"Then let me tell you my view about them. I do not see them, and\r therefore the distinctions of figure, colour, and the like, which\r enable me to discern the differences of some things, do not apply to\r them. In speaking of a faculty I think only of its sphere and its\r result; and that which has the same sphere and the same result I call\r the same faculty, but that which has another sphere and another result\r I call different. Would that be your way of speaking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1444"},"sequenceIndex":1905},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1445","text":"And will you be so very good as to answer one more question? Would you\r say that knowledge is a faculty, or in what class would you place it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1445"},"sequenceIndex":1906},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1446","text":"Certainly, he said; for opinion is that with which we are able to form\r an opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1446"},"sequenceIndex":1907},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1447","text":"And yet you were acknowledging a little while ago that knowledge is not\r the same as opinion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1447"},"sequenceIndex":1908},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1448","text":"Why, yes, he said: how can any reasonable being ever identify that\r which is infallible with that which errs?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1448"},"sequenceIndex":1909},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1449","text":"An excellent answer, proving, I said, that we are quite conscious of a\r distinction between them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1449"},"sequenceIndex":1910},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1450","text":"Then knowledge and opinion having distinct powers have also distinct\r spheres or subject-matters?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1450"},"sequenceIndex":1911},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1451","text":"Being is the sphere or subject-matter of knowledge, and knowledge is to\r know the nature of being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1451"},"sequenceIndex":1912},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1452","text":"And do we know what we opine? or is the subject-matter of opinion the\r same as the subject-matter of knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1452"},"sequenceIndex":1913},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1453","text":"Nay, he replied, that has been already disproven; if difference in\r faculty implies difference in the sphere or subject-matter, and if, as\r we were saying, opinion and knowledge are distinct faculties, then the\r sphere of knowledge and of opinion cannot be the same.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1453"},"sequenceIndex":1914},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1454","text":"Then if being is the subject-matter of knowledge, something else must\r be the subject-matter of opinion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1454"},"sequenceIndex":1915},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1455","text":"Well then, is not-being the subject-matter of opinion? or, rather, how\r can there be an opinion at all about not-being? Reflect: when a man has\r an opinion, has he not an opinion about something? Can he have an\r opinion which is an opinion about nothing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1455"},"sequenceIndex":1916},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1456","text":"Of not-being, ignorance was assumed to be the necessary correlative; of\r being, knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1456"},"sequenceIndex":1917},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1457","text":"But is opinion to be sought without and beyond either of them, in a\r greater clearness than knowledge, or in a greater darkness than\r ignorance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1457"},"sequenceIndex":1918},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1458","text":"Then I suppose that opinion appears to you to be darker than knowledge,\r but lighter than ignorance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1458"},"sequenceIndex":1919},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1459","text":"But were we not saying before, that if anything appeared to be of a\r sort which is and is not at the same time, that sort of thing would\r appear also to lie in the interval between pure being and absolute\r not-being; and that the corresponding faculty is neither knowledge nor\r ignorance, but will be found in the interval between them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1459"},"sequenceIndex":1920},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1460","text":"And in that interval there has now been discovered something which we\r call opinion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1460"},"sequenceIndex":1921},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1461","text":"Then what remains to be discovered is the object which partakes equally\r of the nature of being and not-being, and cannot rightly be termed\r either, pure and simple; this unknown term, when discovered, we may\r truly call the subject of opinion, and assign each to their proper\r faculty,—the extremes to the faculties of the extremes and the mean to\r the faculty of the mean.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1461"},"sequenceIndex":1922},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1462","text":"This being premised, I would ask the gentleman who is of opinion that\r there is no absolute or unchangeable idea of beauty—in whose opinion\r the beautiful is the manifold—he, I say, your lover of beautiful\r sights, who cannot bear to be told that the beautiful is one, and the\r just is one, or that anything is one—to him I would appeal, saying,\r Will you be so very kind, sir, as to tell us whether, of all these\r beautiful things, there is one which will not be found ugly; or of the\r just, which will not be found unjust; or of the holy, which will not\r also be unholy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1462"},"sequenceIndex":1923},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1463","text":"No, he replied; the beautiful will in some point of view be found ugly;\r and the same is true of the rest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1463"},"sequenceIndex":1924},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1464","text":"And may not the many which are doubles be also halves?—doubles, that\r is, of one thing, and halves of another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1464"},"sequenceIndex":1925},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1465","text":"And things great and small, heavy and light, as they are termed, will\r not be denoted by these any more than by the opposite names?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1465"},"sequenceIndex":1926},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1466","text":"And can any one of those many things which are called by particular\r names be said to be this rather than not to be this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1466"},"sequenceIndex":1927},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1467","text":"He replied: They are like the punning riddles which are asked at feasts\r or the children’s puzzle about the eunuch aiming at the bat, with what\r he hit him, as they say in the puzzle, and upon what the bat was\r sitting. The individual objects of which I am speaking are also a\r riddle, and have a double sense: nor can you fix them in your mind,\r either as being or not-being, or both, or neither.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1467"},"sequenceIndex":1928},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1468","text":"Then what will you do with them? I said. Can they have a better place\r than between being and not-being? For they are clearly not in greater\r darkness or negation than not-being, or more full of light and\r existence than being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1468"},"sequenceIndex":1929},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1469","text":"Thus then we seem to have discovered that the many ideas which the\r multitude entertain about the beautiful and about all other things are\r tossing about in some region which is half-way between pure being and\r pure not-being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1469"},"sequenceIndex":1930},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1470","text":"Yes; and we had before agreed that anything of this kind which we might\r find was to be described as matter of opinion, and not as matter of\r knowledge; being the intermediate flux which is caught and detained by\r the intermediate faculty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1470"},"sequenceIndex":1931},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1471","text":"Then those who see the many beautiful, and who yet neither see absolute\r beauty, nor can follow any guide who points the way thither; who see\r the many just, and not absolute justice, and the like,—such persons may\r be said to have opinion but not knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1471"},"sequenceIndex":1932},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1472","text":"But those who see the absolute and eternal and immutable may be said to\r know, and not to have opinion only?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1472"},"sequenceIndex":1933},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1473","text":"The one love and embrace the subjects of knowledge, the other those of\r opinion? The latter are the same, as I dare say you will remember, who\r listened to sweet sounds and gazed upon fair colours, but would not\r tolerate the existence of absolute beauty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1473"},"sequenceIndex":1934},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1474","text":"Shall we then be guilty of any impropriety in calling them lovers of\r opinion rather than lovers of wisdom, and will they be very angry with\r us for thus describing them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1474"},"sequenceIndex":1935},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1475","text":"But those who love the truth in each thing are to be called lovers of\r wisdom and not lovers of opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1475"},"sequenceIndex":1936},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1476","text":"And thus, Glaucon, after the argument has gone a weary way, the true\r and the false philosophers have at length appeared in view.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1476"},"sequenceIndex":1937},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1477","text":"I suppose not, I said; and yet I believe that we might have had a\r better view of both of them if the discussion could have been confined\r to this one subject and if there were not many other questions awaiting\r us, which he who desires to see in what respect the life of the just\r differs from that of the unjust must consider.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1477"},"sequenceIndex":1938},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1478","text":"Surely, I said, the one which follows next in order. Inasmuch as\r philosophers only are able to grasp the eternal and unchangeable, and\r those who wander in the region of the many and variable are not\r philosophers, I must ask you which of the two classes should be the\r rulers of our State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1478"},"sequenceIndex":1939},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1479","text":"Whichever of the two are best able to guard the laws and institutions\r of our State—let them be our guardians.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1479"},"sequenceIndex":1940},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1480","text":"Neither, I said, can there be any question that the guardian who is to\r keep anything should have eyes rather than no eyes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1480"},"sequenceIndex":1941},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1481","text":"And are not those who are verily and indeed wanting in the knowledge of\r the true being of each thing, and who have in their souls no clear\r pattern, and are unable as with a painter’s eye to look at the absolute\r truth and to that original to repair, and having perfect vision of the\r other world to order the laws about beauty, goodness, justice in this,\r if not already ordered, and to guard and preserve the order of them—are\r not such persons, I ask, simply blind?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1481"},"sequenceIndex":1942},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1482","text":"And shall they be our guardians when there are others who, besides\r being their equals in experience and falling short of them in no\r particular of virtue, also know the very truth of each thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1482"},"sequenceIndex":1943},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1483","text":"There can be no reason, he said, for rejecting those who have this\r greatest of all great qualities; they must always have the first place\r unless they fail in some other respect.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1483"},"sequenceIndex":1944},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1484","text":"Suppose then, I said, that we determine how far they can unite this and\r the other excellences.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1484"},"sequenceIndex":1945},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1485","text":"In the first place, as we began by observing, the nature of the\r philosopher has to be ascertained. We must come to an understanding\r about him, and, when we have done so, then, if I am not mistaken, we\r shall also acknowledge that such an union of qualities is possible, and\r that those in whom they are united, and those only, should be rulers in\r the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1485"},"sequenceIndex":1946},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1486","text":"Let us suppose that philosophical minds always love knowledge of a sort\r which shows them the eternal nature not varying from generation and\r corruption.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1486"},"sequenceIndex":1947},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1487","text":"And further, I said, let us agree that they are lovers of all true\r being; there is no part whether greater or less, or more or less\r honourable, which they are willing to renounce; as we said before of\r the lover and the man of ambition.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1487"},"sequenceIndex":1948},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1488","text":"And if they are to be what we were describing, is there not another\r quality which they should also possess?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1488"},"sequenceIndex":1949},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1489","text":"Truthfulness: they will never intentionally receive into their mind\r falsehood, which is their detestation, and they will love the truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1489"},"sequenceIndex":1950},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1490","text":"‘May be,’ my friend, I replied, is not the word; say rather ‘must be\r affirmed:’ for he whose nature is amorous of anything cannot help\r loving all that belongs or is akin to the object of his affections.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1490"},"sequenceIndex":1951},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1491","text":"The true lover of learning then must from his earliest youth, as far as\r in him lies, desire all truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1491"},"sequenceIndex":1952},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1492","text":"But then again, as we know by experience, he whose desires are strong\r in one direction will have them weaker in others; they will be like a\r stream which has been drawn off into another channel.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1492"},"sequenceIndex":1953},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1493","text":"He whose desires are drawn towards knowledge in every form will be\r absorbed in the pleasures of the soul, and will hardly feel bodily\r pleasure—I mean, if he be a true philosopher and not a sham one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1493"},"sequenceIndex":1954},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1494","text":"Such an one is sure to be temperate and the reverse of covetous; for\r the motives which make another man desirous of having and spending,\r have no place in his character.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1494"},"sequenceIndex":1955},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1495","text":"There should be no secret corner of illiberality; nothing can be more\r antagonistic than meanness to a soul which is ever longing after the\r whole of things both divine and human.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1495"},"sequenceIndex":1956},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1496","text":"Then how can he who has magnificence of mind and is the spectator of\r all time and all existence, think much of human life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1496"},"sequenceIndex":1957},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1497","text":"Or again: can he who is harmoniously constituted, who is not covetous\r or mean, or a boaster, or a coward—can he, I say, ever be unjust or\r hard in his dealings?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1497"},"sequenceIndex":1958},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1498","text":"Then you will soon observe whether a man is just and gentle, or rude\r and unsociable; these are the signs which distinguish even in youth the\r philosophical nature from the unphilosophical.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1498"},"sequenceIndex":1959},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1499","text":"Whether he has or has not a pleasure in learning; for no one will love\r that which gives him pain, and in which after much toil he makes little\r progress.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1499"},"sequenceIndex":1960},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1500","text":"And again, if he is forgetful and retains nothing of what he learns,\r will he not be an empty vessel?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1500"},"sequenceIndex":1961},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1501","text":"Labouring in vain, he must end in hating himself and his fruitless\r occupation? Yes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1501"},"sequenceIndex":1962},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1502","text":"Then a soul which forgets cannot be ranked among genuine philosophic\r natures; we must insist that the philosopher should have a good memory?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1502"},"sequenceIndex":1963},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1503","text":"And once more, the inharmonious and unseemly nature can only tend to\r disproportion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1503"},"sequenceIndex":1964},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1504","text":"Then, besides other qualities, we must try to find a naturally\r well-proportioned and gracious mind, which will move spontaneously\r towards the true being of everything.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1504"},"sequenceIndex":1965},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1505","text":"Well, and do not all these qualities, which we have been enumerating,\r go together, and are they not, in a manner, necessary to a soul, which\r is to have a full and perfect participation of being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1505"},"sequenceIndex":1966},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1506","text":"And must not that be a blameless study which he only can pursue who has\r the gift of a good memory, and is quick to learn,—noble, gracious, the\r friend of truth, justice, courage, temperance, who are his kindred?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1506"},"sequenceIndex":1967},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1507","text":"And to men like him, I said, when perfected by years and education, and\r to these only you will entrust the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1507"},"sequenceIndex":1968},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1508","text":"Here Adeimantus interposed and said: To these statements, Socrates, no\r one can offer a reply; but when you talk in this way, a strange feeling\r passes over the minds of your hearers: They fancy that they are led\r astray a little at each step in the argument, owing to their own want\r of skill in asking and answering questions; these littles accumulate,\r and at the end of the discussion they are found to have sustained a\r mighty overthrow and all their former notions appear to be turned\r upside down. And as unskilful players of draughts are at last shut up\r by their more skilful adversaries and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1508"},"sequenceIndex":1969},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1509","text":"Then how can you be justified in saying that cities will not cease from\r evil until philosophers rule in them, when philosophers are\r acknowledged by us to be of no use to them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1509"},"sequenceIndex":1970},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1510","text":"Yes, Socrates; and that is a way of speaking to which you are not at\r all accustomed, I suppose.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1510"},"sequenceIndex":1971},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1511","text":"I perceive, I said, that you are vastly amused at having plunged me\r into such a hopeless discussion; but now hear the parable, and then you\r will be still more amused at the meagreness of my imagination: for the\r manner in which the best men are treated in their own States is so\r grievous that no single thing on earth is comparable to it; and\r therefore, if I am to plead their cause, I must have recourse to\r fiction, and put together a figure made up of many things, like the\r fabulous unions of goats and stags which are found in pictures. Imagine\r then a fleet or a ship in which there is a ca","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1511"},"sequenceIndex":1972},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1512","text":"Then you will hardly need, I said, to hear the interpretation of the\r figure, which describes the true philosopher in his relation to the\r State; for you understand already.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1512"},"sequenceIndex":1973},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1513","text":"Then suppose you now take this parable to the gentleman who is\r surprised at finding that philosophers have no honour in their cities;\r explain it to him and try to convince him that their having honour\r would be far more extraordinary.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1513"},"sequenceIndex":1974},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1514","text":"Say to him, that, in deeming the best votaries of philosophy to be\r useless to the rest of the world, he is right; but also tell him to\r attribute their uselessness to the fault of those who will not use\r them, and not to themselves. The pilot should not humbly beg the\r sailors to be commanded by him—that is not the order of nature; neither\r are ‘the wise to go to the doors of the rich’—the ingenious author of\r this saying told a lie—but the truth is, that, when a man is ill,\r whether he be rich or poor, to the physician he must go, and he who\r wants to be governed, to him who is able to gover","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1514"},"sequenceIndex":1975},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1515","text":"For these reasons, and among men like these, philosophy, the noblest\r pursuit of all, is not likely to be much esteemed by those of the\r opposite faction; not that the greatest and most lasting injury is done\r to her by her opponents, but by her own professing followers, the same\r of whom you suppose the accuser to say, that the greater number of them\r are arrant rogues, and the best are useless; in which opinion I agreed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1515"},"sequenceIndex":1976},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1516","text":"Then shall we proceed to show that the corruption of the majority is\r also unavoidable, and that this is not to be laid to the charge of\r philosophy any more than the other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1516"},"sequenceIndex":1977},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1517","text":"And let us ask and answer in turn, first going back to the description\r of the gentle and noble nature. Truth, as you will remember, was his\r leader, whom he followed always and in all things; failing in this, he\r was an impostor, and had no part or lot in true philosophy.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1517"},"sequenceIndex":1978},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1518","text":"Well, and is not this one quality, to mention no others, greatly at\r variance with present notions of him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1518"},"sequenceIndex":1979},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1519","text":"And have we not a right to say in his defence, that the true lover of\r knowledge is always striving after being—that is his nature; he will\r not rest in the multiplicity of individuals which is an appearance\r only, but will go on—the keen edge will not be blunted, nor the force\r of his desire abate until he have attained the knowledge of the true\r nature of every essence by a sympathetic and kindred power in the soul,\r and by that power drawing near and mingling and becoming incorporate\r with very being, having begotten mind and truth, he will have knowledge\r and will live and grow truly, and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1519"},"sequenceIndex":1980},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1520","text":"And will the love of a lie be any part of a philosopher’s nature? Will\r he not utterly hate a lie?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1520"},"sequenceIndex":1981},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1521","text":"And when truth is the captain, we cannot suspect any evil of the band\r which he leads?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1521"},"sequenceIndex":1982},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1522","text":"Justice and health of mind will be of the company, and temperance will\r follow after?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1522"},"sequenceIndex":1983},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1523","text":"Neither is there any reason why I should again set in array the\r philosopher’s virtues, as you will doubtless remember that courage,\r magnificence, apprehension, memory, were his natural gifts. And you\r objected that, although no one could deny what I then said, still, if\r you leave words and look at facts, the persons who are thus described\r are some of them manifestly useless, and the greater number utterly\r depraved; we were then led to enquire into the grounds of these\r accusations, and have now arrived at the point of asking why are the\r majority bad, which question of necessity brought u","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1523"},"sequenceIndex":1984},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1524","text":"And we have next to consider the corruptions of the philosophic nature,\r why so many are spoiled and so few escape spoiling—I am speaking of\r those who were said to be useless but not wicked—and, when we have done\r with them, we will speak of the imitators of philosophy, what manner of\r men are they who aspire after a profession which is above them and of\r which they are unworthy, and then, by their manifold inconsistencies,\r bring upon philosophy, and upon all philosophers, that universal\r reprobation of which we speak.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1524"},"sequenceIndex":1985},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1525","text":"I will see if I can explain them to you. Every one will admit that a\r nature having in perfection all the qualities which we required in a\r philosopher, is a rare plant which is seldom seen among men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1525"},"sequenceIndex":1986},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1526","text":"In the first place there are their own virtues, their courage,\r temperance, and the rest of them, every one of which praiseworthy\r qualities (and this is a most singular circumstance) destroys and\r distracts from philosophy the soul which is the possessor of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1526"},"sequenceIndex":1987},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1527","text":"Then there are all the ordinary goods of life—beauty, wealth, strength,\r rank, and great connections in the State—you understand the sort of\r things—these also have a corrupting and distracting effect.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1527"},"sequenceIndex":1988},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1528","text":"I understand; but I should like to know more precisely what you mean\r about them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1528"},"sequenceIndex":1989},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1529","text":"Grasp the truth as a whole, I said, and in the right way; you will then\r have no difficulty in apprehending the preceding remarks, and they will\r no longer appear strange to you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1529"},"sequenceIndex":1990},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1530","text":"Why, I said, we know that all germs or seeds, whether vegetable or\r animal, when they fail to meet with proper nutriment or climate or\r soil, in proportion to their vigour, are all the more sensitive to the\r want of a suitable environment, for evil is a greater enemy to what is\r good than to what is not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1530"},"sequenceIndex":1991},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1531","text":"There is reason in supposing that the finest natures, when under alien\r conditions, receive more injury than the inferior, because the contrast\r is greater.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1531"},"sequenceIndex":1992},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1532","text":"And may we not say, Adeimantus, that the most gifted minds, when they\r are ill-educated, become pre-eminently bad? Do not great crimes and the\r spirit of pure evil spring out of a fulness of nature ruined by\r education rather than from any inferiority, whereas weak natures are\r scarcely capable of any very great good or very great evil?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1532"},"sequenceIndex":1993},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1533","text":"And our philosopher follows the same analogy—he is like a plant which,\r having proper nurture, must necessarily grow and mature into all\r virtue, but, if sown and planted in an alien soil, becomes the most\r noxious of all weeds, unless he be preserved by some divine power. Do\r you really think, as people so often say, that our youth are corrupted\r by Sophists, or that private teachers of the art corrupt them in any\r degree worth speaking of? Are not the public who say these things the\r greatest of all Sophists? And do they not educate to perfection young\r and old, men and women alike, and fash","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1533"},"sequenceIndex":1994},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1534","text":"When they meet together, and the world sits down at an assembly, or in\r a court of law, or a theatre, or a camp, or in any other popular\r resort, and there is a great uproar, and they praise some things which\r are being said or done, and blame other things, equally exaggerating\r both, shouting and clapping their hands, and the echo of the rocks and\r the place in which they are assembled redoubles the sound of the praise\r or blame—at such a time will not a young man’s heart, as they say, leap\r within him? Will any private training enable him to stand firm against\r the overwhelming flood of popu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1534"},"sequenceIndex":1995},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1535","text":"And yet, I said, there is a still greater necessity, which has not been\r mentioned.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1535"},"sequenceIndex":1996},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1536","text":"The gentle force of attainder or confiscation or death, which, as you\r are aware, these new Sophists and educators, who are the public, apply\r when their words are powerless.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1536"},"sequenceIndex":1997},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1537","text":"Now what opinion of any other Sophist, or of any private person, can be\r expected to overcome in such an unequal contest?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1537"},"sequenceIndex":1998},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1538","text":"No, indeed, I said, even to make the attempt is a great piece of folly;\r there neither is, nor has been, nor is ever likely to be, any different\r type of character which has had no other training in virtue but that\r which is supplied by public opinion—I speak, my friend, of human virtue\r only; what is more than human, as the proverb says, is not included:\r for I would not have you ignorant that, in the present evil state of\r governments, whatever is saved and comes to good is saved by the power\r of God, as we may truly say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1538"},"sequenceIndex":1999},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1539","text":"Why, that all those mercenary individuals, whom the many call Sophists\r and whom they deem to be their adversaries, do, in fact, teach nothing\r but the opinion of the many, that is to say, the opinions of their\r assemblies; and this is their wisdom. I might compare them to a man who\r should study the tempers and desires of a mighty strong beast who is\r fed by him—he would learn how to approach and handle him, also at what\r times and from what causes he is dangerous or the reverse, and what is\r the meaning of his several cries, and by what sounds, when another\r utters them, he is soothed or inf","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1539"},"sequenceIndex":2000},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1540","text":"And in what way does he who thinks that wisdom is the discernment of\r the tempers and tastes of the motley multitude, whether in painting or\r music, or, finally, in politics, differ from him whom I have been\r describing? For when a man consorts with the many, and exhibits to them\r his poem or other work of art or the service which he has done the\r State, making them his judges when he is not obliged, the so-called\r necessity of Diomede will oblige him to produce whatever they praise.\r And yet the reasons are utterly ludicrous which they give in\r confirmation of their own notions about the hono","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1540"},"sequenceIndex":2001},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1541","text":"You recognise the truth of what I have been saying? Then let me ask you\r to consider further whether the world will ever be induced to believe\r in the existence of absolute beauty rather than of the many beautiful,\r or of the absolute in each kind rather than of the many in each kind?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1541"},"sequenceIndex":2002},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1542","text":"And therefore philosophers must inevitably fall under the censure of\r the world?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1542"},"sequenceIndex":2003},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1543","text":"Then, do you see any way in which the philosopher can be preserved in\r his calling to the end? and remember what we were saying of him, that\r he was to have quickness and memory and courage and magnificence—these\r were admitted by us to be the true philosopher’s gifts.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1543"},"sequenceIndex":2004},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1544","text":"Will not such an one from his early childhood be in all things first\r among all, especially if his bodily endowments are like his mental\r ones?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1544"},"sequenceIndex":2005},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1545","text":"And his friends and fellow-citizens will want to use him as he gets\r older for their own purposes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1545"},"sequenceIndex":2006},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1546","text":"Falling at his feet, they will make requests to him and do him honour\r and flatter him, because they want to get into their hands now, the\r power which he will one day possess.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1546"},"sequenceIndex":2007},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1547","text":"And what will a man such as he is be likely to do under such\r circumstances, especially if he be a citizen of a great city, rich and\r noble, and a tall proper youth? Will he not be full of boundless\r aspirations, and fancy himself able to manage the affairs of Hellenes\r and of barbarians, and having got such notions into his head will he\r not dilate and elevate himself in the fulness of vain pomp and\r senseless pride?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1547"},"sequenceIndex":2008},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1548","text":"Now, when he is in this state of mind, if some one gently comes to him\r and tells him that he is a fool and must get understanding, which can\r only be got by slaving for it, do you think that, under such adverse\r circumstances, he will be easily induced to listen?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1548"},"sequenceIndex":2009},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1549","text":"And even if there be some one who through inherent goodness or natural\r reasonableness has had his eyes opened a little and is humbled and\r taken captive by philosophy, how will his friends behave when they\r think that they are likely to lose the advantage which they were hoping\r to reap from his companionship? Will they not do and say anything to\r prevent him from yielding to his better nature and to render his\r teacher powerless, using to this end private intrigues as well as\r public prosecutions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1549"},"sequenceIndex":2010},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1550","text":"Then were we not right in saying that even the very qualities which\r make a man a philosopher may, if he be ill-educated, divert him from\r philosophy, no less than riches and their accompaniments and the other\r so-called goods of life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1550"},"sequenceIndex":2011},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1551","text":"Thus, my excellent friend, is brought about all that ruin and failure\r which I have been describing of the natures best adapted to the best of\r all pursuits; they are natures which we maintain to be rare at any\r time; this being the class out of which come the men who are the\r authors of the greatest evil to States and individuals; and also of the\r greatest good when the tide carries them in that direction; but a small\r man never was the doer of any great thing either to individuals or to\r States.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1551"},"sequenceIndex":2012},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1552","text":"And so philosophy is left desolate, with her marriage rite incomplete:\r for her own have fallen away and forsaken her, and while they are\r leading a false and unbecoming life, other unworthy persons, seeing\r that she has no kinsmen to be her protectors, enter in and dishonour\r her; and fasten upon her the reproaches which, as you say, her\r reprovers utter, who affirm of her votaries that some are good for\r nothing, and that the greater number deserve the severest punishment.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1552"},"sequenceIndex":2013},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1553","text":"Yes; and what else would you expect, I said, when you think of the puny\r creatures who, seeing this land open to them—a land well stocked with\r fair names and showy titles—like prisoners running out of prison into a\r sanctuary, take a leap out of their trades into philosophy; those who\r do so being probably the cleverest hands at their own miserable crafts?\r For, although philosophy be in this evil case, still there remains a\r dignity about her which is not to be found in the arts. And many are\r thus attracted by her whose natures are imperfect and whose souls are\r maimed and disfigured by the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1553"},"sequenceIndex":2014},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1554","text":"Are they not exactly like a bald little tinker who has just got out of\r durance and come into a fortune; he takes a bath and puts on a new\r coat, and is decked out as a bridegroom going to marry his master’s\r daughter, who is left poor and desolate?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1554"},"sequenceIndex":2015},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1555","text":"And when persons who are unworthy of education approach philosophy and\r make an alliance with her who is in a rank above them what sort of\r ideas and opinions are likely to be generated? Will they not be\r sophisms captivating to the ear, having nothing in them genuine, or\r worthy of or akin to true wisdom?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1555"},"sequenceIndex":2016},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1556","text":"Then, Adeimantus, I said, the worthy disciples of philosophy will be\r but a small remnant: perchance some noble and well-educated person,\r detained by exile in her service, who in the absence of corrupting\r influences remains devoted to her; or some lofty soul born in a mean\r city, the politics of which he contemns and neglects; and there may be\r a gifted few who leave the arts, which they justly despise, and come to\r her;—or peradventure there are some who are restrained by our friend\r Theages’ bridle; for everything in the life of Theages conspired to\r divert him from philosophy; but ill-hea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1556"},"sequenceIndex":2017},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1557","text":"A great work—yes; but not the greatest, unless he find a State suitable\r to him; for in a State which is suitable to him, he will have a larger\r growth and be the saviour of his country, as well as of himself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1557"},"sequenceIndex":2018},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1558","text":"The causes why philosophy is in such an evil name have now been\r sufficiently explained: the injustice of the charges against her has\r been shown—is there anything more which you wish to say?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1558"},"sequenceIndex":2019},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1559","text":"Nothing more on that subject, he replied; but I should like to know\r which of the governments now existing is in your opinion the one\r adapted to her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1559"},"sequenceIndex":2020},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1560","text":"Not any of them, I said; and that is precisely the accusation which I\r bring against them—not one of them is worthy of the philosophic nature,\r and hence that nature is warped and estranged;—as the exotic seed which\r is sown in a foreign land becomes denaturalized, and is wont to be\r overpowered and to lose itself in the new soil, even so this growth of\r philosophy, instead of persisting, degenerates and receives another\r character. But if philosophy ever finds in the State that perfection\r which she herself is, then will be seen that she is in truth divine,\r and that all other things, whether","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1560"},"sequenceIndex":2021},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1561","text":"No, he said; there you are wrong, for I was going to ask another\r question—whether it is the State of which we are the founders and\r inventors, or some other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1561"},"sequenceIndex":2022},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1562","text":"Yes, I replied, ours in most respects; but you may remember my saying\r before, that some living authority would always be required in the\r State having the same idea of the constitution which guided you when as\r legislator you were laying down the laws.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1562"},"sequenceIndex":2023},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1563","text":"Yes, but not in a satisfactory manner; you frightened us by interposing\r objections, which certainly showed that the discussion would be long\r and difficult; and what still remains is the reverse of easy.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1563"},"sequenceIndex":2024},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1564","text":"The question how the study of philosophy may be so ordered as not to be\r the ruin of the State: All great attempts are attended with risk; ‘hard\r is the good,’ as men say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1564"},"sequenceIndex":2025},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1565","text":"Still, he said, let the point be cleared up, and the enquiry will then\r be complete.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1565"},"sequenceIndex":2026},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1566","text":"I shall not be hindered, I said, by any want of will, but, if at all,\r by a want of power: my zeal you may see for yourselves; and please to\r remark in what I am about to say how boldly and unhesitatingly I\r declare that States should pursue philosophy, not as they do now, but\r in a different spirit.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1566"},"sequenceIndex":2027},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1567","text":"At present, I said, the students of philosophy are quite young;\r beginning when they are hardly past childhood, they devote only the\r time saved from moneymaking and housekeeping to such pursuits; and even\r those of them who are reputed to have most of the philosophic spirit,\r when they come within sight of the great difficulty of the subject, I\r mean dialectic, take themselves off. In after life when invited by some\r one else, they may, perhaps, go and hear a lecture, and about this they\r make much ado, for philosophy is not considered by them to be their\r proper business: at last, when they ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1567"},"sequenceIndex":2028},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1568","text":"Just the opposite. In childhood and youth their study, and what\r philosophy they learn, should be suited to their tender years: during\r this period while they are growing up towards manhood, the chief and\r special care should be given to their bodies that they may have them to\r use in the service of philosophy; as life advances and the intellect\r begins to mature, let them increase the gymnastics of the soul; but\r when the strength of our citizens fails and is past civil and military\r duties, then let them range at will and engage in no serious labour, as\r we intend them to live happily here, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1568"},"sequenceIndex":2029},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1569","text":"How truly in earnest you are, Socrates! he said; I am sure of that; and\r yet most of your hearers, if I am not mistaken, are likely to be still\r more earnest in their opposition to you, and will never be convinced;\r Thrasymachus least of all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1569"},"sequenceIndex":2030},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1570","text":"Do not make a quarrel, I said, between Thrasymachus and me, who have\r recently become friends, although, indeed, we were never enemies; for I\r shall go on striving to the utmost until I either convert him and other\r men, or do something which may profit them against the day when they\r live again, and hold the like discourse in another state of existence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1570"},"sequenceIndex":2031},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1571","text":"Rather, I replied, of a time which is as nothing in comparison with\r eternity. Nevertheless, I do not wonder that the many refuse to\r believe; for they have never seen that of which we are now speaking\r realized; they have seen only a conventional imitation of philosophy,\r consisting of words artificially brought together, not like these of\r ours having a natural unity. But a human being who in word and work is\r perfectly moulded, as far as he can be, into the proportion and\r likeness of virtue—such a man ruling in a city which bears the same\r image, they have never yet seen, neither one nor m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1571"},"sequenceIndex":2032},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1572","text":"No, my friend, and they have seldom, if ever, heard free and noble\r sentiments; such as men utter when they are earnestly and by every\r means in their power seeking after truth for the sake of knowledge,\r while they look coldly on the subtleties of controversy, of which the\r end is opinion and strife, whether they meet with them in the courts of\r law or in society.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1572"},"sequenceIndex":2033},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1573","text":"And this was what we foresaw, and this was the reason why truth forced\r us to admit, not without fear and hesitation, that neither cities nor\r States nor individuals will ever attain perfection until the small\r class of philosophers whom we termed useless but not corrupt are\r providentially compelled, whether they will or not, to take care of the\r State, and until a like necessity be laid on the State to obey them; or\r until kings, or if not kings, the sons of kings or princes, are\r divinely inspired with a true love of true philosophy. That either or\r both of these alternatives are impossible","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1573"},"sequenceIndex":2034},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1574","text":"If then, in the countless ages of the past, or at the present hour in\r some foreign clime which is far away and beyond our ken, the perfected\r philosopher is or has been or hereafter shall be compelled by a\r superior power to have the charge of the State, we are ready to assert\r to the death, that this our constitution has been, and is—yea, and will\r be whenever the Muse of Philosophy is queen. There is no impossibility\r in all this; that there is a difficulty, we acknowledge ourselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1574"},"sequenceIndex":2035},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1575","text":"O my friend, I said, do not attack the multitude: they will change\r their minds, if, not in an aggressive spirit, but gently and with the\r view of soothing them and removing their dislike of over-education, you\r show them your philosophers as they really are and describe as you were\r just now doing their character and profession, and then mankind will\r see that he of whom you are speaking is not such as they supposed—if\r they view him in this new light, they will surely change their notion\r of him, and answer in another strain. Who can be at enmity with one who\r loves them, who that is himself","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1575"},"sequenceIndex":2036},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1576","text":"And do you not also think, as I do, that the harsh feeling which the\r many entertain towards philosophy originates in the pretenders, who\r rush in uninvited, and are always abusing them, and finding fault with\r them, who make persons instead of things the theme of their\r conversation? and nothing can be more unbecoming in philosophers than\r this.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1576"},"sequenceIndex":2037},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1577","text":"For he, Adeimantus, whose mind is fixed upon true being, has surely no\r time to look down upon the affairs of earth, or to be filled with\r malice and envy, contending against men; his eye is ever directed\r towards things fixed and immutable, which he sees neither injuring nor\r injured by one another, but all in order moving according to reason;\r these he imitates, and to these he will, as far as he can, conform\r himself. Can a man help imitating that with which he holds reverential\r converse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1577"},"sequenceIndex":2038},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1578","text":"And the philosopher holding converse with the divine order, becomes\r orderly and divine, as far as the nature of man allows; but like every\r one else, he will suffer from detraction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1578"},"sequenceIndex":2039},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1579","text":"And if a necessity be laid upon him of fashioning, not only himself,\r but human nature generally, whether in States or individuals, into that\r which he beholds elsewhere, will he, think you, be an unskilful\r artificer of justice, temperance, and every civil virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1579"},"sequenceIndex":2040},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1580","text":"And if the world perceives that what we are saying about him is the\r truth, will they be angry with philosophy? Will they disbelieve us,\r when we tell them that no State can be happy which is not designed by\r artists who imitate the heavenly pattern?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1580"},"sequenceIndex":2041},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1581","text":"They will not be angry if they understand, he said. But how will they\r draw out the plan of which you are speaking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1581"},"sequenceIndex":2042},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1582","text":"They will begin by taking the State and the manners of men, from which,\r as from a tablet, they will rub out the picture, and leave a clean\r surface. This is no easy task. But whether easy or not, herein will lie\r the difference between them and every other legislator,—they will have\r nothing to do either with individual or State, and will inscribe no\r laws, until they have either found, or themselves made, a clean\r surface.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1582"},"sequenceIndex":2043},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1583","text":"Having effected this, they will proceed to trace an outline of the\r constitution?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1583"},"sequenceIndex":2044},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1584","text":"And when they are filling in the work, as I conceive, they will often\r turn their eyes upwards and downwards: I mean that they will first look\r at absolute justice and beauty and temperance, and again at the human\r copy; and will mingle and temper the various elements of life into the\r image of a man; and this they will conceive according to that other\r image, which, when existing among men, Homer calls the form and\r likeness of God.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1584"},"sequenceIndex":2045},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1585","text":"And one feature they will erase, and another they will put in, until\r they have made the ways of men, as far as possible, agreeable to the\r ways of God?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1585"},"sequenceIndex":2046},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1586","text":"And now, I said, are we beginning to persuade those whom you described\r as rushing at us with might and main, that the painter of constitutions\r is such an one as we are praising; at whom they were so very indignant\r because to his hands we committed the State; and are they growing a\r little calmer at what they have just heard?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1586"},"sequenceIndex":2047},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1587","text":"Why, where can they still find any ground for objection? Will they\r doubt that the philosopher is a lover of truth and being?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1587"},"sequenceIndex":2048},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1588","text":"Or that his nature, being such as we have delineated, is akin to the\r highest good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1588"},"sequenceIndex":2049},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1589","text":"But again, will they tell us that such a nature, placed under\r favourable circumstances, will not be perfectly good and wise if any\r ever was? Or will they prefer those whom we have rejected?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1589"},"sequenceIndex":2050},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1590","text":"Then will they still be angry at our saying, that, until philosophers\r bear rule, States and individuals will have no rest from evil, nor will\r this our imaginary State ever be realized?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1590"},"sequenceIndex":2051},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1591","text":"Shall we assume that they are not only less angry but quite gentle, and\r that they have been converted and for very shame, if for no other\r reason, cannot refuse to come to terms?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1591"},"sequenceIndex":2052},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1592","text":"Then let us suppose that the reconciliation has been effected. Will any\r one deny the other point, that there may be sons of kings or princes\r who are by nature philosophers?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1592"},"sequenceIndex":2053},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1593","text":"And when they have come into being will any one say that they must of\r necessity be destroyed; that they can hardly be saved is not denied\r even by us; but that in the whole course of ages no single one of them\r can escape—who will venture to affirm this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1593"},"sequenceIndex":2054},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1594","text":"But, said I, one is enough; let there be one man who has a city\r obedient to his will, and he might bring into existence the ideal\r polity about which the world is so incredulous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1594"},"sequenceIndex":2055},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1595","text":"The ruler may impose the laws and institutions which we have been\r describing, and the citizens may possibly be willing to obey them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1595"},"sequenceIndex":2056},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1596","text":"And that others should approve, of what we approve, is no miracle or\r impossibility?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1596"},"sequenceIndex":2057},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1597","text":"But we have sufficiently shown, in what has preceded, that all this, if\r only possible, is assuredly for the best.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1597"},"sequenceIndex":2058},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1598","text":"And now we say not only that our laws, if they could be enacted, would\r be for the best, but also that the enactment of them, though difficult,\r is not impossible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1598"},"sequenceIndex":2059},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1599","text":"And so with pain and toil we have reached the end of one subject, but\r more remains to be discussed;—how and by what studies and pursuits will\r the saviours of the constitution be created, and at what ages are they\r to apply themselves to their several studies?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1599"},"sequenceIndex":2060},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1600","text":"I omitted the troublesome business of the possession of women, and the\r procreation of children, and the appointment of the rulers, because I\r knew that the perfect State would be eyed with jealousy and was\r difficult of attainment; but that piece of cleverness was not of much\r service to me, for I had to discuss them all the same. The women and\r children are now disposed of, but the other question of the rulers must\r be investigated from the very beginning. We were saying, as you will\r remember, that they were to be lovers of their country, tried by the\r test of pleasures and pains, and neith","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1600"},"sequenceIndex":2061},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1601","text":"Yes, my friend, I said, and I then shrank from hazarding the bold word;\r but now let me dare to say—that the perfect guardian must be a\r philosopher.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1601"},"sequenceIndex":2062},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1602","text":"And do not suppose that there will be many of them; for the gifts which\r were deemed by us to be essential rarely grow together; they are mostly\r found in shreds and patches.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1602"},"sequenceIndex":2063},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1603","text":"You are aware, I replied, that quick intelligence, memory, sagacity,\r cleverness, and similar qualities, do not often grow together, and that\r persons who possess them and are at the same time high-spirited and\r magnanimous are not so constituted by nature as to live orderly and in\r a peaceful and settled manner; they are driven any way by their\r impulses, and all solid principle goes out of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1603"},"sequenceIndex":2064},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1604","text":"On the other hand, those steadfast natures which can better be depended\r upon, which in a battle are impregnable to fear and immovable, are\r equally immovable when there is anything to be learned; they are always\r in a torpid state, and are apt to yawn and go to sleep over any\r intellectual toil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1604"},"sequenceIndex":2065},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1605","text":"And yet we were saying that both qualities were necessary in those to\r whom the higher education is to be imparted, and who are to share in\r any office or command.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1605"},"sequenceIndex":2066},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1606","text":"Then the aspirant must not only be tested in those labours and dangers\r and pleasures which we mentioned before, but there is another kind of\r probation which we did not mention—he must be exercised also in many\r kinds of knowledge, to see whether the soul will be able to endure the\r highest of all, or will faint under them, as in any other studies and\r exercises.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1606"},"sequenceIndex":2067},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1607","text":"Yes, he said, you are quite right in testing him. But what do you mean\r by the highest of all knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1607"},"sequenceIndex":2068},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1608","text":"You may remember, I said, that we divided the soul into three parts;\r and distinguished the several natures of justice, temperance, courage,\r and wisdom?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1608"},"sequenceIndex":2069},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1609","text":"We were saying, if I am not mistaken, that he who wanted to see them in\r their perfect beauty must take a longer and more circuitous way, at the\r end of which they would appear; but that we could add on a popular\r exposition of them on a level with the discussion which had preceded.\r And you replied that such an exposition would be enough for you, and so\r the enquiry was continued in what to me seemed to be a very inaccurate\r manner; whether you were satisfied or not, it is for you to say.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1609"},"sequenceIndex":2070},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1610","text":"Yes, he said, I thought and the others thought that you gave us a fair\r measure of truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1610"},"sequenceIndex":2071},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1611","text":"But, my friend, I said, a measure of such things which in any degree\r falls short of the whole truth is not fair measure; for nothing\r imperfect is the measure of anything, although persons are too apt to\r be contented and think that they need search no further.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1611"},"sequenceIndex":2072},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1612","text":"Yes, I said; and there cannot be any worse fault in a guardian of the\r State and of the laws.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1612"},"sequenceIndex":2073},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1613","text":"The guardian then, I said, must be required to take the longer circuit,\r and toil at learning as well as at gymnastics, or he will never reach\r the highest knowledge of all which, as we were just now saying, is his\r proper calling.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1613"},"sequenceIndex":2074},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1614","text":"What, he said, is there a knowledge still higher than this—higher than\r justice and the other virtues?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1614"},"sequenceIndex":2075},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1615","text":"Yes, I said, there is. And of the virtues too we must behold not the\r outline merely, as at present—nothing short of the most finished\r picture should satisfy us. When little things are elaborated with an\r infinity of pains, in order that they may appear in their full beauty\r and utmost clearness, how ridiculous that we should not think the\r highest truths worthy of attaining the highest accuracy!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1615"},"sequenceIndex":2076},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1616","text":"A right noble thought; but do you suppose that we shall refrain from\r asking you what is this highest knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1616"},"sequenceIndex":2077},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1617","text":"Nay, I said, ask if you will; but I am certain that you have heard the\r answer many times, and now you either do not understand me or, as I\r rather think, you are disposed to be troublesome; for you have often\r been told that the idea of good is the highest knowledge, and that all\r other things become useful and advantageous only by their use of this.\r You can hardly be ignorant that of this I was about to speak,\r concerning which, as you have often heard me say, we know so little;\r and, without which, any other knowledge or possession of any kind will\r profit us nothing. Do you think that the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1617"},"sequenceIndex":2078},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1618","text":"You are further aware that most people affirm pleasure to be the good,\r but the finer sort of wits say it is knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1618"},"sequenceIndex":2079},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1619","text":"And you are aware too that the latter cannot explain what they mean by\r knowledge, but are obliged after all to say knowledge of the good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1619"},"sequenceIndex":2080},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1620","text":"Yes, I said, that they should begin by reproaching us with our\r ignorance of the good, and then presume our knowledge of it—for the\r good they define to be knowledge of the good, just as if we understood\r them when they use the term ‘good’—this is of course ridiculous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1620"},"sequenceIndex":2081},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1621","text":"And those who make pleasure their good are in equal perplexity; for\r they are compelled to admit that there are bad pleasures as well as\r good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1621"},"sequenceIndex":2082},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1622","text":"There can be no doubt about the numerous difficulties in which this\r question is involved.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1622"},"sequenceIndex":2083},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1623","text":"Further, do we not see that many are willing to do or to have or to\r seem to be what is just and honourable without the reality; but no one\r is satisfied with the appearance of good—the reality is what they seek;\r in the case of the good, appearance is despised by every one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1623"},"sequenceIndex":2084},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1624","text":"Of this then, which every soul of man pursues and makes the end of all\r his actions, having a presentiment that there is such an end, and yet\r hesitating because neither knowing the nature nor having the same\r assurance of this as of other things, and therefore losing whatever\r good there is in other things,—of a principle such and so great as this\r ought the best men in our State, to whom everything is entrusted, to be\r in the darkness of ignorance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1624"},"sequenceIndex":2085},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1625","text":"I am sure, I said, that he who does not know how the beautiful and the\r just are likewise good will be but a sorry guardian of them; and I\r suspect that no one who is ignorant of the good will have a true\r knowledge of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1625"},"sequenceIndex":2086},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1626","text":"And if we only have a guardian who has this knowledge our State will be\r perfectly ordered?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1626"},"sequenceIndex":2087},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1627","text":"Of course, he replied; but I wish that you would tell me whether you\r conceive this supreme principle of the good to be knowledge or\r pleasure, or different from either?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1627"},"sequenceIndex":2088},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1628","text":"Aye, I said, I knew all along that a fastidious gentleman like you\r would not be contented with the thoughts of other people about these\r matters.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1628"},"sequenceIndex":2089},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1629","text":"True, Socrates; but I must say that one who like you has passed a\r lifetime in the study of philosophy should not be always repeating the\r opinions of others, and never telling his own.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1629"},"sequenceIndex":2090},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1630","text":"Not, he said, with the assurance of positive certainty; he has no right\r to do that: but he may say what he thinks, as a matter of opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1630"},"sequenceIndex":2091},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1631","text":"And do you not know, I said, that all mere opinions are bad, and the\r best of them blind? You would not deny that those who have any true\r notion without intelligence are only like blind men who feel their way\r along the road?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1631"},"sequenceIndex":2092},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1632","text":"And do you wish to behold what is blind and crooked and base, when\r others will tell you of brightness and beauty?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1632"},"sequenceIndex":2093},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1633","text":"Still, I must implore you, Socrates, said Glaucon, not to turn away\r just as you are reaching the goal; if you will only give such an\r explanation of the good as you have already given of justice and\r temperance and the other virtues, we shall be satisfied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1633"},"sequenceIndex":2094},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1634","text":"Yes, my friend, and I shall be at least equally satisfied, but I cannot\r help fearing that I shall fail, and that my indiscreet zeal will bring\r ridicule upon me. No, sweet sirs, let us not at present ask what is the\r actual nature of the good, for to reach what is now in my thoughts\r would be an effort too great for me. But of the child of the good who\r is likest him, I would fain speak, if I could be sure that you wished\r to hear—otherwise, not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1634"},"sequenceIndex":2095},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1635","text":"By all means, he said, tell us about the child, and you shall remain in\r our debt for the account of the parent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1635"},"sequenceIndex":2096},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1636","text":"I do indeed wish, I replied, that I could pay, and you receive, the\r account of the parent, and not, as now, of the offspring only; take,\r however, this latter by way of interest, and at the same time have a\r care that I do not render a false account, although I have no intention\r of deceiving you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1636"},"sequenceIndex":2097},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1637","text":"Yes, I said, but I must first come to an understanding with you, and\r remind you of what I have mentioned in the course of this discussion,\r and at many other times.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1637"},"sequenceIndex":2098},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1638","text":"The old story, that there is a many beautiful and a many good, and so\r of other things which we describe and define; to all of them the term\r ‘many’ is applied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1638"},"sequenceIndex":2099},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1639","text":"And there is an absolute beauty and an absolute good, and of other\r things to which the term ‘many’ is applied there is an absolute; for\r they may be brought under a single idea, which is called the essence of\r each.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1639"},"sequenceIndex":2100},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1640","text":"The many, as we say, are seen but not known, and the ideas are known\r but not seen.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1640"},"sequenceIndex":2101},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1641","text":"And with the hearing, I said, we hear, and with the other senses\r perceive the other objects of sense?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1641"},"sequenceIndex":2102},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1642","text":"But have you remarked that sight is by far the most costly and complex\r piece of workmanship which the artificer of the senses ever contrived?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1642"},"sequenceIndex":2103},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1643","text":"Then reflect; has the ear or voice need of any third or additional\r nature in order that the one may be able to hear and the other to be\r heard?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1643"},"sequenceIndex":2104},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1644","text":"No, indeed, I replied; and the same is true of most, if not all, the\r other senses—you would not say that any of them requires such an\r addition?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1644"},"sequenceIndex":2105},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1645","text":"But you see that without the addition of some other nature there is no\r seeing or being seen?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1645"},"sequenceIndex":2106},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1646","text":"Sight being, as I conceive, in the eyes, and he who has eyes wanting to\r see; colour being also present in them, still unless there be a third\r nature specially adapted to the purpose, the owner of the eyes will see\r nothing and the colours will be invisible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1646"},"sequenceIndex":2107},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1647","text":"Noble, then, is the bond which links together sight and visibility, and\r great beyond other bonds by no small difference of nature; for light is\r their bond, and light is no ignoble thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1647"},"sequenceIndex":2108},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1648","text":"And which, I said, of the gods in heaven would you say was the lord of\r this element? Whose is that light which makes the eye to see perfectly\r and the visible to appear?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1648"},"sequenceIndex":2109},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1649","text":"And the power which the eye possesses is a sort of effluence which is\r dispensed from the sun?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1649"},"sequenceIndex":2110},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1650","text":"And this is he whom I call the child of the good, whom the good begat\r in his own likeness, to be in the visible world, in relation to sight\r and the things of sight, what the good is in the intellectual world in\r relation to mind and the things of mind:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1650"},"sequenceIndex":2111},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1651","text":"Why, you know, I said, that the eyes, when a person directs them\r towards objects on which the light of day is no longer shining, but the\r moon and stars only, see dimly, and are nearly blind; they seem to have\r no clearness of vision in them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1651"},"sequenceIndex":2112},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1652","text":"But when they are directed towards objects on which the sun shines,\r they see clearly and there is sight in them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1652"},"sequenceIndex":2113},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1653","text":"And the soul is like the eye: when resting upon that on which truth and\r being shine, the soul perceives and understands, and is radiant with\r intelligence; but when turned towards the twilight of becoming and\r perishing, then she has opinion only, and goes blinking about, and is\r first of one opinion and then of another, and seems to have no\r intelligence?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1653"},"sequenceIndex":2114},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1654","text":"Now, that which imparts truth to the known and the power of knowing to\r the knower is what I would have you term the idea of good, and this you\r will deem to be the cause of science, and of truth in so far as the\r latter becomes the subject of knowledge; beautiful too, as are both\r truth and knowledge, you will be right in esteeming this other nature\r as more beautiful than either; and, as in the previous instance, light\r and sight may be truly said to be like the sun, and yet not to be the\r sun, so in this other sphere, science and truth may be deemed to be\r like the good, but not the good; t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1654"},"sequenceIndex":2115},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1655","text":"What a wonder of beauty that must be, he said, which is the author of\r science and truth, and yet surpasses them in beauty; for you surely\r cannot mean to say that pleasure is the good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1655"},"sequenceIndex":2116},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1656","text":"God forbid, I replied; but may I ask you to consider the image in\r another point of view?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1656"},"sequenceIndex":2117},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1657","text":"You would say, would you not, that the sun is not only the author of\r visibility in all visible things, but of generation and nourishment and\r growth, though he himself is not generation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1657"},"sequenceIndex":2118},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1658","text":"In like manner the good may be said to be not only the author of\r knowledge to all things known, but of their being and essence, and yet\r the good is not essence, but far exceeds essence in dignity and power.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1658"},"sequenceIndex":2119},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1659","text":"Glaucon said, with a ludicrous earnestness: By the light of heaven, how\r amazing!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1659"},"sequenceIndex":2120},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1660","text":"Yes, I said, and the exaggeration may be set down to you; for you made\r me utter my fancies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1660"},"sequenceIndex":2121},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1661","text":"And pray continue to utter them; at any rate let us hear if there is\r anything more to be said about the similitude of the sun.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1661"},"sequenceIndex":2122},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1662","text":"I will do my best, I said; but I should think that a great deal will\r have to be omitted.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1662"},"sequenceIndex":2123},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1663","text":"You have to imagine, then, that there are two ruling powers, and that\r one of them is set over the intellectual world, the other over the\r visible. I do not say heaven, lest you should fancy that I am playing\r upon the name (‘ourhanoz, orhatoz’). May I suppose that you have this\r distinction of the visible and intelligible fixed in your mind?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1663"},"sequenceIndex":2124},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1664","text":"Now take a line which has been cut into two unequal parts, and divide\r each of them again in the same proportion, and suppose the two main\r divisions to answer, one to the visible and the other to the\r intelligible, and then compare the subdivisions in respect of their\r clearness and want of clearness, and you will find that the first\r section in the sphere of the visible consists of images. And by images\r I mean, in the first place, shadows, and in the second place,\r reflections in water and in solid, smooth and polished bodies and the\r like: Do you understand?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1664"},"sequenceIndex":2125},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1665","text":"Imagine, now, the other section, of which this is only the resemblance,\r to include the animals which we see, and everything that grows or is\r made.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1665"},"sequenceIndex":2126},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1666","text":"Would you not admit that both the sections of this division have\r different degrees of truth, and that the copy is to the original as the\r sphere of opinion is to the sphere of knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1666"},"sequenceIndex":2127},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1667","text":"Next proceed to consider the manner in which the sphere of the\r intellectual is to be divided.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1667"},"sequenceIndex":2128},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1668","text":"Thus:—There are two subdivisions, in the lower of which the soul uses\r the figures given by the former division as images; the enquiry can\r only be hypothetical, and instead of going upwards to a principle\r descends to the other end; in the higher of the two, the soul passes\r out of hypotheses, and goes up to a principle which is above\r hypotheses, making no use of images as in the former case, but\r proceeding only in and through the ideas themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1668"},"sequenceIndex":2129},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1669","text":"Then I will try again; you will understand me better when I have made\r some preliminary remarks. You are aware that students of geometry,\r arithmetic, and the kindred sciences assume the odd and the even and\r the figures and three kinds of angles and the like in their several\r branches of science; these are their hypotheses, which they and every\r body are supposed to know, and therefore they do not deign to give any\r account of them either to themselves or others; but they begin with\r them, and go on until they arrive at last, and in a consistent manner,\r at their conclusion?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1669"},"sequenceIndex":2130},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1670","text":"And do you not know also that although they make use of the visible\r forms and reason about them, they are thinking not of these, but of the\r ideals which they resemble; not of the figures which they draw, but of\r the absolute square and the absolute diameter, and so on—the forms\r which they draw or make, and which have shadows and reflections in\r water of their own, are converted by them into images, but they are\r really seeking to behold the things themselves, which can only be seen\r with the eye of the mind?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1670"},"sequenceIndex":2131},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1671","text":"And of this kind I spoke as the intelligible, although in the search\r after it the soul is compelled to use hypotheses; not ascending to a\r first principle, because she is unable to rise above the region of\r hypothesis, but employing the objects of which the shadows below are\r resemblances in their turn as images, they having in relation to the\r shadows and reflections of them a greater distinctness, and therefore a\r higher value.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1671"},"sequenceIndex":2132},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1672","text":"I understand, he said, that you are speaking of the province of\r geometry and the sister arts.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1672"},"sequenceIndex":2133},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1673","text":"And when I speak of the other division of the intelligible, you will\r understand me to speak of that other sort of knowledge which reason\r herself attains by the power of dialectic, using the hypotheses not as\r first principles, but only as hypotheses—that is to say, as steps and\r points of departure into a world which is above hypotheses, in order\r that she may soar beyond them to the first principle of the whole; and\r clinging to this and then to that which depends on this, by successive\r steps she descends again without the aid of any sensible object, from\r ideas, through ideas, and in idea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1673"},"sequenceIndex":2134},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1674","text":"I understand you, he replied; not perfectly, for you seem to me to be\r describing a task which is really tremendous; but, at any rate, I\r understand you to say that knowledge and being, which the science of\r dialectic contemplates, are clearer than the notions of the arts, as\r they are termed, which proceed from hypotheses only: these are also\r contemplated by the understanding, and not by the senses: yet, because\r they start from hypotheses and do not ascend to a principle, those who\r contemplate them appear to you not to exercise the higher reason upon\r them, although when a first principle ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1674"},"sequenceIndex":2135},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1675","text":"You have quite conceived my meaning, I said; and now, corresponding to\r these four divisions, let there be four faculties in the soul—reason\r answering to the highest, understanding to the second, faith (or\r conviction) to the third, and perception of shadows to the last—and let\r there be a scale of them, and let us suppose that the several faculties\r have clearness in the same degree that their objects have truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1675"},"sequenceIndex":2136},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1676","text":"And now, I said, let me show in a figure how far our nature is\r enlightened or unenlightened:—Behold! human beings living in a\r underground den, which has a mouth open towards the light and reaching\r all along the den; here they have been from their childhood, and have\r their legs and necks chained so that they cannot move, and can only see\r before them, being prevented by the chains from turning round their\r heads. Above and behind them a fire is blazing at a distance, and\r between the fire and the prisoners there is a raised way; and you will\r see, if you look, a low wall built along the way","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1676"},"sequenceIndex":2137},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1677","text":"And do you see, I said, men passing along the wall carrying all sorts\r of vessels, and statues and figures of animals made of wood and stone\r and various materials, which appear over the wall? Some of them are\r talking, others silent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1677"},"sequenceIndex":2138},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1678","text":"Like ourselves, I replied; and they see only their own shadows, or the\r shadows of one another, which the fire throws on the opposite wall of\r the cave?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1678"},"sequenceIndex":2139},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1679","text":"True, he said; how could they see anything but the shadows if they were\r never allowed to move their heads?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1679"},"sequenceIndex":2140},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1680","text":"And of the objects which are being carried in like manner they would\r only see the shadows?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1680"},"sequenceIndex":2141},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1681","text":"And if they were able to converse with one another, would they not\r suppose that they were naming what was actually before them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1681"},"sequenceIndex":2142},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1682","text":"And suppose further that the prison had an echo which came from the\r other side, would they not be sure to fancy when one of the passers-by\r spoke that the voice which they heard came from the passing shadow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1682"},"sequenceIndex":2143},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1683","text":"To them, I said, the truth would be literally nothing but the shadows\r of the images.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1683"},"sequenceIndex":2144},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1684","text":"And now look again, and see what will naturally follow if the prisoners\r are released and disabused of their error. At first, when any of them\r is liberated and compelled suddenly to stand up and turn his neck round\r and walk and look towards the light, he will suffer sharp pains; the\r glare will distress him, and he will be unable to see the realities of\r which in his former state he had seen the shadows; and then conceive\r some one saying to him, that what he saw before was an illusion, but\r that now, when he is approaching nearer to being and his eye is turned\r towards more real existence, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1684"},"sequenceIndex":2145},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1685","text":"And if he is compelled to look straight at the light, will he not have\r a pain in his eyes which will make him turn away to take refuge in the\r objects of vision which he can see, and which he will conceive to be in\r reality clearer than the things which are now being shown to him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1685"},"sequenceIndex":2146},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1686","text":"And suppose once more, that he is reluctantly dragged up a steep and\r rugged ascent, and held fast until he is forced into the presence of\r the sun himself, is he not likely to be pained and irritated? When he\r approaches the light his eyes will be dazzled, and he will not be able\r to see anything at all of what are now called realities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1686"},"sequenceIndex":2147},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1687","text":"He will require to grow accustomed to the sight of the upper world. And\r first he will see the shadows best, next the reflections of men and\r other objects in the water, and then the objects themselves; then he\r will gaze upon the light of the moon and the stars and the spangled\r heaven; and he will see the sky and the stars by night better than the\r sun or the light of the sun by day?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1687"},"sequenceIndex":2148},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1688","text":"Last of all he will be able to see the sun, and not mere reflections of\r him in the water, but he will see him in his own proper place, and not\r in another; and he will contemplate him as he is.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1688"},"sequenceIndex":2149},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1689","text":"He will then proceed to argue that this is he who gives the season and\r the years, and is the guardian of all that is in the visible world, and\r in a certain way the cause of all things which he and his fellows have\r been accustomed to behold?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1689"},"sequenceIndex":2150},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1690","text":"And when he remembered his old habitation, and the wisdom of the den\r and his fellow-prisoners, do you not suppose that he would felicitate\r himself on the change, and pity them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1690"},"sequenceIndex":2151},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1691","text":"And if they were in the habit of conferring honours among themselves on\r those who were quickest to observe the passing shadows and to remark\r which of them went before, and which followed after, and which were\r together; and who were therefore best able to draw conclusions as to\r the future, do you think that he would care for such honours and\r glories, or envy the possessors of them? Would he not say with Homer,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1691"},"sequenceIndex":2152},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1692","text":"and to endure anything, rather than think as they do and live after\r their manner?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1692"},"sequenceIndex":2153},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1693","text":"Yes, he said, I think that he would rather suffer anything than\r entertain these false notions and live in this miserable manner.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1693"},"sequenceIndex":2154},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1694","text":"Imagine once more, I said, such an one coming suddenly out of the sun\r to be replaced in his old situation; would he not be certain to have\r his eyes full of darkness?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1694"},"sequenceIndex":2155},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1695","text":"And if there were a contest, and he had to compete in measuring the\r shadows with the prisoners who had never moved out of the den, while\r his sight was still weak, and before his eyes had become steady (and\r the time which would be needed to acquire this new habit of sight might\r be very considerable), would he not be ridiculous? Men would say of him\r that up he went and down he came without his eyes; and that it was\r better not even to think of ascending; and if any one tried to loose\r another and lead him up to the light, let them only catch the offender,\r and they would put him to death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1695"},"sequenceIndex":2156},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1696","text":"This entire allegory, I said, you may now append, dear Glaucon, to the\r previous argument; the prison-house is the world of sight, the light of\r the fire is the sun, and you will not misapprehend me if you interpret\r the journey upwards to be the ascent of the soul into the intellectual\r world according to my poor belief, which, at your desire, I have\r expressed—whether rightly or wrongly God knows. But, whether true or\r false, my opinion is that in the world of knowledge the idea of good\r appears last of all, and is seen only with an effort; and, when seen,\r is also inferred to be the univers","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1696"},"sequenceIndex":2157},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1697","text":"Moreover, I said, you must not wonder that those who attain to this\r beatific vision are unwilling to descend to human affairs; for their\r souls are ever hastening into the upper world where they desire to\r dwell; which desire of theirs is very natural, if our allegory may be\r trusted.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1697"},"sequenceIndex":2158},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1698","text":"And is there anything surprising in one who passes from divine\r contemplations to the evil state of man, misbehaving himself in a\r ridiculous manner; if, while his eyes are blinking and before he has\r become accustomed to the surrounding darkness, he is compelled to fight\r in courts of law, or in other places, about the images or the shadows\r of images of justice, and is endeavouring to meet the conceptions of\r those who have never yet seen absolute justice?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1698"},"sequenceIndex":2159},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1699","text":"Any one who has common sense will remember that the bewilderments of\r the eyes are of two kinds, and arise from two causes, either from\r coming out of the light or from going into the light, which is true of\r the mind’s eye, quite as much as of the bodily eye; and he who\r remembers this when he sees any one whose vision is perplexed and weak,\r will not be too ready to laugh; he will first ask whether that soul of\r man has come out of the brighter life, and is unable to see because\r unaccustomed to the dark, or having turned from darkness to the day is\r dazzled by excess of light. And he will c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1699"},"sequenceIndex":2160},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1700","text":"But then, if I am right, certain professors of education must be wrong\r when they say that they can put a knowledge into the soul which was not\r there before, like sight into blind eyes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1700"},"sequenceIndex":2161},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1701","text":"Whereas, our argument shows that the power and capacity of learning\r exists in the soul already; and that just as the eye was unable to turn\r from darkness to light without the whole body, so too the instrument of\r knowledge can only by the movement of the whole soul be turned from the\r world of becoming into that of being, and learn by degrees to endure\r the sight of being, and of the brightest and best of being, or in other\r words, of the good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1701"},"sequenceIndex":2162},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1702","text":"And must there not be some art which will effect conversion in the\r easiest and quickest manner; not implanting the faculty of sight, for\r that exists already, but has been turned in the wrong direction, and is\r looking away from the truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1702"},"sequenceIndex":2163},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1703","text":"And whereas the other so-called virtues of the soul seem to be akin to\r bodily qualities, for even when they are not originally innate they can\r be implanted later by habit and exercise, the virtue of wisdom more\r than anything else contains a divine element which always remains, and\r by this conversion is rendered useful and profitable; or, on the other\r hand, hurtful and useless. Did you never observe the narrow\r intelligence flashing from the keen eye of a clever rogue—how eager he\r is, how clearly his paltry soul sees the way to his end; he is the\r reverse of blind, but his keen eye-sight ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1703"},"sequenceIndex":2164},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1704","text":"But what if there had been a circumcision of such natures in the days\r of their youth; and they had been severed from those sensual pleasures,\r such as eating and drinking, which, like leaden weights, were attached\r to them at their birth, and which drag them down and turn the vision of\r their souls upon the things that are below—if, I say, they had been\r released from these impediments and turned in the opposite direction,\r the very same faculty in them would have seen the truth as keenly as\r they see what their eyes are turned to now.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1704"},"sequenceIndex":2165},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1705","text":"Yes, I said; and there is another thing which is likely, or rather a\r necessary inference from what has preceded, that neither the uneducated\r and uninformed of the truth, nor yet those who never make an end of\r their education, will be able ministers of State; not the former,\r because they have no single aim of duty which is the rule of all their\r actions, private as well as public; nor the latter, because they will\r not act at all except upon compulsion, fancying that they are already\r dwelling apart in the islands of the blest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1705"},"sequenceIndex":2166},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1706","text":"Then, I said, the business of us who are the founders of the State will\r be to compel the best minds to attain that knowledge which we have\r already shown to be the greatest of all—they must continue to ascend\r until they arrive at the good; but when they have ascended and seen\r enough we must not allow them to do as they do now.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1706"},"sequenceIndex":2167},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1707","text":"I mean that they remain in the upper world: but this must not be\r allowed; they must be made to descend again among the prisoners in the\r den, and partake of their labours and honours, whether they are worth\r having or not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1707"},"sequenceIndex":2168},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1708","text":"But is not this unjust? he said; ought we to give them a worse life,\r when they might have a better?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1708"},"sequenceIndex":2169},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1709","text":"You have again forgotten, my friend, I said, the intention of the\r legislator, who did not aim at making any one class in the State happy\r above the rest; the happiness was to be in the whole State, and he held\r the citizens together by persuasion and necessity, making them\r benefactors of the State, and therefore benefactors of one another; to\r this end he created them, not to please themselves, but to be his\r instruments in binding up the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1709"},"sequenceIndex":2170},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1710","text":"Observe, Glaucon, that there will be no injustice in compelling our\r philosophers to have a care and providence of others; we shall explain\r to them that in other States, men of their class are not obliged to\r share in the toils of politics: and this is reasonable, for they grow\r up at their own sweet will, and the government would rather not have\r them. Being self-taught, they cannot be expected to show any gratitude\r for a culture which they have never received. But we have brought you\r into the world to be rulers of the hive, kings of yourselves and of the\r other citizens, and have educated","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1710"},"sequenceIndex":2171},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1711","text":"And will our pupils, when they hear this, refuse to take their turn at\r the toils of State, when they are allowed to spend the greater part of\r their time with one another in the heavenly light?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1711"},"sequenceIndex":2172},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1712","text":"Impossible, he answered; for they are just men, and the commands which\r we impose upon them are just; there can be no doubt that every one of\r them will take office as a stern necessity, and not after the fashion\r of our present rulers of State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1712"},"sequenceIndex":2173},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1713","text":"Yes, my friend, I said; and there lies the point. You must contrive for\r your future rulers another and a better life than that of a ruler, and\r then you may have a well-ordered State; for only in the State which\r offers this, will they rule who are truly rich, not in silver and gold,\r but in virtue and wisdom, which are the true blessings of life. Whereas\r if they go to the administration of public affairs, poor and hungering\r after their own private advantage, thinking that hence they are to\r snatch the chief good, order there can never be; for they will be\r fighting about office, and the ci","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1713"},"sequenceIndex":2174},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1714","text":"And the only life which looks down upon the life of political ambition\r is that of true philosophy. Do you know of any other?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1714"},"sequenceIndex":2175},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1715","text":"And those who govern ought not to be lovers of the task? For, if they\r are, there will be rival lovers, and they will fight.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1715"},"sequenceIndex":2176},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1716","text":"Who then are those whom we shall compel to be guardians? Surely they\r will be the men who are wisest about affairs of State, and by whom the\r State is best administered, and who at the same time have other honours\r and another and a better life than that of politics?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1716"},"sequenceIndex":2177},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1717","text":"And now shall we consider in what way such guardians will be produced,\r and how they are to be brought from darkness to light,—as some are said\r to have ascended from the world below to the gods?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1717"},"sequenceIndex":2178},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1718","text":"The process, I said, is not the turning over of an oyster-shell (In\r allusion to a game in which two parties fled or pursued according as an\r oyster-shell which was thrown into the air fell with the dark or light\r side uppermost.), but the turning round of a soul passing from a day\r which is little better than night to the true day of being, that is,\r the ascent from below, which we affirm to be true philosophy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1718"},"sequenceIndex":2179},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1719","text":"And should we not enquire what sort of knowledge has the power of\r effecting such a change?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1719"},"sequenceIndex":2180},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1720","text":"What sort of knowledge is there which would draw the soul from becoming\r to being? And another consideration has just occurred to me: You will\r remember that our young men are to be warrior athletes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1720"},"sequenceIndex":2181},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1721","text":"There was gymnastic which presided over the growth and decay of the\r body, and may therefore be regarded as having to do with generation and\r corruption?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1721"},"sequenceIndex":2182},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1722","text":"But what do you say of music, which also entered to a certain extent\r into our former scheme?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1722"},"sequenceIndex":2183},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1723","text":"Music, he said, as you will remember, was the counterpart of gymnastic,\r and trained the guardians by the influences of habit, by harmony making\r them harmonious, by rhythm rhythmical, but not giving them science; and\r the words, whether fabulous or possibly true, had kindred elements of\r rhythm and harmony in them. But in music there was nothing which tended\r to that good which you are now seeking.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1723"},"sequenceIndex":2184},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1724","text":"You are most accurate, I said, in your recollection; in music there\r certainly was nothing of the kind. But what branch of knowledge is\r there, my dear Glaucon, which is of the desired nature; since all the\r useful arts were reckoned mean by us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1724"},"sequenceIndex":2185},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1725","text":"Undoubtedly; and yet if music and gymnastic are excluded, and the arts\r are also excluded, what remains?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1725"},"sequenceIndex":2186},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1726","text":"Well, I said, there may be nothing left of our special subjects; and\r then we shall have to take something which is not special, but of\r universal application.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1726"},"sequenceIndex":2187},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1727","text":"A something which all arts and sciences and intelligences use in\r common, and which every one first has to learn among the elements of\r education.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1727"},"sequenceIndex":2188},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1728","text":"The little matter of distinguishing one, two, and three—in a word,\r number and calculation:—do not all arts and sciences necessarily\r partake of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1728"},"sequenceIndex":2189},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1729","text":"Then Palamedes, whenever he appears in tragedy, proves Agamemnon\r ridiculously unfit to be a general. Did you never remark how he\r declares that he had invented number, and had numbered the ships and\r set in array the ranks of the army at Troy; which implies that they had\r never been numbered before, and Agamemnon must be supposed literally to\r have been incapable of counting his own feet—how could he if he was\r ignorant of number? And if that is true, what sort of general must he\r have been?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1729"},"sequenceIndex":2190},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1730","text":"Certainly he should, if he is to have the smallest understanding of\r military tactics, or indeed, I should rather say, if he is to be a man\r at all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1730"},"sequenceIndex":2191},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1731","text":"I should like to know whether you have the same notion which I have of\r this study?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1731"},"sequenceIndex":2192},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1732","text":"It appears to me to be a study of the kind which we are seeking, and\r which leads naturally to reflection, but never to have been rightly\r used; for the true use of it is simply to draw the soul towards being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1732"},"sequenceIndex":2193},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1733","text":"I will try, I said; and I wish you would share the enquiry with me, and\r say ‘yes’ or ‘no’ when I attempt to distinguish in my own mind what\r branches of knowledge have this attracting power, in order that we may\r have clearer proof that arithmetic is, as I suspect, one of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1733"},"sequenceIndex":2194},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1734","text":"I mean to say that objects of sense are of two kinds; some of them do\r not invite thought because the sense is an adequate judge of them;\r while in the case of other objects sense is so untrustworthy that\r further enquiry is imperatively demanded.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1734"},"sequenceIndex":2195},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1735","text":"You are clearly referring, he said, to the manner in which the senses\r are imposed upon by distance, and by painting in light and shade.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1735"},"sequenceIndex":2196},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1736","text":"When speaking of uninviting objects, I mean those which do not pass\r from one sensation to the opposite; inviting objects are those which\r do; in this latter case the sense coming upon the object, whether at a\r distance or near, gives no more vivid idea of anything in particular\r than of its opposite. An illustration will make my meaning\r clearer:—here are three fingers—a little finger, a second finger, and a\r middle finger.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1736"},"sequenceIndex":2197},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1737","text":"Each of them equally appears a finger, whether seen in the middle or at\r the extremity, whether white or black, or thick or thin—it makes no\r difference; a finger is a finger all the same. In these cases a man is\r not compelled to ask of thought the question what is a finger? for the\r sight never intimates to the mind that a finger is other than a finger.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1737"},"sequenceIndex":2198},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1738","text":"And therefore, I said, as we might expect, there is nothing here which\r invites or excites intelligence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1738"},"sequenceIndex":2199},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1739","text":"But is this equally true of the greatness and smallness of the fingers?\r Can sight adequately perceive them? and is no difference made by the\r circumstance that one of the fingers is in the middle and another at\r the extremity? And in like manner does the touch adequately perceive\r the qualities of thickness or thinness, of softness or hardness? And so\r of the other senses; do they give perfect intimations of such matters?\r Is not their mode of operation on this wise—the sense which is\r concerned with the quality of hardness is necessarily concerned also\r with the quality of softness, and only","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1739"},"sequenceIndex":2200},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1740","text":"And must not the soul be perplexed at this intimation which the sense\r gives of a hard which is also soft? What, again, is the meaning of\r light and heavy, if that which is light is also heavy, and that which\r is heavy, light?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1740"},"sequenceIndex":2201},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1741","text":"Yes, he said, these intimations which the soul receives are very\r curious and require to be explained.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1741"},"sequenceIndex":2202},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1742","text":"Yes, I said, and in these perplexities the soul naturally summons to\r her aid calculation and intelligence, that she may see whether the\r several objects announced to her are one or two.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1742"},"sequenceIndex":2203},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1743","text":"And if each is one, and both are two, she will conceive the two as in a\r state of division, for if there were undivided they could only be\r conceived of as one?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1743"},"sequenceIndex":2204},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1744","text":"The eye certainly did see both small and great, but only in a confused\r manner; they were not distinguished.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1744"},"sequenceIndex":2205},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1745","text":"Whereas the thinking mind, intending to light up the chaos, was\r compelled to reverse the process, and look at small and great as\r separate and not confused.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1745"},"sequenceIndex":2206},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1746","text":"Was not this the beginning of the enquiry ‘What is great?’ and ‘What is\r small?’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1746"},"sequenceIndex":2207},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1747","text":"This was what I meant when I spoke of impressions which invited the\r intellect, or the reverse—those which are simultaneous with opposite\r impressions, invite thought; those which are not simultaneous do not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1747"},"sequenceIndex":2208},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1748","text":"Think a little and you will see that what has preceded will supply the\r answer; for if simple unity could be adequately perceived by the sight\r or by any other sense, then, as we were saying in the case of the\r finger, there would be nothing to attract towards being; but when there\r is some contradiction always present, and one is the reverse of one and\r involves the conception of plurality, then thought begins to be aroused\r within us, and the soul perplexed and wanting to arrive at a decision\r asks ‘What is absolute unity?’ This is the way in which the study of\r the one has a power of drawin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1748"},"sequenceIndex":2209},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1749","text":"And surely, he said, this occurs notably in the case of one; for we see\r the same thing to be both one and infinite in multitude?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1749"},"sequenceIndex":2210},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1750","text":"Then this is knowledge of the kind for which we are seeking, having a\r double use, military and philosophical; for the man of war must learn\r the art of number or he will not know how to array his troops, and the\r philosopher also, because he has to rise out of the sea of change and\r lay hold of true being, and therefore he must be an arithmetician.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1750"},"sequenceIndex":2211},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1751","text":"Then this is a kind of knowledge which legislation may fitly prescribe;\r and we must endeavour to persuade those who are to be the principal men\r of our State to go and learn arithmetic, not as amateurs, but they must\r carry on the study until they see the nature of numbers with the mind\r only; nor again, like merchants or retail-traders, with a view to\r buying or selling, but for the sake of their military use, and of the\r soul herself; and because this will be the easiest way for her to pass\r from becoming to truth and being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1751"},"sequenceIndex":2212},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1752","text":"Yes, I said, and now having spoken of it, I must add how charming the\r science is! and in how many ways it conduces to our desired end, if\r pursued in the spirit of a philosopher, and not of a shopkeeper!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1752"},"sequenceIndex":2213},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1753","text":"I mean, as I was saying, that arithmetic has a very great and elevating\r effect, compelling the soul to reason about abstract number, and\r rebelling against the introduction of visible or tangible objects into\r the argument. You know how steadily the masters of the art repel and\r ridicule any one who attempts to divide absolute unity when he is\r calculating, and if you divide, they multiply (Meaning either (1) that\r they integrate the number because they deny the possibility of\r fractions; or (2) that division is regarded by them as a process of\r multiplication, for the fractions of one contin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1753"},"sequenceIndex":2214},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1754","text":"Now, suppose a person were to say to them: O my friends, what are these\r wonderful numbers about which you are reasoning, in which, as you say,\r there is a unity such as you demand, and each unit is equal,\r invariable, indivisible,—what would they answer?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1754"},"sequenceIndex":2215},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1755","text":"They would answer, as I should conceive, that they were speaking of\r those numbers which can only be realized in thought.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1755"},"sequenceIndex":2216},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1756","text":"Then you see that this knowledge may be truly called necessary,\r necessitating as it clearly does the use of the pure intelligence in\r the attainment of pure truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1756"},"sequenceIndex":2217},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1757","text":"And have you further observed, that those who have a natural talent for\r calculation are generally quick at every other kind of knowledge; and\r even the dull, if they have had an arithmetical training, although they\r may derive no other advantage from it, always become much quicker than\r they would otherwise have been.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1757"},"sequenceIndex":2218},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1758","text":"And indeed, you will not easily find a more difficult study, and not\r many as difficult.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1758"},"sequenceIndex":2219},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1759","text":"And, for all these reasons, arithmetic is a kind of knowledge in which\r the best natures should be trained, and which must not be given up.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1759"},"sequenceIndex":2220},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1760","text":"Let this then be made one of our subjects of education. And next, shall\r we enquire whether the kindred science also concerns us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1760"},"sequenceIndex":2221},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1761","text":"Clearly, he said, we are concerned with that part of geometry which\r relates to war; for in pitching a camp, or taking up a position, or\r closing or extending the lines of an army, or any other military\r manoeuvre, whether in actual battle or on a march, it will make all the\r difference whether a general is or is not a geometrician.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1761"},"sequenceIndex":2222},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1762","text":"Yes, I said, but for that purpose a very little of either geometry or\r calculation will be enough; the question relates rather to the greater\r and more advanced part of geometry—whether that tends in any degree to\r make more easy the vision of the idea of good; and thither, as I was\r saying, all things tend which compel the soul to turn her gaze towards\r that place, where is the full perfection of being, which she ought, by\r all means, to behold.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1762"},"sequenceIndex":2223},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1763","text":"Then if geometry compels us to view being, it concerns us; if becoming\r only, it does not concern us?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1763"},"sequenceIndex":2224},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1764","text":"Yet anybody who has the least acquaintance with geometry will not deny\r that such a conception of the science is in flat contradiction to the\r ordinary language of geometricians.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1764"},"sequenceIndex":2225},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1765","text":"They have in view practice only, and are always speaking, in a narrow\r and ridiculous manner, of squaring and extending and applying and the\r like—they confuse the necessities of geometry with those of daily life;\r whereas knowledge is the real object of the whole science.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1765"},"sequenceIndex":2226},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1766","text":"That the knowledge at which geometry aims is knowledge of the eternal,\r and not of aught perishing and transient.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1766"},"sequenceIndex":2227},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1767","text":"Then, my noble friend, geometry will draw the soul towards truth, and\r create the spirit of philosophy, and raise up that which is now\r unhappily allowed to fall down.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1767"},"sequenceIndex":2228},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1768","text":"Then nothing should be more sternly laid down than that the inhabitants\r of your fair city should by all means learn geometry. Moreover the\r science has indirect effects, which are not small.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1768"},"sequenceIndex":2229},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1769","text":"There are the military advantages of which you spoke, I said; and in\r all departments of knowledge, as experience proves, any one who has\r studied geometry is infinitely quicker of apprehension than one who has\r not.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1769"},"sequenceIndex":2230},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1770","text":"Then shall we propose this as a second branch of knowledge which our\r youth will study?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1770"},"sequenceIndex":2231},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1771","text":"I am strongly inclined to it, he said; the observation of the seasons\r and of months and years is as essential to the general as it is to the\r farmer or sailor.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1771"},"sequenceIndex":2232},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1772","text":"I am amused, I said, at your fear of the world, which makes you guard\r against the appearance of insisting upon useless studies; and I quite\r admit the difficulty of believing that in every man there is an eye of\r the soul which, when by other pursuits lost and dimmed, is by these\r purified and re-illumined; and is more precious far than ten thousand\r bodily eyes, for by it alone is truth seen. Now there are two classes\r of persons: one class of those who will agree with you and will take\r your words as a revelation; another class to whom they will be utterly\r unmeaning, and who will naturally","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1772"},"sequenceIndex":2233},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1773","text":"Then take a step backward, for we have gone wrong in the order of the\r sciences.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1773"},"sequenceIndex":2234},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1774","text":"After plane geometry, I said, we proceeded at once to solids in\r revolution, instead of taking solids in themselves; whereas after the\r second dimension the third, which is concerned with cubes and\r dimensions of depth, ought to have followed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1774"},"sequenceIndex":2235},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1775","text":"That is true, Socrates; but so little seems to be known as yet about\r these subjects.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1775"},"sequenceIndex":2236},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1776","text":"Why, yes, I said, and for two reasons:—in the first place, no\r government patronises them; this leads to a want of energy in the\r pursuit of them, and they are difficult; in the second place, students\r cannot learn them unless they have a director. But then a director can\r hardly be found, and even if he could, as matters now stand, the\r students, who are very conceited, would not attend to him. That,\r however, would be otherwise if the whole State became the director of\r these studies and gave honour to them; then disciples would want to\r come, and there would be continuous and earnest search","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1776"},"sequenceIndex":2237},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1777","text":"Yes, he said, there is a remarkable charm in them. But I do not clearly\r understand the change in the order. First you began with a geometry of\r plane surfaces?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1777"},"sequenceIndex":2238},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1778","text":"Yes, and I have delayed you by my hurry; the ludicrous state of solid\r geometry, which, in natural order, should have followed, made me pass\r over this branch and go on to astronomy, or motion of solids.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1778"},"sequenceIndex":2239},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1779","text":"Then assuming that the science now omitted would come into existence if\r encouraged by the State, let us go on to astronomy, which will be\r fourth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1779"},"sequenceIndex":2240},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1780","text":"The right order, he replied. And now, Socrates, as you rebuked the\r vulgar manner in which I praised astronomy before, my praise shall be\r given in your own spirit. For every one, as I think, must see that\r astronomy compels the soul to look upwards and leads us from this world\r to another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1780"},"sequenceIndex":2241},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1781","text":"Every one but myself, I said; to every one else this may be clear, but\r not to me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1781"},"sequenceIndex":2242},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1782","text":"I should rather say that those who elevate astronomy into philosophy\r appear to me to make us look downwards and not upwards.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1782"},"sequenceIndex":2243},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1783","text":"You, I replied, have in your mind a truly sublime conception of our\r knowledge of the things above. And I dare say that if a person were to\r throw his head back and study the fretted ceiling, you would still\r think that his mind was the percipient, and not his eyes. And you are\r very likely right, and I may be a simpleton: but, in my opinion, that\r knowledge only which is of being and of the unseen can make the soul\r look upwards, and whether a man gapes at the heavens or blinks on the\r ground, seeking to learn some particular of sense, I would deny that he\r can learn, for nothing of that sort","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1783"},"sequenceIndex":2244},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1784","text":"I acknowledge, he said, the justice of your rebuke. Still, I should\r like to ascertain how astronomy can be learned in any manner more\r conducive to that knowledge of which we are speaking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1784"},"sequenceIndex":2245},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1785","text":"I will tell you, I said: The starry heaven which we behold is wrought\r upon a visible ground, and therefore, although the fairest and most\r perfect of visible things, must necessarily be deemed inferior far to\r the true motions of absolute swiftness and absolute slowness, which are\r relative to each other, and carry with them that which is contained in\r them, in the true number and in every true figure. Now, these are to be\r apprehended by reason and intelligence, but not by sight.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1785"},"sequenceIndex":2246},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1786","text":"The spangled heavens should be used as a pattern and with a view to\r that higher knowledge; their beauty is like the beauty of figures or\r pictures excellently wrought by the hand of Daedalus, or some other\r great artist, which we may chance to behold; any geometrician who saw\r them would appreciate the exquisiteness of their workmanship, but he\r would never dream of thinking that in them he could find the true equal\r or the true double, or the truth of any other proportion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1786"},"sequenceIndex":2247},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1787","text":"And will not a true astronomer have the same feeling when he looks at\r the movements of the stars? Will he not think that heaven and the\r things in heaven are framed by the Creator of them in the most perfect\r manner? But he will never imagine that the proportions of night and\r day, or of both to the month, or of the month to the year, or of the\r stars to these and to one another, and any other things that are\r material and visible can also be eternal and subject to no\r deviation—that would be absurd; and it is equally absurd to take so\r much pains in investigating their exact truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1787"},"sequenceIndex":2248},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1788","text":"Then, I said, in astronomy, as in geometry, we should employ problems,\r and let the heavens alone if we would approach the subject in the right\r way and so make the natural gift of reason to be of any real use.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1788"},"sequenceIndex":2249},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1789","text":"Yes, I said; and there are many other things which must also have a\r similar extension given to them, if our legislation is to be of any\r value. But can you tell me of any other suitable study?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1789"},"sequenceIndex":2250},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1790","text":"Motion, I said, has many forms, and not one only; two of them are\r obvious enough even to wits no better than ours; and there are others,\r as I imagine, which may be left to wiser persons.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1790"},"sequenceIndex":2251},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1791","text":"The second, I said, would seem relatively to the ears to be what the\r first is to the eyes; for I conceive that as the eyes are designed to\r look up at the stars, so are the ears to hear harmonious motions; and\r these are sister sciences—as the Pythagoreans say, and we, Glaucon,\r agree with them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1791"},"sequenceIndex":2252},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1792","text":"But this, I said, is a laborious study, and therefore we had better go\r and learn of them; and they will tell us whether there are any other\r applications of these sciences. At the same time, we must not lose\r sight of our own higher object.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1792"},"sequenceIndex":2253},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1793","text":"There is a perfection which all knowledge ought to reach, and which our\r pupils ought also to attain, and not to fall short of, as I was saying\r that they did in astronomy. For in the science of harmony, as you\r probably know, the same thing happens. The teachers of harmony compare\r the sounds and consonances which are heard only, and their labour, like\r that of the astronomers, is in vain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1793"},"sequenceIndex":2254},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1794","text":"Yes, by heaven! he said; and ’tis as good as a play to hear them\r talking about their condensed notes, as they call them; they put their\r ears close alongside of the strings like persons catching a sound from\r their neighbour’s wall—one set of them declaring that they distinguish\r an intermediate note and have found the least interval which should be\r the unit of measurement; the others insisting that the two sounds have\r passed into the same—either party setting their ears before their\r understanding.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1794"},"sequenceIndex":2255},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1795","text":"You mean, I said, those gentlemen who tease and torture the strings and\r rack them on the pegs of the instrument: I might carry on the metaphor\r and speak after their manner of the blows which the plectrum gives, and\r make accusations against the strings, both of backwardness and\r forwardness to sound; but this would be tedious, and therefore I will\r only say that these are not the men, and that I am referring to the\r Pythagoreans, of whom I was just now proposing to enquire about\r harmony. For they too are in error, like the astronomers; they\r investigate the numbers of the harmonies which ar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1795"},"sequenceIndex":2256},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1796","text":"A thing, I replied, which I would rather call useful; that is, if\r sought after with a view to the beautiful and good; but if pursued in\r any other spirit, useless.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1796"},"sequenceIndex":2257},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1797","text":"Now, when all these studies reach the point of inter-communion and\r connection with one another, and come to be considered in their mutual\r affinities, then, I think, but not till then, will the pursuit of them\r have a value for our objects; otherwise there is no profit in them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1797"},"sequenceIndex":2258},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1798","text":"What do you mean? I said; the prelude or what? Do you not know that all\r this is but the prelude to the actual strain which we have to learn?\r For you surely would not regard the skilled mathematician as a\r dialectician?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1798"},"sequenceIndex":2259},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1799","text":"Assuredly not, he said; I have hardly ever known a mathematician who\r was capable of reasoning.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1799"},"sequenceIndex":2260},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1800","text":"But do you imagine that men who are unable to give and take a reason\r will have the knowledge which we require of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1800"},"sequenceIndex":2261},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1801","text":"And so, Glaucon, I said, we have at last arrived at the hymn of\r dialectic. This is that strain which is of the intellect only, but\r which the faculty of sight will nevertheless be found to imitate; for\r sight, as you may remember, was imagined by us after a while to behold\r the real animals and stars, and last of all the sun himself. And so\r with dialectic; when a person starts on the discovery of the absolute\r by the light of reason only, and without any assistance of sense, and\r perseveres until by pure intelligence he arrives at the perception of\r the absolute good, he at last finds himsel","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1801"},"sequenceIndex":2262},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1802","text":"But the release of the prisoners from chains, and their translation\r from the shadows to the images and to the light, and the ascent from\r the underground den to the sun, while in his presence they are vainly\r trying to look on animals and plants and the light of the sun, but are\r able to perceive even with their weak eyes the images in the water\r (which are divine), and are the shadows of true existence (not shadows\r of images cast by a light of fire, which compared with the sun is only\r an image)—this power of elevating the highest principle in the soul to\r the contemplation of that which is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1802"},"sequenceIndex":2263},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1803","text":"I agree in what you are saying, he replied, which may be hard to\r believe, yet, from another point of view, is harder still to deny.\r This, however, is not a theme to be treated of in passing only, but\r will have to be discussed again and again. And so, whether our\r conclusion be true or false, let us assume all this, and proceed at\r once from the prelude or preamble to the chief strain (A play upon the\r Greek word, which means both ‘law’ and ‘strain.’), and describe that in\r like manner. Say, then, what is the nature and what are the divisions\r of dialectic, and what are the paths which lead ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1803"},"sequenceIndex":2264},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1804","text":"Dear Glaucon, I said, you will not be able to follow me here, though I\r would do my best, and you should behold not an image only but the\r absolute truth, according to my notion. Whether what I told you would\r or would not have been a reality I cannot venture to say; but you would\r have seen something like reality; of that I am confident.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1804"},"sequenceIndex":2265},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1805","text":"But I must also remind you, that the power of dialectic alone can\r reveal this, and only to one who is a disciple of the previous\r sciences.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1805"},"sequenceIndex":2266},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1806","text":"And assuredly no one will argue that there is any other method of\r comprehending by any regular process all true existence or of\r ascertaining what each thing is in its own nature; for the arts in\r general are concerned with the desires or opinions of men, or are\r cultivated with a view to production and construction, or for the\r preservation of such productions and constructions; and as to the\r mathematical sciences which, as we were saying, have some apprehension\r of true being—geometry and the like—they only dream about being, but\r never can they behold the waking reality so long as they le","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1806"},"sequenceIndex":2267},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1807","text":"Then dialectic, and dialectic alone, goes directly to the first\r principle and is the only science which does away with hypotheses in\r order to make her ground secure; the eye of the soul, which is\r literally buried in an outlandish slough, is by her gentle aid lifted\r upwards; and she uses as handmaids and helpers in the work of\r conversion, the sciences which we have been discussing. Custom terms\r them sciences, but they ought to have some other name, implying greater\r clearness than opinion and less clearness than science: and this, in\r our previous sketch, was called understanding. But why","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1807"},"sequenceIndex":2268},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1808","text":"Why indeed, he said, when any name will do which expresses the thought\r of the mind with clearness?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1808"},"sequenceIndex":2269},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1809","text":"At any rate, we are satisfied, as before, to have four divisions; two\r for intellect and two for opinion, and to call the first division\r science, the second understanding, the third belief, and the fourth\r perception of shadows, opinion being concerned with becoming, and\r intellect with being; and so to make a proportion:—","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1809"},"sequenceIndex":2270},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1810","text":"As being is to becoming, so is pure intellect to opinion. And as\r intellect is to opinion, so is science to belief, and understanding to\r the perception of shadows.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1810"},"sequenceIndex":2271},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1811","text":"But let us defer the further correlation and subdivision of the\r subjects of opinion and of intellect, for it will be a long enquiry,\r many times longer than this has been.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1811"},"sequenceIndex":2272},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1812","text":"And do you also agree, I said, in describing the dialectician as one\r who attains a conception of the essence of each thing? And he who does\r not possess and is therefore unable to impart this conception, in\r whatever degree he fails, may in that degree also be said to fail in\r intelligence? Will you admit so much?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1812"},"sequenceIndex":2273},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1813","text":"And you would say the same of the conception of the good? Until the\r person is able to abstract and define rationally the idea of good, and\r unless he can run the gauntlet of all objections, and is ready to\r disprove them, not by appeals to opinion, but to absolute truth, never\r faltering at any step of the argument—unless he can do all this, you\r would say that he knows neither the idea of good nor any other good; he\r apprehends only a shadow, if anything at all, which is given by opinion\r and not by science;—dreaming and slumbering in this life, before he is\r well awake here, he arrives at t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1813"},"sequenceIndex":2274},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1814","text":"And surely you would not have the children of your ideal State, whom\r you are nurturing and educating—if the ideal ever becomes a reality—you\r would not allow the future rulers to be like posts (Literally ‘lines,’\r probably the starting-point of a race-course.), having no reason in\r them, and yet to be set in authority over the highest matters?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1814"},"sequenceIndex":2275},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1815","text":"Then you will make a law that they shall have such an education as will\r enable them to attain the greatest skill in asking and answering\r questions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1815"},"sequenceIndex":2276},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1816","text":"Dialectic, then, as you will agree, is the coping-stone of the\r sciences, and is set over them; no other science can be placed\r higher—the nature of knowledge can no further go?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1816"},"sequenceIndex":2277},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1817","text":"But to whom we are to assign these studies, and in what way they are to\r be assigned, are questions which remain to be considered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1817"},"sequenceIndex":2278},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1818","text":"The same natures must still be chosen, and the preference again given\r to the surest and the bravest, and, if possible, to the fairest; and,\r having noble and generous tempers, they should also have the natural\r gifts which will facilitate their education.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1818"},"sequenceIndex":2279},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1819","text":"Such gifts as keenness and ready powers of acquisition; for the mind\r more often faints from the severity of study than from the severity of\r gymnastics: the toil is more entirely the mind’s own, and is not shared\r with the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1819"},"sequenceIndex":2280},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1820","text":"Further, he of whom we are in search should have a good memory, and be\r an unwearied solid man who is a lover of labour in any line; or he will\r never be able to endure the great amount of bodily exercise and to go\r through all the intellectual discipline and study which we require of\r him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1820"},"sequenceIndex":2281},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1821","text":"The mistake at present is, that those who study philosophy have no\r vocation, and this, as I was before saying, is the reason why she has\r fallen into disrepute: her true sons should take her by the hand and\r not bastards.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1821"},"sequenceIndex":2282},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1822","text":"In the first place, her votary should not have a lame or halting\r industry—I mean, that he should not be half industrious and half idle:\r as, for example, when a man is a lover of gymnastic and hunting, and\r all other bodily exercises, but a hater rather than a lover of the\r labour of learning or listening or enquiring. Or the occupation to\r which he devotes himself may be of an opposite kind, and he may have\r the other sort of lameness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1822"},"sequenceIndex":2283},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1823","text":"And as to truth, I said, is not a soul equally to be deemed halt and\r lame which hates voluntary falsehood and is extremely indignant at\r herself and others when they tell lies, but is patient of involuntary\r falsehood, and does not mind wallowing like a swinish beast in the mire\r of ignorance, and has no shame at being detected?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1823"},"sequenceIndex":2284},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1824","text":"And, again, in respect of temperance, courage, magnificence, and every\r other virtue, should we not carefully distinguish between the true son\r and the bastard? for where there is no discernment of such qualities\r states and individuals unconsciously err; and the state makes a ruler,\r and the individual a friend, of one who, being defective in some part\r of virtue, is in a figure lame or a bastard.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1824"},"sequenceIndex":2285},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1825","text":"All these things, then, will have to be carefully considered by us; and\r if only those whom we introduce to this vast system of education and\r training are sound in body and mind, justice herself will have nothing\r to say against us, and we shall be the saviours of the constitution and\r of the State; but, if our pupils are men of another stamp, the reverse\r will happen, and we shall pour a still greater flood of ridicule on\r philosophy than she has to endure at present.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1825"},"sequenceIndex":2286},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1826","text":"Certainly not, I said; and yet perhaps, in thus turning jest into\r earnest I am equally ridiculous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1826"},"sequenceIndex":2287},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1827","text":"I had forgotten, I said, that we were not serious, and spoke with too\r much excitement. For when I saw philosophy so undeservedly trampled\r under foot of men I could not help feeling a sort of indignation at the\r authors of her disgrace: and my anger made me too vehement.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1827"},"sequenceIndex":2288},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1828","text":"But I, who am the speaker, felt that I was. And now let me remind you\r that, although in our former selection we chose old men, we must not do\r so in this. Solon was under a delusion when he said that a man when he\r grows old may learn many things—for he can no more learn much than he\r can run much; youth is the time for any extraordinary toil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1828"},"sequenceIndex":2289},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1829","text":"And, therefore, calculation and geometry and all the other elements of\r instruction, which are a preparation for dialectic, should be presented\r to the mind in childhood; not, however, under any notion of forcing our\r system of education.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1829"},"sequenceIndex":2290},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1830","text":"Because a freeman ought not to be a slave in the acquisition of\r knowledge of any kind. Bodily exercise, when compulsory, does no harm\r to the body; but knowledge which is acquired under compulsion obtains\r no hold on the mind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1830"},"sequenceIndex":2291},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1831","text":"Then, my good friend, I said, do not use compulsion, but let early\r education be a sort of amusement; you will then be better able to find\r out the natural bent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1831"},"sequenceIndex":2292},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1832","text":"Do you remember that the children, too, were to be taken to see the\r battle on horseback; and that if there were no danger they were to be\r brought close up and, like young hounds, have a taste of blood given\r them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1832"},"sequenceIndex":2293},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1833","text":"The same practice may be followed, I said, in all these things—labours,\r lessons, dangers—and he who is most at home in all of them ought to be\r enrolled in a select number.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1833"},"sequenceIndex":2294},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1834","text":"At the age when the necessary gymnastics are over: the period whether\r of two or three years which passes in this sort of training is useless\r for any other purpose; for sleep and exercise are unpropitious to\r learning; and the trial of who is first in gymnastic exercises is one\r of the most important tests to which our youth are subjected.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1834"},"sequenceIndex":2295},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1835","text":"After that time those who are selected from the class of twenty years\r old will be promoted to higher honour, and the sciences which they\r learned without any order in their early education will now be brought\r together, and they will be able to see the natural relationship of them\r to one another and to true being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1835"},"sequenceIndex":2296},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1836","text":"Yes, I said; and the capacity for such knowledge is the great criterion\r of dialectical talent: the comprehensive mind is always the\r dialectical.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1836"},"sequenceIndex":2297},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1837","text":"These, I said, are the points which you must consider; and those who\r have most of this comprehension, and who are most steadfast in their\r learning, and in their military and other appointed duties, when they\r have arrived at the age of thirty have to be chosen by you out of the\r select class, and elevated to higher honour; and you will have to prove\r them by the help of dialectic, in order to learn which of them is able\r to give up the use of sight and the other senses, and in company with\r truth to attain absolute being: And here, my friend, great caution is\r required.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1837"},"sequenceIndex":2298},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1838","text":"Do you not remark, I said, how great is the evil which dialectic has\r introduced?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1838"},"sequenceIndex":2299},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1839","text":"Do you think that there is anything so very unnatural or inexcusable in\r their case? or will you make allowance for them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1839"},"sequenceIndex":2300},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1840","text":"I want you, I said, by way of parallel, to imagine a supposititious son\r who is brought up in great wealth; he is one of a great and numerous\r family, and has many flatterers. When he grows up to manhood, he learns\r that his alleged are not his real parents; but who the real are he is\r unable to discover. Can you guess how he will be likely to behave\r towards his flatterers and his supposed parents, first of all during\r the period when he is ignorant of the false relation, and then again\r when he knows? Or shall I guess for you?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1840"},"sequenceIndex":2301},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1841","text":"Then I should say, that while he is ignorant of the truth he will be\r likely to honour his father and his mother and his supposed relations\r more than the flatterers; he will be less inclined to neglect them when\r in need, or to do or say anything against them; and he will be less\r willing to disobey them in any important matter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1841"},"sequenceIndex":2302},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1842","text":"But when he has made the discovery, I should imagine that he would\r diminish his honour and regard for them, and would become more devoted\r to the flatterers; their influence over him would greatly increase; he\r would now live after their ways, and openly associate with them, and,\r unless he were of an unusually good disposition, he would trouble\r himself no more about his supposed parents or other relations.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1842"},"sequenceIndex":2303},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1843","text":"Well, all that is very probable. But how is the image applicable to the\r disciples of philosophy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1843"},"sequenceIndex":2304},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1844","text":"In this way: you know that there are certain principles about justice\r and honour, which were taught us in childhood, and under their parental\r authority we have been brought up, obeying and honouring them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1844"},"sequenceIndex":2305},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1845","text":"There are also opposite maxims and habits of pleasure which flatter and\r attract the soul, but do not influence those of us who have any sense\r of right, and they continue to obey and honour the maxims of their\r fathers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1845"},"sequenceIndex":2306},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1846","text":"Now, when a man is in this state, and the questioning spirit asks what\r is fair or honourable, and he answers as the legislator has taught him,\r and then arguments many and diverse refute his words, until he is\r driven into believing that nothing is honourable any more than\r dishonourable, or just and good any more than the reverse, and so of\r all the notions which he most valued, do you think that he will still\r honour and obey them as before?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1846"},"sequenceIndex":2307},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1847","text":"And when he ceases to think them honourable and natural as heretofore,\r and he fails to discover the true, can he be expected to pursue any\r life other than that which flatters his desires?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1847"},"sequenceIndex":2308},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1848","text":"Now all this is very natural in students of philosophy such as I have\r described, and also, as I was just now saying, most excusable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1848"},"sequenceIndex":2309},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1849","text":"Therefore, that your feelings may not be moved to pity about our\r citizens who are now thirty years of age, every care must be taken in\r introducing them to dialectic.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1849"},"sequenceIndex":2310},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1850","text":"There is a danger lest they should taste the dear delight too early;\r for youngsters, as you may have observed, when they first get the taste\r in their mouths, argue for amusement, and are always contradicting and\r refuting others in imitation of those who refute them; like puppy-dogs,\r they rejoice in pulling and tearing at all who come near them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1850"},"sequenceIndex":2311},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1851","text":"And when they have made many conquests and received defeats at the\r hands of many, they violently and speedily get into a way of not\r believing anything which they believed before, and hence, not only\r they, but philosophy and all that relates to it is apt to have a bad\r name with the rest of the world.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1851"},"sequenceIndex":2312},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1852","text":"But when a man begins to get older, he will no longer be guilty of such\r insanity; he will imitate the dialectician who is seeking for truth,\r and not the eristic, who is contradicting for the sake of amusement;\r and the greater moderation of his character will increase instead of\r diminishing the honour of the pursuit.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1852"},"sequenceIndex":2313},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1853","text":"And did we not make special provision for this, when we said that the\r disciples of philosophy were to be orderly and steadfast, not, as now,\r any chance aspirant or intruder?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1853"},"sequenceIndex":2314},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1854","text":"Suppose, I said, the study of philosophy to take the place of\r gymnastics and to be continued diligently and earnestly and exclusively\r for twice the number of years which were passed in bodily exercise—will\r that be enough?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1854"},"sequenceIndex":2315},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1855","text":"Say five years, I replied; at the end of the time they must be sent\r down again into the den and compelled to hold any military or other\r office which young men are qualified to hold: in this way they will get\r their experience of life, and there will be an opportunity of trying\r whether, when they are drawn all manner of ways by temptation, they\r will stand firm or flinch.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1855"},"sequenceIndex":2316},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1856","text":"Fifteen years, I answered; and when they have reached fifty years of\r age, then let those who still survive and have distinguished themselves\r in every action of their lives and in every branch of knowledge come at\r last to their consummation: the time has now arrived at which they must\r raise the eye of the soul to the universal light which lightens all\r things, and behold the absolute good; for that is the pattern according\r to which they are to order the State and the lives of individuals, and\r the remainder of their own lives also; making philosophy their chief\r pursuit, but, when their tu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1856"},"sequenceIndex":2317},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1857","text":"You are a sculptor, Socrates, and have made statues of our governors\r faultless in beauty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1857"},"sequenceIndex":2318},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1858","text":"Yes, I said, Glaucon, and of our governesses too; for you must not\r suppose that what I have been saying applies to men only and not to\r women as far as their natures can go.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1858"},"sequenceIndex":2319},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1859","text":"There you are right, he said, since we have made them to share in all\r things like the men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1859"},"sequenceIndex":2320},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1860","text":"Well, I said, and you would agree (would you not?) that what has been\r said about the State and the government is not a mere dream, and\r although difficult not impossible, but only possible in the way which\r has been supposed; that is to say, when the true philosopher kings are\r born in a State, one or more of them, despising the honours of this\r present world which they deem mean and worthless, esteeming above all\r things right and the honour that springs from right, and regarding\r justice as the greatest and most necessary of all things, whose\r ministers they are, and whose principles will b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1860"},"sequenceIndex":2321},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1861","text":"They will begin by sending out into the country all the inhabitants of\r the city who are more than ten years old, and will take possession of\r their children, who will be unaffected by the habits of their parents;\r these they will train in their own habits and laws, I mean in the laws\r which we have given them: and in this way the State and constitution of\r which we were speaking will soonest and most easily attain happiness,\r and the nation which has such a constitution will gain most.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1861"},"sequenceIndex":2322},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1862","text":"Yes, that will be the best way. And I think, Socrates, that you have\r very well described how, if ever, such a constitution might come into\r being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1862"},"sequenceIndex":2323},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1863","text":"Enough then of the perfect State, and of the man who bears its\r image—there is no difficulty in seeing how we shall describe him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1863"},"sequenceIndex":2324},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1864","text":"There is no difficulty, he replied; and I agree with you in thinking\r that nothing more need be said.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1864"},"sequenceIndex":2325},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1865","text":"And so, Glaucon, we have arrived at the conclusion that in the perfect\r State wives and children are to be in common; and that all education\r and the pursuits of war and peace are also to be common, and the best\r philosophers and the bravest warriors are to be their kings?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1865"},"sequenceIndex":2326},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1866","text":"Yes, I said; and we have further acknowledged that the governors, when\r appointed themselves, will take their soldiers and place them in houses\r such as we were describing, which are common to all, and contain\r nothing private, or individual; and about their property, you remember\r what we agreed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1866"},"sequenceIndex":2327},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1867","text":"Yes, I remember that no one was to have any of the ordinary possessions\r of mankind; they were to be warrior athletes and guardians, receiving\r from the other citizens, in lieu of annual payment, only their\r maintenance, and they were to take care of themselves and of the whole\r State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1867"},"sequenceIndex":2328},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1868","text":"True, I said; and now that this division of our task is concluded, let\r us find the point at which we digressed, that we may return into the\r old path.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1868"},"sequenceIndex":2329},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1869","text":"There is no difficulty in returning; you implied, then as now, that you\r had finished the description of the State: you said that such a State\r was good, and that the man was good who answered to it, although, as\r now appears, you had more excellent things to relate both of State and\r man. And you said further, that if this was the true form, then the\r others were false; and of the false forms, you said, as I remember,\r that there were four principal ones, and that their defects, and the\r defects of the individuals corresponding to them, were worth examining.\r When we had seen all the individu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1869"},"sequenceIndex":2330},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1870","text":"Then, like a wrestler, he replied, you must put yourself again in the\r same position; and let me ask the same questions, and do you give me\r the same answer which you were about to give me then.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1870"},"sequenceIndex":2331},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1871","text":"I shall particularly wish to hear what were the four constitutions of\r which you were speaking.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1871"},"sequenceIndex":2332},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1872","text":"That question, I said, is easily answered: the four governments of\r which I spoke, so far as they have distinct names, are, first, those of\r Crete and Sparta, which are generally applauded; what is termed\r oligarchy comes next; this is not equally approved, and is a form of\r government which teems with evils: thirdly, democracy, which naturally\r follows oligarchy, although very different: and lastly comes tyranny,\r great and famous, which differs from them all, and is the fourth and\r worst disorder of a State. I do not know, do you? of any other\r constitution which can be said to have a distin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1872"},"sequenceIndex":2333},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1873","text":"Yes, he replied, we certainly hear of many curious forms of government\r which exist among them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1873"},"sequenceIndex":2334},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1874","text":"Do you know, I said, that governments vary as the dispositions of men\r vary, and that there must be as many of the one as there are of the\r other? For we cannot suppose that States are made of ‘oak and rock,’\r and not out of the human natures which are in them, and which in a\r figure turn the scale and draw other things after them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1874"},"sequenceIndex":2335},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1875","text":"Yes, he said, the States are as the men are; they grow out of human\r characters.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1875"},"sequenceIndex":2336},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1876","text":"Then if the constitutions of States are five, the dispositions of\r individual minds will also be five?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1876"},"sequenceIndex":2337},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1877","text":"Him who answers to aristocracy, and whom we rightly call just and good,\r we have already described.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1877"},"sequenceIndex":2338},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1878","text":"Then let us now proceed to describe the inferior sort of natures, being\r the contentious and ambitious, who answer to the Spartan polity; also\r the oligarchical, democratical, and tyrannical. Let us place the most\r just by the side of the most unjust, and when we see them we shall be\r able to compare the relative happiness or unhappiness of him who leads\r a life of pure justice or pure injustice. The enquiry will then be\r completed. And we shall know whether we ought to pursue injustice, as\r Thrasymachus advises, or in accordance with the conclusions of the\r argument to prefer justice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1878"},"sequenceIndex":2339},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1879","text":"Shall we follow our old plan, which we adopted with a view to\r clearness, of taking the State first and then proceeding to the\r individual, and begin with the government of honour?—I know of no name\r for such a government other than timocracy, or perhaps timarchy. We\r will compare with this the like character in the individual; and, after\r that, consider oligarchy and the oligarchical man; and then again we\r will turn our attention to democracy and the democratical man; and\r lastly, we will go and view the city of tyranny, and once more take a\r look into the tyrant’s soul, and try to arrive at","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1879"},"sequenceIndex":2340},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1880","text":"First, then, I said, let us enquire how timocracy (the government of\r honour) arises out of aristocracy (the government of the best).\r Clearly, all political changes originate in divisions of the actual\r governing power; a government which is united, however small, cannot be\r moved.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1880"},"sequenceIndex":2341},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1881","text":"In what way, then, will our city be moved, and in what manner will the\r two classes of auxiliaries and rulers disagree among themselves or with\r one another? Shall we, after the manner of Homer, pray the Muses to\r tell us ‘how discord first arose’? Shall we imagine them in solemn\r mockery, to play and jest with us as if we were children, and to\r address us in a lofty tragic vein, making believe to be in earnest?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1881"},"sequenceIndex":2342},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1882","text":"After this manner:—A city which is thus constituted can hardly be\r shaken; but, seeing that everything which has a beginning has also an\r end, even a constitution such as yours will not last for ever, but will\r in time be dissolved. And this is the dissolution:—In plants that grow\r in the earth, as well as in animals that move on the earth’s surface,\r fertility and sterility of soul and body occur when the circumferences\r of the circles of each are completed, which in short-lived existences\r pass over a short space, and in long-lived ones over a long space. But\r to the knowledge of human fecun","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1882"},"sequenceIndex":2343},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1883","text":"Why, yes, I said, of course they answer truly; how can the Muses speak\r falsely?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1883"},"sequenceIndex":2344},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1884","text":"When discord arose, then the two races were drawn different ways: the\r iron and brass fell to acquiring money and land and houses and gold and\r silver; but the gold and silver races, not wanting money but having the\r true riches in their own nature, inclined towards virtue and the\r ancient order of things. There was a battle between them, and at last\r they agreed to distribute their land and houses among individual\r owners; and they enslaved their friends and maintainers, whom they had\r formerly protected in the condition of freemen, and made of them\r subjects and servants; and they themselves","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1884"},"sequenceIndex":2345},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1885","text":"And the new government which thus arises will be of a form intermediate\r between oligarchy and aristocracy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1885"},"sequenceIndex":2346},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1886","text":"Such will be the change, and after the change has been made, how will\r they proceed? Clearly, the new State, being in a mean between oligarchy\r and the perfect State, will partly follow one and partly the other, and\r will also have some peculiarities.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1886"},"sequenceIndex":2347},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1887","text":"In the honour given to rulers, in the abstinence of the warrior class\r from agriculture, handicrafts, and trade in general, in the institution\r of common meals, and in the attention paid to gymnastics and military\r training—in all these respects this State will resemble the former.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1887"},"sequenceIndex":2348},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1888","text":"But in the fear of admitting philosophers to power, because they are no\r longer to be had simple and earnest, but are made up of mixed elements;\r and in turning from them to passionate and less complex characters, who\r are by nature fitted for war rather than peace; and in the value set by\r them upon military stratagems and contrivances, and in the waging of\r everlasting wars—this State will be for the most part peculiar.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1888"},"sequenceIndex":2349},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1889","text":"Yes, I said; and men of this stamp will be covetous of money, like\r those who live in oligarchies; they will have, a fierce secret longing\r after gold and silver, which they will hoard in dark places, having\r magazines and treasuries of their own for the deposit and concealment\r of them; also castles which are just nests for their eggs, and in which\r they will spend large sums on their wives, or on any others whom they\r please.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1889"},"sequenceIndex":2350},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1890","text":"And they are miserly because they have no means of openly acquiring the\r money which they prize; they will spend that which is another man’s on\r the gratification of their desires, stealing their pleasures and\r running away like children from the law, their father: they have been\r schooled not by gentle influences but by force, for they have neglected\r her who is the true Muse, the companion of reason and philosophy, and\r have honoured gymnastic more than music.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1890"},"sequenceIndex":2351},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1891","text":"Undoubtedly, he said, the form of government which you describe is a\r mixture of good and evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1891"},"sequenceIndex":2352},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1892","text":"Why, there is a mixture, I said; but one thing, and one thing only, is\r predominantly seen,—the spirit of contention and ambition; and these\r are due to the prevalence of the passionate or spirited element.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1892"},"sequenceIndex":2353},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1893","text":"Such is the origin and such the character of this State, which has been\r described in outline only; the more perfect execution was not required,\r for a sketch is enough to show the type of the most perfectly just and\r most perfectly unjust; and to go through all the States and all the\r characters of men, omitting none of them, would be an interminable\r labour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1893"},"sequenceIndex":2354},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1894","text":"Now what man answers to this form of government-how did he come into\r being, and what is he like?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1894"},"sequenceIndex":2355},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1895","text":"I think, said Adeimantus, that in the spirit of contention which\r characterises him, he is not unlike our friend Glaucon.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1895"},"sequenceIndex":2356},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1896","text":"Perhaps, I said, he may be like him in that one point; but there are\r other respects in which he is very different.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1896"},"sequenceIndex":2357},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1897","text":"He should have more of self-assertion and be less cultivated, and yet a\r friend of culture; and he should be a good listener, but no speaker.\r Such a person is apt to be rough with slaves, unlike the educated man,\r who is too proud for that; and he will also be courteous to freemen,\r and remarkably obedient to authority; he is a lover of power and a\r lover of honour; claiming to be a ruler, not because he is eloquent, or\r on any ground of that sort, but because he is a soldier and has\r performed feats of arms; he is also a lover of gymnastic exercises and\r of the chase.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1897"},"sequenceIndex":2358},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1898","text":"Such an one will despise riches only when he is young; but as he gets\r older he will be more and more attracted to them, because he has a\r piece of the avaricious nature in him, and is not single-minded towards\r virtue, having lost his best guardian.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1898"},"sequenceIndex":2359},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1899","text":"Philosophy, I said, tempered with music, who comes and takes up her\r abode in a man, and is the only saviour of his virtue throughout life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1899"},"sequenceIndex":2360},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1900","text":"Such, I said, is the timocratical youth, and he is like the\r timocratical State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1900"},"sequenceIndex":2361},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1901","text":"His origin is as follows:—He is often the young son of a brave father,\r who dwells in an ill-governed city, of which he declines the honours\r and offices, and will not go to law, or exert himself in any way, but\r is ready to waive his rights in order that he may escape trouble.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1901"},"sequenceIndex":2362},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1902","text":"The character of the son begins to develope when he hears his mother\r complaining that her husband has no place in the government, of which\r the consequence is that she has no precedence among other women.\r Further, when she sees her husband not very eager about money, and\r instead of battling and railing in the law courts or assembly, taking\r whatever happens to him quietly; and when she observes that his\r thoughts always centre in himself, while he treats her with very\r considerable indifference, she is annoyed, and says to her son that his\r father is only half a man and far too easy-going: ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1902"},"sequenceIndex":2363},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1903","text":"Yes, said Adeimantus, they give us plenty of them, and their complaints\r are so like themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1903"},"sequenceIndex":2364},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1904","text":"And you know, I said, that the old servants also, who are supposed to\r be attached to the family, from time to time talk privately in the same\r strain to the son; and if they see any one who owes money to his\r father, or is wronging him in any way, and he fails to prosecute them,\r they tell the youth that when he grows up he must retaliate upon people\r of this sort, and be more of a man than his father. He has only to walk\r abroad and he hears and sees the same sort of thing: those who do their\r own business in the city are called simpletons, and held in no esteem,\r while the busy-bodies are h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1904"},"sequenceIndex":2365},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1905","text":"Then we have now, I said, the second form of government and the second\r type of character?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1905"},"sequenceIndex":2366},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1906","text":"A government resting on a valuation of property, in which the rich have\r power and the poor man is deprived of it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1906"},"sequenceIndex":2367},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1907","text":"Ought I not to begin by describing how the change from timocracy to\r oligarchy arises?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1907"},"sequenceIndex":2368},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1908","text":"Well, I said, no eyes are required in order to see how the one passes\r into the other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1908"},"sequenceIndex":2369},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1909","text":"The accumulation of gold in the treasury of private individuals is the\r ruin of timocracy; they invent illegal modes of expenditure; for what\r do they or their wives care about the law?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1909"},"sequenceIndex":2370},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1910","text":"And then one, seeing another grow rich, seeks to rival him, and thus\r the great mass of the citizens become lovers of money.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1910"},"sequenceIndex":2371},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1911","text":"And so they grow richer and richer, and the more they think of making a\r fortune the less they think of virtue; for when riches and virtue are\r placed together in the scales of the balance, the one always rises as\r the other falls.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1911"},"sequenceIndex":2372},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1912","text":"And in proportion as riches and rich men are honoured in the State,\r virtue and the virtuous are dishonoured.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1912"},"sequenceIndex":2373},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1913","text":"And so at last, instead of loving contention and glory, men become\r lovers of trade and money; they honour and look up to the rich man, and\r make a ruler of him, and dishonour the poor man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1913"},"sequenceIndex":2374},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1914","text":"They next proceed to make a law which fixes a sum of money as the\r qualification of citizenship; the sum is higher in one place and lower\r in another, as the oligarchy is more or less exclusive; and they allow\r no one whose property falls below the amount fixed to have any share in\r the government. These changes in the constitution they effect by force\r of arms, if intimidation has not already done their work.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1914"},"sequenceIndex":2375},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1915","text":"Yes, he said; but what are the characteristics of this form of\r government, and what are the defects of which we were speaking?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1915"},"sequenceIndex":2376},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1916","text":"First of all, I said, consider the nature of the qualification. Just\r think what would happen if pilots were to be chosen according to their\r property, and a poor man were refused permission to steer, even though\r he were a better pilot?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1916"},"sequenceIndex":2377},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1917","text":"Nay, he said, the case of a city is the strongest of all, inasmuch as\r the rule of a city is the greatest and most difficult of all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1917"},"sequenceIndex":2378},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1918","text":"The inevitable division: such a State is not one, but two States, the\r one of poor, the other of rich men; and they are living on the same\r spot and always conspiring against one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1918"},"sequenceIndex":2379},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1919","text":"Another discreditable feature is, that, for a like reason, they are\r incapable of carrying on any war. Either they arm the multitude, and\r then they are more afraid of them than of the enemy; or, if they do not\r call them out in the hour of battle, they are oligarchs indeed, few to\r fight as they are few to rule. And at the same time their fondness for\r money makes them unwilling to pay taxes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1919"},"sequenceIndex":2380},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1920","text":"And, as we said before, under such a constitution the same persons have\r too many callings—they are husbandmen, tradesmen, warriors, all in one.\r Does that look well?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1920"},"sequenceIndex":2381},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1921","text":"There is another evil which is, perhaps, the greatest of all, and to\r which this State first begins to be liable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1921"},"sequenceIndex":2382},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1922","text":"A man may sell all that he has, and another may acquire his property;\r yet after the sale he may dwell in the city of which he is no longer a\r part, being neither trader, nor artisan, nor horseman, nor hoplite, but\r only a poor, helpless creature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1922"},"sequenceIndex":2383},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1923","text":"The evil is certainly not prevented there; for oligarchies have both\r the extremes of great wealth and utter poverty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1923"},"sequenceIndex":2384},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1924","text":"But think again: In his wealthy days, while he was spending his money,\r was a man of this sort a whit more good to the State for the purposes\r of citizenship? Or did he only seem to be a member of the ruling body,\r although in truth he was neither ruler nor subject, but just a\r spendthrift?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1924"},"sequenceIndex":2385},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1925","text":"May we not say that this is the drone in the house who is like the\r drone in the honeycomb, and that the one is the plague of the city as\r the other is of the hive?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1925"},"sequenceIndex":2386},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1926","text":"And God has made the flying drones, Adeimantus, all without stings,\r whereas of the walking drones he has made some without stings but\r others have dreadful stings; of the stingless class are those who in\r their old age end as paupers; of the stingers come all the criminal\r class, as they are termed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1926"},"sequenceIndex":2387},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1927","text":"Clearly then, whenever you see paupers in a State, somewhere in that\r neighborhood there are hidden away thieves, and cut-purses and robbers\r of temples, and all sorts of malefactors.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1927"},"sequenceIndex":2388},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1928","text":"And may we be so bold as to affirm that there are also many criminals\r to be found in them, rogues who have stings, and whom the authorities\r are careful to restrain by force?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1928"},"sequenceIndex":2389},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1929","text":"The existence of such persons is to be attributed to want of education,\r ill-training, and an evil constitution of the State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1929"},"sequenceIndex":2390},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1930","text":"Such, then, is the form and such are the evils of oligarchy; and there\r may be many other evils.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1930"},"sequenceIndex":2391},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1931","text":"Then oligarchy, or the form of government in which the rulers are\r elected for their wealth, may now be dismissed. Let us next proceed to\r consider the nature and origin of the individual who answers to this\r State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1931"},"sequenceIndex":2392},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1932","text":"A time arrives when the representative of timocracy has a son: at first\r he begins by emulating his father and walking in his footsteps, but\r presently he sees him of a sudden foundering against the State as upon\r a sunken reef, and he and all that he has is lost; he may have been a\r general or some other high officer who is brought to trial under a\r prejudice raised by informers, and either put to death, or exiled, or\r deprived of the privileges of a citizen, and all his property taken\r from him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1932"},"sequenceIndex":2393},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1933","text":"And the son has seen and known all this—he is a ruined man, and his\r fear has taught him to knock ambition and passion headforemost from his\r bosom’s throne; humbled by poverty he takes to money-making and by mean\r and miserly savings and hard work gets a fortune together. Is not such\r an one likely to seat the concupiscent and covetous element on the\r vacant throne and to suffer it to play the great king within him, girt\r with tiara and chain and scimitar?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1933"},"sequenceIndex":2394},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1934","text":"And when he has made reason and spirit sit down on the ground\r obediently on either side of their sovereign, and taught them to know\r their place, he compels the one to think only of how lesser sums may be\r turned into larger ones, and will not allow the other to worship and\r admire anything but riches and rich men, or to be ambitious of anything\r so much as the acquisition of wealth and the means of acquiring it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1934"},"sequenceIndex":2395},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1935","text":"Of all changes, he said, there is none so speedy or so sure as the\r conversion of the ambitious youth into the avaricious one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1935"},"sequenceIndex":2396},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1936","text":"Yes, he said; at any rate the individual out of whom he came is like\r the State out of which oligarchy came.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1936"},"sequenceIndex":2397},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1937","text":"First, then, they resemble one another in the value which they set upon\r wealth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1937"},"sequenceIndex":2398},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1938","text":"Also in their penurious, laborious character; the individual only\r satisfies his necessary appetites, and confines his expenditure to\r them; his other desires he subdues, under the idea that they are\r unprofitable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1938"},"sequenceIndex":2399},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1939","text":"He is a shabby fellow, who saves something out of everything and makes\r a purse for himself; and this is the sort of man whom the vulgar\r applaud. Is he not a true image of the State which he represents?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1939"},"sequenceIndex":2400},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1940","text":"He appears to me to be so; at any rate money is highly valued by him as\r well as by the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1940"},"sequenceIndex":2401},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1941","text":"I imagine not, he said; had he been educated he would never have made a\r blind god director of his chorus, or given him chief honour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1941"},"sequenceIndex":2402},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1942","text":"Excellent! I said. Yet consider: Must we not further admit that owing\r to this want of cultivation there will be found in him dronelike\r desires as of pauper and rogue, which are forcibly kept down by his\r general habit of life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1942"},"sequenceIndex":2403},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1943","text":"You should see him where he has some great opportunity of acting\r dishonestly, as in the guardianship of an orphan.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1943"},"sequenceIndex":2404},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1944","text":"It will be clear enough then that in his ordinary dealings which give\r him a reputation for honesty he coerces his bad passions by an enforced\r virtue; not making them see that they are wrong, or taming them by\r reason, but by necessity and fear constraining them, and because he\r trembles for his possessions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1944"},"sequenceIndex":2405},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1945","text":"Yes, indeed, my dear friend, but you will find that the natural desires\r of the drone commonly exist in him all the same whenever he has to\r spend what is not his own.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1945"},"sequenceIndex":2406},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1946","text":"The man, then, will be at war with himself; he will be two men, and not\r one; but, in general, his better desires will be found to prevail over\r his inferior ones.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1946"},"sequenceIndex":2407},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1947","text":"For these reasons such an one will be more respectable than most\r people; yet the true virtue of a unanimous and harmonious soul will\r flee far away and never come near him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1947"},"sequenceIndex":2408},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1948","text":"And surely, the miser individually will be an ignoble competitor in a\r State for any prize of victory, or other object of honourable ambition;\r he will not spend his money in the contest for glory; so afraid is he\r of awakening his expensive appetites and inviting them to help and join\r in the struggle; in true oligarchical fashion he fights with a small\r part only of his resources, and the result commonly is that he loses\r the prize and saves his money.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1948"},"sequenceIndex":2409},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1949","text":"Can we any longer doubt, then, that the miser and money-maker answers\r to the oligarchical State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1949"},"sequenceIndex":2410},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1950","text":"Next comes democracy; of this the origin and nature have still to be\r considered by us; and then we will enquire into the ways of the\r democratic man, and bring him up for judgment.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1950"},"sequenceIndex":2411},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1951","text":"Well, I said, and how does the change from oligarchy into democracy\r arise? Is it not on this wise?—The good at which such a State aims is\r to become as rich as possible, a desire which is insatiable?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1951"},"sequenceIndex":2412},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1952","text":"The rulers, being aware that their power rests upon their wealth,\r refuse to curtail by law the extravagance of the spendthrift youth\r because they gain by their ruin; they take interest from them and buy\r up their estates and thus increase their own wealth and importance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1952"},"sequenceIndex":2413},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1953","text":"There can be no doubt that the love of wealth and the spirit of\r moderation cannot exist together in citizens of the same state to any\r considerable extent; one or the other will be disregarded.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1953"},"sequenceIndex":2414},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1954","text":"And in oligarchical States, from the general spread of carelessness and\r extravagance, men of good family have often been reduced to beggary?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1954"},"sequenceIndex":2415},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1955","text":"And still they remain in the city; there they are, ready to sting and\r fully armed, and some of them owe money, some have forfeited their\r citizenship; a third class are in both predicaments; and they hate and\r conspire against those who have got their property, and against\r everybody else, and are eager for revolution.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1955"},"sequenceIndex":2416},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1956","text":"On the other hand, the men of business, stooping as they walk, and\r pretending not even to see those whom they have already ruined, insert\r their sting—that is, their money—into some one else who is not on his\r guard against them, and recover the parent sum many times over\r multiplied into a family of children: and so they make drone and pauper\r to abound in the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1956"},"sequenceIndex":2417},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1957","text":"The evil blazes up like a fire; and they will not extinguish it, either\r by restricting a man’s use of his own property, or by another remedy:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1957"},"sequenceIndex":2418},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1958","text":"One which is the next best, and has the advantage of compelling the\r citizens to look to their characters:—Let there be a general rule that\r every one shall enter into voluntary contracts at his own risk, and\r there will be less of this scandalous money-making, and the evils of\r which we were speaking will be greatly lessened in the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1958"},"sequenceIndex":2419},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1959","text":"At present the governors, induced by the motives which I have named,\r treat their subjects badly; while they and their adherents, especially\r the young men of the governing class, are habituated to lead a life of\r luxury and idleness both of body and mind; they do nothing, and are\r incapable of resisting either pleasure or pain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1959"},"sequenceIndex":2420},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1960","text":"They themselves care only for making money, and are as indifferent as\r the pauper to the cultivation of virtue.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1960"},"sequenceIndex":2421},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1961","text":"Such is the state of affairs which prevails among them. And often\r rulers and their subjects may come in one another’s way, whether on a\r journey or on some other occasion of meeting, on a pilgrimage or a\r march, as fellow-soldiers or fellow-sailors; aye and they may observe\r the behaviour of each other in the very moment of danger—for where\r danger is, there is no fear that the poor will be despised by the\r rich—and very likely the wiry sunburnt poor man may be placed in battle\r at the side of a wealthy one who has never spoilt his complexion and\r has plenty of superfluous flesh—when he sees ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1961"},"sequenceIndex":2422},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1962","text":"And, as in a body which is diseased the addition of a touch from\r without may bring on illness, and sometimes even when there is no\r external provocation a commotion may arise within—in the same way\r wherever there is weakness in the State there is also likely to be\r illness, of which the occasion may be very slight, the one party\r introducing from without their oligarchical, the other their\r democratical allies, and then the State falls sick, and is at war with\r herself; and may be at times distracted, even when there is no external\r cause.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1962"},"sequenceIndex":2423},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1963","text":"And then democracy comes into being after the poor have conquered their\r opponents, slaughtering some and banishing some, while to the remainder\r they give an equal share of freedom and power; and this is the form of\r government in which the magistrates are commonly elected by lot.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1963"},"sequenceIndex":2424},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1964","text":"Yes, he said, that is the nature of democracy, whether the revolution\r has been effected by arms, or whether fear has caused the opposite\r party to withdraw.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1964"},"sequenceIndex":2425},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1965","text":"And now what is their manner of life, and what sort of a government\r have they? for as the government is, such will be the man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1965"},"sequenceIndex":2426},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1966","text":"In the first place, are they not free; and is not the city full of\r freedom and frankness—a man may say and do what he likes?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1966"},"sequenceIndex":2427},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1967","text":"And where freedom is, the individual is clearly able to order for\r himself his own life as he pleases?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1967"},"sequenceIndex":2428},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1968","text":"Then in this kind of State there will be the greatest variety of human\r natures?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1968"},"sequenceIndex":2429},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1969","text":"This, then, seems likely to be the fairest of States, being like an\r embroidered robe which is spangled with every sort of flower. And just\r as women and children think a variety of colours to be of all things\r most charming, so there are many men to whom this State, which is\r spangled with the manners and characters of mankind, will appear to be\r the fairest of States.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1969"},"sequenceIndex":2430},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1970","text":"Yes, my good Sir, and there will be no better in which to look for a\r government.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1970"},"sequenceIndex":2431},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1971","text":"Because of the liberty which reigns there—they have a complete\r assortment of constitutions; and he who has a mind to establish a\r State, as we have been doing, must go to a democracy as he would to a\r bazaar at which they sell them, and pick out the one that suits him;\r then, when he has made his choice, he may found his State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1971"},"sequenceIndex":2432},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1972","text":"And there being no necessity, I said, for you to govern in this State,\r even if you have the capacity, or to be governed, unless you like, or\r go to war when the rest go to war, or to be at peace when others are at\r peace, unless you are so disposed—there being no necessity also,\r because some law forbids you to hold office or be a dicast, that you\r should not hold office or be a dicast, if you have a fancy—is not this\r a way of life which for the moment is supremely delightful?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1972"},"sequenceIndex":2433},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1973","text":"And is not their humanity to the condemned in some cases quite\r charming? Have you not observed how, in a democracy, many persons,\r although they have been sentenced to death or exile, just stay where\r they are and walk about the world—the gentleman parades like a hero,\r and nobody sees or cares?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1973"},"sequenceIndex":2434},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1974","text":"See too, I said, the forgiving spirit of democracy, and the ‘don’t\r care’ about trifles, and the disregard which she shows of all the fine\r principles which we solemnly laid down at the foundation of the city—as\r when we said that, except in the case of some rarely gifted nature,\r there never will be a good man who has not from his childhood been used\r to play amid things of beauty and make of them a joy and a study—how\r grandly does she trample all these fine notions of ours under her feet,\r never giving a thought to the pursuits which make a statesman, and\r promoting to honour any one who pr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1974"},"sequenceIndex":2435},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1975","text":"These and other kindred characteristics are proper to democracy, which\r is a charming form of government, full of variety and disorder, and\r dispensing a sort of equality to equals and unequals alike.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1975"},"sequenceIndex":2436},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1976","text":"Consider now, I said, what manner of man the individual is, or rather\r consider, as in the case of the State, how he comes into being.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1976"},"sequenceIndex":2437},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1977","text":"Is not this the way—he is the son of the miserly and oligarchical\r father who has trained him in his own habits?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1977"},"sequenceIndex":2438},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1978","text":"And, like his father, he keeps under by force the pleasures which are\r of the spending and not of the getting sort, being those which are\r called unnecessary?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1978"},"sequenceIndex":2439},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1979","text":"Would you like, for the sake of clearness, to distinguish which are the\r necessary and which are the unnecessary pleasures?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1979"},"sequenceIndex":2440},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1980","text":"Are not necessary pleasures those of which we cannot get rid, and of\r which the satisfaction is a benefit to us? And they are rightly called\r so, because we are framed by nature to desire both what is beneficial\r and what is necessary, and cannot help it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1980"},"sequenceIndex":2441},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1981","text":"And the desires of which a man may get rid, if he takes pains from his\r youth upwards—of which the presence, moreover, does no good, and in\r some cases the reverse of good—shall we not be right in saying that all\r these are unnecessary?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1981"},"sequenceIndex":2442},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1982","text":"Suppose we select an example of either kind, in order that we may have\r a general notion of them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1982"},"sequenceIndex":2443},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1983","text":"Will not the desire of eating, that is, of simple food and condiments,\r in so far as they are required for health and strength, be of the\r necessary class?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1983"},"sequenceIndex":2444},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1984","text":"The pleasure of eating is necessary in two ways; it does us good and it\r is essential to the continuance of life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1984"},"sequenceIndex":2445},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1985","text":"And the desire which goes beyond this, of more delicate food, or other\r luxuries, which might generally be got rid of, if controlled and\r trained in youth, and is hurtful to the body, and hurtful to the soul\r in the pursuit of wisdom and virtue, may be rightly called unnecessary?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1985"},"sequenceIndex":2446},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1986","text":"May we not say that these desires spend, and that the others make money\r because they conduce to production?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1986"},"sequenceIndex":2447},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1987","text":"And the drone of whom we spoke was he who was surfeited in pleasures\r and desires of this sort, and was the slave of the unnecessary desires,\r whereas he who was subject to the necessary only was miserly and\r oligarchical?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1987"},"sequenceIndex":2448},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1988","text":"Again, let us see how the democratical man grows out of the\r oligarchical: the following, as I suspect, is commonly the process.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1988"},"sequenceIndex":2449},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1989","text":"When a young man who has been brought up as we were just now\r describing, in a vulgar and miserly way, has tasted drones’ honey and\r has come to associate with fierce and crafty natures who are able to\r provide for him all sorts of refinements and varieties of\r pleasure—then, as you may imagine, the change will begin of the\r oligarchical principle within him into the democratical?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1989"},"sequenceIndex":2450},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1990","text":"And as in the city like was helping like, and the change was effected\r by an alliance from without assisting one division of the citizens, so\r too the young man is changed by a class of desires coming from without\r to assist the desires within him, that which is akin and alike again\r helping that which is akin and alike?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1990"},"sequenceIndex":2451},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1991","text":"And if there be any ally which aids the oligarchical principle within\r him, whether the influence of a father or of kindred, advising or\r rebuking him, then there arises in his soul a faction and an opposite\r faction, and he goes to war with himself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1991"},"sequenceIndex":2452},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1992","text":"And there are times when the democratical principle gives way to the\r oligarchical, and some of his desires die, and others are banished; a\r spirit of reverence enters into the young man’s soul and order is\r restored.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1992"},"sequenceIndex":2453},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1993","text":"And then, again, after the old desires have been driven out, fresh ones\r spring up, which are akin to them, and because he their father does not\r know how to educate them, wax fierce and numerous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1993"},"sequenceIndex":2454},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1994","text":"They draw him to his old associates, and holding secret intercourse\r with them, breed and multiply in him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1994"},"sequenceIndex":2455},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1995","text":"At length they seize upon the citadel of the young man’s soul, which\r they perceive to be void of all accomplishments and fair pursuits and\r true words, which make their abode in the minds of men who are dear to\r the gods, and are their best guardians and sentinels.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1995"},"sequenceIndex":2456},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1996","text":"And so the young man returns into the country of the lotus-eaters, and\r takes up his dwelling there in the face of all men; and if any help be\r sent by his friends to the oligarchical part of him, the aforesaid vain\r conceits shut the gate of the king’s fastness; and they will neither\r allow the embassy itself to enter, nor if private advisers offer the\r fatherly counsel of the aged will they listen to them or receive them.\r There is a battle and they gain the day, and then modesty, which they\r call silliness, is ignominiously thrust into exile by them, and\r temperance, which they nickname unm","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1996"},"sequenceIndex":2457},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1997","text":"And when they have emptied and swept clean the soul of him who is now\r in their power and who is being initiated by them in great mysteries,\r the next thing is to bring back to their house insolence and anarchy\r and waste and impudence in bright array having garlands on their heads,\r and a great company with them, hymning their praises and calling them\r by sweet names; insolence they term breeding, and anarchy liberty, and\r waste magnificence, and impudence courage. And so the young man passes\r out of his original nature, which was trained in the school of\r necessity, into the freedom and libe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1997"},"sequenceIndex":2458},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1998","text":"After this he lives on, spending his money and labour and time on\r unnecessary pleasures quite as much as on necessary ones; but if he be\r fortunate, and is not too much disordered in his wits, when years have\r elapsed, and the heyday of passion is over—supposing that he then\r re-admits into the city some part of the exiled virtues, and does not\r wholly give himself up to their successors—in that case he balances his\r pleasures and lives in a sort of equilibrium, putting the government of\r himself into the hands of the one which comes first and wins the turn;\r and when he has had enough of tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1998"},"sequenceIndex":2459},{"id":"plato-the-repu-1999","text":"Neither does he receive or let pass into the fortress any true word of\r advice; if any one says to him that some pleasures are the\r satisfactions of good and noble desires, and others of evil desires,\r and that he ought to use and honour some and chastise and master the\r others—whenever this is repeated to him he shakes his head and says\r that they are all alike, and that one is as good as another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"1999"},"sequenceIndex":2460},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2000","text":"Yes, I said, he lives from day to day indulging the appetite of the\r hour; and sometimes he is lapped in drink and strains of the flute;\r then he becomes a water-drinker, and tries to get thin; then he takes a\r turn at gymnastics; sometimes idling and neglecting everything, then\r once more living the life of a philosopher; often he is busy with\r politics, and starts to his feet and says and does whatever comes into\r his head; and, if he is emulous of any one who is a warrior, off he is\r in that direction, or of men of business, once more in that. His life\r has neither law nor order; and this d","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2000"},"sequenceIndex":2461},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2001","text":"Yes, I said; his life is motley and manifold and an epitome of the\r lives of many;—he answers to the State which we described as fair and\r spangled. And many a man and many a woman will take him for their\r pattern, and many a constitution and many an example of manners is\r contained in him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2001"},"sequenceIndex":2462},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2002","text":"Let him then be set over against democracy; he may truly be called the\r democratic man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2002"},"sequenceIndex":2463},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2003","text":"Last of all comes the most beautiful of all, man and State alike,\r tyranny and the tyrant; these we have now to consider.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2003"},"sequenceIndex":2464},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2004","text":"Say then, my friend, In what manner does tyranny arise?—that it has a\r democratic origin is evident.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2004"},"sequenceIndex":2465},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2005","text":"And does not tyranny spring from democracy in the same manner as\r democracy from oligarchy—I mean, after a sort?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2005"},"sequenceIndex":2466},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2006","text":"The good which oligarchy proposed to itself and the means by which it\r was maintained was excess of wealth—am I not right?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2006"},"sequenceIndex":2467},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2007","text":"And the insatiable desire of wealth and the neglect of all other things\r for the sake of money-getting was also the ruin of oligarchy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2007"},"sequenceIndex":2468},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2008","text":"And democracy has her own good, of which the insatiable desire brings\r her to dissolution?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2008"},"sequenceIndex":2469},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2009","text":"Freedom, I replied; which, as they tell you in a democracy, is the\r glory of the State—and that therefore in a democracy alone will the\r freeman of nature deign to dwell.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2009"},"sequenceIndex":2470},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2010","text":"I was going to observe, that the insatiable desire of this and the\r neglect of other things introduces the change in democracy, which\r occasions a demand for tyranny.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2010"},"sequenceIndex":2471},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2011","text":"When a democracy which is thirsting for freedom has evil cup-bearers\r presiding over the feast, and has drunk too deeply of the strong wine\r of freedom, then, unless her rulers are very amenable and give a\r plentiful draught, she calls them to account and punishes them, and\r says that they are cursed oligarchs.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2011"},"sequenceIndex":2472},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2012","text":"Yes, I said; and loyal citizens are insultingly termed by her slaves\r who hug their chains and men of naught; she would have subjects who are\r like rulers, and rulers who are like subjects: these are men after her\r own heart, whom she praises and honours both in private and public.\r Now, in such a State, can liberty have any limit?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2012"},"sequenceIndex":2473},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2013","text":"By degrees the anarchy finds a way into private houses, and ends by\r getting among the animals and infecting them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2013"},"sequenceIndex":2474},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2014","text":"I mean that the father grows accustomed to descend to the level of his\r sons and to fear them, and the son is on a level with his father, he\r having no respect or reverence for either of his parents; and this is\r his freedom, and the metic is equal with the citizen and the citizen\r with the metic, and the stranger is quite as good as either.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2014"},"sequenceIndex":2475},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2015","text":"And these are not the only evils, I said—there are several lesser ones:\r In such a state of society the master fears and flatters his scholars,\r and the scholars despise their masters and tutors; young and old are\r all alike; and the young man is on a level with the old, and is ready\r to compete with him in word or deed; and old men condescend to the\r young and are full of pleasantry and gaiety; they are loth to be\r thought morose and authoritative, and therefore they adopt the manners\r of the young.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2015"},"sequenceIndex":2476},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2016","text":"The last extreme of popular liberty is when the slave bought with\r money, whether male or female, is just as free as his or her purchaser;\r nor must I forget to tell of the liberty and equality of the two sexes\r in relation to each other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2016"},"sequenceIndex":2477},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2017","text":"That is what I am doing, I replied; and I must add that no one who does\r not know would believe, how much greater is the liberty which the\r animals who are under the dominion of man have in a democracy than in\r any other State: for truly, the she-dogs, as the proverb says, are as\r good as their she-mistresses, and the horses and asses have a way of\r marching along with all the rights and dignities of freemen; and they\r will run at any body who comes in their way if he does not leave the\r road clear for them: and all things are just ready to burst with\r liberty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2017"},"sequenceIndex":2478},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2018","text":"When I take a country walk, he said, I often experience what you\r describe. You and I have dreamed the same thing.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2018"},"sequenceIndex":2479},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2019","text":"And above all, I said, and as the result of all, see how sensitive the\r citizens become; they chafe impatiently at the least touch of\r authority, and at length, as you know, they cease to care even for the\r laws, written or unwritten; they will have no one over them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2019"},"sequenceIndex":2480},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2020","text":"Such, my friend, I said, is the fair and glorious beginning out of\r which springs tyranny.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2020"},"sequenceIndex":2481},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2021","text":"The ruin of oligarchy is the ruin of democracy; the same disease\r magnified and intensified by liberty overmasters democracy—the truth\r being that the excessive increase of anything often causes a reaction\r in the opposite direction; and this is the case not only in the seasons\r and in vegetable and animal life, but above all in forms of government.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2021"},"sequenceIndex":2482},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2022","text":"The excess of liberty, whether in States or individuals, seems only to\r pass into excess of slavery.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2022"},"sequenceIndex":2483},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2023","text":"And so tyranny naturally arises out of democracy, and the most\r aggravated form of tyranny and slavery out of the most extreme form of\r liberty?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2023"},"sequenceIndex":2484},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2024","text":"That, however, was not, as I believe, your question—you rather desired\r to know what is that disorder which is generated alike in oligarchy and\r democracy, and is the ruin of both?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2024"},"sequenceIndex":2485},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2025","text":"Well, I said, I meant to refer to the class of idle spendthrifts, of\r whom the more courageous are the leaders and the more timid the\r followers, the same whom we were comparing to drones, some stingless,\r and others having stings.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2025"},"sequenceIndex":2486},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2026","text":"These two classes are the plagues of every city in which they are\r generated, being what phlegm and bile are to the body. And the good\r physician and lawgiver of the State ought, like the wise bee-master, to\r keep them at a distance and prevent, if possible, their ever coming in;\r and if they have anyhow found a way in, then he should have them and\r their cells cut out as speedily as possible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2026"},"sequenceIndex":2487},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2027","text":"Then, in order that we may see clearly what we are doing, let us\r imagine democracy to be divided, as indeed it is, into three classes;\r for in the first place freedom creates rather more drones in the\r democratic than there were in the oligarchical State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2027"},"sequenceIndex":2488},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2028","text":"Because in the oligarchical State they are disqualified and driven from\r office, and therefore they cannot train or gather strength; whereas in\r a democracy they are almost the entire ruling power, and while the\r keener sort speak and act, the rest keep buzzing about the bema and do\r not suffer a word to be said on the other side; hence in democracies\r almost everything is managed by the drones.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2028"},"sequenceIndex":2489},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2029","text":"They are the orderly class, which in a nation of traders is sure to be\r the richest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2029"},"sequenceIndex":2490},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2030","text":"They are the most squeezable persons and yield the largest amount of\r honey to the drones.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2030"},"sequenceIndex":2491},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2031","text":"The people are a third class, consisting of those who work with their\r own hands; they are not politicians, and have not much to live upon.\r This, when assembled, is the largest and most powerful class in a\r democracy.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2031"},"sequenceIndex":2492},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2032","text":"True, he said; but then the multitude is seldom willing to congregate\r unless they get a little honey.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2032"},"sequenceIndex":2493},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2033","text":"And do they not share? I said. Do not their leaders deprive the rich of\r their estates and distribute them among the people; at the same time\r taking care to reserve the larger part for themselves?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2033"},"sequenceIndex":2494},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2034","text":"And the persons whose property is taken from them are compelled to\r defend themselves before the people as they best can?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2034"},"sequenceIndex":2495},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2035","text":"And then, although they may have no desire of change, the others charge\r them with plotting against the people and being friends of oligarchy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2035"},"sequenceIndex":2496},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2036","text":"And the end is that when they see the people, not of their own accord,\r but through ignorance, and because they are deceived by informers,\r seeking to do them wrong, then at last they are forced to become\r oligarchs in reality; they do not wish to be, but the sting of the\r drones torments them and breeds revolution in them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2036"},"sequenceIndex":2497},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2037","text":"The people have always some champion whom they set over them and nurse\r into greatness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2037"},"sequenceIndex":2498},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2038","text":"This and no other is the root from which a tyrant springs; when he\r first appears above ground he is a protector.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2038"},"sequenceIndex":2499},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2039","text":"How then does a protector begin to change into a tyrant? Clearly when\r he does what the man is said to do in the tale of the Arcadian temple\r of Lycaean Zeus.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2039"},"sequenceIndex":2500},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2040","text":"The tale is that he who has tasted the entrails of a single human\r victim minced up with the entrails of other victims is destined to\r become a wolf. Did you never hear it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2040"},"sequenceIndex":2501},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2041","text":"And the protector of the people is like him; having a mob entirely at\r his disposal, he is not restrained from shedding the blood of kinsmen;\r by the favourite method of false accusation he brings them into court\r and murders them, making the life of man to disappear, and with unholy\r tongue and lips tasting the blood of his fellow citizens; some he kills\r and others he banishes, at the same time hinting at the abolition of\r debts and partition of lands: and after this, what will be his destiny?\r Must he not either perish at the hands of his enemies, or from being a\r man become a wolf—that is,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2041"},"sequenceIndex":2502},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2042","text":"After a while he is driven out, but comes back, in spite of his\r enemies, a tyrant full grown.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2042"},"sequenceIndex":2503},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2043","text":"And if they are unable to expel him, or to get him condemned to death\r by a public accusation, they conspire to assassinate him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2043"},"sequenceIndex":2504},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2044","text":"Then comes the famous request for a body-guard, which is the device of\r all those who have got thus far in their tyrannical career—‘Let not the\r people’s friend,’ as they say, ‘be lost to them.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2044"},"sequenceIndex":2505},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2045","text":"The people readily assent; all their fears are for him—they have none\r for themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2045"},"sequenceIndex":2506},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2046","text":"And when a man who is wealthy and is also accused of being an enemy of\r the people sees this, then, my friend, as the oracle said to Croesus,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2046"},"sequenceIndex":2507},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2047","text":"‘By pebbly Hermus’ shore he flees and rests not, and is not ashamed to\r be a coward.’","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2047"},"sequenceIndex":2508},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2048","text":"And he, the protector of whom we spoke, is to be seen, not ‘larding the\r plain’ with his bulk, but himself the overthrower of many, standing up\r in the chariot of State with the reins in his hand, no longer\r protector, but tyrant absolute.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2048"},"sequenceIndex":2509},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2049","text":"And now let us consider the happiness of the man, and also of the State\r in which a creature like him is generated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2049"},"sequenceIndex":2510},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2050","text":"At first, in the early days of his power, he is full of smiles, and he\r salutes every one whom he meets;—he to be called a tyrant, who is\r making promises in public and also in private! liberating debtors, and\r distributing land to the people and his followers, and wanting to be so\r kind and good to every one!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2050"},"sequenceIndex":2511},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2051","text":"But when he has disposed of foreign enemies by conquest or treaty, and\r there is nothing to fear from them, then he is always stirring up some\r war or other, in order that the people may require a leader.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2051"},"sequenceIndex":2512},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2052","text":"Has he not also another object, which is that they may be impoverished\r by payment of taxes, and thus compelled to devote themselves to their\r daily wants and therefore less likely to conspire against him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2052"},"sequenceIndex":2513},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2053","text":"And if any of them are suspected by him of having notions of freedom,\r and of resistance to his authority, he will have a good pretext for\r destroying them by placing them at the mercy of the enemy; and for all\r these reasons the tyrant must be always getting up a war.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2053"},"sequenceIndex":2514},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2054","text":"Then some of those who joined in setting him up, and who are in power,\r speak their minds to him and to one another, and the more courageous of\r them cast in his teeth what is being done.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2054"},"sequenceIndex":2515},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2055","text":"And the tyrant, if he means to rule, must get rid of them; he cannot\r stop while he has a friend or an enemy who is good for anything.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2055"},"sequenceIndex":2516},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2056","text":"And therefore he must look about him and see who is valiant, who is\r high-minded, who is wise, who is wealthy; happy man, he is the enemy of\r them all, and must seek occasion against them whether he will or no,\r until he has made a purgation of the State.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2056"},"sequenceIndex":2517},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2057","text":"Yes, I said, not the sort of purgation which the physicians make of the\r body; for they take away the worse and leave the better part, but he\r does the reverse.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2057"},"sequenceIndex":2518},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2058","text":"What a blessed alternative, I said:—to be compelled to dwell only with\r the many bad, and to be by them hated, or not to live at all!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2058"},"sequenceIndex":2519},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2059","text":"And the more detestable his actions are to the citizens the more\r satellites and the greater devotion in them will he require?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2059"},"sequenceIndex":2520},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2060","text":"He will rob the citizens of their slaves; he will then set them free\r and enrol them in his body-guard.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2060"},"sequenceIndex":2521},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2061","text":"What a blessed creature, I said, must this tyrant be; he has put to\r death the others and has these for his trusted friends.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2061"},"sequenceIndex":2522},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2062","text":"Yes, I said, and these are the new citizens whom he has called into\r existence, who admire him and are his companions, while the good hate\r and avoid him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2062"},"sequenceIndex":2523},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2063","text":"and he clearly meant to say that they are the wise whom the tyrant\r makes his companions.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2063"},"sequenceIndex":2524},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2064","text":"Yes, he said, and he also praises tyranny as godlike; and many other\r things of the same kind are said by him and by the other poets.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2064"},"sequenceIndex":2525},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2065","text":"And therefore, I said, the tragic poets being wise men will forgive us\r and any others who live after our manner if we do not receive them into\r our State, because they are the eulogists of tyranny.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2065"},"sequenceIndex":2526},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2066","text":"But they will continue to go to other cities and attract mobs, and hire\r voices fair and loud and persuasive, and draw the cities over to\r tyrannies and democracies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2066"},"sequenceIndex":2527},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2067","text":"Moreover, they are paid for this and receive honour—the greatest\r honour, as might be expected, from tyrants, and the next greatest from\r democracies; but the higher they ascend our constitution hill, the more\r their reputation fails, and seems unable from shortness of breath to\r proceed further.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2067"},"sequenceIndex":2528},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2068","text":"But we are wandering from the subject: Let us therefore return and\r enquire how the tyrant will maintain that fair and numerous and various\r and ever-changing army of his.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2068"},"sequenceIndex":2529},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2069","text":"If, he said, there are sacred treasures in the city, he will confiscate\r and spend them; and in so far as the fortunes of attainted persons may\r suffice, he will be able to diminish the taxes which he would otherwise\r have to impose upon the people.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2069"},"sequenceIndex":2530},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2070","text":"Why, clearly, he said, then he and his boon companions, whether male or\r female, will be maintained out of his father’s estate.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2070"},"sequenceIndex":2531},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2071","text":"You mean to say that the people, from whom he has derived his being,\r will maintain him and his companions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2071"},"sequenceIndex":2532},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2072","text":"But what if the people fly into a passion, and aver that a grown-up son\r ought not to be supported by his father, but that the father should be\r supported by the son? The father did not bring him into being, or\r settle him in life, in order that when his son became a man he should\r himself be the servant of his own servants and should support him and\r his rabble of slaves and companions; but that his son should protect\r him, and that by his help he might be emancipated from the government\r of the rich and aristocratic, as they are termed. And so he bids him\r and his companions depart, just as ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2072"},"sequenceIndex":2533},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2073","text":"By heaven, he said, then the parent will discover what a monster he has\r been fostering in his bosom; and, when he wants to drive him out, he\r will find that he is weak and his son strong.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2073"},"sequenceIndex":2534},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2074","text":"Why, you do not mean to say that the tyrant will use violence? What!\r beat his father if he opposes him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2074"},"sequenceIndex":2535},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2075","text":"Then he is a parricide, and a cruel guardian of an aged parent; and\r this is real tyranny, about which there can be no longer a mistake: as\r the saying is, the people who would escape the smoke which is the\r slavery of freemen, has fallen into the fire which is the tyranny of\r slaves. Thus liberty, getting out of all order and reason, passes into\r the harshest and bitterest form of slavery.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2075"},"sequenceIndex":2536},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2076","text":"Very well; and may we not rightly say that we have sufficiently\r discussed the nature of tyranny, and the manner of the transition from\r democracy to tyranny?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2076"},"sequenceIndex":2537},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2077","text":"Last of all comes the tyrannical man; about whom we have once more to\r ask, how is he formed out of the democratical? and how does he live, in\r happiness or in misery?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2077"},"sequenceIndex":2538},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2078","text":"I do not think that we have adequately determined the nature and number\r of the appetites, and until this is accomplished the enquiry will\r always be confused.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2078"},"sequenceIndex":2539},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2079","text":"Very true, I said; and observe the point which I want to understand:\r Certain of the unnecessary pleasures and appetites I conceive to be\r unlawful; every one appears to have them, but in some persons they are\r controlled by the laws and by reason, and the better desires prevail\r over them—either they are wholly banished or they become few and weak;\r while in the case of others they are stronger, and there are more of\r them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2079"},"sequenceIndex":2540},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2080","text":"I mean those which are awake when the reasoning and human and ruling\r power is asleep; then the wild beast within us, gorged with meat or\r drink, starts up and having shaken off sleep, goes forth to satisfy his\r desires; and there is no conceivable folly or crime—not excepting\r incest or any other unnatural union, or parricide, or the eating of\r forbidden food—which at such a time, when he has parted company with\r all shame and sense, a man may not be ready to commit.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2080"},"sequenceIndex":2541},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2081","text":"But when a man’s pulse is healthy and temperate, and when before going\r to sleep he has awakened his rational powers, and fed them on noble\r thoughts and enquiries, collecting himself in meditation; after having\r first indulged his appetites neither too much nor too little, but just\r enough to lay them to sleep, and prevent them and their enjoyments and\r pains from interfering with the higher principle—which he leaves in the\r solitude of pure abstraction, free to contemplate and aspire to the\r knowledge of the unknown, whether in past, present, or future: when\r again he has allayed the passion","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2081"},"sequenceIndex":2542},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2082","text":"In saying this I have been running into a digression; but the point\r which I desire to note is that in all of us, even in good men, there is\r a lawless wild-beast nature, which peers out in sleep. Pray, consider\r whether I am right, and you agree with me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2082"},"sequenceIndex":2543},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2083","text":"And now remember the character which we attributed to the democratic\r man. He was supposed from his youth upwards to have been trained under\r a miserly parent, who encouraged the saving appetites in him, but\r discountenanced the unnecessary, which aim only at amusement and\r ornament?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2083"},"sequenceIndex":2544},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2084","text":"And then he got into the company of a more refined, licentious sort of\r people, and taking to all their wanton ways rushed into the opposite\r extreme from an abhorrence of his father’s meanness. At last, being a\r better man than his corruptors, he was drawn in both directions until\r he halted midway and led a life, not of vulgar and slavish passion, but\r of what he deemed moderate indulgence in various pleasures. After this\r manner the democrat was generated out of the oligarch?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2084"},"sequenceIndex":2545},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2085","text":"And now, I said, years will have passed away, and you must conceive\r this man, such as he is, to have a son, who is brought up in his\r father’s principles.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2085"},"sequenceIndex":2546},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2086","text":"Then you must further imagine the same thing to happen to the son which\r has already happened to the father:—he is drawn into a perfectly\r lawless life, which by his seducers is termed perfect liberty; and his\r father and friends take part with his moderate desires, and the\r opposite party assist the opposite ones. As soon as these dire\r magicians and tyrant-makers find that they are losing their hold on\r him, they contrive to implant in him a master passion, to be lord over\r his idle and spendthrift lusts—a sort of monstrous winged drone—that is\r the only image which will adequately describe ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2086"},"sequenceIndex":2547},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2087","text":"And when his other lusts, amid clouds of incense and perfumes and\r garlands and wines, and all the pleasures of a dissolute life, now let\r loose, come buzzing around him, nourishing to the utmost the sting of\r desire which they implant in his drone-like nature, then at last this\r lord of the soul, having Madness for the captain of his guard, breaks\r out into a frenzy: and if he finds in himself any good opinions or\r appetites in process of formation, and there is in him any sense of\r shame remaining, to these better principles he puts an end, and casts\r them forth until he has purged away temp","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2087"},"sequenceIndex":2548},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2088","text":"And you know that a man who is deranged and not right in his mind, will\r fancy that he is able to rule, not only over men, but also over the\r gods?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2088"},"sequenceIndex":2549},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2089","text":"And the tyrannical man in the true sense of the word comes into being\r when, either under the influence of nature, or habit, or both, he\r becomes drunken, lustful, passionate? O my friend, is not that so?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2089"},"sequenceIndex":2550},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2090","text":"I imagine, I said, at the next step in his progress, that there will be\r feasts and carousals and revellings and courtezans, and all that sort\r of thing; Love is the lord of the house within him, and orders all the\r concerns of his soul.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2090"},"sequenceIndex":2551},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2091","text":"Yes; and every day and every night desires grow up many and formidable,\r and their demands are many.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2091"},"sequenceIndex":2552},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2092","text":"When he has nothing left, must not his desires, crowding in the nest\r like young ravens, be crying aloud for food; and he, goaded on by them,\r and especially by love himself, who is in a manner the captain of them,\r is in a frenzy, and would fain discover whom he can defraud or despoil\r of his property, in order that he may gratify them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2092"},"sequenceIndex":2553},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2093","text":"And as in himself there was a succession of pleasures, and the new got\r the better of the old and took away their rights, so he being younger\r will claim to have more than his father and his mother, and if he has\r spent his own share of the property, he will take a slice of theirs.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2093"},"sequenceIndex":2554},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2094","text":"And if his parents will not give way, then he will try first of all to\r cheat and deceive them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2094"},"sequenceIndex":2555},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2095","text":"And if the old man and woman fight for their own, what then, my friend?\r Will the creature feel any compunction at tyrannizing over them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2095"},"sequenceIndex":2556},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2096","text":"But, O heavens! Adeimantus, on account of some new-fangled love of a\r harlot, who is anything but a necessary connection, can you believe\r that he would strike the mother who is his ancient friend and necessary\r to his very existence, and would place her under the authority of the\r other, when she is brought under the same roof with her; or that, under\r like circumstances, he would do the same to his withered old father,\r first and most indispensable of friends, for the sake of some\r newly-found blooming youth who is the reverse of indispensable?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2096"},"sequenceIndex":2557},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2097","text":"He first takes their property, and when that fails, and pleasures are\r beginning to swarm in the hive of his soul, then he breaks into a\r house, or steals the garments of some nightly wayfarer; next he\r proceeds to clear a temple. Meanwhile the old opinions which he had\r when a child, and which gave judgment about good and evil, are\r overthrown by those others which have just been emancipated, and are\r now the body-guard of love and share his empire. These in his\r democratic days, when he was still subject to the laws and to his\r father, were only let loose in the dreams of sleep. But now that","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2097"},"sequenceIndex":2558},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2098","text":"And if there are only a few of them in the State, and the rest of the\r people are well disposed, they go away and become the body-guard or\r mercenary soldiers of some other tyrant who may probably want them for\r a war; and if there is no war, they stay at home and do many little\r pieces of mischief in the city.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2098"},"sequenceIndex":2559},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2099","text":"For example, they are the thieves, burglars, cut-purses, foot-pads,\r robbers of temples, man-stealers of the community; or if they are able\r to speak they turn informers, and bear false witness, and take bribes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2099"},"sequenceIndex":2560},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2100","text":"A small catalogue of evils, even if the perpetrators of them are few in\r number.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2100"},"sequenceIndex":2561},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2101","text":"Yes, I said; but small and great are comparative terms, and all these\r things, in the misery and evil which they inflict upon a State, do not\r come within a thousand miles of the tyrant; when this noxious class and\r their followers grow numerous and become conscious of their strength,\r assisted by the infatuation of the people, they choose from among\r themselves the one who has most of the tyrant in his own soul, and him\r they create their tyrant.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2101"},"sequenceIndex":2562},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2102","text":"If the people yield, well and good; but if they resist him, as he began\r by beating his own father and mother, so now, if he has the power, he\r beats them, and will keep his dear old fatherland or motherland, as the\r Cretans say, in subjection to his young retainers whom he has\r introduced to be their rulers and masters. This is the end of his\r passions and desires.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2102"},"sequenceIndex":2563},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2103","text":"When such men are only private individuals and before they get power,\r this is their character; they associate entirely with their own\r flatterers or ready tools; or if they want anything from anybody, they\r in their turn are equally ready to bow down before them: they profess\r every sort of affection for them; but when they have gained their point\r they know them no more.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2103"},"sequenceIndex":2564},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2104","text":"They are always either the masters or servants and never the friends of\r anybody; the tyrant never tastes of true freedom or friendship.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2104"},"sequenceIndex":2565},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2105","text":"Let us then sum up in a word, I said, the character of the worst man:\r he is the waking reality of what we dreamed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2105"},"sequenceIndex":2566},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2106","text":"And this is he who being by nature most of a tyrant bears rule, and the\r longer he lives the more of a tyrant he becomes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2106"},"sequenceIndex":2567},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2107","text":"And will not he who has been shown to be the wickedest, be also the\r most miserable? and he who has tyrannized longest and most, most\r continually and truly miserable; although this may not be the opinion\r of men in general?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2107"},"sequenceIndex":2568},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2108","text":"And must not the tyrannical man be like the tyrannical State, and the\r democratical man like the democratical State; and the same of the\r others?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2108"},"sequenceIndex":2569},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2109","text":"And as State is to State in virtue and happiness, so is man in relation\r to man?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2109"},"sequenceIndex":2570},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2110","text":"Then comparing our original city, which was under a king, and the city\r which is under a tyrant, how do they stand as to virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2110"},"sequenceIndex":2571},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2111","text":"They are the opposite extremes, he said, for one is the very best and\r the other is the very worst.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2111"},"sequenceIndex":2572},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2112","text":"There can be no mistake, I said, as to which is which, and therefore I\r will at once enquire whether you would arrive at a similar decision\r about their relative happiness and misery. And here we must not allow\r ourselves to be panic-stricken at the apparition of the tyrant, who is\r only a unit and may perhaps have a few retainers about him; but let us\r go as we ought into every corner of the city and look all about, and\r then we will give our opinion.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2112"},"sequenceIndex":2573},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2113","text":"A fair invitation, he replied; and I see, as every one must, that a\r tyranny is the wretchedest form of government, and the rule of a king\r the happiest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2113"},"sequenceIndex":2574},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2114","text":"And in estimating the men too, may I not fairly make a like request,\r that I should have a judge whose mind can enter into and see through\r human nature? he must not be like a child who looks at the outside and\r is dazzled at the pompous aspect which the tyrannical nature assumes to\r the beholder, but let him be one who has a clear insight. May I suppose\r that the judgment is given in the hearing of us all by one who is able\r to judge, and has dwelt in the same place with him, and been present at\r his dally life and known him in his family relations, where he may be\r seen stripped of his trage","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2114"},"sequenceIndex":2575},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2115","text":"Shall I assume that we ourselves are able and experienced judges and\r have before now met with such a person? We shall then have some one who\r will answer our enquiries.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2115"},"sequenceIndex":2576},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2116","text":"Let me ask you not to forget the parallel of the individual and the\r State; bearing this in mind, and glancing in turn from one to the other\r of them, will you tell me their respective conditions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2116"},"sequenceIndex":2577},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2117","text":"Beginning with the State, I replied, would you say that a city which is\r governed by a tyrant is free or enslaved?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2117"},"sequenceIndex":2578},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2118","text":"Yes, he said, I see that there are—a few; but the people, speaking\r generally, and the best of them are miserably degraded and enslaved.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2118"},"sequenceIndex":2579},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2119","text":"Then if the man is like the State, I said, must not the same rule\r prevail? his soul is full of meanness and vulgarity—the best elements\r in him are enslaved; and there is a small ruling part, which is also\r the worst and maddest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2119"},"sequenceIndex":2580},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2120","text":"And would you say that the soul of such an one is the soul of a\r freeman, or of a slave?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2120"},"sequenceIndex":2581},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2121","text":"And the State which is enslaved under a tyrant is utterly incapable of\r acting voluntarily?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2121"},"sequenceIndex":2582},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2122","text":"And also the soul which is under a tyrant (I am speaking of the soul\r taken as a whole) is least capable of doing what she desires; there is\r a gadfly which goads her, and she is full of trouble and remorse?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2122"},"sequenceIndex":2583},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2123","text":"Is there any State in which you will find more of lamentation and\r sorrow and groaning and pain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2123"},"sequenceIndex":2584},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2124","text":"And is there any man in whom you will find more of this sort of misery\r than in the tyrannical man, who is in a fury of passions and desires?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2124"},"sequenceIndex":2585},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2125","text":"Reflecting upon these and similar evils, you held the tyrannical State\r to be the most miserable of States?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2125"},"sequenceIndex":2586},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2126","text":"Certainly, I said. And when you see the same evils in the tyrannical\r man, what do you say of him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2126"},"sequenceIndex":2587},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2127","text":"He who is of a tyrannical nature, and instead of leading a private life\r has been cursed with the further misfortune of being a public tyrant.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2127"},"sequenceIndex":2588},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2128","text":"Yes, I replied, but in this high argument you should be a little more\r certain, and should not conjecture only; for of all questions, this\r respecting good and evil is the greatest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2128"},"sequenceIndex":2589},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2129","text":"Let me then offer you an illustration, which may, I think, throw a\r light upon this subject.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2129"},"sequenceIndex":2590},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2130","text":"The case of rich individuals in cities who possess many slaves: from\r them you may form an idea of the tyrant’s condition, for they both have\r slaves; the only difference is that he has more slaves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2130"},"sequenceIndex":2591},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2131","text":"You know that they live securely and have nothing to apprehend from\r their servants?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2131"},"sequenceIndex":2592},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2132","text":"Yes; the reason is, that the whole city is leagued together for the\r protection of each individual.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2132"},"sequenceIndex":2593},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2133","text":"Very true, I said. But imagine one of these owners, the master say of\r some fifty slaves, together with his family and property and slaves,\r carried off by a god into the wilderness, where there are no freemen to\r help him—will he not be in an agony of fear lest he and his wife and\r children should be put to death by his slaves?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2133"},"sequenceIndex":2594},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2134","text":"The time has arrived when he will be compelled to flatter divers of his\r slaves, and make many promises to them of freedom and other things,\r much against his will—he will have to cajole his own servants.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2134"},"sequenceIndex":2595},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2135","text":"And suppose the same god, who carried him away, to surround him with\r neighbours who will not suffer one man to be the master of another, and\r who, if they could catch the offender, would take his life?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2135"},"sequenceIndex":2596},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2136","text":"His case will be still worse, if you suppose him to be everywhere\r surrounded and watched by enemies.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2136"},"sequenceIndex":2597},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2137","text":"And is not this the sort of prison in which the tyrant will be bound—he\r who being by nature such as we have described, is full of all sorts of\r fears and lusts? His soul is dainty and greedy, and yet alone, of all\r men in the city, he is never allowed to go on a journey, or to see the\r things which other freemen desire to see, but he lives in his hole like\r a woman hidden in the house, and is jealous of any other citizen who\r goes into foreign parts and sees anything of interest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2137"},"sequenceIndex":2598},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2138","text":"And amid evils such as these will not he who is ill-governed in his own\r person—the tyrannical man, I mean—whom you just now decided to be the\r most miserable of all—will not he be yet more miserable when, instead\r of leading a private life, he is constrained by fortune to be a public\r tyrant? He has to be master of others when he is not master of himself:\r he is like a diseased or paralytic man who is compelled to pass his\r life, not in retirement, but fighting and combating with other men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2138"},"sequenceIndex":2599},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2139","text":"Is not his case utterly miserable? and does not the actual tyrant lead\r a worse life than he whose life you determined to be the worst?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2139"},"sequenceIndex":2600},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2140","text":"He who is the real tyrant, whatever men may think, is the real slave,\r and is obliged to practise the greatest adulation and servility, and to\r be the flatterer of the vilest of mankind. He has desires which he is\r utterly unable to satisfy, and has more wants than any one, and is\r truly poor, if you know how to inspect the whole soul of him: all his\r life long he is beset with fear and is full of convulsions and\r distractions, even as the State which he resembles: and surely the\r resemblance holds?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2140"},"sequenceIndex":2601},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2141","text":"Moreover, as we were saying before, he grows worse from having power:\r he becomes and is of necessity more jealous, more faithless, more\r unjust, more friendless, more impious, than he was at first; he is the\r purveyor and cherisher of every sort of vice, and the consequence is\r that he is supremely miserable, and that he makes everybody else as\r miserable as himself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2141"},"sequenceIndex":2602},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2142","text":"Come then, I said, and as the general umpire in theatrical contests\r proclaims the result, do you also decide who in your opinion is first\r in the scale of happiness, and who second, and in what order the others\r follow: there are five of them in all—they are the royal, timocratical,\r oligarchical, democratical, tyrannical.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2142"},"sequenceIndex":2603},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2143","text":"The decision will be easily given, he replied; they shall be choruses\r coming on the stage, and I must judge them in the order in which they\r enter, by the criterion of virtue and vice, happiness and misery.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2143"},"sequenceIndex":2604},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2144","text":"Need we hire a herald, or shall I announce, that the son of Ariston\r (the best) has decided that the best and justest is also the happiest,\r and that this is he who is the most royal man and king over himself;\r and that the worst and most unjust man is also the most miserable, and\r that this is he who being the greatest tyrant of himself is also the\r greatest tyrant of his State?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2144"},"sequenceIndex":2605},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2145","text":"Then this, I said, will be our first proof; and there is another, which\r may also have some weight.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2145"},"sequenceIndex":2606},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2146","text":"The second proof is derived from the nature of the soul: seeing that\r the individual soul, like the State, has been divided by us into three\r principles, the division may, I think, furnish a new demonstration.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2146"},"sequenceIndex":2607},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2147","text":"It seems to me that to these three principles three pleasures\r correspond; also three desires and governing powers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2147"},"sequenceIndex":2608},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2148","text":"There is one principle with which, as we were saying, a man learns,\r another with which he is angry; the third, having many forms, has no\r special name, but is denoted by the general term appetitive, from the\r extraordinary strength and vehemence of the desires of eating and\r drinking and the other sensual appetites which are the main elements of\r it; also money-loving, because such desires are generally satisfied by\r the help of money.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2148"},"sequenceIndex":2609},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2149","text":"If we were to say that the loves and pleasures of this third part were\r concerned with gain, we should then be able to fall back on a single\r notion; and might truly and intelligibly describe this part of the soul\r as loving gain or money.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2149"},"sequenceIndex":2610},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2150","text":"Again, is not the passionate element wholly set on ruling and\r conquering and getting fame?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2150"},"sequenceIndex":2611},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2151","text":"On the other hand, every one sees that the principle of knowledge is\r wholly directed to the truth, and cares less than either of the others\r for gain or fame.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2151"},"sequenceIndex":2612},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2152","text":"‘Lover of wisdom,’ ‘lover of knowledge,’ are titles which we may fitly\r apply to that part of the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2152"},"sequenceIndex":2613},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2153","text":"One principle prevails in the souls of one class of men, another in\r others, as may happen?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2153"},"sequenceIndex":2614},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2154","text":"Then we may begin by assuming that there are three classes of\r men—lovers of wisdom, lovers of honour, lovers of gain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2154"},"sequenceIndex":2615},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2155","text":"Now, if you examine the three classes of men, and ask of them in turn\r which of their lives is pleasantest, each will be found praising his\r own and depreciating that of others: the money-maker will contrast the\r vanity of honour or of learning if they bring no money with the solid\r advantages of gold and silver?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2155"},"sequenceIndex":2616},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2156","text":"And the lover of honour—what will be his opinion? Will he not think\r that the pleasure of riches is vulgar, while the pleasure of learning,\r if it brings no distinction, is all smoke and nonsense to him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2156"},"sequenceIndex":2617},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2157","text":"And are we to suppose, I said, that the philosopher sets any value on\r other pleasures in comparison with the pleasure of knowing the truth,\r and in that pursuit abiding, ever learning, not so far indeed from the\r heaven of pleasure? Does he not call the other pleasures necessary,\r under the idea that if there were no necessity for them, he would\r rather not have them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2157"},"sequenceIndex":2618},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2158","text":"Since, then, the pleasures of each class and the life of each are in\r dispute, and the question is not which life is more or less honourable,\r or better or worse, but which is the more pleasant or painless—how\r shall we know who speaks truly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2158"},"sequenceIndex":2619},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2159","text":"Well, but what ought to be the criterion? Is any better than experience\r and wisdom and reason?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2159"},"sequenceIndex":2620},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2160","text":"Then, I said, reflect. Of the three individuals, which has the greatest\r experience of all the pleasures which we enumerated? Has the lover of\r gain, in learning the nature of essential truth, greater experience of\r the pleasure of knowledge than the philosopher has of the pleasure of\r gain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2160"},"sequenceIndex":2621},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2161","text":"The philosopher, he replied, has greatly the advantage; for he has of\r necessity always known the taste of the other pleasures from his\r childhood upwards: but the lover of gain in all his experience has not\r of necessity tasted—or, I should rather say, even had he desired, could\r hardly have tasted—the sweetness of learning and knowing truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2161"},"sequenceIndex":2622},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2162","text":"Then the lover of wisdom has a great advantage over the lover of gain,\r for he has a double experience?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2162"},"sequenceIndex":2623},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2163","text":"Again, has he greater experience of the pleasures of honour, or the\r lover of honour of the pleasures of wisdom?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2163"},"sequenceIndex":2624},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2164","text":"Nay, he said, all three are honoured in proportion as they attain their\r object; for the rich man and the brave man and the wise man alike have\r their crowd of admirers, and as they all receive honour they all have\r experience of the pleasures of honour; but the delight which is to be\r found in the knowledge of true being is known to the philosopher only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2164"},"sequenceIndex":2625},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2165","text":"Further, the very faculty which is the instrument of judgment is not\r possessed by the covetous or ambitious man, but only by the\r philosopher?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2165"},"sequenceIndex":2626},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2166","text":"If wealth and gain were the criterion, then the praise or blame of the\r lover of gain would surely be the most trustworthy?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2166"},"sequenceIndex":2627},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2167","text":"Or if honour or victory or courage, in that case the judgment of the\r ambitious or pugnacious would be the truest?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2167"},"sequenceIndex":2628},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2168","text":"The only inference possible, he replied, is that pleasures which are\r approved by the lover of wisdom and reason are the truest.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2168"},"sequenceIndex":2629},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2169","text":"And so we arrive at the result, that the pleasure of the intelligent\r part of the soul is the pleasantest of the three, and that he of us in\r whom this is the ruling principle has the pleasantest life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2169"},"sequenceIndex":2630},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2170","text":"Unquestionably, he said, the wise man speaks with authority when he\r approves of his own life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2170"},"sequenceIndex":2631},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2171","text":"And what does the judge affirm to be the life which is next, and the\r pleasure which is next?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2171"},"sequenceIndex":2632},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2172","text":"Clearly that of the soldier and lover of honour; who is nearer to\r himself than the money-maker.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2172"},"sequenceIndex":2633},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2173","text":"Twice in succession, then, has the just man overthrown the unjust in\r this conflict; and now comes the third trial, which is dedicated to\r Olympian Zeus the saviour: a sage whispers in my ear that no pleasure\r except that of the wise is quite true and pure—all others are a shadow\r only; and surely this will prove the greatest and most decisive of\r falls?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2173"},"sequenceIndex":2634},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2174","text":"A state which is intermediate, and a sort of repose of the soul about\r either—that is what you mean?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2174"},"sequenceIndex":2635},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2175","text":"That after all nothing is pleasanter than health. But then they never\r knew this to be the greatest of pleasures until they were ill.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2175"},"sequenceIndex":2636},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2176","text":"And when persons are suffering from acute pain, you must have heard\r them say that there is nothing pleasanter than to get rid of their\r pain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2176"},"sequenceIndex":2637},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2177","text":"And there are many other cases of suffering in which the mere rest and\r cessation of pain, and not any positive enjoyment, is extolled by them\r as the greatest pleasure?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2177"},"sequenceIndex":2638},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2178","text":"But that which is neither was just now shown to be rest and not motion,\r and in a mean between them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2178"},"sequenceIndex":2639},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2179","text":"How, then, can we be right in supposing that the absence of pain is\r pleasure, or that the absence of pleasure is pain?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2179"},"sequenceIndex":2640},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2180","text":"This then is an appearance only and not a reality; that is to say, the\r rest is pleasure at the moment and in comparison of what is painful,\r and painful in comparison of what is pleasant; but all these\r representations, when tried by the test of true pleasure, are not real\r but a sort of imposition?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2180"},"sequenceIndex":2641},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2181","text":"Look at the other class of pleasures which have no antecedent pains and\r you will no longer suppose, as you perhaps may at present, that\r pleasure is only the cessation of pain, or pain of pleasure.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2181"},"sequenceIndex":2642},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2182","text":"There are many of them: take as an example the pleasures of smell,\r which are very great and have no antecedent pains; they come in a\r moment, and when they depart leave no pain behind them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2182"},"sequenceIndex":2643},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2183","text":"Let us not, then, be induced to believe that pure pleasure is the\r cessation of pain, or pain of pleasure.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2183"},"sequenceIndex":2644},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2184","text":"Still, the more numerous and violent pleasures which reach the soul\r through the body are generally of this sort—they are reliefs of pain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2184"},"sequenceIndex":2645},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2185","text":"You would allow, I said, that there is in nature an upper and lower and\r middle region?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2185"},"sequenceIndex":2646},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2186","text":"And if a person were to go from the lower to the middle region, would\r he not imagine that he is going up; and he who is standing in the\r middle and sees whence he has come, would imagine that he is already in\r the upper region, if he has never seen the true upper world?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2186"},"sequenceIndex":2647},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2187","text":"But if he were taken back again he would imagine, and truly imagine,\r that he was descending?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2187"},"sequenceIndex":2648},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2188","text":"All that would arise out of his ignorance of the true upper and middle\r and lower regions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2188"},"sequenceIndex":2649},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2189","text":"Then can you wonder that persons who are inexperienced in the truth, as\r they have wrong ideas about many other things, should also have wrong\r ideas about pleasure and pain and the intermediate state; so that when\r they are only being drawn towards the painful they feel pain and think\r the pain which they experience to be real, and in like manner, when\r drawn away from pain to the neutral or intermediate state, they firmly\r believe that they have reached the goal of satiety and pleasure; they,\r not knowing pleasure, err in contrasting pain with the absence of pain,\r which is like contrasting ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2189"},"sequenceIndex":2650},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2190","text":"Look at the matter thus:—Hunger, thirst, and the like, are inanitions\r of the bodily state?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2190"},"sequenceIndex":2651},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2191","text":"And is the satisfaction derived from that which has less or from that\r which has more existence the truer?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2191"},"sequenceIndex":2652},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2192","text":"What classes of things have a greater share of pure existence in your\r judgment—those of which food and drink and condiments and all kinds of\r sustenance are examples, or the class which contains true opinion and\r knowledge and mind and all the different kinds of virtue? Put the\r question in this way:—Which has a more pure being—that which is\r concerned with the invariable, the immortal, and the true, and is of\r such a nature, and is found in such natures; or that which is concerned\r with and found in the variable and mortal, and is itself variable and\r mortal?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2192"},"sequenceIndex":2653},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2193","text":"Far purer, he replied, is the being of that which is concerned with the\r invariable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2193"},"sequenceIndex":2654},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2194","text":"And does the essence of the invariable partake of knowledge in the same\r degree as of essence?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2194"},"sequenceIndex":2655},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2195","text":"Then, in general, those kinds of things which are in the service of the\r body have less of truth and essence than those which are in the service\r of the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2195"},"sequenceIndex":2656},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2196","text":"What is filled with more real existence, and actually has a more real\r existence, is more really filled than that which is filled with less\r real existence and is less real?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2196"},"sequenceIndex":2657},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2197","text":"And if there be a pleasure in being filled with that which is according\r to nature, that which is more really filled with more real being will\r more really and truly enjoy true pleasure; whereas that which\r participates in less real being will be less truly and surely\r satisfied, and will participate in an illusory and less real pleasure?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2197"},"sequenceIndex":2658},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2198","text":"Those then who know not wisdom and virtue, and are always busy with\r gluttony and sensuality, go down and up again as far as the mean; and\r in this region they move at random throughout life, but they never pass\r into the true upper world; thither they neither look, nor do they ever\r find their way, neither are they truly filled with true being, nor do\r they taste of pure and abiding pleasure. Like cattle, with their eyes\r always looking down and their heads stooping to the earth, that is, to\r the dining-table, they fatten and feed and breed, and, in their\r excessive love of these delights, th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2198"},"sequenceIndex":2659},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2199","text":"Verily, Socrates, said Glaucon, you describe the life of the many like\r an oracle.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2199"},"sequenceIndex":2660},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2200","text":"Their pleasures are mixed with pains—how can they be otherwise? For\r they are mere shadows and pictures of the true, and are coloured by\r contrast, which exaggerates both light and shade, and so they implant\r in the minds of fools insane desires of themselves; and they are fought\r about as Stesichorus says that the Greeks fought about the shadow of\r Helen at Troy in ignorance of the truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2200"},"sequenceIndex":2661},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2201","text":"And must not the like happen with the spirited or passionate element of\r the soul? Will not the passionate man who carries his passion into\r action, be in the like case, whether he is envious and ambitious, or\r violent and contentious, or angry and discontented, if he be seeking to\r attain honour and victory and the satisfaction of his anger without\r reason or sense?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2201"},"sequenceIndex":2662},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2202","text":"Then may we not confidently assert that the lovers of money and honour,\r when they seek their pleasures under the guidance and in the company of\r reason and knowledge, and pursue after and win the pleasures which\r wisdom shows them, will also have the truest pleasures in the highest\r degree which is attainable to them, inasmuch as they follow truth; and\r they will have the pleasures which are natural to them, if that which\r is best for each one is also most natural to him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2202"},"sequenceIndex":2663},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2203","text":"And when the whole soul follows the philosophical principle, and there\r is no division, the several parts are just, and do each of them their\r own business, and enjoy severally the best and truest pleasures of\r which they are capable?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2203"},"sequenceIndex":2664},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2204","text":"But when either of the two other principles prevails, it fails in\r attaining its own pleasure, and compels the rest to pursue after a\r pleasure which is a shadow only and which is not their own?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2204"},"sequenceIndex":2665},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2205","text":"And the greater the interval which separates them from philosophy and\r reason, the more strange and illusive will be the pleasure?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2205"},"sequenceIndex":2666},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2206","text":"And is not that farthest from reason which is at the greatest distance\r from law and order?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2206"},"sequenceIndex":2667},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2207","text":"And the lustful and tyrannical desires are, as we saw, at the greatest\r distance? Yes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2207"},"sequenceIndex":2668},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2208","text":"Then the tyrant will live at the greatest distance from true or natural\r pleasure, and the king at the least?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2208"},"sequenceIndex":2669},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2209","text":"But if so, the tyrant will live most unpleasantly, and the king most\r pleasantly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2209"},"sequenceIndex":2670},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2210","text":"There appear to be three pleasures, one genuine and two spurious: now\r the transgression of the tyrant reaches a point beyond the spurious; he\r has run away from the region of law and reason, and taken up his abode\r with certain slave pleasures which are his satellites, and the measure\r of his inferiority can only be expressed in a figure.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2210"},"sequenceIndex":2671},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2211","text":"I assume, I said, that the tyrant is in the third place from the\r oligarch; the democrat was in the middle?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2211"},"sequenceIndex":2672},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2212","text":"And if there is truth in what has preceded, he will be wedded to an\r image of pleasure which is thrice removed as to truth from the pleasure\r of the oligarch?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2212"},"sequenceIndex":2673},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2213","text":"And the oligarch is third from the royal; since we count as one royal\r and aristocratical?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2213"},"sequenceIndex":2674},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2214","text":"Then the tyrant is removed from true pleasure by the space of a number\r which is three times three?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2214"},"sequenceIndex":2675},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2215","text":"The shadow then of tyrannical pleasure determined by the number of\r length will be a plane figure.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2215"},"sequenceIndex":2676},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2216","text":"And if you raise the power and make the plane a solid, there is no\r difficulty in seeing how vast is the interval by which the tyrant is\r parted from the king.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2216"},"sequenceIndex":2677},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2217","text":"Or if some person begins at the other end and measures the interval by\r which the king is parted from the tyrant in truth of pleasure, he will\r find him, when the multiplication is completed, living 729 times more\r pleasantly, and the tyrant more painfully by this same interval.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2217"},"sequenceIndex":2678},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2218","text":"What a wonderful calculation! And how enormous is the distance which\r separates the just from the unjust in regard to pleasure and pain!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2218"},"sequenceIndex":2679},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2219","text":"Yet a true calculation, I said, and a number which nearly concerns\r human life, if human beings are concerned with days and nights and\r months and years. (729 NEARLY equals the number of days and nights in\r the year.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2219"},"sequenceIndex":2680},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2220","text":"Then if the good and just man be thus superior in pleasure to the evil\r and unjust, his superiority will be infinitely greater in propriety of\r life and in beauty and virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2220"},"sequenceIndex":2681},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2221","text":"Well, I said, and now having arrived at this stage of the argument, we\r may revert to the words which brought us hither: Was not some one\r saying that injustice was a gain to the perfectly unjust who was\r reputed to be just?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2221"},"sequenceIndex":2682},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2222","text":"Now then, having determined the power and quality of justice and\r injustice, let us have a little conversation with him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2222"},"sequenceIndex":2683},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2223","text":"Let us make an image of the soul, that he may have his own words\r presented before his eyes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2223"},"sequenceIndex":2684},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2224","text":"An ideal image of the soul, like the composite creations of ancient\r mythology, such as the Chimera or Scylla or Cerberus, and there are\r many others in which two or more different natures are said to grow\r into one.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2224"},"sequenceIndex":2685},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2225","text":"Then do you now model the form of a multitudinous, many-headed monster,\r having a ring of heads of all manner of beasts, tame and wild, which he\r is able to generate and metamorphose at will.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2225"},"sequenceIndex":2686},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2226","text":"You suppose marvellous powers in the artist; but, as language is more\r pliable than wax or any similar substance, let there be such a model as\r you propose.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2226"},"sequenceIndex":2687},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2227","text":"Suppose now that you make a second form as of a lion, and a third of a\r man, the second smaller than the first, and the third smaller than the\r second.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2227"},"sequenceIndex":2688},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2228","text":"Next fashion the outside of them into a single image, as of a man, so\r that he who is not able to look within, and sees only the outer hull,\r may believe the beast to be a single human creature.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2228"},"sequenceIndex":2689},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2229","text":"And now, to him who maintains that it is profitable for the human\r creature to be unjust, and unprofitable to be just, let us reply that,\r if he be right, it is profitable for this creature to feast the\r multitudinous monster and strengthen the lion and the lion-like\r qualities, but to starve and weaken the man, who is consequently liable\r to be dragged about at the mercy of either of the other two; and he is\r not to attempt to familiarize or harmonize them with one another—he\r ought rather to suffer them to fight and bite and devour one another.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2229"},"sequenceIndex":2690},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2230","text":"To him the supporter of justice makes answer that he should ever so\r speak and act as to give the man within him in some way or other the\r most complete mastery over the entire human creature. He should watch\r over the many-headed monster like a good husbandman, fostering and\r cultivating the gentle qualities, and preventing the wild ones from\r growing; he should be making the lion-heart his ally, and in common\r care of them all should be uniting the several parts with one another\r and with himself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2230"},"sequenceIndex":2691},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2231","text":"And so from every point of view, whether of pleasure, honour, or\r advantage, the approver of justice is right and speaks the truth, and\r the disapprover is wrong and false and ignorant?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2231"},"sequenceIndex":2692},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2232","text":"Come, now, and let us gently reason with the unjust, who is not\r intentionally in error. ‘Sweet Sir,’ we will say to him, ‘what think\r you of things esteemed noble and ignoble? Is not the noble that which\r subjects the beast to the man, or rather to the god in man; and the\r ignoble that which subjects the man to the beast?’ He can hardly avoid\r saying Yes—can he now?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2232"},"sequenceIndex":2693},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2233","text":"But, if he agree so far, we may ask him to answer another question:\r ‘Then how would a man profit if he received gold and silver on the\r condition that he was to enslave the noblest part of him to the worst?\r Who can imagine that a man who sold his son or daughter into slavery\r for money, especially if he sold them into the hands of fierce and evil\r men, would be the gainer, however large might be the sum which he\r received? And will any one say that he is not a miserable caitiff who\r remorselessly sells his own divine being to that which is most godless\r and detestable? Eriphyle took the neck","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2233"},"sequenceIndex":2694},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2234","text":"Has not the intemperate been censured of old, because in him the huge\r multiform monster is allowed to be too much at large?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2234"},"sequenceIndex":2695},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2235","text":"And men are blamed for pride and bad temper when the lion and serpent\r element in them disproportionately grows and gains strength?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2235"},"sequenceIndex":2696},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2236","text":"And luxury and softness are blamed, because they relax and weaken this\r same creature, and make a coward of him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2236"},"sequenceIndex":2697},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2237","text":"And is not a man reproached for flattery and meanness who subordinates\r the spirited animal to the unruly monster, and, for the sake of money,\r of which he can never have enough, habituates him in the days of his\r youth to be trampled in the mire, and from being a lion to become a\r monkey?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2237"},"sequenceIndex":2698},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2238","text":"And why are mean employments and manual arts a reproach? Only because\r they imply a natural weakness of the higher principle; the individual\r is unable to control the creatures within him, but has to court them,\r and his great study is how to flatter them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2238"},"sequenceIndex":2699},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2239","text":"And therefore, being desirous of placing him under a rule like that of\r the best, we say that he ought to be the servant of the best, in whom\r the Divine rules; not, as Thrasymachus supposed, to the injury of the\r servant, but because every one had better be ruled by divine wisdom\r dwelling within him; or, if this be impossible, then by an external\r authority, in order that we may be all, as far as possible, under the\r same government, friends and equals.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2239"},"sequenceIndex":2700},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2240","text":"And this is clearly seen to be the intention of the law, which is the\r ally of the whole city; and is seen also in the authority which we\r exercise over children, and the refusal to let them be free until we\r have established in them a principle analogous to the constitution of a\r state, and by cultivation of this higher element have set up in their\r hearts a guardian and ruler like our own, and when this is done they\r may go their ways.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2240"},"sequenceIndex":2701},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2241","text":"From what point of view, then, and on what ground can we say that a man\r is profited by injustice or intemperance or other baseness, which will\r make him a worse man, even though he acquire money or power by his\r wickedness?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2241"},"sequenceIndex":2702},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2242","text":"What shall he profit, if his injustice be undetected and unpunished? He\r who is undetected only gets worse, whereas he who is detected and\r punished has the brutal part of his nature silenced and humanized; the\r gentler element in him is liberated, and his whole soul is perfected\r and ennobled by the acquirement of justice and temperance and wisdom,\r more than the body ever is by receiving gifts of beauty, strength and\r health, in proportion as the soul is more honourable than the body.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2242"},"sequenceIndex":2703},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2243","text":"To this nobler purpose the man of understanding will devote the\r energies of his life. And in the first place, he will honour studies\r which impress these qualities on his soul and will disregard others?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2243"},"sequenceIndex":2704},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2244","text":"In the next place, he will regulate his bodily habit and training, and\r so far will he be from yielding to brutal and irrational pleasures,\r that he will regard even health as quite a secondary matter; his first\r object will be not that he may be fair or strong or well, unless he is\r likely thereby to gain temperance, but he will always desire so to\r attemper the body as to preserve the harmony of the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2244"},"sequenceIndex":2705},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2245","text":"And in the acquisition of wealth there is a principle of order and\r harmony which he will also observe; he will not allow himself to be\r dazzled by the foolish applause of the world, and heap up riches to his\r own infinite harm?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2245"},"sequenceIndex":2706},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2246","text":"He will look at the city which is within him, and take heed that no\r disorder occur in it, such as might arise either from superfluity or\r from want; and upon this principle he will regulate his property and\r gain or spend according to his means.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2246"},"sequenceIndex":2707},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2247","text":"And, for the same reason, he will gladly accept and enjoy such honours\r as he deems likely to make him a better man; but those, whether private\r or public, which are likely to disorder his life, he will avoid?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2247"},"sequenceIndex":2708},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2248","text":"By the dog of Egypt, he will! in the city which is his own he certainly\r will, though in the land of his birth perhaps not, unless he have a\r divine call.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2248"},"sequenceIndex":2709},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2249","text":"I understand; you mean that he will be a ruler in the city of which we\r are the founders, and which exists in idea only; for I do not believe\r that there is such an one anywhere on earth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2249"},"sequenceIndex":2710},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2250","text":"In heaven, I replied, there is laid up a pattern of it, methinks, which\r he who desires may behold, and beholding, may set his own house in\r order. But whether such an one exists, or ever will exist in fact, is\r no matter; for he will live after the manner of that city, having\r nothing to do with any other.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2250"},"sequenceIndex":2711},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2251","text":"Of the many excellences which I perceive in the order of our State,\r there is none which upon reflection pleases me better than the rule\r about poetry.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2251"},"sequenceIndex":2712},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2252","text":"To the rejection of imitative poetry, which certainly ought not to be\r received; as I see far more clearly now that the parts of the soul have\r been distinguished.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2252"},"sequenceIndex":2713},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2253","text":"Speaking in confidence, for I should not like to have my words repeated\r to the tragedians and the rest of the imitative tribe—but I do not mind\r saying to you, that all poetical imitations are ruinous to the\r understanding of the hearers, and that the knowledge of their true\r nature is the only antidote to them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2253"},"sequenceIndex":2714},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2254","text":"Well, I will tell you, although I have always from my earliest youth\r had an awe and love of Homer, which even now makes the words falter on\r my lips, for he is the great captain and teacher of the whole of that\r charming tragic company; but a man is not to be reverenced more than\r the truth, and therefore I will speak out.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2254"},"sequenceIndex":2715},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2255","text":"Very true, he said; but in your presence, even if I had any faint\r notion, I could not muster courage to utter it. Will you enquire\r yourself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2255"},"sequenceIndex":2716},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2256","text":"Well then, shall we begin the enquiry in our usual manner: Whenever a\r number of individuals have a common name, we assume them to have also a\r corresponding idea or form:—do you understand me?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2256"},"sequenceIndex":2717},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2257","text":"Let us take any common instance; there are beds and tables in the\r world—plenty of them, are there not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2257"},"sequenceIndex":2718},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2258","text":"But there are only two ideas or forms of them—one the idea of a bed,\r the other of a table.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2258"},"sequenceIndex":2719},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2259","text":"And the maker of either of them makes a bed or he makes a table for our\r use, in accordance with the idea—that is our way of speaking in this\r and similar instances—but no artificer makes the ideas themselves: how\r could he?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2259"},"sequenceIndex":2720},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2260","text":"Wait a little, and there will be more reason for your saying so. For\r this is he who is able to make not only vessels of every kind, but\r plants and animals, himself and all other things—the earth and heaven,\r and the things which are in heaven or under the earth; he makes the\r gods also.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2260"},"sequenceIndex":2721},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2261","text":"Oh! you are incredulous, are you? Do you mean that there is no such\r maker or creator, or that in one sense there might be a maker of all\r these things but in another not? Do you see that there is a way in\r which you could make them all yourself?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2261"},"sequenceIndex":2722},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2262","text":"An easy way enough; or rather, there are many ways in which the feat\r might be quickly and easily accomplished, none quicker than that of\r turning a mirror round and round—you would soon enough make the sun and\r the heavens, and the earth and yourself, and other animals and plants,\r and all the other things of which we were just now speaking, in the\r mirror.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2262"},"sequenceIndex":2723},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2263","text":"Very good, I said, you are coming to the point now. And the painter too\r is, as I conceive, just such another—a creator of appearances, is he\r not?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2263"},"sequenceIndex":2724},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2264","text":"But then I suppose you will say that what he creates is untrue. And yet\r there is a sense in which the painter also creates a bed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2264"},"sequenceIndex":2725},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2265","text":"And what of the maker of the bed? were you not saying that he too\r makes, not the idea which, according to our view, is the essence of the\r bed, but only a particular bed?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2265"},"sequenceIndex":2726},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2266","text":"Then if he does not make that which exists he cannot make true\r existence, but only some semblance of existence; and if any one were to\r say that the work of the maker of the bed, or of any other workman, has\r real existence, he could hardly be supposed to be speaking the truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2266"},"sequenceIndex":2727},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2267","text":"At any rate, he replied, philosophers would say that he was not\r speaking the truth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2267"},"sequenceIndex":2728},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2268","text":"Suppose now that by the light of the examples just offered we enquire\r who this imitator is?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2268"},"sequenceIndex":2729},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2269","text":"Well then, here are three beds: one existing in nature, which is made\r by God, as I think that we may say—for no one else can be the maker?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2269"},"sequenceIndex":2730},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2270","text":"Beds, then, are of three kinds, and there are three artists who\r superintend them: God, the maker of the bed, and the painter?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2270"},"sequenceIndex":2731},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2271","text":"God, whether from choice or from necessity, made one bed in nature and\r one only; two or more such ideal beds neither ever have been nor ever\r will be made by God.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2271"},"sequenceIndex":2732},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2272","text":"Because even if He had made but two, a third would still appear behind\r them which both of them would have for their idea, and that would be\r the ideal bed and not the two others.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2272"},"sequenceIndex":2733},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2273","text":"God knew this, and He desired to be the real maker of a real bed, not a\r particular maker of a particular bed, and therefore He created a bed\r which is essentially and by nature one only.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2273"},"sequenceIndex":2734},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2274","text":"Yes, he replied; inasmuch as by the natural process of creation He is\r the author of this and of all other things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2274"},"sequenceIndex":2735},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2275","text":"I think, he said, that we may fairly designate him as the imitator of\r that which the others make.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2275"},"sequenceIndex":2736},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2276","text":"Good, I said; then you call him who is third in the descent from nature\r an imitator?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2276"},"sequenceIndex":2737},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2277","text":"And the tragic poet is an imitator, and therefore, like all other\r imitators, he is thrice removed from the king and from the truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2277"},"sequenceIndex":2738},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2278","text":"Then about the imitator we are agreed. And what about the painter?—I\r would like to know whether he may be thought to imitate that which\r originally exists in nature, or only the creations of artists?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2278"},"sequenceIndex":2739},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2279","text":"I mean, that you may look at a bed from different points of view,\r obliquely or directly or from any other point of view, and the bed will\r appear different, but there is no difference in reality. And the same\r of all things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2279"},"sequenceIndex":2740},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2280","text":"Now let me ask you another question: Which is the art of painting\r designed to be—an imitation of things as they are, or as they appear—of\r appearance or of reality?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2280"},"sequenceIndex":2741},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2281","text":"Then the imitator, I said, is a long way off the truth, and can do all\r things because he lightly touches on a small part of them, and that\r part an image. For example: A painter will paint a cobbler, carpenter,\r or any other artist, though he knows nothing of their arts; and, if he\r is a good artist, he may deceive children or simple persons, when he\r shows them his picture of a carpenter from a distance, and they will\r fancy that they are looking at a real carpenter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2281"},"sequenceIndex":2742},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2282","text":"And whenever any one informs us that he has found a man who knows all\r the arts, and all things else that anybody knows, and every single\r thing with a higher degree of accuracy than any other man—whoever tells\r us this, I think that we can only imagine him to be a simple creature\r who is likely to have been deceived by some wizard or actor whom he\r met, and whom he thought all-knowing, because he himself was unable to\r analyse the nature of knowledge and ignorance and imitation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2282"},"sequenceIndex":2743},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2283","text":"And so, when we hear persons saying that the tragedians, and Homer, who\r is at their head, know all the arts and all things human, virtue as\r well as vice, and divine things too, for that the good poet cannot\r compose well unless he knows his subject, and that he who has not this\r knowledge can never be a poet, we ought to consider whether here also\r there may not be a similar illusion. Perhaps they may have come across\r imitators and been deceived by them; they may not have remembered when\r they saw their works that these were but imitations thrice removed from\r the truth, and could easily be","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2283"},"sequenceIndex":2744},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2284","text":"Now do you suppose that if a person were able to make the original as\r well as the image, he would seriously devote himself to the\r image-making branch? Would he allow imitation to be the ruling\r principle of his life, as if he had nothing higher in him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2284"},"sequenceIndex":2745},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2285","text":"The real artist, who knew what he was imitating, would be interested in\r realities and not in imitations; and would desire to leave as memorials\r of himself works many and fair; and, instead of being the author of\r encomiums, he would prefer to be the theme of them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2285"},"sequenceIndex":2746},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2286","text":"Then, I said, we must put a question to Homer; not about medicine, or\r any of the arts to which his poems only incidentally refer: we are not\r going to ask him, or any other poet, whether he has cured patients like\r Asclepius, or left behind him a school of medicine such as the\r Asclepiads were, or whether he only talks about medicine and other arts\r at second-hand; but we have a right to know respecting military\r tactics, politics, education, which are the chiefest and noblest\r subjects of his poems, and we may fairly ask him about them. ‘Friend\r Homer,’ then we say to him, ‘if you are only i","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2286"},"sequenceIndex":2747},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2287","text":"I think not, said Glaucon; not even the Homerids themselves pretend\r that he was a legislator.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2287"},"sequenceIndex":2748},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2288","text":"Well, but is there any war on record which was carried on successfully\r by him, or aided by his counsels, when he was alive?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2288"},"sequenceIndex":2749},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2289","text":"Or is there any invention of his, applicable to the arts or to human\r life, such as Thales the Milesian or Anacharsis the Scythian, and other\r ingenious men have conceived, which is attributed to him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2289"},"sequenceIndex":2750},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2290","text":"But, if Homer never did any public service, was he privately a guide or\r teacher of any? Had he in his lifetime friends who loved to associate\r with him, and who handed down to posterity an Homeric way of life, such\r as was established by Pythagoras who was so greatly beloved for his\r wisdom, and whose followers are to this day quite celebrated for the\r order which was named after him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2290"},"sequenceIndex":2751},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2291","text":"Nothing of the kind is recorded of him. For surely, Socrates,\r Creophylus, the companion of Homer, that child of flesh, whose name\r always makes us laugh, might be more justly ridiculed for his\r stupidity, if, as is said, Homer was greatly neglected by him and\r others in his own day when he was alive?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2291"},"sequenceIndex":2752},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2292","text":"Yes, I replied, that is the tradition. But can you imagine, Glaucon,\r that if Homer had really been able to educate and improve mankind—if he\r had possessed knowledge and not been a mere imitator—can you imagine, I\r say, that he would not have had many followers, and been honoured and\r loved by them? Protagoras of Abdera, and Prodicus of Ceos, and a host\r of others, have only to whisper to their contemporaries: ‘You will\r never be able to manage either your own house or your own State until\r you appoint us to be your ministers of education’—and this ingenious\r device of theirs has such an effe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2292"},"sequenceIndex":2753},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2293","text":"Then must we not infer that all these poetical individuals, beginning\r with Homer, are only imitators; they copy images of virtue and the\r like, but the truth they never reach? The poet is like a painter who,\r as we have already observed, will make a likeness of a cobbler though\r he understands nothing of cobbling; and his picture is good enough for\r those who know no more than he does, and judge only by colours and\r figures.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2293"},"sequenceIndex":2754},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2294","text":"In like manner the poet with his words and phrases may be said to lay\r on the colours of the several arts, himself understanding their nature\r only enough to imitate them; and other people, who are as ignorant as\r he is, and judge only from his words, imagine that if he speaks of\r cobbling, or of military tactics, or of anything else, in metre and\r harmony and rhythm, he speaks very well—such is the sweet influence\r which melody and rhythm by nature have. And I think that you must have\r observed again and again what a poor appearance the tales of poets make\r when stripped of the colours which ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2294"},"sequenceIndex":2755},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2295","text":"They are like faces which were never really beautiful, but only\r blooming; and now the bloom of youth has passed away from them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2295"},"sequenceIndex":2756},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2296","text":"Here is another point: The imitator or maker of the image knows nothing\r of true existence; he knows appearances only. Am I not right?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2296"},"sequenceIndex":2757},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2297","text":"Then let us have a clear understanding, and not be satisfied with half\r an explanation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2297"},"sequenceIndex":2758},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2298","text":"But does the painter know the right form of the bit and reins? Nay,\r hardly even the workers in brass and leather who make them; only the\r horseman who knows how to use them—he knows their right form.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2298"},"sequenceIndex":2759},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2299","text":"That there are three arts which are concerned with all things: one\r which uses, another which makes, a third which imitates them?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2299"},"sequenceIndex":2760},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2300","text":"And the excellence or beauty or truth of every structure, animate or\r inanimate, and of every action of man, is relative to the use for which\r nature or the artist has intended them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2300"},"sequenceIndex":2761},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2301","text":"Then the user of them must have the greatest experience of them, and he\r must indicate to the maker the good or bad qualities which develop\r themselves in use; for example, the flute-player will tell the\r flute-maker which of his flutes is satisfactory to the performer; he\r will tell him how he ought to make them, and the other will attend to\r his instructions?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2301"},"sequenceIndex":2762},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2302","text":"The one knows and therefore speaks with authority about the goodness\r and badness of flutes, while the other, confiding in him, will do what\r he is told by him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2302"},"sequenceIndex":2763},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2303","text":"The instrument is the same, but about the excellence or badness of it\r the maker will only attain to a correct belief; and this he will gain\r from him who knows, by talking to him and being compelled to hear what\r he has to say, whereas the user will have knowledge?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2303"},"sequenceIndex":2764},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2304","text":"But will the imitator have either? Will he know from use whether or no\r his drawing is correct or beautiful? or will he have right opinion from\r being compelled to associate with another who knows and gives him\r instructions about what he should draw?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2304"},"sequenceIndex":2765},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2305","text":"Then he will no more have true opinion than he will have knowledge\r about the goodness or badness of his imitations?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2305"},"sequenceIndex":2766},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2306","text":"The imitative artist will be in a brilliant state of intelligence about\r his own creations?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2306"},"sequenceIndex":2767},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2307","text":"And still he will go on imitating without knowing what makes a thing\r good or bad, and may be expected therefore to imitate only that which\r appears to be good to the ignorant multitude?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2307"},"sequenceIndex":2768},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2308","text":"Thus far then we are pretty well agreed that the imitator has no\r knowledge worth mentioning of what he imitates. Imitation is only a\r kind of play or sport, and the tragic poets, whether they write in\r Iambic or in Heroic verse, are imitators in the highest degree?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2308"},"sequenceIndex":2769},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2309","text":"And now tell me, I conjure you, has not imitation been shown by us to\r be concerned with that which is thrice removed from the truth?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2309"},"sequenceIndex":2770},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2310","text":"I will explain: The body which is large when seen near, appears small\r when seen at a distance?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2310"},"sequenceIndex":2771},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2311","text":"And the same object appears straight when looked at out of the water,\r and crooked when in the water; and the concave becomes convex, owing to\r the illusion about colours to which the sight is liable. Thus every\r sort of confusion is revealed within us; and this is that weakness of\r the human mind on which the art of conjuring and of deceiving by light\r and shadow and other ingenious devices imposes, having an effect upon\r us like magic.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2311"},"sequenceIndex":2772},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2312","text":"And the arts of measuring and numbering and weighing come to the rescue\r of the human understanding—there is the beauty of them—and the apparent\r greater or less, or more or heavier, no longer have the mastery over\r us, but give way before calculation and measure and weight?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2312"},"sequenceIndex":2773},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2313","text":"And this, surely, must be the work of the calculating and rational\r principle in the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2313"},"sequenceIndex":2774},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2314","text":"And when this principle measures and certifies that some things are\r equal, or that some are greater or less than others, there occurs an\r apparent contradiction?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2314"},"sequenceIndex":2775},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2315","text":"But were we not saying that such a contradiction is impossible—the same\r faculty cannot have contrary opinions at the same time about the same\r thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2315"},"sequenceIndex":2776},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2316","text":"Then that part of the soul which has an opinion contrary to measure is\r not the same with that which has an opinion in accordance with measure?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2316"},"sequenceIndex":2777},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2317","text":"And the better part of the soul is likely to be that which trusts to\r measure and calculation?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2317"},"sequenceIndex":2778},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2318","text":"And that which is opposed to them is one of the inferior principles of\r the soul?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2318"},"sequenceIndex":2779},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2319","text":"This was the conclusion at which I was seeking to arrive when I said\r that painting or drawing, and imitation in general, when doing their\r own proper work, are far removed from truth, and the companions and\r friends and associates of a principle within us which is equally\r removed from reason, and that they have no true or healthy aim.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2319"},"sequenceIndex":2780},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2320","text":"The imitative art is an inferior who marries an inferior, and has\r inferior offspring.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2320"},"sequenceIndex":2781},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2321","text":"And is this confined to the sight only, or does it extend to the\r hearing also, relating in fact to what we term poetry?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2321"},"sequenceIndex":2782},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2322","text":"Do not rely, I said, on a probability derived from the analogy of\r painting; but let us examine further and see whether the faculty with\r which poetical imitation is concerned is good or bad.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2322"},"sequenceIndex":2783},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2323","text":"We may state the question thus:—Imitation imitates the actions of men,\r whether voluntary or involuntary, on which, as they imagine, a good or\r bad result has ensued, and they rejoice or sorrow accordingly. Is there\r anything more?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2323"},"sequenceIndex":2784},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2324","text":"But in all this variety of circumstances is the man at unity with\r himself—or rather, as in the instance of sight there was confusion and\r opposition in his opinions about the same things, so here also is there\r not strife and inconsistency in his life? Though I need hardly raise\r the question again, for I remember that all this has been already\r admitted; and the soul has been acknowledged by us to be full of these\r and ten thousand similar oppositions occurring at the same moment?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2324"},"sequenceIndex":2785},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2325","text":"Yes, I said, thus far we were right; but there was an omission which\r must now be supplied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2325"},"sequenceIndex":2786},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2326","text":"Were we not saying that a good man, who has the misfortune to lose his\r son or anything else which is most dear to him, will bear the loss with\r more equanimity than another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2326"},"sequenceIndex":2787},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2327","text":"But will he have no sorrow, or shall we say that although he cannot\r help sorrowing, he will moderate his sorrow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2327"},"sequenceIndex":2788},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2328","text":"Tell me: will he be more likely to struggle and hold out against his\r sorrow when he is seen by his equals, or when he is alone?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2328"},"sequenceIndex":2789},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2329","text":"When he is by himself he will not mind saying or doing many things\r which he would be ashamed of any one hearing or seeing him do?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2329"},"sequenceIndex":2790},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2330","text":"There is a principle of law and reason in him which bids him resist, as\r well as a feeling of his misfortune which is forcing him to indulge his\r sorrow?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2330"},"sequenceIndex":2791},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2331","text":"But when a man is drawn in two opposite directions, to and from the\r same object, this, as we affirm, necessarily implies two distinct\r principles in him?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2331"},"sequenceIndex":2792},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2332","text":"The law would say that to be patient under suffering is best, and that\r we should not give way to impatience, as there is no knowing whether\r such things are good or evil; and nothing is gained by impatience;\r also, because no human thing is of serious importance, and grief stands\r in the way of that which at the moment is most required.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2332"},"sequenceIndex":2793},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2333","text":"That we should take counsel about what has happened, and when the dice\r have been thrown order our affairs in the way which reason deems best;\r not, like children who have had a fall, keeping hold of the part struck\r and wasting time in setting up a howl, but always accustoming the soul\r forthwith to apply a remedy, raising up that which is sickly and\r fallen, banishing the cry of sorrow by the healing art.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2333"},"sequenceIndex":2794},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2334","text":"Yes, I said; and the higher principle is ready to follow this\r suggestion of reason?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2334"},"sequenceIndex":2795},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2335","text":"And the other principle, which inclines us to recollection of our\r troubles and to lamentation, and can never have enough of them, we may\r call irrational, useless, and cowardly?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2335"},"sequenceIndex":2796},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2336","text":"And does not the latter—I mean the rebellious principle—furnish a great\r variety of materials for imitation? Whereas the wise and calm\r temperament, being always nearly equable, is not easy to imitate or to\r appreciate when imitated, especially at a public festival when a\r promiscuous crowd is assembled in a theatre. For the feeling\r represented is one to which they are strangers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2336"},"sequenceIndex":2797},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2337","text":"Then the imitative poet who aims at being popular is not by nature\r made, nor is his art intended, to please or to affect the rational\r principle in the soul; but he will prefer the passionate and fitful\r temper, which is easily imitated?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2337"},"sequenceIndex":2798},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2338","text":"And now we may fairly take him and place him by the side of the\r painter, for he is like him in two ways: first, inasmuch as his\r creations have an inferior degree of truth—in this, I say, he is like\r him; and he is also like him in being concerned with an inferior part\r of the soul; and therefore we shall be right in refusing to admit him\r into a well-ordered State, because he awakens and nourishes and\r strengthens the feelings and impairs the reason. As in a city when the\r evil are permitted to have authority and the good are put out of the\r way, so in the soul of man, as we maintain, the im","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2338"},"sequenceIndex":2799},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2339","text":"But we have not yet brought forward the heaviest count in our\r accusation:—the power which poetry has of harming even the good (and\r there are very few who are not harmed), is surely an awful thing?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2339"},"sequenceIndex":2800},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2340","text":"Hear and judge: The best of us, as I conceive, when we listen to a\r passage of Homer, or one of the tragedians, in which he represents some\r pitiful hero who is drawling out his sorrows in a long oration, or\r weeping, and smiting his breast—the best of us, you know, delight in\r giving way to sympathy, and are in raptures at the excellence of the\r poet who stirs our feelings most.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2340"},"sequenceIndex":2801},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2341","text":"But when any sorrow of our own happens to us, then you may observe that\r we pride ourselves on the opposite quality—we would fain be quiet and\r patient; this is the manly part, and the other which delighted us in\r the recitation is now deemed to be the part of a woman.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2341"},"sequenceIndex":2802},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2342","text":"Now can we be right in praising and admiring another who is doing that\r which any one of us would abominate and be ashamed of in his own\r person?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2342"},"sequenceIndex":2803},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2343","text":"If you consider, I said, that when in misfortune we feel a natural\r hunger and desire to relieve our sorrow by weeping and lamentation, and\r that this feeling which is kept under control in our own calamities is\r satisfied and delighted by the poets;—the better nature in each of us,\r not having been sufficiently trained by reason or habit, allows the\r sympathetic element to break loose because the sorrow is another’s; and\r the spectator fancies that there can be no disgrace to himself in\r praising and pitying any one who comes telling him what a good man he\r is, and making a fuss about his tro","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2343"},"sequenceIndex":2804},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2344","text":"And does not the same hold also of the ridiculous? There are jests\r which you would be ashamed to make yourself, and yet on the comic\r stage, or indeed in private, when you hear them, you are greatly amused\r by them, and are not at all disgusted at their unseemliness;—the case\r of pity is repeated;—there is a principle in human nature which is\r disposed to raise a laugh, and this which you once restrained by\r reason, because you were afraid of being thought a buffoon, is now let\r out again; and having stimulated the risible faculty at the theatre,\r you are betrayed unconsciously to yourself in","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2344"},"sequenceIndex":2805},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2345","text":"And the same may be said of lust and anger and all the other\r affections, of desire and pain and pleasure, which are held to be\r inseparable from every action—in all of them poetry feeds and waters\r the passions instead of drying them up; she lets them rule, although\r they ought to be controlled, if mankind are ever to increase in\r happiness and virtue.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2345"},"sequenceIndex":2806},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2346","text":"Therefore, Glaucon, I said, whenever you meet with any of the eulogists\r of Homer declaring that he has been the educator of Hellas, and that he\r is profitable for education and for the ordering of human things, and\r that you should take him up again and again and get to know him and\r regulate your whole life according to him, we may love and honour those\r who say these things—they are excellent people, as far as their lights\r extend; and we are ready to acknowledge that Homer is the greatest of\r poets and first of tragedy writers; but we must remain firm in our\r conviction that hymns to the g","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2346"},"sequenceIndex":2807},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2347","text":"And now since we have reverted to the subject of poetry, let this our\r defence serve to show the reasonableness of our former judgment in\r sending away out of our State an art having the tendencies which we\r have described; for reason constrained us. But that she may not impute\r to us any harshness or want of politeness, let us tell her that there\r is an ancient quarrel between philosophy and poetry; of which there are\r many proofs, such as the saying of ‘the yelping hound howling at her\r lord,’ or of one ‘mighty in the vain talk of fools,’ and ‘the mob of\r sages circumventing Zeus,’ and the ‘","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2347"},"sequenceIndex":2808},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2348","text":"Shall I propose, then, that she be allowed to return from exile, but\r upon this condition only—that she make a defence of herself in lyrical\r or some other metre?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2348"},"sequenceIndex":2809},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2349","text":"And we may further grant to those of her defenders who are lovers of\r poetry and yet not poets the permission to speak in prose on her\r behalf: let them show not only that she is pleasant but also useful to\r States and to human life, and we will listen in a kindly spirit; for if\r this can be proved we shall surely be the gainers—I mean, if there is a\r use in poetry as well as a delight?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2349"},"sequenceIndex":2810},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2350","text":"If her defence fails, then, my dear friend, like other persons who are\r enamoured of something, but put a restraint upon themselves when they\r think their desires are opposed to their interests, so too must we\r after the manner of lovers give her up, though not without a struggle.\r We too are inspired by that love of poetry which the education of noble\r States has implanted in us, and therefore we would have her appear at\r her best and truest; but so long as she is unable to make good her\r defence, this argument of ours shall be a charm to us, which we will\r repeat to ourselves while we listen","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2350"},"sequenceIndex":2811},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2351","text":"Yes, I said, my dear Glaucon, for great is the issue at stake, greater\r than appears, whether a man is to be good or bad. And what will any one\r be profited if under the influence of honour or money or power, aye, or\r under the excitement of poetry, he neglect justice and virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2351"},"sequenceIndex":2812},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2352","text":"Yes, he said; I have been convinced by the argument, as I believe that\r any one else would have been.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2352"},"sequenceIndex":2813},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2353","text":"And yet no mention has been made of the greatest prizes and rewards\r which await virtue.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2353"},"sequenceIndex":2814},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2354","text":"What, are there any greater still? If there are, they must be of an\r inconceivable greatness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2354"},"sequenceIndex":2815},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2355","text":"Why, I said, what was ever great in a short time? The whole period of\r three score years and ten is surely but a little thing in comparison\r with eternity?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2355"},"sequenceIndex":2816},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2356","text":"And should an immortal being seriously think of this little space\r rather than of the whole?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2356"},"sequenceIndex":2817},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2357","text":"He looked at me in astonishment, and said: No, by heaven: And are you\r really prepared to maintain this?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2357"},"sequenceIndex":2818},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2358","text":"I see a great difficulty; but I should like to hear you state this\r argument of which you make so light.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2358"},"sequenceIndex":2819},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2359","text":"Would you agree with me in thinking that the corrupting and destroying\r element is the evil, and the saving and improving element the good?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2359"},"sequenceIndex":2820},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2360","text":"And you admit that every thing has a good and also an evil; as\r ophthalmia is the evil of the eyes and disease of the whole body; as\r mildew is of corn, and rot of timber, or rust of copper and iron: in\r everything, or in almost everything, there is an inherent evil and\r disease?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2360"},"sequenceIndex":2821},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2361","text":"And anything which is infected by any of these evils is made evil, and\r at last wholly dissolves and dies?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2361"},"sequenceIndex":2822},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2362","text":"The vice and evil which is inherent in each is the destruction of each;\r and if this does not destroy them there is nothing else that will; for\r good certainly will not destroy them, nor again, that which is neither\r good nor evil.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2362"},"sequenceIndex":2823},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2363","text":"If, then, we find any nature which having this inherent corruption\r cannot be dissolved or destroyed, we may be certain that of such a\r nature there is no destruction?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2363"},"sequenceIndex":2824},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2364","text":"Yes, he said, there are all the evils which we were just now passing in\r review: unrighteousness, intemperance, cowardice, ignorance.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2364"},"sequenceIndex":2825},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2365","text":"But does any of these dissolve or destroy her?—and here do not let us\r fall into the error of supposing that the unjust and foolish man, when\r he is detected, perishes through his own injustice, which is an evil of\r the soul. Take the analogy of the body: The evil of the body is a\r disease which wastes and reduces and annihilates the body; and all the\r things of which we were just now speaking come to annihilation through\r their own corruption attaching to them and inhering in them and so\r destroying them. Is not this true?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2365"},"sequenceIndex":2826},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2366","text":"Consider the soul in like manner. Does the injustice or other evil\r which exists in the soul waste and consume her? Do they by attaching to\r the soul and inhering in her at last bring her to death, and so\r separate her from the body?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2366"},"sequenceIndex":2827},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2367","text":"And yet, I said, it is unreasonable to suppose that anything can perish\r from without through affection of external evil which could not be\r destroyed from within by a corruption of its own?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2367"},"sequenceIndex":2828},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2368","text":"Consider, I said, Glaucon, that even the badness of food, whether\r staleness, decomposition, or any other bad quality, when confined to\r the actual food, is not supposed to destroy the body; although, if the\r badness of food communicates corruption to the body, then we should say\r that the body has been destroyed by a corruption of itself, which is\r disease, brought on by this; but that the body, being one thing, can be\r destroyed by the badness of food, which is another, and which does not\r engender any natural infection—this we shall absolutely deny?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2368"},"sequenceIndex":2829},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2369","text":"And, on the same principle, unless some bodily evil can produce an evil\r of the soul, we must not suppose that the soul, which is one thing, can\r be dissolved by any merely external evil which belongs to another?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2369"},"sequenceIndex":2830},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2370","text":"Either, then, let us refute this conclusion, or, while it remains\r unrefuted, let us never say that fever, or any other disease, or the\r knife put to the throat, or even the cutting up of the whole body into\r the minutest pieces, can destroy the soul, until she herself is proved\r to become more unholy or unrighteous in consequence of these things\r being done to the body; but that the soul, or anything else if not\r destroyed by an internal evil, can be destroyed by an external one, is\r not to be affirmed by any man.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2370"},"sequenceIndex":2831},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2371","text":"And surely, he replied, no one will ever prove that the souls of men\r become more unjust in consequence of death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2371"},"sequenceIndex":2832},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2372","text":"But if some one who would rather not admit the immortality of the soul\r boldly denies this, and says that the dying do really become more evil\r and unrighteous, then, if the speaker is right, I suppose that\r injustice, like disease, must be assumed to be fatal to the unjust, and\r that those who take this disorder die by the natural inherent power of\r destruction which evil has, and which kills them sooner or later, but\r in quite another way from that in which, at present, the wicked receive\r death at the hands of others as the penalty of their deeds?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2372"},"sequenceIndex":2833},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2373","text":"Nay, he said, in that case injustice, if fatal to the unjust, will not\r be so very terrible to him, for he will be delivered from evil. But I\r rather suspect the opposite to be the truth, and that injustice which,\r if it have the power, will murder others, keeps the murderer alive—aye,\r and well awake too; so far removed is her dwelling-place from being a\r house of death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2373"},"sequenceIndex":2834},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2374","text":"True, I said; if the inherent natural vice or evil of the soul is\r unable to kill or destroy her, hardly will that which is appointed to\r be the destruction of some other body, destroy a soul or anything else\r except that of which it was appointed to be the destruction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2374"},"sequenceIndex":2835},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2375","text":"But the soul which cannot be destroyed by an evil, whether inherent or\r external, must exist for ever, and if existing for ever, must be\r immortal?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2375"},"sequenceIndex":2836},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2376","text":"That is the conclusion, I said; and, if a true conclusion, then the\r souls must always be the same, for if none be destroyed they will not\r diminish in number. Neither will they increase, for the increase of the\r immortal natures must come from something mortal, and all things would\r thus end in immortality.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2376"},"sequenceIndex":2837},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2377","text":"But this we cannot believe—reason will not allow us—any more than we\r can believe the soul, in her truest nature, to be full of variety and\r difference and dissimilarity.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2377"},"sequenceIndex":2838},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2378","text":"The soul, I said, being, as is now proven, immortal, must be the\r fairest of compositions and cannot be compounded of many elements?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2378"},"sequenceIndex":2839},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2379","text":"Her immortality is demonstrated by the previous argument, and there are\r many other proofs; but to see her as she really is, not as we now\r behold her, marred by communion with the body and other miseries, you\r must contemplate her with the eye of reason, in her original purity;\r and then her beauty will be revealed, and justice and injustice and all\r the things which we have described will be manifested more clearly.\r Thus far, we have spoken the truth concerning her as she appears at\r present, but we must remember also that we have seen her only in a\r condition which may be compared to that ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2379"},"sequenceIndex":2840},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2380","text":"At her love of wisdom. Let us see whom she affects, and what society\r and converse she seeks in virtue of her near kindred with the immortal\r and eternal and divine; also how different she would become if wholly\r following this superior principle, and borne by a divine impulse out of\r the ocean in which she now is, and disengaged from the stones and\r shells and things of earth and rock which in wild variety spring up\r around her because she feeds upon earth, and is overgrown by the good\r things of this life as they are termed: then you would see her as she\r is, and know whether she have one sh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2380"},"sequenceIndex":2841},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2381","text":"And thus, I said, we have fulfilled the conditions of the argument; we\r have not introduced the rewards and glories of justice, which, as you\r were saying, are to be found in Homer and Hesiod; but justice in her\r own nature has been shown to be best for the soul in her own nature.\r Let a man do what is just, whether he have the ring of Gyges or not,\r and even if in addition to the ring of Gyges he put on the helmet of\r Hades.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2381"},"sequenceIndex":2842},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2382","text":"And now, Glaucon, there will be no harm in further enumerating how many\r and how great are the rewards which justice and the other virtues\r procure to the soul from gods and men, both in life and after death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2382"},"sequenceIndex":2843},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2383","text":"The assumption that the just man should appear unjust and the unjust\r just: for you were of opinion that even if the true state of the case\r could not possibly escape the eyes of gods and men, still this\r admission ought to be made for the sake of the argument, in order that\r pure justice might be weighed against pure injustice. Do you remember?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2383"},"sequenceIndex":2844},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2384","text":"Then, as the cause is decided, I demand on behalf of justice that the\r estimation in which she is held by gods and men and which we\r acknowledge to be her due should now be restored to her by us; since\r she has been shown to confer reality, and not to deceive those who\r truly possess her, let what has been taken from her be given back, that\r so she may win that palm of appearance which is hers also, and which\r she gives to her own.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2384"},"sequenceIndex":2845},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2385","text":"In the first place, I said—and this is the first thing which you will\r have to give back—the nature both of the just and unjust is truly known\r to the gods.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2385"},"sequenceIndex":2846},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2386","text":"And if they are both known to them, one must be the friend and the\r other the enemy of the gods, as we admitted from the beginning?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2386"},"sequenceIndex":2847},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2387","text":"And the friend of the gods may be supposed to receive from them all\r things at their best, excepting only such evil as is the necessary\r consequence of former sins?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2387"},"sequenceIndex":2848},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2388","text":"Then this must be our notion of the just man, that even when he is in\r poverty or sickness, or any other seeming misfortune, all things will\r in the end work together for good to him in life and death: for the\r gods have a care of any one whose desire is to become just and to be\r like God, as far as man can attain the divine likeness, by the pursuit\r of virtue?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2388"},"sequenceIndex":2849},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2389","text":"And what do they receive of men? Look at things as they really are, and\r you will see that the clever unjust are in the case of runners, who run\r well from the starting-place to the goal but not back again from the\r goal: they go off at a great pace, but in the end only look foolish,\r slinking away with their ears draggling on their shoulders, and without\r a crown; but the true runner comes to the finish and receives the prize\r and is crowned. And this is the way with the just; he who endures to\r the end of every action and occasion of his entire life has a good\r report and carries off the pri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2389"},"sequenceIndex":2850},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2390","text":"And now you must allow me to repeat of the just the blessings which you\r were attributing to the fortunate unjust. I shall say of them, what you\r were saying of the others, that as they grow older, they become rulers\r in their own city if they care to be; they marry whom they like and\r give in marriage to whom they will; all that you said of the others I\r now say of these. And, on the other hand, of the unjust I say that the\r greater number, even though they escape in their youth, are found out\r at last and look foolish at the end of their course, and when they come\r to be old and miserable ar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2390"},"sequenceIndex":2851},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2391","text":"These, then, are the prizes and rewards and gifts which are bestowed\r upon the just by gods and men in this present life, in addition to the\r other good things which justice of herself provides.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2391"},"sequenceIndex":2852},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2392","text":"And yet, I said, all these are as nothing either in number or greatness\r in comparison with those other recompenses which await both just and\r unjust after death. And you ought to hear them, and then both just and\r unjust will have received from us a full payment of the debt which the\r argument owes to them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2392"},"sequenceIndex":2853},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2393","text":"Well, I said, I will tell you a tale; not one of the tales which\r Odysseus tells to the hero Alcinous, yet this too is a tale of a hero,\r Er the son of Armenius, a Pamphylian by birth. He was slain in battle,\r and ten days afterwards, when the bodies of the dead were taken up\r already in a state of corruption, his body was found unaffected by\r decay, and carried away home to be buried. And on the twelfth day, as\r he was lying on the funeral pile, he returned to life and told them\r what he had seen in the other world. He said that when his soul left\r the body he went on a journey with a great c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2393"},"sequenceIndex":2854},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2394","text":"Now when the spirits which were in the meadow had tarried seven days,\r on the eighth they were obliged to proceed on their journey, and, on\r the fourth day after, he said that they came to a place where they\r could see from above a line of light, straight as a column, extending\r right through the whole heaven and through the earth, in colour\r resembling the rainbow, only brighter and purer; another day’s journey\r brought them to the place, and there, in the midst of the light, they\r saw the ends of the chains of heaven let down from above: for this\r light is the belt of heaven, and holds toget","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2394"},"sequenceIndex":2855},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2395","text":"When Er and the spirits arrived, their duty was to go at once to\r Lachesis; but first of all there came a prophet who arranged them in\r order; then he took from the knees of Lachesis lots and samples of\r lives, and having mounted a high pulpit, spoke as follows: ‘Hear the\r word of Lachesis, the daughter of Necessity. Mortal souls, behold a new\r cycle of life and mortality. Your genius will not be allotted to you,\r but you will choose your genius; and let him who draws the first lot\r have the first choice, and the life which he chooses shall be his\r destiny. Virtue is free, and as a man honours","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2395"},"sequenceIndex":2856},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2396","text":"And according to the report of the messenger from the other world this\r was what the prophet said at the time: ‘Even for the last comer, if he\r chooses wisely and will live diligently, there is appointed a happy and\r not undesirable existence. Let not him who chooses first be careless,\r and let not the last despair.’ And when he had spoken, he who had the\r first choice came forward and in a moment chose the greatest tyranny;\r his mind having been darkened by folly and sensuality, he had not\r thought out the whole matter before he chose, and did not at first\r sight perceive that he was fated, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2396"},"sequenceIndex":2857},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2397","text":"All the souls had now chosen their lives, and they went in the order of\r their choice to Lachesis, who sent with them the genius whom they had\r severally chosen, to be the guardian of their lives and the fulfiller\r of the choice: this genius led the souls first to Clotho, and drew them\r within the revolution of the spindle impelled by her hand, thus\r ratifying the destiny of each; and then, when they were fastened to\r this, carried them to Atropos, who spun the threads and made them\r irreversible, whence without turning round they passed beneath the\r throne of Necessity; and when they had all ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2397"},"sequenceIndex":2858},{"id":"plato-the-repu-2398","text":"And thus, Glaucon, the tale has been saved and has not perished, and\r will save us if we are obedient to the word spoken; and we shall pass\r safely over the river of Forgetfulness and our soul will not be\r defiled. Wherefore my counsel is, that we hold fast ever to the\r heavenly way and follow after justice and virtue always, considering\r that the soul is immortal and able to endure every sort of good and\r every sort of evil. Thus shall we live dear to one another and to the\r gods, both while remaining here and when, like conquerors in the games\r who go round to gather gifts, we receive our re","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — The Republic (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"The Republic","section":"2398"},"sequenceIndex":2859},{"id":"plato-symposiu-1","text":"Mr. Bronte afflicted with blindness, and relieved by a successful\r operation for cataract--Charlotte Bronte's first work of fiction, \"The\r Professor\"--She commences \"Jane Eyre\"--Circumstances attending its\r composition--Her ideas of a heroine--Her attachment to home--Haworth in\r December--A letter of confession and counsel.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"1"},"sequenceIndex":2860},{"id":"plato-symposiu-2","text":"State of Charlotte Bronte's health at the commencement of\r 1847--Family trials--\"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\" accepted\r by a publisher--\"The Professor\" rejected--Completion of \"Jane Eyre\",\r its reception and publication--The reviews of \"Jane Eyre\", and the\r author's comments on them--Her father's reception of the book--Public\r interest excited by \"Jane Eyre\"--Dedication of the second edition to\r Mr. Thackeray--Correspondence of Currer Bell with Mr. Lewes on \"Jane\r Eyre\"--Publication of \"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\"--Miss\r Bronte's account of the authoress of \"Wuthering Heights\"--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"2"},"sequenceIndex":2861},{"id":"plato-symposiu-3","text":"The Quarterly Review on \"Jane Eyre\"--Severe illness of Anne Bronte--Her\r last verses--She is removed to Scarborough--Her last hours, and death\r and burial there--Charlotte's return to Haworth, and her loneliness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2862},{"id":"plato-symposiu-4","text":"Commencement and completion of \"Shirley\"--Originals of the characters,\r and circumstances under which it was written--Loss on railway\r shares--Letters to Mr. Lewes and other friends on \"Shirley,\" and the\r reviews of it--Miss Bronte visits London, meets Mr. Thackeray, and makes\r the acquaintance of Miss Martineau--Her impressions of literary men.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"4"},"sequenceIndex":2863},{"id":"plato-symposiu-5","text":"\"Currer Bell\" identified as Miss Bronte at Haworth and the vicinity--Her\r letter to Mr. Lewes on his review of \"Shirley\"--Solitude and\r heavy mental sadness and anxiety--She visits Sir J. and Lady Kay\r Shuttleworth--Her comments on critics, and remarks on Thackeray's\r \"Pendennis\" and Scott's \"Suggestions on Female Education\"--Opinions of\r \"Shirley\" by Yorkshire readers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"5"},"sequenceIndex":2864},{"id":"plato-symposiu-6","text":"An unhealthy spring at Haworth--Miss Bronte's proposed visit to\r London--Her remarks on \"The Leader\"--Associations of her walks on the\r moors--Letter to an unknown admirer of her works--Incidents of her visit\r to London--Her impressions of a visit to Scotland--Her portrait, by\r Richmond--Anxiety about her father.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"6"},"sequenceIndex":2865},{"id":"plato-symposiu-7","text":"Visit to Sir J. and Lady Kay Shuttleworth--The biographer's impressions\r of Miss Bronte--Miss Bronte's account of her visit to the Lakes of\r Westmoreland--Her disinclination for acquaintance and visiting--Remarks\r on \"Woman's Mission,\" Tennyson's \"In Memoriam,\" etc.--Impressions of her\r visit to Scotland--Remarks on a review in the \"Palladium.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"7"},"sequenceIndex":2866},{"id":"plato-symposiu-8","text":"Intended republication of \"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\"--Reaction\r after her visit to Scotland--Her first meeting with Mr. Lewes--Her\r opinion of Balzac and George Sand--A characteristic incident--Account of\r a friendly visit to Haworth Parsonage--Remarks on \"The Roman,\" by Sydney\r Dobell, and on the character of Dr. Arnold--Letter to Mr. Dobell.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"8"},"sequenceIndex":2867},{"id":"plato-symposiu-9","text":"Miss Bronte's visit to Miss Martineau, and estimate of her\r hostess--Remarks on Mr. Ruskin's \"Stones of Venice\"--Preparations for\r another visit to London--Letter to Mr. Sydney Dobell: the moors in\r autumn--Mr. Thackeray's second lecture at Willis's Rooms, and sensation\r produced by Currer Bell's appearance there--Her account of her visit to\r London--She breakfasts with Mr. Rogers, visits the Great Exhibition,\r and sees Lord Westminster's pictures--Return to Haworth and letter\r thence--Her comment on Mr. Thackeray's Lecture--Counsel on development\r of character.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"9"},"sequenceIndex":2868},{"id":"plato-symposiu-10","text":"Remarks on friendship--Letter to Mrs. Gaskell on her and Miss\r Martineau's views of the Great Exhibition and Mr. Thackeray's\r lecture, and on the \"Saint's Tragedy\"--Miss Bronte's feelings\r towards children--Her comments on Mr. J. S. Mill's article on the\r Emancipation of Women--More illness at Haworth Parsonage--Letter\r on Emigration--Periodical returns of illness--Miss Wooler visits\r Haworth--Miss Bronte's impressions of her visit to London--Her account\r of the progress of Villette--Her increasing illness and sufferings\r during winter--Her letter on Mr. Thackeray's Esmond--Revival of sorrows\r","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"10"},"sequenceIndex":2869},{"id":"plato-symposiu-11","text":"Miss Bronte revisits Scarborough--Serious illness and ultimate\r convalescence of her father--Her own illness--\"Villette\" nearly\r completed--Further remarks on \"Esmond\" and \"Uncle Tom's Cabin\"--Letter\r respecting \"Villette\"--Another letter about \"Villette\"--Instance of\r extreme sensibility.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"11"},"sequenceIndex":2870},{"id":"plato-symposiu-12","text":"The biographer's difficulty--Deep and enduring attachment of Mr.\r Nicholls for Miss Bronte--Instance of her self-abnegation--She\r again visits London--Impressions of this visit--Letter to Mrs.\r Gaskell--Reception of the critiques on \"Villette\"--Misunderstanding\r with Miss Martineau--Letter on Mr. Thackeray's portrait--Visit of the\r Bishop of Ripon to Haworth Parsonage--Her wish to see the unfavourable\r critiques on her works--Her nervous shyness of strangers, and its\r cause--Letter on Mr. Thackeray's lectures.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"12"},"sequenceIndex":2871},{"id":"plato-symposiu-13","text":"Letter to Mrs. Gaskell on writing fiction, etc.--The biographer's\r account of her visit to Haworth, and reminiscences of conversations with\r Miss Bronte--Letters from Miss Bronte to her friends--Her engagement to\r Mr. Nicholls, and preparations for the marriage--The marriage ceremony\r and wedding tour--Her happiness in the married state--New symptoms\r of illness, and their cause--The two last letters written by Mrs.\r Nicholls--An alarming change--Her death.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"13"},"sequenceIndex":2872},{"id":"plato-symposiu-14","text":"During this summer of 1846, while her literary hopes were waning, an\r anxiety of another kind was increasing. Her father's eyesight had become\r seriously impaired by the progress of the cataract which was forming.\r He was nearly blind. He could grope his way about, and recognise the\r figures of those he knew well, when they were placed against a strong\r light; but he could no longer see to read; and thus his eager appetite\r for knowledge and information of all kinds was severely balked. He\r continued to preach. I have heard that he was led up into the pulpit,\r and that his sermons were never s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"14"},"sequenceIndex":2873},{"id":"plato-symposiu-15","text":"Under his great sorrow he was always patient. As in times of far greater\r affliction, he enforced a quiet endurance of his woe upon himself. But\r so many interests were quenched by this blindness that he was driven\r inwards, and must have dwelt much on what was painful and distressing\r in regard to his only son. No wonder that his spirits gave way, and\r were depressed. For some time before this autumn, his daughters had\r been collecting all the information they could respecting the probable\r success of operations for cataract performed on a person of their\r father's age. About the end of July,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"15"},"sequenceIndex":2874},{"id":"plato-symposiu-16","text":"\"I just scribble a line to you to let you know where I am, in order\r that you may write to me here, for it seems to me that a letter from\r you would relieve me from the feeling of strangeness I have in this\r big town. Papa and I came here on Wednesday; we saw Mr. Wilson, the\r oculist, the same day; he pronounced papa's eyes quite ready for an\r operation, and has fixed next Monday for the performance of it. Think of\r us on that day! We got into our lodgings yesterday. I think we shall be\r comfortable; at least our rooms are very good, but there is no mistress\r of the house (she is very ill, and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"16"},"sequenceIndex":2875},{"id":"plato-symposiu-17","text":"\"The operation is over; it took place yesterday Mr. Wilson performed\r it; two other surgeons assisted. Mr. Wilson says, he considers it\r quite successful; but papa cannot yet see anything. The affair lasted\r precisely a quarter of an hour; it was not the simple operation of\r couching Mr. C. described, but the more complicated one of extracting\r the cataract. Mr. Wilson entirely disapproves of couching. Papa\r displayed extraordinary patience and firmness; the surgeons seemed\r surprised. I was in the room all the time; as it was his wish that I\r should be there; of course, I neither spoke nor mo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"17"},"sequenceIndex":2876},{"id":"plato-symposiu-18","text":"\"Greatly was I amused by your account of ----'s flirtations; and yet\r something saddened also. I think Nature intended him for something\r better than to fritter away his time in making a set of poor, unoccupied\r spinsters unhappy. The girls, unfortunately, are forced to care for him,\r and such as him, because, while their minds are mostly unemployed, their\r sensations are all unworn, and, consequently, fresh and green; and he,\r on the contrary, has had his fill of pleasure, and can with impunity\r make a mere pastime of other people's torments. This is an unfair state\r of things; the match is n","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"18"},"sequenceIndex":2877},{"id":"plato-symposiu-19","text":"A few days later, she writes thus: \"Papa is still lying in bed, in a\r dark room, with his eyes bandaged. No inflammation ensued, but still it\r appears the greatest care, perfect quiet, and utter privation of light\r are necessary to ensure a good result from the operation. He is very\r patient, but, of course, depressed and weary. He was allowed to try\r his sight for the first time yesterday. He could see dimly. Mr. Wilson\r seemed perfectly satisfied, and said all was right. I have had bad\r nights from the toothache since I came to Manchester.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"19"},"sequenceIndex":2878},{"id":"plato-symposiu-20","text":"All this time, notwithstanding the domestic anxieties which were\r harassing them--notwithstanding the ill-success of their poems--the\r three sisters were trying that other literary venture, to which\r Charlotte made allusion in one of her letters to the Messrs. Aylott.\r Each of them had written a prose tale, hoping that the three might be\r published together. \"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\" are before\r the world. The third--Charlotte's contribution--is yet in manuscript,\r but will be published shortly after the appearance of this memoir.\r The plot in itself is of no great interest; but it ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"20"},"sequenceIndex":2879},{"id":"plato-symposiu-21","text":"The three tales had tried their fate in vain together, at length they\r were sent forth separately, and for many months with still-continued\r ill success. I have mentioned this here, because, among the dispiriting\r circumstances connected with her anxious visit to Manchester, Charlotte\r told me that her tale came back upon her hands, curtly rejected by\r some publisher, on the very day when her father was to submit to his\r operation. But she had the heart of Robert Bruce within her, and failure\r upon failure daunted her no more than him. Not only did \"The Professor\"\r return again to try his chan","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"21"},"sequenceIndex":2880},{"id":"plato-symposiu-22","text":"I believe I have already mentioned that some of her surviving friends\r consider that an incident which she heard, when at school at Miss\r Wooler's, was the germ of the story of Jane Eyre. But of this nothing\r can be known, except by conjecture. Those to whom she spoke upon\r the subject of her writings are dead and silent; and the reader may\r probably have noticed, that in the correspondence from which I have\r quoted, there has been no allusion whatever to the publication of her\r poems, nor is there the least hint of the intention of the sisters to\r publish any tales. I remember, however, many ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"22"},"sequenceIndex":2881},{"id":"plato-symposiu-23","text":"Any one who has studied her writings,--whether in print or in her\r letters; any one who has enjoyed the rare privilege of listening to her\r talk, must have noticed her singular felicity in the choice of words.\r She herself, in writing her books, was solicitous on this point. One set\r of words was the truthful mirror of her thoughts; no others, however\r apparently identical in meaning, would do. She had that strong practical\r regard for the simple holy truth of expression, which Mr. Trench has\r enforced, as a duty too often neglected. She would wait patiently\r searching for the right term, unti","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"23"},"sequenceIndex":2882},{"id":"plato-symposiu-24","text":"The sisters retained the old habit, which was begun in their aunt's\r life-time, of putting away their work at nine o'clock, and beginning\r their study, pacing up and down the sitting room. At this time, they\r talked over the stories they were engaged upon, and described their\r plots. Once or twice a week, each read to the others what she had\r written, and heard what they had to say about it. Charlotte told me,\r that the remarks made had seldom any effect in inducing her to alter\r her work, so possessed was she with the feeling that she had described\r reality; but the readings were of great and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"24"},"sequenceIndex":2883},{"id":"plato-symposiu-25","text":"The writer of the beautiful obituary article on \"the death of Currer\r Bell\" most likely learnt from herself what is there stated, and which I\r will take the liberty of quoting, about Jane Eyre.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"25"},"sequenceIndex":2884},{"id":"plato-symposiu-26","text":"\"She once told her sisters that they were wrong--even morally wrong--in\r making their heroines beautiful as a matter of course. They replied that\r it was impossible to make a heroine interesting on any other terms. Her\r answer was, 'I will prove to you that you are wrong; I will show you a\r heroine as plain and as small as myself, who shall be as interesting\r as any of yours.' Hence 'Jane Eyre,' said she in telling the anecdote:\r 'but she is not myself, any further than that.' As the work went on, the\r interest deepened to the writer. When she came to 'Thornfield' she could\r not stop. Being sh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"26"},"sequenceIndex":2885},{"id":"plato-symposiu-27","text":"This is all, I believe, which can now be told respecting the conception\r and composition of this wonderful book, which was, however, only at its\r commencement when Miss Bronte returned with her father to Haworth, after\r their anxious expedition to Manchester.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"27"},"sequenceIndex":2886},{"id":"plato-symposiu-28","text":"They arrived at home about the end of September. Mr. Bronte was daily\r gaining strength, but he was still forbidden to exercise his sight much.\r Things had gone on more comfortably while she was away than Charlotte\r had dared to hope, and she expresses herself thankful for the good\r ensured and the evil spared during her absence.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"28"},"sequenceIndex":2887},{"id":"plato-symposiu-29","text":"Soon after this some proposal, of which I have not been able to gain a\r clear account, was again mooted for Miss Bronte's opening a school at\r some place distant from Haworth. It elicited the following fragment of a\r characteristic reply:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"29"},"sequenceIndex":2888},{"id":"plato-symposiu-30","text":"\"Leave home!--I shall neither be able to find place nor employment,\r perhaps, too, I shall be quite past the prime of life, my faculties will\r be rusted, and my few acquirements in a great measure forgotten. These\r ideas sting me keenly sometimes; but, whenever I consult my conscience,\r it affirms that I am doing right in staying at home, and bitter are its\r upbraidings when I yield to an eager desire for release. I could hardly\r expect success if I were to err against such warnings. I should like to\r hear from you again soon. Bring ---- to the point, and make him give you\r a clear, not a vagu","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"30"},"sequenceIndex":2889},{"id":"plato-symposiu-31","text":"Whatever might be the nature and extent of this negotiation, the end of\r it was that Charlotte adhered to the decision of her conscience, which\r bade her remain at home, as long as her presence could cheer or comfort\r those who were in distress, or had the slightest influence over him who\r was the cause of it. The next extract gives us a glimpse into the cares\r of that home. It is from a letter dated December 15th.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"31"},"sequenceIndex":2890},{"id":"plato-symposiu-32","text":"\"I hope you are not frozen up; the cold here is dreadful. I do not\r remember such a series of North-Pole days. England might really have\r taken a slide up into the Arctic Zone; the sky looks like ice; the earth\r is frozen; the wind is as keen as a two-edged blade. We have all had\r severe colds and coughs in consequence of the weather. Poor Anne has\r suffered greatly from asthma, but is now, we are glad to say, rather\r better. She had two nights last week when her cough and difficulty of\r breathing were painful indeed to hear and witness, and must have been\r most distressing to suffer; she bore","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"32"},"sequenceIndex":2891},{"id":"plato-symposiu-33","text":"\"I feel as if it was almost a farce to sit down and write to you now,\r with nothing to say worth listening to; and, indeed, if it were not for\r two reasons, I should put off the business at least a fortnight hence.\r The first reason is, I want another letter from you, for your letters\r are interesting, they have something in them; some results of experience\r and observation; one receives them with pleasure, and reads them with\r relish; and these letters I cannot expect to get, unless I reply to\r them. I wish the correspondence could be managed so as to be all on one\r side. The second reason is","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"33"},"sequenceIndex":2892},{"id":"plato-symposiu-34","text":"The next year opened with a spell of cold dreary weather, which told\r severely on a constitution already tried by anxiety and care. Miss\r Bronte describes herself as having utterly lost her appetite, and as\r looking \"grey, old, worn and sunk,\" from her sufferings during the\r inclement season. The cold brought on severe toothache; toothache\r was the cause of a succession of restless miserable nights; and long\r wakefulness told acutely upon her nerves, making them feel with\r redoubled sensitiveness all the harass of her oppressive life. Yet she\r would not allow herself to lay her bad health to t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"34"},"sequenceIndex":2893},{"id":"plato-symposiu-35","text":"\"Even at the risk of appearing very exacting, I can't help saying that I\r should like a letter as long as your last, every time you write. Short\r notes give one the feeling of a very small piece of a very good thing\r to eat,--they set the appetite on edge, and don't satisfy it,--a letter\r leaves you more contented; and yet, after all, I am very glad to get\r notes; so don't think, when you are pinched for time and materials, that\r it is useless to write a few lines; be assured, a few lines are very\r acceptable as far as they go; and though I like long letters, I would\r by no means have you to m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"35"},"sequenceIndex":2894},{"id":"plato-symposiu-36","text":"\"It is at Haworth, if all be well, that we must next see each other\r again. I owe you a grudge for giving Miss M---- some very exaggerated\r account about my not being well, and setting her on to urge my leaving\r home as quite a duty. I'll take care not to tell you next time, when I\r think I am looking specially old and ugly; as if people could not have\r that privilege, without being supposed to be at the last gasp! I shall\r be thirty-one next birthday. My youth is gone like a dream; and very\r little use have I ever made of it. What have I done these last thirty\r years? Precious little.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"36"},"sequenceIndex":2895},{"id":"plato-symposiu-37","text":"The quiet, sad year stole on. The sisters were contemplating near at\r hand, and for a long time, the terrible effects of talents misused and\r faculties abused in the person of that brother, once their fond darling\r and dearest pride. They had to cheer the poor old father, into whose\r heart all trials sank the deeper, because of the silent stoicism of\r his endurance. They had to watch over his health, of which, whatever\r was its state, he seldom complained. They had to save, as much as they\r could, the precious remnants of his sight. They had to order the frugal\r household with increased care, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"37"},"sequenceIndex":2896},{"id":"plato-symposiu-38","text":"In the intervals of such a life as this, \"Jane Eyre\" was making\r progress. \"The Professor\" was passing slowly and heavily from publisher\r to publisher. \"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\" had been accepted by\r another publisher, \"on terms somewhat impoverishing to the two authors;\"\r a bargain to be alluded to more fully hereafter. It was lying in his\r hands, awaiting his pleasure for its passage through the press, during\r all the months of early summer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"38"},"sequenceIndex":2897},{"id":"plato-symposiu-39","text":"The piece of external brightness to which the sisters looked during\r these same summer months, was the hope that the friend to whom so many\r of Charlotte's letters are addressed, and who was her chosen companion,\r whenever circumstances permitted them to be together, as well as a\r favourite with Emily and Anne, would be able to pay them a visit at\r Haworth. Fine weather had come in May, Charlotte writes, and they hoped\r to make their visitor decently comfortable. Their brother was tolerably\r well, having got to the end of a considerable sum of money which he\r became possessed of in the spring,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"39"},"sequenceIndex":2898},{"id":"plato-symposiu-40","text":"\"Friday will suit us very well. I DO trust nothing will now arise to\r prevent your coming. I shall be anxious about the weather on that day;\r if it rains, I shall cry. Don't expect me to meet you; where would be\r the good of it? I neither like to meet, nor to be met. Unless, indeed,\r you had a box or a basket for me to carry; then there would be some\r sense in it. Come in black, blue, pink, white, or scarlet, as you like.\r Come shabby or smart, neither the colour nor the condition signifies;\r provided only the dress contain E----, all will be right.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"40"},"sequenceIndex":2899},{"id":"plato-symposiu-41","text":"But there came the first of a series of disappointments to be borne. One\r feels how sharp it must have been to have wrung out the following words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"41"},"sequenceIndex":2900},{"id":"plato-symposiu-42","text":"\"Your letter of yesterday did indeed give me a cruel chill of\r disappointment. I cannot blame you, for I know it was not your fault. I\r do not altogether exempt ---- from reproach. . . . This is bitter, but I\r feel bitter. As to going to B----, I will not go near the place till you\r have been to Haworth. My respects to all and sundry, accompanied with a\r large amount of wormwood and gall, from the effusion of which you and\r your mother are alone excepted.--C. B.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"42"},"sequenceIndex":2901},{"id":"plato-symposiu-43","text":"\"You are quite at liberty to tell what I think, if you judge proper.\r Though it is true I may be somewhat unjust, for I am deeply annoyed. I\r thought I had arranged your visit tolerably comfortable for you this\r time. I may find it more difficult on another occasion.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"43"},"sequenceIndex":2902},{"id":"plato-symposiu-44","text":"I must give one sentence from a letter written about this time, as it\r shows distinctly the clear strong sense of the writer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"44"},"sequenceIndex":2903},{"id":"plato-symposiu-45","text":"\"I was amused by what she says respecting her wish that, when she\r marries, her husband will, at least, have a will of his own, even should\r he be a tyrant. Tell her, when she forms that aspiration again, she\r must make it conditional if her husband has a strong will, he must also\r have strong sense, a kind heart, and a thoroughly correct notion of\r justice; because a man with a WEAK BRAIN and a STRONG WILL, is merely an\r intractable brute; you can have no hold of him; you can never lead him\r right. A TYRANT under any circumstances is a curse.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"45"},"sequenceIndex":2904},{"id":"plato-symposiu-46","text":"Meanwhile, \"The Professor\" had met with many refusals from different\r publishers; some, I have reason to believe, not over-courteously worded\r in writing to an unknown author, and none alleging any distinct reasons\r for its rejection. Courtesy is always due; but it is, perhaps, hardly to\r be expected that, in the press of business in a great publishing house,\r they should find time to explain why they decline particular works. Yet,\r though one course of action is not to be wondered at, the opposite may\r fall upon a grieved and disappointed mind with all the graciousness of\r dew; and I can well","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"46"},"sequenceIndex":2905},{"id":"plato-symposiu-47","text":"\"As a forlorn hope, we tried one publishing house more. Ere long, in\r a much shorter space than that on which experience had taught him\r to calculate, there came a letter, which he opened in the dreary\r anticipation of finding two hard hopeless lines, intimating that\r 'Messrs. Smith and Elder were not disposed to publish the MS.,' and,\r instead, he took out of the envelope a letter of two pages. He read\r it trembling. It declined, indeed, to publish that tale, for business\r reasons, but it discussed its merits and demerits, so courteously,\r so considerately, in a spirit so rational, with a dis","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"47"},"sequenceIndex":2906},{"id":"plato-symposiu-48","text":"Mr. Smith has told me a little circumstance connected with the reception\r of this manuscript, which seems to me indicative of no ordinary\r character. It came (accompanied by the note given below) in a brown\r paper parcel, to 65 Cornhill. Besides the address to Messrs. Smith and\r Co., there were on it those of other publishers to whom the tale had\r been sent, not obliterated, but simply scored through, so that Messrs.\r Smith at once perceived the names of some of the houses in the trade to\r which the unlucky parcel had gone, without success.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"48"},"sequenceIndex":2907},{"id":"plato-symposiu-49","text":"\"Gentlemen--I beg to submit to your consideration the accompanying\r manuscript. I should be glad to learn whether it be such as you approve,\r and would undertake to publish at as early a period as possible.\r Address, Mr. Currer Bell, under cover to Miss Bronte, Haworth, Bradford,\r Yorkshire.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"49"},"sequenceIndex":2908},{"id":"plato-symposiu-50","text":"A little circumstance may be mentioned here, though it belongs to a\r somewhat earlier period, as showing Miss Bronte's inexperience of the\r ways of the world, and willing deference to the opinion of others. She\r had written to a publisher about one of her manuscripts, which she had\r sent him, and, not receiving any reply, she consulted her brother as\r to what could be the reason for the prolonged silence. He at once set\r it down to her not having enclosed a postage-stamp in her letter. She\r accordingly wrote again, to repair her former omission, and apologise\r for it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"50"},"sequenceIndex":2909},{"id":"plato-symposiu-51","text":"\"Gentlemen,--About three weeks since, I sent for your consideration a\r MS. entitled \"The Professor\", a tale by Currer Bell. I should be glad\r to know whether it reached your hands safely, and likewise to learn, at\r your earliest convenience, whether it be such as you can undertake to\r publish.--I am, gentlemen, yours respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"51"},"sequenceIndex":2910},{"id":"plato-symposiu-52","text":"This time her note met with a prompt answer; for, four days later, she\r writes (in reply to the letter which she afterwards characterised in the\r Preface to the second edition of \"Wuthering Heights\", as containing a\r refusal so delicate, reasonable, and courteous, as to be more cheering\r than some acceptances):","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"52"},"sequenceIndex":2911},{"id":"plato-symposiu-53","text":"\"Your objection to the want of varied interest in the tale is, I am\r aware, not without grounds; yet it appears to me that it might be\r published without serious risk, if its appearance were speedily followed\r up by another work from the same pen, of a more striking and exciting\r character. The first work might serve as an introduction, and accustom\r the public to the author's the success of the second might thereby be\r rendered more probable. I have a second narrative in three volumes,\r now in progress, and nearly completed, to which I have endeavoured\r to impart a more vivid interest than be","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"53"},"sequenceIndex":2912},{"id":"plato-symposiu-54","text":"While the minds of the three sisters were in this state of suspense,\r their long-expected friend came to pay her promised visit. She was with\r them at the beginning of the glowing August of that year. They were\r out on the moors for the greater part of the day basking in the golden\r sunshine, which was bringing on an unusual plenteousness of harvest,\r for which, somewhat later, Charlotte expressed her earnest desire that\r there should be a thanksgiving service in all the churches. August was\r the season of glory for the neighbourhood of Haworth. Even the smoke,\r lying in the valley between tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"54"},"sequenceIndex":2913},{"id":"plato-symposiu-55","text":"Throughout this time--during all these confidences--not a word was\r uttered to their friend of the three tales in London; two accepted and\r in the press--one trembling in the balance of a publisher's judgment;\r nor did she hear of that other story \"nearly completed,\" lying in\r manuscript in the grey old parsonage down below. She might have her\r suspicions that they all wrote with an intention of publication some\r time; but she knew the bounds which they set to themselves in their\r communications; nor could she, nor can any one else, wonder at their\r reticence, when remembering how scheme after","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"55"},"sequenceIndex":2914},{"id":"plato-symposiu-56","text":"Mr. Bronte, too, had his suspicions of something going on; but, never\r being spoken to, he did not speak on the subject, and consequently his\r ideas were vague and uncertain, only just prophetic enough to keep him\r from being actually stunned when, later on, he heard of the success of\r \"Jane Eyre\"; to the progress of which we must now return.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"56"},"sequenceIndex":2915},{"id":"plato-symposiu-57","text":"\"I now send you per rail a MS. entitled 'Jane Eyre,' a novel in three\r volumes, by Currer Bell. I find I cannot prepay the carriage of\r the parcel, as money for that purpose is not received at the small\r station-house where it is left. If, when you acknowledge the receipt\r of the MS., you would have the goodness to mention the amount charged\r on delivery, I will immediately transmit it in postage stamps. It is\r better in future to address Mr. Currer Bell, under cover to Miss Bronte,\r Haworth, Bradford, Yorkshire, as there is a risk of letters otherwise\r directed not reaching me at present. To ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"57"},"sequenceIndex":2916},{"id":"plato-symposiu-58","text":"While it was in the press, Miss Bronte went to pay a short visit to\r her friend at B----. The proofs were forwarded to her there, and she\r occasionally sat at the same table with her friend, correcting them; but\r they did not exchange a word on the subject.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"58"},"sequenceIndex":2917},{"id":"plato-symposiu-59","text":"\"I had a very wet, windy walk home from Keighley; but my fatigue quite\r disappeared when I reached home, and found all well. Thank God for it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"59"},"sequenceIndex":2918},{"id":"plato-symposiu-60","text":"\"My boxes came safe this morning. I have distributed the presents.\r Papa says I am to remember him most kindly to you. The screen will be\r very useful, and he thanks you for it. Tabby was charmed with her cap.\r She said, 'she never thought o' naught o' t' sort as Miss sending her\r aught, and, she is sure, she can never thank her enough for it.' I was\r infuriated on finding a jar in my trunk. At first, I hoped it was empty,\r but when I found it heavy and replete, I could have hurled it all the\r way back to B----. However, the inscription A. B. softened me much. It\r was at once kind and villaino","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"60"},"sequenceIndex":2919},{"id":"plato-symposiu-61","text":"When the manuscript of \"Jane Eyre\" had been received by the future\r publishers of that remarkable novel, it fell to the share of a gentleman\r connected with the firm to read it first. He was so powerfully struck\r by the character of the tale, that he reported his impression in very\r strong terms to Mr. Smith, who appears to have been much amused by the\r admiration excited. \"You seem to have been so enchanted, that I do not\r know how to believe you,\" he laughingly said. But when a second reader,\r in the person of a clear-headed Scotchman, not given to enthusiasm, had\r taken the MS. home in the ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"61"},"sequenceIndex":2920},{"id":"plato-symposiu-62","text":"On its publication, copies were presented to a few private literary\r friends. Their discernment had been rightly reckoned upon. They were of\r considerable standing in the world of letters; and one and all returned\r expressions of high praise along with their thanks for the book. Among\r them was the great writer of fiction for whom Miss Bronte felt so strong\r an admiration; he immediately appreciated, and, in a characteristic note\r to the publishers, acknowledged its extraordinary merits.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"62"},"sequenceIndex":2921},{"id":"plato-symposiu-63","text":"The Reviews were more tardy, or more cautious. The Athenaeum and the\r Spectator gave short notices, containing qualified admissions of the\r power of the author. The Literary Gazette was uncertain as to whether it\r was safe to praise an unknown author. The Daily News declined accepting\r the copy which had been sent, on the score of a rule \"never to review\r novels;\" but a little later on, there appeared a notice of the Bachelor\r of the Albany in that paper; and Messrs. Smith and Elder again forwarded\r a copy of \"Jane Eyre\" to the Editor, with a request for a notice. This\r time the work was accep","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"63"},"sequenceIndex":2922},{"id":"plato-symposiu-64","text":"The Examiner came forward to the rescue, as far as the opinions of\r professional critics were concerned. The literary articles in that paper\r were always remarkable for their genial and generous appreciation of\r merit nor was the notice of \"Jane Eyre\" an exception; it was full of\r hearty, yet delicate and discriminating praise. Otherwise, the press in\r general did little to promote the sale of the novel; the demand for it\r among librarians had begun before the appearance of the review in the\r Examiner; the power of fascination of the tale itself made its merits\r known to the public, without th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"64"},"sequenceIndex":2923},{"id":"plato-symposiu-65","text":"I will insert two or three of Miss Bronte's letters to her publishers,\r in order to show how timidly the idea of success was received by one so\r unaccustomed to adopt a sanguine view of any subject in which she was\r individually concerned. The occasions on which these notes were written,\r will explain themselves.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"65"},"sequenceIndex":2924},{"id":"plato-symposiu-66","text":"\"Gentlemen,--The six copies of \"Jane Eyre\" reached me this morning. You\r have given the work every advantage which good paper, clear type, and\r a seemly outside can supply;--if it fails, the fault will lie with the\r author,--you are exempt.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"66"},"sequenceIndex":2925},{"id":"plato-symposiu-67","text":"\"I now await the judgment of the press and the public.--I am, Gentlemen,\r yours respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"67"},"sequenceIndex":2926},{"id":"plato-symposiu-68","text":"\"Gentlemen,--I have received the newspapers. They speak quite as\r favourably of \"Jane Eyre\" as I expected them to do. The notice in the\r Literary Gazette seems certainly to have been indited in rather a flat\r mood, and the Athenaeum has a style of its own, which I respect, but\r cannot exactly relish; still when one considers that journals of that\r standing have a dignity to maintain which would be deranged by a too\r cordial recognition of the claims of an obscure author, I suppose there\r is every reason to be satisfied.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"68"},"sequenceIndex":2927},{"id":"plato-symposiu-69","text":"\"Meantime a brisk sale would be effectual support under the hauteur of\r lofty critics.--I am, Gentlemen, yours respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"69"},"sequenceIndex":2928},{"id":"plato-symposiu-70","text":"\"Gentlemen,--I have to acknowledge the receipt of yours of the 11th\r inst., and to thank you for the information it communicates. The notice\r from the People's Journal also duly reached me, and this morning I\r received the Spectator. The critique in the Spectator gives that view of\r the book which will naturally be taken by a certain class of minds; I\r shall expect it to be followed by other notices of a similar nature. The\r way to detraction has been pointed out, and will probably be pursued.\r Most future notices will in all likelihood have a reflection of the\r Spectator in them. I fear this ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"70"},"sequenceIndex":2929},{"id":"plato-symposiu-71","text":"\"Gentlemen,--I have received the Economist, but not the Examiner; from\r some cause that paper has missed, as the Spectator did on a former\r occasion; I am glad, however, to learn through your letter, that its\r notice of \"Jane Eyre\" was favourable, and also that the prospects of the\r work appear to improve.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"71"},"sequenceIndex":2930},{"id":"plato-symposiu-72","text":"\"I am obliged to you for the information respecting \"Wuthering\r Heights\".--I am, Gentlemen, yours respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"72"},"sequenceIndex":2931},{"id":"plato-symposiu-73","text":"\"Gentlemen,--The Examiner reached me to-day; it had been missent on\r account of the direction, which was to Currer Bell, care of Miss Bronte.\r Allow me to intimate that it would be better in future not to put the\r name of Currer Bell on the outside of communications; if directed simply\r to Miss Bronte they will be more likely to reach their destination\r safely. Currer Bell is not known in the district, and I have no wish\r that he should become known. The notice in the Examiner gratified\r me very much; it appears to be from the pen of an able man who has\r understood what he undertakes to critic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"73"},"sequenceIndex":2932},{"id":"plato-symposiu-74","text":"\"I received likewise seven other notices from provincial papers enclosed\r in an envelope. I thank you very sincerely for so punctually sending me\r all the various criticisms on \"Jane Eyre\".\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"74"},"sequenceIndex":2933},{"id":"plato-symposiu-75","text":"\"Gentlemen,--I beg to acknowledge the receipt of your letter inclosing\r a bank post bill, for which I thank you. Having already expressed my\r sense of your kind and upright conduct, I can now only say that I trust\r you will always have reason to be as well content with me as I am with\r you. If the result of any future exertions I may be able to make should\r prove agreeable and advantageous to you, I shall be well satisfied; and\r it would be a serious source of regret to me if I thought you ever had\r reason to repent being my publishers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"75"},"sequenceIndex":2934},{"id":"plato-symposiu-76","text":"\"You need not apologise, Gentlemen, for having written to me so seldom;\r of course I am always glad to hear from you, but I am truly glad to\r hear from Mr. Williams likewise; he was my first favourable critic; he\r first gave me encouragement to persevere as an author, consequently I\r naturally respect him and feel grateful to him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"76"},"sequenceIndex":2935},{"id":"plato-symposiu-77","text":"\"Excuse the informality of my letter, and believe me, Gentlemen, yours\r respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"77"},"sequenceIndex":2936},{"id":"plato-symposiu-78","text":"There is little record remaining of the manner in which the first news\r of its wonderful success reached and affected the one heart of the three\r sisters. I once asked Charlotte--we were talking about the description\r of Lowood school, and she was saying that she was not sure whether she\r should have written it, if she had been aware how instantaneously it\r would have been identified with Cowan Bridge--whether the popularity\r to which the novel attained had taken her by surprise. She hesitated\r a little, and then said: \"I believed that what had impressed me so\r forcibly when I wrote it, must m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"78"},"sequenceIndex":2937},{"id":"plato-symposiu-79","text":"The sisters had kept the knowledge of their literary ventures from their\r father, fearing to increase their own anxieties and disappointment by\r witnessing his; for he took an acute interest in all that befell his\r children, and his own tendency had been towards literature in the days\r when he was young and hopeful. It was true he did not much manifest\r his feelings in words; he would have thought that he was prepared for\r disappointment as the lot of man, and that he could have met it with\r stoicism; but words are poor and tardy interpreters of feelings to those\r who love one another, and his","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"79"},"sequenceIndex":2938},{"id":"plato-symposiu-80","text":"Now, however, when the demand for the work had assured success to\r \"Jane Eyre,\" her sisters urged Charlotte to tell their father of its\r publication. She accordingly went into his study one afternoon after\r his early dinner, carrying with her a copy of the book, and one or two\r reviews, taking care to include a notice adverse to it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"80"},"sequenceIndex":2939},{"id":"plato-symposiu-81","text":"She informed me that something like the following conversation took\r place between her and him. (I wrote down her words the day after I heard\r them; and I am pretty sure they are quite accurate.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"81"},"sequenceIndex":2940},{"id":"plato-symposiu-82","text":"\"My dear! you've never thought of the expense it will be! It will be\r almost sure to be a loss, for how can you get a book sold? No one knows\r you or your name.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"82"},"sequenceIndex":2941},{"id":"plato-symposiu-83","text":"\"But, papa, I don't think it will be a loss; no more will you, if you\r will just let me read you a review or two, and tell you more about it.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"83"},"sequenceIndex":2942},{"id":"plato-symposiu-84","text":"So she sate down and read some of the reviews to her father; and then,\r giving him the copy of \"Jane Eyre\" that she intended for him, she left\r him to read it. When he came in to tea, he said, \"Girls, do you know\r Charlotte has been writing a book, and it is much better than likely?\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"84"},"sequenceIndex":2943},{"id":"plato-symposiu-85","text":"But while the existence of Currer Bell, the author, was like a piece of\r a dream to the quiet inhabitants of Haworth Parsonage, who went on with\r their uniform household life,--their cares for their brother being its\r only variety,--the whole reading-world of England was in a ferment to\r discover the unknown author. Even the publishers of \"Jane Eyre\" were\r ignorant whether Currer Bell was a real or an assumed name,--whether it\r belonged to a man or a woman. In every town people sought out the list\r of their friends and acquaintances, and turned away in disappointment.\r No one they knew had gen","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"85"},"sequenceIndex":2944},{"id":"plato-symposiu-86","text":"I am not going to write an analysis of a book with which every one who\r reads this biography is sure to be acquainted; much less a criticism\r upon a work, which the great flood of public opinion has lifted up from\r the obscurity in which it first appeared, and laid high and safe on the\r everlasting hills of fame.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"86"},"sequenceIndex":2945},{"id":"plato-symposiu-87","text":"Before me lies a packet of extracts from newspapers and periodicals,\r which Mr. Bronte has sent me. It is touching to look them over, and see\r how there is hardly any notice, however short and clumsily-worded, in\r any obscure provincial paper, but what has been cut out and carefully\r ticketed with its date by the poor, bereaved father,--so proud when he\r first read them--so desolate now. For one and all are full of praise\r of this great, unknown genius, which suddenly appeared amongst us.\r Conjecture as to the authorship ran about like wild-fire. People in\r London, smooth and polished as the A","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"87"},"sequenceIndex":2946},{"id":"plato-symposiu-88","text":"When the second edition appeared, in the January of the following\r year, with the dedication to Mr. Thackeray, people looked at each\r other and wondered afresh. But Currer Bell knew no more of William\r Makepeace Thackeray as an individual man--of his life, age, fortunes, or\r circumstances--than she did of those of Mr. Michael Angelo Titmarsh. The\r one had placed his name as author upon the title-page of Vanity Fair,\r the other had not. She was thankful for the opportunity of expressing\r her high admiration of a writer, whom, as she says, she regarded \"as the\r social regenerator of his day--as ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"88"},"sequenceIndex":2947},{"id":"plato-symposiu-89","text":"Anne Bronte had been more than usually delicate all the summer, and\r her sensitive spirit had been deeply affected by the great anxiety of\r her home. But now that \"Jane Eyre\" gave such indications of success,\r Charlotte began to plan schemes of future pleasure,--perhaps relaxation\r from care, would be the more correct expression,--for their darling\r younger sister, the \"little one\" of the household. But, although Anne\r was cheered for a time by Charlotte's success, the fact was, that\r neither her spirits nor her bodily strength were such as to incline\r her to much active exertion, and she led ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"89"},"sequenceIndex":2948},{"id":"plato-symposiu-90","text":"Any author of a successful novel is liable to an inroad of letters\r from unknown readers, containing commendation--sometimes of so\r fulsome and indiscriminating a character as to remind the recipient\r of Dr. Johnson's famous speech to one who offered presumptuous and\r injudicious praise--sometimes saying merely a few words, which have\r power to stir the heart \"as with the sound of a trumpet,\" and in the\r high humility they excite, to call forth strong resolutions to make\r all future efforts worthy of such praise; and occasionally containing\r that true appreciation of both merits and demerits, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"90"},"sequenceIndex":2949},{"id":"plato-symposiu-91","text":"\"When 'Jane Eyre' first appeared, the publishers courteously sent me\r a copy. The enthusiasm with which I read it, made me go down to Mr.\r Parker, and propose to write a review of it for Frazer's Magazine.\r He would not consent to an unknown novel--for the papers had not yet\r declared themselves--receiving such importance, but thought it might\r make one on 'Recent Novels: English and French'--which appeared in\r Frazer, December, 1847. Meanwhile I had written to Miss Bronte to\r tell her the delight with which her book filled me; and seem to have\r sermonised her, to judge from her reply.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"91"},"sequenceIndex":2950},{"id":"plato-symposiu-92","text":"\"Dear Sir,--Your letter reached me yesterday; I beg to assure you, that\r I appreciate fully the intention with which it was written, and I thank\r you sincerely both for its cheering commendation and valuable advice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"92"},"sequenceIndex":2951},{"id":"plato-symposiu-93","text":"\"You warn me to beware of melodrama, and you exhort me to adhere to the\r real. When I first began to write, so impressed was I with the truth of\r the principles you advocate, that I determined to take Nature and Truth\r as my sole guides, and to follow in their very footprints; I restrained\r imagination, eschewed romance, repressed excitement; over-bright\r colouring, too, I avoided, and sought to produce something which should\r be soft, grave, and true.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"93"},"sequenceIndex":2952},{"id":"plato-symposiu-94","text":"\"My work (a tale in one volume) being completed, I offered it to a\r publisher. He said it was original, faithful to nature, but he did not\r feel warranted in accepting it; such a work would not sell. I tried\r six publishers in succession; they all told me it was deficient in\r 'startling incident' and 'thrilling excitement,' that it would never\r suit the circulating libraries, and, as it was on those libraries the\r success of works of fiction mainly depended, they could not undertake to\r publish what would be overlooked there.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"94"},"sequenceIndex":2953},{"id":"plato-symposiu-95","text":"\"'Jane Eyre' was rather objected to at first, on the same grounds, but\r finally found acceptance.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"95"},"sequenceIndex":2954},{"id":"plato-symposiu-96","text":"\"I mention this to you, not with a view of pleading exemption from\r censure, but in order to direct your attention to the root of certain\r literary evils. If, in your forthcoming article in Frazer, you would\r bestow a few words of enlightenment on the public who support the\r circulating libraries, you might, with your powers, do some good.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"96"},"sequenceIndex":2955},{"id":"plato-symposiu-97","text":"\"You advise me, too, not to stray far from the ground of experience, as\r I become weak when I enter the region of fiction; and you say, 'real\r experience is perennially interesting, and to all men.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"97"},"sequenceIndex":2956},{"id":"plato-symposiu-98","text":"\"I feel that this also is true; but, dear Sir, is not the real\r experience of each individual very limited? And, if a writer dwells upon\r that solely or principally, is he not in danger of repeating himself,\r and also of becoming an egotist? Then, too, imagination is a strong,\r restless faculty, which claims to be heard and exercised: are we to be\r quite deaf to her cry, and insensate to her struggles? When she shows\r us bright pictures, are we never to look at them, and try to reproduce\r them? And when she is eloquent, and speaks rapidly and urgently in our\r ear, are we not to write to her di","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"98"},"sequenceIndex":2957},{"id":"plato-symposiu-99","text":"\"I shall anxiously search the next number of Fraser for your opinions on\r these points.--Believe me, dear Sir, yours gratefully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"99"},"sequenceIndex":2958},{"id":"plato-symposiu-100","text":"But while gratified by appreciation as an author, she was cautious as\r to the person from whom she received it; for much of the value of the\r praise depended on the sincerity and capability of the person rendering\r it. Accordingly, she applied to Mr. Williams (a gentleman connected\r with her publishers' firm) for information as to who and what Mr. Lewes\r was. Her reply, after she had learnt something of the character of her\r future critic, and while awaiting his criticism, must not be omitted.\r Besides the reference to him, it contains some amusing allusions to the\r perplexity which began to b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"100"},"sequenceIndex":2959},{"id":"plato-symposiu-101","text":"\"Dear Sir,--I have received the Britannia and the Sun, but not the\r Spectator which I rather regret, as censure, though not pleasant, is\r often wholesome.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"101"},"sequenceIndex":2960},{"id":"plato-symposiu-102","text":"\"Thank you for your information regarding Mr. Lewes. I am glad to hear\r that he is a clever and sincere man: such being the case, I can await\r his critical sentence with fortitude; even if it goes against me, I\r shall not murmur; ability and honesty have a right to condemn, where\r they think condemnation is deserved. From what you say, however, I trust\r rather to obtain at least a modified approval.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"102"},"sequenceIndex":2961},{"id":"plato-symposiu-103","text":"\"Your account of the various surmises respecting the identity of the\r brothers Bell, amused me much: were the enigma solved, it would probably\r be found not worth the trouble of solution; but I will let it alone; it\r suits ourselves to remain quiet, and certainly injures no one else.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"103"},"sequenceIndex":2962},{"id":"plato-symposiu-104","text":"\"The reviewer who noticed the little book of poems, in the Dublin\r Magazine, conjectured that the soi-disant three personages were in\r reality but one, who, endowed with an unduly prominent organ of\r self-esteem, and consequently impressed with a somewhat weighty notion\r of his own merits, thought them too vast to be concentrated in a\r single individual, and accordingly divided himself into three, out of\r consideration, I suppose, for the nerves of the much-to-be-astounded\r public! This was an ingenious thought in the reviewer,--very original\r and striking, but not accurate. We are three.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"104"},"sequenceIndex":2963},{"id":"plato-symposiu-105","text":"\"A prose work, by Ellis and Acton, will soon appear: it should have\r been out, indeed, long since; for the first proof-sheets were already\r in the press at the commencement of last August, before Currer Bell\r had placed the MS. of \"Jane Eyre\" in your hands. Mr.----, however,\r does not do business like Messrs. Smith and Elder; a different spirit\r seems to preside at ---- Street, to that which guides the helm at\r 65, Cornhill. . . . My relations have suffered from exhausting delay\r and procrastination, while I have to acknowledge the benefits of a\r management at once business-like and gentleman-","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"105"},"sequenceIndex":2964},{"id":"plato-symposiu-106","text":"\"I should like to know if Mr. ---- often acts as he has done to my\r relations, or whether this is an exceptional instance of his method. Do\r you know, and can you tell me anything about him? You must excuse me\r for going to the point at once, when I want to learn anything: if my\r questions are importunate, you are, of course, at liberty to decline\r answering them.--I am, yours respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"106"},"sequenceIndex":2965},{"id":"plato-symposiu-107","text":"\"Dear Sir,--I have now read 'Ranthorpe.' I could not get it till a\r day or two ago; but I have got it and read it at last; and in reading\r 'Ranthorpe,' I have read a new book,--not a reprint--not a reflection of\r any other book, but a NEW BOOK.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"107"},"sequenceIndex":2966},{"id":"plato-symposiu-108","text":"\"I did not know such books were written now. It is very different to any\r of the popular works of fiction: it fills the mind with fresh knowledge.\r Your experience and your convictions are made the reader's; and to an\r author, at least, they have a value and an interest quite unusual. I\r await your criticism on 'Jane Eyre' now with other sentiments than I\r entertained before the perusal of 'Ranthorpe.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"108"},"sequenceIndex":2967},{"id":"plato-symposiu-109","text":"\"You were a stranger to me. I did not particularly respect you. I did\r not feel that your praise or blame would have any special weight. I knew\r little of your right to condemn or approve. NOW I am informed on these\r points.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"109"},"sequenceIndex":2968},{"id":"plato-symposiu-110","text":"\"You will be severe; your last letter taught me as much. Well! I shall\r try to extract good out of your severity: and besides, though I am now\r sure you are a just, discriminating man, yet, being mortal, you must be\r fallible; and if any part of your censure galls me too keenly to the\r quick--gives me deadly pain--I shall for the present disbelieve it, and\r put it quite aside, till such time as I feel able to receive it without\r torture.--I am, dear Sir, yours very respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"110"},"sequenceIndex":2969},{"id":"plato-symposiu-111","text":"In December, 1847, \"Wuthering Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\" appeared. The\r first-named of these stories has revolted many readers by the power with\r which wicked and exceptional characters are depicted. Others, again,\r have felt the attraction of remarkable genius, even when displayed on\r grim and terrible criminals. Miss Bronte herself says, with regard to\r this tale, \"Where delineation of human character is concerned, the case\r is different. I am bound to avow that she had scarcely more practical\r knowledge of the peasantry amongst whom she lived, than a nun has of\r the country-people that pass ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"111"},"sequenceIndex":2970},{"id":"plato-symposiu-112","text":"Whether justly or unjustly, the productions of the two younger Miss\r Brontes were not received with much favour at the time of their\r publication. \"Critics failed to do them justice. The immature, but very\r real, powers revealed in 'Wuthering Heights,' were scarcely recognised;\r its import and nature were misunderstood; the identity of its author was\r misrepresented: it was said that this was an earlier and ruder attempt\r of the same pen which had produced 'Jane Eyre.'\" . . . \"Unjust and\r grievous error! We laughed at it at first, but I deeply lament it now.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"112"},"sequenceIndex":2971},{"id":"plato-symposiu-113","text":"Henceforward Charlotte Bronte's existence becomes divided into two\r parallel currents--her life as Currer Bell, the author; her life as\r Charlotte Bronte, the woman. There were separate duties belonging to\r each character--not opposing each other; not impossible, but difficult\r to be reconciled. When a man becomes an author, it is probably merely\r a change of employment to him. He takes a portion of that time which\r has hitherto been devoted to some other study or pursuit; he gives up\r something of the legal or medical profession, in which he has hitherto\r endeavoured to serve others, or relin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"113"},"sequenceIndex":2972},{"id":"plato-symposiu-114","text":"The year 1848 opened with sad domestic distress. It is necessary,\r however painful, to remind the reader constantly of what was always\r present to the hearts of father and sisters at this time. It is well\r that the thoughtless critics, who spoke of the sad and gloomy views\r of life presented by the Brontes in their tales, should know how such\r words were wrung out of them by the living recollection of the long\r agony they suffered. It is well, too, that they who have objected to the\r representation of coarseness and shrank from it with repugnance, as if\r such conceptions arose out of the write","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"114"},"sequenceIndex":2973},{"id":"plato-symposiu-115","text":"\"We have not been very comfortable here at home lately. Branwell has,\r by some means, contrived to get more money from the old quarter, and\r has led us a sad life. . . . Papa is harassed day and night; we have\r little peace, he is always sick; has two or three times fallen down in\r fits; what will be the ultimate end, God knows. But who is without their\r drawback, their scourge, their skeleton behind the curtain? It remains\r only to do one's best, and endure with patience what God sends.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"115"},"sequenceIndex":2974},{"id":"plato-symposiu-116","text":"I suppose that she had read Mr. Lewes' review on \"Recent Novels,\" when\r it appeared in the December of the last year, but I find no allusion to\r it till she writes to him on January 12th, 1848.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"116"},"sequenceIndex":2975},{"id":"plato-symposiu-117","text":"\"Dear Sir,--I thank you then sincerely for your generous review; and it\r is with the sense of double content I express my gratitude, because I\r am now sure the tribute is not superfluous or obtrusive. You were not\r severe on 'Jane Eyre;' you were very lenient. I am glad you told me my\r faults plainly in private, for in your public notice you touch on them\r so lightly, I should perhaps have passed them over thus indicated, with\r too little reflection.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"117"},"sequenceIndex":2976},{"id":"plato-symposiu-118","text":"\"I mean to observe your warning about being careful how I undertake\r new works; my stock of materials is not abundant, but very slender;\r and, besides, neither my experience, my acquirements, nor my powers,\r are sufficiently varied to justify my ever becoming a frequent writer.\r I tell you this, because your article in Frazer left in me an uneasy\r impression that you were disposed to think better of the author of\r 'Jane Eyre' than that individual deserved; and I would rather you had a\r correct than a flattering opinion of me, even though I should never see\r you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"118"},"sequenceIndex":2977},{"id":"plato-symposiu-119","text":"\"If I ever DO write another book, I think I will have nothing of what\r you call 'melodrama;' I think so, but I am not sure. I THINK, too, I\r will endeavour to follow the counsel which shines out of Miss Austen's\r 'mild eyes,' 'to finish more and be more subdued;' but neither am I\r sure of that. When authors write best, or, at least, when they write\r most fluently, an influence seems to waken in them, which becomes their\r master--which will have its own way--putting out of view all behests but\r its own, dictating certain words, and insisting on their being used,\r whether vehement or measured in","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"119"},"sequenceIndex":2978},{"id":"plato-symposiu-120","text":"\"Is it not so? And should we try to counteract this influence? Can we\r indeed counteract it?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"120"},"sequenceIndex":2979},{"id":"plato-symposiu-121","text":"\"I am glad that another work of yours will soon appear; most curious\r shall I be to see whether you will write up to your own principles,\r and work out your own theories. You did not do it altogether in\r 'Ranthorpe'--at least not in the latter part; but the first portion was,\r I think, nearly without fault; then it had a pith, truth, significance\r in it, which gave the book sterling value; but to write so, one must\r have seen and known a great deal, and I have seen and known very little.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"121"},"sequenceIndex":2980},{"id":"plato-symposiu-122","text":"\"Why do you like Miss Austen so very much? I am puzzled on that point.\r What induced you to say that you would have rather written \"Pride and\r Prejudice,' or 'Tom Jones,' than any of the 'Waverley Novels'?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"122"},"sequenceIndex":2981},{"id":"plato-symposiu-123","text":"\"I had not seen 'Pride and Prejudice' till I read that sentence of\r yours, and then I got the book. And what did I find? An accurate,\r daguerreotyped portrait of a commonplace face; a carefully-fenced,\r highly-cultivated garden, with neat borders and delicate flowers; but no\r glance of a bright, vivid physiognomy, no open country, no fresh air, no\r blue hill, no bonny beck. I should hardly like to live with her ladies\r and gentlemen, in their elegant but confined houses. These observations\r will probably irritate you, but I shall run the risk.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"123"},"sequenceIndex":2982},{"id":"plato-symposiu-124","text":"\"Now I can understand admiration of George Sand; for though I never saw\r any of her works which I admired throughout (even 'Consuelo,' which is\r the best, or the best that I have read, appears to me to couple strange\r extravagance with wondrous excellence), yet she has a grasp of mind,\r which, if I cannot fully comprehend, I can very deeply respect; she is\r sagacious and profound;--Miss Austen is only shrewd and observant.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"124"},"sequenceIndex":2983},{"id":"plato-symposiu-125","text":"\"Am I wrong--or, were you hasty in what you said? If you have time, I\r should be glad to hear further on this subject; if not, or if you think\r the questions frivolous, do not trouble yourself to reply.--I am, yours\r respectfully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"125"},"sequenceIndex":2984},{"id":"plato-symposiu-126","text":"\"Dear Sir,--I must write one more note, though I had not intended to\r trouble you again so soon. I have to agree with you, and to differ from\r you.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"126"},"sequenceIndex":2985},{"id":"plato-symposiu-127","text":"\"You correct my crude remarks on the subject of the 'influence'; well, I\r accept your definition of what the effects of that influence should be;\r I recognise the wisdom of your rules for its regulation. . . .","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"127"},"sequenceIndex":2986},{"id":"plato-symposiu-128","text":"\"What a strange lecture comes next in your letter! You say I must\r familiarise my mind with the fact, that 'Miss Austen is not a poetess,\r has no \"sentiment\" (you scornfully enclose the word in inverted commas),\r no eloquence, none of the ravishing enthusiasm of poetry,'--and then you\r add, I MUST 'learn to acknowledge her as ONE OF THE GREATEST ARTISTS, OF\r THE GREATEST PAINTERS OF HUMAN CHARACTER, and one of the writers with\r the nicest sense of means to an end that ever lived.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"128"},"sequenceIndex":2987},{"id":"plato-symposiu-129","text":"\"What I call--what I will bend to, as a great artist then--cannot be\r destitute of the divine gift. But by POETRY, I am sure, you understand\r something different to what I do, as you do by 'sentiment.' It is\r POETRY, as I comprehend the word, which elevates that masculine George\r Sand, and makes out of something coarse, something Godlike. It is\r 'sentiment,' in my sense of the term--sentiment jealously hidden, but\r genuine, which extracts the venom from that formidable Thackeray, and\r converts what might be corrosive poison into purifying elixir.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"129"},"sequenceIndex":2988},{"id":"plato-symposiu-130","text":"\"If Thackeray did not cherish in his large heart deep feeling for his\r kind, he would delight to exterminate; as it is, I believe, he wishes\r only to reform. Miss Austen being, as you say, without 'sentiment,'\r without Poetry, maybe IS sensible, real (more REAL than TRUE), but she\r cannot be great.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"130"},"sequenceIndex":2989},{"id":"plato-symposiu-131","text":"\"I submit to your anger, which I have now excited (for have I not\r questioned the perfection of your darling?); the storm may pass over\r me. Nevertheless, I will, when I can (I do not know when that will be,\r as I have no access to a circulating library), diligently peruse all\r Miss Austen's works, as you recommend. . . . You must forgive me for\r not always being able to think as you do, and still believe me, yours\r gratefully,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"131"},"sequenceIndex":2990},{"id":"plato-symposiu-132","text":"I have hesitated a little, before inserting the following extract from\r a letter to Mr. Williams, but it is strikingly characteristic; and the\r criticism contained in it is, from that circumstance, so interesting\r (whether we agree with it or not), that I have determined to do so,\r though I thereby displace the chronological order of the letters,\r in order to complete this portion of a correspondence which is very\r valuable, as showing the purely intellectual side of her character.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"132"},"sequenceIndex":2991},{"id":"plato-symposiu-133","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I have now read 'Rose, Blanche, and Violet,' and I\r will tell you, as well as I can, what I think of it. Whether it is an\r improvement on 'Ranthorpe' I do not know, for I liked 'Ranthorpe' much;\r but, at any rate, it contains more of a good thing. I find in it the\r same power, but more fully developed.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"133"},"sequenceIndex":2992},{"id":"plato-symposiu-134","text":"\"The author's character is seen in every page, which makes the book\r interesting--far more interesting than any story could do; but it is\r what the writer himself says that attracts far more than what he puts\r into the mouths of his characters. G. H. Lewes is, to my perception,\r decidedly the most original character in the book. . . . The didactic\r passages seem to me the best--far the best--in the work; very acute,\r very profound, are some of the views there given, and very clearly they\r are offered to the reader. He is a just thinker; he is a sagacious\r observer; there is wisdom in his theor","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"134"},"sequenceIndex":2993},{"id":"plato-symposiu-135","text":"\"Mr. Lewes, I divine, with all his talents and honesty, must have some\r faults of manner; there must be a touch too much of dogmatism; a dash\r extra of confidence in him, sometimes. This you think while you are\r reading the book; but when you have closed it and laid it down, and sat\r a few minutes collecting your thoughts, and settling your impressions,\r you find the idea or feeling predominant in your mind to be pleasure at\r the fuller acquaintance you have made with a fine mind and a true heart,\r with high abilities and manly principles. I hope he will not be long\r ere he publishes another b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"135"},"sequenceIndex":2994},{"id":"plato-symposiu-136","text":"\"He gives no charming picture of London literary society, and especially\r the female part of it; but all coteries, whether they be literary,\r scientific, political, or religious, must, it seems to me, have a\r tendency to change truth into affectation. When people belong to a\r clique, they must, I suppose, in some measure, write, talk, think, and\r live for that clique; a harassing and narrowing necessity. I trust,\r the press and the public show themselves disposed to give the book the\r reception it merits, and that is a very cordial one, far beyond anything\r due to a Bulwer or D'Israeli product","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"136"},"sequenceIndex":2995},{"id":"plato-symposiu-137","text":"Let us return from Currer Bell to Charlotte Bronte. The winter in\r Haworth had been a sickly season. Influenza had prevailed amongst the\r villagers, and where there was a real need for the presence of the\r clergyman's daughters, they were never found wanting, although they\r were shy of bestowing mere social visits on the parishioners. They had\r themselves suffered from the epidemic; Anne severely, as in her case it\r had been attended with cough and fever enough to make her elder sisters\r very anxious about her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"137"},"sequenceIndex":2996},{"id":"plato-symposiu-138","text":"There is no doubt that the proximity of the crowded church-yard rendered\r the Parsonage unhealthy, and occasioned much illness to its inmates.\r Mr. Bronte represented the unsanitary state at Haworth pretty forcibly\r to the Board of Health; and, after the requisite visits from their\r officers, obtained a recommendation that all future interments in the\r churchyard should be forbidden, a new graveyard opened on the hill-side,\r and means set on foot for obtaining a water-supply to each house,\r instead of the weary, hard-worked housewives having to carry every\r bucketful, from a distance of severa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"138"},"sequenceIndex":2997},{"id":"plato-symposiu-139","text":"In February, 1848, Louis Philippe was dethroned. The quick succession\r of events at that time called forth the following expression of Miss\r Bronte's thoughts on the subject, in a letter addressed to Miss Wooler,\r and dated March 31st.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"139"},"sequenceIndex":2998},{"id":"plato-symposiu-140","text":"\"I remember well wishing my lot had been cast in the troubled times of\r the late war, and seeing in its exciting incidents a kind of stimulating\r charm, which it made my pulses beat fast to think of I remember even,\r I think; being a little impatient, that you would not fully sympathise\r with my feelings on those subjects; that you heard my aspirations and\r speculations very tranquilly, and by no means seemed to think the\r flaming swords could be any pleasant addition to Paradise. I have now\r out-lived youth; and, though I dare not say that I have outlived all its\r illusions--that the romance ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"140"},"sequenceIndex":2999},{"id":"plato-symposiu-141","text":"Her birthday came round. She wrote to the friend whose birthday was\r within a week of hers; wrote the accustomed letter; but, reading it with\r our knowledge of what she had done, we perceive the difference between\r her thoughts and what they were a year or two ago, when she said \"I have\r done nothing.\" There must have been a modest consciousness of having\r \"done something\" present in her mind, as she wrote this year:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"141"},"sequenceIndex":3000},{"id":"plato-symposiu-142","text":"\"I am now thirty-two. Youth is gone--gone,--and will never come back:\r can't help it. . . . It seems to me, that sorrow must come some time to\r everybody, and those who scarcely taste it in their youth, often have\r a more brimming and bitter cup to drain in after life; whereas, those\r who exhaust the dregs early, who drink the lees before the wine, may\r reasonably hope for more palatable draughts to succeed.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"142"},"sequenceIndex":3001},{"id":"plato-symposiu-143","text":"The authorship of \"Jane Eyre\" was as yet a close secret in the Bronte\r family; not even this friend, who was all but a sister knew more about\r it than the rest of the world. She might conjecture, it is true, both\r from her knowledge of previous habits, and from the suspicious fact of\r the proofs having been corrected at B----, that some literary project\r was afoot; but she knew nothing, and wisely said nothing, until she\r heard a report from others, that Charlotte Bronte was an author--had\r published a novel! Then she wrote to her; and received the two following\r letters; confirmatory enough, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"143"},"sequenceIndex":3002},{"id":"plato-symposiu-144","text":"\"Write another letter, and explain that last note of yours distinctly.\r If your allusions are to myself, which I suppose they are, understand\r this,--I have given no one a right to gossip about me, and am not to be\r judged by frivolous conjectures, emanating from any quarter whatever.\r Let me know what you heard, and from whom you heard it.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"144"},"sequenceIndex":3003},{"id":"plato-symposiu-145","text":"\"All I can say to you about a certain matter is this: the report--if\r report there be--and if the lady, who seems to have been rather\r mystified, had not dreamt what she fancied had been told to her--must\r have had its origin in some absurd misunderstanding. I have given NO\r ONE a right either to affirm, or to hint, in the most distant manner,\r that I was 'publishing'--(humbug!) Whoever has said it--if any one has,\r which I doubt--is no friend of mine. Though twenty books were ascribed\r to me, I should own none. I scout the idea utterly. Whoever, after\r I have distinctly rejected the charge, u","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"145"},"sequenceIndex":3004},{"id":"plato-symposiu-146","text":"The reason why Miss Bronte was so anxious to preserve her secret, was, I\r am told, that she had pledged her word to her sisters that it should not\r be revealed through her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"146"},"sequenceIndex":3005},{"id":"plato-symposiu-147","text":"The dilemmas attendant on the publication of the sisters' novels, under\r assumed names, were increasing upon them. Many critics insisted on\r believing, that all the fictions published as by three Bells were the\r works of one author, but written at different periods of his development\r and maturity. No doubt, this suspicion affected the reception of the\r books. Ever since the completion of Anne Bronte's tale of \"Agnes Grey\",\r she had been labouring at a second, \"The Tenant of Wildfell Hall.\" It\r is little known; the subject--the deterioration of a character, whose\r profligacy and ruin took thei","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"147"},"sequenceIndex":3006},{"id":"plato-symposiu-148","text":"In the June of this year, 'The Tenant of Wildfell Hall' was sufficiently\r near its completion to be submitted to the person who had previously\r published for Ellis and Acton Bell.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"148"},"sequenceIndex":3007},{"id":"plato-symposiu-149","text":"In consequence of his mode of doing business, considerable annoyance\r was occasioned both to Miss Bronte and to them. The circumstances,\r as detailed in a letter of hers to a friend in New Zealand, were\r these:--One morning, at the beginning of July, a communication was\r received at the Parsonage from Messrs. Smith and Elder, which disturbed\r its quiet inmates not a little, as, though the matter brought under\r their notice was merely referred to as one which affected their literary\r reputation, they conceived it to have a bearing likewise upon their\r character. \"Jane Eyre\" had had a great run ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"149"},"sequenceIndex":3008},{"id":"plato-symposiu-150","text":"Though Messrs. Smith and Elder distinctly stated in their letter that\r they did not share in such \"belief,\" the sisters were impatient till\r they had shown its utter groundlessness, and set themselves perfectly\r straight. With rapid decision, they resolved that Charlotte and Anne\r should start, for London, that very day, in order to prove their\r separate identity to Messrs. Smith and Elder, and demand from the\r credulous publisher his reasons for a \"belief\" so directly at variance\r with an assurance which had several times been given to him. Having\r arrived at this determination, they made the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"150"},"sequenceIndex":3009},{"id":"plato-symposiu-151","text":"About eight o'clock on the Saturday morning, they arrived at the Chapter\r Coffee-house, Paternoster Row--a strange place, but they did not well\r know where else to go. They refreshed themselves by washing, and had\r some breakfast. Then they sat still for a few minutes, to consider what\r next should be done.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"151"},"sequenceIndex":3010},{"id":"plato-symposiu-152","text":"When they had been discussing their project in the quiet of Haworth\r Parsonage the day before, and planning the mode of setting about the\r business on which they were going to London, they had resolved to take\r a cab, if they should find it desirable, from their inn to Cornhill;\r but that, amidst the bustle and \"queer state of inward excitement\" in\r which they found themselves, as they sat and considered their position\r on the Saturday morning, they quite forgot even the possibility of\r hiring a conveyance; and when they set forth, they became so dismayed by\r the crowded streets, and the imped","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"152"},"sequenceIndex":3011},{"id":"plato-symposiu-153","text":"On reaching Mr. Smith's, Charlotte put his own letter into his hands;\r the same letter which had excited so much disturbance at Haworth\r Parsonage only twenty-four hours before. \"Where did you get this?\"\r said he,--as if he could not believe that the two young ladies dressed\r in black, of slight figures and diminutive stature, looking pleased\r yet agitated, could be the embodied Currer and Acton Bell, for whom\r curiosity had been hunting so eagerly in vain. An explanation ensued,\r and Mr. Smith at once began to form plans for their amusement and\r pleasure during their stay in London. He urged ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"153"},"sequenceIndex":3012},{"id":"plato-symposiu-154","text":"The sisters were equally persevering in declining Mr. Smith's\r invitations to stay at his house. They refused to leave their quarters,\r saying they were not prepared for a long stay.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"154"},"sequenceIndex":3013},{"id":"plato-symposiu-155","text":"When they returned back to their inn, poor Charlotte paid for the\r excitement of the interview, which had wound up the agitation and hurry\r of the last twenty-four hours, by a racking headache and harassing\r sickness. Towards evening, as she rather expected some of the ladies\r of Mr. Smith's family to call, she prepared herself for the chance,\r by taking a strong dose of sal-volatile, which roused her a little,\r but still, as she says, she was \"in grievous bodily case,\" when their\r visitors were announced, in full evening costume. The sisters had not\r understood that it had been settled that t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"155"},"sequenceIndex":3014},{"id":"plato-symposiu-156","text":"Charlotte says, in an account which she gives to her friend of this\r visit to London, describing the entrance of her party into the\r Opera-house:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"156"},"sequenceIndex":3015},{"id":"plato-symposiu-157","text":"\"Fine ladies and gentlemen glanced at us, as we stood by the box-door,\r which was not yet opened, with a slight, graceful superciliousness,\r quite warranted by the circumstances. Still I felt pleasurably excited\r in spite of headache, sickness, and conscious clownishness; and I saw\r Anne was calm and gentle, which she always is. The performance was\r Rossini's 'Barber of Seville,'--very brilliant, though I fancy there\r are things I should like better. We got home after one o'clock. We had\r never been in bed the night before; had been in constant excitement for\r twenty-four hours; you may imagin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"157"},"sequenceIndex":3016},{"id":"plato-symposiu-158","text":"\"On Monday we went to the Exhibition of the Royal Academy, the National\r Gallery, dined again at Mr. Smith's, and then went home to tea with Mr.\r Williams at his house.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"158"},"sequenceIndex":3017},{"id":"plato-symposiu-159","text":"\"On Tuesday morning, we left London, laden with books Mr. Smith had\r given us, and got safely home. A more jaded wretch than I looked, it\r would be difficult to conceive. I was thin when I went, but I was meagre\r indeed when I returned, my face looking grey and very old, with strange\r deep lines ploughed in it--my eyes stared unnaturally. I was weak and\r yet restless. In a while, however, these bad effects of excitement went\r off, and I regained my normal condition.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"159"},"sequenceIndex":3018},{"id":"plato-symposiu-160","text":"The impression Miss Bronte made upon those with whom she first became\r acquainted during this visit to London, was of a person with clear\r judgment and fine sense; and though reserved, possessing unconsciously\r the power of drawing out others in conversation. She never expressed\r an opinion without assigning a reason for it; she never put a question\r without a definite purpose; and yet people felt at their ease in talking\r with her. All conversation with her was genuine and stimulating; and\r when she launched forth in praise or reprobation of books, or deeds, or\r works of art, her eloquence wa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"160"},"sequenceIndex":3019},{"id":"plato-symposiu-161","text":"Not the least singular part of their proceedings was the place at which\r the sisters had chosen to stay.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"161"},"sequenceIndex":3020},{"id":"plato-symposiu-162","text":"Paternoster Row was for many years sacred to publishers. It is a narrow\r flagged street, lying under the shadow of St. Paul's; at each end there\r are posts placed, so as to prevent the passage of carriages, and thus\r preserve a solemn silence for the deliberations of the \"Fathers of the\r Row.\" The dull warehouses on each side are mostly occupied at present\r by wholesale stationers; if they be publishers' shops, they show no\r attractive front to the dark and narrow street. Half-way up, on the\r left-hand side, is the Chapter Coffee-house. I visited it last June.\r It was then unoccupied. It had t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"162"},"sequenceIndex":3021},{"id":"plato-symposiu-163","text":"Years later, it became the tavern frequented by university men and\r country clergymen, who were up in London for a few days, and, having\r no private friends or access into society, were glad to learn what was\r going on in the world of letters, from the conversation which they were\r sure to hear in the Coffee-room. In Mr. Bronte's few and brief visits to\r town, during his residence at Cambridge, and the period of his curacy in\r Essex, he had stayed at this house; hither he had brought his daughters,\r when he was convoying them to Brussels; and here they came now, from\r very ignorance where else","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"163"},"sequenceIndex":3022},{"id":"plato-symposiu-164","text":"\"Since those days, I have seen the West End, the parks, the fine\r squares; but I love the City far better. The City seems so much more\r in earnest; its business, its rush, its roar, are such serious things,\r sights, sounds. The City is getting its living--the West End but\r enjoying its pleasure. At the West End you may be amused; but in the\r City you are deeply excited.\" (Villette, vol. i. p. 89.)","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"164"},"sequenceIndex":3023},{"id":"plato-symposiu-165","text":"Their wish had been to hear Dr. Croly on the Sunday morning, and Mr.\r Williams escorted them to St. Stephen's, Walbrook; but they were\r disappointed, as Dr. Croly did not preach. Mr. Williams also took them\r (as Miss Bronte has mentioned) to drink tea at his house. On the way\r thither, they had to pass through Kensington Gardens, and Miss Bronte\r was much \"struck with the beauty of the scene, the fresh verdure of\r the turf, and the soft rich masses of foliage.\" From remarks on the\r different character of the landscape in the South to what it was in the\r North, she was led to speak of the softn","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"165"},"sequenceIndex":3024},{"id":"plato-symposiu-166","text":"The next notice I find of Charlotte's life at this time is of a\r different character to anything telling of enjoyment.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"166"},"sequenceIndex":3025},{"id":"plato-symposiu-167","text":"\"Branwell is the same in conduct as ever. His constitution seems much\r shattered. Papa, and sometimes all of us, have sad nights with him. He\r sleeps most of the day, and consequently will lie awake at night. But\r has not every house its trial?\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"167"},"sequenceIndex":3026},{"id":"plato-symposiu-168","text":"While her most intimate friends were yet in ignorance of the fact of\r her authorship of \"Jane Eyre,\" she received a letter from one of them,\r making inquiries about Casterton School. It is but right to give her\r answer, written on August 28th, 1848.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"168"},"sequenceIndex":3027},{"id":"plato-symposiu-169","text":"\"Since you wish to hear from me while you are from home, I will write\r without further delay. It often happens that when we linger at first\r in answering a friend's letter, obstacles occur to retard us to an\r inexcusably late period. In my last, I forgot to answer a question which\r you asked me, and was sorry afterwards for the omission. I will begin,\r therefore, by replying to it, though I fear what information I can\r give will come a little late. You said Mrs. ---- had some thoughts of\r sending ---- to school, and wished to know whether the Clergy Daughters'\r School at Casterton was an eligi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"169"},"sequenceIndex":3028},{"id":"plato-symposiu-170","text":"But the dark cloud was hanging over that doomed household, and gathering\r blackness every hour.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"170"},"sequenceIndex":3029},{"id":"plato-symposiu-171","text":"\"The past three weeks have been a dark interval in our humble home.\r Branwell's constitution had been failing fast all the summer; but still,\r neither the doctors nor himself thought him so near his end as he was.\r He was entirely confined to his bed but for one single day, and was in\r the village two days before his death. He died, after twenty minutes'\r struggle, on Sunday morning, September 24th. He was perfectly conscious\r till the last agony came on. His mind had undergone the peculiar change\r which frequently precedes death, two days previously; the calm of better\r feelings filled it; a ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"171"},"sequenceIndex":3030},{"id":"plato-symposiu-172","text":"I have heard, from one who attended Branwell in his last illness, that\r he resolved on standing up to die. He had repeatedly said, that as long\r as there was life there was strength of will to do what it chose; and\r when the last agony came on, he insisted on assuming the position just\r mentioned. I have previously stated, that when his fatal attack came on,\r his pockets were found filled with old letters from the woman to whom\r he was attached. He died! she lives still,--in May Fair. The Eumenides,\r I suppose, went out of existence at the time when the wail was heard,\r \"Great Pan is dead.\" I ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"172"},"sequenceIndex":3031},{"id":"plato-symposiu-173","text":"\"I think I have now nearly got over the effects of my late illness,\r and am almost restored to my normal condition of health. I sometimes\r wish that it was a little higher, but we ought to be content with such\r blessings as we have, and not pine after those that are out of our\r reach. I feel much more uneasy about my sister than myself just now.\r Emily's cold and cough are very obstinate. I fear she has pain in her\r chest, and I sometimes catch a shortness in her breathing, when she has\r moved at all quickly. She looks very thin and pale. Her reserved nature\r occasions me great uneasiness of m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"173"},"sequenceIndex":3032},{"id":"plato-symposiu-174","text":"I go on now with her own affecting words in the biographical notice of\r her sisters.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"174"},"sequenceIndex":3033},{"id":"plato-symposiu-175","text":"\"But a great change approached. Affliction came in that shape which to\r anticipate is dread; to look back on grief. In the very heat and burden\r of the day, the labourers failed over their work. My sister Emily first\r declined. . . . Never in all her life had she lingered over any task\r that lay before her, and she did not linger now. She sank rapidly.\r She made haste to leave us. . . . Day by day, when I, saw with what a\r front she met suffering, I looked on her with an anguish of wonder and\r love: I have seen nothing like it; but, indeed, I have never seen her\r parallel in anything. Stronger","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"175"},"sequenceIndex":3034},{"id":"plato-symposiu-176","text":"In fact, Emily never went out of doors after the Sunday succeeding\r Branwell's death. She made no complaint; she would not endure\r questioning; she rejected sympathy and help. Many a time did Charlotte\r and Anne drop their sewing, or cease from their writing, to listen with\r wrung hearts to the failing step, the laboured breathing, the frequent\r pauses, with which their sister climbed the short staircase; yet they\r dared not notice what they observed, with pangs of suffering even deeper\r than hers. They dared not notice it in words, far less by the caressing\r assistance of a helping arm or han","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"176"},"sequenceIndex":3035},{"id":"plato-symposiu-177","text":"\"I told you Emily was ill, in my last letter. She has not rallied yet.\r She is VERY ill. I believe, if you were to see her, your impression\r would be that there is no hope. A more hollow, wasted, pallid aspect I\r have not beheld. The deep tight cough continues; the breathing after the\r least exertion is a rapid pant; and these symptoms are accompanied by\r pains in the chest and side. Her pulse, the only time she allowed it be\r to felt, was found to beat 115 per minute. In this state she resolutely\r refuses to see a doctor; she will give no explanation of her feelings,\r she will scarcely allow ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"177"},"sequenceIndex":3036},{"id":"plato-symposiu-178","text":"When a doctor had been sent for, and was in the very house, Emily\r refused to see him. Her sisters could only describe to him what symptoms\r they had observed; and the medicines which he sent she would not take,\r denying that she was ill.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"178"},"sequenceIndex":3037},{"id":"plato-symposiu-179","text":"\"I hardly know what to say to you about the subject which now interests\r me the most keenly of anything in this world, for, in truth, I hardly\r know what to think myself. Hope and fear fluctuate daily. The pain in\r her side and chest is better; the cough, the shortness of breath, the\r extreme emaciation continue. I have endured, however, such tortures\r of uncertainty on this subject that, at length, I could endure it\r no longer; and as her repugnance to seeing a medical man continues\r immutable,--as she declares 'no poisoning doctor' shall come near\r her,--I have written unknown to her, to an ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"179"},"sequenceIndex":3038},{"id":"plato-symposiu-180","text":"\"The ----s (Anne Bronte's former pupils) were here about a week ago.\r They are attractive and stylish-looking girls. They seemed overjoyed to\r see Anne: when I went into the room, they were clinging round her like\r two children--she, meantime, looking perfectly quiet and passive. . . .\r I. and H. took it into their heads to come here. I think it probable\r offence was taken on that occasion,--from what cause, I know not; and\r as, if such be the case, the grudge must rest upon purely imaginary\r grounds,--and since, besides, I have other things to think about, my\r mind rarely dwells upon the subj","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"180"},"sequenceIndex":3039},{"id":"plato-symposiu-181","text":"But Emily was growing rapidly worse. I remember Miss Bronte's shiver at\r recalling the pang she felt when, after having searched in the little\r hollows and sheltered crevices of the moors for a lingering spray of\r heather--just one spray, however withered--to take in to Emily, she saw\r that the flower was not recognised by the dim and indifferent eyes. Yet,\r to the last, Emily adhered tenaciously to her habits of independence.\r She would suffer no one to assist her. Any effort to do so roused the\r old stern spirit. One Tuesday morning, in December, she arose and\r dressed herself as usual, maki","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"181"},"sequenceIndex":3040},{"id":"plato-symposiu-182","text":"\"I should have written to you before, if I had had one word of hope to\r say; but I have not. She grows daily weaker. The physician's opinion was\r expressed too obscurely to be of use. He sent some medicine, which she\r would not take. Moments so dark as these I have never known. I pray for\r God's support to us all. Hitherto He has granted it.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"182"},"sequenceIndex":3041},{"id":"plato-symposiu-183","text":"The morning drew on to noon. Emily was worse: she could only whisper in\r gasps. Now, when it was too late, she said to Charlotte, \"If you will\r send for a doctor, I will see him now.\" About two o'clock she died.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"183"},"sequenceIndex":3042},{"id":"plato-symposiu-184","text":"\"Emily suffers no more from pain or weakness now. She never will suffer\r more in this world. She is gone, after a hard short conflict. She died\r on TUESDAY, the very day I wrote to you. I thought it very possible she\r might be with us still for weeks; and a few hours afterwards, she was in\r eternity. Yes; there is no Emily in time or on earth now. Yesterday we\r put her poor, wasted, mortal frame quietly under the church pavement.\r We are very calm at present. Why should we be otherwise? The anguish of\r seeing her suffer is over; the spectacle of the pains of death is gone\r by; the funeral day ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"184"},"sequenceIndex":3043},{"id":"plato-symposiu-185","text":"\"God has sustained me, in a way that I marvel at, through such agony\r as I had not conceived. I now look at Anne, and wish she were well and\r strong; but she is neither; nor is papa. Could you now come to us for\r a few days? I would not ask you to stay long. Write and tell me if you\r could come next week, and by what train. I would try to send a gig for\r you to Keighley. You will, I trust, find us tranquil. Try to come. I\r never so much needed the consolation of a friend's presence. Pleasure,\r of course, there would be none for you in the visit, except what your\r kind heart would teach you to ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"185"},"sequenceIndex":3044},{"id":"plato-symposiu-186","text":"As the old, bereaved father and his two surviving children followed\r the coffin to the grave, they were joined by Keeper, Emily's fierce,\r faithful bull-dog. He walked alongside of the mourners, and into the\r church, and stayed quietly there all the time that the burial service\r was being read. When he came home, he lay down at Emily's chamber door,\r and howled pitifully for many days. Anne Bronte drooped and sickened\r more rapidly from that time; and so ended the year 1848.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"186"},"sequenceIndex":3045},{"id":"plato-symposiu-187","text":"An article on \"Vanity Fair\" and \"Jane Eyre\" had appeared in the\r Quarterly Review of December, 1848. Some weeks after, Miss Bronte\r wrote to her publishers, asking why it had not been sent to her; and\r conjecturing that it was unfavourable, she repeated her previous\r request, that whatever was done with the laudatory, all critiques\r adverse to the novel might be forwarded to her without fail. The\r Quarterly Review was accordingly sent. I am not aware that Miss Bronte\r took any greater notice of the article than to place a few sentences out\r of it in the mouth of a hard and vulgar woman in \"Shi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"187"},"sequenceIndex":3046},{"id":"plato-symposiu-188","text":"Every one has a right to form his own conclusion respecting the merits\r and demerits of a book. I complain not of the judgment which the\r reviewer passes on \"Jane Eyre.\" Opinions as to its tendency varied then,\r as they do now. While I write, I receive a letter from a clergyman in\r America in which he says: \"We have in our sacred of sacreds a special\r shelf, highly adorned, as a place we delight to honour, of novels which\r we recognise as having had a good influence on character OUR character.\r Foremost is 'Jane Eyre.'\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"188"},"sequenceIndex":3047},{"id":"plato-symposiu-189","text":"Nor do I deny the existence of a diametrically opposite judgment. And so\r (as I trouble not myself about the reviewer's style of composition) I\r leave his criticisms regarding the merits of the work on one side. But\r when--forgetting the chivalrous spirit of the good and noble Southey,\r who said: \"In reviewing anonymous works myself, when I have known the\r authors I have never mentioned them, taking it for granted they had\r sufficient reasons for avoiding the publicity\"--the Quarterly reviewer\r goes on into gossiping conjectures as to who Currer Bell really is, and\r pretends to decide on what ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"189"},"sequenceIndex":3048},{"id":"plato-symposiu-190","text":"\"Anne had a very tolerable day yesterday, and a pretty quiet night last\r night, though she did not sleep much. Mr. Wheelhouse ordered the blister\r to be put on again. She bore it without sickness. I have just dressed\r it, and she is risen and come down-stairs. She looks somewhat pale and\r sickly. She has had one dose of the cod-liver oil; it smells and tastes\r like train oil. I am trying to hope, but the day is windy, cloudy, and\r stormy. My spirits fall at intervals very low; then I look where you\r counsel me to look, beyond earthly tempests and sorrows. I seem to get\r strength, if not consol","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"190"},"sequenceIndex":3049},{"id":"plato-symposiu-191","text":"\"I can scarcely say that Anne is worse, nor can I say she is better. She\r varies often in the course of a day, yet each day is passed pretty much\r the same. The morning is usually the best time; the afternoon and the\r evening the most feverish. Her cough is the most troublesome at night,\r but it is rarely violent. The pain in her arm still disturbs her. She\r takes the cod-liver oil and carbonate of iron regularly; she finds them\r both nauseous, but especially the oil. Her appetite is small indeed.\r Do not fear that I shall relax in my care of her. She is too precious\r not to be cherished with ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"191"},"sequenceIndex":3050},{"id":"plato-symposiu-192","text":"\"As to your queries about myself, I can only say, that if I continue as\r I am I shall do very well. I have not yet got rid of the pains in my\r chest and back. They oddly return with every change of weather; and are\r still sometimes accompanied with a little soreness and hoarseness, but I\r combat them steadily with pitch plasters and bran tea. I should think it\r silly and wrong indeed not to be regardful of my own health at present;\r it would not do to be ill NOW.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"192"},"sequenceIndex":3051},{"id":"plato-symposiu-193","text":"\"I avoid looking forward or backward, and try to keep looking upward.\r This is not the time to regret, dread, or weep. What I have and ought\r to do is very distinctly laid out for me; what I want, and pray for,\r is strength to perform it. The days pass in a slow, dark march; the\r nights are the test; the sudden wakings from restless sleep, the revived\r knowledge that one lies in her grave, and another not at my side, but in\r a separate and sick bed. However, God is over all.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"193"},"sequenceIndex":3052},{"id":"plato-symposiu-194","text":"\"Anne really did seem to be a little better during some mild days last\r week, but to-day she looks very pale and languid again. She perseveres\r with the cod-liver oil, but still finds it very nauseous.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"194"},"sequenceIndex":3053},{"id":"plato-symposiu-195","text":"\"She is truly obliged to you for the soles for her shoes, and finds\r them extremely comfortable. I am to commission you to get her just such\r a respirator as Mrs. ---- had. She would not object to give a higher\r price, if you thought it better. If it is not too much trouble, you may\r likewise get me a pair of soles; you can send them and the respirator\r when you send the box. You must put down the price of all, and we will\r pay you in a Post Office order. \"Wuthering Heights\" was given to you. I\r have sent ---- neither letter nor parcel. I had nothing but dreary news\r to write, so preferred tha","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"195"},"sequenceIndex":3054},{"id":"plato-symposiu-196","text":"\"We received the box and its contents quite safely to-day. The penwipers\r are very pretty, and we are very much obliged to you for them. I hope\r the respirator will be useful to Anne, in case she should ever be well\r enough to go out again. She continues very much in the same state--I\r trust not greatly worse, though she is becoming very thin. I fear\r it would be only self-delusion to fancy her better. What effect the\r advancing season may have on her, I know not; perhaps the return of\r really warm weather may give nature a happy stimulus. I tremble at the\r thought of any change to cold wind o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"196"},"sequenceIndex":3055},{"id":"plato-symposiu-197","text":"\"We have found the past week a somewhat trying one; it has not been\r cold, but still there have been changes of temperature whose effect\r Anne has felt unfavourably. She is not, I trust, seriously worse, but\r her cough is at times very hard and painful, and her strength rather\r diminished than improved. I wish the month of March was well over. You\r are right in conjecturing that I am somewhat depressed; at times I\r certainly am. It was almost easier to bear up when the trial was at its\r crisis than now. The feeling of Emily's loss does not diminish as time\r wears on; it often makes itself most","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"197"},"sequenceIndex":3056},{"id":"plato-symposiu-198","text":"Anne had been delicate all her life; a fact which perhaps made them less\r aware than they would otherwise have been of the true nature of those\r fatal first symptoms. Yet they seem to have lost but little time before\r they sent for the first advice that could be procured. She was examined\r with the stethoscope, and the dreadful fact was announced that her\r lungs were affected, and that tubercular consumption had already made\r considerable progress. A system of treatment was prescribed, which was\r afterwards ratified by the opinion of Dr. Forbes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"198"},"sequenceIndex":3057},{"id":"plato-symposiu-199","text":"For a short time they hoped that the disease was arrested.\r Charlotte--herself ill with a complaint that severely tried her\r spirits--was the ever-watchful nurse of this youngest, last sister. One\r comfort was that Anne was the patientest, gentlest invalid that could\r be. Still, there were hours, days, weeks of inexpressible anguish to be\r borne; under the pressure of which Charlotte could only pray and pray\r she did, right earnestly. Thus she writes on March 24th;--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"199"},"sequenceIndex":3058},{"id":"plato-symposiu-200","text":"\"Anne's decline is gradual and fluctuating; but its nature is not\r doubtful. . . . In spirit she is resigned: at heart she is, I believe,\r a true Christian. . . . May God support her and all of us through\r the trial of lingering sickness, and aid her in the last hour when\r the struggle which separates soul from body must be gone through!\r We saw Emily torn from the midst of us when our hearts clung to her\r with intense attachment. . . She was scarce buried when Anne's health\r failed. . . . These things would be too much, if reason, unsupported by\r religion, were condemned to bear them alone. I","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"200"},"sequenceIndex":3059},{"id":"plato-symposiu-201","text":"All through this illness of Anne's, Charlotte had the comfort of being\r able to talk to her about her state; a comfort rendered inexpressibly\r great by the contrast which it presented to the recollection of Emily's\r rejection of all sympathy. If a proposal for Anne's benefit was made,\r Charlotte could speak to her about it, and the nursing and dying sister\r could consult with each other as to its desirability. I have seen but\r one of Anne's letters; it is the only time we seem to be brought into\r direct personal contact with this gentle, patient girl. In order to give\r the requisite preliminar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"201"},"sequenceIndex":3060},{"id":"plato-symposiu-202","text":"\"I read your kind note to Anne, and she wishes me to thank you sincerely\r for your friendly proposal. She feels, of course, that it would not do\r to take advantage of it, by quartering an invalid upon the inhabitants\r of ----; but she intimates there is another way in which you might\r serve her, perhaps with some benefit to yourself as well as to her.\r Should it, a month or two hence, be deemed advisable that she should go\r either to the sea-side, or to some inland watering-place--and should\r papa be disinclined to move, and I consequently obliged to remain at\r home--she asks, could you be her","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"202"},"sequenceIndex":3061},{"id":"plato-symposiu-203","text":"\"My dear Miss ----,--I thank you greatly for your kind letter, and your\r ready compliance with my proposal, as far as the WILL can go at least. I\r see, however, that your friends are unwilling that you should undertake\r the responsibility of accompanying me under present circumstances. But\r I do not think there would be any great responsibility in the matter.\r I know, and everybody knows, that you would be as kind and helpful as\r any one could possibly be, and I hope I should not be very troublesome.\r It would be as a companion, not as a nurse, that I should wish for your\r company; otherwise I","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"203"},"sequenceIndex":3062},{"id":"plato-symposiu-204","text":"It must have been about this time that Anne composed her last verses,\r before \"the desk was closed, and the pen laid aside for ever.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"204"},"sequenceIndex":3063},{"id":"plato-symposiu-205","text":"\"I hoped that with the brave and strong\r     My portioned task might lie;\r     To toil amid the busy throng,\r     With purpose pure and high.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"205"},"sequenceIndex":3064},{"id":"plato-symposiu-206","text":"\"But God has fixed another part,\r     And He has fixed it well:\r     I said so with my bleeding heart,\r     When first the anguish fell.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"206"},"sequenceIndex":3065},{"id":"plato-symposiu-207","text":"\"Thou God, hast taken our delight,\r     Our treasured hope, away;\r     Thou bid'st us now weep through the night\r     And sorrow through the day.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"207"},"sequenceIndex":3066},{"id":"plato-symposiu-208","text":"\"These weary hours will not be lost,\r     These days of misery,--\r     These nights of darkness, anguish-tost,--\r     Can I but turn to Thee.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"208"},"sequenceIndex":3067},{"id":"plato-symposiu-209","text":"\"With secret labour to sustain\r     In humble patience every blow;\r     To gather fortitude from pain,\r     And hope and holiness from woe.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"209"},"sequenceIndex":3068},{"id":"plato-symposiu-210","text":"\"Thus let me serve Thee from my heart,\r     Whate'er may be my written fate;\r     Whether thus early to depart,\r     Or yet a while to wait.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"210"},"sequenceIndex":3069},{"id":"plato-symposiu-211","text":"\"If Thou should'st bring me back to life,\r     More humbled I should be;\r     More wise--more strengthened for the strife,\r     More apt to lean on Thee.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"211"},"sequenceIndex":3070},{"id":"plato-symposiu-212","text":"\"Should death be standing at the gate,\r     Thus should I keep my vow;\r     But, Lord, whatever be my fate,\r     Oh let me serve Thee now!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"212"},"sequenceIndex":3071},{"id":"plato-symposiu-213","text":"I take Charlotte's own words as the best record of her thoughts and\r feelings during all this terrible time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"213"},"sequenceIndex":3072},{"id":"plato-symposiu-214","text":"\"I read Anne's letter to you; it was touching enough, as you say.\r If there were no hope beyond this world,--no eternity, no life\r to come,--Emily's fate, and that which threatens Anne, would be\r heart-breaking. I cannot forget Emily's death-day; it becomes a more\r fixed, a darker, a more frequently recurring idea in my mind than ever.\r It was very terrible. She was torn, conscious, panting, reluctant,\r though resolute, out of a happy life. But it WILL NOT do to dwell on\r these things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"214"},"sequenceIndex":3073},{"id":"plato-symposiu-215","text":"\"I am glad your friends object to your going with Anne: it would never\r do. To speak truth, even if your mother and sisters had consented, I\r never could. It is not that there is any laborious attention to pay\r her; she requires, and will accept, but little nursing; but there would\r be hazard, and anxiety of mind, beyond what you ought to be subject\r to. If, a month or six weeks hence, she continues to wish for a change\r as much as she does now, I shall (D. V.) go with her myself. It will\r certainly be my paramount duty; other cares must be made subservient to\r that. I have consulted Mr. T----","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"215"},"sequenceIndex":3074},{"id":"plato-symposiu-216","text":"The progress of Anne's illness was slower than that of Emily's had been;\r and she was too unselfish to refuse trying means, from which, if she\r herself had little hope of benefit, her friends might hereafter derive a\r mournful satisfaction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"216"},"sequenceIndex":3075},{"id":"plato-symposiu-217","text":"\"I began to flatter myself she was getting strength. But the change to\r frost has told upon her; she suffers more of late. Still her illness has\r none of the fearful rapid symptoms which appalled in Emily's case. Could\r she only get over the spring, I hope summer may do much for her, and\r then early removal to a warmer locality for the winter might, at least,\r prolong her life. Could we only reckon upon another year, I should be\r thankful; but can we do this for the healthy? A few days ago I wrote\r to have Dr. Forbes' opinion. . . . He warned us against entertaining\r sanguine hopes of recovery","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"217"},"sequenceIndex":3076},{"id":"plato-symposiu-218","text":"\"I was glad to hear that when we go to Scarborough, you will be at\r liberty to go with us, but the journey and its consequences still\r continue a source of great anxiety to me, I must try to put it off two\r or three weeks longer if I can; perhaps by that time the milder season\r may have given Anne more strength,perhaps it will be otherwise; I cannot\r tell. The change to fine weather has not proved beneficial to her so\r far. She has sometimes been so weak, and suffered so much from pain\r in the side, during the last few days, that I have not known what to\r think. . . . She may rally again, and ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"218"},"sequenceIndex":3077},{"id":"plato-symposiu-219","text":"May had come, and brought the milder weather longed for; but Anne was\r worse for the very change. A little later on it became colder, and she\r rallied, and poor Charlotte began to hope that, if May were once over,\r she might last for a long time. Miss Bronte wrote to engage the lodgings\r at Scarborough,--a place which Anne had formerly visited with the family\r to whom she was governess. They took a good-sized sitting-room, and an\r airy double-bedded room (both commanding a sea-view), in one of the best\r situations of the town. Money was as nothing in comparison with life;\r besides, Anne had a ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"219"},"sequenceIndex":3078},{"id":"plato-symposiu-220","text":"\"It is with a heavy heart I prepare; and earnestly do I wish the\r fatigue of the journey were well over. It may be borne better than I\r expect; for temporary stimulus often does much; but when I see the\r daily increasing weakness, I know not what to think. I fear you will\r be shocked when you see Anne; but be on your guard, dear E----, not to\r express your feelings; indeed, I can trust both your self-possession\r and your kindness. I wish my judgment sanctioned the step of going to\r Scarborough, more fully than it does. You ask how I have arranged about\r leaving Papa. I could make no special ar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"220"},"sequenceIndex":3079},{"id":"plato-symposiu-221","text":"They planned to rest and spend a night at York; and, at Anne's desire,\r arranged to make some purchases there. Charlotte ends the letter to her\r friend, in which she tells her all this, with--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"221"},"sequenceIndex":3080},{"id":"plato-symposiu-222","text":"\"I wish it seemed less like a dreary mockery in us to talk of buying\r bonnets, etc. Anne was very ill yesterday. She had difficulty of\r breathing all day, even when sitting perfectly still. To-day she seems\r better again. I long for the moment to come when the experiment of the\r sea-air will be tried. Will it do her good? I cannot tell; I can only\r wish. Oh! if it would please God to strengthen and revive Anne, how\r happy we might be together: His will, however, be done!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"222"},"sequenceIndex":3081},{"id":"plato-symposiu-223","text":"The two sisters left Haworth on Thursday, May 24th. They were to\r have done so the day before, and had made an appointment with their\r friend to meet them at the Leeds Station, in order that they might all\r proceed together. But on Wednesday morning Anne was so ill, that it was\r impossible for the sisters to set out; yet they had no means of letting\r their friend know of this, and she consequently arrived at Leeds station\r at the time specified. There she sate waiting for several hours. It\r struck her as strange at the time--and it almost seems ominous to her\r fancy now--that twice over, from ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"223"},"sequenceIndex":3082},{"id":"plato-symposiu-224","text":"The next day she could bear suspense no longer, and set out for Haworth,\r reaching there just in time to carry the feeble, fainting invalid into\r the chaise which stood at the gate to take them down to Keighley. The\r servant who stood at the Parsonage gates, saw Death written on her\r face, and spoke of it. Charlotte saw it and did not speak of it,--it\r would have been giving the dread too distinct a form; and if this last\r darling yearned for the change to Scarborough, go she should, however\r Charlotte's heart might be wrung by impending fear. The lady who\r accompanied them, Charlotte's belove","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"224"},"sequenceIndex":3083},{"id":"plato-symposiu-225","text":"\"She left her home May 24th, 1849--died May 28th. Her life was calm,\r quiet, spiritual: SUCH was her end. Through the trials and fatigues of\r the journey, she evinced the pious courage and fortitude of a martyr.\r Dependence and helplessness were ever with her a far sorer trial than\r hard, racking pain.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"225"},"sequenceIndex":3084},{"id":"plato-symposiu-226","text":"\"The first stage of our journey was to York; and here the dear invalid\r was so revived, so cheerful, and so happy, we drew consolation, and\r trusted that at least temporary improvement was to be derived from the\r change which SHE had so longed for, and her friends had so dreaded for\r her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"226"},"sequenceIndex":3085},{"id":"plato-symposiu-227","text":"\"By her request we went to the Minster, and to her it was an\r overpowering pleasure; not for its own imposing and impressive grandeur\r only, but because it brought to her susceptible nature a vital and\r overwhelming sense of omnipotence. She said, while gazing at the\r structure, 'If finite power can do this, what is the . . . ?' and here\r emotion stayed her speech, and she was hastened to a less exciting scene.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"227"},"sequenceIndex":3086},{"id":"plato-symposiu-228","text":"\"Her weakness of body was great, but her gratitude for every mercy was\r greater. After such an exertion as walking to her bed-room, she would\r clasp her hands and raise her eyes in silent thanks, and she did this\r not to the exclusion of wonted prayer, for that too was performed on\r bended knee, ere she accepted the rest of her couch.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"228"},"sequenceIndex":3087},{"id":"plato-symposiu-229","text":"\"On the 25th we arrived at Scarborough; our dear invalid having, during\r the journey, directed our attention to every prospect worthy of notice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"229"},"sequenceIndex":3088},{"id":"plato-symposiu-230","text":"\"On the 26th she drove on the sands for an hour; and lest the poor\r donkey should be urged by its driver to a greater speed than her tender\r heart thought right, she took the reins, and drove herself. When joined\r by her friend, she was charging the boy-master of the donkey to treat\r the poor animal well. She was ever fond of dumb things, and would give\r up her own comfort for them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"230"},"sequenceIndex":3089},{"id":"plato-symposiu-231","text":"\"On Sunday, the 27th, she wished to go to church, and her eye\r brightened with the thought of once more worshipping her God amongst\r her fellow-creatures. We thought it prudent to dissuade her from the\r attempt, though it was evident her heart was longing to join in the\r public act of devotion and praise.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"231"},"sequenceIndex":3090},{"id":"plato-symposiu-232","text":"\"She walked a little in the afternoon, and meeting with a sheltered and\r comfortable seat near the beach, she begged we would leave her, and\r enjoy the various scenes near at hand, which were new to us but familiar\r to her. She loved the place, and wished us to share her preference.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"232"},"sequenceIndex":3091},{"id":"plato-symposiu-233","text":"\"The evening closed in with the most glorious sunset ever witnessed.\r The castle on the cliff stood in proud glory gilded by the rays of\r the declining sun. The distant ships glittered like burnished gold;\r the little boats near the beach heaved on the ebbing tide, inviting\r occupants. The view was grand beyond description. Anne was drawn in her\r easy chair to the window, to enjoy the scene with us. Her face became\r illumined almost as much as the glorious scene she gazed upon. Little\r was said, for it was plain that her thoughts were driven by the imposing\r view before her to penetrate forwar","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"233"},"sequenceIndex":3092},{"id":"plato-symposiu-234","text":"\"The night was passed without any apparent accession of illness. She\r rose at seven o'clock, and performed most of her toilet herself, by her\r expressed wish. Her sister always yielded such points, believing it was\r the truest kindness not to press inability when it was not acknowledged.\r Nothing occurred to excite alarm till about 11 A. M. She then spoke of\r feeling a change. She believed she had not long to live. Could she reach\r home alive, if we prepared immediately for departure? A physician was\r sent for. Her address to him was made with perfect composure. She begged\r him to say how long","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"234"},"sequenceIndex":3093},{"id":"plato-symposiu-235","text":"\"Ere long the restlessness of approaching death appeared, and she\r was borne to the sofa; on being asked if she were easier, she looked\r gratefully at her questioner, and said, 'It is not YOU who can give me\r ease, but soon all will be well, through the merits of our Redeemer.'\r Shortly after this, seeing that her sister could hardly restrain her\r grief, she said, 'Take courage, Charlotte; take courage.' Her faith\r never failed, and her eye never dimmed till about two o'clock, when\r she calmly and without a sigh passed from the temporal to the eternal.\r So still, and so hallowed were her last ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"235"},"sequenceIndex":3094},{"id":"plato-symposiu-236","text":"'Where the south sun warms the now dear sod, Where the ocean billows\r lave and strike the steep and turf-covered rock.'\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"236"},"sequenceIndex":3095},{"id":"plato-symposiu-237","text":"Anne died on the Monday. On the Tuesday Charlotte wrote to her father;\r but, knowing that his presence was required for some annual Church\r solemnity at Haworth, she informed him that she had made all necessary\r arrangements for the interment and that the funeral would take place so\r soon, that he could hardly arrive in time for it. The surgeon who had\r visited Anne on the day of her death, offered his attendance, but it was\r respectfully declined.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"237"},"sequenceIndex":3096},{"id":"plato-symposiu-238","text":"Mr. Bronte wrote to urge Charlotte's longer stay at the seaside. Her\r health and spirits were sorely shaken; and much as he naturally longed\r to see his only remaining child, he felt it right to persuade her to\r take, with her friend, a few more weeks' change of scene,--though\r even that could not bring change of thought. Late in June the friends\r returned homewards,--parting rather suddenly (it would seem) from each\r other, when their paths diverged.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"238"},"sequenceIndex":3097},{"id":"plato-symposiu-239","text":"\"I intended to have written a line to you to-day, if I had not received\r yours. We did indeed part suddenly; it made my heart ache that we were\r severed without the time to exchange a word; and yet perhaps it was\r better. I got here a little before eight o'clock. All was clean and\r bright waiting for me. Papa and the servants were well; and all received\r me with an affection which should have consoled. The dogs seemed in\r strange ecstasy. I am certain they regarded me as the harbinger of\r others. The dumb creatures thought that as I was returned, those who had\r been so long absent were not far","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"239"},"sequenceIndex":3098},{"id":"plato-symposiu-240","text":"\"I left Papa soon, and went into the dining-room: I shut the door--I\r tried to be glad that I was come home. I have always been glad\r before--except once--even then I was cheered. But this time joy was\r not to be the sensation. I felt that the house was all silent--the\r rooms were all empty. I remembered where the three were laid--in what\r narrow dark dwellings--never more to reappear on earth. So the sense of\r desolation and bitterness took possession of me. The agony that WAS to\r be undergone, and WAS NOT to be avoided, came on. I underwent it, and\r passed a dreary evening and night, and a m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"240"},"sequenceIndex":3099},{"id":"plato-symposiu-241","text":"\"I do not know how life will pass, but I certainly do feel confidence\r in Him who has upheld me hitherto. Solitude may be cheered, and made\r endurable beyond what I can believe. The great trial is when evening\r closes and night approaches. At that hour, we used to assemble in the\r dining-room--we used to talk. Now I sit by myself--necessarily I am\r silent. I cannot help thinking of their last days, remembering their\r sufferings, and what they said and did, and how they looked in mortal\r affliction. Perhaps all this will become less poignant in time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"241"},"sequenceIndex":3100},{"id":"plato-symposiu-242","text":"\"Let me thank you once more, dear E----, for your kindness to me, which\r I do not mean to forget. How did you think all looking at your home?\r Papa thought me a little stronger; he said my eyes were not so sunken.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"242"},"sequenceIndex":3101},{"id":"plato-symposiu-243","text":"\"I do not much like giving an account of myself. I like better to go out\r of myself, and talk of something more cheerful. My cold, wherever I got\r it, whether at Easton or elsewhere, is not vanished yet. It began in my\r head, then I had a sore throat, and then a sore chest, with a cough, but\r only a trifling cough, which I still have at times. The pain between my\r shoulders likewise amazed me much. Say nothing about it, for I confess\r I am too much disposed to be nervous. This nervousness is a horrid\r phantom. I dare communicate no ailment to Papa; his anxiety harasses me\r inexpressibly.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"243"},"sequenceIndex":3102},{"id":"plato-symposiu-244","text":"\"My life is what I expected it to be. Sometimes when I wake in the\r morning, and know that Solitude, Remembrance, and Longing are to be\r almost my sole companions all day through--that at night I shall go to\r bed with them, that they will long keep me sleepless--that next morning\r I shall wake to them again,--sometimes, Nell, I have a heavy heart of\r it. But crushed I am not, yet; nor robbed of elasticity, nor of hope,\r nor quite of endeavour. I have some strength to fight the battle of\r life. I am aware, and can acknowledge, I have many comforts, many\r mercies. Still I can GET ON. But I do ho","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"244"},"sequenceIndex":3103},{"id":"plato-symposiu-245","text":"\"I write to you freely, because I believe you will hear me with\r moderation--that you will not take alarm or think me in any way worse\r off than I am.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"245"},"sequenceIndex":3104},{"id":"plato-symposiu-246","text":"The tale of \"Shirley\" had been begun soon after the publication of\r \"Jane Eyre.\" If the reader will refer to the account I have given of\r Miss Bronte's schooldays at Roe Head, he will there see how every\r place surrounding that house was connected with the Luddite riots, and\r will learn how stories and anecdotes of that time were rife among the\r inhabitants of the neighbouring villages; how Miss Wooler herself,\r and the elder relations of most of her schoolfellows, must have known\r the actors in those grim disturbances. What Charlotte had heard there\r as a girl came up in her mind when, as a w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"246"},"sequenceIndex":3105},{"id":"plato-symposiu-247","text":"The character of Shirley herself, is Charlotte's representation of\r Emily. I mention this, because all that I, a stranger, have been able\r to learn about her has not tended to give either me, or my readers,\r a pleasant impression of her. But we must remember how little we are\r acquainted with her, compared to that sister, who, out of her more\r intimate knowledge, says that she \"was genuinely good, and truly great,\"\r and who tried to depict her character in Shirley Keeldar, as what Emily\r Bronte would have been, had she been placed in health and prosperity.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"247"},"sequenceIndex":3106},{"id":"plato-symposiu-248","text":"Miss Bronte took extreme pains with \"Shirley.\" She felt that the fame\r she had acquired imposed upon her a double responsibility. She tried\r to make her novel like a piece of actual life,--feeling sure that, if\r she but represented the product of personal experience and observation\r truly, good would come out of it in the long run. She carefully studied\r the different reviews and criticisms that had appeared on \"Jane Eyre,\"\r in hopes of extracting precepts and advice from which to profit.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"248"},"sequenceIndex":3107},{"id":"plato-symposiu-249","text":"Down into the very midst of her writing came the bolts of death. She had\r nearly finished the second volume of her tale when Branwell died,--after\r him Emily,--after her Anne;--the pen, laid down when there were three\r sisters living and loving, was taken up when one alone remained. Well\r might she call the first chapter that she wrote after this, \"The Valley\r of the Shadow of Death.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"249"},"sequenceIndex":3108},{"id":"plato-symposiu-250","text":"I knew in part what the unknown author of \"Shirley\" must have suffered,\r when I read those pathetic words which occur at the end of this and the\r beginning of the succeeding chapter:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"250"},"sequenceIndex":3109},{"id":"plato-symposiu-251","text":"\"Not always do those who dare such divine conflict prevail. Night after\r night the sweat of agony may burst dark on the forehead; the supplicant\r may cry for mercy with that soundless voice the soul utters when its\r appeal is to the Invisible. 'Spare my beloved,' it may implore. 'Heal my\r life's life. Rend not from me what long affection entwines with my whole\r nature. God of Heaven--bend--hear--be clement!' And after this cry and\r strife, the sun may rise and see him worsted. That opening morn, which\r used to salute him with the whispers of zephyrs, the carol of skylarks,\r may breathe, as its","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"251"},"sequenceIndex":3110},{"id":"plato-symposiu-252","text":"\"Then the watcher approaches the patient's pillow, and sees a new and\r strange moulding of the familiar features, feels at once that the\r insufferable moment draws nigh, knows that it is God's will his idol\r should be broken, and bends his head, and subdues his soul to the\r sentence he cannot avert, and scarce can bear. . . .","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"252"},"sequenceIndex":3111},{"id":"plato-symposiu-253","text":"\"No piteous, unconscious moaning sound--which so wastes our strength\r that, even if we have sworn to be firm, a rush of unconquerable tears\r sweeps away the oath--preceded her waking. No space of deaf apathy\r followed. The first words spoken were not those of one becoming\r estranged from this world, and already permitted to stray at times into\r realms foreign to the living.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"253"},"sequenceIndex":3112},{"id":"plato-symposiu-254","text":"She went on with her work steadily. But it was dreary to write without\r any one to listen to the progress of her tale,--to find fault or to\r sympathise,--while pacing the length of the parlour in the evenings,\r as in the days that were no more. Three sisters had done this,--then\r two, the other sister dropping off from the walk,--and now one was left\r desolate, to listen for echoing steps that never came,--and to hear the\r wind sobbing at the windows, with an almost articulate sound.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"254"},"sequenceIndex":3113},{"id":"plato-symposiu-255","text":"But she wrote on, struggling against her own feelings of illness;\r \"continually recurring feelings of slight cold; slight soreness in the\r throat and chest, of which, do what I will,\" she writes, \"I cannot get\r rid.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"255"},"sequenceIndex":3114},{"id":"plato-symposiu-256","text":"\"Papa has not been well at all lately. He has had another attack of\r bronchitis. I felt very uneasy about him for some days--more wretched\r indeed than I care to tell you. After what has happened, one trembles\r at any appearance of sickness; and when anything ails Papa, I feel too\r keenly that he is the LAST--the only near and dear relative I have in\r the world. Yesterday and to-day he has seemed much better, for which I\r am truly thankful. . . .","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"256"},"sequenceIndex":3115},{"id":"plato-symposiu-257","text":"\"From what you say of Mr. ----, I think I should like him very much.\r ---- wants shaking to be put out about his appearance. What does it\r matter whether her husband dines in a dress-coat, or a market-coat,\r provided there be worth, and honesty, and a clean shirt underneath?\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"257"},"sequenceIndex":3116},{"id":"plato-symposiu-258","text":"\"My piece of work is at last finished, and despatched to its\r destination. You must now tell me when there is a chance of your being\r able to come here. I fear it will now be difficult to arrange, as it is\r so near the marriage-day. Note well, it would spoil all my pleasure, if\r you put yourself or any one else to inconvenience to come to Haworth.\r But when it is CONVENIENT, I shall be truly glad to see you. . . . Papa,\r I am thankful to say, is better, though not strong. He is often troubled\r with a sensation of nausea. My cold is very much less troublesome, I am\r sometimes quite free from it","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"258"},"sequenceIndex":3117},{"id":"plato-symposiu-259","text":"\"If duty and the well-being of others require that you should stay at\r home, I cannot permit myself to complain, still, I am very, VERY sorry\r that circumstances will not permit us to meet just now. I would without\r hesitation come to ----, if Papa were stronger; but uncertain as are\r both his health and spirits, I could not possibly prevail on myself to\r leave him now. Let us hope that when we do see each other our meeting\r will be all the more pleasurable for being delayed. Dear E----, you\r certainly have a heavy burden laid on your shoulders, but such burdens,\r if well borne, benefit the ch","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"259"},"sequenceIndex":3118},{"id":"plato-symposiu-260","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I am obliged to you for preserving my secret, being at\r least as anxious as ever (MORE anxious I cannot well be) to keep quiet.\r You asked me in one of your letters lately, whether I thought I should\r escape identification in Yorkshire. I am so little known, that I think I\r shall. Besides, the book is far less founded on the Real, than perhaps\r appears. It would be difficult to explain to you how little actual\r experience I have had of life, how few persons I have known, and how\r very few have known me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"260"},"sequenceIndex":3119},{"id":"plato-symposiu-261","text":"\"As an instance how the characters have been managed, take that of Mr.\r Helstone. If this character had an original, it was in the person of\r a clergyman who died some years since at the advanced age of eighty.\r I never saw him except once--at the consecration of a church--when I\r was a child of ten years old. I was then struck with his appearance,\r and stern, martial air. At a subsequent period, I heard him talked\r about in the neighbourhood where he had resided: some mention him with\r enthusiasm--others with detestation. I listened to various anecdotes,\r balanced evidence against evidence, a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"261"},"sequenceIndex":3120},{"id":"plato-symposiu-262","text":"\"No matter,--whether known or unknown--misjudged, or the contrary,--I\r am resolved not to write otherwise. I shall bend as my powers tend. The\r two human beings who understood me, and whom I understood, are gone:\r I have some that love me yet, and whom I love, without expecting, or\r having a right to expect, that they shall perfectly understand me. I am\r satisfied; but I must have my own way in the matter of writing. The loss\r of what we possess nearest and dearest to us in this world, produces\r an effect upon the character we search out what we have yet left that\r can support, and, when found","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"262"},"sequenceIndex":3121},{"id":"plato-symposiu-263","text":"At the time when this letter was written, both Tabby and the young\r servant whom they had to assist her were ill in bed; and, with the\r exception of occasional aid, Miss Bronte had all the household work to\r perform, as well as to nurse the two invalids.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"263"},"sequenceIndex":3122},{"id":"plato-symposiu-264","text":"The serious illness of the younger servant was at its height, when a\r cry from Tabby called Miss Bronte into the kitchen, and she found the\r poor old woman of eighty laid on the floor, with her head under the\r kitchen-grate; she had fallen from her chair in attempting to rise. When\r I saw her, two years later, she described to me the tender care which\r Charlotte had taken of her at this time; and wound up her account of\r \"how her own mother could not have had more thought for her nor Miss\r Bronte had,\" by saying, \"Eh! she's a good one--she IS!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"264"},"sequenceIndex":3123},{"id":"plato-symposiu-265","text":"But there was one day when the strung nerves gave way--when, as she\r says, \"I fairly broke down for ten minutes; sat and cried like a fool.\r Tabby could neither stand nor walk. Papa had just been declaring that\r Martha was in imminent danger. I was myself depressed with headache\r and sickness. That day I hardly knew what to do, or where to turn.\r Thank God! Martha is now convalescent: Tabby, I trust, will be better\r soon. Papa is pretty well. I have the satisfaction of knowing that my\r publishers are delighted with what I sent them. This supports me. But\r life is a battle. May we all be enable","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"265"},"sequenceIndex":3124},{"id":"plato-symposiu-266","text":"The kind friend, to whom she thus wrote, saw how the poor over-taxed\r system needed bracing, and accordingly sent her a shower-bath--a thing\r for which she had long been wishing. The receipt of it was acknowledged\r as follows:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"266"},"sequenceIndex":3125},{"id":"plato-symposiu-267","text":"\"Sept. 28th, 1849. \". . . Martha is now almost well, and Tabby much\r better. A huge monster-package, from 'Nelson, Leeds,' came yesterday.\r You want chastising roundly and soundly. Such are the thanks you get\r for all your trouble. . . . Whenever you come to Haworth, you shall\r certainly have a thorough drenching in your own shower-bath. I have not\r yet unpacked the wretch.--\"Yours, as you deserve,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"267"},"sequenceIndex":3126},{"id":"plato-symposiu-268","text":"There was misfortune of another kind impending over her. There were\r some railway shares, which, so early as 1846, she had told Miss Wooler\r she wished to sell, but had kept because she could not persuade her\r sisters to look upon the affair as she did, and so preferred running\r the risk of loss, to hurting Emily's feelings by acting in opposition\r to her opinion. The depreciation of these same shares was now\r verifying Charlotte's soundness of judgment. They were in the York and\r North-Midland Company, which was one of Mr. Hudson's pet lines, and had\r the full benefit of his peculiar system o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"268"},"sequenceIndex":3127},{"id":"plato-symposiu-269","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I must not THANK you for, but acknowledge the receipt of\r your letter. The business is certainly very bad; worse than I thought,\r and much worse than my father has any idea of. In fact, the little\r railway property I possessed, according to original prices, formed\r already a small competency for me, with my views and habits. Now,\r scarcely any portion of it can, with security, be calculated upon. I\r must open this view of the case to my father by degrees; and, meanwhile,\r wait patiently till I see how affairs are likely to turn. . . . However\r the matter may terminate, I ought p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"269"},"sequenceIndex":3128},{"id":"plato-symposiu-270","text":"Towards the close of October in this year, she went to pay a visit\r to her friend; but her enjoyment in the holiday, which she had so\r long promised herself when her work was completed, was deadened by a\r continual feeling of ill-health; either the change of air or the foggy\r weather produced constant irritation at the chest. Moreover, she was\r anxious about the impression which her second work would produce on\r the public mind. For obvious reasons an author is more susceptible to\r opinions pronounced on the book which follows a great success, than he\r has ever been before. Whatever be the val","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"270"},"sequenceIndex":3129},{"id":"plato-symposiu-271","text":"When it came out, but before reading it, Mr. Lewes wrote to tell her of\r his intention of reviewing it in the Edinburgh. Her correspondence with\r him had ceased for some time: much had occurred since.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"271"},"sequenceIndex":3130},{"id":"plato-symposiu-272","text":"\"My dear Sir,--It is about a year and a half since you wrote to me; but\r it seems a longer period, because since then it has been my lot to pass\r some black milestones in the journey of life. Since then there have been\r intervals when I have ceased to care about literature and critics and\r fame; when I have lost sight of whatever was prominent in my thoughts\r at the first publication of 'Jane Eyre;' but now I want these things\r to come back vividly, if possible: consequently, it was a pleasure to\r receive your note. I wish you did not think me a woman. I wish all\r reviewers believed 'Currer Be","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"272"},"sequenceIndex":3131},{"id":"plato-symposiu-273","text":"Miss Bronte, as we have seen, had been as anxious as ever to preserve\r her incognito in \"Shirley.\" She even fancied that there were fewer\r traces of a female pen in it than in \"Jane Eyre\"; and thus, when the\r earliest reviews were published, and asserted that the mysterious writer\r must be a woman, she was much disappointed. She especially disliked the\r lowering of the standard by which to judge a work of fiction, if it\r proceeded from a feminine pen; and praise mingled with pseudo-gallant\r allusions to her sex, mortified her far more than actual blame.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"273"},"sequenceIndex":3132},{"id":"plato-symposiu-274","text":"But the secret, so jealously preserved, was oozing out at last. The\r publication of \"Shirley\" seemed to fix the conviction that the writer\r was an inhabitant of the district where the story was laid. And a clever\r Haworth man, who had somewhat risen in the world, and gone to settle\r in Liverpool, read the novel, and was struck with some of the names\r of places mentioned, and knew the dialect in which parts of it were\r written. He became convinced that it was the production of some one in\r Haworth. But he could not imagine who in that village could have written\r such a work except Miss Bronte. ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"274"},"sequenceIndex":3133},{"id":"plato-symposiu-275","text":"\"I was indeed very much interested in the books you sent 'Eckermann's\r Conversations with Goethe,' 'Guesses as Truth,' 'Friends in Council,'\r and the little work on English social life, pleased me particularly,\r and the last not least. We sometimes take a partiality to books as\r to characters, not on account of any brilliant intellect or striking\r peculiarity they boast, but for the sake of something good, delicate,\r and genuine. I thought that small book the production of a lady, and an\r amiable, sensible woman, and I liked it. You must not think of selecting\r any more works for me yet; my st","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"275"},"sequenceIndex":3134},{"id":"plato-symposiu-276","text":"\"I accept your offer respecting the 'Athenaeum;' it is a paper I should\r like much to see, providing that you can send it without trouble. It\r shall be punctually returned.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"276"},"sequenceIndex":3135},{"id":"plato-symposiu-277","text":"In a letter to her friend she complains of the feelings of illness from\r which she was seldom or never free.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"277"},"sequenceIndex":3136},{"id":"plato-symposiu-278","text":"You are not to suppose any of the characters in 'Shirley' intended as\r literal portraits. It would not suit the rules of art, nor of my own\r feelings; to write in that style. We only suffer reality to SUGGEST,\r never to DICTATE. The heroines are abstractions and the heroes also.\r Qualities I have seen, loved, and admired, are here and there put in\r as decorative gems, to be preserved in that sitting. Since you say you\r could recognise the originals of all except the heroines, pray whom did\r you suppose the two Moores to represent? I send you a couple of reviews;\r the one is in the Examiner, wr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"278"},"sequenceIndex":3137},{"id":"plato-symposiu-279","text":"In consequence of this long-protracted state of languor, headache, and\r sickness, to which the slightest exposure to cold added sensations of\r hoarseness and soreness at the chest, she determined to take the evil\r in time, as much for her father's sake as for her own, and to go up to\r London and consult some physician there. It was not her first intention\r to visit anywhere; but the friendly urgency of her publishers prevailed,\r and it was decided that she was to become the guest of Mr. Smith. Before\r she went, she wrote two characteristic letters about \"Shirley,\" from\r which I shall take a fe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"279"},"sequenceIndex":3138},{"id":"plato-symposiu-280","text":"\"'Shirley' makes her way. The reviews shower in fast. . . . The best\r critique which has yet appeared is in the Revue des deux Mondes, a\r sort of European Cosmopolitan periodical, whose head-quarters are at\r Paris. Comparatively few reviewers, even in their praise, evince a just\r comprehension of the author's meaning. Eugene Forcarde, the reviewer\r in question, follows Currer Bell through every winding, discerns every\r point, discriminates every shade, proves himself master of the subject,\r and lord of the aim. With that man I would shake hands, if I saw him.\r I would say, 'You know me, Monsie","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"280"},"sequenceIndex":3139},{"id":"plato-symposiu-281","text":"\"It is like you to pronounce the reviews not good enough, and belongs\r to that part of your character which will not permit you to bestow\r unqualified approbation on any dress, decoration, etc., belonging to\r you. Know that the reviews are superb; and were I dissatisfied with\r them, I should be a conceited ape. Nothing higher is ever said, FROM\r PERFECTLY DISINTERESTED MOTIVES, of any living authors. If all be well,\r I go to London this week; Wednesday, I think. The dress-maker has done\r my small matters pretty well, but I wish you could have looked them\r over, and given a dictum. I insisted o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"281"},"sequenceIndex":3140},{"id":"plato-symposiu-282","text":"At the end of November she went up to the \"big Babylon,\" and was\r immediately plunged into what appeared to her a whirl; for changes, and\r scenes, and stimulus which would have been a trifle to others, were\r much to her. As was always the case with strangers, she was a little\r afraid at first of the family into which she was now received, fancying\r that the ladies looked on her with a mixture of respect and alarm; but\r in a few days, if this state of feeling ever existed, her simple, shy,\r quiet manners, her dainty personal and household ways, had quite done\r away with it, and she says that sh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"282"},"sequenceIndex":3141},{"id":"plato-symposiu-283","text":"\"As to being happy, I am under scenes and circumstances of excitement;\r but I suffer acute pain sometimes,--mental pain, I mean. At the moment\r Mr. Thackeray presented himself, I was thoroughly faint from inanition,\r having eaten nothing since a very slight breakfast, and it was then\r seven o'clock in the evening. Excitement and exhaustion made savage work\r of me that evening. What he thought of me I cannot tell.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"283"},"sequenceIndex":3142},{"id":"plato-symposiu-284","text":"She told me how difficult she found it, this first time of meeting Mr.\r Thackeray, to decide whether he was speaking in jest or in earnest, and\r that she had (she believed) completely misunderstood an inquiry of his,\r made on the gentlemen's coming into the drawing-room. He asked her \"if\r she had perceived the secret of their cigars;\" to which she replied\r literally, discovering in a minute afterwards, by the smile on several\r faces, that he was alluding to a passage in \"Jane Eyre\". Her hosts took\r pleasure in showing her the sights of London. On one of the days which\r had been set apart for s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"284"},"sequenceIndex":3143},{"id":"plato-symposiu-285","text":"Miss Martineau, in acknowledging this note and the copy of \"Shirley,\"\r dated her letter from a friend's house in the neighbourhood of Mr.\r Smith's residence; and when, a week or two afterwards, Miss Bronte\r found how near she was to her correspondent, she wrote, in the name\r of Currer Bell, to propose a visit to her. Six o'clock, on a certain\r Sunday afternoon (Dec. 10th), was the time appointed. Miss Martineau's\r friends had invited the unknown Currer Bell to their early tea; they\r were ignorant whether the name was that of a man or a woman; and had\r had various conjectures as to sex, age, an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"285"},"sequenceIndex":3144},{"id":"plato-symposiu-286","text":"After some discussion on the subject, and a stipulation that she should\r not be specially introduced to any one, some gentlemen were invited by\r Mr. Smith to meet her at dinner the evening before she left town. Her\r natural place would have been at the bottom of the table by her host;\r and the places of those who were to be her neighbours were arranged\r accordingly; but, on entering the dining-room, she quickly passed up\r so as to sit next to the lady of the house, anxious to shelter herself\r near some one of her own sex. This slight action arose out of the same\r womanly seeking after protecti","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"286"},"sequenceIndex":3145},{"id":"plato-symposiu-287","text":"Respecting this particular dinner-party she thus wrote to the Brussels\r schoolfellow of former days, whose friendship had been renewed during\r her present visit to London:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"287"},"sequenceIndex":3146},{"id":"plato-symposiu-288","text":"\"The evening after I left you passed better than I expected. Thanks to\r my substantial lunch and cheering cup of coffee, I was able to wait the\r eight o'clock dinner with complete resignation, and to endure its length\r quite courageously, nor was I too much exhausted to converse; and of\r this I was glad, for otherwise I know my kind host and hostess would\r have been much disappointed. There were only seven gentlemen at dinner\r besides Mr. Smith, but of these five were critics--men more dreaded in\r the world of letters than you can conceive. I did not know how much\r their presence and conversat","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"288"},"sequenceIndex":3147},{"id":"plato-symposiu-289","text":"\"Here I am at Haworth once more. I feel as if I had come out of an\r exciting whirl. Not that the hurry and stimulus would have seemed much\r to one accustomed to society and change, but to me they were very\r marked. My strength and spirits too often proved quite insufficient to\r the demand on their exertions. I used to bear up as long as I possibly\r could, for, when I flagged, I could see Mr. Smith became disturbed; he\r always thought that something had been said or done to annoy me--which\r never once happened, for I met with perfect good breeding even from\r antagonists--men who had done their ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"289"},"sequenceIndex":3148},{"id":"plato-symposiu-290","text":"\"Thackeray is a Titan of mind. His presence and powers impress one\r deeply in an intellectual sense; I do not see him or know him as a man.\r All the others are subordinate. I have esteem for some, and, I trust,\r courtesy for all. I do not, of course, know what they thought of me,\r but I believe most of them expected me to come out in a more marked,\r eccentric, striking light. I believe they desired more to admire and\r more to blame. I felt sufficiently at my ease with all but Thackeray;\r with him I was fearfully stupid.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"290"},"sequenceIndex":3149},{"id":"plato-symposiu-291","text":"She returned to her quiet home, and her noiseless daily duties. Her\r father had quite enough of the spirit of hero-worship in him to make him\r take a vivid pleasure in the accounts of what she had heard and whom she\r had seen. It was on the occasion of one of her visits to London that\r he had desired her to obtain a sight of Prince Albert's armoury, if\r possible. I am not aware whether she managed to do this; but she went\r to one or two of the great national armouries in order that she might\r describe the stern steel harness and glittering swords to her father,\r whose imagination was forcibly ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"291"},"sequenceIndex":3150},{"id":"plato-symposiu-292","text":"Her life at Haworth was so unvaried that the postman's call was the\r event of her day. Yet she dreaded the great temptation of centring all\r her thoughts upon this one time, and losing her interest in the smaller\r hopes and employments of the remaining hours. Thus she conscientiously\r denied herself the pleasure of writing letters too frequently, because\r the answers (when she received them) took the flavour out of the rest\r of her life; or the disappointment, when the replies did not arrive,\r lessened her energy for her home duties.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"292"},"sequenceIndex":3151},{"id":"plato-symposiu-293","text":"The winter of this year in the north was hard and cold; it affected\r Miss Bronte's health less than usual, however, probably because the\r change and the medical advice she had taken in London had done her good;\r probably, also, because her friend had come to pay her a visit, and\r enforced that attention to bodily symptoms which Miss Bronte was too apt\r to neglect, from a fear of becoming nervous herself about her own state\r and thus infecting her father. But she could scarcely help feeling much\r depressed in spirits as the anniversary of her sister Emily's death came\r round; all the recollecti","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"293"},"sequenceIndex":3152},{"id":"plato-symposiu-294","text":"\"What, I sometimes ask, could I do without them? I have recourse to\r them as to friends; they shorten and cheer many an hour that would be\r too long and too desolate otherwise; even when my tired sight will\r not permit me to continue reading, it is pleasant to see them on the\r shelf, or on the table. I am still very rich, for my stock is far from\r exhausted. Some other friends have sent me books lately. The perusal\r of Harriet Martineau's 'Eastern Life' has afforded me great pleasure;\r and I have found a deep and interesting subject of study in Newman's\r work on the Soul. Have you read this wo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"294"},"sequenceIndex":3153},{"id":"plato-symposiu-295","text":"By this time, \"Airedale, Wharfedale, Calderdale, and Ribblesdale\"\r all knew the place of residence of Currer Bell. She compared herself\r to the ostrich hiding its head in the sand; and says that she still\r buries hers in the heath of Haworth moors; but \"the concealment is but\r self-delusion.\" Indeed it was. Far and wide in the West Riding had\r spread the intelligence that Currer Bell was no other than a daughter\r of the venerable clergyman of Haworth; the village itself caught up the\r excitement.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"295"},"sequenceIndex":3154},{"id":"plato-symposiu-296","text":"\"Mr. ----, having finished 'Jane Eyre,' is now crying out for the\r 'other book;' he is to have it next week. . . . Mr. R ---- has finished\r 'Shirley;' he is delighted with it. John ----'s wife seriously thought\r him gone wrong in the head, as she heard him giving vent to roars of\r laughter as he sat alone, clapping and stamping on the floor. He would\r read all the scenes about the curates aloud to papa.\" . . . \"Martha came\r in yesterday, puffing and blowing, and much excited. 'I've heard sich\r news!' she began. 'What about?' 'Please, ma'am, you've been and written\r two books--the grandest book","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"296"},"sequenceIndex":3155},{"id":"plato-symposiu-297","text":"The tone of these extracts is thoroughly consonant with the spirit of\r Yorkshire and Lancashire people, who try as long as they can to conceal\r their emotions of pleasure under a bantering exterior, almost as if\r making fun of themselves. Miss Bronte was extremely touched in the\r secret places of her warm heart by the way in which those who had known\r her from her childhood were proud and glad of her success. All round\r about the news had spread; strangers came \"from beyond Burnley\" to see\r her, as she went quietly and unconsciously into church and the sexton\r \"gained many a half-crown\" for po","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"297"},"sequenceIndex":3156},{"id":"plato-symposiu-298","text":"But there were drawbacks to this hearty and kindly appreciation which\r was so much more valuable than fame. The January number of the Edinburgh\r Review had contained the article on Shirley, of which her correspondent,\r Mr. Lewes, was the writer. I have said that Miss Bronte was especially\r anxious to be criticised as a writer, without relation to her sex as a\r woman. Whether right or wrong, her feeling was strong on this point. Now\r in this review of Shirley, the heading of the first two pages ran thus:\r \"Mental Equality of the Sexes?\" \"Female Literature,\" and through the\r whole article the fa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"298"},"sequenceIndex":3157},{"id":"plato-symposiu-299","text":"A few days after the review appeared, Mr. Lewes received the following\r note,--rather in the style of Anne Countess of Pembroke, Dorset, and\r Montgomery.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"299"},"sequenceIndex":3158},{"id":"plato-symposiu-300","text":"In some explanatory notes on her letters to him, with which Mr. Lewes\r has favoured me, he says:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"300"},"sequenceIndex":3159},{"id":"plato-symposiu-301","text":"\"Seeing that she was unreasonable because angry, I wrote to remonstrate\r with her on quarrelling with the severity or frankness of a review,\r which certainly was dictated by real admiration and real friendship;\r even under its objections the friend's voice could be heard.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"301"},"sequenceIndex":3160},{"id":"plato-symposiu-302","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I will tell you why I was so hurt by that review in the\r Edinburgh; not because its criticism was keen or its blame sometimes\r severe; not because its praise was stinted (for, indeed, I think you\r give me quite as much praise as I deserve), but because after I had said\r earnestly that I wished critics would judge me as an AUTHOR, not as a\r woman, you so roughly--I even thought so cruelly--handled the question\r of sex. I dare say you meant no harm, and perhaps you will not now be\r able to understand why I was so grieved at what you will probably deem\r such a trifle; but grieved I","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"302"},"sequenceIndex":3161},{"id":"plato-symposiu-303","text":"\"However, I will not bear malice against you for it; I know what your\r nature is: it is not a bad or unkind one, though you would often jar\r terribly on some feelings with whose recoil and quiver you could not\r possibly sympathise. I imagine you are both enthusiastic and implacable,\r as you are at once sagacious and careless; you know much and discover\r much, but you are in such a hurry to tell it all you never give yourself\r time to think how your reckless eloquence may affect others; and, what\r is more, if you knew how it did affect them, you would not much care.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"303"},"sequenceIndex":3162},{"id":"plato-symposiu-304","text":"\"However, I shake hands with you: you have excellent points; you can be\r generous. I still feel angry, and think I do well to be angry; but it is\r the anger one experiences for rough play rather than for foul play.--I\r am yours, with a certain respect, and more chagrin,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"304"},"sequenceIndex":3163},{"id":"plato-symposiu-305","text":"As Mr. Lewes says, \"the tone of this letter is cavalier.\" But I thank\r him for having allowed me to publish what is so characteristic of\r one phase of Miss Bronte's mind. Her health, too, was suffering at\r this time. \"I don't know what heaviness of spirit has beset me of\r late\" (she writes, in pathetic words, wrung out of the sadness of her\r heart), \"made my faculties dull, made rest weariness, and occupation\r burdensome. Now and then, the silence of the house, the solitude of the\r room, has pressed on me with a weight I found it difficult to bear, and\r recollection has not failed to be as ale","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"305"},"sequenceIndex":3164},{"id":"plato-symposiu-306","text":"\"I had rather a foolish letter the other day from ----. Some things in\r it nettled me, especially an unnecessarily earnest assurance that, in\r spite of all I had done in the writing line, I still retained a place in\r her esteem. My answer took strong and high ground at once. I said I had\r been troubled by no doubts on the subject; that I neither did her nor\r myself the injustice to suppose there was anything in what I had written\r to incur the just forfeiture of esteem. . . .","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"306"},"sequenceIndex":3165},{"id":"plato-symposiu-307","text":"\"A few days since, a little incident happened which curiously\r touched me. Papa put into my hands a little packet of letters and\r papers,--telling me that they were mamma's, and that I might read them.\r I did read them, in a frame of mind I cannot describe. The papers were\r yellow with time, all having been written before I was born it was\r strange now to peruse, for the first time, the records of a mind whence\r my own sprang; and most strange, and at once sad and sweet, to find\r that mind of a truly fine, pure, and elevated order. They were written\r to papa before they were married. There is ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"307"},"sequenceIndex":3166},{"id":"plato-symposiu-308","text":"The reader may remember the strange prophetic vision, which dictated a\r few words, written on the occasion of the death of a pupil of hers in\r January, 1840:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"308"},"sequenceIndex":3167},{"id":"plato-symposiu-309","text":"\"Wherever I seek for her now in this world, she cannot be found; no more\r than a flower or a leaf which withered twenty years ago. A bereavement\r of this kind gives one a glimpse of the feeling those must have, who\r have seen all drop round them--friend after friend, and are left to end\r their pilgrimage alone.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"309"},"sequenceIndex":3168},{"id":"plato-symposiu-310","text":"to wear, with slow dropping but perpetual pain, upon their spirits,\r the nerves and appetite will give way in solitude. How much more must\r it have been so with Miss Bronte, delicate and frail in constitution,\r tried by much anxiety and sorrow in early life, and now left to face\r her life alone. Owing to Mr. Bronte's great age, and long-formed habits\r of solitary occupation when in the house, his daughter was left to\r herself for the greater part of the day. Ever since his serious attacks\r of illness, he had dined alone; a portion of her dinner, regulated by\r strict attention to the diet most ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"310"},"sequenceIndex":3169},{"id":"plato-symposiu-311","text":"The reader, who has even faintly pictured to himself her life at this\r time,--the solitary days,--the waking, watching nights,--may imagine to\r what a sensitive pitch her nerves were strung, and how such a state was\r sure to affect her health.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"311"},"sequenceIndex":3170},{"id":"plato-symposiu-312","text":"It was no bad thing for her that about this time various people began to\r go over to Haworth, curious to see the scenery described in \"Shirley,\"\r if a sympathy with the writer, of a more generous kind than to be called\r mere curiosity, did not make them wish to know whether they could not in\r some way serve or cheer one who had suffered so deeply.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"312"},"sequenceIndex":3171},{"id":"plato-symposiu-313","text":"Among this number were Sir James and Lady Kay Shuttleworth. Their house\r lies over the crest of the moors which rise above Haworth, at about a\r dozen miles' distance as the crow flies, though much further by the\r road. But, according to the acceptation of the word in that uninhabited\r district, they were neighbours, if they so willed it. Accordingly, Sir\r James and his wife drove over one morning, at the beginning of March, to\r call upon Miss Bronte and her father. Before taking leave, they pressed\r her to visit them at Gawthorpe Hall, their residence on the borders\r of East Lancashire. After ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"313"},"sequenceIndex":3172},{"id":"plato-symposiu-314","text":"She took great pleasure in the \"quiet drives to old ruins and old\r halls, situated among older hills and woods; the dialogues by the old\r fireside in the antique oak-panneled drawing-room, while they suited\r him, did not too much oppress and exhaust me. The house, too, is much\r to my taste; near three centuries old, grey, stately, and picturesque.\r On the whole, now that the visit is over, I do not regret having paid\r it. The worst of it is, that there is now some menace hanging over my\r head of an invitation to go to them in London during the season. This,\r which would be a great enjoyment to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"314"},"sequenceIndex":3173},{"id":"plato-symposiu-315","text":"On the same day on which she wrote the above, she sent the following\r letter to Mr. Smith.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"315"},"sequenceIndex":3174},{"id":"plato-symposiu-316","text":"\"I return Mr. H----'s note, after reading it carefully. I tried very\r hard to understand all he says about art; but, to speak truth, my\r efforts were crowned with incomplete success. There is a certain jargon\r in use amongst critics on this point through which it is physically\r and morally impossible to me to see daylight. One thing however, I\r see plainly enough, and that is, Mr. Currer Bell needs improvement,\r and ought to strive after it; and this (D. V.) he honestly intends to\r do--taking his time, however, and following as his guides Nature and\r Truth. If these lead to what the critics ca","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"316"},"sequenceIndex":3175},{"id":"plato-symposiu-317","text":"\"Any promise you require respecting the books shall be willingly\r given, provided only I am allowed the Jesuit's principle of a mental\r reservation, giving licence to forget and promise whenever oblivion\r shall appear expedient. The last two or three numbers of Pendennis will\r not, I dare say, be generally thought sufficiently exciting, yet I like\r them. Though the story lingers, (for me) the interest does not flag.\r Here and there we feel that the pen has been guided by a tired hand,\r that the mind of the writer has been somewhat chafed and depressed by\r his recent illness, or by some other c","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"317"},"sequenceIndex":3176},{"id":"plato-symposiu-318","text":"The books lent her by her publishers were, as I have before said, a\r great solace and pleasure to her. There was much interest in opening\r the Cornhill parcel. But there was pain too; for, as she untied the\r cords, and took out the volumes one by one, she could scarcely fail\r to be reminded of those who once, on similar occasions, looked on so\r eagerly. \"I miss familiar voices, commenting mirthfully and pleasantly;\r the room seems very still--very empty; but yet there is consolation in\r remembering that Papa will take pleasure in some of the books. Happiness\r quite unshared can scarcely be cal","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"318"},"sequenceIndex":3177},{"id":"plato-symposiu-319","text":"\"I wonder how you can choose so well; on no account would I forestall\r the choice. I am sure any selection I might make for myself would be\r less satisfactory than the selection others so kindly and judiciously\r make for me; besides, if I knew all that was coming, it would be\r comparatively flat. I would much rather not know.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"319"},"sequenceIndex":3178},{"id":"plato-symposiu-320","text":"\"Amongst the especially welcome works are 'Southey's Life', the 'Women\r of France,' Hazlitt's 'Essays,' Emerson's 'Representative Men;' but it\r seems invidious to particularise when all are good. . . . I took up a\r second small book, Scott's 'Suggestions on Female Education;' that,\r too, I read, and with unalloyed pleasure. It is very good; justly\r thought, and clearly and felicitously expressed. The girls of this\r generation have great advantages; it seems to me that they receive much\r encouragement in the acquisition of knowledge, and the cultivation of\r their minds; in these days, women may","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"320"},"sequenceIndex":3179},{"id":"plato-symposiu-321","text":"\"As to the Times, as you say, the acrimony of its critique has proved,\r in some measure, its own antidote; to have been more effective, it\r should have been juster. I think it has had little weight up here in\r the North it may be that annoying remarks, if made, are not suffered\r to reach my ear; but certainly, while I have heard little condemnatory\r of Shirley, more than once have I been deeply moved by manifestations\r of even enthusiastic approbation. I deem it unwise to dwell much on\r these matters; but for once I must permit myself to remark, that\r the generous pride many of the Yorkshire p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"321"},"sequenceIndex":3180},{"id":"plato-symposiu-322","text":"During the earlier months of this spring, Haworth was extremely\r unhealthy. The weather was damp, low fever was prevalent, and the\r household at the Parsonage suffered along with its neighbours. Charlotte\r says, \"I have felt it (the fever) in frequent thirst and infrequent\r appetite; Papa too, and even Martha, have complained.\" This depression\r of health produced depression of spirits, and she grew more and more\r to dread the proposed journey to London with Sir James and Lady Kay\r Shuttleworth. \"I know what the effect and what the pain will be, how\r wretched I shall often feel, and how thin an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"322"},"sequenceIndex":3181},{"id":"plato-symposiu-323","text":"But the sensations of illness in the family increased; the symptoms were\r probably aggravated, if not caused, by the immediate vicinity of the\r church-yard, \"paved with rain-blackened tomb-stones.\" On April 29th she\r writes:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"323"},"sequenceIndex":3182},{"id":"plato-symposiu-324","text":"\"We have had but a poor week of it at Haworth. Papa continues far\r from well; he is often very sickly in the morning, a symptom which I\r have remarked before in his aggravated attacks of bronchitis; unless\r he should get much better, I shall never think of leaving him to go\r to London. Martha has suffered from tic-douloureux, with sickness and\r fever, just like you. I have a bad cold, and a stubborn sore throat; in\r short, everybody but old Tabby is out of sorts. When ---- was here, he\r complained of a sudden headache, and the night after he was gone I had\r something similar, very bad, lasting","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"324"},"sequenceIndex":3183},{"id":"plato-symposiu-325","text":"\"I did not think Papa well enough to be left, and accordingly begged\r Sir James and Lady Kay Shuttleworth to return to London without me.\r It was arranged that we were to stay at several of their friends' and\r relatives' houses on the way; a week or more would have been taken\r up on the journey. I cannot say that I regret having missed this\r ordeal; I would as lief have walked among red-hot plough-shares; but\r I do regret one great treat, which I shall now miss. Next Wednesday\r is the anniversary dinner of the Royal Literary Fund Society, held in\r Freemasons' Hall. Octavian Blewitt, the secret","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"325"},"sequenceIndex":3184},{"id":"plato-symposiu-326","text":"It became requisite, however, before long, that she should go to London\r on business; and as Sir James Kay Shuttleworth was detained in the\r country by indisposition, she accepted Mrs. Smith's invitation to stay\r quietly at her house, while she transacted her affairs.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"326"},"sequenceIndex":3185},{"id":"plato-symposiu-327","text":"In the interval between the relinquishment of the first plan and the\r adoption of the second, she wrote the following letter to one who was\r much valued among her literary friends:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"327"},"sequenceIndex":3186},{"id":"plato-symposiu-328","text":"\"I had thought to bring the Leader and the Athenaeum myself this time,\r and not to have to send them by post, but it turns out otherwise; my\r journey to London is again postponed, and this time indefinitely. Sir\r James Kay Shuttleworth's state of health is the cause--a cause, I fear,\r not likely to be soon removed. . . . Once more, then, I settle myself\r down in the quietude of Haworth Parsonage, with books for my household\r companions, and an occasional letter for a visitor; a mute society, but\r neither quarrelsome, nor vulgarising, nor unimproving.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"328"},"sequenceIndex":3187},{"id":"plato-symposiu-329","text":"\"One of the pleasures I had promised myself consisted in asking you\r several questions about the Leader, which is really, in its way, an\r interesting paper. I wanted, amongst other things, to ask you the\r real names of some of the contributors, and also what Lewes writes\r besides his Apprenticeship of Life. I always think the article headed\r 'Literature' is his. Some of the communications in the 'Open Council'\r department are odd productions; but it seems to me very fair and right\r to admit them. Is not the system of the paper altogether a novel one? I\r do not remember seeing anything precisel","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"329"},"sequenceIndex":3188},{"id":"plato-symposiu-330","text":"\"I have just received yours of this morning; thank you for the enclosed\r note. The longings for liberty and leisure which May sunshine wakens\r in you, stir my sympathy. I am afraid Cornhill is little better than a\r prison for its inmates on warm spring or summer days. It is a pity to\r think of you all toiling at your desks in such genial weather as this.\r For my part, I am free to walk on the moors; but when I go out there\r alone, everything reminds me of the times when others were with me, and\r then the moors seem a wilderness, featureless, solitary, saddening.\r My sister Emily had a particul","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"330"},"sequenceIndex":3189},{"id":"plato-symposiu-331","text":"She had to write many letters, about this time, to authors who sent her\r their books, and strangers who expressed their admiration of her own.\r The following was in reply to one of the latter class, and was addressed\r to a young man at Cambridge:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"331"},"sequenceIndex":3190},{"id":"plato-symposiu-332","text":"\"Apologies are indeed unnecessary for a 'reality of feeling, for a\r genuine unaffected impulse of the spirit,' such as prompted you to write\r the letter which I now briefly acknowledge.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"332"},"sequenceIndex":3191},{"id":"plato-symposiu-333","text":"\"Certainly it is 'something to me' that what I write should be\r acceptable to the feeling heart and refined intellect; undoubtedly it is\r much to me that my creations (such as they are) should find harbourage,\r appreciation, indulgence, at any friendly hand, or from any generous\r mind. You are very welcome to take Jane, Caroline, and Shirley for your\r sisters, and I trust they will often speak to their adopted brother\r when he is solitary, and soothe him when he is sad. If they cannot\r make themselves at home in a thoughtful, sympathetic mind, and diffuse\r through its twilight a cheering, dome","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"333"},"sequenceIndex":3192},{"id":"plato-symposiu-334","text":"\"What does it matter that part of your pleasure in such beings has its\r source in the poetry of your own youth rather than in any magic of\r theirs? What, that perhaps, ten years hence, you may smile to remember\r your present recollections, and view under another light both 'Currer\r Bell' and his writings? To me this consideration does not detract from\r the value of what you now feel. Youth has its romance, and maturity its\r wisdom, as morning and spring have their freshness, noon and summer\r their power, night and winter their repose. Each attribute is good in\r its own season. Your letter gave","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"334"},"sequenceIndex":3193},{"id":"plato-symposiu-335","text":"Miss Bronte went up to town at the beginning of June, and much enjoyed\r her stay there; seeing very few persons, according to the agreement she\r made before she went; and limiting her visit to a fortnight, dreading\r the feverishness and exhaustion which were the inevitable consequences\r of the slightest excitement upon her susceptible frame.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"335"},"sequenceIndex":3194},{"id":"plato-symposiu-336","text":"\"Since I wrote to you last, I have not had many moments to myself,\r except such as it was absolutely necessary to give to rest. On the\r whole, however, I have thus far got on very well, suffering much less\r from exhaustion than I did last time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"336"},"sequenceIndex":3195},{"id":"plato-symposiu-337","text":"\"Of course I cannot give you in a letter a regular chronicle of how my\r time has been spent. I can only--just notify. what I deem three of its\r chief incidents: a sight of the Duke of Wellington at the Chapel Royal\r (he is a real grand old man), a visit to the House of Commons (which I\r hope to describe to you some day when I see you), and last, not least,\r an interview with Mr. Thackeray. He made a morning call, and sat above\r two hours. Mr. Smith only was in the room the whole time. He described\r it afterwards as a 'queer scene,' and--I suppose it was. The giant sate\r before me; I was moved ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"337"},"sequenceIndex":3196},{"id":"plato-symposiu-338","text":"\"I have seen Lewes too. . . . I could not feel otherwise to him than\r half-sadly, half-tenderly,--a queer word that last, but I use it\r because the aspect of Lewes's face almost moves me to tears; it is\r so wonderfully like Emily,--her eyes, her features, the very nose,\r the somewhat prominent mouth, the forehead, even, at moments, the\r expression: whatever Lewes says, I believe I cannot hate him. Another\r likeness I have seen, too, that touched me sorrowfully. You remember\r my speaking of a Miss K., a young authoress, who supported her mother\r by writing? Hearing that she had a longing to see","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"338"},"sequenceIndex":3197},{"id":"plato-symposiu-339","text":"She soon followed her letter to the friend to whom it was written; but\r her visit was a very short one, for, in accordance with a plan made\r before leaving London, she went on to Edinburgh to join the friends\r with whom she had been staying in town. She remained only a few days in\r Scotland, and those were principally spent in Edinburgh, with which she\r was delighted, calling London a \"dreary place\" in comparison.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"339"},"sequenceIndex":3198},{"id":"plato-symposiu-340","text":"\"My stay in Scotland\" (she wrote some weeks later) \"was short, and\r what I saw was chiefly comprised in Edinburgh and the neighbourhood,\r in Abbotsford and in Melrose, for I was obliged to relinquish my first\r intention of going from Glasgow to Oban, and thence through a portion\r of the Highlands; but though the time was brief, and the view of\r objects limited, I found such a charm of situation, association, and\r circumstance, that I think the enjoyment experienced in that little\r space equalled in degree, and excelled in kind, all which London yielded\r during a month's sojourn. Edinburgh, com","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"340"},"sequenceIndex":3199},{"id":"plato-symposiu-341","text":"\"I would not write to you immediately on my arrival at home, because\r each return to this old house brings with it a phase of feeling which it\r is better to pass through quietly before beginning to indite letters.\r The six weeks of change and enjoyment are past, but they are not lost;\r memory took a sketch of each as it went by, and, especially, a distinct\r daguerreotype of the two days I spent in Scotland. Those were two\r very pleasant days. I always liked Scotland as an idea, but now, as a\r reality, I like it far better; it furnished me with some hours as happy\r almost as any I ever spent. D","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"341"},"sequenceIndex":3200},{"id":"plato-symposiu-342","text":"On her return from Scotland, she again spent a few days with her\r friends, and then made her way to Haworth.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"342"},"sequenceIndex":3201},{"id":"plato-symposiu-343","text":"I got home very well, and full glad was I that no insuperable obstacle\r had deferred my return one single day longer. Just at the foot of\r Bridgehouse hill, I met John, staff in hand; he fortunately saw me in\r the cab, stopped, and informed me he was setting off to B----, by Mr.\r Bronte's orders, to see how I was, for that he had been quite miserable\r ever since he got Miss ----'s letter. I found, on my arrival, that Papa\r had worked himself up to a sad pitch of nervous excitement and alarm,\r in which Martha and Tabby were but too obviously joining him. . . . The\r house looks very clean, and, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"343"},"sequenceIndex":3202},{"id":"plato-symposiu-344","text":"While Miss Bronte was staying in London, she was induced to sit for\r her portrait to Richmond. It is a crayon drawing; in my judgment an\r admirable likeness, though of course there is some difference of opinion\r on the subject; and, as usual, those best acquainted with the original\r were least satisfied with the resemblance. Mr. Bronte thought that it\r looked older than Charlotte did, and that her features had not been\r flattered; but he acknowledged that the expression was wonderfully good\r and life-like. She sent the following amusing account of the arrival of\r the portrait to the donor:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"344"},"sequenceIndex":3203},{"id":"plato-symposiu-345","text":"\"The little box for me came at the same time as the large one for Papa.\r When you first told me that you had had the Duke's picture framed, and\r had given it to me, I felt half provoked with you for performing such\r a work of supererogation, but now, when I see it again, I cannot but\r acknowledge that, in so doing, you were felicitously inspired. It is\r his very image, and, as Papa said when he saw it, scarcely in the least\r like the ordinary portraits; not only the expression, but even the form\r of the head is different, and of a far nobler character. I esteem it a\r treasure. The lady who lef","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"345"},"sequenceIndex":3204},{"id":"plato-symposiu-346","text":"It may easily be conceived that two people living together as Mr.\r Bronte and his daughter did, almost entirely dependent on each\r other for society, and loving each other deeply (although not\r demonstratively)--that these two last members of a family would have\r their moments of keen anxiety respecting each other's health. There\r is not one letter of hers which I have read, that does not contain\r some mention of her father's state in this respect. Either she thanks\r God with simple earnestness that he is well, or some infirmities of\r age beset him, and she mentions the fact, and then winces a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"346"},"sequenceIndex":3205},{"id":"plato-symposiu-347","text":"She evidently felt that this natural anxiety on the part of her father\r and friend increased the nervous depression of her own spirits, whenever\r she was ill; and in the following letter she expresses her strong\r wish that the subject of her health should be as little alluded to as\r possible.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"347"},"sequenceIndex":3206},{"id":"plato-symposiu-348","text":"\"I am truly sorry that I allowed the words to which you refer to escape\r my lips, since their effect on you has been unpleasant; but try to\r chase every shadow of anxiety from your mind, and, unless the restraint\r be very disagreeable to you, permit me to add an earnest request that\r you will broach the subject to me no more. It is the undisguised and\r most harassing anxiety of others that has fixed in my mind thoughts and\r expectations which must canker wherever they take root; against which\r every effort of religion or philosophy must at times totally fail; and\r subjugation to which is a cru","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"348"},"sequenceIndex":3207},{"id":"plato-symposiu-349","text":"Her father was always anxious to procure every change that was\r possible for her, seeing, as he did, the benefit which she derived\r from it, however reluctant she might have been to leave her home and\r him beforehand. This August she was invited to go for a week to the\r neighbourhood of Bowness, where Sir James Kay Shuttleworth had taken a\r house; but she says, \"I consented to go, with reluctance, chiefly to\r please Papa, whom a refusal on my part would much have annoyed; but I\r dislike to leave him. I trust he is not worse, but his complaint is\r still weakness. It is not right to anticipate e","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"349"},"sequenceIndex":3208},{"id":"plato-symposiu-350","text":"It was during this visit at the Briery--Lady Kay Shuttleworth having\r kindly invited me to meet her there--that I first made acquaintance with\r Miss Bronte. If I copy out part of a letter, which I wrote soon after\r this to a friend, who was deeply interested in her writings, I shall\r probably convey my first impressions more truly and freshly than by\r amplifying what I then said into a longer description.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"350"},"sequenceIndex":3209},{"id":"plato-symposiu-351","text":"\"Dark when I got to Windermere station; a drive along the level road\r to Low-wood; then a stoppage at a pretty house, and then a pretty\r drawing-room, in which were Sir James and Lady Kay Shuttleworth, and\r a little lady in a black-silk gown, whom I could not see at first for\r the dazzle in the room; she came up and shook hands with me at once. I\r went up to unbonnet, etc.; came down to tea; the little lady worked away\r and hardly spoke but I had time for a good look at her. She is (as she\r calls herself) UNDEVELOPED, thin, and more than half a head shorter than\r I am; soft brown hair, not ver","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"351"},"sequenceIndex":3210},{"id":"plato-symposiu-352","text":"\"We were only three days together; the greater part of which was\r spent in driving about, in order to show Miss Bronte the Westmoreland\r scenery, as she had never been there before. We were both included in an\r invitation to drink tea quietly at Fox How; and I then saw how severely\r her nerves were taxed by the effort of going amongst strangers. We knew\r beforehand that the number of the party would not exceed twelve; but she\r suffered the whole day from an acute headache brought on by apprehension\r of the evening.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"352"},"sequenceIndex":3211},{"id":"plato-symposiu-353","text":"\"Brierly Close was situated high above Low-wood, and of course commanded\r an extensive view and wide horizon. I was struck by Miss Bronte's\r careful examination of the shape of the clouds and the signs of the\r heavens, in which she read, as from a book, what the coming weather\r would be. I told her that I saw she must have a view equal in extent\r at her own home. She said that I was right, but that the character of\r the prospect from Haworth was very different; that I had no idea what a\r companion the sky became to any one living in solitude,--more than any\r inanimate object on earth,--more th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"353"},"sequenceIndex":3212},{"id":"plato-symposiu-354","text":"The following extracts convey some of her own impressions and feelings\r respecting this visit:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"354"},"sequenceIndex":3213},{"id":"plato-symposiu-355","text":"\"You said I should stay longer than a week in Westmoreland; you ought\r by this time to know me better. Is it my habit to keep dawdling at a\r place long after the time I first fixed on for departing? I have got\r home, and I am thankful to say Papa seems,--to say the least,--no worse\r than when I left him, yet I wish he were stronger. My visit passed off\r very well; I am glad I went. The scenery is, of course, grand; could I\r have wandered about amongst those hills ALONE, I could have drank in\r all their beauty; even in a carriage with company, it was very well.\r Sir James was all the while as k","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"355"},"sequenceIndex":3214},{"id":"plato-symposiu-356","text":"\"If I could only have dropped unseen out of the carriage, and gone away\r by myself in amongst those grand hills and sweet dales, I should have\r drank in the full power of this glorious scenery. In company this can\r hardly be. Sometimes, while ---- was warning me against the faults of\r the artist-class, all the while vagrant artist instincts were busy in\r the mind of his listener.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"356"},"sequenceIndex":3215},{"id":"plato-symposiu-357","text":"\"I forget to tell you that, about a week before I went to Westmoreland,\r there came an invitation to Harden Grange; which, of course, I declined.\r Two or three days after, a large party made their appearance here,\r consisting of Mrs. F---- and sundry other ladies and two gentlemen; one\r tall and stately, black haired and whiskered, who turned out to be Lord\r John Manners,--the other not so distinguished-looking, shy, and a little\r queer, who was Mr. Smythe, the son of Lord Strangford. I found Mrs. F.\r a true lady in manners and appearance, very gentle and unassuming. Lord\r John Manners brought","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"357"},"sequenceIndex":3216},{"id":"plato-symposiu-358","text":"To these extracts I must add one other from a letter referring to this\r time. It is addressed to Miss Wooler, the kind friend of both her\r girlhood and womanhood, who had invited her to spend a fortnight with\r her at her cottage lodgings.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"358"},"sequenceIndex":3217},{"id":"plato-symposiu-359","text":"\"When I tell you that I have already been to the Lakes this season,\r and that it is scarcely more than a month since I returned, you will\r understand that it is no longer within my option to accept your kind\r invitation. I wish I could have gone to you. I have already had my\r excursion, and there is an end of it. Sir James Kay Shuttleworth is\r residing near Windermere, at a house called the 'Briery,' and it was\r there I was staying for a little time this August. He very kindly showed\r me the neighbourhood, as it can be seen from a carriage, and I discerned\r that the Lake country is a glorious ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"359"},"sequenceIndex":3218},{"id":"plato-symposiu-360","text":"\"You say that you suspect I have formed a large circle of acquaintance\r by this time. No: I cannot say that I have. I doubt whether I possess\r either the wish or the power to do so. A few friends I should like\r to have, and these few I should like to know well; If such knowledge\r brought proportionate regard, I could not help concentrating my\r feelings; dissipation, I think, appears synonymous with dilution.\r However, I have, as yet, scarcely been tried. During the month I spent\r in London in the spring, I kept very quiet, having the fear of lionising\r before my eyes. I only went out once to d","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"360"},"sequenceIndex":3219},{"id":"plato-symposiu-361","text":"\"Somebody in D---- professes to have authority for saying, that 'when\r Miss Bronte was in London she neglected to attend Divine service on\r the Sabbath, and in the week spent her time in going about to balls,\r theatres, and operas.' On the other hand, the London quidnuncs make my\r seclusion a matter of wonder, and devise twenty romantic fictions to\r account for it. Formerly I used to listen to report with interest, and a\r certain credulity; but I am now grown deaf and sceptical: experience has\r taught me how absolutely devoid of foundation her stories may be.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"361"},"sequenceIndex":3220},{"id":"plato-symposiu-362","text":"I must now quote from the first letter I had the privilege of receiving\r from Miss Bronte. It is dated August the 27th.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"362"},"sequenceIndex":3221},{"id":"plato-symposiu-363","text":"\"Papa and I have just had tea; he is sitting quietly in his room, and I\r in mine; 'storms of rain' are sweeping over the garden and churchyard:\r as to the moors, they are hidden in thick fog. Though alone, I am not\r unhappy; I have a thousand things to be thankful for, and, amongst the\r rest, that this morning I received a letter from you, and that this\r evening I have the privilege of answering it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"363"},"sequenceIndex":3222},{"id":"plato-symposiu-364","text":"\"I do not know the 'Life of Sydney Taylor;' whenever I have the\r opportunity I will get it. The little French book you mention shall also\r take its place on the list of books to be procured as soon as possible.\r It treats a subject interesting to all women--perhaps, more especially\r to single women; though, indeed, mothers, like you, study it for the\r sake of their daughters. The Westminster Review is not a periodical I\r see regularly, but some time since I got hold of a number--for last\r January, I think--in which there was an article entitled 'Woman's\r Mission' (the phrase is hackneyed), con","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"364"},"sequenceIndex":3223},{"id":"plato-symposiu-365","text":"\"I have read Tennyson's 'In Memoriam,' or rather part of it; I closed\r the book when I had got about half way. It is beautiful; it is mournful;\r it is monotonous. Many of the feelings expressed bear, in their\r utterance, the stamp of truth; yet, if Arthur Hallam had been somewhat\r nearer Alfred Tennyson, his brother instead of his friend,--I should\r have distrusted this rhymed, and measured, and printed monument of\r grief. What change the lapse of years may work I do not know; but it\r seems to me that bitter sorrow, while recent, does not flow out in verse.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"365"},"sequenceIndex":3224},{"id":"plato-symposiu-366","text":"\"I promised to send you Wordsworth's 'Prelude,' and, accordingly,\r despatch it by this post; the other little volume shall follow in a\r day or two. I shall be glad to hear from you whenever you have time to\r write to me, but you are never, on any account, to do this except when\r inclination prompts and leisure permits. I should never thank you for a\r letter which you had felt it a task to write.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"366"},"sequenceIndex":3225},{"id":"plato-symposiu-367","text":"A short time after we had met at the Briery, she sent me the volume of\r Currer, Ellis, and Acton Bell's poems; and thus alludes to them in the\r note that accompanied the parcel:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"367"},"sequenceIndex":3226},{"id":"plato-symposiu-368","text":"\"The little book of rhymes was sent by way of fulfilling a rashly-made\r promise; and the promise was made to prevent you from throwing away four\r shillings in an injudicious purchase. I do not like my own share of the\r work, nor care that it should be read: Ellis Bell's I think good and\r vigorous, and Acton's have the merit of truth and simplicity. Mine are\r chiefly juvenile productions; the restless effervescence of a mind that\r would not be still. In those days, the sea too often 'wrought and was\r tempestuous,' and weed, sand, shingle--all turned up in the tumult. This\r image is much too mag","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"368"},"sequenceIndex":3227},{"id":"plato-symposiu-369","text":"Another letter of some interest was addressed, about this time, to a\r literary friend, on Sept. 5th:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"369"},"sequenceIndex":3228},{"id":"plato-symposiu-370","text":"\"The reappearance of the Athenaeum is very acceptable, not merely\r for its own sake,--though I esteem the opportunity of its perusal\r a privilege,--but because, as a weekly token of the remembrance of\r friends, it cheers and gives pleasure. I only fear that its regular\r transmission may become a task to you; in this case, discontinue it at\r once.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"370"},"sequenceIndex":3229},{"id":"plato-symposiu-371","text":"\"I did indeed enjoy my trip to Scotland, and yet I saw little of the\r face of the country; nothing of its grandeur or finer scenic features;\r but Edinburgh, Melrose, Abbotsford--these three in themselves sufficed\r to stir feelings of such deep interest and admiration, that neither at\r the time did I regret, nor have I since regretted, the want of wider\r space over which to diffuse the sense of enjoyment. There was room and\r variety enough to be very happy, and 'enough,' the proverb says, 'is\r as good as a feast.' The queen, indeed, was right to climb Arthur's\r Seat with her husband and childre","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"371"},"sequenceIndex":3230},{"id":"plato-symposiu-372","text":"\"The article in the Palladium is one of those notices over which an\r author rejoices trembling. He rejoices to find his work finely, fully,\r fervently appreciated, and trembles under the responsibility such\r appreciation seems to devolve upon him. I am counselled to wait and\r watch--D. V. I will do so; yet it is harder to wait with the hands\r bound, and the observant and reflective faculties at their silent and\r unseen work, than to labour mechanically.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"372"},"sequenceIndex":3231},{"id":"plato-symposiu-373","text":"\"I need not say how I felt the remarks on 'Wuthering Heights;' they\r woke the saddest yet most grateful feelings; they are true, they\r are discriminating, they are full of late justice, but it is very\r late--alas! in one sense, TOO late. Of this, however, and of the pang\r of regret for a light prematurely extinguished, it is not wise to speak\r much. Whoever the author of this article may be, I remain his debtor.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"373"},"sequenceIndex":3232},{"id":"plato-symposiu-374","text":"\"Yet, you see, even here, Shirley is disparaged in comparison with \"Jane\r Eyre\"; and yet I took great pains with Shirley. I did not hurry; I tried\r to do my best, and my own impression was that it was not inferior to\r the former work; indeed, I had bestowed on it more time, thought, and\r anxiety: but great part of it was written under the shadow of impending\r calamity; and the last volume, I cannot deny, was composed in the eager,\r restless endeavour to combat mental sufferings that were scarcely\r tolerable.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"374"},"sequenceIndex":3233},{"id":"plato-symposiu-375","text":"\"You sent the tragedy of 'Galileo Galilei,' by Samuel Brown, in one\r of the Cornhill parcels; it contained, I remember, passages of very\r great beauty. Whenever you send any more books (but that must not be\r till I return what I now have) I should be glad if you would include\r amongst them the 'Life of Dr. Arnold.' Do you know also the 'Life of\r Sydney Taylor?' I am not familiar even with the name, but it has been\r recommended to me as a work meriting perusal. Of course, when I name any\r book, it is always understood that it should be quite convenient to send\r it.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"375"},"sequenceIndex":3234},{"id":"plato-symposiu-376","text":"It was thought desirable about this time, to republish \"Wuthering\r Heights\" and \"Agnes Grey\", the works of the two sisters, and Charlotte\r undertook the task of editing them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"376"},"sequenceIndex":3235},{"id":"plato-symposiu-377","text":"She wrote to Mr. Williams, September 29th, 1850, \"It is my intention\r to write a few lines of remark on 'Wuthering Heights,' which, however,\r I propose to place apart as a brief preface before the tale. I am\r likewise compelling myself to read it over, for the first time of\r opening the book since my sister's death. Its power fills me with\r renewed admiration; but yet I am oppressed: the reader is scarcely\r ever permitted a taste of unalloyed pleasure; every beam of sunshine\r is poured down through black bars of threatening cloud; every page\r is surcharged with a sort of moral electricity; and","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"377"},"sequenceIndex":3236},{"id":"plato-symposiu-378","text":"\"And this makes me reflect,--perhaps I am too incapable of perceiving\r the faults and peculiarities of my own style.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"378"},"sequenceIndex":3237},{"id":"plato-symposiu-379","text":"\"I should wish to revise the proofs, if it be not too great an\r inconvenience to send them. It seems to me advisable to modify the\r orthography of the old servant Joseph's speeches; for though, as it\r stands, it exactly renders the Yorkshire dialect to a Yorkshire ear,\r yet, I am sure Southerns must find it unintelligible; and thus one of\r the most graphic characters in the book is lost on them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"379"},"sequenceIndex":3238},{"id":"plato-symposiu-380","text":"To her own dear friend, as to one who had known and loved her sisters,\r she writes still more fully respecting the painfulness of her task.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"380"},"sequenceIndex":3239},{"id":"plato-symposiu-381","text":"\"There is nothing wrong, and I am writing you a line as you desire,\r merely to say that I AM busy just now. Mr. Smith wishes to reprint some\r of Emily's and Annie's works, with a few little additions from the\r papers they have left; and I have been closely engaged in revising,\r transcribing, preparing a preface, notice, etc. As the time for doing\r this is limited, I am obliged to be industrious. I found the task at\r first exquisitely painful and depressing; but regarding it in the light\r of a SACRED DUTY, I went on, and now can bear it better. It is work,\r however, that I cannot do in the even","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"381"},"sequenceIndex":3240},{"id":"plato-symposiu-382","text":"\"I have just received a kind letter from Miss Martineau. She has got\r back to Ambleside, and had heard of my visit to the Lakes. She expressed\r her regret, etc., at not being at home.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"382"},"sequenceIndex":3241},{"id":"plato-symposiu-383","text":"\"I am both angry and surprised at myself for not being in better\r spirits; for not growing accustomed, or at least resigned, to the\r solitude and isolation of my lot. But my late occupation left a\r result for some days, and indeed still, very painful. The reading\r over of papers, the renewal of remembrances brought back the pang\r of bereavement, and occasioned a depression of spirits well nigh\r intolerable. For one or two nights, I scarcely knew how to get on till\r morning; and when morning came, I was still haunted with a sense of\r sickening distress. I tell you these things, because it is ab","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"383"},"sequenceIndex":3242},{"id":"plato-symposiu-384","text":"\"I thought to find occupation and interest in writing, when alone at\r home, but hitherto my efforts have been vain; the deficiency of every\r stimulus is so complete. You will recommend me, I dare say, to go from\r home; but that does no good, even could I again leave Papa with an easy\r mind (thank God! he is better). I cannot describe what a time of it I\r had after my return from London, Scotland, etc. There was a reaction\r that sunk me to the earth; the deadly silence, solitude, desolation,\r were awful; the craving for companionship, the hopelessness of relief,\r were what I should dread to fee","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"384"},"sequenceIndex":3243},{"id":"plato-symposiu-385","text":"\"Dear ----, when I think of you, it is with a compassion and tenderness\r that scarcely cheer me. Mentally, I fear, you also are too lonely and\r too little occupied. It seems our doom, for the present at least. May\r God in His mercy help us to bear it!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"385"},"sequenceIndex":3244},{"id":"plato-symposiu-386","text":"During her last visit to London, as mentioned in one of her letters,\r she had made the acquaintance of her correspondent, Mr. Lewes. That\r gentleman says:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"386"},"sequenceIndex":3245},{"id":"plato-symposiu-387","text":"\"Some months after\" (the appearance of the review of \"Shirley\" in the\r Edinburgh), \"Currer Bell came to London, and I was invited to meet her\r at your house. You may remember, she asked you not to point me out to\r her, but allow her to discover me if she could. She DID recognise me\r almost as soon as I came into the room. You tried me in the same way;\r I was less sagacious. However, I sat by her side a great part of the\r evening and was greatly interested by her conversation. On parting we\r shook hands, and she said, 'We are friends now, are we not?' 'Were we\r not always, then?' I asked. 'No! ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"387"},"sequenceIndex":3246},{"id":"plato-symposiu-388","text":"\"I am sure you will have thought me very dilatory in returning the books\r you so kindly lent me. The fact is, having some other books to send, I\r retained yours to enclose them in the same parcel.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"388"},"sequenceIndex":3247},{"id":"plato-symposiu-389","text":"\"Accept my thanks for some hours of pleasant reading. Balzac was for me\r quite a new author; and in making big acquaintance, through the medium\r of 'Modeste Mignon,' and 'Illusions perdues,' you cannot doubt I have\r felt some interest. At first, I thought he was going to be painfully\r minute, and fearfully tedious; one grew impatient of his long parade\r of detail, his slow revelation of unimportant circumstances, as he\r assembled his personages on the stage; but by and bye I seemed to enter\r into the mystery of his craft, and to discover, with delight, where\r his force lay: is it not in the an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"389"},"sequenceIndex":3248},{"id":"plato-symposiu-390","text":"\"Fantastic, fanatical, unpractical enthusiast as she often is--far from\r truthful as are many of her views of life--misled, as she is apt to be,\r by her feelings--George Sand has a better nature than M. de Balzac; her\r brain is larger, her heart warmer than his. The 'Lettres d'un Voyageur'\r are full of the writer's self; and I never felt so strongly, as in the\r perusal of this work, that most of her very faults spring from the\r excess of her good qualities: it is this excess which has often hurried\r her into difficulty, which has prepared for her enduring regret.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"390"},"sequenceIndex":3249},{"id":"plato-symposiu-391","text":"\"But I believe her mind is of that order which disastrous experience\r teaches, without weakening or too much disheartening; and, in that case,\r the longer she lives the better she will grow. A hopeful point in all\r her writings is the scarcity of false French sentiment; I wish I could\r say its absence; but the weed flourishes here and there, even in the\r 'Lettres.'\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"391"},"sequenceIndex":3250},{"id":"plato-symposiu-392","text":"I remember the good expression of disgust which Miss Bronte made use of\r in speaking to me of some of Balzac's novels: \"They leave such a bad\r taste in my mouth.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"392"},"sequenceIndex":3251},{"id":"plato-symposiu-393","text":"The reader will notice that most of the letters from which I now quote\r are devoted to critical and literary subjects. These were, indeed, her\r principal interests at this time; the revision of her sister's works,\r and writing a short memoir of them, was the painful employment of every\r day during the dreary autumn of 1850. Wearied out by the vividness\r of her sorrowful recollections, she sought relief in long walks on\r the moors. A friend of hers, who wrote to me on the appearance of the\r eloquent article in the Daily News upon the \"Death of Currer Bell,\"\r gives an anecdote which may well com","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"393"},"sequenceIndex":3252},{"id":"plato-symposiu-394","text":"\"They are mistaken in saying she was too weak to roam the hills for\r the benefit of the air. I do not think any one, certainly not any\r woman, in this locality, went so much on the moors as she did, when the\r weather permitted. Indeed, she was so much in the habit of doing so,\r that people, who live quite away on the edge of the common, knew her\r perfectly well. I remember on one occasion an old woman saw her at a\r little distance, and she called out, 'How! Miss Bronte! Hey yah (have\r you) seen ought o' my cofe (calf)?' Miss Bronte told her she could not\r say, for she did not know it. 'Well!' ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"394"},"sequenceIndex":3253},{"id":"plato-symposiu-395","text":"It must have been about this time that a visit was paid to her by\r some neighbours, who were introduced to her by a mutual friend. This\r visit has been described in a letter from which I am permitted to\r give extracts, which will show the impression made upon strangers by\r the character of the country round her home, and other circumstances.\r \"Though the weather was drizzly, we resolved to make our long-planned\r excursion to Haworth; so we packed ourselves into the buffalo-skin,\r and that into the gig, and set off about eleven. The rain ceased, and\r the day was just suited to the scenery,--wil","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"395"},"sequenceIndex":3254},{"id":"plato-symposiu-396","text":"\"Miss Bronte put me so in mind of her own 'Jane Eyre.' She looked\r smaller than ever, and moved about so quietly, and noiselessly, just\r like a little bird, as Rochester called her, barring that all birds are\r joyous, and that joy can never have entered that house since it was\r first built; and yet, perhaps, when that old man married, and took home\r his bride, and children's voices and feet were heard about the house,\r even that desolate crowded grave-yard and biting blast could not quench\r cheerfulness and hope. Now there is something touching in the sight of\r that little creature entombed in","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"396"},"sequenceIndex":3255},{"id":"plato-symposiu-397","text":"In one of the preceding letters, Miss Bronte referred to am article in\r the Palladium, which had rendered what she considered the due meed of\r merit to \"Wuthering Heights\", her sister Emily's tale. Her own works\r were praised, and praised with discrimination, and she was grateful for\r this. But her warm heart was filled to the brim with kindly feelings\r towards him who had done justice to the dead. She anxiously sought out\r the name of the writer; and having discovered that it was Mr. Sydney\r Dobell he immediately became one of her","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"397"},"sequenceIndex":3256},{"id":"plato-symposiu-398","text":"She looked with interest upon everything he wrote; and before long we\r shall find that they corresponded.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"398"},"sequenceIndex":3257},{"id":"plato-symposiu-399","text":"\"The box of books came last night, and, as usual, I have only gratefully\r to admire the selection made: 'Jeffrey's Essays,' 'Dr. Arnold's Life,'\r 'The Roman,' 'Alton Loche,' these were all wished for and welcome.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"399"},"sequenceIndex":3258},{"id":"plato-symposiu-400","text":"\"You say I keep no books; pardon me--I am ashamed of my own\r rapaciousness I have kept 'Macaulay's History,' and Wordsworth's\r 'Prelude', and Taylor's 'Philip Van Artevelde.' I soothe my conscience\r by saying that the two last,--being poetry--do not count. This is a\r convenient doctrine for me I meditate acting upon it with reference to\r the Roman, so I trust nobody in Cornhill will dispute its validity or\r affirm that 'poetry' has a value, except for trunk-makers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"400"},"sequenceIndex":3259},{"id":"plato-symposiu-401","text":"\"I have already had 'Macaulay's Essays,' 'Sidney Smith's Lectures\r on Moral Philosophy,' and 'Knox on Race.' Pickering's work on the\r same subject I have not seen; nor all the volumes of Leigh Hunt's\r Autobiography. However, I am now abundantly supplied for a long time to\r come. I liked Hazlitt's Essays much.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"401"},"sequenceIndex":3260},{"id":"plato-symposiu-402","text":"\"The autumn, as you say, has been very fine. I and solitude and memory\r have often profited by its sunshine on the moors.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"402"},"sequenceIndex":3261},{"id":"plato-symposiu-403","text":"\"I had felt some disappointment at the non-arrival of the proof-sheets\r of 'Wuthering Heights;' a feverish impatience to complete the revision\r is apt to beset me. The work of looking over papers, etc., could not be\r gone through with impunity, and with unaltered spirits; associations too\r tender, regrets too bitter, sprang out of it. Meantime, the Cornhill\r books now, as heretofore, are my best medicine,--affording a solace\r which could not be yielded by the very same books procured from a common\r library.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"403"},"sequenceIndex":3262},{"id":"plato-symposiu-404","text":"\"Already I have read the greatest part of the 'Roman;' passages in\r it possess a kindling virtue such as true poetry alone can boast;\r there are images of genuine grandeur; there are lines that at once\r stamp themselves on the memory. Can it be true that a new planet has\r risen on the heaven, whence all stars seemed fast fading? I believe\r it is; for this Sydney or Dobell speaks with a voice of his own,\r unborrowed, unmimicked. You hear Tennyson, indeed, sometimes, and Byron\r sometimes, in some passages of the Roman; but then again you have a new\r note,--nowhere clearer than in a certain brief","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"404"},"sequenceIndex":3263},{"id":"plato-symposiu-405","text":"The following extract will be read with interest as conveying her\r thoughts after the perusal of Dr. Arnold's Life:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"405"},"sequenceIndex":3264},{"id":"plato-symposiu-406","text":"\"I have just finished reading the 'Life of Dr. Arnold;' but now when I\r wish, according to your request, to express what I think of it, I do\r not find the task very easy; proper terms seem wanting. This is not\r a character to be dismissed with a few laudatory words; it is not a\r one-sided character; pure panegyric would be inappropriate. Dr. Arnold\r (it seems to me) was not quite saintly; his greatness was cast in a\r mortal mould; he was a little severe, almost a little hard; he was\r vehement and somewhat oppugnant. Himself the most indefatigable of\r workers, I know not whether he could have u","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"406"},"sequenceIndex":3265},{"id":"plato-symposiu-407","text":"\"But this is not all, and I am glad of it. Besides high intellect and\r stainless rectitude, his letters and his life attest his possession of\r the most true-hearted affection. WITHOUT this, however one might admire,\r we could not love him; but WITH it I think we love him much. A hundred\r such men--fifty--nay, ten or five such righteous men might save any\r country; might victoriously champion any cause.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"407"},"sequenceIndex":3266},{"id":"plato-symposiu-408","text":"\"I was struck, too, by the almost unbroken happiness of his life; a\r happiness resulting chiefly, no doubt, from the right use to which he\r put that health and strength which God had given him, but also owing\r partly to a singular exemption from those deep and bitter griefs which\r most human beings are called on to endure. His wife was what he wished;\r his children were healthy and promising; his own health was excellent;\r his undertakings were crowned with success; even death was kind,--for,\r however sharp the pains of his last hour, they were but brief. God's\r blessing seems to have accompan","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"408"},"sequenceIndex":3267},{"id":"plato-symposiu-409","text":"\"When I was in Westmoreland last August, I spent an evening at Fox How,\r where Mrs. Arnold and her daughters still reside. It was twilight as\r I drove to the place, and almost dark ere I reached it; still I could\r perceive that the situation was lovely. The house looked like a nest\r half buried in flowers and creepers: and, dusk as it was, I could FEEL\r that the valley and the hills round were beautiful as imagination could\r dream.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"409"},"sequenceIndex":3268},{"id":"plato-symposiu-410","text":"If I say again what I have said already before, it is only to impress\r and re-impress upon my readers the dreary monotony of her life at this\r time. The dark, bleak season of the year brought back the long evenings,\r which tried her severely: all the more so, because her weak eyesight\r rendered her incapable of following any occupation but knitting by\r candle-light. For her father's sake, as well as for her own, she found\r it necessary to make some exertion to ward off settled depression of\r spirits. She accordingly accepted an invitation to spend a week or ten\r days with Miss Martineau at Amb","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"410"},"sequenceIndex":3269},{"id":"plato-symposiu-411","text":"\"My dear Mrs. Gaskell,--Miss ----'s kindness and yours is such that I am\r placed in the dilemma of not knowing how adequately to express my sense\r of it. THIS I know, however, very well-that if I COULD go and be with\r you for a week or two in such a quiet south-country house, and with such\r kind people as you describe, I should like it much. I find the proposal\r marvellously to my taste; it is the pleasantest, gentlest, sweetest,\r temptation possible; but, delectable as it is, its solicitations are by\r no means to be yielded to without the sanction of reason, and therefore\r I desire for the pr","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"411"},"sequenceIndex":3270},{"id":"plato-symposiu-412","text":"On the 10th of December, the second edition of \"Wuthering Heights\" was\r published. She sent a copy of it to Mr. Dobell, with the following\r letter:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"412"},"sequenceIndex":3271},{"id":"plato-symposiu-413","text":"\"I offer this little book to my critic in the 'Palladium,' and he must\r believe it accompanied by a tribute of the sincerest gratitude; not so\r much for anything he has said of myself, as for the noble justice he\r has rendered to one dear to me as myself--perhaps dearer; and perhaps\r one kind word spoken for her awakens a deeper, tenderer, sentiment\r of thankfulness than eulogies heaped on my own head. As you will see\r when you have read the biographical notice, my sister cannot thank\r you herself; she is gone out of your sphere and mine, and human blame\r and praise are nothing to her now. But","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"413"},"sequenceIndex":3272},{"id":"plato-symposiu-414","text":"\"Tell me, when you have read the introduction, whether any doubts still\r linger in your mind respecting the authorship of 'Wuthering Heights,'\r 'Wildfell Hall,' etc. Your mistrust did me some injustice; it proved a\r general conception of character such as I should be sorry to call mine;\r but these false ideas will naturally arise when we only judge an author\r from his works. In fairness, I must also disclaim the flattering side\r of the portrait. I am no 'young Penthesilea mediis in millibus,' but a\r plain country parson's daughter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"414"},"sequenceIndex":3273},{"id":"plato-symposiu-415","text":"Immediately after the republication of her sisters' book she went to\r Miss Martineau's.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"415"},"sequenceIndex":3274},{"id":"plato-symposiu-416","text":"\"I can write to you now, dear E----, for I am away from home) and\r relieved, temporarily, at least, by change of air and scene, from the\r heavy burden of depression which, I confess, has for nearly three months\r been sinking me to the earth. I never shall forget last autumn! Some\r days and nights have been cruel; but now, having once told you this, I\r need say no more on the subject. My loathing of solitude grew extreme;\r my recollection of my sisters intolerably poignant. I am better now.\r I am at Miss Martineau's for a week. Her house is very pleasant, both\r within and without; arranged at; ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"416"},"sequenceIndex":3275},{"id":"plato-symposiu-417","text":"Miss Bronte paid the visit she here proposes to her friend, but only\r remained two or three days. She then returned home, and immediately\r began to suffer from her old enemy, sickly and depressing headache. This\r was all the more trying to bear, as she was obliged to take an active\r share in the household work,--one servant being ill in bed, and the\r other, Tabby, aged upwards of eighty.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"417"},"sequenceIndex":3276},{"id":"plato-symposiu-418","text":"This visit to Ambleside did Miss Bronte much good, and gave her a\r stock of pleasant recollections, and fresh interests, to dwell upon in\r her solitary life. There are many references in her letters to Miss\r Martineau's character and kindness.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"418"},"sequenceIndex":3277},{"id":"plato-symposiu-419","text":"\"She is certainly a woman of wonderful endowments, both intellectual\r and physical; and though I share few of her opinions, and regard her\r as fallible on certain points of judgment, I must still award her my\r sincerest esteem. The manner in which she combines the highest mental\r culture with the nicest discharge of feminine duties filled me with\r admiration; while her affectionate kindness earned my gratitude.\" \"I\r think her good and noble qualities far outweigh her defects. It is my\r habit to consider the individual apart from his (or her) reputation,\r practice independent of theory, natural","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"419"},"sequenceIndex":3278},{"id":"plato-symposiu-420","text":"\"Your last letter evinced such a sincere and discriminating admiration\r for Dr. Arnold, that perhaps you will not be wholly uninterested in\r hearing that, during my late visit to Miss Martineau, I saw much more of\r Fox How and its inmates, and daily admired, in the widow and children\r of one of the greatest and best men of his time, the possession of\r qualities the most estimable and endearing. Of my kind hostess herself,\r I cannot speak in terms too high. Without being able to share all her\r opinions, philosophical, political, or religious,--without adopting\r her theories,--I yet find a worth","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"420"},"sequenceIndex":3279},{"id":"plato-symposiu-421","text":"\"I must not, however, fall into the error of talking too much about\r her merely because my own mind is just now deeply impressed with what\r I have seen of her intellectual power and moral worth. Faults she has;\r but to me they appear very trivial weighed in the balance against her\r excellences.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"421"},"sequenceIndex":3280},{"id":"plato-symposiu-422","text":"\"Your account of Mr. A---- tallies exactly with Miss M----'s. She, too,\r said that placidity and mildness (rather than originality and power)\r were his external characteristics. She described him as a combination of\r the antique Greek sage with the European modern man of science. Perhaps\r it was mere perversity in me to get the notion that torpid veins, and\r a cold, slow-beating heart, lay under his marble outside. But he is a\r materialist: he serenely denies us our hope of immortality, and quietly\r blots from man's future Heaven and the Life to come. That is why a\r savour of bitterness season","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"422"},"sequenceIndex":3281},{"id":"plato-symposiu-423","text":"\"All you say of Mr. Thackeray is most graphic and characteristic. He\r stirs in me both sorrow and anger. Why should he lead so harassing\r a life? Why should his mocking tongue so perversely deny the better\r feelings of his better moods?\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"423"},"sequenceIndex":3282},{"id":"plato-symposiu-424","text":"For some time, whenever she was well enough in health and spirits, she\r had been employing herself upon Villette; but she was frequently unable\r to write, and was both grieved and angry with herself for her inability.\r In February, she writes as follows to Mr. Smith:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"424"},"sequenceIndex":3283},{"id":"plato-symposiu-425","text":"\"Something you say about going to London; but the words are dreamy,\r and fortunately I am not obliged to hear or answer them. London and\r summer are many months away: our moors are all white with snow just\r now, and little redbreasts come every morning to the window for crumbs.\r One can lay no plans three or four months beforehand. Besides, I don't\r deserve to go to London; nobody merits a change or a treat less. I\r secretly think, on the contrary, I ought to be put in prison, and kept\r on bread and water in solitary confinement--without even a letter from\r Cornhill--till I had written a book.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"425"},"sequenceIndex":3284},{"id":"plato-symposiu-426","text":"Meanwhile, she was disturbed and distressed by the publication of Miss\r Martineau's \"Letters,\" etc.; they came down with a peculiar force and\r heaviness upon a heart that looked, with fond and earnest faith, to a\r future life as to the meeting-place with those who were \"loved and lost\r awhile.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"426"},"sequenceIndex":3285},{"id":"plato-symposiu-427","text":"\"My dear Sir,--Have you yet read Miss Martineau's and Mr. Atkinson's new\r work, 'Letters on the Nature and Development of Man'? If you have not,\r it would be worth your while to do so.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"427"},"sequenceIndex":3286},{"id":"plato-symposiu-428","text":"\"Of the impression this book has made on me, I will not now say much.\r It is the first exposition of avowed atheism and materialism I have\r ever read; the first unequivocal declaration of disbelief in the\r existence of a God or a future life I have ever seen. In judging of\r such exposition and declaration, one would wish entirely to put aside\r the sort of instinctive horror they awaken, and to consider them in an\r impartial spirit and collected mood. This I find it difficult to do. The\r strangest thing is, that we are called on to rejoice over this hopeless\r blank--to receive this bitter berea","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"428"},"sequenceIndex":3287},{"id":"plato-symposiu-429","text":"\"Sincerely, for my own part, do I wish to find and know the Truth; but\r if this be Truth, well may she guard herself with mysteries, and cover\r herself with a veil. If this be Truth, man or woman who beholds her\r can but curse the day he or she was born. I said, however, I would not\r dwell on what I thought; I wish to hear, rather, what some other person\r thinks,--some one whose feelings are unapt to bias his judgment. Read\r the book, then, in an unprejudiced spirit, and candidly say what you\r think of it. I mean, of course, if you have time--NOT OTHERWISE.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"429"},"sequenceIndex":3288},{"id":"plato-symposiu-430","text":"And yet she could not bear the contemptuous tone in which this work\r was spoken of by many critics; it made her more indignant than almost\r any other circumstance during my acquaintance with her. Much as she\r regretted the publication of the book, she could not see that it had\r given any one a right to sneer at an action, certainly prompted by no\r worldly motive, and which was but one error--the gravity of which she\r admitted--in the conduct of a person who had, all her life long, been\r striving, by deep thought and noble words, to serve her kind.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"430"},"sequenceIndex":3289},{"id":"plato-symposiu-431","text":"\"Your remarks on Miss Martineau and her book pleased me greatly, from\r their tone and spirit. I have even taken the liberty of transcribing for\r her benefit one or two phrases, because I know they will cheer her; she\r likes sympathy and appreciation (as all people do who deserve them); and\r most fully do I agree with you in the dislike you express of that hard,\r contemptuous tone in which her work is spoken of by many critics.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"431"},"sequenceIndex":3290},{"id":"plato-symposiu-432","text":"Before I return from the literary opinions of the author to the domestic\r interests of the woman, I must copy out what she felt and thought about\r \"The Stones of Venice\".","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"432"},"sequenceIndex":3291},{"id":"plato-symposiu-433","text":"\"'The Stones of Venice' seem nobly laid and chiselled. How grandly the\r quarry of vast marbles is disclosed! Mr. Ruskin seems to me one of the\r few genuine writers, as distinguished from book-makers, of this age.\r His earnestness even amuses me in certain passages; for I cannot help\r laughing to think how utilitarians will fume and fret over his deep,\r serious (and as THEY will think), fanatical reverence for Art. That pure\r and severe mind you ascribed to him speaks in every line. He writes like\r a consecrated Priest of the Abstract and Ideal.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"433"},"sequenceIndex":3292},{"id":"plato-symposiu-434","text":"\"I shall bring with me 'The Stones of Venice'; all the foundations of\r marble and of granite, together with the mighty quarry out of which they\r were hewn; and, into the bargain, a small assortment of crotchets and\r dicta--the private property of one John Ruskin, Esq.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"434"},"sequenceIndex":3293},{"id":"plato-symposiu-435","text":"As spring drew on, the depression of spirits to which she was subject\r began to grasp her again, and \"to crush her with a day- and night-mare.\"\r She became afraid of sinking as low as she had done in the autumn; and\r to avoid this, she prevailed on her old friend and schoolfellow to come\r and stay with her for a few weeks in March. She found great benefit from\r this companionship,--both from the congenial society in itself, and from\r the self-restraint of thought imposed by the necessity of entertaining\r her and looking after her comfort. On this occasion, Miss Bronte said,\r \"It will not do to","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"435"},"sequenceIndex":3294},{"id":"plato-symposiu-436","text":"I shall now make an extract from one of her letters, which is purposely\r displaced as to time. I quote it because it relates to a third offer of\r marriage which she had, and because I find that some are apt to imagine,\r from the extraordinary power with which she represented the passion of\r love in her novels, that she herself was easily susceptible of it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"436"},"sequenceIndex":3295},{"id":"plato-symposiu-437","text":"\"Could I ever feel enough for ----, to accept of him as a husband?\r Friendship--gratitude--esteem--I have; but each moment he came near me,\r and that I could see his eyes fastened on me, my veins ran ice. Now\r that he is away, I feel far more gently towards him, it is only close\r by that I grow rigid, stiffening with a strange mixture of apprehension\r and anger, which nothing softens but his retreat, and a perfect subduing\r of his manner. I did not want to be proud, nor intend to be proud, but\r I was forced to be so. Most true it is, that we are over-ruled by One\r above us; that in His hands o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"437"},"sequenceIndex":3296},{"id":"plato-symposiu-438","text":"I have now named all the offers of marriage she ever received, until\r that was made which she finally accepted. The gentle-man referred to in\r this letter retained so much regard for her as to be her friend to the\r end of her life; a circumstance to his credit and to hers.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"438"},"sequenceIndex":3297},{"id":"plato-symposiu-439","text":"Before her friend E---- took her departure, Mr. Bronte caught cold,\r and continued for some weeks much out of health, with an attack of\r bronchitis. His spirits, too, became much depressed; and all his\r daughter's efforts were directed towards cheering him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"439"},"sequenceIndex":3298},{"id":"plato-symposiu-440","text":"When he grew better, and had regained his previous strength, she\r resolved to avail herself of an invitation which she had received some\r time before, to pay a visit in London. This year, 1851, was, as every\r one remembers, the time of the great Exhibition; but even with that\r attraction in prospect, she did not intend to stay there long; and, as\r usual, she made an agreement with her friends, before finally accepting\r their offered hospitality, that her sojourn at their house was to be as\r quiet as ever, since any other way of proceeding disagreed with her both\r mentally and physically. She n","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"440"},"sequenceIndex":3299},{"id":"plato-symposiu-441","text":"Her preparations in the way of dress for this visit, in the gay time of\r that gay season, were singularly in accordance with her feminine taste;\r quietly anxious to satisfy her love for modest, dainty, neat attire, and\r not regardless of the becoming, yet remembering consistency, both with\r her general appearance and with her means, in every selection she made.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"441"},"sequenceIndex":3300},{"id":"plato-symposiu-442","text":"\"By the bye, I meant to ask you when you went to Leeds, to do a small\r errand for me, but fear your hands will be too full of business. It\r was merely this: in case you chanced to be in any shop where the lace\r cloaks, both black and white, of which I spoke, were sold, to ask their\r price. I suppose they would hardly like to send a few to Haworth to be\r looked at; indeed, if they cost very much, it would be useless, but\r if they are reasonable and they would send them, I should like to see\r them; and also some chemisettes of small size (the full woman's size\r don't fit me), both of simple styl","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"442"},"sequenceIndex":3301},{"id":"plato-symposiu-443","text":"\"Do you know that I was in Leeds on the very same day with you--last\r Wednesday? I had thought of telling you where I was going, and having\r your help and company in buying a bonnet, etc., but then I reflected\r this would merely be making a selfish use of you, so I determined to\r manage or mismanage the matter alone. I went to Hurst and Hall's for the\r bonnet, and got one which seemed grave and quiet there amongst all the\r splendours; but now it looks infinitely too gay with its pink lining. I\r saw some beautiful silks of pale sweet colours, but had not the spirit\r nor the means to launch out ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"443"},"sequenceIndex":3302},{"id":"plato-symposiu-444","text":"\"Your poor mother is like Tabby, Martha and Papa; all these fancy I\r am somehow, by some mysterious process, to be married in London, or\r to engage myself to matrimony. How I smile internally! How groundless\r and improbable is the idea! Papa seriously told me yesterday, that\r if I married and left him he should give up housekeeping and go into\r lodgings!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"444"},"sequenceIndex":3303},{"id":"plato-symposiu-445","text":"I copy the following, for the sake of the few words describing the\r appearance of the heathery moors in late summer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"445"},"sequenceIndex":3304},{"id":"plato-symposiu-446","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I hasten to send Mrs. Dobell the autograph. It was the\r word 'Album' that frightened me I thought she wished me to write a\r sonnet on purpose for it, which I could not do.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"446"},"sequenceIndex":3305},{"id":"plato-symposiu-447","text":"\"Your proposal respecting a journey to Switzerland is deeply kind; it\r draws me with the force of a mighty Temptation, but the stern Impossible\r holds me back. No! I cannot go to Switzerland this summer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"447"},"sequenceIndex":3306},{"id":"plato-symposiu-448","text":"\"Why did the editor of the 'Eclectic' erase that most powerful and\r pictorial passage? He could not be insensible to its beauty; perhaps he\r thought it profane. Poor man!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"448"},"sequenceIndex":3307},{"id":"plato-symposiu-449","text":"\"I know nothing of such an orchard-country as you describe. I have never\r seen such a region. Our hills only confess the coming of summer by\r growing green with young fern and moss, in secret little hollows. Their\r bloom is reserved for autumn; then they burn with a kind of dark glow,\r different, doubtless, from the blush of garden blossoms. About the close\r of next month, I expect to go to London, to pay a brief and quiet visit.\r I fear chance will not be so propitious as to bring you to town while I\r am there; otherwise, how glad I should be if you would call. With kind\r regards to Mrs. Dobe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"449"},"sequenceIndex":3308},{"id":"plato-symposiu-450","text":"\"I came here on Wednesday, being summoned a day sooner than I expected,\r in order to be in time for Thackeray's second lecture, which was\r delivered on Thursday afternoon. This, as you may suppose, was a genuine\r treat to me, and I was glad not to miss it. It was given in Willis'\r Rooms, where the Almacks balls are held--a great painted and gilded\r saloon with long sofas for benches. The audience was said to be the\r cream of London society, and it looked so. I did not at all expect the\r great lecturer would know me or notice me under these circumstances,\r with admiring duchesses and countesses","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"450"},"sequenceIndex":3309},{"id":"plato-symposiu-451","text":"\"Thackeray called too, separately. I had a long talk with him, and I\r think he knows me now a little better than he did: but of this I cannot\r yet be sure; he is a great and strange man. There is quite a furor\r for his lectures. They are a sort of essays, characterised by his own\r peculiar originality and power, and delivered with a finished taste and\r ease, which is felt, but cannot be described. Just before the lecture\r began, somebody came behind me, leaned over and said, 'Permit me, as a\r Yorkshireman, to introduce myself.' I turned round--saw a strange, not\r handsome, face, which puzzled ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"451"},"sequenceIndex":3310},{"id":"plato-symposiu-452","text":"\"Afterwards came another man with the same plea, that he was a\r Yorkshireman, and this turned out to be Mr. Monckton Milnes. Then came\r Dr. Forbes, whom I was sincerely glad to see. On Friday, I went to the\r Crystal Palace; it is a marvellous, stirring, bewildering sight--a\r mixture of a genii palace, and a mighty bazaar, but it is not much in\r my way; I liked the lecture better. On Saturday I saw the Exhibition\r at Somerset House; about half a dozen of the pictures are good and\r interesting, the rest of little worth. Sunday--yesterday--was a day to\r be marked with a white stone; through most ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"452"},"sequenceIndex":3311},{"id":"plato-symposiu-453","text":"The lady, who accompanied Miss Bronte to the lecture at Thackeray's\r alluded to, says that, soon after they had taken their places, she\r was aware that he was pointing out her companion to several of his\r friends, but she hoped that Miss Bronte herself would not perceive\r it. After some time, however, during which many heads had been turned\r round, and many glasses put up, in order to look at the author of \"Jane\r Eyre\", Miss Bronte said, \"I am afraid Mr. Thackeray has been playing\r me a trick;\" but she soon became too much absorbed in the lecture to\r notice the attention which was being paid t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"453"},"sequenceIndex":3312},{"id":"plato-symposiu-454","text":"\"As our party left the Hall, he stood at the entrance; he saw and knew\r me, and lifted his hat; he offered his hand in passing, and uttered\r the words 'Qu'en dites-vous?'--question eminently characteristic, and\r reminding me, even in this his moment of triumph, of that inquisitive\r restlessness, that absence of what I considered desirable self-control,\r which were amongst his faults. He should not have cared just then to ask\r what I thought, or what anybody thought; but he DID care, and he was too\r natural to conceal, too impulsive to repress his wish. Well! if I blamed\r his over-eagerness, I ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"454"},"sequenceIndex":3313},{"id":"plato-symposiu-455","text":"As they were preparing to leave the room, her companion saw with dismay\r that many of the audience were forming themselves into two lines, on\r each side of the aisle down which they had to pass before reaching the\r door. Aware that any delay would only make the ordeal more trying, her\r friend took Miss Bronte's arm in hers, and they went along the avenue\r of eager and admiring faces. During this passage through the \"cream\r of society,\" Miss Bronte's hand trembled to such a degree, that her\r companion feared lest she should turn faint and be unable to proceed;\r and she dared not express her sym","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"455"},"sequenceIndex":3314},{"id":"plato-symposiu-456","text":"Surely, such thoughtless manifestation of curiosity is a blot on the\r scutcheon of true politeness! The rest of the account of this, her\r longest visit to London, shall be told in her own words.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"456"},"sequenceIndex":3315},{"id":"plato-symposiu-457","text":"\"I sit down to write to you this morning in an inexpressibly flat state;\r having spent the whole of yesterday and the day before in a gradually\r increasing headache, which grew at last rampant and violent, ended with\r excessive sickness, and this morning I am quite weak and washy. I hoped\r to leave my headaches behind me at Haworth; but it seems I brought them\r carefully packed in my trunk, and very much have they been in my way\r since I came. . . . Since I wrote last, I have seen various things worth\r describing; Rachel, the great French actress, amongst the number. But\r to-day I really have ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"457"},"sequenceIndex":3316},{"id":"plato-symposiu-458","text":"\"I cannot boast that London has agreed with me well this time; the\r oppression of frequent headache, sickness, and a low tone of spirits,\r has poisoned many moments which might otherwise have been pleasant.\r Sometimes I have felt this hard, and been tempted to murmur at Fate,\r which compels me to comparative silence and solitude for eleven months\r in the year, and in the twelfth, while offering social enjoyment, takes\r away the vigour and cheerfulness which should turn it to account. But\r circumstances are ordered for us, and we must submit.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"458"},"sequenceIndex":3317},{"id":"plato-symposiu-459","text":"\"Your letter would have been answered yesterday, but I was already gone\r out before post time, and was out all day. People are very kind, and\r perhaps I shall be glad of what I have seen afterwards, but it is often\r a little trying at the time. On Thursday, the Marquis of Westminster\r asked me to a great party, to which I was to go with Mrs. D----, a\r beautiful, and, I think, a kind woman too; but this I resolutely\r declined. On Friday I dined at the ----'s, and met Mrs. D---- and Mr.\r Monckton Milnes. On Saturday I went to hear and see Rachel; a wonderful\r sight--terrible as if the earth had ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"459"},"sequenceIndex":3318},{"id":"plato-symposiu-460","text":"\"----may have told you that I have spent a month in London this summer.\r When you come, you shall ask what questions you like on that point, and\r I will answer to the best of my stammering ability. Do not press me much\r on the subject of the 'Crystal Palace.' I went there five times, and\r certainly saw some interesting things, and the 'coup d'oeil' is striking\r and bewildering enough; but I never was able to get any raptures on the\r subject, and each renewed visit was made under coercion rather than my\r own free will. It is an excessively bustling place; and, after all, its\r wonders appeal too","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"460"},"sequenceIndex":3319},{"id":"plato-symposiu-461","text":"Miss Bronte returned from London by Manchester, and paid us a visit of\r a couple of days at the end of June. The weather was so intensely hot,\r and she herself so much fatigued with her London sight-seeing, that we\r did little but sit in-doors, with open windows, and talk. The only thing\r she made a point of exerting herself to procure was a present for Tabby.\r It was to be a shawl, or rather a large handkerchief, such as she could\r pin across her neck and shoulders, in the old-fashioned country manner.\r Miss Bronte took great pains in seeking out one which she thought\r would please the old wo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"461"},"sequenceIndex":3320},{"id":"plato-symposiu-462","text":"\"My dear Mrs. Smith,--Once more I am at home, where, I am thankful to\r say, I found my father very well. The journey to Manchester was a little\r hot and dusty, but otherwise pleasant enough. The two stout gentlemen,\r who filled a portion of the carriage when I got in, quitted it at Rugby,\r and two other ladies and myself had it to ourselves the rest of the\r way. The visit to Mrs. Gaskell formed a cheering break in the journey.\r Haworth Parsonage is rather a contrast, yet even Haworth Parsonage does\r not look gloomy in this bright summer weather; it is somewhat still,\r but with the windows open","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"462"},"sequenceIndex":3321},{"id":"plato-symposiu-463","text":"\"My dear Sir,--Thackeray's last lecture must, I think, have been his\r best. What he says about Sterne is true. His observations on literary\r men, and their social obligations and individual duties, seem to me\r also true and full of mental and moral vigour. . . . The International\r Copyright Meeting seems to have had but a barren result, judging from\r the report in the Literary Gazette. I cannot see that Sir E. Bulwer and\r the rest DID anything; nor can I well see what it is in their power to\r do. The argument brought forward about the damage accruing to American\r national literature from the p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"463"},"sequenceIndex":3322},{"id":"plato-symposiu-464","text":"\"Before I received your last, I had made up my mind to tell you that I\r should expect no letter for three months to come (intending afterwards\r to extend this abstinence to six months, for I am jealous of becoming\r dependent on this indulgence: you doubtless cannot see why, because you\r do not live my life). Nor shall I now expect a letter; but since you say\r that you would like to write now and then, I cannot say 'never write,'\r without imposing on my real wishes a falsehood which they reject, and\r doing to them a violence, to which they entirely refuse to submit. I\r can only observe that whe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"464"},"sequenceIndex":3323},{"id":"plato-symposiu-465","text":"Soon after she returned home, her friend paid her a visit. While she\r stayed at Haworth, Miss Bronte wrote the letter from which the following\r extract is taken. The strong sense and right feeling displayed in it on\r the subject of friendship, sufficiently account for the constancy of\r affection which Miss Bronte earned from all those who once became her\r friends.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"465"},"sequenceIndex":3324},{"id":"plato-symposiu-466","text":"\". . . I could not help wondering whether Cornhill will ever change for\r me, as Oxford has changed for you. I have some pleasant associations\r connected with it now--will these alter their character some day?","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"466"},"sequenceIndex":3325},{"id":"plato-symposiu-467","text":"\"Perhaps they may--though I have faith to the contrary, because, I\r THINK, I do not exaggerate my partialities; I THINK I take faults along\r with excellences--blemishes together with beauties. And, besides, in the\r matter of friendship, I have observed that disappointment here arises\r chiefly, NOT from liking our friends too well, or thinking of them too\r highly, but rather from an over-estimate of THEIR liking for and opinion\r of US; and that if we guard ourselves with sufficient scrupulousness of\r care from error in this direction, and can be content, and even happy\r to give more affection t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"467"},"sequenceIndex":3326},{"id":"plato-symposiu-468","text":"\"How interesting your old maiden-cousin's gossip about your parents\r must have been to you; and how gratifying to find that the reminiscence\r turned on none but pleasant facts and characteristics! Life must,\r indeed, be slow in that little decaying hamlet amongst the chalk hills.\r After all, depend upon it, it is better to be worn out with work in a\r thronged community, than to perish of inaction in a stagnant solitude:\r take this truth into consideration whenever you get tired of work and\r bustle.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"468"},"sequenceIndex":3327},{"id":"plato-symposiu-469","text":"I received a letter from her a little later than this; and though there\r is reference throughout to what I must have said in writing to her, all\r that it called forth in reply is so peculiarly characteristic, that I\r cannot prevail upon myself to pass it over without a few extracts:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"469"},"sequenceIndex":3328},{"id":"plato-symposiu-470","text":"\"My dear Mrs. Gaskell,--I was too much pleased with your letter, when I\r got it at last, to feel disposed to murmur now about the delay.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"470"},"sequenceIndex":3329},{"id":"plato-symposiu-471","text":"\"About a fortnight ago, I received a letter from Miss Martineau; also\r a long letter, and treating precisely the same subjects on which yours\r dwelt, viz., the Exhibition and Thackeray's last lecture. It was\r interesting mentally to place the two documents side by side--to study\r the two aspects of mind--to view, alternately, the same scene through\r two mediums. Full striking was the difference; and the more striking\r because it was not the rough contrast of good and evil, but the more\r subtle opposition, the more delicate diversity of different kinds of\r good. The excellences of one nature re","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"471"},"sequenceIndex":3330},{"id":"plato-symposiu-472","text":"\"I very much agree with you in all you say. For the sake of variety, I\r could almost wish that the concord of opinion were less complete.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"472"},"sequenceIndex":3331},{"id":"plato-symposiu-473","text":"\"To begin with Trafalgar Square. My taste goes with yours and Meta's\r completely on this point. I have always thought it a fine site (and\r SIGHT also). The view from the summit of those steps has ever struck\r me as grand and imposing--Nelson Column included the fountains I could\r dispense with. With respect, also, to the Crystal Palace, my thoughts\r are precisely yours.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"473"},"sequenceIndex":3332},{"id":"plato-symposiu-474","text":"\"Then I feel sure you speak justly of Thackeray's lecture. You do well\r to set aside odious comparisons, and to wax impatient of that trite\r twaddle about 'nothing newness'--a jargon which simply proves, in those\r who habitually use it, a coarse and feeble faculty of appreciation; an\r inability to discern the relative value of ORIGINALITY and NOVELTY; a\r lack of that refined perception which, dispensing with the stimulus of\r an ever-new subject, can derive sufficiency of pleasure from freshness\r of treatment. To such critics, the prime of a summer morning would\r bring no delight; wholly occupi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"474"},"sequenceIndex":3333},{"id":"plato-symposiu-475","text":"\"Is it Mr. ----'s family experience which has influenced your feelings\r about the Catholics? I own, I cannot be sorry for this commencing\r change. Good people--VERY good people--I doubt not, there are amongst\r the Romanists, but the system is not one which would have such sympathy\r as YOURS. Look at Popery taking off the mask in Naples!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"475"},"sequenceIndex":3334},{"id":"plato-symposiu-476","text":"\"I have read the 'Saints' Tragedy.' As a 'work of art' it seems to me\r far superior to either 'Alton Locke' or 'Yeast.' Faulty it may be,\r crude and unequal, yet there are portions where some of the deep chords\r of human nature are swept with a hand which is strong even while it\r falters. We see throughout (I THINK) that Elizabeth has not, and never\r had, a mind perfectly sane. From the time that she was what she herself,\r in the exaggeration of her humility, calls 'an idiot girl,' to the hour\r when she lay moaning in visions on her dying bed, a slight craze runs\r through her whole existence. ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"476"},"sequenceIndex":3335},{"id":"plato-symposiu-477","text":"\"Deep truths are touched on in this tragedy--touched on, not fully\r elicited; truths that stir a peculiar pity--a compassion hot with wrath,\r and bitter with pain. This is no poet's dream: we know that such things\r HAVE been done; that minds HAVE been thus subjugated, and lives thus\r laid waste.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"477"},"sequenceIndex":3336},{"id":"plato-symposiu-478","text":"\"Remember me kindly and respectfully to Mr. Gaskell, and though I\r have not seen Marianne, I must beg to include her in the love I send\r the others. Could you manage to convey a small kiss to that dear, but\r dangerous little person, Julia? She surreptitiously possessed herself of\r a minute fraction of my heart, which has been missing, ever since I saw\r her.--Believe me, sincerely and affectionately yours,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"478"},"sequenceIndex":3337},{"id":"plato-symposiu-479","text":"The reference which she makes at the end of this letter is to my\r youngest little girl, between whom and her a strong mutual attraction\r existed. The child would steal her little hand into Miss Bronte's\r scarcely larger one, and each took pleasure in this apparently\r unobserved caress. Yet once when I told Julia to take and show her the\r way to some room in the house, Miss Bronte shrunk back: \"Do not BID her\r do anything for me,\" she said; \"it has been so sweet hitherto to have\r her rendering her little kindnesses SPONTANEOUSLY.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"479"},"sequenceIndex":3338},{"id":"plato-symposiu-480","text":"As illustrating her feelings with regard to children, I may give what\r she says ill another of her letters to me.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"480"},"sequenceIndex":3339},{"id":"plato-symposiu-481","text":"\"Whenever I see Florence and Julia again, I shall feel like a fond but\r bashful suitor, who views at a distance the fair personage to whom, in\r his clownish awe, he dare not risk a near approach. Such is the clearest\r idea I can give you of my feeling towards children I like, but to\r whom I am a stranger;--and to what children am I not a stranger? They\r seem to me little wonders; their talk, their ways are all matter of\r half-admiring, half-puzzled speculation.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"481"},"sequenceIndex":3340},{"id":"plato-symposiu-482","text":"The following is part of a long letter which I received from her, dated\r September 20th, 1851:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"482"},"sequenceIndex":3341},{"id":"plato-symposiu-483","text":"\". . . Beautiful are those sentences out of James Martineau's sermons;\r some of them gems most pure and genuine; ideas deeply conceived, finely\r expressed. I should like much to see his review of his sister's book.\r Of all the articles respecting which you question me, I have seen none,\r except that notable one in the 'Westminster' on the Emancipation of\r Women. But why are you and I to think (perhaps I should rather say to\r FEEL) so exactly alike on some points that there can be no discussion\r between us? Your words on this paper express my thoughts. Well-argued\r it is,--clear, logical,--but ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"483"},"sequenceIndex":3342},{"id":"plato-symposiu-484","text":"\"I send by this post Ruskin's 'Stones of Venice,' and I hope you\r and Meta will find passages in it that will please you. Some parts\r would be dry and technical were it not for the character, the marked\r individuality which pervades every page. I wish Marianne had come to\r speak to me at the lecture; it would have given me such pleasure. What\r you say of that small sprite Julia, amuses me much. I believe you don't\r know that she has a great deal of her mama's nature (modified) in her;\r yet I think you will find she has as she grows up.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"484"},"sequenceIndex":3343},{"id":"plato-symposiu-485","text":"\"Will it not be a great mistake, if Mr. Thackeray should deliver his\r lectures at Manchester under such circumstances and conditions as will\r exclude people like you and Mr. Gaskell from the number of his audience?\r I thought his London-plan too narrow. Charles Dickens would not thus\r limit his sphere of action.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"485"},"sequenceIndex":3344},{"id":"plato-symposiu-486","text":"\"You charge me to write about myself. What can I say on that precious\r topic? My health is pretty good. My spirits are not always alike.\r Nothing happens to me. I hope and expect little in this world, and am\r thankful that I do not despond and suffer more. Thank you for inquiring\r after our old servant; she is pretty well; the little shawl, etc.,\r pleased her much. Papa likewise, I am glad to say, is pretty well; with\r his and my kindest regards to you and Mr. Gaskell--Believe me sincerely\r and affectionately yours,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"486"},"sequenceIndex":3345},{"id":"plato-symposiu-487","text":"Before the autumn was far advanced, the usual effects of her solitary\r life, and of the unhealthy situation of Haworth Parsonage, began to\r appear in the form of sick headaches, and miserable, starting, wakeful\r nights. She does not dwell on this in her letters; but there is an\r absence of all cheerfulness of tone, and an occasional sentence forced\r out of her, which imply far more than many words could say. There was\r illness all through the Parsonage household--taking its accustomed forms\r of lingering influenza and low fever; she herself was outwardly the\r strongest of the family, and all d","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"487"},"sequenceIndex":3346},{"id":"plato-symposiu-488","text":"\"As I laid down your letter, after reading with interest the graphic\r account it gives of a very striking scene, I could not help feeling with\r renewed force a truth, trite enough, yet ever impressive; viz., that it\r is good to be attracted out of ourselves--to be forced to take a near\r view of the sufferings, the privations, the efforts, the difficulties\r of others. If we ourselves live in fulness of content, it is well to be\r reminded that thousands of our fellow-creatures undergo a different lot;\r it is well to have sleepy sympathies excited, and lethargic selfishness\r shaken up. If, on the","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"488"},"sequenceIndex":3347},{"id":"plato-symposiu-489","text":"\"All those crowded emigrants had their troubles,--their untoward causes\r of banishment; you, the looker-on, had 'your wishes and regrets,'--your\r anxieties, alloying your home happiness and domestic bliss; and the\r parallel might be pursued further, and still it would be true,--still\r the same; a thorn in the flesh for each; some burden, some conflict for\r all.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"489"},"sequenceIndex":3348},{"id":"plato-symposiu-490","text":"\"How far this state of things is susceptible of amelioration from\r changes in public institutions,--alterations in national habits,--may\r and ought to be earnestly considered: but this is a problem not easily\r solved. The evils, as you point them out, are great, real, and most\r obvious; the remedy is obscure and vague; yet for such difficulties as\r spring from over-competition, emigration must be good; the new life\r in a new country must give a new lease of hope; the wider field, less\r thickly peopled, must open a new path for endeavour. But I always think\r great physical powers of exertion an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"490"},"sequenceIndex":3349},{"id":"plato-symposiu-491","text":"\"Perhaps Currer Bell has his secret moan about these matters; but if so,\r he will keep it to himself. It is an affair about which no words need\r be wasted, for no words can make a change: it is between him and his\r position, his faculties and his fate.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"491"},"sequenceIndex":3350},{"id":"plato-symposiu-492","text":"My husband and I were anxious that she should pay us a visit before\r the winter had set completely in; and she thus wrote, declining our\r invitation:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"492"},"sequenceIndex":3351},{"id":"plato-symposiu-493","text":"\"If anybody would tempt me from home, you would; but, just now, from\r home I must not, will not go. I feel greatly better at present than\r I did three weeks ago. For a month or six weeks about the equinox\r (autumnal or vernal) is a period of the year which, I have noticed,\r strangely tries me. Sometimes the strain falls on the mental, sometimes\r on the physical part of me; I am ill with neuralgic headache, or I am\r ground to the dust with deep dejection of spirits (not, however, such\r dejection but I can keep it to myself). That weary time has, I think\r and trust, got over for this year. It wa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"493"},"sequenceIndex":3352},{"id":"plato-symposiu-494","text":"\"As to running away from home every time I have a battle of this sort\r to fight, it would not do besides, the 'weird' would follow. As to\r shaking it off, that cannot be. I have declined to go to Mrs. ----, to\r Miss Martineau, and now I decline to go to you. But listen do not think\r that I throw your kindness away; or that it fails of doing the good you\r desire. On the contrary, the feeling expressed in your letter,--proved\r by your invitation--goes RIGHT HOME where you would have it to go, and\r heals as you would have it to heal.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"494"},"sequenceIndex":3353},{"id":"plato-symposiu-495","text":"\"Your description of Frederika Bremer tallies exactly with one I read\r somewhere, in I know not what book. I laughed out when I got to the\r mention of Frederika's special accomplishment, given by you with a\r distinct simplicity that, to my taste, is what the French would call\r 'impayable.' Where do you find the foreigner who is without some little\r drawback of this description? It is a pity.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"495"},"sequenceIndex":3354},{"id":"plato-symposiu-496","text":"A visit from Miss Wooler at this period did Miss Bronte much good for\r the time. She speaks of her guest's company as being very pleasant,\"like\r good wine,\" both to her father and to herself. But Miss Wooler could\r not remain with her long; and then again the monotony of her life\r returned upon her in all its force; the only events of her days and\r weeks consisting in the small changes which occasional letters brought.\r It must be remembered that her health was often such as to prevent her\r stirring out of the house in inclement or wintry weather. She was liable\r to sore throat, and depressing","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"496"},"sequenceIndex":3355},{"id":"plato-symposiu-497","text":"A letter from her late visitor touched and gratified her much; it was\r simply expressive of gratitude for attention and kindness shown to her,\r but it wound up by saying that she had not for many years experienced\r so much enjoyment as during the ten days passed at Haworth. This little\r sentence called out a wholesome sensation of modest pleasure in Miss\r Bronte's mind; and she says, \"it did me good.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"497"},"sequenceIndex":3356},{"id":"plato-symposiu-498","text":"I find, in a letter to a distant friend, written about this time, a\r retrospect of her visit to London. It is too ample to be considered as\r a mere repetition of what she had said before; and, besides, it shows\r that her first impressions of what she saw and heard were not crude and\r transitory, but stood the tests of time and after-thought.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"498"},"sequenceIndex":3357},{"id":"plato-symposiu-499","text":"\"I spent a few weeks in town last summer, as you have heard; and was\r much interested by many things I heard and saw there. What now chiefly\r dwells in my memory are Mr. Thackeray's lectures, Mademoiselle Rachel's\r acting, D'Aubigne's, Melville's, and Maurice's preaching, and the\r Crystal Palace.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"499"},"sequenceIndex":3358},{"id":"plato-symposiu-500","text":"\"Mr. Thackeray's lectures you will have seen mentioned and commented on\r in the papers; they were very interesting. I could not always coincide\r with the sentiments expressed, or the opinions broached; but I admired\r the gentlemanlike ease, the quiet humour, the taste, the talent, the\r simplicity, and the originality of the lecturer.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"500"},"sequenceIndex":3359},{"id":"plato-symposiu-501","text":"\"Rachel's acting transfixed me with wonder, enchained me with interest,\r and thrilled me with horror. The tremendous force with which she\r expresses the very worst passions in their strongest essence forms an\r exhibition as exciting as the bull fights of Spain, and the gladiatorial\r combats of old Rome, and (it seemed to me) not one whit more moral\r than these poisoned stimulants to popular ferocity. It is scarcely\r human nature that she shows you; it is something wilder and worse; the\r feelings and fury of a fiend. The great gift of genius she undoubtedly\r has; but, I fear, she rather abuses ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"501"},"sequenceIndex":3360},{"id":"plato-symposiu-502","text":"\"With all the three preachers I was greatly pleased. Melville seemed to\r me the most eloquent, Maurice the most in earnest; had I the choice, it\r is Maurice whose ministry I should frequent.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"502"},"sequenceIndex":3361},{"id":"plato-symposiu-503","text":"\"On the Crystal Palace I need not comment. You must already have heard\r too much of it. It struck me at the first with only a vague sort of\r wonder and admiration; but having one day the privilege of going over it\r in company with an eminent countryman of yours, Sir David Brewster, and\r hearing, in his friendly Scotch accent, his lucid explanation of many\r things that had been to me before a sealed book, I began a little better\r to comprehend it, or at least a small part of it: whether its final\r results will equal expectation, I know not.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"503"},"sequenceIndex":3362},{"id":"plato-symposiu-504","text":"Her increasing indisposition subdued her at last, in spite of all her\r efforts of reason and will. She tried to forget oppressive recollections\r in writing. Her publishers were importunate for a new book from her pen.\r \"Villette\" was begun, but she lacked power to continue it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"504"},"sequenceIndex":3363},{"id":"plato-symposiu-505","text":"\"It is not at all likely\" (she says) \"that my book will be ready at the\r time you mention. If my health is spared, I shall get on with it as\r fast as is consistent with its being done, if not WELL, yet as well as\r I can do it. NOT ONE WHIT FASTER. When the mood leaves me (it has left\r me now, without vouchsafing so much as a word or a message when it will\r return) I put by the MS. and wait till it comes back again. God knows,\r I sometimes have to wait long--VERY long it seems to me. Meantime, if\r I might make a request to you, it would be this. Please to say nothing\r about my book till it is w","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"505"},"sequenceIndex":3364},{"id":"plato-symposiu-506","text":"The \"mood\" here spoken of did not go off; it had a physical origin.\r Indigestion, nausea, headache, sleeplessness,--all combined to produce\r miserable depression of spirits. A little event which occurred about\r this time, did not tend to cheer her. It was the death of poor old\r faithful Keeper, Emily's dog. He had come to the Parsonage in the\r fierce strength of his youth. Sullen and ferocious he had met with his\r master in the indomitable Emily. Like most dogs of his kind, he feared,\r respected, and deeply loved her who subdued him. He had mourned her with\r the pathetic fidelity of his nature","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"506"},"sequenceIndex":3365},{"id":"plato-symposiu-507","text":"When Miss Bronte wrote this, on December 8th, she was suffering from a\r bad cold, and pain in her side. Her illness increased, and on December\r 17th, she--so patient, silent, and enduring of suffering--so afraid of\r any unselfish taxing of others--had to call to her friend for help:","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"507"},"sequenceIndex":3366},{"id":"plato-symposiu-508","text":"\"I cannot at present go to see you, but I would be grateful if you could\r come and see me, even were it only for a few days. To speak truth, I\r have put on but a poor time of it during this month past. I kept hoping\r to be better, but was at last obliged to have recourse to a medical man.\r Sometimes I have felt very weak and low, and longed much for society,\r but could not persuade myself to commit the selfish act of asking you\r merely for my own relief. The doctor speaks encouragingly, but as yet\r I get no better. As the illness has been coming on for a long time,\r it cannot, I suppose, be ex","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"508"},"sequenceIndex":3367},{"id":"plato-symposiu-509","text":"Of course, her friend went; and a certain amount of benefit was derived\r from her society, always so grateful to Miss Bronte. But the evil was\r now too deep-rooted to be more than palliated for a time by \"the little\r cheerful society\" for which she so touchingly besought.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"509"},"sequenceIndex":3368},{"id":"plato-symposiu-510","text":"A relapse came on before long. She was very ill, and the remedies\r employed took an unusual effect on her peculiar sensitiveness of\r constitution. Mr. Bronte was miserably anxious about the state of\r his only remaining child, for she was reduced to the last degree of\r weakness, as she had been unable to swallow food for above a week\r before. She rallied, and derived her sole sustenance from half-a-tea-cup\r of liquid, administered by tea-spoonfuls, in the course of the day. Yet\r she kept out of bed, for her father's sake, and struggled in solitary\r patience through her worst hours.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"510"},"sequenceIndex":3369},{"id":"plato-symposiu-511","text":"When she was recovering, her spirits needed support, and then she\r yielded to her friend's entreaty that she would visit her. All the time\r that Miss Bronte's illness had lasted, Miss ---- had been desirous\r of coming to her; but she refused to avail herself of this kindness,\r saying, that \"it was enough to burden herself; that it would be\r misery to annoy another;\" and, even at her worst time, she tells her\r friend, with humorous glee, how coolly she had managed to capture one\r of Miss ----'s letters to Mr. Bronte, which she suspected was of a\r kind to aggravate his alarm about his daughter's","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"511"},"sequenceIndex":3370},{"id":"plato-symposiu-512","text":"Happily for all parties, Mr. Bronte was wonderfully well this winter;\r good sleep, good spirits, and an excellent steady appetite, all seemed\r to mark vigour; and in such a state of health, Charlotte could leave him\r to spend a week with her friend, without any great anxiety.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"512"},"sequenceIndex":3371},{"id":"plato-symposiu-513","text":"She benefited greatly by the kind attentions and cheerful society of\r the family with whom she went to stay. They did not care for her in\r the least as \"Currer Bell,\" but had known and loved her for years as\r Charlotte Bronte. To them her invalid weakness was only a fresh claim\r upon their tender regard, from the solitary woman, whom they had first\r known as a little, motherless school-girl.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"513"},"sequenceIndex":3372},{"id":"plato-symposiu-514","text":"Miss Bronte wrote to me about this time, and told me something of what\r she had suffered.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"514"},"sequenceIndex":3373},{"id":"plato-symposiu-515","text":"\"Certainly, the past winter has been to me a strange time; had I the\r prospect before me of living it over again, my prayer must necessarily\r be, 'Let this cup pass from me.' That depression of spirits, which I\r thought was gone by when I wrote last, came back again with a heavy\r recoil; internal congestion ensued, and then inflammation. I had severe\r pain in my right side, frequent burning and aching in my chest; sleep\r almost forsook me, or would never come, except accompanied by ghastly\r dreams; appetite vanished, and slow fever was my continual companion.\r It was some time before I could b","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"515"},"sequenceIndex":3374},{"id":"plato-symposiu-516","text":"It was a great interest to her to be allowed an early reading of Esmond;\r and she expressed her thoughts on the subject, in a criticising letter\r to Mr. Smith, who had given her this privilege.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"516"},"sequenceIndex":3375},{"id":"plato-symposiu-517","text":"\"My dear Sir,--It has been a great delight to me to read Mr. Thackeray's\r work; and I so seldom now express my sense of kindness that, for once,\r you must permit me, without rebuke, to thank you for a pleasure so rare\r and special. Yet I am not going to praise either Mr. Thackeray or his\r book. I have read, enjoyed, been interested, and, after all, feel full\r as much ire and sorrow as gratitude and admiration. And still one can\r never lay down a book of his without the last two feelings having their\r part, be the subject or treatment what it may. In the first half of\r the book, what chiefly st","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"517"},"sequenceIndex":3376},{"id":"plato-symposiu-518","text":"\"As usual, he is unjust to women; quite unjust. There is hardly any\r punishment he does not deserve for making Lady Castlewood peep through a\r keyhole, listen at a door, and be jealous of a boy and a milkmaid. Many\r other things I noticed that, for my part, grieved and exasperated me as\r I read; but then, again, came passages so true, so deeply thought, so\r tenderly felt, one could not help forgiving and admiring.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"518"},"sequenceIndex":3377},{"id":"plato-symposiu-519","text":"But I wish he could be told not to care much for dwelling on the\r political or religious intrigues of the times. Thackeray, in his heart,\r does not value political or religious intrigues of any age or date. He\r likes to show us human nature at home, as he himself daily sees it; his\r wonderful observant faculty likes to be in action. In him this faculty\r is a sort of captain and leader; and if ever any passage in his writings\r lacks interest, it is when this master-faculty is for a time thrust into\r a subordinate position. I think such is the case in the former half\r of the present volume. Towa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"519"},"sequenceIndex":3378},{"id":"plato-symposiu-520","text":"Miss Bronte's health continued such, that she could not apply herself\r to writing as she wished, for many weeks after the serious attack from\r which she had suffered. There was not very much to cheer her in the\r few events that touched her interests during this time. She heard in\r March of the death of a friend's relation in the Colonies; and we see\r something of what was the corroding dread at her heart.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"520"},"sequenceIndex":3379},{"id":"plato-symposiu-521","text":"\"The news of E----'s death came to me last week in a letter from M ----;\r a long letter, which wrung my heart so, in its simple, strong, truthful\r emotion, I have only ventured to read it once. It ripped up half-scarred\r wounds with terrible force. The death-bed was just the same,--breath\r failing, etc. She fears she shall now, in her dreary solitude, become a\r 'stern, harsh, selfish woman.' This fear struck home; again and again\r have I felt it for myself, and what is MY position to M----'s? May God\r help her, as God only can help!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"521"},"sequenceIndex":3380},{"id":"plato-symposiu-522","text":"Again and again, her friend urged her to leave home; nor were various\r invitations wanting to enable her to do this, when these constitutional\r accesses of low spirits preyed too much upon her in her solitude. But\r she would not allow herself any such indulgence, unless it became\r absolutely necessary from the state of her health. She dreaded the\r perpetual recourse to such stimulants as change of scene and society,\r because of the reaction that was sure to follow. As far as she could\r see, her life was ordained to be lonely, and she must subdue her\r nature to her life, and, if possible, bring","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"522"},"sequenceIndex":3381},{"id":"plato-symposiu-523","text":"This was the case all through the present spring; and anxious as her\r publishers were for its completion, Villette stood still. Even her\r letters to her friend are scarce and brief. Here and there I find a\r sentence in them which can be extracted, and which is worth preserving.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"523"},"sequenceIndex":3382},{"id":"plato-symposiu-524","text":"\"M----'s letter is very interesting; it shows a mind one cannot but\r truly admire. Compare its serene trusting strength, with poor ----'s\r vacillating dependence. When the latter was in her first burst of\r happiness, I never remember the feeling finding vent in expressions of\r gratitude to God. There was always a continued claim upon your sympathy\r in the mistrust and doubt she felt of her own bliss. M---- believes;\r her faith is grateful and at peace; yet while happy in herself, how\r thoughtful she is for others!\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"524"},"sequenceIndex":3383},{"id":"plato-symposiu-525","text":"\"You say, dear E----, that you often wish I would chat on paper, as you\r do. How can I? Where are my materials? Is my life fertile in subjects of\r chat? What callers do I see? What visits do I pay? No, you must chat,\r and I must listen, and say 'Yes,' and 'No,' and 'Thank you!' for five\r minutes' recreation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"525"},"sequenceIndex":3384},{"id":"plato-symposiu-526","text":"\"I am amused at the interest you take in politics. Don't expect to\r rouse me; to me, all ministries and all oppositions seem to be pretty\r much alike. D'Israeli was factious as leader of the Opposition; Lord\r John Russell is going to be factious, now that he has stepped into\r D'Israeli's shoes. Lord Derby's 'Christian love and spirit,' is worth\r three half-pence farthing.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"526"},"sequenceIndex":3385},{"id":"plato-symposiu-527","text":"\"My dear Sir,--Mr. Smith intimated a short time since, that he had some\r thoughts of publishing a reprint of Shirley. Having revised the work,\r I now enclose the errata. I have likewise sent off to-day, per rail, a\r return-box of Cornhill books.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"527"},"sequenceIndex":3386},{"id":"plato-symposiu-528","text":"\"I have lately read with great pleasure, 'The Two Families.' This work,\r it seems, should have reached me in January; but owing to a mistake,\r it was detained at the Dead Letter Office, and lay there nearly two\r months. I liked the commencement very much; the close seemed to me\r scarcely equal to 'Rose Douglas.' I thought the authoress committed a\r mistake in shifting the main interest from the two personages on whom\r it first rests--viz., Ben Wilson and Mary--to other characters of quite\r inferior conception. Had she made Ben and Mary her hero and heroine, and\r continued the development of th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"528"},"sequenceIndex":3387},{"id":"plato-symposiu-529","text":"\"I ought long since to have acknowledged the gratification with which\r I read Miss Kavanagh's 'Women of Christianity.' Her charity and (on\r the whole) her impartiality are very beautiful. She touches, indeed,\r with too gentle a hand the theme of Elizabeth of Hungary; and, in her\r own mind, she evidently misconstrues the fact of Protestant charities\r SEEMING to be fewer than Catholic. She forgets, or does not know, that\r Protestantism is a quieter creed than Romanism; as it does not clothe\r its priesthood in scarlet, so neither does it set up its good women for\r saints, canonise their names, an","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"529"},"sequenceIndex":3388},{"id":"plato-symposiu-530","text":"\"With kind regards to yourself and family, who, I trust, have all safely\r weathered the rough winter lately past, as well as the east winds, which\r are still nipping our spring in Yorkshire,--I am, my dear Sir, yours\r sincerely,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"530"},"sequenceIndex":3389},{"id":"plato-symposiu-531","text":"\"My dear Sir,--The box arrived quite safely, and I very much thank you\r for the contents, which are most kindly selected.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"531"},"sequenceIndex":3390},{"id":"plato-symposiu-532","text":"\"As you wished me to say what I thought of 'The School for Fathers,'\r I hastened to read it. The book seems to me clever, interesting, very\r amusing, and likely to please generally. There is a merit in the choice\r of ground, which is not yet too hackneyed; the comparative freshness of\r subject, character, and epoch give the tale a certain attractiveness.\r There is also, I think, a graphic rendering of situations, and a lively\r talent for describing whatever is visible and tangible--what the eye\r meets on the surface of things. The humour appears to me such as would\r answer well on the stage; m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"532"},"sequenceIndex":3391},{"id":"plato-symposiu-533","text":"\"Your description of the model man of business is true enough, I doubt\r not; but we will not fear that society will ever be brought quite to\r this standard; human nature (bad as it is) has, after all, elements that\r forbid it. But the very tendency to such a consummation--the marked\r tendency, I fear, of the day--produces, no doubt, cruel suffering. Yet,\r when the evil of competition passes a certain limit, must it not in time\r work its own cure? I suppose it will, but then through some convulsed\r crisis, shattering all around it like an earthquake. Meantime, for how\r many is life made a strug","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"533"},"sequenceIndex":3392},{"id":"plato-symposiu-534","text":"A letter to her old Brussels schoolfellow gives a short retrospect of\r the dreary winter she had passed through.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"534"},"sequenceIndex":3393},{"id":"plato-symposiu-535","text":"\". . . I struggled through the winter, and the early part of the spring,\r often with great difficulty. My friend stayed with me a few days in the\r early part of January; she could not be spared longer. I was better\r during her visit, but had a relapse soon after she left me, which\r reduced my strength very much. It cannot be denied that the solitude\r of my position fearfully aggravated its other evils. Some long stormy\r days and nights there were, when I felt such a craving for support and\r companionship as I cannot express. Sleepless, I lay awake night after\r night, weak and unable to occupy ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"535"},"sequenceIndex":3394},{"id":"plato-symposiu-536","text":"\"I am better now; and very grateful do I feel for the restoration of\r tolerable health; but, as if there was always to be some affliction,\r papa, who enjoyed wonderful health during the whole winter, is ailing\r with his spring attack of bronchitis. I earnestly trust it may pass over\r in the comparatively ameliorated form in which it has hitherto shown\r itself.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"536"},"sequenceIndex":3395},{"id":"plato-symposiu-537","text":"\"Let me not forget to answer your question about the cataract. Tell your\r papa that MY father was seventy at the time he underwent an operation;\r he was most reluctant to try the experiment; could not believe that, at\r his age, and with his want of robust strength, it would succeed. I was\r obliged to be very decided in the matter, and to act entirely on my own\r responsibility. Nearly six years have now elapsed since the cataract\r was extracted (it was not merely depressed); he has never once during\r that time regretted the step, and a day seldom passes that he does not\r express gratitude and p","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"537"},"sequenceIndex":3396},{"id":"plato-symposiu-538","text":"I had given Miss Bronte; in one of my letters, an outline of the story\r on which I was then engaged, and in reply she says:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"538"},"sequenceIndex":3397},{"id":"plato-symposiu-539","text":"\"The sketch you give of your work (respecting which I am, of course,\r dumb) seems to me very noble; and its purpose may be as useful in\r practical result as it is high and just in theoretical tendency. Such a\r book may restore hope and energy to many who thought they had forfeited\r their right to both; and open a clear course for honourable effort to\r some who deemed that they and all honour had parted company in this\r world.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"539"},"sequenceIndex":3398},{"id":"plato-symposiu-540","text":"\"My heart fails me already at the thought of the pang it will have to\r undergo. And yet you must follow the impulse of your own inspiration.\r If THAT commands the slaying of the victim, no bystander has a right to\r put out his hand to stay the sacrificial knife: but I hold you a stern\r priestess in these matters.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"540"},"sequenceIndex":3399},{"id":"plato-symposiu-541","text":"As the milder weather came on, her health improved, and her power of\r writing increased. She set herself with redoubled vigour to the work\r before her; and denied herself pleasure for the purpose of steady\r labour. Hence she writes to her friend:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"541"},"sequenceIndex":3400},{"id":"plato-symposiu-542","text":"\"Dear E----, --I must adhere to my resolution of neither visiting nor\r being visited at present. Stay you quietly at B., till you go to S., as\r I shall stay at Haworth; as sincere a farewell can be taken with the\r heart as with the lips, and perhaps less painful. I am glad the weather\r is changed; the return of the south-west wind suits me; but I hope you\r have no cause to regret the departure of your favourite east wind. What\r you say about ---- does not surprise me; I have had many little notes\r (whereof I answer about one in three) breathing the same spirit,--self\r and child the sole all-ab","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"542"},"sequenceIndex":3401},{"id":"plato-symposiu-543","text":"\"I wish you, dear E., all health and enjoyment in your visit; and, as\r far as one can judge at present, there seems a fair prospect of the wish\r being realised.--Yours sincerely,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"543"},"sequenceIndex":3402},{"id":"plato-symposiu-544","text":"The reader will remember that Anne Bronte had been interred in the\r churchyard of the Old Church at Scarborough. Charlotte had left\r directions for a tombstone to be placed over her; but many a time during\r the solitude of the past winter, her sad, anxious thoughts had revisited\r the scene of that last great sorrow, and she had wondered whether all\r decent services had been rendered to the memory of the dead, until at\r last she came to a silent resolution to go and see for herself whether\r the stone and inscription were in a satisfactory state of preservation.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"544"},"sequenceIndex":3403},{"id":"plato-symposiu-545","text":"\"Dear E----, --I am at Filey utterly alone. Do not be angry, the step\r is right. I considered it, and resolved on it with due deliberation.\r Change of air was necessary; there were reasons why I should NOT go to\r the south, and why I should come here. On Friday I went to Scarborough,\r visited the churchyard and stone. It must be refaced and relettered;\r there are five errors. I gave the necessary directions. THAT duty, then,\r is done; long has it lain heavy on my mind; and that was a pilgrimage I\r felt I could only make alone.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"545"},"sequenceIndex":3404},{"id":"plato-symposiu-546","text":"\"I am in our old lodgings at Mrs. Smith's; not, however, in the same\r rooms, but in less expensive apartments. They seemed glad to see me,\r remembered you and me very well, and, seemingly, with great good will.\r The daughter who used to wait on us is just married. Filey seems to me\r much altered; more lodging-houses--some of them very handsome--have been\r built; the sea has all its old grandeur. I walk on the sands a good\r deal, and try NOT to feel desolate and melancholy. How sorely my heart\r longs for you, I need not say. I have bathed once; it seemed to do me\r good. I may, perhaps, stay her","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"546"},"sequenceIndex":3405},{"id":"plato-symposiu-547","text":"\"Dear E----, --Be quite easy about me. I really think I am better for my\r stay at Filey; that I have derived more benefit from it than I dared to\r anticipate. I believe, could I stay here two months, and enjoy something\r like social cheerfulness as well as exercise and good air, my health\r would be quite renewed. This, however, cannot possibly be; but I am most\r thankful for the good received. I stay here another week.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"547"},"sequenceIndex":3406},{"id":"plato-symposiu-548","text":"\"I return ----'s letter. I am sorry for her: I believe she suffers; but\r I do not much like her style of expressing herself. . . . Grief as well\r as joy manifests itself in most different ways in different people;\r and I doubt not she is sincere and in earnest when she talks of her\r 'precious, sainted father;' but I could wish she used simpler language.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"548"},"sequenceIndex":3407},{"id":"plato-symposiu-549","text":"Soon after her return from Filey, she was alarmed by a very serious and\r sharp attack of illness with which Mr. Bronte was seized. There was\r some fear, for a few days, that his sight was permanently lost, and his\r spirits sank painfully under this dread.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"549"},"sequenceIndex":3408},{"id":"plato-symposiu-550","text":"\"This prostration of spirits,\" writes his daughter, \"which accompanies\r anything like a relapse is almost the most difficult point to manage.\r Dear E----, you are tenderly kind in offering your society; but\r rest very tranquil where you are; be fully assured that it is not\r now, nor under present circumstances, that I feel the lack either\r of society or occupation; my time is pretty well filled up, and my\r thoughts appropriated. . . . I cannot permit myself to comment much\r on the chief contents of your last; advice is not necessary: as far\r as I can judge, you seem hitherto enabled to take th","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"550"},"sequenceIndex":3409},{"id":"plato-symposiu-551","text":"I suppose that, during the very time when her thoughts were thus fully\r occupied with anxiety for her father, she received some letter from her\r publishers, making inquiry as to the progress of the work which they\r knew she had in hand, as I find the following letter to Mr. Williams,\r bearing reference to some of Messrs. Smith and Elder's proposed\r arrangements.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"551"},"sequenceIndex":3410},{"id":"plato-symposiu-552","text":"\"My dear Sir,--Is it in contemplation to publish the new edition\r of 'Shirley' soon? Would it not be better to defer it for a time?\r In reference to a part of your letter, permit me to express this\r wish,--and I trust in doing so, I shall not be regarded as stepping out\r of my position as an author, and encroaching on the arrangements of\r business,--viz.: that no announcement of a new work by the author of\r 'Jane Eyre' shall be made till the MS. of such work is actually in my\r publisher's hands. Perhaps we are none of us justified in speaking very\r decidedly where the future is concerned; but ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"552"},"sequenceIndex":3411},{"id":"plato-symposiu-553","text":"\"Last autumn I got on for a time quickly. I ventured to look forward to\r spring as the period of publication: my health gave way; I passed such\r a winter as, having been once experienced, will never be forgotten.\r The spring proved little better than a protraction of trial. The warm\r weather and a visit to the sea have done me much good physically; but as\r yet I have recovered neither elasticity of animal spirits, nor flow of\r the power of composition. And if it were otherwise, the difference would\r be of no avail; my time and thoughts are at present taken up with close\r attendance on my fathe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"553"},"sequenceIndex":3412},{"id":"plato-symposiu-554","text":"Before the end of August, Mr. Bronte's convalescence became quite\r established, and he was anxious to resume his duties for some time\r before his careful daughter would permit him.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"554"},"sequenceIndex":3413},{"id":"plato-symposiu-555","text":"On September the 14th the \"great duke\" died. He had been, as we have\r seen, her hero from childhood; but I find no further reference to him at\r this time than what is given in the following extract from a letter to\r her friend:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"555"},"sequenceIndex":3414},{"id":"plato-symposiu-556","text":"\"I do hope and believe the changes you have been having this summer will\r do you permanent good, notwithstanding the pain with which they have\r been too often mingled. Yet I feel glad that you are soon coming home;\r and I really must not trust myself to say how much I wish the time were\r come when, without let or hindrance, I could once more welcome you to\r Haworth. But oh I don't get on; I feel fretted--incapable--sometimes\r very low. However, at present, the subject must not be dwelt upon; it\r presses me too hardly--nearly--and painfully. Less than ever can I taste\r or know pleasure till thi","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"556"},"sequenceIndex":3415},{"id":"plato-symposiu-557","text":"\"Papa's health continues satisfactory, thank God! As for me, my wretched\r liver has been disordered again of late, but I hope it is now going to\r be on better behaviour; it hinders me in working--depresses both power\r and tone of feeling. I must expect this derangement from time to time.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"557"},"sequenceIndex":3416},{"id":"plato-symposiu-558","text":"Haworth was in an unhealthy state, as usual; and both Miss Bronte and\r Tabby suffered severely from the prevailing epidemics. The former was\r long in shaking off the effects of this illness. In vain she resolved\r against allowing herself any society or change of scene until she had\r accomplished her labour. She was too ill to write; and with illness\r came on the old heaviness of heart, recollections of the past, and\r anticipations of the future. At last Mr. Bronte expressed so strong a\r wish that her friend should be asked to visit her, and she felt some\r little refreshment so absolutely neces","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"558"},"sequenceIndex":3417},{"id":"plato-symposiu-559","text":"\"I thought I would persist in denying myself till I had done my work,\r but I find it won't do; the matter refuses to progress, and this\r excessive solitude presses too heavily; so let me see your dear face,\r E., just for one reviving week.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"559"},"sequenceIndex":3418},{"id":"plato-symposiu-560","text":"But she would only accept of the company of her friend for the exact\r time specified. She thus writes to Miss Wooler on October the 21st:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"560"},"sequenceIndex":3419},{"id":"plato-symposiu-561","text":"\"E---- has only been my companion one little week. I would not have her\r any longer, for I am disgusted with myself and my delays; and consider\r it was a weak yielding to temptation in me to send for her at all; but\r in truth, my spirits were getting low--prostrate sometimes--and she has\r done me inexpressible good. I wonder when I shall see you at Haworth\r again; both my father and the servants have again and again insinuated\r a distinct wish that you should be requested to come in the course of\r the summer and autumn, but I have always turned rather a deaf ear;\r 'not yet,' was my thought, 'I","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"561"},"sequenceIndex":3420},{"id":"plato-symposiu-562","text":"Miss ----'s visit had done her much good. Pleasant companionship during\r the day produced, for the time, the unusual blessing of calm repose at\r night; and after her friend's departure she was well enough to \"fall to\r business,\" and write away, almost incessantly, at her story of Villette,\r now drawing to a conclusion. The following letter to Mr. Smith, seems to\r have accompanied the first part of the MS.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"562"},"sequenceIndex":3421},{"id":"plato-symposiu-563","text":"\"My dear Sir,--You must notify honestly what you think of 'Villette'\r when you have read it. I can hardly tell you how I hunger to hear some\r opinion besides my own, and how I have sometimes desponded, and almost\r despaired, because there was no one to whom to read a line, or of whom\r to ask a counsel. 'Jane Eyre' was not written under such circumstances,\r nor were two-thirds of 'Shirley'. I got so miserable about it, I could\r bear no allusion to the book. It is not finished yet; but now I hope.\r As to the anonymous publication, I have this to say: If the withholding\r of the author's name shou","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"563"},"sequenceIndex":3422},{"id":"plato-symposiu-564","text":"\"The third volume seemed to me to possess the most sparkle, impetus,\r and interest. Of the first and second my judgment was, that parts of\r them were admirable; but there was the fault of containing too much\r History--too little story. I hold that a work of fiction ought to be a\r work of creation: that the REAL should be sparingly introduced in pages\r dedicated to the IDEAL. Plain household bread is a far more wholesome\r and necessary thing than cake; yet who would like to see the brown loaf\r placed on the table for dessert? In the second volume, the author gives\r us an ample supply of excelle","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"564"},"sequenceIndex":3423},{"id":"plato-symposiu-565","text":"Her letter to Mr. Smith, containing the allusion to 'Esmond,' which\r reminded me of the quotation just given continues:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"565"},"sequenceIndex":3424},{"id":"plato-symposiu-566","text":"\"You will see that 'Villette' touches on no matter of public interest.\r I cannot write books handling the topics of the day; it is of no use\r trying. Nor can I write a book for its moral. Nor can I take up a\r philanthropic scheme, though I honour philanthropy; and voluntarily and\r sincerely veil my face before such a mighty subject as that handled in\r Mrs. Beecher Stowe's work, 'Uncle Tom's Cabin.' To manage these great\r matters rightly, they must be long and practically studied--their\r bearings known intimately, and their evils felt genuinely; they must not\r be taken up as a business matter, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"566"},"sequenceIndex":3425},{"id":"plato-symposiu-567","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I feel very grateful for your letter; it relieved me\r much, for I was a good deal harassed by doubts as to how 'Villette'\r might appear in other eyes than my own. I feel in some degree authorised\r to rely on your favourable impressions, because you are quite right\r where you hint disapprobation. You have exactly hit two points at\r least where I was conscious of defect;--the discrepancy, the want of\r perfect harmony, between Graham's boyhood and manhood,--the angular\r abruptness of his change of sentiment towards Miss Fanshawe. You must\r remember, though, that in secret he had fo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"567"},"sequenceIndex":3426},{"id":"plato-symposiu-568","text":"\"Colonel Henry Esmond is just arrived. He looks very antique and\r distinguished in his Queen Anne's garb; the periwig, sword, lace, and\r ruffles are very well represented by the old 'Spectator' type.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"568"},"sequenceIndex":3427},{"id":"plato-symposiu-569","text":"In reference to a sentence towards the close of this letter, I may\r mention what she told me; that Mr. Bronte was anxious that her new\r tale should end well, as he disliked novels which left a melancholy\r impression upon the mind; and he requested her to make her hero and\r heroine (like the heroes and heroines in fairy-tales) \"marry, and live\r very happily ever after.\" But the idea of M. Paul Emanuel's death at sea\r was stamped on her imagination till it assumed the distinct force of\r reality; and she could no more alter her fictitious ending than if they\r had been facts which she was relating","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"569"},"sequenceIndex":3428},{"id":"plato-symposiu-570","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I must not delay thanking you for your kind letter,\r with its candid and able commentary on 'Villette.' With many of your\r strictures I concur. The third volume may, perhaps, do away with some\r of the objections; others still remain in force. I do not think the\r interest culminates anywhere to the degree you would wish. What climax\r there is does not come on till near the conclusion; and even then, I\r doubt whether the regular novel-reader will consider the 'agony piled\r sufficiently high' (as the Americans say), or the colours dashed on to\r the canvas with the proper amount of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"570"},"sequenceIndex":3429},{"id":"plato-symposiu-571","text":"\"Unless I am mistaken, the emotion of the book will be found to be kept\r throughout in tolerable subjection. As to the name of the heroine, I\r can hardly express what subtlety of thought made me decide upon giving\r her a cold name; but, at first, I called her 'Lucy Snowe' (spelt with\r an 'e'); which Snowe I afterwards changed to 'Frost.' Subsequently, I\r rather regretted the change, and wished it 'Snowe' again. If not too\r late, I should like the alteration to be made now throughout the MS. A\r COLD name she must have; partly, perhaps, on the 'lucus a non lucendo'\r principle--partly on that of ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"571"},"sequenceIndex":3430},{"id":"plato-symposiu-572","text":"\"You say that she may be thought morbid and weak, unless the history of\r her life be more fully given. I consider that she is both morbid and\r weak at times; her character sets up no pretensions to unmixed strength,\r and anybody living her life would necessarily become morbid. It was no\r impetus of healthy feeling which urged her to the confessional, for\r instance; it was the semi-delirium of solitary grief and sickness. If,\r however, the book does not express all this, there must be a great fault\r somewhere. I might explain away a few other points, but it would be too\r much like drawing a pic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"572"},"sequenceIndex":3431},{"id":"plato-symposiu-573","text":"\"Thanking you again for the clearness and fulness with which you have\r responded to my request for a statement of impressions, I am, my dear\r Sir, yours very sincerely,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"573"},"sequenceIndex":3432},{"id":"plato-symposiu-574","text":"\"I trust the work will be seen in MS. by no one except Mr. Smith and\r yourself.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"574"},"sequenceIndex":3433},{"id":"plato-symposiu-575","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I only wished the publication of 'Shirley' to be delayed\r till 'Villette' was nearly ready; so that there can now be no objection\r to its being issued whenever you think fit. About putting the MS. into\r type, I can only say that, should I be able to proceed with the third\r volume at my average rate of composition, and with no more than the\r average amount of interruptions, I should hope to have it ready in about\r three weeks. I leave it to you to decide whether it would be better to\r delay the printing that space of time, or to commence it immediately.\r It would certainly be mor","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"575"},"sequenceIndex":3434},{"id":"plato-symposiu-576","text":"On a Saturday, a little later in this month, Miss Bronte completed\r 'Villette,' and sent it off to her publishers. \"I said my prayers when\r I had done it. Whether it is well or ill done, I don't know; D. V., I\r will now try and wait the issue quietly. The book, I think, will not be\r considered pretentious; nor is it of a character to excite hostility.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"576"},"sequenceIndex":3435},{"id":"plato-symposiu-577","text":"As her labour was ended, she felt at liberty to allow herself a little\r change. There were several friends anxious to see her and welcome her\r to their homes Miss Martineau, Mrs. Smith, and her own faithful E----.\r With the last, in the same letter as that in which she announced the\r completion of 'Villette,' she offered to spend a week. She began, also,\r to consider whether it might not be well to avail herself of Mrs.\r Smith's kind invitation, with a view to the convenience of being on the\r spot to correct the proofs.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"577"},"sequenceIndex":3436},{"id":"plato-symposiu-578","text":"The following letter is given, not merely on account of her own\r criticisms on 'Villette,' but because it shows how she had learned to\r magnify the meaning of trifles, as all do who live a self-contained\r and solitary life. Mr. Smith had been unable to write by the same post\r as that which brought the money for 'Villette,' and she consequently\r received it without a line. The friend with whom she was staying says,\r that she immediately fancied there was some disappointment about\r 'Villette,' or that some word or act of hers had given offence; and had\r not the Sunday intervened, and so allowed ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"578"},"sequenceIndex":3437},{"id":"plato-symposiu-579","text":"\"My dear Sir,--The receipts have reached me safely. I received the first\r on Saturday, enclosed in a cover without a line, and had made up my\r mind to take the train on Monday, and go up to London to see what was\r the matter, and what had struck my publisher mute. On Sunday morning\r your letter came, and you have thus been spared the visitation of the\r unannounced and unsummoned apparition of Currer Bell in Cornhill.\r Inexplicable delays should be avoided when possible, for they are apt to\r urge those subjected to their harassment to sudden and impulsive steps.\r I must pronounce you right agai","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"579"},"sequenceIndex":3438},{"id":"plato-symposiu-580","text":"The difficulty that presented itself most strongly to me, when I first\r had the honour of being requested to write this biography, was how I\r could show what a noble, true, and tender woman Charlotte Bronte really\r was, without mingling up with her life too much of the personal history\r of her nearest and most intimate friends. After much consideration of\r this point, I came to the resolution of writing truly, if I wrote at\r all; of withholding nothing, though some things, from their very nature,\r could not be spoken of so fully as others.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"580"},"sequenceIndex":3439},{"id":"plato-symposiu-581","text":"One of the deepest interests of her life centres naturally round\r her marriage, and the preceding circumstances; but more than all\r other events (because of more recent date, and concerning another as\r intimately as herself), it requires delicate handling on my part, lest\r I intrude too roughly on what is most sacred to memory. Yet I have\r two reasons, which seem to me good and valid ones, for giving some\r particulars of the course of events which led to her few months of\r wedded life--that short spell of exceeding happiness. The first is my\r desire to call attention to the fact that Mr. Nicho","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"581"},"sequenceIndex":3440},{"id":"plato-symposiu-582","text":"In silence he had watched her, and loved her long. The love of such\r a man--a daily spectator of her manner of life for years--is a great\r testimony to her character as a woman.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"582"},"sequenceIndex":3441},{"id":"plato-symposiu-583","text":"How deep his affection was I scarcely dare to tell, even if I could\r in words. She did not know--she had hardly begun to suspect--that she\r was the object of any peculiar regard on his part, when, in this very\r December, he came one evening to tea. After tea, she returned from the\r study to her own sitting-room, as was her custom, leaving her father\r and his curate together. Presently she heard the study-door open, and\r expected to hear the succeeding clash of the front door. Instead, came\r a tap; and, \"like lightning, it flashed upon me what was coming. He\r entered. He stood before me. What h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"583"},"sequenceIndex":3442},{"id":"plato-symposiu-584","text":"So deep, so fervent, and so enduring was the affection Miss Bronte had\r inspired in the heart of this good man! It is an honour to her; and,\r as such, I have thought it my duty to speak thus much, and quote thus\r fully from her letter about it. And now I pass to my second reason for\r dwelling on a subject which may possibly be considered by some, at\r first sight, of too private a nature for publication. When Mr. Nicholls\r had left her, Charlotte went immediately to her father and told him\r all. He always disapproved of marriages, and constantly talked against\r them. But he more than disapprove","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"584"},"sequenceIndex":3443},{"id":"plato-symposiu-585","text":"The immediate result of Mr. Nicholls' declaration of attachment was,\r that he sent in his resignation of the curacy of Haworth; and that\r Miss Bronte held herself simply passive, as far as words and actions\r went, while she suffered acute pain from the strong expressions which\r her father used in speaking of Mr. Nicholls, and from the too evident\r distress and failure of health on the part of the latter. Under these\r circumstances she, more gladly than ever, availed herself of Mrs.\r Smith's proposal, that she should again visit them in London; and\r thither she accordingly went in the first wee","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"585"},"sequenceIndex":3444},{"id":"plato-symposiu-586","text":"From thence I received the following letter. It is with a sad, proud\r pleasure I copy her words of friendship now.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"586"},"sequenceIndex":3445},{"id":"plato-symposiu-587","text":"\"It is with YOU the ball rests. I have not heard from you since I wrote\r last; but I thought I knew the reason of your silence, viz. application\r to work,--and therefore I accept it, not merely with resignation, but\r with satisfaction.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"587"},"sequenceIndex":3446},{"id":"plato-symposiu-588","text":"\"I am now in London, as the date above will show; staying very quietly\r at my publisher's, and correcting proofs, etc. Before receiving yours,\r I had felt, and expressed to Mr. Smith, reluctance to come in the\r way of 'Ruth;' not that I think SHE would suffer from contact with\r 'Villette'--we know not but that the damage might be the other way; but\r I have ever held comparisons to be odious, and would fain that neither I\r nor my friends should be made subjects for the same. Mr. Smith proposes,\r accordingly, to defer the publication of my book till the 24th inst.;\r he says that will give 'Ruth'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"588"},"sequenceIndex":3447},{"id":"plato-symposiu-589","text":"\"I dare say, arrange as we may, we shall not be able wholly to prevent\r comparisons; it is the nature of some critics to be invidious; but we\r need not care we can set them at defiance; they SHALL not make us foes,\r they SHALL not mingle with our mutual feelings one taint of jealousy\r there is my hand on that; I know you will give clasp for clasp.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"589"},"sequenceIndex":3448},{"id":"plato-symposiu-590","text":"\"'Villette' has indeed no right to push itself before 'Ruth.' There is a\r goodness, a philanthropic purpose, a social use in the latter to which\r the former cannot for an instant pretend; nor can it claim precedence on\r the ground of surpassing power I think it much quieter than 'Jane Eyre.'","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"590"},"sequenceIndex":3449},{"id":"plato-symposiu-591","text":"\"I wish to see YOU, probably at least as much as you can wish to see ME,\r and therefore shall consider your invitation for March as an engagement;\r about the close of that month, then, I hope to pay you a brief visit.\r With kindest remembrances to Mr. Gaskell and all your precious circle, I\r am,\" etc.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"591"},"sequenceIndex":3450},{"id":"plato-symposiu-592","text":"This visit at Mrs. Smith's was passed more quietly than any previous\r one, and was consequently more in accordance with her own tastes. She\r saw things rather than persons; and being allowed to have her own choice\r of sights, she selected the \"REAL in preference to the DECORATIVE\r side of life.\" She went over two prisons,--one ancient, the other\r modern,--Newgate and Pentonville; over two hospitals, the Foundling and\r Bethlehem. She was also taken, at her own request, to see several of the\r great City sights; the Bank, the Exchange, Rothschild's, etc.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"592"},"sequenceIndex":3451},{"id":"plato-symposiu-593","text":"The power of vast yet minute organisation, always called out her respect\r and admiration. She appreciated it more fully than most women are able\r to do. All that she saw during this last visit to London impressed\r her deeply--so much so as to render her incapable of the immediate\r expression of her feelings, or of reasoning upon her impressions while\r they were so vivid. If she had lived, her deep heart would sooner or\r later have spoken out on these things.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"593"},"sequenceIndex":3452},{"id":"plato-symposiu-594","text":"What she saw dwelt in her thoughts, and lay heavy on her spirits. She\r received the utmost kindness from her hosts, and had the old, warm, and\r grateful regard for them. But looking back, with the knowledge of what\r was then the future, which Time has given, one cannot but imagine that\r there was a toning-down in preparation for the final farewell to these\r kind friends, whom she saw for the last time on a Wednesday morning in\r February. She met her friend E---- at Keighley, on her return, and the\r two proceeded to Haworth together.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"594"},"sequenceIndex":3453},{"id":"plato-symposiu-595","text":"\"Villette\"--which, if less interesting as a mere story than \"Jane\r Eyre,\" displays yet more of the extraordinary genius of the author--was\r received with one burst of acclamation. Out of so small a circle of\r characters, dwelling in so dull and monotonous an area as a \"pension,\"\r this wonderful tale was evolved!","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"595"},"sequenceIndex":3454},{"id":"plato-symposiu-596","text":"\"I got a budget of no less than seven papers yesterday and to-day.\r The import of all the notices is such as to make my heart swell with\r thankfulness to Him, who takes note both of suffering, and work, and\r motives. Papa is pleased too. As to friends in general, I believe I can\r love them still, without expecting them to take any large share in this\r sort of gratification. The longer I live, the more plainly I see that\r gentle must be the strain on fragile human nature; it will not bear\r much.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"596"},"sequenceIndex":3455},{"id":"plato-symposiu-597","text":"I suspect that the touch of slight disappointment, perceptible in the\r last few lines, arose from her great susceptibility to an opinion\r she valued much,--that of Miss Martineau, who, both in an article on\r 'Villette' in the Daily News, and in a private letter to Miss Bronte,\r wounded her to the quick by expressions of censure which she believed\r to be unjust and unfounded, but which, if correct and true, went deeper\r than any merely artistic fault. An author may bring himself to believe\r that he can bear blame with equanimity, from whatever quarter it comes;\r but its force is derived altoget","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"597"},"sequenceIndex":3456},{"id":"plato-symposiu-598","text":"She had long before asked Miss Martineau to tell her whether she\r considered that any want of womanly delicacy or propriety was betrayed\r in \"Jane Eyre\". And on receiving Miss Martineau's assurance that she\r did not, Miss Bronte entreated her to declare it frankly if she thought\r there was any failure of this description in any future work of \"Currer\r Bell's.\" The promise then given of faithful truth-speaking, Miss\r Martineau fulfilled when \"Villette\" appeared. Miss Bronte writhed under\r what she felt to be injustice.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"598"},"sequenceIndex":3457},{"id":"plato-symposiu-599","text":"This seems a fitting place to state how utterly unconscious she was of\r what was, by some, esteemed coarse in her writings. One day, during\r that visit at the Briery when I first met her, the conversation turned\r upon the subject of women's writing fiction; and some one remarked on\r the fact that, in certain instances, authoresses had much outstepped\r the line which men felt to be proper in works of this kind. Miss Bronte\r said she wondered how far this was a natural consequence of allowing the\r imagination to work too constantly; Sir James and Lady Kay Shuttleworth\r and I expressed our belief","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"599"},"sequenceIndex":3458},{"id":"plato-symposiu-600","text":"Again, she was invariably shocked and distressed when she heard of any\r disapproval of \"Jane Eyre\" on the ground above-mentioned. Some one said\r to her in London, \"You know, you and I, Miss Bronte, have both written\r naughty books!\" She dwelt much on this; and, as if it weighed on her\r mind, took an opportunity to ask Mrs. Smith, as she would have asked a\r mother--if she had not been motherless from earliest childhood--whether,\r indeed, there was anything so wrong in \"Jane Eyre.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"600"},"sequenceIndex":3459},{"id":"plato-symposiu-601","text":"I do not deny for myself the existence of coarseness here and there\r in her works, otherwise so entirely noble. I only ask those who read\r them to consider her life,--which has been openly laid bare before\r them,--and to say how it could be otherwise. She saw few men; and among\r these few were one or two with whom she had been acquainted since early\r girlhood,--who had shown her much friendliness and kindness,--through\r whose family she had received many pleasures,--for whose intellect she\r had a great respect,--but who talked before her, if not to her with\r as little reticence as Rochester ta","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"601"},"sequenceIndex":3460},{"id":"plato-symposiu-602","text":"The misunderstanding with Miss Martineau on account of \"Villette,\" was\r the cause of bitter regret to Miss Bronte. Her woman's nature had been\r touched, as she thought, with insulting misconception; and she had\r dearly loved the person who had thus unconsciously wounded her. It was\r but in the January just past that she had written as follows, in reply\r to a friend, the tenor of whose letter we may guess from this answer:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"602"},"sequenceIndex":3461},{"id":"plato-symposiu-603","text":"\"I read attentively all you say about Miss Martineau; the sincerity\r and constancy of your solicitude touch me very much; I should grieve\r to neglect or oppose your advice, and yet I do not feel it would be\r right to give Miss Martineau up entirely. There is in her nature much\r that is very noble; hundreds have forsaken her, more, I fear, in the\r apprehension that their fair names may suffer, if seen in connection\r with hers, than from any pure convictions, such as you suggest, of harm\r consequent on her fatal tenets. With these fair-weather friends I cannot\r bear to rank; and for her sin, is ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"603"},"sequenceIndex":3462},{"id":"plato-symposiu-604","text":"\"To speak the truth, my dear Miss ----, I believe, if you were in my\r place, and knew Miss Martineau as I do,--if you had shared with me\r the proofs of her genuine kindliness, and had seen how she secretly\r suffers from abandonment,--you would be the last to give her up; you\r would separate the sinner from the sin, and feel as if the right lay\r rather in quietly adhering to her in her strait, while that adherence is\r unfashionable and unpopular, than in turning on her your back when the\r world sets the example. I believe she is one of those whom opposition\r and desertion make obstinate in erro","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"604"},"sequenceIndex":3463},{"id":"plato-symposiu-605","text":"Kindly and faithful words! which Miss Martineau never knew of; to be\r repaid in words more grand and tender, when Charlotte lay deaf and cold\r by her dead sisters. In spite of their short sorrowful misunderstanding,\r they were a pair of noble women and faithful friends.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"605"},"sequenceIndex":3464},{"id":"plato-symposiu-606","text":"I turn to a pleasanter subject. While she was in London, Miss Bronte had\r seen Lawrence's portrait of Mr. Thackeray, and admired it extremely. Her\r first words, after she had stood before it some time in silence, were,\r \"And there came up a Lion out of Judah!\" The likeness was by this time\r engraved, and Mr. Smith sent her a copy of it.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"606"},"sequenceIndex":3465},{"id":"plato-symposiu-607","text":"\"My dear Sir,--At a late hour yesterday evening, I had the honour of\r receiving, at Haworth Parsonage, a distinguished guest, none other than\r W. M. Thackeray, Esq. Mindful of the rites of hospitality, I hung him up\r in state this morning. He looks superb in his beautiful, tasteful gilded\r gibbet. For companion he has the Duke of Wellington, (do you remember\r giving me that picture?) and for contrast and foil Richmond's portrait\r of an unworthy individual, who, in such society, must be name-less.\r Thackeray looks away from the latter character with a grand scorn,\r edifying to witness. I wonder","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"607"},"sequenceIndex":3466},{"id":"plato-symposiu-608","text":"Miss Bronte was in much better health during this winter of 1852-3, than\r she had been the year before.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"608"},"sequenceIndex":3467},{"id":"plato-symposiu-609","text":"\"For my part,\" (she wrote to me in February) \"I have thus far borne the\r cold weather well. I have taken long walks on the crackling snow, and\r felt the frosty air bracing. This winter has, for me, not been like last\r winter. December, January, February, '51-2, passed like a long stormy\r night, conscious of one painful dream) all solitary grief and sickness.\r The corresponding l in '52-3 have gone over my head quietly and not\r uncheerfully. Thank God for the change and the repose! How welcome it\r has been He only knows! My father too has borne the season well; and my\r book, and its reception t","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"609"},"sequenceIndex":3468},{"id":"plato-symposiu-610","text":"In March the quiet Parsonage had the honour of receiving a visit from\r the then Bishop of Ripon. He remained one night with Mr. Bronte. In the\r evening, some of the neighbouring clergy were invited to meet him at\r tea and supper; and during the latter meal, some of the \"curates\" began\r merrily to upbraid Miss Bronte with \"putting them into a book;\" and she,\r shrinking from thus having her character as authoress thrust upon her at\r her own table, and in the presence of a stranger, pleasantly appealed\r to the bishop as to whether it was quite fair thus to drive her, into a\r corner. His Lordship,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"610"},"sequenceIndex":3469},{"id":"plato-symposiu-611","text":"\"The Bishop has been, and is gone. He is certainly a most charming\r Bishop; the most benignant gentleman that ever put on lawn sleeves;\r yet stately too, and quite competent to check encroachments. His\r visit passed capitally well; and at its close, as he was going away,\r he expressed himself thoroughly gratified with all he had seen. The\r Inspector has been also in the course of the past week; so that I have\r had a somewhat busy time of it. If you could have been at Haworth to\r share the pleasures of the company, without having been inconvenienced\r by the little bustle of the preparation, I s","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"611"},"sequenceIndex":3470},{"id":"plato-symposiu-612","text":"By this time some of the Reviews had began to find fault with\r \"Villette.\" Miss Bronte made her old request.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"612"},"sequenceIndex":3471},{"id":"plato-symposiu-613","text":"\"My dear Sir,--Were a review to appear, inspired with treble their\r animus, PRAY do not withhold it from me. I like to see the satisfactory\r notices,--especially I like to carry them to my father; but I MUST see\r such as are UNsatisfactory and hostile; these are for my own especial\r edification;--it is in these I best read public feeling and opinion.\r To shun examination into the dangerous and disagreeable seems to me\r cowardly. I long always to know what really IS, and am only unnerved\r when kept in the dark. . . . . . .","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"613"},"sequenceIndex":3472},{"id":"plato-symposiu-614","text":"\"As to the character of 'Lucy Snowe,' my intention from the first was\r that she should not occupy the pedestal to which 'Jane Eyre' was raised\r by some injudicious admirers. She is where I meant her to be, and where\r no charge of self-laudation can touch her.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"614"},"sequenceIndex":3473},{"id":"plato-symposiu-615","text":"\"The note you sent this morning from Lady Harriette St. Clair, is\r precisely to the same purport as Miss Muloch's request,--an application\r for exact and authentic information respecting the fate of M. Paul\r Emanuel! You see how much the ladies think of this little man, whom you\r none of you like. I had a letter the other day; announcing that a lady\r of some note, who had always determined that whenever she married, her\r husband should be the counterpart of 'Mr. Knightly' in Miss Austen's\r 'Emma,' had now changed her mind, and vowed that she would either find\r the duplicate of Professor Emanue","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"615"},"sequenceIndex":3474},{"id":"plato-symposiu-616","text":"When Easter, with its duties arising out of sermons to be preached\r by strange clergymen who had afterwards to be entertained at\r the Parsonage,--with Mechanics' Institute Meetings, and school\r tea-drinkings, was over and gone; she came, at the close of April, to\r visit us in Manchester. We had a friend, a young lady, staying with us.\r Miss Bronte had expected to find us alone; and although our friend was\r gentle and sensible after Miss Bronte's own heart, yet her presence was\r enough to create a nervous tremour. I was aware that both of our guests\r were unusually silent; and I saw a little sh","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"616"},"sequenceIndex":3475},{"id":"plato-symposiu-617","text":"It was now two or three years since I had witnessed a similar effect\r produced on her; in anticipation of a quiet evening at Fox-How; and\r since then she had seen many and various people in London: but the\r physical sensations produced by shyness were still the same; and on\r the following day she laboured under severe headache. I had several\r opportunities of perceiving how this nervousness was ingrained in her\r constitution, and how acutely she suffered in striving to overcome it.\r One evening we had, among other guests, two sisters who sang Scottish\r ballads exquisitely. Miss Bronte had been","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"617"},"sequenceIndex":3476},{"id":"plato-symposiu-618","text":"There was another circumstance that came to my knowledge at this period\r which told secrets about the finely-strung frame. One night I was on\r the point of relating some dismal ghost story, just before bed-time.\r She shrank from hearing it, and confessed that she was superstitious,\r and, prone at all times to the involuntary recurrence of any thoughts of\r ominous gloom which might have been suggested to her. She said that on\r first coming to us, she had found a letter on her dressing-table from a\r friend in Yorkshire, containing a story which had impressed her vividly\r ever since;--that it min","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"618"},"sequenceIndex":3477},{"id":"plato-symposiu-619","text":"One day we asked two gentlemen to meet her at dinner; expecting that\r she and they would have a mutual pleasure in making each other's\r acquaintance. To our disappointment she drew back with timid reserve\r from all their advances, replying to their questions and remarks in the\r briefest manner possible; till at last they gave up their efforts to\r draw her into conversation in despair, and talked to each other and my\r husband on subjects of recent local interest. Among these Thackeray's\r Lectures (which had lately been delivered in Manchester) were spoken of\r and that on Fielding especially dwe","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"619"},"sequenceIndex":3478},{"id":"plato-symposiu-620","text":"What she said, and which part she took, in the dispute about Thackeray's\r lecture, may be gathered from the following letter, referring to the\r same subject:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"620"},"sequenceIndex":3479},{"id":"plato-symposiu-621","text":"\"The Lectures arrived safely; I have read them through twice. They\r must be studied to be appreciated. I thought well of them when I heard\r them delivered, but now I see their real power; and it is great. The\r lecture on Swift was new to me; I thought it almost matchless. Not\r that by any means I always agree with Mr. Thackeray's opinions, but\r his force, his penetration, his pithy simplicity, his eloquence--his\r manly sonorous eloquence,--command entire admiration. . . . Against\r his errors I protest, were it treason to do so. I was present at the\r Fielding lecture: the hour spent in listenin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"621"},"sequenceIndex":3480},{"id":"plato-symposiu-622","text":"After her visit to Manchester, she had to return to a re-opening of the\r painful circumstances of the previous winter, as the time drew near for\r Mr. Nicholl's departure from Haworth. A testimonial of respect from\r the parishioners was presented, at a public meeting, to one who had\r faithfully served them for eight years: and he left the place, and she\r saw no chance of hearing a word about him in the future, unless it was\r some second-hand scrap of intelligence, dropped out accidentally by one\r of the neighbouring clergymen.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"622"},"sequenceIndex":3481},{"id":"plato-symposiu-623","text":"I had promised to pay her a visit on my return from London in June; but,\r after the day was fixed, a letter came from Mr. Bronte, saying that she\r was suffering from so severe an attack of influenza, accompanied with\r such excruciating pain in the head, that he must request me to defer my\r visit until she was better. While sorry for the cause, I did not regret\r that my going was delayed till the season when the moors would be all\r glorious with the purple bloom of the heather; and thus present a scene\r about which she had often spoken to me. So we agreed that I should\r not come to her before A","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"623"},"sequenceIndex":3482},{"id":"plato-symposiu-624","text":"\"Thank you for your letter; it was as pleasant as a quiet chat, as\r welcome as spring showers, as reviving as a friend's visit; in short,\r it was very like a page of 'Cranford.' . . . A thought strikes me. Do\r you, who have so many friends,--so large a circle of acquaintance,--find\r it easy, when you sit down to write, to isolate yourself from all\r those ties, and their sweet associations, so as to be your OWN WOMAN,\r uninfluenced or swayed by the consciousness of how your work may affect\r other minds; what blame or what sympathy it may call forth? Does no\r luminous cloud ever come between you","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"624"},"sequenceIndex":3483},{"id":"plato-symposiu-625","text":"Towards the latter end of September I went to Haworth. At the risk of\r repeating something which I have previously said, I will copy out parts\r of a letter which I wrote at the time.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"625"},"sequenceIndex":3484},{"id":"plato-symposiu-626","text":"\"It was a dull, drizzly Indian-inky day, all the way on the railroad to\r Keighley, which is a rising wool-manufacturing town, lying in a hollow\r between hills--not a pretty hollow, but more what the Yorkshire people\r call a 'bottom,' or 'botham.' I left Keighley in a car for Haworth,\r four miles off--four tough, steep, scrambling miles, the road winding\r between the wavelike hills that rose and fell on every side of the\r horizon, with a long illimitable sinuous look, as if they were a part of\r the line of the Great Serpent, which the Norse legend says girdles the\r world. The day was lead-colou","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"626"},"sequenceIndex":3485},{"id":"plato-symposiu-627","text":"\"I don't know that I ever saw a spot more exquisitely clean; the\r most dainty place for that I ever saw. To be sure, the life is like\r clock-work. No one comes to the house; nothing disturbs the deep repose;\r hardly a voice is heard; you catch the ticking of the clock in the\r kitchen, or the buzzing of a fly in the parlour, all over the house.\r Miss Bronte sits alone in her parlour; breakfasting with her father in\r his study at nine o'clock. She helps in the housework; for one of their\r servants, Tabby, is nearly ninety, and the other only a girl. Then I\r accompanied her in her walks on the sw","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"627"},"sequenceIndex":3486},{"id":"plato-symposiu-628","text":"\"She cannot see well, and does little beside knitting. The way she\r weakened her eyesight was this: When she was sixteen or seventeen, she\r wanted much to draw; and she copied niminipimini copper-plate engravings\r out of annuals, ('stippling,' don't the artists call it?) every\r little point put in, till at the end of six months she had produced\r an exquisitely faithful copy of the engraving. She wanted to learn to\r express her ideas by drawing. After she had tried to DRAW stories, and\r not succeeded, she took the better mode of writing; but in so small a\r hand, that it is almost impossible to ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"628"},"sequenceIndex":3487},{"id":"plato-symposiu-629","text":"\"But now to return to our quiet hour of rest after dinner. I soon\r observed that her habits of order were such that she could not go on\r with the conversation, if a chair was out of its place; everything was\r arranged with delicate regularity. We talked over the old times of her\r childhood; of her elder sister's (Maria's) death,--just like that of\r Helen Burns in 'Jane Eyre;' of those strange, starved days at school; of\r the desire (almost amounting to illness) of expressing herself in some\r way,--writing or drawing; of her weakened eyesight, which prevented her\r doing anything for two years, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"629"},"sequenceIndex":3488},{"id":"plato-symposiu-630","text":"\"We have generally had another walk before tea, which is at six; at\r half-past eight, prayers; and by nine, all the household are in bed,\r except ourselves. We sit up together till ten, or past; and after I go,\r I hear Miss Bronte comedown and walk up and down the room for an hour or\r so.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"630"},"sequenceIndex":3489},{"id":"plato-symposiu-631","text":"Copying this letter has brought the days of that pleasant visit very\r clear before me,--very sad in their clearness. We were so happy\r together; we were so full of interest in each other's subjects. The\r day seemed only too short for what we had to say and to hear. I\r understood her life the better for seeing the place where it had been\r spent--where she had loved and suffered. Mr. Bronte was a most courteous\r host; and when he was with us,--at breakfast in his study, or at tea\r in Charlotte's parlour,--he had a sort of grand and stately way of\r describing past times, which tallied well with h","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"631"},"sequenceIndex":3490},{"id":"plato-symposiu-632","text":"I remember two or three subjects of the conversations which she and I\r held in the evenings, besides those alluded to in my letter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"632"},"sequenceIndex":3491},{"id":"plato-symposiu-633","text":"I asked her whether she had ever taken opium, as the description\r given of its effects in \"Villette\" was so exactly like what I had\r experienced,--vivid and exaggerated presence of objects, of which the\r outlines were indistinct, or lost in golden mist, etc. She replied, that\r she had never, to her knowledge, taken a grain of it in any shape, but\r that she had followed the process she always adopted when she had to\r describe anything which had not fallen within her own experience; she\r had thought intently on it for many and many a night before falling to\r sleep,--wondering what it was like, o","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"633"},"sequenceIndex":3492},{"id":"plato-symposiu-634","text":"She made many inquiries as to Mrs. Stowe's personal appearance; and\r it evidently harmonised well with some theory of hers, to hear that\r the author of Uncle Tom's Cabin was small and slight. It was another\r theory of hers, that no mixtures of blood produced such fine characters,\r mentally and morally, as the Scottish and English.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"634"},"sequenceIndex":3493},{"id":"plato-symposiu-635","text":"I recollect, too, her saying how acutely she dreaded a charge of\r plagiarism, when, after she had written \"Jane Eyre;\" she read the\r thrilling effect of the mysterious scream at midnight in Mrs. Marsh's\r story of the \"Deformed.\" She also said that, when she read the\r \"Neighbours,\" she thought every one would fancy that she must have\r taken her conception of Jane Eyre's character from that of \"Francesca,\"\r the narrator of Miss Bremer's story. For my own part, I cannot see the\r slightest resemblance between the two characters, and so I told her;\r but she persisted in saying that Francesca was Ja","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"635"},"sequenceIndex":3494},{"id":"plato-symposiu-636","text":"We went, not purposely, but accidentally, to see various poor people in\r our distant walks. From one we had borrowed an umbrella; in the house of\r another we had taken shelter from a rough September storm. In all these\r cottages, her quiet presence was known. At three miles from her home,\r the chair was dusted for her, with a kindly \"Sit ye down, Miss Bronte;\"\r and she knew what absent or ailing members of the family to inquire\r after. Her quiet, gentle words, few though they might be, were evidently\r grateful to those Yorkshire ears. Their welcome to her, though rough and\r curt, was sincere a","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"636"},"sequenceIndex":3495},{"id":"plato-symposiu-637","text":"We talked about the different courses through which life ran. She said,\r in her own composed manner, as if she had accepted the theory as a fact,\r that she believed some were appointed beforehand to sorrow and much\r disappointment; that it did not fall to the lot of all--as Scripture\r told us--to have their lines fall in pleasant places; that it was well\r for those who had rougher paths, to perceive that such was God's will\r concerning them, and try to moderate their expectations, leaving hope to\r those of a different doom, and seeking patience and resignation as the\r virtues they were to cult","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"637"},"sequenceIndex":3496},{"id":"plato-symposiu-638","text":"In connection with this conversation, she named a little abortive plan\r which I had not heard of till then; how, in the previous July, she had\r been tempted to join some friends (a married couple and their child)\r in an excursion to Scotland. They set out joyfully; she with especial\r gladness, for Scotland was a land which had its roots deep down in her\r imaginative affections, and the glimpse of two days at Edinburgh was all\r she had as yet seen of it. But, at the first stage after Carlisle, the\r little yearling child was taken with a slight indisposition; the anxious\r parents fancied that st","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"638"},"sequenceIndex":3497},{"id":"plato-symposiu-639","text":"We parted with many intentions, on both sides, of renewing very\r frequently the pleasure we had had in being together. We agreed that\r when she wanted bustle, or when I wanted quiet, we were to let each\r other know, and exchange visits as occasion required.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"639"},"sequenceIndex":3498},{"id":"plato-symposiu-640","text":"I was aware that she had a great anxiety on her mind at this time; and\r being acquainted with its nature, I could not but deeply admire the\r patient docility which she displayed in her conduct towards her father.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"640"},"sequenceIndex":3499},{"id":"plato-symposiu-641","text":"Soon after I left Haworth, she went on a visit to Miss Wooler, who was\r then staying at Hornsea. The time passed quietly and happily with this\r friend, whose society was endeared to her by every year.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"641"},"sequenceIndex":3500},{"id":"plato-symposiu-642","text":"\"I wonder how you are spending these long winter evenings. Alone,\r probably, like me. The thought often crosses me, as I sit by myself, how\r pleasant it would be if you lived within a walking distance, and I could\r go to you sometimes, or have you to come and spend a day and night with\r me. Yes; I did enjoy that week at Hornsea, and I look forward to spring\r as the period when you will fulfil your promise of coming to visit me.\r I fear you must be very solitary at Hornsea. How hard to some people\r of the world it would seem to live your life! how utterly impossible\r to live it with a serene sp","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"642"},"sequenceIndex":3501},{"id":"plato-symposiu-643","text":"Of course, as I draw nearer to the years so recently closed, it becomes\r impossible for me to write with the same fulness of detail as I have\r hitherto not felt it wrong to use. Miss Bronte passed the winter of\r 1853-4 in a solitary and anxious manner. But the great conqueror Time\r was slowly achieving his victory over strong prejudice and human\r resolve. By degrees Mr. Bronte became reconciled to the idea of his\r daughter's marriage.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"643"},"sequenceIndex":3502},{"id":"plato-symposiu-644","text":"There is one other letter, addressed to Mr. Dobell, which developes the\r intellectual side of her character, before we lose all thought of the\r authoress in the timid and conscientious woman about to become a wife,\r and in the too short, almost perfect, happiness of her nine months of\r wedded life.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"644"},"sequenceIndex":3503},{"id":"plato-symposiu-645","text":"\"My dear Sir,--I can hardly tell you how glad I am to have an\r opportunity of explaining that taciturnity to which you allude. Your\r letter came at a period of danger and care, when my father was very\r ill, and I could not leave his bedside. I answered no letters at that\r time, and yours was one of three or four that, when leisure returned\r to me, and I came to consider their purport, it seemed to me such that\r the time was past for answering them, and I laid them finally aside. If\r you remember, you asked me to go to London; it was too late either to\r go or to decline. I was sure you had left","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"645"},"sequenceIndex":3504},{"id":"plato-symposiu-646","text":"\"'Balder' arrived safely. I looked at him, before cutting his leaves\r with singular pleasure. Remembering well his elder brother, the potent\r 'Roman,' it was natural to give a cordial welcome to a fresh scion of\r the same house and race. I have read him. He impressed me thus he teems\r with power; I found in him a wild wealth of life, but I thought his\r favourite and favoured child would bring his sire trouble--would make\r his heart ache. It seemed to me, that his strength and beauty were not\r so much those of Joseph, the pillar of Jacob's age, as of the Prodigal\r Son, who troubled his father, ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"646"},"sequenceIndex":3505},{"id":"plato-symposiu-647","text":"\"How is it that while the first-born of genius often brings honour, the\r second as almost often proves a source of depression and care? I could\r almost prophesy that your third will atone for any anxiety inflicted by\r this his immediate predecessor.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"647"},"sequenceIndex":3506},{"id":"plato-symposiu-648","text":"\"There is power in that character of 'Balder,' and to me a certain\r horror. Did you mean it to embody, along with force, any of the\r special defects of the artistic character? It seems to me that those\r defects were never thrown out in stronger lines. I did not and could\r not think you meant to offer him as your cherished ideal of the\r true, great poet; I regarded him as a vividly-coloured picture of\r inflated self-esteem, almost frantic aspiration; of a nature that has\r made a Moloch of intellect--offered up; in pagan fires, the natural\r affections--sacrificed the heart to the brain. Do we no","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"648"},"sequenceIndex":3507},{"id":"plato-symposiu-649","text":"\"But if the critics err now (as yet I have seen none of their\r lucubrations), you shall one day set them right in the second part of\r 'Balder.' You shall show them that you too know--better, perhaps, than\r they--that the truly great man is too sincere in his affections to\r grudge a sacrifice; too much absorbed in his work to talk loudly about\r it; too intent on finding the best way to accomplish what he undertakes\r to think great things of himself--the instrument. And if God places\r seeming impediments in his way--if his duties sometimes seem to hamper\r his powers--he feels keenly, perhaps wri","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"649"},"sequenceIndex":3508},{"id":"plato-symposiu-650","text":"\"Whoever speaks to me of 'Balder'--though I live too retired a life to\r come often in the way of comment--shall be answered according to your\r suggestion and my own impression. Equity demands that you should be your\r own interpreter. Good-bye for the present, and believe me,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"650"},"sequenceIndex":3509},{"id":"plato-symposiu-651","text":"A letter to her Brussels schoolfellow gives an idea of the external\r course of things during this winter.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"651"},"sequenceIndex":3510},{"id":"plato-symposiu-652","text":"\"I was very glad to see your handwriting again. It is, I believe, a year\r since I heard from you. Again and again you have recurred to my thoughts\r lately, and I was beginning to have some sad presages as to the cause of\r your silence. Your letter happily does away with all these; it brings,\r on the whole, glad tidings both of your papa, mama, your sisters, and,\r last but not least, your dear respected English self.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"652"},"sequenceIndex":3511},{"id":"plato-symposiu-653","text":"\"My dear father has borne the severe winter very well, a circumstance\r for which I feel the more thankful as he had many weeks of very\r precarious health last summer, following an attack from which he\r suffered in June, and which for a few hours deprived him totally of\r sight, though neither his mind, speech, nor even his powers of motion\r were in the least affected. I can hardly tell you how thankful I\r was, when, after that dreary and almost despairing interval of utter\r darkness, some gleam of daylight became visible to him once more. I\r had feared that paralysis had seized the optic nerve.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"653"},"sequenceIndex":3512},{"id":"plato-symposiu-654","text":"\"Circumstanced as I have been, you will comprehend that I have had\r neither the leisure nor the inclination to go from home much during\r the past year. I spent a week with Mrs. Gaskell in the spring, and a\r fortnight with some other friends more recently, and that includes the\r whole of my visiting since I saw you last. My life is, indeed, very\r uniform and retired--more so than is quite healthful either for mind or\r body; yet I find reason for often-renewed feelings of gratitude, in the\r sort of support which still comes and cheers me on from time to time.\r My health, though not unbroken, is,","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"654"},"sequenceIndex":3513},{"id":"plato-symposiu-655","text":"\"My dear Miss Wooler,--The truly kind interest which you always taken\r in my affairs makes me feel that it is due to you to transmit an early\r communication on a subject respecting which I have already consulted you\r more than once. I must tell you then, that since I wrote last, papa's\r mind has gradually come round to a view very different to that which\r he once took; and that after some correspondence, and as the result of\r a visit Mr. Nicholls paid here about a week ago, it was agreed that he\r was to resume the curacy of Haworth, as soon as papa's present assistant\r is provided with a situa","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"655"},"sequenceIndex":3514},{"id":"plato-symposiu-656","text":"\"It gives me unspeakable content to see that now my father has once\r admitted this new view of the case, he dwells on it very complacently.\r In all arrangements, his convenience and seclusion will be scrupulously\r respected. Mr. Nicholls seems deeply to feel the wish to comfort and\r sustain his declining years. I think from Mr. Nicholls' character I may\r depend on this not being a mere transitory impulsive feeling, but rather\r that it will be accepted steadily as a duty, and discharged tenderly as\r an office of affection. The destiny which Providence in His goodness and\r wisdom seems to offer ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"656"},"sequenceIndex":3515},{"id":"plato-symposiu-657","text":"\"When you write to me, tell me how you are. . . . I have now decidedly\r declined the visit to London; the ensuing three months will bring me\r abundance of occupation; I could not afford to throw away a month. . . .\r Papa has just got a letter from the good and dear bishop, which has\r touched and pleased us much; it expresses so cordial an approbation of\r Mr. Nicholls' return to Haworth (respecting which he was consulted), and\r such kind gratification at the domestic arrangements which are to ensue.\r It seems his penetration discovered the state of things when he was here\r in June 1853.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"657"},"sequenceIndex":3516},{"id":"plato-symposiu-658","text":"She expressed herself in other letters, as thankful to One who had\r guided her through much difficulty and much distress and perplexity of\r mind; and yet she felt what most thoughtful women do, who marry when\r the first flush of careless youth is over, that there was a strange\r half-sad feeling, in making announcements of an engagement--for cares\r and fears came mingled inextricably with hopes. One great relief to her\r mind at this time was derived from the conviction that her father took\r a positive pleasure in all the thoughts about and preparations for her\r wedding. He was anxious that thin","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"658"},"sequenceIndex":3517},{"id":"plato-symposiu-659","text":"At the beginning of May, Miss Bronte left home to pay three visits\r before her marriage. The first was to us. She only remained three days,\r as she had to go to the neighbourhood of Leeds, there to make such\r purchases as were required for her marriage. Her preparations, as she\r said, could neither be expensive nor extensive; consisting chiefly in a\r modest replenishing of her wardrobe, some re-papering and re-painting\r in the Parsonage; and, above all, converting the small flagged\r passage-room, hitherto used only for stores (which was behind her\r sitting room), into a study for her husband. ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"659"},"sequenceIndex":3518},{"id":"plato-symposiu-660","text":"\"Since I came home I have been very busy stitching; the little new\r room is got into order, and the green and white curtains are up; they\r exactly suit the papering, and look neat and clean enough. I had a\r letter a day or two since, announcing that Mr. Nicholls comes to-morrow.\r I feel anxious about him; more anxious on one point than I dare quite\r express to myself. It seems he has again been suffering sharply from\r his rheumatic affection. I hear this not from himself, but from another\r quarter. He was ill while I was in Manchester and B----. He uttered no\r complaint to me; dropped no hint ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"660"},"sequenceIndex":3519},{"id":"plato-symposiu-661","text":"Mr. Bronte had a slight illness which alarmed her much. Besides, all\r the weight of care involved in the household preparations pressed on\r the bride in this case--not unpleasantly, only to the full occupation\r of her time. She was too busy to unpack her wedding dresses for several\r days after they arrived from Halifax; yet not too busy to think of\r arrangements by which Miss Wooler's journey to be present at the\r marriage could be facilitated.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"661"},"sequenceIndex":3520},{"id":"plato-symposiu-662","text":"\"I write to Miss Wooler to-day. Would it not be better, dear, if you and\r she could arrange to come to Haworth on the same day, arrive at Keighley\r by the same train; then I could order the cab to meet you at the\r station, and bring you on with your luggage? In this hot weather walking\r would be quite out of the question, either for you or for her; and I\r know she would persist in doing it if left to herself, and arrive half\r killed. I thought it better to mention this arrangement to you first,\r and then, if you liked it, you could settle the time, etc., with Miss\r Wooler, and let me know. Be ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"662"},"sequenceIndex":3521},{"id":"plato-symposiu-663","text":"\"Mr. Nicholls is a kind, considerate fellow. With all his masculine\r faults, he enters into my wishes about having the thing done quietly, in\r a way that makes me grateful; and if nobody interferes and spoils his\r arrangements, he will manage it so that not a soul in Haworth shall be\r aware of the day. He is so thoughtful, too, about 'the ladies,'--that\r is, you and Miss Wooler. Anticipating, too, the very arrangements I was\r going to propose to him about providing for your departure, etc. He and\r Mr. S---- come to ---- the evening before; write me a note to let me\r know they are there; precis","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"663"},"sequenceIndex":3522},{"id":"plato-symposiu-664","text":"It was fixed that the marriage was to take place on the 29th of June.\r Her two friends arrived at Haworth Parsonage the day before; and the\r long summer afternoon and evening were spent by Charlotte in thoughtful\r arrangements for the morrow, and for her father's comfort during\r her absence from home. When all was finished--the trunk packed, the\r morning's breakfast arranged, the wedding-dress laid out,--just at\r bedtime, Mr. Bronte announced his intention of stopping at home while\r the others went to church. What was to be done? Who was to give the\r bride away? There were only to be the offic","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"664"},"sequenceIndex":3523},{"id":"plato-symposiu-665","text":"The news of the wedding had slipt abroad before the little party came\r out of church, and many old and humble friends were there, seeing her\r look \"like a snow-drop,\" as they say. Her dress was white embroidered\r muslin, with a lace mantle, and white bonnet trimmed with green leaves,\r which perhaps might suggest the resemblance to the pale wintry flower.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"665"},"sequenceIndex":3524},{"id":"plato-symposiu-666","text":"Mr. Nicholls and she went to visit his friends and relations in Ireland;\r and made a tour by Killarney, Glengariff, Tarbert, Tralee, and Cork,\r seeing scenery, of which she says, \"some parts exceeded all I had\r ever imagined.\" . . . \"I must say I like my new relations. My dear\r husband, too, appears in a new light in his own country. More than once\r I have had deep pleasure in hearing his praises on all sides. Some\r of the old servants and followers of the family tell me I am a most\r fortunate person; for that I have got one of the best gentlemen in the\r country. . . . I trust I feel thankful ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"666"},"sequenceIndex":3525},{"id":"plato-symposiu-667","text":"Henceforward the sacred doors of home are closed upon her married life.\r We, her loving friends, standing outside, caught occasional glimpses\r of brightness, and pleasant peaceful murmurs of sound, telling of the\r gladness within; and we looked at each other, and gently said, \"After a\r hard and long struggle--after many cares and many bitter sorrows--she is\r tasting happiness now!\" We thought of the slight astringencies of her\r character, and how they would turn to full ripe sweetness in that calm\r sunshine of domestic peace. We remembered her trials, and were glad in\r the idea that God had se","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"667"},"sequenceIndex":3526},{"id":"plato-symposiu-668","text":"\"I really seem to have had scarcely a spare moment since that dim quiet\r June morning, when you, E----, and myself all walked down to Haworth\r Church. Not that I have been wearied or oppressed; but the fact is,\r my time is not my own now; somebody else wants a good portion of it,\r and says, 'we must do so and so.' We DO so and so, accordingly; and it\r generally seems the right thing. . . . We have had many callers from a\r distance, and latterly some little occupation in the way of preparing\r for a small village entertainment. Both Mr. Nicholls and myself wished\r much to make some response for ","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"668"},"sequenceIndex":3527},{"id":"plato-symposiu-669","text":"\"Yes! I am thankful to say my husband is in improved health and spirits.\r It makes me content and grateful to hear him from time to time avow his\r happiness in the brief, plain phrase of sincerity. My own life is more\r occupied than it used to be I have not so much time for thinking I am\r obliged to be more practical, for my dear Arthur is a very practical,\r as well as a very punctual and methodical man. Every morning he is in\r the National School by nine o'clock; he gives the children religious\r instruction till half-past ten. Almost every afternoon he pays visits\r amongst the poor parishione","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"669"},"sequenceIndex":3528},{"id":"plato-symposiu-670","text":"Her friend and bridesmaid came to pay them a visit in October. I was to\r have gone also, but I allowed some little obstacle to intervene, to my\r lasting regret.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"670"},"sequenceIndex":3529},{"id":"plato-symposiu-671","text":"\"I say nothing about the war; but when I read of its horrors, I cannot\r help thinking that it is one of the greatest curses that ever fell upon\r mankind. I trust it may not last long, for it really seems to me that\r no glory to be gained can compensate for the sufferings which must be\r endured. This may seem a little ignoble and unpatriotic; but I think\r that as we advance towards middle age, nobleness and patriotism have a\r different signification to us to that which we accept while young.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"671"},"sequenceIndex":3530},{"id":"plato-symposiu-672","text":"\"You kindly inquire after Papa. He is better, and seems to gain strength\r as the weather gets colder; indeed, of late years health has always\r been better in winter than in summer. We are all indeed pretty well;\r and, for my own part, it is long since I have known such comparative\r immunity from headache, etc., as during the last three months. My life\r is different from what it used to be. May God make me thankful for it! I\r have a good, kind, attached husband; and every day my own attachment to\r him grows stronger.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"672"},"sequenceIndex":3531},{"id":"plato-symposiu-673","text":"Late in the autumn, Sir James Kay Shuttleworth crossed the border-hills\r that separate Lancashire from Yorkshire, and spent two or three days\r with them.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"673"},"sequenceIndex":3532},{"id":"plato-symposiu-674","text":"About this time, Mr. Nicholls was offered a living of much greater value\r than his curacy at Haworth, and in many ways the proposal was a very\r advantageous one; but he felt himself bound to Haworth as long as Mr.\r Bronte lived. Still, this offer gave his wife great and true pleasure,\r as a proof of the respect in which her husband was held.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"674"},"sequenceIndex":3533},{"id":"plato-symposiu-675","text":"\"I intended to have written a line yesterday, but just as I was sitting\r down for the purpose, Arthur called to me to take a walk. We set off,\r not intending to go far; but, though wild and cloudy, it was fair in\r the morning; when we had got about half a mile on the moors, Arthur\r suggested the idea of the waterfall; after the melted snow, he said, it\r would be fine. I had often wished to see it in its winter power,--so we\r walked on. It was fine indeed; a perfect torrent racing over the rocks,\r white and beautiful! It began to rain while we were watching it, and\r we returned home under a str","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"675"},"sequenceIndex":3534},{"id":"plato-symposiu-676","text":"She did not achieve this walk of seven or eight miles, in such weather,\r with impunity. She began to shiver soon after her return home, in spite\r of every precaution, and had a bad lingering sore throat and cold, which\r hung about her; and made her thin and weak.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"676"},"sequenceIndex":3535},{"id":"plato-symposiu-677","text":"\"Did I tell you that our poor little Flossy is dead? She drooped for a\r single day, and died quietly in the night without pain. The loss even of\r a dog was very saddening; yet, perhaps, no dog ever had a happier life,\r or an easier death.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"677"},"sequenceIndex":3536},{"id":"plato-symposiu-678","text":"On Christmas-day she and her husband walked to the poor old woman (whose\r calf she had been set to seek in former and less happy days), carrying\r with them a great spice-cake to make glad her heart. On Christmas-day\r many a humble meal in Haworth was made more plentiful by her gifts.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"678"},"sequenceIndex":3537},{"id":"plato-symposiu-679","text":"Early in the new year (1855), Mr. and Mrs. Nicholls went to visit Sir\r James Kay Shuttleworth at Gawthorpe. They only remained two or three\r days, but it so fell out that she increased her lingering cold, by a\r long walk over damp ground in thin shoes.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"679"},"sequenceIndex":3538},{"id":"plato-symposiu-680","text":"Soon after her return, she was attacked by new sensations of perpetual\r nausea, and ever-recurring faintness. After this state of things had\r lasted for some time; she yielded to Mr. Nicholls' wish that a doctor\r should be sent for. He came, and assigned a natural cause for her\r miserable indisposition; a little patience, and all would go right. She,\r who was ever patient in illness, tried hard to bear up and bear on.\r But the dreadful sickness increased and increased, till the very sight\r of food occasioned nausea. \"A wren would have starved on what she ate\r during those last six weeks,\" says","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"680"},"sequenceIndex":3539},{"id":"plato-symposiu-681","text":"\"I must write one line out of my weary bed. The news of M----'s probable\r recovery came like a ray of joy to me. I am not going to talk of my\r sufferings--it would be useless and painful. I want to give you an\r assurance, which I know will comfort you--and that is, that I find in\r my husband the tenderest nurse, the kindest support, the best earthly\r comfort that ever woman had. His patience never fails, and it is tried\r by sad days and broken nights. Write and tell me about Mrs. ----'s case;\r how long was she ill, and in what way? Papa--thank God!--is better. Our\r poor old Tabby is DEAD and B","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"681"},"sequenceIndex":3540},{"id":"plato-symposiu-682","text":"The other--also in faint, faint pencil marks--was to her Brussels\r schoolfellow.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"682"},"sequenceIndex":3541},{"id":"plato-symposiu-683","text":"\"A few lines of acknowledgment your letter SHALL have, whether well or\r ill. At present I am confined to my bed with illness, and have been\r so for three weeks. Up to this period, since my marriage, I have had\r excellent health. My husband and I live at home with my father; of\r course, I could not leave HIM. He is pretty well, better than last\r summer. No kinder, better husband than mine, it seems to me, there can\r be in the world. I do not want now for kind companionship in health and\r the tenderest nursing in sickness. Deeply I sympathise in all you tell\r me about Dr. W. and your excellent m","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"683"},"sequenceIndex":3542},{"id":"plato-symposiu-684","text":"I do not think she ever wrote a line again. Long days and longer nights\r went by; still the same relentless nausea and faintness, and still borne\r on in patient trust. About the third week in March there was a change;\r a low wandering delirium came on; and in it she begged constantly for\r food and even for stimulants. She swallowed eagerly now; but it was too\r late. Wakening for an instant from this stupor of intelligence, she saw\r her husband's woe-worn face, and caught the sound of some murmured words\r of prayer that God would spare her. \"Oh!\" she whispered forth, \"I am not\r going to die, am","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"684"},"sequenceIndex":3543},{"id":"plato-symposiu-685","text":"Early on Saturday morning, March 31st, the solemn tolling of Haworth\r church-bell spoke forth the fact of her death to the villagers who had\r known her from a child, and whose hearts shivered within them as they\r thought of the two sitting desolate and alone in the old grey house.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"685"},"sequenceIndex":3544},{"id":"plato-symposiu-686","text":"I have always been much struck with a passage in Mr. Forster's Life of\r Goldsmith. Speaking of the scene after his death, the writer says:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"686"},"sequenceIndex":3545},{"id":"plato-symposiu-687","text":"\"The staircase of Brick Court is said to have been filled with mourners,\r the reverse of domestic; women without a home, without domesticity of\r any kind, with no friend but him they had come to weep for; outcasts of\r that great, solitary, wicked city, to whom he had never forgotten to be\r kind and charitable.\"","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"687"},"sequenceIndex":3546},{"id":"plato-symposiu-688","text":"This came into my mind when I heard of some of the circumstances\r attendant on Charlotte's funeral.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"688"},"sequenceIndex":3547},{"id":"plato-symposiu-689","text":"Few beyond that circle of hills knew that she, whom the nations praised\r far off, lay dead that Easter mooring. Of kith and kin she had more in\r the grave to which she was soon to be borne, than among the living. The\r two mourners, stunned with their great grief, desired not the sympathy\r of strangers. One member out of most of the families in the parish was\r bidden to the funeral; and it became an act of self-denial in many a\r poor household to give up to another the privilege of paying their last\r homage to her; and those who were excluded from the formal train of\r mourners thronged the chur","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"689"},"sequenceIndex":3548},{"id":"plato-symposiu-690","text":"Among those humble friends who passionately grieved over the dead, was\r a village girl who had been seduced some little time before, but who\r had found a holy sister in Charlotte. She had sheltered her with her\r help, her counsel, her strengthening words; had ministered to her needs\r in her time of trial. Bitter, bitter was the grief of this poor young\r woman, when she heard that her friend was sick unto death, and deep\r is her mourning until this day. A blind girl, living some four miles\r from Haworth, loved Mrs. Nicholls so dearly that, with many cries and\r entreaties, she implored those abo","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"690"},"sequenceIndex":3549},{"id":"plato-symposiu-691","text":"I have little more to say. If my readers find that I have not said\r enough, I have said too much. I cannot measure or judge of such a\r character as hers. I cannot map out vices, and virtues, and debatable\r land. One who knew her long and well,--the \"Mary\" of this Life--writes\r thus of her dead friend:--","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"691"},"sequenceIndex":3550},{"id":"plato-symposiu-692","text":"\"She thought much of her duty, and had loftier and clearer notions of it\r than most people, and held fast to them with more success. It was done,\r it seems to me, with much more difficulty than people have of stronger\r nerves, and better fortunes. All her life was but labour and pain; and\r she never threw down the burden for the sake of present pleasure. I\r don't know what use you can make of all I have said. I have written it\r with the strong desire to obtain appreciation for her. Yet, what does\r it matter? She herself appealed to the world's judgment for her use of\r some of the faculties she","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"692"},"sequenceIndex":3551},{"id":"plato-symposiu-693","text":"But I turn from the critical, unsympathetic public--inclined to judge\r harshly because they have only seen superficially and not thought\r deeply. I appeal to that larger and more solemn public, who know how to\r look with tender humility at faults and errors; how to admire generously\r extraordinary genius, and how to reverence with warm, full hearts all\r noble virtue. To that Public I commit the memory of Charlotte Bronte.","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"693"},"sequenceIndex":3552},{"id":"plato-symposiu-694","text":"End of the Project Gutenberg EBook of Life of Charlotte Bronte, by\r Elizabeth Cleghorn Gaskell","author":"Plato","source":"Plato — Symposium (Jowett trans.)","tags":["philosophy","ancient-greek","language:english","collection:plato"],"groups":{"work":"Symposium","section":"694"},"sequenceIndex":3553}]}